Name: iDRAC Message Registry
Description: This registry defines the iDRAC messages for Redfish

RAC1160.Description: Unable to set USB group objects because the user account identified in the message does not have the System Control privilege, which is required for this operation.
RAC1160.Resolution: Contact the iDRAC system administrator and get the System Control privilege added to the account identified in the message or use account credentials that have System Control privilege and retry the operation.
RAC1160.Message: Unable to set USB group objects because of insufficient privilege for user account %1.

RED021.Description: The component InstanceID specified could not be located on the system.
RED021.Resolution: Ensure the component specified for updates is present in the system. Restart the system with Collect System Inventory on Restart enabled and verify that the component is represented by an instance of DCIM_SoftwareIdentity.
RED021.Message: The component InstanceID specified is not present on the system.

RAC0256.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the Preferred DNS IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0256.Resolution: Enter a valid Preferred DNS Server Address. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0256.Message: The Preferred DNS Server Address is invalid. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].

SYS401.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because the media type entered is not supported.
SYS401.Resolution: Enter a media type that is supported and retry the operation. For more information about the supported media types, see the Redfish User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS401.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the media type entered is not supported.

SYS432.Description: The Power Cap value cannot be set because the PowerCapSetting feature is disabled.
SYS432.Resolution: Enable the PowerCapSetting feature by using the PATCH operation on the Redfish OemAttributes URL, and then retry the operation.
SYS432.Message: Unable to set the Power Cap value because the PowerCapSetting feature is disabled.

UEFI0238.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - Calibration phase.
UEFI0238.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0238.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

LC076.Description: Unable to perform the Custom Signed Certificate (CSC) certificate delete operation. This may be due to IPMI communications issues.
LC076.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation.
LC076.Message: Unable to perform the Custom Signed Certificate (CSC) certificate delete operation.

SEC0702.Description: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is enabled.
SEC0702.Message: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is enabled.

PST0000.Description: The BIOS provided a progress code to the iDRAC, but that progress code is not recognized by the current iDRAC firmware.
PST0000.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the iDRAC firmware. 2) Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

SWC8513.Description: The user name identified in the message was successfully deleted.

ASR0009.Description: The system is communicating to the baseboard management controller (BMC).
ASR0009.Message: The system returned from a watchdog timer event.

SWC0090.Description: iDRAC is successfully configured by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.
SWC0090.Message: iDRAC is successfully configured by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.

SRV099.Description: The SupportAssist Collection cannot be saved on iDRAC because the iDRAC partition is not available.
SRV099.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
SRV099.Message: Unable to save the SupportAssist Collection on iDRAC because the iDRAC partition is not available.

SEL1209.Description: System policies or permissions may prevent the action from executing. If configured, the system will not execute the action on a platform event (power down, cycle, interrupt, send alert).
SEL1209.Message: The platform event filter action failed.

UEFI0082.Description: The system was reset due to a timeout from the watchdog timer.
UEFI0082.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) or crash dumps from Operating System to identify the source that caused the watchdog timer reset. Update the firmware or driver for the identified device.
UEFI0082.Message: The system was reset due to a timeout from the watchdog timer.

RAC1156.Description: The server network interface information cannot be received because the iDRAC Service Module is not installed or not running on the server operating system (OS) or collection of the OS data is disabled.
RAC1156.Resolution: Run the command 'racadm get iDRAC.ServiceModule' to check if iDRAC Service Module is installed and running on the server operation system, and the collection of the OS data is enabled.
RAC1156.Message: Unable to display the information about the server network interfaces.

VFL0017.Description: The file system on the specified vFlash media partition could not be recognized. Data on the partition may be corrupted.
VFL0017.Resolution: Format the vFlash SD Card using the 'racadm vflashsd initialize' command and retry the operation.
VFL0017.Message: Unable to perform the vFlash media operation because the vFlash media partition is corrupted.

CTL19.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL19.Message: Abort CC on Error, Copyback, and Load Balance has changed for %1.

RAC0127.Description: Size must be a whole number.
RAC0127.Resolution: Enter a whole number for the size field.
RAC0127.Message: The specified size must be a non-fractional numeric value.

CBL0003.Description: The backplane cable identified in the message is disconnected or no cable is detected.
CBL0003.Resolution: Reconnect or replace the cable identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

GMGR0072.Description: The group job cannot be deleted because the job is running.
GMGR0072.Resolution: Do any one of the following: 1) Wait for the job to run successfully and then delete the job. 2) Stop the job and then delete the job.
GMGR0072.Message: Unable to delete the group job because the job is already running.

RAC0643.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'month' while scheduling a job.
RAC0643.Resolution: Enter a correct numerical value in the following format: Day [1 to 31] of every [1 to 12] month(s). For example, Day 4 of every 11 months. Retry the operation.
RAC0643.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid 'month' value is entered.

RAC939.Description: The request to perform a system profile export or import operation cannot be started because a firmware update operation is already in progress.
RAC939.Resolution: Wait until the update operation is completed or cancel the update operation, and retry.
RAC939.Message: Unable to start the system configuration profile export or import operation.

STOR037.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because one or more input parameters identified in the message are not specified.
STOR037.Resolution: Enter all the required parameters and retry the operation.

BIOS038.Description: The SecureBoot policy cannot be read because of unknown issues.
BIOS038.Resolution: Perform the Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) operation, see the report, and then retry the operation.
BIOS038.Message: Unable to read the SecureBoot policy because of unknown issues.

UEFI0110.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Write DQ/DQS initialization.
UEFI0110.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0110.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

RAC930.Description: Racadm is currently unable to obtain the inlet temperature data. This happens if there is no data populated in the temperature tables or if the instrumentation does not return valid values.
RAC930.Resolution: Wait for the instrumentation to populate the thermal tables. Retry the operation. If the problem persists, contact the service provider.
RAC930.Message: Unable to export the inlet temperature data.

SRV117.Description: The scheduled SupportAssist Collection job was not executed as another SupportAssist job is running on the server.
SRV117.Resolution: The next Auto SupportAssist Collection will be attempted at the subsequent schedule.
SRV117.Message: Unable to execute the scheduled SupportAssist Collection job as another SupportAssist job is running on the server.

SWC0053.Description: The file extension of the Update Package is not supported or the Update Package is invalid.
SWC0053.Resolution: Use a valid Windows-based Update Package with an .exe extension.
SWC0053.Message: File extension is not supported or the Update Package is invalid.

UEFI0126.Description: The primary SD card is in write-protected mode.
UEFI0126.Resolution: No response action is required if this is intentional.
UEFI0126.Message: The primary SD card is in write-protected mode.

RAC966.Description: Any operation involving remote share (CIFS) cannot continue if user name, password, or both are not specified. The u and p options represent the user name and password for the remote share.
RAC966.Resolution: Make sure to specify both user name and password for the remote share, and retry the operation. To view the list of options that can used for the required subcommand, use the racadm help <subcommand> command.
RAC966.Message: Unable to continue with the operation because the user name or password is not specified.

UEFI0189.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Transmit DQS DCC phase.
UEFI0189.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0189.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

PCI3006.Description: Either the BIOS or BMC/iDRAC firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3006.Resolution: Update BIOS, and BMC/iDRAC firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3006.Message: Failed to get Link Tuning or FlexAddress data from iDRAC.

SYS068.Description: Some configuration changes that require system reboot were not applied because the values specified in the input XML file are incorrect.
SYS068.Resolution: Use the GetConfigResults() method to get the configuration job results or export the Lifecycle Log and review the configuration job results to identify the errors. Make changes to the input XML to correct the errors. Retry the import operation.
SYS068.Message: Configuration changes that require system reboot were not applied.

RAC1040.Description: The requested RAID storage operation was successfully accepted and now must be applied by creating a RAID storage configuration job.
RAC1040.Resolution: To apply the configuration operation, create a configuration job, and then restart the server. To create the required commit and reboot jobs, run the jobqueue command. For more information about the jobqueue command, enter the RACADM command "racadm help jobqueue".
RAC1040.Message: Successfully accepted the RAID storage configuration operation. The change is in pending state.

HWC3002.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-insert.

BAR065.Description: Collecting the Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration and copying it into the server profile backup file.
BAR065.Message: Collecting Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration.

MEM9003.Description: A correctable error was detected in propagation of signals between processor and memory through the Intel SMI 2 memory interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9003.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your services provider.
MEM9003.Message: Intel SMI 2 Memory interconnect %1 has a correctable error.

SUP0527.Description: The Update Package does not have this system in the supported platform list.
SUP0527.Resolution: Download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0527.Message: The Update Package is not supported for this system.

RDU8523.Description: The CMC identified in the message was reset by other CMC. This occurs during failover and CMC firmware update to the standby CMC.

RAC0116.Description: The entered IPv6 address does not conform to the addressing standard or the supported IPv6 address range.
RAC0116.Resolution: Enter a valid Destination IPv6 Address.

UEFI0166.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because the number of allowable Target Address Decode (TAD) rules exceeded during memory initialization.
UEFI0166.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0166.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

BAR046.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) is preparing to switch over to the recently loaded firmware. During this switch over, the connection to iDRAC is lost. The server will startup after iDRAC restarts.
BAR046.Message: Host System will power up approximately 10 minutes after Integrated Remote Access Controller Restore (iDRAC).

CMC8603.Description: CMC cannot read the information about the FRU, because of an internal issue with the CMC and the server. Some information such as model number may not be reported. The server may not power up if the server planar FRU cannot be read.
CMC8603.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the server. The Chassis Management Controller will retry the read operation of the FRU information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8603.Message: Unable to read the FRU information from the server %1, status %2.

SWC8614.Description: The setting identified in the message is not recognized because the profile is not in a usable format or contains settings that are no longer supported.
SWC8614.Resolution: Recreate the profile or use a different profile.
SWC8614.Message: Legacy profile setting: %1 is not recognized.

UEFI0046.Description: An issue in observed in the previous invocation of TXT SINIT Authenticated Code Module (ACM) because the TXT information stored in the TPM chip may be corrupted.
UEFI0046.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the BIOS firmware. 2) Go to System Setup > System Security page, click the "Clear" option under TPM command. Restart the system, go to System Setup > System Security page, click the "Activate" option under TPM command, and then enable TXT.
UEFI0046.Message: An issue is observed in the previous invocation of TXT SINIT Authenticated Code Module (ACM) because the TXT information stored in the TPM chip may be corrupted.

CMC8557.Description: The code number specified in the message is displayed after a firmware error occurs before a failover .
CMC8557.Message: The system health failover is requested. Code %1.

RFM1034.Description: The SD card is not detected or not installed.
RFM1034.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
RFM1034.Message: Media not present for Removable Flash Media.

PWR1005.Description: To avoid exceeding the user defined capacity, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1005.Resolution: If unintended, review system configuration changes and power policy.
PWR1005.Message: The system performance degraded because of user-defined power capacity has changed.

SWC8621.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to process inventory data from the server slot identified in the message. This can happen if there is no free temporary storage in CMC.
SWC8621.Resolution: Restart the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). To restart the CMC, start an SSH session to the CMC and enter the command "racadm racreset". Wait for the CMC to finish restarting and check if the inventory data is collected. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8621.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to process inventory data from the server in slot %1.

BAR022.Description: The host system is powering up to perform component firmware and configuration restoration.
BAR022.Message: System powering up to perform component updates.

PCI1344.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1344.Message: An I/O channel check error was detected.

FAN0000.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.
FAN0000.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan at the next scheduled service window. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0000.Message: Fan %1 RPM is less than the lower warning threshold.

SYS175.Description: Selective Export / Import could not find any matches for the FQDDs specified.
SYS175.Resolution: Make sure that only valid FQDDs are entered as input to the Target parameter, and then retry the operation.
SYS175.Message: Unable to find a device configuration for the FQDD entered.

RAC1003.Description: The smart card certificate revocation list (CRL) cannot be enabled, because the object SmartCardLogonEnable is disabled.
RAC1003.Resolution: Enable the object SmartCardLogonEnable using "racadm set iDRAC.SmartCard.SmartCardLogonEnable <1 | Enabled>", and retry the operation.
RAC1003.Message: The smart card certificate revocation list (CRL) cannot be enabled.

UEFI0273.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv4 server is invalid.
UEFI0273.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reconfigure the DHCPv4 server root path option, and note that server name must be specified. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable Target Info via DHCP and configure the parameters manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0273.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv4 server is invalid.

PWR8594.Description: The available power is not sufficient to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode feature.
PWR8594.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode feature. Go to, the Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis.
PWR8594.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to set the Enhanced Cooling Mode because the requested power %1 AC Watt is more than available power %2 AC Watt.

UEFI0035.Description: The BIOS passwords are disabled because the PWRD_EN jumper is removed from the system board.
UEFI0035.Resolution: To enable the BIOS passwords, install the PWRD_EN jumper.
UEFI0035.Message: The BIOS passwords are disabled because the PWRD_EN jumper is removed from the system board.

SRV024.Description: The OS and Application Data cannot be collected because the OS Collector is not installed on the iDRAC.
SRV024.Resolution: Install OS Collector on the iDRAC and retry the operation. To install the OS Collector using the iDRAC Web UI, get the latest OS Collector update package and then select the Update and Rollback link from the iDRAC Web UI home page and upload the install package.
SRV024.Message: Unable to collect OS and Application Data because the OS Collector is not installed on the iDRAC.

SYS423.Description: The test event cannot be sent because there are no subscriptions.
SYS423.Resolution: Create a subscription using HTTP POST operation to the URI of the subscription resource.
SYS423.Message: Unable to send the test event because there are no subscriptions.

CTL63.Description: The controller is unable to retrieve storage configuration saved during last shut down. This can generally happen if some configured physical disks are removed from the system when the system was shutdown.
CTL63.Resolution: Shut down the system. Re-insert the removed physical disks and re-start the system.
CTL63.Message: Previous configuration was found completely missing during boot time on %1.

VFL1017.Message: Media is present for Removable Flash Media %1.

STOR063.Description: In order to prevent data loss, the system has prevented the assignment of a Virtual Disk to multiple Virtual Adapters because the clustered assignment mode is not enabled.
STOR063.Resolution: Enable clustered assignment mode or unassign the virtual disk from the Virtual Adapter it is currently assigned to and retry the operation.
STOR063.Message: Unable to assign the specified virtual disk to multiple Virtual Adapters in single assignment mode.

FC017.Description: An internal error occurred in iDRAC and the operation cannot continue. An iDRAC reset is required to recover from the error.
FC017.Resolution: Disconnect the AC power source from the system, reconnect the power source, and retry the operation.
FC017.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an internal error in iDRAC.

SEC0040.Description: Operating system generated critical stop IPMI event. (Sensor type code = 20H).
SEC0040.Resolution: Check video and operating system logs for additional information.
SEC0040.Message: A critical stop occurred during OS load.

CMC8569.Description: The server slot specified in the message is enabled for DVD drive mapping. The DVD drive can be mapped to this server slot.
CMC8569.Message: The server slot %1 is enabled for DVD drive mapping.

ISM0017.Description: The BMC watchdog auto-recovery action is changed from the original action identified in the message to the new action identified in the message.
ISM0017.Message: The BMC watchdog auto-recovery action is changed from %1 to %2.

NIC101.Description: The transition from network link not started (down) to network link started (up) has been detected on the NIC controller port identified in the message.
NIC101.Message: The %1 Port %2 network link is started.

BAR013.Description: The request to shut the Host system down did not complete successfully.
BAR013.Resolution: Restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) and retry the operation.

UEFI0148.Description: The SAS cable for the primary SAS expander daughter card is missing or misconfigured.
UEFI0148.Resolution: Check the cable configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0148.Message: The SAS cable %1 for the primary SAS expander daughter card is missing or misconfigured.

UEFI0013.Description: A CPU floating point error (type 0x10) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0013.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0013.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x10: Floating Point Error (Software).

SWC1905.Description: RAC Virtual Console configuration has been changed.
SWC1905.Message: RAC Virtual Console configuration has been changed.

SEL1205.Message: The unknown system hardware failure was corrected.

RAC0752.Description: The value for information or warning threshold should not be greater than upper critical threshold value.
RAC0752.Resolution: Enter a threshold value that is lower than the upper warning or critical threshold values and retry the operation.
RAC0752.Message: The threshold value entered is greater than the upper warning or critical threshold.

CTL98.Description: The security key provided as input has been assigned to the controller identified in the message.

UEFI0219.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Read Timing Centering 2D Training phase.
UEFI0219.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0219.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SWC1909.Description: The privilege level of the iDRAC User ID indicated in the message has been changed.
SWC1909.Message: User ID %1 RAC Privilege has been changed.

SWC0081.Description: Dell Integrated Data Center mode enabled.

PSU0023.Message: Power supply %1 operating at 110 volts has been acknowledged by user.

SYS011.Description: A configuration job is scheduled to apply pending set attribute operations. Set operations are not allowed if there is an existing configuration job for a component.
SYS011.Resolution: Wait for the scheduled job to complete or delete the configuration jobs before attempting more set attribute operations.
SYS011.Message: Pending configuration values are already committed, unable to perform another set operation.

UEFI0044.Description: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the processor does not support TXT.
UEFI0044.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the motherboard chipset does not support TXT.

LC048.Description: The value provided to set the attribute identified in the message is invalid.
LC048.Resolution: For more information on the valid values, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation. Retry the operation with a valid value for the IPChangeNotifyPS attribute.

PDR24.Description: A disk has received a SMART alert (predictive failure) due to test conditions.
PDR24.Message: Failure prediction threshold exceeded on %1 due to test. No action needed.

SEL1502.Description: An action or failure has taken place that degrades CMC redundancy. This includes firmware mismatch between CMC's and a CMC missing SD card.
SEL1502.Resolution: Chassis management controller (CMC) redundancy is degraded.
SEL1502.Message: Chassis management controller (CMC) redundancy is degraded.

HWC7006.Description: Server <number> health changed to a non-recoverable state from a less severe state.
HWC7006.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7006.Message: Server %1 health changed to a non-recoverable state from a less severe state.

DIS102.Description: The AutoConfig configuration import operation could not be started, because the AutoConfig .xml file is not available in the sharename or location specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS102.Resolution: Update the sharename or location in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC, make sure the AutoConfig import file is available, and then retry the operation.
DIS102.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig import operation, because the AutoConfig import file is not available.

BAR006.Description: The system profile backup file is being finalized and closed.

GMGR0000.Description: The iDRAC Group Manager feature is disabled. iDRAC will no longer be able to create or join iDRAC local groups. However, all the earlier settings of Group Manager are preserved. To enable the Group Manager, log in to iDRAC. On the Dashboard page, from the Open Group Manager menu, select Enable Group Manager.
GMGR0000.Message: The iDRAC Group Manager feature is disabled.

SYS057.Description: The current system configuration is being collected and the Server Configuration Profile is being generated.

PWR8540.Description: The interval for remote logging of power information is set to the value identified in the message.
PWR8540.Message: Power Remote Logging Interval set to %1.

SWC0025.Description: The operation completed successfully, however the system is unable to automatically shut down.
SWC0025.Resolution: Manually shut down the system. For more information about the failure, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0025.Message: The operation completed successfully, however the system is unable to automatically shut down.

CMC8528.Description: CMC is unable to obtain the link tuning or flex address information for the newly installed hardware (server, Input Output Module, or Mezzanine card), or is unable to send the link tuning or flex address information to iDRAC.
CMC8528.Resolution: Make sure that the currently installed CMC firmware is the latest. Otherwise, update the CMC with the latest CMC firmware and retry the operation.
CMC8528.Message: Unable to obtain or send link tuning or flex address data to server-%1.

SYS162.Description: The server will be turned on to enter UEFI System Services Manager (SSM). The storage-related erase operations selected, if any, will be processed by SSM.
SYS162.Message: Turning on the server to perform System Erase tasks.

CMC8550.Description: If the chassis health status changes, new status is logged. The possible states are Invalid, Other, Unknown, Healthy, Non-critical, Critical, and Non-recoverable.

PDR19.Description: A disk on the specified controller has received a SMART alert (predictive failure) indicating that the disk is likely to fail in the near future.
PDR19.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk causes the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.

UEFI0021.Description: The Lifecycle Controller feature is disabled. The feature was disabled because of one of the following conditions: 1) The feature was disabled manually using the F2 System Setup utility or through an iDRAC interface, 2) BIOS encountered an issue starting the feature and automatically disabled it.
UEFI0021.Resolution: To enable the Lifecycle Controller (LC) feature using F2 System Setup, select the iDRAC Settings > Lifecycle Controller and then select Enabled. If LC becomes disabled automatically, update the Lifecycle Controller firmware or apply the Lifecycle Controller Repair Package.
UEFI0021.Message: The Lifecycle Controller feature is disabled.

RAC081.Description: The Export File operation cannot be started because an export operation is already in progress.
RAC081.Resolution: Wait till the current process is completed and retry the operation.
RAC081.Message: Unable to start the Export File operation because an export operation is already in progress.

SWC8518.Description: Unable to modify the password of the User identified in the message.
SWC8518.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name and password given are valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8518.Message: Unable to modify password of User %1: %2-%3

BAR089.Description: A problem has been detected with the installation of the Unified Server Configurator (USC). This needs to be corrected before a valid Backup file can be created.
BAR089.Resolution: Obtain the Dell update package for the Unified Server Configurator and apply it. Then perform a Backup operation to save this data, for later restore.
BAR089.Message: Lifecycle Controller needs to be updated.

RAC1194.Description: The server firmware is up to date and matches the catalog definitions.
RAC1194.Message: Successfully compared the firmware versions on the server to the versions defined in the specified catalog. The server firmware is up to date and matches the catalog definitions.

FC018.Description: The configuration operation cannot be started because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.
FC018.Resolution: Make sure that the Lockdown.1#SystemLockdown attribute is set to Disabled in the DCIM_iDracCardEnumeration class by running the WS-Man get command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation.
FC018.Message: Unable to start the configuration operation because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.

CTL67.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL67.Message: Attempted to import Virtual Disk with missing span on %1.

JCP018.Description: A new job cannot be created until the existing Export job is completed or the job is deleted. There can only be one Export Server Profile job running at a time.
JCP018.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation after the Export Server Profile job is completed. 2) Delete the scheduled Export job and retry the operation.
JCP018.Message: Cannot create new jobs until the existing Export job is completed or the job is cancelled.

LIC014.Description: An attempt to lock the License Manager database for Lifecycle Controller backup or restore occurred when the License Manager database was already locked. This may occur when two or more users attempt to do a backup or restore operation simultaneously.
LIC014.Resolution: Repeat the Lifecycle Controller backup or restore operation.
LIC014.Message: Multiple backup or restore operations have been simultaneously attempted on the License Manager database.

PST0141.Description: Quick Path Interconnect failed during system POST. Reboot the system. If problem persists, remove input power and reseat processors. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.
PST0141.Resolution: Reboot the system. If problem persists, remove input power and reseat processors.

OSE1006.Description: The system has successfully booted to diagnostics.

BAR018.Description: A system profile backup file validation request has completed.

RAC025.Description: Unable to set static values for DNS1 or DNS2 when DNS from DHCP is Enabled.
RAC025.Resolution: Disable DNS from DHCP to set values for DNS1 or DNS2.
RAC025.Message: Unable to set values for DNS1 or DNS2 attributes because DNS from DHCP is Enabled.

UEFI0237.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - Memory Test phase.
UEFI0237.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0237.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SRV049.Description: There is no cached copy of OS and Application data in the iDRAC flash storage.
SRV049.Resolution: Collect the OS and Application Data using the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service and then retry the operation.
SRV049.Message: Cached OS and Application Data is not available in the iDRAC.

SUP0506.Description: The catalog file in the selected repository is corrupt or compressed in an unsupported format.
SUP0506.Resolution: Select a repository with a valid catalog file, and retry the operation.
SUP0506.Message: Unable to decompress the catalog file.

UEFI0296.Description: The Boot Guard detected a corrupted BIOS in the server. A BIOS recovery process is automatically started.
UEFI0296.Message: The Boot Guard detected a corrupted BIOS in the server.

RED040.Description: The job identified in the message was created by an Automatic Server Profile Backup, Automatic Update, or other recurring operation.
RED040.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 created a job %2.

PWR8549.Description: The requested chassis shutdown operation did not complete successfully.
PWR8549.Message: Chassis shutdown did not complete successfully.

STOR038.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because one or more input parameters identified in the message are not valid.
STOR038.Resolution: Specify a valid value for identified parameter.

RAC1109.Description: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Share type was entered.
RAC1109.Resolution: Enter an appropriate Share location of the following types: FTP, NFS, or CIFS. For more information, run the "racadm help update" command.
RAC1109.Message: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Share type is entered.

PWR8527.Description: Server slot power priorities were changed. Power to servers is being reallocated.
PWR8527.Message: Server slot power priorities changed - reallocating power.

PWR2200.Message: The system is in the ON state.

JCP006.Description: One or more of the specified values for creating a job are invalid or an internal error has occurred when scheduling the job.
JCP006.Resolution: Use the correct value for the job attribute and retry the operation.

ASR0000.Description: The operating system or potentially an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC) within the timeout period.
ASR0000.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.

MEM9001.Description: The memory interconnect is functioning normally.

BAR014.Description: Unable to access the server profile Backup file and the operation cannot continue. This can be due to a media error or loss of connectivity.
BAR014.Resolution: If using vFlash media replace media and try again. If a network share, make sure there is connectivity to and existence of the destination.
BAR014.Message: Backup file or partition access error.

BIOS017.Description: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration.
BIOS017.Resolution: Remove AC power from system and after restoring AC power, retry the operation.
BIOS017.Message: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration

SWC0274.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0274.Resolution: Enter the same command with a legal value to the object.
SWC0274.Message: Invalid syntax. An object value must be specified.

BAR092.Description: The attempt to disconnect from the specified NFS location was not successful.
BAR092.Resolution: If this happens on a backup request, restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller and try the operation again. If this is a restore request the Integrated Remote Access will be restarted during the execution of the request. Only restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller if it does not restart on its own.

SYS299.Description: The compressed file cannot be opened because there is a password entered for the ZipPassword attribute on the iDRAC, while no password is used to protect the compressed file.
SYS299.Resolution: Make sure that the password entered for ZipPassword attribute on the iDRAC is same the password used to encrypt the compressed file.
SYS299.Message: Unable to open the compressed file because the ZipPassword attribute is set and no password is used for protecting the compressed file.

SWU8662.Description: The IOA firmware cannot be updated because of an issue in the network communication session between CMC and IOA.
SWU8662.Resolution: Power-cycle the IOA and if the firmware version is unchanged, retry the firmware update operation.
SWU8662.Message: Unable to update the I/O Aggregator (IOA) firmware because of an issue in the network communication session between CMC and IOA in slot %1.

PST0006.Description: System BIOS has started initialization multiprocessor support.

NIC007.Description: A configuration job already exists for the specified target. No further configuration operation is allowed until the existing job completes or the job is cancelled.
NIC007.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Wait for the existing configuration job to complete and retry the operation, 2) To continue with a configuration change, cancel the existing job and retry the operation.
NIC007.Message: A configuration job already exists, Cannot create another configuration job on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled

SWC0119.Description: The syntax of the sslcertview command is invalid.
SWC0119.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertview subcommand.
SWC0119.Message: Invalid certificate type specified with -t option.

SYS065.Description: An internal error occurred opening the input configuration XML file. An iDRAC reset is required.
SYS065.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
SYS065.Message: Input file for import configuration operation cannot be found or opened.

SEL1504.Description: There is not enough available power for two CMC's to operate.
SEL1504.Resolution: Check overall power consumption and power status.
SEL1504.Message: The chassis management controller (CMC) is not redundant. Insufficient resources to maintain normal operations.

NIC006.Description: A configuration job already exists for the specified target. No further configuration operation is allowed until the existing job completes or the job is cancelled.
NIC006.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Wait for the existing configuration job to complete and retry the operation, 2) To continue with a configuration change, cancel the existing job and retry the operation.
NIC006.Message: A configuration job already exists, Cannot set attribute on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled

CTL85.Description: The controller identified in the message experienced a PCIe training error and is operating at less than full bandwidth. Until this issue is resolved, a reduction in the storage performance is expected.
CTL85.Resolution: Perform a Powercycle operation on the Chassis. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CTL85.Message: %1 is operating at less than optimal bandwidth.

UEFI0030.Description: A keyboard device is not connected to the system.
UEFI0030.Resolution: Connect a keyboard device to the system.
UEFI0030.Message: A keyboard device is not connected to the system.

SYS177.Description: There was an issue retrieving Hardware data from the iDRAC internal storage. This may be because Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled and has never executed or the iDRAC Remote Services API status may not be in the Ready state.
SYS177.Resolution: Make sure the Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) is enabled and has run at least once before retrying this operation. For remote web services API access, make sure the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status before trying this operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
SYS177.Message: There was an issue retrieving Hardware data.

RAC929.Description: The category or subcategory specified is incorrect. The recurrence interval is applicable only to the TMPS subcategory and system category.
RAC929.Resolution: See the command help text, for a list of valid categories.

FC102.Description: The FC controller port link identified in the message is not functioning either because the FC cable is not connected or the FC device is not functioning.
FC102.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure that the FC port is enabled. 2) Make sure the Activity/Speed LEDs are lit if the physical port has LEDs. 3) Check the FC cable and FC cable connections for proper installation. 4) Check that the attached FC switch is functioning.
FC102.Message: The %1 port %2 link is not functioning either because the FC cable is not connected or the FC device is not functioning.

BAR073.Description: The operation to delete the vFlash backup partition did not complete successfully.
BAR073.Resolution: Enable and initialize the vFlash media and retry the export. If the error continues, try a new vFlash media or use the network share option(s).
BAR073.Message: Delete of vFlash Backup partition unsuccessful.

PWR8667.Description: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is resetting iKVM to its default settings.
PWR8667.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is resetting iKVM to its default settings.

LIC903.Description: One or more parameters were not specified for the invoked method.
LIC903.Resolution: To provide the correct parameters, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

UEFI0220.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write Voltage Training phase.
UEFI0220.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0220.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

UEFI0309.Description: The Baseboard UPI B cable is not connected.
UEFI0309.Resolution: Connect the Baseboard UPI B cable. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0309.Message: The Baseboard UPI B cable is not connected.

DH004.Resolution: Boot the OS. If the error persists, contact technical support.
DH004.Message: iDRAC does not have sufficient free resources to generate keys.

RAC0773.Description: The BIOS configuration settings cannot be modified because a BIOS configuration job is already running.
RAC0773.Resolution: Wait till the current BIOS configuration job is completed, and then retry the operation. To view the status of a job, on the iDRAC Settings page, click Job Queue.
RAC0773.Message: Unable to modify the BIOS configuration settings because a BIOS configuration job is already running.

RAC1190.Description: Unable to configure the provisioning server.
RAC1190.Message: Unable to configure the Provisioning Server feature settings. The required options are either invalid or not provided.

FC005.Description: The number of AttributeName and AttributeValue array elements are not equal.
FC005.Resolution: Provide equal number of array elements for AttributeName and AttributeValue parameters. For more information about input parameters, see FC HBA Profile specification.
FC005.Message: The number of AttributeName array elements does not match the AttributeValue array element count.

DIS119.Description: The AutoConfig operation Timeout value is set to the duration as identified in the message.
DIS119.Message: The AutoConfig operation Timeout value is set to %1 minutes.

SWC8505.Description: The description for the Profile identified in the message was edited.

PCI1321.Description: A high-severity issue is detected in the component identified in the message.
PCI1321.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the component identified in the message, and then monitor the log for a re-occurrence of the issue. If the issue persists, and occurs during server startup, update the component firmware. If the issue persists and occurs during OS runtime, restart the server and update the OS drivers for the component identified in the message.
PCI1321.Message: A high-severity issue is detected in a component of the bus %1, device 0, function %2.

SRV106.Description: The Debug Logs are excluded from the SupportAssist collection because Collection data is being filtered for personally identifiable information.
SRV106.Message: The Debug Logs are excluded from the SupportAssist collection because the Collection data is being filtered for personally identifiable information.

BIOS025.Description: The status of the password is Locked in BIOS and must be set to Unlocked for the operation to succeed.
BIOS025.Resolution: Change BIOS password status in the BIOS setup from Locked to Unlocked and retry the operation.
BIOS025.Message: Unable set the BIOS password as the BIOS password status is locked.

PSU0910.Description: The system did not respond correctly to a power down request.
PSU0910.Message: Soft power control failure detected on power unit %1.

PST0143.Description: TXT boot failed. This could be related to memory errors or an error with the system TXT configuration. A socketed TPM module may have been removed. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.
PST0143.Resolution: Check TPM presence. Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PST0143.Message: Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) fatal error.

VDR59.Description: This alert message occurs if virtual disk security has failed.

CMC003.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the parameter identified in the message is missing.
CMC003.Resolution: Enter the missing parameter and retry the operation. For information about the parameters, see the CMC Profile document available on the support site.
CMC003.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the parameter %1 is missing.

SWC0309.Description: The platform does not support the specified functionality of fwupdate.
SWC0309.Message: The -p option is not supported with the interface being used.

STOR0505.Description: Unable to delete the existing virtual disks for unknown reasons.
STOR0505.Resolution: Exit the RAID Configuration wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists do the following: 1) Reboot the system. 2) Press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller. 3) Retry the operation.

RAC1070.Description: The maximum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is greater than or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.
RAC1070.Resolution: Check the maximum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the maximum critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1070.Message: Unable to set the maximum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.

SRV116.Description: The operation cannot be started because the parameter specified in the message is not supported by the iDRAC 9.0 and later versions.
SRV116.Resolution: Make sure that the parameter is supported by iDRAC and retry the operation. For more informaition, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SRV116.Message: Unable to start the operation because the parameter %1 entered is not supported by the iDRAC 9.0 and later versions.

SWC0076.Description: Lifecycle Controller detected that the iDRAC internal storage partitions identified in the message were not made available by BIOS during the boot process.
SWC0076.Resolution: No response action required. If the issue occurs consistently during system startup, restart the iDRAC and then restart the system. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC0076.Message: The following iDRAC internal storage partitions present in the system were not mounted during the system startup: %1.

LC045.Description: The CreateConfigJob operation is currently running. The current operation and system restart must complete before the operation can be attempted again.
LC045.Resolution: Wait for the CreateConfigJob operation that is currently running to complete before requesting another operation.
LC045.Message: An instance of CreateConfigJob is already running.

RAC053.Description: One or more attributes being set are dependent on OS to iDRAC pass-through being enabled.
RAC053.Resolution: Enable OS to iDRAC pass-through and retry the previous command.
RAC053.Message: OS to iDRAC pass-through is disabled.

TMP0138.Description: Disabling the C1E state in servers with processors that have their Thermal Design Power (TDP) value set to equal to or greater than 155 Watt results in increased fan speed during high CPU workloads.
TMP0138.Message: The C1 Enhance (C1E) state is disabled in the server. Increased fan speeds can be expected during high CPU workload.

PWR8518.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned on.
PWR8518.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned on.

SWC0214.Message: Makes a remote ISO image available to the server

PST0091.Description: A problem was detected in Memory Reference Code (MRC). The next logged message contains more specific details for the detected issue.
PST0091.Resolution: Review the next logged message for the recommended response action to resolve the problem.
PST0091.Message: A problem was detected in Memory Reference Code (MRC).

UEFI0011.Description: A CPU general protection (type 0x0D) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0011.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

RAC976.Description: The configuration XML file export operation was initiated.
RAC976.Resolution: Use the racadm jobqueue view i <Job ID> command to view the status of the operation.
RAC976.Message: Export configuration XML file operation initiated.

SWC4005.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between iDRAC in slot %1 and CMC.

SYS066.Description: No iDRAC, System, or Lifecycle Controller configuration changes were applied. The settings specified in the system configuration XML input file match the current configuration for these components.
SYS066.Message: No changes detected for iDRAC, System, or Lifecycle Controller configuration.

PWR222.Description: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is already enabled.
PWR222.Message: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is already enabled.

CMC8610.Description: The read operation cannot be done because the Field Replaceable Unit (FRU) is not functioning on the sled identified in the message.
CMC8610.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation. 1) Reset iDRAC on the sled identified in the message or reseat the sled. 2) Reset Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and wait few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.Reset iDRAC using racadm racreset -m server-nReset CMC using racadm racreset. From GUI, navigate to Chassis Overview->Troubleshooting Reset CMC using Reset/Failover CMC. Reset iDRAC using iDRAC reset from dropdown.
CMC8610.Message: Unable to read because the Field Replaceable Unit (FRU) is not functioning on the sled %1.

UEFI0201.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Write Training phase.
UEFI0201.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0201.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

UEFI0041.Description: Unable to turn on the TXT feature because the Virtualization Technology (VT) feature is not enabled on the processor.
UEFI0041.Resolution: From System Setup, enable VT, and then enable TXT. If the issue persists, update the system BIOS firmware.
UEFI0041.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the Virtualization Technology (VT) feature is not enabled on the processor.

SRV013.Description: Unable to retrieve Storage Controller Logs because no storage controllers are detected in the server.
SRV013.Resolution: Make sure that at least one storage controller is present in the server, and then retry the operation.
SRV013.Message: Unable to retrieve Storage Controller Logs because no storage controllers are detected in the server.

RAC1046.Description: Unable to view the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.
RAC1046.Resolution: Configure the Automatic Update feature by running the RACADM command "racadm autoupdatescheduler create" with the desired option settings.
RAC1046.Message: Unable to view the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.

SYS196.Description: The OEM ID module installation process tried to apply all settings and branding information, but had issues during installation.
SYS196.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log report to analyze the issue. Review settings and branding information that the ID module configured, resolve the issue, and then retry the installation process.
SYS196.Message: The OEM ID module is installed but with some errors. %1

LC049.Description: The value provided to set the attribute identified in the message is invalid.
LC049.Resolution: For more information on the valid values, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation. Retry the operation with a valid value for the VirtualAddressManagement attribute.

SWC0279.Description: The group is not indexed and does not require an index to be specified.
SWC0279.Resolution: Enter the command without the index.
SWC0279.Message: The specified group is not indexed and does not support -i.

UEFI0174.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.
UEFI0174.Resolution: Quad Rank and Octal Rank DIMM modules cannot be mixed on a channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0174.Message: A Quad Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after an Octal Rank DIMM module.

ISM0034.Description: The Auto Update feature successfully completed the task on the Host OS, where the server operating system (OS) user is as identified in the message.
ISM0034.Message: The Auto Update feature successfully %1 the iDRAC Service Module to version %2, where the server operating system (OS) user is %3.

SWC1928.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-write mode.
SWC1928.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-write mode.

PSUA0016.Description: The supply has been removed or has failed.
PSUA0016.Resolution: Install the power supply if needed.

GMGR0052.Description: The role of current iDRAC Group Manager cannot be determined because of an internal error.
GMGR0052.Resolution: Wait for some time and try again, Do the following if issue persists: 1) Disable and then enable the Group Manager by using the iDRAC home page. 2) Make sure that network connections are correct. 3) Restart the iDRAC. If the issue still persists, contact your service provider.
GMGR0052.Message: Unable to determine the current iDRAC Group Manager role because of an internal error.

UEFI0161.Description: An unsupported DIMM population has been detected on memory slots identified by this message.
UEFI0161.Resolution: Remove all unsupported DIMM modules from the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0161.Message: An unsupported DIMM population has been detected on memory slots: %1.

SWC0235.Description: All public keys stored on the iDRAC have been deleted.

TMP8500.Description: The temperature of the I/O Module identified in the message has increased beyond the operational range. Thermal protection shut down the I/O Module. Factors external to the I/O Module may have caused this situation.
TMP8500.Resolution: Check the chassis event log for fan issues and fix any issues present. If no fan issues are detected, check chassis ambient temperature and make sure the temperature is within operating range. Utilize the RACADM command "racadm getsensorinfo" to check the chassis ambient temperature.
TMP8500.Message: I/O Module %1 temperature exceeded operating range.

GMGR0074.Description: The requested Group Manager Configuration operation is successfully completed.
GMGR0074.Resolution: Wait for 60 seconds before performing another Group Manager operation.
GMGR0074.Message: The requested Group Manager Configuration operation is successfully completed.

IOV1003.Description: One or more parameters identified in the message required for the method are missing.
IOV1003.Resolution: Refer to the DCIM Chassis PCI Management Profile document and provide the required parameter.

SYS255.Description: The file cannot be transferred because a verify certificate value is not entered, or the entered value is not supported.
SYS255.Resolution: Make sure that the correct verify certificate value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS255.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported verify certificate value.

HWC0017.Description: Cannot start Lifecycle Controller because Lifecycle Controller is unable to communicate with iDRAC because of internal issues.
HWC0017.Resolution: Issue is because of an internal error. To resolve the issue:1) Turn off the server and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for 10 seconds, reconnect the power cord, turn on the server, and retry starting Lifecycle Controller by pressing F10 when the company logo is displayed. 3) If the issue persists, update iDRAC firmware to the latest version, and then retry the operation. Else, contact your service provider.
HWC0017.Message: Unable to start Lifecycle Controller because Lifecycle Controller cannot communicate with iDRAC, because of internal issues %1.

DIS003.Description: Auto Discovery process will try to connect to a Provisioning Server over the next 24 hours.

ENC6.Description: The controller is unable to communicate with an enclosure. There are several reasons for communication loss. For example, there may be a bad or loose cable. An unusual amount of I/O may also interrupt communication with the enclosure. In addition, communication loss may be caused by software, hardware, or firmware problems, bad or failed power supplies, and enclosure shutdown.
ENC6.Resolution: Check for problems with the cables. See the Cables attached correctly section for more information on checking the cables. You should also check to see if the enclosure has degraded or failed components. To do this, select the enclosure object in the tree view and click the Health subtab. The Health subtab displays the status of the enclosure components. Verify that the controller has the supported driver and firmware versions installed and that each Enclosure Management Modules (EMMs) are running the same version of supported firmware.

NIC500.Description: The values of IP Address is not allowed to change if DHCP is enabled.
NIC500.Resolution: Disable DHCP and then modify the value.
NIC500.Message: The requested object is not allowed to be configured if DHCP is enabled.

OSD21.Description: Booting to ISO has failed. Either BIOS was unable to boot to the ISO image or the provider did not get a response in 5 minutes from BIOS on successful boot to ISO image.
OSD21.Resolution: 1) Make sure that a POST error did not result in user interaction (Press F1 to continue or F2 to run BIOS setup). 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD21.Message: Unable to boot to ISO image.

ASR8500.Description: Watchdog timer is disabled. The watchdog timer is an internal mechanism used to monitor the health of the Chassis Management Controller. The watchdog timer could be disabled as part of a troubleshooting operation and can be enabled by restarting the Chassis Management Controller.

UEFI0091.Description: A Quad-Rank (QR) DIMM is installed on the memory slot identified in the message. QR DIMMs should be installed on the first DIMM slot in a channel if there is only one QR DIMM in the channel. QR DIMMs cannot be installed on the third slot of the channel.
UEFI0091.Resolution: Install the QR DIMM in the correct channel. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0091.Message: A Quad-Rank (QR) DIMM is installed on memory slot: %1. QR DIMMs should be installed on the first DIMM slot in a channel if there is only one QR DIMM in the channel. QR DIMMs cannot be installed on the third slot of the channel.

JCP010.Description: The method invoked was successfully completed.

PSU8512.Description: The firmware update operation for the PSU identified in the message did not complete, because of internal communication errors.
PSU8512.Resolution: Retry the firmware update operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8512.Message: Unable to update the firmware for the PSU in slot %1. Error=0x%2 (%3)

CTL16.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL16.Message: None of the %1 properties are set.

RED088.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because an update operation is already in progress.
RED088.Resolution: Wait until the current update operation is completed, and then retry the operation.
RED088.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware because an update operation is already in progress.

DIS013.Description: Default client certificate is being used. Auto Discovery client is using this certificate for the SSL connection with the Provisioning Server.
DIS013.Message: Auto Discovery client using default client certificate.

UEFI0028.Description: The iDRAC is not responding after a recovery system reset was performed. BIOS will continue POST startup with iDRAC in a non functional state.
UEFI0028.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0028.Message: iDRAC is not responding after a recovery system reset was performed.

SWC1949.Description: The Quick Sync feature is set to automatically disable after a specified inactivity time.
SWC1949.Message: The Quick Sync inactivity timeout feature is enabled.

PDR108.Description: The physical disk identified in the message that had been assigned as a hot spare has been unassigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically by the storage management software. When one of the disks in a virtual disk fails, data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, The hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. In this situation, assigning a new hot spare to maintain data protection in recommended.
PDR108.Resolution: No response action is required. Assigning a new global hot spare is recommended.
PDR108.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is unassigned as a global hot spare.

PCI1312.Message: An EISA fail-safe time-out was detected.

RAC0601.Description: The server encountered an unexpected condition. This may be due to invalid JavaScript Object Notation.
RAC0601.Resolution: Wait for few minutes and refresh the page. If the problem persists, contact service provider.
RAC0601.Message: Unable to retrieve alert recurrence information.

VF022.Description: The size specified is lower than the minimum allowed for a partition.

VDR21.Description: This message is generated after a consistency check completes on a virtual disk.

MEM1206.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed.
MEM1206.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>.
MEM1206.Message: Memory mirror redundancy is degraded. Check memory device at location %1.

DIS014.Description: Auto Discovery client is using the customer provided Certificate Authority certificate to authenticate the Provisioning Server for the SSL connection.
DIS014.Message: Auto Discovery client using customer provided CA certificate to authenticate Provisioning Server.

GMGR0054.Description: The operation cannot be started by opening the Group Manager because either the primary or secondary servers are unavailable.
GMGR0054.Resolution: Do any one of the following: 1) Wait 10 minutes and retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, delete the existing group and create a new group.
GMGR0054.Message: Unable to start the operation by opening the Group Manager because either the primary or secondary servers are unavailable.

JCP024.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage due to use by another application or operation. This job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.
JCP024.Resolution: Wait for current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is: 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs.
JCP024.Message: Lifecycle Controller is in use. This job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.

RAC952.Description: The allocated size for the Lifecycle Log entries has reached its maximum limit, and no further work notes can be added to the Lifecycle Log.
RAC952.Message: There is no free space to add new work notes to the Lifecycle Log.

UEFI0117.Description: Card identification signature is not present on Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card 1.
UEFI0117.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Check the IDSDM or the SD card media. 2) Try reseat or replace the SD card media. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0117.Message: Card identification signature is not present on Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card 1.

SRV027.Description: The partition cannot be exposed to the server Operating System (OS) because of an unknown issue in the iDRAC.
SRV027.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
SRV027.Message: Unable to expose the partition to the server Operating System (OS) because of an unknown issue in iDRAC.

RED050.Description: The download of the update package was not successful because the user name or password provided to access the network share or the proxy server settings were not correct.
RED050.Resolution: Check the network connection and access to the update package from the iDRAC. Verify that the user access credentials and proxy server settings are correct.
RED050.Message: The specified user credentials necessary for downloading an update package were not correct.

SWC0083.Description: The iDRAC has been successfully removed from Integrated Data Center network per user action. The iDRAC will now be set to Factory defaults. The iDRAC will be able to show up in an Integrated Data Center only when it is rediscovered.
SWC0083.Message: The iDRAC is successfully removed from the Integrated Data Center network.

HWC4013.Resolution: Check presence, re-install or reconnect, then re-attempt the update. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC4013.Message: Hardware unsuccessfully updated for embedded NIC.

RED060.Description: The specified repository catalog is either not supported or the structure is incorrect. Only Windows Update Packages are supported by iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller for the operation. If the structure is incorrect, either the expected elements are not present, or unexpected elements are present in the catalog XML file. The catalog XML file should be generated by the Repository Manager tool.
RED060.Resolution: Check the repository catalog file name and contents. Rebuild the catalog XML file using Repository Manager by selecting Windows Update Packages only, and retry the operation.
RED060.Message: The specified repository catalog is not supported.

CMC8523.Description: The Mezz card 3 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8523.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8523.Message: The Mezz card 3 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.

UEFI0248.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. A resource allocation was forced because resources were not requested for the identified processor. .
UEFI0248.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0248.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected on processor %1.

OSD55.Description: Cannot attach the ISO image since it is already attached to the host.
OSD55.Resolution: ISO Image is already attached to the host server. Detach the ISO and then rerun the command.
OSD55.Message: ISO Image is attached to host

PR16.Description: The device could not apply some of the configuration settings. This may indicate configuration changes since the last system inventory or mutually exclusive settings.
PR16.Resolution: Check the current system configuration and ensure all settings are correct. If not, retry the operation.
PR16.Message: Some of the configuration values could not be applied to device: %1

SRV035.Description: The XML transform operation cannot be completed on the data collected because the collected data is in an unexpected format.
SRV035.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SRV035.Message: Unable to complete XML transform on the data collected because the collected data is in an unexpected format.

PCI5001.Description: A PCIe card carrier containing a PCIe card is present in the slot identified in the message. This PCIe card will be enabled when the associated server is turned on or power cycled.
PCI5001.Resolution: Turn on or power cycle the associated server to enable the PCIe card.
PCI5001.Message: A PCIe card carrier containing a PCIe card is inserted in PCIe slot%1 .

RED049.Description: When an Automatic Backup or Automatic Update recurring operation is disabled or the license for this feature is expired, the next job in the sequence had not started yet and was deleted.
RED049.Message: The job %1 is deleted because the recurring operation %2 is currently not enabled.

CPU0002.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is inserted correctly, if the processor is removable. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0002.Message: CPU %1 has failed the built-in self-test (BIST).

PSU0092.Description: The rating of the power supply unit identified in the message does not exceed system power distribution limits.
PSU0092.Message: Power supply unit %1 rating is appropriate for the system power distribution limits.

RAC050.Description: The country code is not entered in the correct format or does not exist. Refer to ISO 3166 for the correct country code format.
RAC050.Resolution: Enter country code in the correct format as defined in ISO 3166. For example, United States = US.

HWC5002.Description: The fabric type for the IOM and mezzanine cards must match. Once an IOM or mezzanine card is inserted into the chassis, the fabric type is then set for the CMC and the CMC will ensure that all subsequent IOM's and mezzanine cards match.
HWC5002.Resolution: Check chassis fabric type in CMC GUI and compare to the type of IOM or mezzanine card.

OSE1009.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. Verify the media in the CDROM is bootable. See system video for additional information.

SUP016.Description: Only jobs with the job status of Downloading / Downloaded / Pending Reboot can be scheduled.
SUP016.Resolution: In case there is an update job, wait until the job status is Downloaded and then retry the action.

RAC915.Description: The auto-negotiation property for the iDRAC NIC can be changed only if the NIC is in dedicated mode. To change the NIC mode to dedicated, an iDRAC Enterprise license is required.
RAC915.Resolution: Change the NIC mode to dedicated mode by using "racadm set idrac.nic.selection <1 | Dedicated>", and retry the operation.
RAC915.Message: Unable to change auto-negotiation property for the NIC.

LIC204.Description: This error occurs when the Lifecycle Controller restore operation is interrupted before it completes. This can occur due to a power outage or when the iDRAC is reset while the restore operation is in progress.
LIC204.Resolution: Repeat the Lifecycle Controller restore operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC204.Message: The License Manager database restore operation failed.

TMP0134.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0134.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0134.Message: The control panel temperature is outside of range.

GMGR0015.Description: The iDRAC cannot be added to local group identified in the message because the maximum possible iDRACs are already added to group.
GMGR0015.Resolution: Remove existing iDRAC(s) from the local group to free up slots. If there are more than the maximum possible iDRACs, consider upgrading to OpenManage Consoles.
GMGR0015.Message: Unable to add iDRAC to local group %1 because the maximum possible iDRACs are already added to group.

RAC0771.Description: The iDRAC Service Module (iSM) cannot be installed because the iSM DUP cannot be mounted on to the host operating system (OS).
RAC0771.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0771.Message: Unable to install iDRAC Service Module (iSM) because the iSM DUP cannot be mounted on to the host OS partition.

RAC0292.Description: This error is displayed when LDAP or Active Directory cannot find its certificate.
RAC0292.Message: A valid certificate is not loaded.

RED007.Description: The Update Package security signature cannot be verified.
RED007.Resolution: Re-acquire the Update Package from the service provider.
RED007.Message: Unable to verify Update Package signature.

PWR205.Description: The Server Performance Over Power Redundancy (SPOPR) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.
PWR205.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR205.Message: The Server Performance Over Power Redundancy (SPOPR) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.

USR0200.Description: The user identified in the message has successfully entered proper credentials to access Quick Sync.
USR0200.Message: User %1 has successfully logged in to Quick Sync %2.

SYS078.Description: Unable to retrieve the Server Configuration Profile from the network share for the requested preview operation. This may be due to issues with network accessibility.
SYS078.Resolution: If the configuration profile is on an NFS share, make sure that the network share is accessible from iDRAC. If the configuration profile is on a CIFS share, make sure that the network share is accessible from iDRAC using the share credentials specified. Test the network share access using the Test Network Connection method. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
SYS078.Message: Unable to retrieve the Server Configuration Profile from the network share for preview.

PWR8592.Description: The request to turn on or turn off the chassis was issued before the previous power operation was completed.
PWR8592.Resolution: Retry the operation after the current operation is complete.
PWR8592.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on or turn off the chassis because another chassis power operation is in progress.

UEFI0150.Description: The system has detected a storage backplane that is not supported in this system or configuration. The backplanes functionality may be degraded or disabled.
UEFI0150.Resolution: Install a supported backplane configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
