UEFI0150.Message: The system has detected a storage backplane that is not supported in this system or configuration. The backplanes functionality may be degraded or disabled.

CTL55.Description: The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation. This text is from events in the controller event log that were generated while Storage Management was not running.
CTL55.Resolution: If there is a problem, review the controller event log and the Server Administrator alert log for significant events or alerts that may assist in diagnosing the problem. Verify the health of the storage components. See the hardware documentation for more information.

SRV018.Description: Unable to start the Storage Controller Log collection because the server is powered off.
SRV018.Resolution: Turn on the server, wait until the OS finishes booting, and then retry the operation.
SRV018.Message: Unable to start the Storage Controller Log collection because the server is powered off.

RFM1024.Description: At boot, the Card Identification (CID) signature of the card is different from the Non-volatile (NV) storage value or the card is the destination of a copy operation that is in-progress.
RFM1024.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.

OSD61.Description: The IP Address format is invalid and cannot be validated. The specified IP address may not be a valid IPv4 or IPv6 address.
OSD61.Resolution: Verify the IP address format and retry the operation.

BAR115.Description: The number of Automatic Server Profile backup files has reached the specified limit. Restarting the numbering from 1 which will overwrite the oldest backup file.
BAR115.Message: The number of Automatic Server Profile backup files has reached the specified limit. Restarting the numbering from 1.

RAC0142.Description: The firmware update process identified an invalid firmware image.
RAC0142.Resolution: Upload a valid iDRAC firmware image.
RAC0142.Message: File is not valid for iDRAC firmware update.

RAC953.Description: The comment was added to the specified entry in the Lifecycle Log.
RAC953.Resolution: View the added comment using the racadm lclog view q <seq. no> -n 1 command.

CTL117.Description: The operation cannot be completed because an invalid passphrase is passed for the controller identified in the message.
CTL117.Resolution: Enter a valid passphrase and retry the operation.
CTL117.Message: Unable to complete the operation because an invalid passphrase is passed for the controller %1.

DIS012.Description: Factory signed client certificate is being used. Auto Discovery client is using this certificate for the SSL connection with the Provisioning Server.
DIS012.Message: Auto Discovery client using factory signed client certificate.

CMC8572.Description: The coin cell battery in the CMC located in the slot specified in the message is not working. The battery needs to be replaced.
CMC8572.Resolution: Replace the coin cell battery of the standby CMC.
CMC8572.Message: The coin cell battery in CMC %1 is not working.

PR29.Description: The device that the job was intended for has no previous information recorded. The request has failed as this information is required to initiate the operation. This has been deprecated.
PR29.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory on Restart attribute of the Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. Alternatively, use the Unified Server Configurator utility.
PR29.Message: Unable to locate device in previous configuration.

UEFI0196.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Error Training phase.
UEFI0196.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0196.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

USR0205.Description: Quick Sync access for the user identified in the message is temporarily disabled because of consecutive unsuccessful Login attempts to Quick Sync from the MAC address identified in the message.
USR0205.Resolution: Contact the server administrator and make sure the username and password credentials used are correct. Check the Lifecycle Controller Log (LC Log) to see if more unauthorized server access attempts are occurring than would be expected due to forgotten account names or passwords.
USR0205.Message: Quick Sync access alert %1 from %2, Quick Sync will be blocked for %3 seconds.

RED008.Description: The firmware payloads in the Update Package cannot be extracted. This may be because the file is not valid or the security signature cannot be verified.
RED008.Resolution: Re-acquire the Update Package from the service provider.
RED008.Message: Unable to extract payloads from Update Package.

CBL0001.Description: A backplane signal cable was detected, but the accompanying power cable was not present.
CBL0001.Resolution: Reconnect or replace the power cable. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

SWC0003.Description: An unrecoverable error occurred while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0003.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0003.Message: Unable to display the Lifecycle log.

SYS290.Description: The System Lockdown feature is enabled.
SYS290.Message: The System Lockdown feature is enabled.

BAR001.Description: A system profile export operation has been requested.

UEFI0097.Description: The Advanced ECC memory operating mode cannot be enabled because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.
UEFI0097.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0097.Message: Unable to enable the Advanced ECC memory operating mode because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.

RAC0641.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'time' while scheduling a job.
RAC0641.Resolution: Enter a correct value in the HH:MM format, and then retry the operation.
RAC0641.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid 'time' value is entered.

LIC206.Description: The license was imported after the user overrode EULA warning.
LIC206.Resolution: Remove the license if the import violates the EULA.
LIC206.Message: EULA warning: Importing license %1 may violate the End-User License Agreement.

SWC1911.Description: User ID Password has been changed.
SWC1911.Message: User ID %1 User Password has been changed.

RAC936.Description: iDRAC cannot enable or disable the hot spare property, because the system has a non-PMBus PSU.
RAC936.Message: Unable to change the hot spare property for the PSU.

SYS182.Description: Collecting OS and Application Data cannot be completed because Lifecycle Controller is used by another operation.
SYS182.Resolution: Make sure all other Lifecycle Controller operations are finished and retry the operation. Using the iDRAC Web UI, select Server > Job Queue, check the job queue for unfinished jobs and wait for the jobs to finish before retrying the operation. Also, check whether there are update packages being executed in the server OS and wait for these operations to finish before retrying the operation. For remote web services API access, make sure that the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status, and then retry the operation.
SYS182.Message: Unable to collect OS and Application Data because another Lifecycle Controller operation is currently in progress.

OSD29.Description: Driver Pack configuration file not found in Lifecycle Controller. Driver Pack may be unusable.
OSD29.Resolution: Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and then rerun the command.
OSD29.Message: Driver Pack configuration file not found in Lifecycle Controller. The Driver Pack might be corrupt.

HWC8502.Description: The internal cable that connects the I/O panel to the system board is properly connected.
HWC8502.Message: The I/O panel cable is connected.

SYS025.Description: There are no pending configurations to be deleted.

VFL0714.Message: SD card is not ready and could not be initialized.

PDR17.Description: A user has have assigned a physical disk as a global hot spare. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC8601.Description: The source profile is not correct in form or content.
SWC8601.Resolution: Recreate source profile or choose a different one.
SWC8601.Message: Quick Deploy Profile unable to apply profile %1 to server %2

SWU8527.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation is successful.
SWU8527.Message: Successfully completed the iKVM firmware update.

RAC1111.Description: Unable to clear pending values or operations from the specified storage device because there are no pending operations for the specified device.
RAC1111.Message: Unable to delete the pending values or operations of the specified device.

LC004.Description: The Provisioning Server parameter information is not formatted correctly.
LC004.Resolution: Verify the string format. Enter a valid IP address or hostname for the Provisioning Server such as: 1) hostname 2) hostname.domain.com 3) 1.1.1.1 4) hostname:8080 5) hostname.dell.com:8080 6) hostname1:80,hostname2:8080.
LC004.Message: Provisioning Server information is not formatted correctly.

SYS173.Description: The TTY Log cannot be retrieved because another operation is in progress on the RAID controller.
SYS173.Resolution: Do the following: 1) View the job queue and make sure all jobs are in a completed state. 2) Retry the operation.
SYS173.Message: Unable to retrieve the TTY Log because another operation is in progress on the RAID controller.

STOR087.Description: The configuration operation cannot be started because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.
STOR087.Resolution: Make sure that the Lockdown.1#SystemLockdown attribute is set to Disabled in the DCIM_iDracCardEnumeration class by running the WS-Man get command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation.
STOR087.Message: Unable to start the configuration operation because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.

UEFI0149.Description: The PERC storage adapter identified in this message is not supported by the installed storage backplane.
UEFI0149.Resolution: Install a compatible storage adapter. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0149.Message: The PERC storage adapter in %1 is not supported by the installed storage backplane.

SYS257.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the verification certificate is not available. The file transfer settings are set to verify the certificate of the remore host server, but the necessary verification certificate is not uploaded.
SYS257.Resolution: Upload the verification certificate or select the Ignore Certificate Warning setting, and then retry the operation.
SYS257.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the verification certificate is not available.

PWR2202.Message: The system is sleeping with lost processor context.

FC003.Description: An invalid number of arguments was provided to the method.
FC003.Resolution: Enter required input parameters and retry. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide or the FC HBA Profile specification.

RAC095.Description: The configuration operation cannot be started because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.
RAC095.Resolution: Make sure that the Lockdown.1#SystemLockdown attribute is set to Disabled in the DCIM_iDracCardEnumeration class by running the WS-Man get command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation.
RAC095.Message: Unable to start the configuration operation because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.

CMC8541.Description: The CMC specified in the message was reset by a watchdog event.
CMC8541.Message: The watchdog has reset the CMC %1.

LIC012.Description: This error may occur if: 1) The license was deleted by another user. 2) The license that is being imported may have been deleted from the temporary storage before the import operation completed.3) At start-up, License Manager does not find the license assigned to the device. This may occur if a power outage occurs before a license delete operation completes.
LIC012.Message: The license file does not exist.

SYS199.Description: The state of Lifecycle Controller is successfully changed to "disabled", but other attributes are not set. When the LifecycleControllerState attribute is set to disabled in the SCP profile, other attributes settings in the SCP profile are not applied.
SYS199.Resolution: The Lifecycle Controller state must be "enabled" before performing the import SCP operation and the LifecycleControllerState attribute should not be set to disabled in the SCP profile while attempting to configure other attribute settings. To set LifecycleControllerState attribute to enabled using the RACADM command line utility, type "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState Enabled".
SYS199.Message: The state of Lifecycle Controller is successfully changed to "disabled", but other attributes specified in the Server Configuration Profile (SCP) profile are not changed.

RAC0215.Description: Login failed because the user does not have 'Login to iDRAC' privilege.
RAC0215.Resolution: Login to iDRAC' privilege is needed.
RAC0215.Message: Login failed: User does not have 'Login to iDRAC' privilege.

LOG303.Description: Unable to rename current Chassis Log file during archive operation. Some log entries may be lost.
LOG303.Message: Unable to archive the Chassis Log file.

JCP025.Description: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller can be enabled in the F2 Setup application or through a remote operation.
JCP025.Resolution: If Lifecycle Controller is in Recovery mode a firmware update of Lifecycle Controller may be required. To change the Lifecycle Controller mode, do the following: 1) Restart the system and press F2 to launch the System Setup application 2) Select iDRAC Configuration 3) Select Lifecycle Controller Settings to enable Lifecycle Controller.

SWU8528.Description: The process of iKVM firmware update is not successful due to a checksum error of the firmware image.
SWU8528.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source folder, and then retry the operation.
SWU8528.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware, because of a checksum error.

RAC026.Description: Unable to set DNS Domain Name because "Domain Name From DHCP" is Enabled.
RAC026.Resolution: Disable "Domain Name From DHCP" to set values for DNS Domain Name.
RAC026.Message: Unable to set DNS Domain Name because "Domain Name From DHCP" is Enabled.

LC033.Description: The Hardware Inventory XML file representing the system configuration as shipped from the factory was successful.
LC033.Message: As-Shipped Hardware Inventory export was successful.

SWC1916.Description: Network Time Protocol server configuration has changed.
SWC1916.Message: Network Time Protocol server configuration has changed.

SRV089.Description: The SupportAssist operation identified in the message is partially completed.
SRV089.Message: The SupportAssist %1 operation is partially completed.

STOR307.Description: Unable to perform the configuration operation because the export log operation is currently in progress.
STOR307.Resolution: Wait until the current export operation is complete, and then try the configuration operation again.
STOR307.Message: Unable to perform the configuration operation because the export log operation is currently in progress.

LC013.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. At least one attribute should be changed to create a configuration job.
LC013.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes before creating a configuration job.
LC013.Message: A configuration job cannot be created because there are no pending values to change.

HWC7014.Description: An invalid cable related hardware configuration detected on the system.
HWC7014.Resolution: Make sure the hardware and related cables are installed correctly. For information about configuration and installation procedures, see the system's Owners Manual available at the support site.
HWC7014.Message: An invalid cable or incorrect cable configuration is detected.

IOV117.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter(VA) identified in the message has been unassigned/unmapped from the server identified in the message.

UEFI0228.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Receive Enable Training - Configuration Write phase.
UEFI0228.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0228.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

CTL10.Description: The controller alarm test has run successfully. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PCI3012.Description: System performance may be degraded. The bus is not operating at maximum speed or width.
PCI3012.Resolution: Reset the system, if the problem persists reinstall processors.

STOR017.Description: The virtual disk specified is not compatible with the requested operation or a specified operation parameter is not appropriate for the virtual disk type specified.
STOR017.Resolution: Make sure the operation parameters are appropriate for the virtual disk type. Specify a compatible virtual disk for the requested operation and retry the operation.
STOR017.Message: The specified Virtual Disk is not valid for the operation.

STOR097.Description: A virtual disk cannot be created because the memory size of the physical disk drive is less than available or entered virtual disk size.
STOR097.Resolution: Enter the FQDD of a physical disk drive that has a larger disk space, and then retry the operation. To view a list of physical disk drives and associated disk space, run the RACADM command "racadm storage get pdisks -o -p size". To view a list of virtual disks and associated size, run the RACADM command "racadm storage get vdisks -o -p size".
STOR097.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the memory size of the physical disk drive is less than the available or entered virtual disk size.

SWU8549.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful, because of a firmware image checksum error.
SWU8549.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8549.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Standby CMC and Active CMC. The checksum process was not successful.

LC071.Description: Unable to export or import server configuration XML because the Lifecycle Controller version on the target does not support this feature.
LC071.Resolution: Update the Lifecycle Controller version on the target system to a version that supports the export and import server configuration XML feature, and retry the operation.
LC071.Message: The Lifecycle Controller version does not support the export or import of the Server Configuration XML file.

TMP0107.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0107.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

CMC8602.Description: The Chassis group identified in the message is deleted. This chassis was the leader of the group.

MEM9031.Description: The NVDIMM device in the slot identified in the message is unable to save the data during the previous system shutdown operation or power loss. The NVDIMM is placed in write-protect mode.
MEM9031.Resolution: Remove and reinstall the Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device. If the issue persists, contact your service provider. For information about removing and reinstalling the NVDIMM, see the system Owner's Manual on the support site.
MEM9031.Message: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device in the slot %1 is unable to save the data during the previous system shutdown operation or power loss.

CMC8502.Description: CMC is unable to access the specified server's IPv6 information. Unable to display the specified server's Launch iDRAC link on the CMC Web interface.
CMC8502.Resolution: Enable IPv6 for the specified server using the CMC command line or CMC Web GUI interface, so that the link to launch iDRAC is displayed on the CMC Web interface. For the command line options or navigation for Web interface, see the Troubleshooting section in the CMC User's Guide.
CMC8502.Message: Unable to access the IPv6 information of the server.

GMGR0001.Description: The iDRAC Group Manager feature is enabled. All the iDRAC Group Manager features, if configured earlier to a group, will be preserved. iDRAC will be able to create or join iDRAC local groups.
GMGR0001.Message: The iDRAC Group Manager feature is enabled.

VDR97.Description: The Patrol Read task has encountered an error such as a bad disk block and remapped data to correct the error.
VDR97.Message: Patrol Read corrected a media error on %1.

SWC0324.Description: There are no records to display. This might be a result of the log being cleared.
SWC0324.Message: There are no records available to display.

RED006.Description: The Update Package cannot be successfully downloaded.
RED006.Resolution: Check the network connection and access to the update package from the iDRAC.

RAC0159.Description: Certificate upload failed because there is no pending Certificate Signing Request (CSR) or private key.
RAC0159.Resolution: Upload failed due to no pending Certificate Signing Request (CSR). Try creating a new CSR and then upload the certificate.
RAC0159.Message: Certificate upload failed: No pending CSR or private key.

CTL76.Description: The controller encountered errors while applying the configuration on the physical disks. The configuration command applied has not taken effect.
CTL76.Resolution: Re-issue the failed configuration command or try with a different set of physical disks. Contact technical support if the problem persists.
CTL76.Message: A configuration command could not be committed to disk on %1

OSD72.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ImageName' is missing.
OSD72.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ImageName" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD72.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ImageName' is missing.

VF043.Description: The file size is too large to be used.

TMP0108.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0108.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0108.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

STOR076.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because at least one other pending operation was found on the RAID controller. This operation needs exclusivity because it involves changing RAID backplane topology.
STOR076.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending operations, allow the job to complete, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR076.Message: Enclosure configuration mode (Split/Unified) cannot be changed because there are already pending operations.

CTL111.Description: The CopyBack Mode the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL111.Message: The CopyBack Mode of %1 is set to %2.

SYS161.Description: The Tech Support Report related data have been deleted from iDRAC non-volatile storage.
SYS161.Message: Tech Support Report related non-volatile storage deleted.

CMC8609.Description: The version number of Complex Programmable Logical Device (CPLD) on the sleeve identified in the message cannot be read because the CPLD version is very old, or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to identify the version.
CMC8609.Resolution: Update the CPLD version of sleeve and retry the operation. For more information about the recommended CPLD versions, see the Chassis Management Controller User's Guide available at the support site.
CMC8609.Message: Unable to read the Complex Programmable Logical Device (CPLD) version number of sleeve %1 because the CPLD version is very old, or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to identify the version.

RAC0603.Description: The Job Queue is updated with the selected update jobs. The status of the update jobs can be viewed and managed within the Job Queue page.
RAC0603.Resolution: Click Job Queue button to view the status of the update jobs.
RAC0603.Message: Updating Job Queue. Status of the update jobs can be viewed and managed within the Job Queue page.

OSD11.Description: Lifecycle Controller does not have any drivers for the selected operating system. The operating system installation uses the native drivers present on the operating system media.
OSD11.Message: Driver Pack does not have drivers for the selected operating system.

VF004.Description: The value of the input parameter identified in the message is not a valid value.
VF004.Resolution: Refer the iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller User Guides for the required input parameters for this method.

RED012.Description: Unable to create a Lifecycle Controller update task. The related job status is marked Failed.
RED012.Resolution: Retry the update operation after one minute.
RED012.Message: Unable to create Lifecycle Controller update task.

SUP0526.Description: Unable to continue the firmware update because the catalog file or the update package is corrupt.
SUP0526.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, download the latest Update Package or Catalog file from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0526.Message: Unable to continue with firmware update.

RAC925.Description: An alert recurrence cannot be set for the specified subcategory. The alert recurrence is applicable only to the TMPS subcategory.
RAC925.Resolution: 1. Check if the alert recurrence is applicable to this subcategory. To check this run racadm eventfilters get.2. To set the notifications for the specified subcategory, run the command without the -r option.
RAC925.Message: Recurrence interval is not applicable for this subcategory.

PR33.Description: The platform system motherboard was replaced.

MEM0006.Message: Memory device at location %1 is present.

FAN0006.Description: The fan may be required for optimal performance.

SYS123.Description: An unexpected issue has occurred. This could be because the application encountered an unexpected exception or was terminated by a user. This issue could also be because the application was running in an unsupported OS.
SYS123.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the OS Collector on the iDRAC to the most recent version available, and then retry the operation.
SYS123.Message: OS Collector: An unexpected issue has been encountered.

UEFI0144.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error happens during the identification of memory module type or memory size.
UEFI0144.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0144.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

USR0150.Description: The VNC client is connected from the IP address identified in the message to the iDRAC VNC Server.
USR0150.Message: Opening a remote VNC session from IP address %1.

SYS146.Description: Starting secure erase-capable drive erase operations because of a System Erase operation request.
SYS146.Message: Starting secure erase-capable drive erase operations.

OSD64.Description: The ConfigurableBootToNetworkISO method cannot be run by specifying the ResetType parameter as 'warm reboot' because the server is in turned-off state.
OSD64.Resolution: Make sure that the server is turned on and retry the operation.
OSD64.Message: Unable to invoke the ConfigurableBootToNetworkISO method by specifying the ResetType parameter as 'warm reboot' because the server is in turned-off state.

GMGR0014.Description: The iDRAC local group cannot be renamed to the new name identified in the message either because a group already exists with the same name or there is an internal issue in the Primary Group Controller.
GMGR0014.Resolution: Do any one of the following and retry the operation: a) Check if another group with the same name appears in the Group Manager Discovered Groups view. b) Restart iDRAC.
GMGR0014.Message: Unable to rename the iDRAC local group to %1 either because a group already exists with the same name or there is an internal issue in the Primary Group Controller.

SWC8620.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate with the iDRAC in server slot identified in the message.
SWC8620.Resolution: Reset the server iDRAC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8620.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate with the iDRAC in server slot %1.

LIC906.Description: The license file is not present or accessible from the network share location.
LIC906.Resolution: Verify the license file is located on the network share and file access permissions are correct, then retry the operation.
LIC906.Message: License file is not accessible on the network share.

RED017.Description: The DUP specified is not compatible with the target system.
RED017.Resolution: Download and use the DUP that matches the system that the installation is targeting.
RED017.Message: The DUP specified is not compatible with the target system.

LC0101.Description: A user cancelled Lifecycle Controller actions. Any remote jobs pending execution were cancelled.
LC0101.Message: Lifecycle Controller action was cancelled by a user.

BAT1012.Description: Diagnostic event for service to determine if there is an ambient temperature problem.
BAT1012.Message: The %1 battery temperature is above normal.

LIC202.Description: This error can occur when:1) Platform table has invalid value for default license feature set and permissible license upgrade path. In this case, the system sets the default licensed feature set to Basic Management and does not restrict the license upgrade path.2) License Manager fails to load due to lack of system resources.
LIC202.Message: A system error was detected during License Manager startup.

PWR220.Description: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because the slot identified in the message is empty.
PWR220.Resolution: Insert an appropriate PSU in the slot identified in the message and retry the operation.
PWR220.Message: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because slot %1 is empty.

ENC33.Description: Data redundancy has been restored to an enclosure that previously suffered a loss of redundancy.
ENC33.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

GMGR0073.Description: The group job cannot be rescheduled because the job is running.
GMGR0073.Resolution: Do any one of the following: 1) Wait for the job to run successfully and then delete the job. 2) Stop the job and then delete the job.
GMGR0073.Message: Unable to reschedule the group job because the job is already running.

SYS031.Description: The configuration is being applied to a component.

SYS094.Description: The Tech Support Report collection job could not be started, because a report collection job is already running on the server.
SYS094.Resolution: Wait until the current Tech Support Report operation is complete and then retry the operation.
SYS094.Message: The iDRAC is unable to start the Tech Support Report job, because a report collection job is already running on the server.

TMP0111.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is within range.

BIOS033.Description: Data cannot be written to the network share either because the network share is read-only or sufficient disk space is unavailable for the export operation.
BIOS033.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Make sure that the network share is not read-only. 2) Make sure that there is sufficient disk space on the network share.
BIOS033.Message: Unable to write to the network share either because the network share is read-only or sufficient disk space is unavailable for the export operation.

SYS265.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the remote host server did not allow file transfer operations even when the remote host is successfully contacted.
SYS265.Resolution: Make sure that the file transfer parameters and credentials, and remote host server configuration are correct, and then retry the operation.
SYS265.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the remote host server did not allow file transfer operations.

RAC0276.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0276.Message: To save the changes and update this page, click Apply.

PR17.Description: Some of the configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to the current device. This may be due to firmware version or other differences in the part.
PR17.Resolution: Check the device's configuration and ensure that the new configuration is correct for the system.
PR17.Message: Some of the configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to device: %1

VF024.Description: The partition is locked by another operation.
VF024.Resolution: Wait for the partition to be unlocked and check the partition status to see if it is attached.

HWC0010.Description: Operation failed because the folder name entered is incorrect or the USB drive is disconnected.
HWC0010.Resolution: Enter a valid folder name or attach the USB drive and retry the operation.
HWC0010.Message: Invalid folder name or USB drive not found.

ASR0103.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was powered down. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset - 02h event 3:0 - 4h).
ASR0103.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0103.Message: The OS watchdog timer powered down the system.

BAR060.Description: Collecting firmware inventory and copying it into the system profile backup file.

STOR052.Description: Virtual disks cannot be created because the maximum number of logical drives per controller or diskgroup is reached.
STOR052.Resolution: Refer to the User's Guide of the specific controller available at the support site for information on the number of supported virtual disks allowed.
STOR052.Message: Unable to create virtual disk, maximum number of created virtual disks per controller or diskgroup has been reached.

BAT0013.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is present.

SEC0606.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0606.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.
SEC0606.Message: The network boot password violation detected.

STOR301.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because there is an operation pending to change the controller mode. This operation is exclusive because it requires a server reboot for changes to apply.
STOR301.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending controller mode change request operation, allow the job to complete, restart the server, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR301.Message: Unable to perform the operation because the controller mode change request is pending.

SEL1512.Description: The Chassis Controller is not responding or is not inserted properly.
SEL1512.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reinsert Chassis Controller, if removed. 2) If Chassis Controller is present but is not responding, reset the Chassis Controller. To reset the Chassis Controller using the graphical user interface (GUI), click Chassis Overview > Power > Control > Reset CMC. To reset by running the RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), enter: "racadm racreset".
SEL1512.Message: The Chassis Controller is not responding or is not inserted properly. The status of Chassis Controller is critical.

RAC0267.Resolution: Enter a valid VLAN Priority. Expected range: 0-7.

IOV013.Description: Unable to assign a virtual adapter (VA) to a server that is already assigned a VA, because a server may be assigned only one VA.
IOV013.Resolution: Unassign the server's current virtual adapter (VA) and retry the operation. To unassign the VA using RACADM, run the following command "racadm setpciecfg".
IOV013.Message: Unable to assign a virtual adapter (VA) to a server that is already assigned a VA, because a server may be assigned only one VA.

PCI1308.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1308.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1308.Message: A PCI parity error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

VDR54.Description: You have cancelled the virtual disk initialization.

SWC8551.Description: The boot identity profile cannot be applied because the profile identified in the message is in use by the server in the slot identified in the message.
SWC8551.Resolution: Clear the boot identity of server identified in the message to apply another profile. Using the CMC GUI, navigate to the Boot Identity page, Boot Identities are cleared using "Clear Identity" option provided "Boot Identity Profiles" tab.
SWC8551.Message: Unable to apply the boot identity profile because the profile %1 is already in use by the server in slot %2.

RAC958.Description: The import or export operation cannot be started because a job is already running.
RAC958.Resolution: Wait for the currently running job to complete and then retry the operation. The currently running job can be an update, backup, export or other job type. To view the status of currently running job using the RACADM command line interface, run the racadm jobqueue view command.
RAC958.Message: Unable to start the import or export operation because a job is already running.

PST0081.Description: System is at F1/F2 prompt because the system BIOS was unable to detect a bootable device.
PST0081.Resolution: Make sure a bootable device is attached to the system and enabled in BIOS setup. If device is attached and enabled, remove and reapply power to server. If the problem persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

RAC0636.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid proxy password is entered.
RAC0636.Resolution: Enter a valid proxy password, and then retry the operation.
RAC0636.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid proxy password is entered.

PDR74.Description: A user cancelled the copyback operation.

CTL103.Description: The Check Consistency Mode value of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL103.Message: The Check Consistency Mode value of %1 is set to %2.

PWR8686.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the storage sled controller identified in the message because iDRAC version installed on the server is not compatible.
PWR8686.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware identified in the message to the supported latest available version and retry the operation. For information about the supported firmware versions, refer to the Chassis Management Controller user's Guide available at the support site.
PWR8686.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the storage sleds associated with server in slot %1 because the iDRAC firmware version in the server does not support the chassis storage module.

SWC0258.Description: Insufficient resources to execute the command.
SWC0258.Resolution: Power Cycle the system and re-enter the command.

RAC914.Description: The specified value is not within the valid range. To set the LED state to off, enter 0. To set the LED state to on, enter 1.
RAC914.Resolution: Set the numeric value to 0 (Off) or 1 (On).
RAC914.Message: Value specified is invalid: Must be 0 (Off) or 1 (On).

BOOT017.Description: The boot device(s) specified in the source argument used in the operation cannot be enabled or disabled. This behavior applies to BCV devices and one-time boot.
BOOT017.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on validity of operation for the boot device specified. For more information on the operation, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
BOOT017.Message: Source argument does not support enable or disable mode.

STOR5.Description: A virtual disk or enclosure has lost data redundancy. In the case of a virtual disk, one or more physical disks included in the virtual disk have failed. Due to the failed physical disk or disks, the virtual disk is no longer maintaining redundant (mirrored or parity) data. The failure of an additional physical disk will result in lost data. In the case of an enclosure, more than one enclosure component has failed. For example, the enclosure may have suffered the loss of all fans or all power supplies.
STOR5.Resolution: Identify and replace the failed components. To identify the failed component, select the Storage object and click the Health subtab. The controller status displayed on the Health subtab indicates whether a controller has a failed or degraded component. Click the controller that displays a Warning or Failed status. This action displays the controller Health subtab which displays the status of the individual controller components. Continue clicking the components with a Warning or Failed status until you identify the failed component. See Storage Health for more information. See the enclosure documentation for information on replacing enclosure components and for other diagnostic information.

STOR077.Description: A Patrol Read State change operation cannot be performed if the Patrol Read Mode is not set to Manual.
STOR077.Resolution: Change the Patrol Read Mode to Manual before performing a Patrol Read State change operation.
STOR077.Message: Unable to change Patrol Read State since Patrol Read Mode is not set to Manual.

GMGR0026.Description: The group passcode cannot be modified because one or more iDRACs did not respond within 48 hours.
GMGR0026.Resolution: Check the group job ID for information about the failed iDRACs in the Group Manager job view. Check network connection and system health of each iDRAC from the GUI. Remove the iDRAC(s) from the group and rejoin the group by using new passcode.
GMGR0026.Message: Unable to modify the group passcode because one or more iDRACs did not respond within 48 hours.

GMGR0055.Description: The Group Manager cannot be accessed because of insufficient privileges to the logged in user.
GMGR0055.Resolution: Contact the system administrator to get necessary privileges. For more information about user privileges, see the Online help by pressing F1, or see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
GMGR0055.Message: Unable to access the Group Manager because of insufficient privileges.

DIS104.Description: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access the network share folder, because an invalid filename is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS104.Resolution: Specify a valid file name in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC using the (-f <filename>).
DIS104.Message: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access the network share folder, because an invalid filename is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

CMC8553.Description: An internal I2C hardware occurred and CMC initiated a failover to clear the hardware error. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8553.Message: An internal error occurred and a failover condition is detected.

CTL23.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL23.Message: Copyback and Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.

UEFI0138.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware is unable to complete a requested task or function.
UEFI0138.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0138.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was unable to complete a requested task or function.

CTL26.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL26.Message: Copyback and Abort CC on Error has changed for %1.

STOR320.Description: The storage controller does not support online capacity expansion and RAID level migration of a Virtual Disk at the same time.
STOR320.Resolution: There are two Reconfiguration operations possible on a Virtual Disk 1) Online Expansion of the storage capacity 2) RAID level migration . Only one of the above two operations can be specified in a Reconfiguration operation. Make sure that only one of the above two operation types is requested and retry the operation. Also make sure that if provided, the Virtual Disk size is at least 1% of the maximum expansion size possible. Also make sure that if provided, the new Virtual Disk RAID level is different from the existing raid level.
STOR320.Message: Unable to start the reconfiguration operation because the requested reconfiguration operation is invalid.

IOV108.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected a power fault in an adapter after the adapter was powered on. A power fault may be caused by a damaged adapter or the adapter power requirements exceed the maximum power limits of the slot.
IOV108.Resolution: Make sure a supported PCIe device is used and that it is properly inserted in the PCIe slot. For a list of supported devices, contact your service provider.
IOV108.Message: Power fault detected on PCIE adapter %1 in %2 %3.

RAC0699.Description: The value for Minimum Fan Speed must be within the range identified in the Recommended Response Action.
RAC0699.Message: Invalid value for Minimum Fan Speed.

RAC957.Description: Another import or export operation cannot be started until the current operation is complete.
RAC957.Resolution: Wait until the current import or export operation is complete before starting another operation. Use the racadm jobqueue view command to check the status of the current import or export operation.
RAC957.Message: An import or export operation is currently in progress.

UEFI0303.Description: The NVDIMM-N module in slot identified in the message has issue because of the reasons described in the message. The NVDIMM-N module identified will be set to fully-functional mode.
UEFI0303.Resolution: Replace the NVDIMM-N module. For information about replacing, see the Owner's Manual on the support site.
UEFI0303.Message: %1 on NVDIMM-N located at %2. The identified NVDIMM-N module will be set to fully functional mode.

TMP0110.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0110.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0110.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is outside of range.

RAC0102.Description: The software to communicate with the Smart Card is not loaded in this browser. Smart Card can be used for log in only if the appropriate Smart Card software is installed in the browser.
RAC0102.Resolution: Install the plug-in prompted by the iDRAC Web GUI to log in using Smart Card.
RAC0102.Message: The Smart Card Logon plug-in is not installed. Install the plug-in from the iDRAC Web GUI to log in using Smart Card.

TMP0100.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0100.Message: The system board %1 temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

SEL1302.Description: The disk in the drive is not formatted correctly or does not contain the necessary operating system files(IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 01h).

PDR83.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PDR94.Description: The attempt to update the physical disk has timed out. This may be due to too much activity on the bus, a bad update package, or a bad disk.
PDR94.Resolution: Retry the update. The update utility may have already performed the retry operation.
PDR94.Message: Microcode update on %1 has timed out.

SEC0600.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0600.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

CTL41.Description: An error involving a single bit has been encountered during a read or write operation. The error correction algorithm has corrected this error.

BAT1023.Description: The battery health has returned to normal.
BAT1023.Message: The charge level for the battery on %1 is within normal limits.

RAC0158.Description: The Kerberos keytab is needed by the iDRAC to authenticate itself to the Kerberos (Active Directory) server. It is created on the AD server, and issued for the iDRAC. Its like a password, and therefore should be kept secret.
RAC0158.Resolution: The Kerberos keytab file may be corrupt. Upload a valid Kerberos keytab file.

TMP0203.Resolution: Check system operating environment, fans, and heatsinks.
TMP0203.Message: CPU %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

RAC963.Description: iDRAC is unable to read Lifecycle Controller status. Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to run the operation.
RAC963.Resolution: Run the racadm get LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState command to get the status of the Lifecycle Controller. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC963.Message: Unable to retrieve the status of Lifecycle Controller.

CMC8558.Description: The system health has recovered from a failover condition.

SRV108.Description: The SupportAssist job identified in the message is completed.

MEM7000.Message: The memory riser mismatch was corrected.

ASR0108.Message: The system returned from an OS watchdog timer event.

CBL0002.Description: A backplane power cable was detected, but the accompanying signal cable was not present.
CBL0002.Resolution: Reconnect or replace the signal cable for the backplane identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

CTL46.Description: The Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) is malfunctioning. Data loss or data corruption may occur.
CTL46.Resolution: Replace the DIMM immediately to avoid data loss or data corruption. The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM.
CTL46.Message: Single-bit ECC error. The %1 DIMM is critically degraded.

SYS275.Description: The file identified in the message cannot be applied because the firmware update prerequisite identified in the message is not installed.
SYS275.Resolution: Make sure that the firmware prerequisite identified in the message is installed, and then retry updating the firmware. For information about prerequisite firmware, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS275.Message: Unable to apply the firmware file %1 because the firmware update prerequisite %2 is not installed.

AMP0319.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0319.Message: Chassis power level current is less than the lower critical threshold.

UEFI0152.Description: This is a test BIOS and must not be used in production environment.
UEFI0152.Resolution: Do not use this BIOS in production.
UEFI0152.Message: This BIOS is for testing purpose only.

UEFI0287.Description: The QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) link of the processor identified in the message has a downgraded clock speed or dropped clock because of an initialization error.
UEFI0287.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system, make sure all processors are of the same type/capacity/model, check for damage, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the Troubleshooting section in the platform Owners Manual. If the issues persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0287.Message: The QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) link %1 of the processor %2 has a downgraded clock speed or dropped clock because of an initialization error.

UEFI0142.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was unable to complete a requested task or function.
UEFI0142.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0142.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was unable to complete a requested task or function.

HWC1002.Resolution: If device disabled unexpectedly, re-enable device.

PCI1314.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable re-install the device at the next scheduled service time.
PCI1314.Message: A bus correctable error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

SRV002.Description: The SupportAssist upload operation is started.

DIS112.Description: The AutoConfig operation is using the file identified in the message.
DIS112.Message: The AutoConfig operation is using the %1 file.

BAR011.Description: Hardware Inventory data collection and export did not complete successfully.
BAR011.Resolution: Enter system services to enter Unified Server Configurator (USC), and select exit and reboot option in USC to instantiate the database, if Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) is not enabled. If the hardware inventory database is present, restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC)and retry.
BAR011.Message: Unable to collect Hardware Inventory information.

SWC0016.Description: The operating system driver pack is missing or not accessible.
SWC0016.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation.
SWC0016.Message: Unable to initialize OS Deployment wizard.

SWC5004.Description: System Controller (SC) has started functioning again because either a server health issue is resolved or SC has completed a firmware update process.

BIOS007.Description: A configuration job is already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job succeeds or the job is cancelled.
BIOS007.Resolution: Wait for the job to complete. To continue with more set operations on the specified target, cancel the job and proceed.
BIOS007.Message: Configuration job already created, cannot create another configuration job on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled.

SWC8616.Description: The server identified in the message cannot be accessed remotely by iDRAC because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller for of the server is disabled.
SWC8616.Resolution: Make sure that the iDRAC on the server identified in the message is operating properly and that Lifecycle Controller is enabled, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform a virtual reseat of the server and retry the operation. The server can be virtually reseated by using the CMC Web GUI interface and selecting Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components and then selecting Virtual Reseat from the drop down menu.
SWC8616.Message: Server in slot %1 is not ready to be accessed remotely because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller for of the server is disabled.

RED054.Description: A job for applying an update package was created.

RDU8512.Description: The firmware versions of the Active CMC and the Standby CMC are different.
RDU8512.Resolution: Update the firmware so that the Active and Standby CMC firmware versions are the same.

SYS183.Description: The memory cannot be allocated because of insufficient storage space in iDRAC.
SYS183.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and then retry the operation.
SYS183.Message: Unable to allocate memory because of insufficient storage space in iDRAC.

CMC8576.Description: The RAC CA Certificate is changed.
CMC8576.Message: The RAC CA Certificate is changed.

CTL118.Description: The RAID controller firmware version identified in the message cannot be updated because the downloaded firmware image file is corrupted.
CTL118.Resolution: Download the correct firmware image file and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CTL118.Message: Unable to update the RAID controller %1 firmware version because the downloaded firmware image file is corrupted.

UEFI0188.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Host Impedance phase.
UEFI0188.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0188.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

VF039.Description: The detaching partition operation did not complete successfully.
VF039.Message: Detach partition operation did not complete successfully.

MEM9000.Description: An issue is detected in the propagation of signals between the processor and the memory.
MEM9000.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

RAC057.Description: The Privacy Protocol for the user cannot be enabled because the Authentication protocol is disabled.
RAC057.Resolution: Enable the Authentication Protocol attribute for the identified user ID account, and retry the operation to set the Privacy Protocol to an enabled state.
RAC057.Message: Unable to set Privacy Protocol to an enabled state because the Authentication Protocol attribute is set to None for the user ID: %1

RAC0638.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid proxy host name or IP address is entered.
RAC0638.Resolution: Enter a valid proxy host name or IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC0638.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid proxy host name or IP address is entered.

USR0174.Description: The Front Panel USB device is removed from the operating system.
USR0174.Message: The Front Panel USB device is removed from the operating system.

SYS246.Description: The file cannot be transferred because a proxy password value is not entered, or the entered value is not supported.
SYS246.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy password value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS246.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported proxy password value.

SYS091.Description: Unable to complete the operation because the method is not supported.
SYS091.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the method is not supported.

SWC5003.Description: The System Controller (SC) has either stopped functioning or is updating a firmware version.
SWC5003.Resolution: Make sure that the System Controller is functioning.
SWC5003.Message: System Controller (SC) has either stopped functioning or is updating a firmware version.

PST0144.Description: System BIOS is unable to load the required BIOS files.
PST0144.Resolution: Remove and reapply power to server. If the problem persists, contact your server provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PST0144.Message: Unable to load required BIOS files.

LOG510.Description: The operation cannot be completed because of an unknown issue.
LOG510.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset CMC and then retry the operation.
LOG510.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of an unknown issue in the CMC.

VLT0225.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0225.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0225.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

PCI3001.Message: Device option ROM on embedded NIC was successfully updated.

BOOT003.Description: This operation is not supported on the current configuration.
BOOT003.Resolution: This operation is not supported on the current configuration, check documentation and try again.

ENC9.Description: You have changed the enclosure asset tag. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

GMGR0006.Description: The iDRAC successfully removed itself from the local group identified in the message. The removed iDRAC can now join any available local groups.
GMGR0006.Message: iDRAC successfully removed itself from the local group %1.

CTL113.Description: The controller identified in the message is operating in Degraded Fault Tolerant Mode because of a mismatch between the encryption key setting of controller and its peer controller.
CTL113.Resolution: Make sure that the encryption key for the peer controllers matches by using controller security operations such as creating a security key, modifying a security key, deleting a security key, and then power-cycle the chassis. Make sure to use same encryption key identifier on two controllers joining cluster.
CTL113.Message: The controller %1 is operating in Degraded Fault Tolerant Mode because of a mismatch between the encryption key setting of the controller and its peer controller.

ISM0001.Description: The iDRAC Service Module detected a OS to iDRAC Pass-through mode as identified in the message. iDRAC Service Module will automatically connect to iDRAC after the OS to iDRAC Pass-through is configured to the USB NIC mode.
ISM0001.Resolution: Configure OS to iDRAC Pass-through to the USB NIC mode by running the commands: 1) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.PTMode usb-p2p 2) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.UsbNicIpAddress <ip address> 3) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.adminstate enabled.
ISM0001.Message: The iDRAC Service Module detected a OS to iDRAC Pass-through in the %1 mode. Switch the OS to iDRAC Pass-through to a USB NIC mode.

UEFI0243.Description: The Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) channel identified in the message is operating at a degraded width. This allows continued uptime although indicates an error condition requiring further investigation. This maybe an early indication of upcoming memory riser failure.
UEFI0243.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0243.Message: Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) operating at reduced width on memory riser %1.

RAC005.Description: The name value pairs do not match in the input specified in the method invocation parameters.
RAC005.Message: Mismatch in AttributeName and AttributeValue count.

DIS009.Description: iDRAC IP address sent to Provisioning Server.
DIS009.Message: Notification of iDRAC IP address changed to %1 sent to Provisioning Server.

HWC1006.Resolution: If adapter disabled unexpectedly, re-enable the storage adapter.

CMC401.Description: Changing the Reserved QuickDeploy IP Addresses setting to <number of IP address> may create an issue in the future if higher density server nodes are inserted in to the Chassis (for example, quarter-height servers).
CMC401.Resolution: Select a higher number to accommodate future higher density server node additions, otherwise no response action is required.
CMC401.Message: Changing the Reserved QuickDeploy IP Addresses setting to %1 may create an issue in the future if higher density server nodes are inserted in to the Chassis (for example, quarter-height servers). Press OK to continue.

PWR8551.Description: This will be logged when a Virtual Infrastructure Device power allocation is configured.
PWR8551.Message: Successfully set Virtual Infrastructure Device power to %1 DC Watt.

PSU0036.Description: This failure may be the result of an electrical issue with cables or subsystem components in the system.
PSU0036.Resolution: 1) Remove and re-install the power supply.2) Check cables and subsystem components in the system for damage. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0036.Message: An over current fault detected on power supply %1.

RAC0156.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about system voltage.
RAC0156.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0156.Message: Unable to retrieve the voltage information. The system is powered off.

RAC0726.Description: Auto-throttling is disabled for the server based on a request from the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) because the CMC is restarting.
RAC0726.Message: Auto-throttling is disabled for the server.

SYS414.Description: A new resource is successfully created.
SYS414.Message: A new resource is successfully created.

SUP030.Description: The value of the ProxySupport parameter must be TRUE if the Proxy IP and User Credentials need to be provided for the operation requested.
SUP030.Resolution: Do not specify Proxy IP and User Credential parameters if the ProxySupport parameter is FALSE.
SUP030.Message: Proxy IP and User Credential pare valid only if the ProxySupport parameter is TRUE.

PDR101.Description: This alert message occurs if there are arrays not protected with a global hot spare.
PDR101.Message: Global Hot Spare %1 does not cover all arrays.

RAC1031.Description: The custom signing certificate on iDRAC cannot be deleted because of an internal error.
RAC1031.Resolution: Verify if iDRAC has a custom signing certificate. If it has the certificate, retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC1031.Message: Unable to delete the custom signing certificate.

PWR1008.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1008.Resolution: Review system configuration, upgrade power supplies or reduce system power consumption.
PWR1008.Message: The system performance degraded because power draw exceeds the power threshold.

CTL5.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL5.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.

CMC8518.Description: A double-height server is detected in the slot identified in the message. However, the iDRAC in the server of slot identified in the message is also responding. If a double-height server is already present in the chassis, the server in the bottom slot must not respond.
CMC8518.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove the server in the bottom slot <slot number>. 2) Restart the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and wait for the CMC to complete the startup process. 3) Reinsert the server identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8518.Message: A double-height server is detected in the slot %1. However, the iDRAC in the server of bottom slot %1 is also responding.

IPA0002.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.

UEFI0101.Description: The total amount of installed memory has exceeded the amount supported by the platform.
UEFI0101.Resolution: Remove memory modules from the system to reduce the total amount of installed memory. For more information on installed memory limit, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0101.Message: Total amount of installed memory has exceeded limit.

CTL22.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

DIS105.Description: The network share folder cannot be accessed, because an unsupported or invalid share type is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS105.Resolution: Enter a valid sharetype in DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC using (-s <0 or 1>) where 0 = NFS, 2 = CIFS.
DIS105.Message: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access the network share folder, because an invalid sharetype value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

SYS174.Description: The Tech Support Report (TSR) cannot be exported because of an issue while connecting to the network share using the provided credentials or other network share parameters.
SYS174.Resolution: Make sure the entered sharetype, sharename, IP address, username and password are valid and retry the operation. The network share connectivity can be tested by using the Test Network Connection feature of the iDRAC.
SYS174.Message: Unable to access network share for exporting Tech Support Report (TSR).

PST0196.Description: System BIOS detected an invalid memory population. Reinstall the memory to match the supported population. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code C4).
PST0196.Resolution: Re-install memory to match supported memory configuration.

CMC8703.Description: The Member chassis identified in the message has joined the chassis group.
CMC8703.Message: The Member chassis has joined the Chassis group%1.

SWC8611.Description: CMC cannot perform the server profile application because the selected profile version and the server identified in the message are not compatible.
SWC8611.Resolution: Make sure to select the correct version of the profile and/or server, and then retry the operation.
SWC8611.Message: Profile "%1" and Server (Service Tag: %2 in Slot %3) are not compatible.

SWC0049.Description: The Import operation cannot continue because backup image file is not present on the vFlash SD card, the image is invalid, or the entered passphrase is incorrect.
SWC0049.Resolution: Make sure that the backup image file is present on the vFlash SD card, the image is valid, and the entered passphrase is correct.
SWC0049.Message: Unable to continue the Import operation.

SWU8557.Description: Invalid firmware: The uploaded firmware image does not contain a verification signature.
SWU8557.Resolution: Use a valid firmware image and retry the operation.
SWU8557.Message: Invalid firmware: The uploaded firmware image does not contain a verification signature.

RAC0275.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0275.Resolution: Disable NIC only if remote access is undesired.
RAC0275.Message: Click OK to disable the NIC. Click Cancel to keep the setting unchanged.

HWC0014.Description: The import operation failed because the vFlash SD card is missing or disabled.
HWC0014.Resolution: Make sure the vFlash SD card is inserted and enabled before retrying the operation.
HWC0014.Message: Unable to detect vFlash SD card.

DIS106.Description: The AutoConfig import file operation could not be successfully completed, because the shutdown type (-d) specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC is incorrect.
DIS106.Resolution: Enter a valid shutdown type in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC using (-d <0 or 1>) where 0 = Graceful shutdown and 1 = Forced shutdown.
DIS106.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because an invalid shutdown type was specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

ENC24.Description: The controller is not receiving a consistent response from the enclosure. There could be a firmware problem or an invalid cabling configuration. If the cables are too long, they degrade the signal.
ENC24.Resolution: Power down all enclosures attached to the system and reboot . If the problem persists, upgrade the firmware to the latest supported version. Verify the cable configuration is valid. See the storage hardware documentation for valid cabling configurations.

DIS107.Description: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because an invalid AutoConfig time-to-wait value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS107.Resolution: In the DHCP scope option field where VendorID=iDRAC, enter a time-to-wait (-t) value more than 300 seconds and less than 3600 seconds and then retry the operation.
DIS107.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because an invalid AutoConfig time-to-wait value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

BAT1000.Description: The controller cannot communicate with the battery. The battery is absent or improperly connected. A battery with a weak or depleted charge may also cause this message.
BAT1000.Resolution: Verify that the device is present and then check the cables. See the storage hardware documentation to verify cabling. In addition check the connection to the controller battery and the battery health. A battery with a weak or depleted charge may cause this message.

STOR018.Description: This operation did not detect any foreign drives. This may be because no foreign drives are present or the only foreign drives are in a secured locked state.
STOR018.Resolution: If the only foreign drives present are in a secured locked state, run a secure erase operation on the drives to securely erase data or unlock these drives and retry the operation. Otherwise the operation was not successful because there are no foreign drives.

SYS295.Description: Configuration changes for the components identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) in the configuration job results were not successfully previewed.
SYS295.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Export the Lifecycle Log report and check the configuration changes that did not complete. 2) Retrieve the configuration results by running the GetConfigResults method at the command line interface (CLI). 3) Retry importing the changes that are not successfully completed.
SYS295.Message: Unable to complete component configuration preview.

ISM0005.Description: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully restarted communication with iDRAC.
ISM0005.Message: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully restarted communication with iDRAC.

OSD22.Description: Unable to detach ISO image from the host because either the image is already detached, or iDRAC may not be operating normally.
OSD22.Message: Unable to detach ISO image from the host.

SWC0723.Description: iDRAC is not responding to the current Reset status query.
SWC0723.Message: Error occurred while Resetting to defaults. The Reset status is not available.

JCP044.Description: The new jobs cannot be created until the current iDRAC job downloading operation is either completed or deleted. Only one Import Server Profile job can be run at a given time.
JCP044.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Wait for the current iDRAC job download operation to complete. 2) Delete the scheduled iDRAC download job.
JCP044.Message: Unable to create new jobs until the current iDRAC job downloading operation is either completed or deleted.

LC069.Description: The certificate does not exist for export or delete operation.

VDR20.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk has failed or is corrupt. You may also have cancelled the rebuild.
VDR20.Resolution: Replace the failed or corrupt disk. You can identify a disk that has failed by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. Restart the virtual disk rebuild.

SYS440.Description: The Job creation cannot be done because the End Time entered is invalid.
SYS440.Resolution: Enter the End Time in the String format, and then retry the operation For example, YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS. For more information about recommended End Time format, see the iDRAC Redfish User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS440.Message: Unable to Create Job because the End Time entered is invalid.

ISM0003.Description: The iDRAC Service Module could not successfully discover iDRAC from the server OS. However, the iDRAC Service Module will continue the discovery operation. Make sure that the IPMI drivers are enabled on the server operating system.
ISM0003.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is unable to discover iDRAC from the operating system of the server.

BAR055.Description: Attempted configuration import was not successful for the specified device.
BAR055.Resolution: The system event log captures the values that were not set, and must be reset manually.
BAR055.Message: Previously stored configuration values not applied to Device: %1.

STOR029.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the specified physical disk is not found.
STOR029.Resolution: Provide a valid physical disk FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) and retry the operation.

SWC0265.Description: The option requested is not available on the DRAC being used.
SWC0265.Resolution: Refer to the help to get the list of commands/options valid for the DRAC.
SWC0265.Message: This option is not supported on this type of DRAC.

SWC0307.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0307.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0307.Message: The -d option requires -p or -g to also be specified.

OSE0004.Description: A separate exception or status condition shutdown the operating system. (IPMI sensor type 20h - offset 04h).
OSE0004.Resolution: Review system event log for platform events capable of shutting the system down.
OSE0004.Message: A soft shut-down initiated by platform event filter.

SYS238.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an incorrect file path value.
SYS238.Resolution: Make sure that the correct file path value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS238.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an incorrect file path value.

ENC2.Description: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) was removed.
ENC2.Resolution: Reinsert the Enclosure Management Module (EMM). See the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the EMM.

SWC1940.Description: The Quick Sync Read Authentication feature is enabled.
SWC1940.Message: The Quick Sync Read Authentication feature is enabled.

GMGR0036.Description: The group job identified in the message can not be deleted because the job is actively running.
GMGR0036.Resolution: Wait for the job to complete or stop it if it is actively running.
GMGR0036.Message: Unable to delete the group job %1 of type %2 because the job is running.

SRV019.Description: The Storage Controller Log collection operation cannot be started because the server is in POST and has not finished the startup process.
