SRV019.Resolution: Wait until the server completes POST and the OS startup process, and then retry the operation.
SRV019.Message: Unable to start the Storage Controller Log collection because the server is in POST and has not finished the startup process.

CTL43.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The text for this alert is generated by the utility that ran the diagnostics and can vary depending on the situation.

RAC0101.Description: The data returned is not in a known format.
RAC0101.Resolution: This error may occur because:1. Smart Card is invalid. Insert a valid Smart Card and try again. 2. Check connection between reader and system.3. There may be an issue with the Smart Card reader. Try reinstalling the reader driver or use a different reader.
RAC0101.Message: The inserted Smart Card is not valid or the Smart Card reader is not supported.

RAC0619.Description: The message appears in Firmware Rollback page when the iDRAC firmware rollback action completed successfully.
RAC0619.Resolution: Reconnect iDRAC communications sessions after iDRAC is restarted. The iDRAC will be ready for login once the restart is complete.
RAC0619.Message: The iDRAC firmware rollback will cause an iDRAC restart and all current user sessions will be closed.

VF035.Description: The image file is not valid.

RAC0288.Description: All characters entered must be alphanumeric or valid symbols.
RAC0288.Resolution: Enter all alphanumeric characters and valid symbols.
RAC0288.Message: Invalid entry: Entry must be exclusively alphanumeric characters and valid symbols.

SYS010.Description: The input value for the specified attribute is not valid.
SYS010.Resolution: Refer to Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and provide valid attribute value for the specified attribute.
SYS010.Message: Invalid character in value for attribute: %1

RAC1049.Description: Successfully configured the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.
RAC1049.Message: Successfully configured the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.

RAC0906.Description: Unable to perform the requested operation.
RAC0906.Resolution: Try again later. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method.

UEFI0232.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Configuration Write phase.
UEFI0232.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0232.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

BIOS004.Description: The value for the specified parameter is invalid.
BIOS004.Resolution: Verify that parameter values passed to the method are entered as they appear in the enumeration and parameter data type matches the documentation.

RAC097.Description: The operation cannot be started because System LockDown is entered as one of the attributes.
RAC097.Resolution: Make sure that the Lockdown.1#SystemLockdown attribute is not there in the input list.
RAC097.Message: Unable to start the operation because System LockDown is entered as one of the attributes.

GMGR0061.Description: The job cannot be run because the server is offline. However, the server is removed from the controller cache, but the server may reappear in the group after the server iDRAC is available online.
GMGR0061.Resolution: Wait for the server to be available online, and then rerun the job.
GMGR0061.Message: Unable to run the job because the server is offline.

SYS059.Description: Configuration changes for the component identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) were successfully applied.
SYS059.Resolution: No response action is required. See Lifecycle Log for details.

SWC0041.Description: The specified source file location is incorrect.
SWC0041.Resolution: Make sure that the specified source file location is correct and retry the operation.
SWC0041.Message: Unable to copy the backup Server Configuration Profile.

CPU0701.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.
CPU0701.Resolution: 1) Check system and operating system logs for exceptions. If no exceptions are found continue. 2) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 3) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 4) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SUP0106.Description: There is no firmware image present at the specified path.
SUP0106.Resolution: Check if the firmware image is present at the specified path.
SUP0106.Message: Unable to locate firmware image file in specified path.

PDR55.Description: The physical disk inserted is too small for the rebuild to occur.
PDR55.Resolution: Replace the physical disk with one of correct protocol (SAS, SATA) with at least the required size. Force rebuild if it does not start automatically.
PDR55.Message: Insufficient space available on the %1 to perform a rebuild.

PDR1022.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is no longer in the failed array.

TMP0122.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0122.Message: The system inlet temperature is outside of range.

IOV106.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to power on adapter. Possible reasons for power failures are: 1) Adapter not an approved adapter. 2) Adapter not fully inserted in the slot 3) Auxiliary power cable not connected (applicable to slot 1 - 3 only). 4) Adapter is damaged.
IOV106.Resolution: Make sure a supported PCIe device is used and that it is properly inserted in the PCIe slot. For a list of supported devices, contact the service provider.
IOV106.Message: Unable to power on PCIe adapter %1 in %2 %3.

SWC8547.Description: Some or all of the Media Access Control (MAC) addresses cannot be added to the pool because they are already present in the MAC address pool.
SWC8547.Message: Unable to add some of the Media Access Control (MAC) addresses because the MAC addresses are already present in the MAC address pool of Boot Identity profile operations.

MEM9015.Description: The memory device identified in the message has encountered a uncorrectable error. System performance may be degraded. The operating system and/or applications may fail as a result.
MEM9015.Resolution: Re-install the memory component identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM9015.Message: Multi-bit memory errors detected on a Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) device %1.

UEFI0137.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This issue is caused by missing LC files.
UEFI0137.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0137.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

RAC1163.Description: The peak utilization value of out-of-band performance monitoring sensor identified in the message is successfully reset.
RAC1163.Message: The peak utilization value of out-of-band performance monitoring sensor %1 is successfully reset.

SYS020.Description: The value provided for the required attribute is invalid.
SYS020.Resolution: The value specified is not valid. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation for more information.

STOR066.Description: The requested operation did not succeed because the selected RAID controller is not T10 Protection Information capable.
STOR066.Resolution: Verify that the RAID controller selected for the operation is T10 Protection Information capable, and then retry the operation.
STOR066.Message: Controller is not T10 Protection Information capable.

IOID118.Description: The iDRAC has applied I/O Identity Configuration on NIC and FC HBA devices. One or more of the setting configuration operations did not complete successfully.
IOID118.Resolution: Review the previous log entries and identify the devices that did not successfully complete configuration operations. For the identified devices, do the following and then restart the server: 1) Make sure the device is installed properly. 2) Make sure the device has latest firmware installed. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
IOID118.Message: Unable to configure some or all I/O Identity settings based on current persistence policy settings.

SYS158.Description: Unable to erase hardware caches during the System Erase operation.
SYS158.Resolution: Retry the System Erase operation with only the hardware cache erase option selected.

SWC4009.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between CMC 1 and CMC 2.

PWR8544.Description: Insufficient power is available for the server identified in the message to function. The server will be turned off until there is sufficient power available.
PWR8544.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis.
PWR8544.Message: Chassis Management Controller turned off the Server %1 because of insufficient power at inventory.

RED009.Resolution: Verify if Lifecycle Controller is installed on the system by pressing F10 on boot up. If the Lifecycle Controller application is not present, use the update package to reinstall it.

STOR015.Description: A new virtual disk cannot be created because the maximum number of virtual disks are already created.
STOR015.Resolution: A new virtual disk cannot be created until one is deleted.
STOR015.Message: Maximum virtual disks allowed for this controller has been reached.

UEFI0085.Description: One or more chipset errors have occurred.
UEFI0085.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the chipset error. Do one of the following: 1) Turn off the input power to the system and turn on again. 2) Update the PCIe device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0085.Message: One or more chipset errors have occurred.

UEFI0057.Description: The MCE is logged during Power-on-Self-Test (POST). MCE could have occurred during either the current or the previous POST.
UEFI0057.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify Machine-Check Exception (MCE) event source. Resolve the issue identified in the SEL that caused the MCE. For further information, contact your service provider.
UEFI0057.Message: A Machine-Check Exception (MCE) error has occurred.

BAT1022.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC0104.Description: An invalid PIN was entered. Too many log in attempts with a Smart Card login can result in a user being locked out of the system.
RAC0104.Resolution: 1. Enter a valid Smart Card PIN and try again.2. Use a different Smart Card.

VF044.Description: File transfer was not successful. This could be because of network problems or an operational problem with the file server.
VF044.Resolution: Try the download again. If the issue persists, validate that the network share is operational.
VF044.Message: TFTP download operation was not successful.

SYS019.Description: The input is missing a required dependency necessary for the operation.
SYS019.Resolution: Provide the required dependency and retry. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation.

ENC27.Description: The enclosure cannot support both SAS and SATA physical disks. Physical disks may be disabled. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
ENC27.Message: SAS or SATA mixing of physical disks is not supported within the %1.

SYS242.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported proxy hostname value.
SYS242.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy hostname value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS242.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported proxy hostname value, %2.

RAC024.Description: Unable to VLAN is Disabled so cannot set VLAN Priority because VLAN is Disabled.
RAC024.Resolution: Enable VLAN to set VLAN Priority.
RAC024.Message: Unable to VLAN is Disabled so cannot set VLAN Priority because VLAN is Disabled.

RDU0031.Description: The system has redundant voltage lines. One of voltage line is no longer available.
RDU0031.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

RAC0401.Description: Critical error from iDRAC service recovery program.

SWU8505.Description: The specified Lifecycle Controller operation is successfully submitted and the operation will be executed on the basis of scheduling criteria.
SWU8505.Message: Successfully scheduled the reinstall/rollback operation on the server %1.

SWU8540.Description: The PSU firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8540.Resolution: Make sure that the PSU firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8540.Message: Unable to update the PSU firmware, because the transfer of Image file is not successful. ErrorCode=0x%1.

SRV034.Description: The OS Collector application is unable to generate a zip archive of the OS and Application Data report.
SRV034.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SRV034.Message: The OS Collector application is unable to generate a zip archive of the OS and Application Data report.

SWC0107.Description: The command takes in only one option which is the Session ID.
SWC0107.Resolution: Enter the command only with one option i.e. the Session ID.
SWC0107.Message: More than one option is not allowed with this command.

SYS302.Description: The vFlash Erase operation is successfully completed.
SYS302.Message: The vFlash Erase operation is successfully completed.

RED048.Description: The next job in the recurring operation sequence identified in the message was not started and was deleted, because an Automatic Server Profile Backup or Automatic Update operation was cleared.
RED048.Message: The job %1 was deleted because the recurring operation %2 was cleared.

STOR047.Description: Unable to change the value of the attribute identified in the message because it is ReadOnly.
STOR047.Message: Unable to change the value of attribute %1 because it is ReadOnly.

BAR107.Description: The vFlash media reader requires a license to function.
BAR107.Resolution: Obtain the license for vFlash media from your service provider. Install the license and retry the operation.
BAR107.Message: vFlash media reader license not present.

PR12.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference and would apply firmware. However, user settings indicate that Part Replacement should perform the upgrade only and not a downgrade to an earlier firmware version.
PR12.Message: Firmware update setting allows version upgrade only and will not be performed.

LC046.Description: The DownloadServerPublicKey operation is in progress. The operation may take a few minutes to complete before the operation can be attempted again.
LC046.Resolution: Wait a few minutes before retrying retry the operation.
LC046.Message: An instance of DownloadServerPublicKey is already running.

RED051.Description: The update package file download was not successful. This could be due to the following: 1) The update package file is missing, 2) The host address, share, user name, and password information are correct but the file name was invalid, 3) The network file share could not be mounted, or 4) The network file share disconnected before the transfer was complete.
RED051.Resolution: Check the network connection and access to the update package from the iDRAC.
RED051.Message: The network file transfer of an update package was not successful.

DH008.Description: Unable to save the provided client certificate to internal persistent storage.
DH008.Resolution: Try again. If the error persists, use RACADM command racresetcfg to clear the issue.
DH008.Message: There was a problem saving the certificate to persistent storage.

LC055.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because the number of AttributeName input parameters provided to the method exceeded the number of attributes available in iDRAC.
LC055.Resolution: Retry the operation with an input parameter array that matches the available attributes in iDRAC.
LC055.Message: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid attribute array.

SWC8536.Description: The add key operation did not complete successfully for the slot identified in the message due to the key being invalid or corrupt.
SWC8536.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8536.Message: Unable to add key for slot %1 of service account, due to corrupt key.

SRV031.Description: The OS Collector application is unable to communicate with the WMI service. This may be because the user context the application is running in does not have appropriate access privileges or firewall/security settings are preventing retrieving registry and software data from WMI.
SRV031.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure the user context the OS Collector application is running in has the appropriate privileges to access WMI. Make sure that firewall or security settings are set to allow access and retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, restart the WMI service and retry the operation. 3) If the issue continues to persists, restart the server OS and retry the operation.
SRV031.Message: The OS Collector application is unable to communicate with WMI services.

RAC1149.Description: The Integrated Service Module (ISM) Installer cannot be made available to the host system because the System Erase operation is performed earlier.
RAC1149.Message: Unable to make the Integrated Service Module (ISM) Installer available to the host system because the System Erase operation is performed earlier.

SWC0215.Description: The process to disable the file share has started. Use the -s option to know more about the status.
SWC0215.Resolution: If required check the status using the -s option.
SWC0215.Message: Disable Remote File Started. Please check status using -s option to know Remote File Share is ENABLED or DISABLED.

SYS119.Description: The OS collector cannot be exposed to the host server because of communication issues between the iDRAC and server OS.
SYS119.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and server OS.
SYS119.Message: Unable to expose the OS Collector to the server OS.

SYS193.Description: A configuration change is detected in the component identified in the message.
SYS193.Message: A configuration change is detected for component: %1.

SWC0159.Message: Kerberos Keytab successfully uploaded to the RAC.

VFL1002.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is IPMI-function ready.

SWC8608.Description: The CMC was unable to perform the operation described in the message because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller of the server is disabled.
SWC8608.Resolution: Make sure that iDRAC on the server identified in the message is operating and that Lifecycle Controller is enabled, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform a virtual reseat of the server and retry the operation. To perform a virtual reseat of the server, on CMC Web interface, select Chassis Overview -> Troubleshooting -> Reset Components. On the Reset Components page, select Virtual Reseat from the drop-down menu for the server identified in the message.
SWC8608.Message: Server Profiles: unable to access server: %1 for operation [%2] because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller of the server is disabled.

UEFI0165.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because the number of allowable System Address Decode (SAD) rules exceeded during memory initialization.
UEFI0165.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0165.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

PWR8500.Description: The chassis power state from the configuration database and the current state are different. The current chassis power state will be updated in the configuration database. This is to insure the chassis power state will be the same if the CMC is rebooted or a CMC failover occurs. Note that the numerical value of the state is intended for technical support use.
PWR8500.Message: Chassis power state updated to %1 from %2.

MEM0005.Description: The memory is operational. This is an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0005.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0005.Message: Persistent correctable memory error limit reached for a memory device at location(s) %1.

RDU8501.Description: The Active CMC has detected a problem or a low memory condition. It is waiting for the Standby CMC to reset the Active CMC.
RDU8501.Message: CMC%1: waiting to be reset by other CMC

RED025.Description: The firmware for the indicated device updated successfully to the identified firmware version.

SUP009.Description: Because of the size of the driver pack, the update process removes the older version of the driver pack from the system before installing the newer version. For that reason, the driver pack update cannot be deleted.
SUP009.Resolution: Wait for the Driver Pack update to complete. To revert to the previous version of the update, download and update the firmware to the version desired.
SUP009.Message: Driver pack update in progress - Delete failed.

SRV103.Description: Not presenting the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer to Host because the iSM installer version on iDRAC is same as iSM service version running in Host OS.
SRV103.Message: Not presenting the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer to Host because the iSM installer version on iDRAC is same as iSM service version running in Host OS.

BAT0004.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0004.Resolution: Check the system board battery to confirm presence.
BAT0004.Message: The system board battery is absent.

SUP0114.Message: The firmware update operation could not be completed successfully.

RAC0662.Description: Clear foreign configuration will delete the foreign virtual disk information from the controller's associated physical disk drives. Clearing will remove metadata associated with the virtual disks, making the physical disk drives available for creating new virtual disks. To remove foreign data, perform an initialization operation.
RAC0662.Message: The Clear Foreign Configuration operation will delete the foreign virtual disk information from the controller's associated physical disk drives. Clearing will remove metadata associated with the virtual disks, making the physical disk drives available for creating new virtual disks. To remove foreign data, perform an initialization operation.

HWC6004.Description: Information and status from the controller is unavailable.
HWC6004.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

STOR025.Description: The pending configuration cannot be deleted because the configuration job is already scheduled.
STOR025.Resolution: Delete the current configuration job for the device to stop pending configuration changes.
STOR025.Message: Unable to delete any pending configuration because the configuration job is already scheduled.

FC103.Description: The network connection of the FC controller port link identified in the message is successfully started.
FC103.Message: The %1 port %2 network connection is successfully started.

HWC2013.Message: Fabric mismatch corrected on fabric %1 with server in slot %2.

BAR090.Description: A request to create a System Profile Backup file has been made by the user of the Unified Server Configurator interface.

TMP0136.Description: The system is automatically turned off because of insufficient cooling.
TMP0136.Resolution: Replace the fans that have stopped functioning, or add the minimum number of fans recommended. For more information, see the system Owner's Manual available at the support site.
TMP0136.Message: The system is automatically turned off because of insufficient cooling.

SWC0142.Message: Certificate successfully uploaded to the RAC.

POW000.Description: Host failed to power up because chassis infrastructure is not ready. This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2250.
POW000.Message: Power on permission error, chassis infrastructure not ready.

VFL0018.Description: The requested operation is currently in progress.
VFL0018.Resolution: Wait for the requested operation to complete.
VFL0018.Message: The requested operation is in progress.

RAC1222.Description: The Client trust certificate is successfully deleted.
RAC1222.Message: The Client trust certificate is successfully deleted.

RAC0226.Description: Sending the test mail failed. This will prevent alert messages from being sent to this email address.
RAC0226.Resolution: Confirm that:1. A valid SMTP server address is configured in the iDRAC. 2. The remote email server is configured properly to send and receive emails.

SYS286.Description: The update status cannot be previewed because the specified catalog file does not exist on the remote share.
SYS286.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Make sure that the specified catalog file is available on the remote share. 2) Make sure that the Repository Update file path has less than 1024 characters and retry the operation.
SYS286.Message: Unable to preview the update status because the specified catalog file does not exist on the remote share.

SWC0101.Description: Racadm is unable to read the available log records at this point. Retry the command.
SWC0101.Message: Unable to read available log records.

PSU0005.Description: The operating requirements for the power supply may be found in product documentation or on the power supply itself.
PSU0005.Resolution: Verify the input power is within the operating requirements for the power supply.
PSU0005.Message: The power input for power supply %1 is outside of the allowable range, but it is attached to the system.

RAC1000.Description: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 Address and IPv6 Gateway, because the object IPv6 Autoconfig is enabled.
RAC1000.Resolution: Disable the object IPv6 AutoConfig using "racadm set iDRAC.IPv6.AutoConfig <0 | Disabled >", and retry the operation.
RAC1000.Message: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 address or gateway.

RAC090.Description: The Connection view refresh operation failed from backend.
RAC090.Resolution: Connection view server port connection data refresh operation failed.
RAC090.Message: Unable to complete the switch connection and switch port connection data refresh operation because of internal error.

SWC0034.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to export the file to the network share because it has insufficient free space.
SWC0034.Resolution: Make sure that the network share has sufficient free space then retry the operation. If the problem persists, check network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0034.Message: Unable to export the file to the network share.

BIOS036.Description: The import operation cannot be started because the public key (PK) certificate is already available.
BIOS036.Resolution: Delete the existing public key (PK) certificate, enter a new PK, and then retry the operation.
BIOS036.Message: Unable to start the import operation because the public key (PK) certificate is already available.

FAN0003.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.
FAN0003.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0003.Message: Fan %1 RPM is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PWR8581.Description: A chassis power operation is currently in progress and the server identified in the message could not be turned on.
PWR8581.Resolution: Wait until the current chassis power operation is complete and the chassis is On and then retry the operation.
PWR8581.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because another chassis power operation is in progress.

UEFI0069.Description: A CMOS checksum error has occurred resulting in an invalid BIOS configuration. BIOS configuration is reset to default settings.
UEFI0069.Resolution: Go to the System Setup and configure the desired settings. Save and exit to apply the settings.
UEFI0069.Message: A CMOS checksum error has occurred. CMOS is reinitialized.

PSU0904.Description: In order to meet service requirements the supply must be shut down.
PSU0904.Resolution: Remove input power at the power supply.
PSU0904.Message: Could not power down 240VA on power unit %1.

CTL12.Description: The controller and attached enclosures are not cabled correctly.
CTL12.Resolution: Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on correct cabling configurations.
CTL12.Message: An invalid SAS configuration has been detected on %1. Details: %2

UEFI0204.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Clock Training FIFO Reset phase.
UEFI0204.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0204.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SYS296.Description: The Server Configuration Profile Import job is scheduled. After the next server reboot, the configurations will be automatically applied.
SYS296.Message: The Server Configuration Profile Import job is scheduled. After the next server reboot, the configurations will be automatically applied.

SYS249.Description: A network connection is successfully started to the remote host, but the file is unable to be transferred.
SYS249.Resolution: Make sure that correct parameters are entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS249.Message: A network connection is successfully started to the remote host, but the file, %1, is unable to be transferred.

UEFI0301.Description: The BIOS Recovery process failed consecutively three times because of unknown issues.
UEFI0301.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Disconnect the input power supply to the server. 2) Restart the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0301.Message: The BIOS Recovery process failed consecutively for three times because of unknown issues.

VF020.Description: The number of partitions exceeded the maximum number allowed on a SD card.
VF020.Resolution: This SD card has reached the partition limit. Delete any partitions that are not necessary and try again.

HWC8509.Description: The heatsinks are critical for providing cooling to the PCIe switches. If a PCIe switch stops functioning due to improper cooling, the PCIe subsystem may no longer function correctly and data loss may occur.
HWC8509.Resolution: Immediately turn off the Chassis by pressing the Chassis power button or removing chassis input power. The Chassis can be turned off remotely by running the following RACADM command "racadm chassisaction -m chassis nongraceshutdown". After turning off, contact your service provider.
HWC8509.Message: One or more PCIe switch heatsinks are not properly attached.

VDR93.Description: This alert message occurs if there are medium errors in the physical drives.
VDR93.Message: %1 bad block medium error is cleared.

SWC0292.Description: The queried object does not exist at the specified index.
SWC0292.Resolution: Check for the objects available at the specified index and re-try.
SWC0292.Message: The specified object at index %1 does not exist.

LOG002.Description: An invalid parameter ID is entered for the instance ID or job ID identified in the message.
LOG002.Resolution: Enter the correct WS-Man parameter for the instance ID or job ID. For information about valid parameters, see the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide available on the support site.
LOG002.Message: An invalid parameter ID is entered for %1.

LC079.Description: The export operation cannot be started because Lifecycle Controller is currently running an instance of Export Message Registry operation.
LC079.Resolution: Wait for the current export process to complete, and then retry the operation.
LC079.Message: Unable to start the export operation because Lifecycle Controller is currently running an instance of Export Message Registry operation.

RED082.Description: The Automatic Update or Automatic Backup feature is disabled.
RED082.Resolution: Enable the correct job schedule type, and then retry the operation. For example, to enable the Automatic Update feature, select the Enable Automatic Update option.
RED082.Message: The requested job cannot be scheduled, because job schedule type such as Automatic Backup or Automatic Update is not enabled.

SUP020.Description: The specified job was successfully deleted from the job queue.

SUP0514.Description: An internal error occurred while performing firmware rollback operation.
SUP0514.Resolution: Exit the Firmware Rollback wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system and retry the operation.

SWC0315.Description: The getconfig subcommand failed to get the object value.

SEC0101.Description: The Storage disk tray in the slot identified in the message has been open for an extended period of time. The tray should be closed as soon as any service action is completed. Leaving it open for extended period may result in drives overheating.
SEC0101.Resolution: Close the Storage disk tray as it may affect the system performance or may cause hard drives to overheat. Check system logs .
SEC0101.Message: The %1 in slot %2 is opened for more than 3 minutes.

DKM1004.Resolution: Check for network connectivity. Review network, server, and client configuration.
DKM1004.Message: The key management server received a bad request.

SWC0110.Description: The build information is not available for racdump.
SWC0110.Message: No build information is currently available.

SWC0014.Description: Unable to apply the changes to the date and time settings because an internal error occurred.
SWC0014.Resolution: Exit the Date and Time wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation.
SWC0014.Message: Unable to set new date and time.

CMC8510.Description: This happens during promotion of extended storage feature from single CMC to dual CMC. If the media on Standby CMC is not healthy, this message is displayed and the feature returns to single CMC state.
CMC8510.Resolution: Do one of the following, and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration and verify if the card on the secondary CMC displays some errors. 2) Do a failover and then reprovision the card from the same GUI page. Reprovisioning is only allowed on the card of primary CMC. However, if both the options 1 and 2 fail, the card may be no longer functional.
CMC8510.Message: Unable to activate the extended storage feature on the secondary CMC: %1. The feature will return to single CMC mode.

RAC0560.Description: RAC Software Initialization error. Monitoring data will not be available for PERC and Network Cards.

PWR8568.Description: The server identified in the message did not gracefully shutdown before the CMC shutdown timer expired. This happens if the server did not show power off status change within 60 seconds after the operation was initiated, or if the OS in the server has not successfully shutdown.
PWR8568.Resolution: Check if the OS in the server identified in the message has successfully shutdown, if not, manually complete the shutdown or wait for the shutdown to complete normally. If the issue persists, perform a forced power down of the server identified in the message.
PWR8568.Message: Server %1 did not gracefully shutdown before the timer expired.

BAR095.Description: The request to restore a System Profile from a Backup file did not complete successfully because there is already a request in progress.
BAR095.Resolution: If possible monitor the in progress job for completion and then retry the request. If that is not possible try clearing all jobs and try the request again. If the issue persists, restart the Integrated Remote Access controller and try the request again.
BAR095.Message: Another Restore operation already in progress.

UEFI0241.Description: An error occurred during Memory Voltage Regulator initialization during the VR1 SVID Ramp phase.
UEFI0241.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0241.Message: An error occurred during Voltage Regulator (VR) initialization on memory riser %1.

PDR27.Description: A user assigned a physical disk as a dedicated hot spare to a virtual disk. See Protecting Your Virtual Disk with a Hot Spare for more information. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC0137.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while changing the read-write state of the vFlash partition.
RAC0137.Message: An error has occurred while changing the read-write state for the partition.

VDR44.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

STOR0111.Description: The specified reference key is invalid.
STOR0111.Resolution: Verify that the correct reference key is specified. See the help text or documentation for valid reference keys.

SYS048.Description: The operation expected a valid profile that is compliant with the system configuration schema. However, the Server Configuration Profile does not contain valid profile content.
SYS048.Resolution: View the file in any Web browser to check for invalid characters. Remove the invalid characters and make sure that the file is a valid XML and is compliant with the system configuration schema published on delltechcenter.com/lc in the LC profile Schema Guide.
SYS048.Message: Server Configuration Profile contains invalid characters, %1 at line %2.

RAC0505.Description: Devices are not displayed. This error may occur because these components are removed or disconnected.
RAC0505.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is ON. 2. Check if the Storage Enclosure is ON. 3. Verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0505.Message: There are no devices to be displayed.

SWC4010.Description: The current CMC firmware does not support the ARI Mode advanced features available in the network device on the server identified in the message.
SWC4010.Resolution: Update the CMC firmware to the latest version and to enable access to the advanced features available in the network device.
SWC4010.Message: %1%2 in Server-%3 requires a version of Chassis Management Controller (CMC) firmware 5.0 or later for using the NParEP (ARI mode) functions.

PWR8512.Description: Power configuration data in memory cannot be accessed due to synchronization issues.
PWR8512.Message: CMC rebooted, because the power configuration data could not be accessed.

SEC0042.Description: TXT CPU microcode boot cannot be completed because system configuration may have changed.
SEC0042.Resolution: Check system hardware inventory for TPM presence, clear and reconfigure TPM and TXT in BIOS setup menu.
SEC0042.Message: Processor detected a problem while performing an Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) operation.

PDR4.Description: A physical drive that was previously in an error state has returned to a ready state.

SWC0043.Description: The Import Server Profile operation has completed with errors. For more information, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0043.Resolution: Exit the Import Server Profile wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0043.Message: Import Server Profile operation completed with errors.

DIS101.Description: The AutoConfig operation is started by iDRAC using the AutoConfig import file specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS101.Message: The execution of AutoConfig operation is started.

FC008.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. To create a Configuration job, change at least one attribute.
FC008.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes and retry creating the Configuration job.
FC008.Message: No pending data present to create a Configuration job.

HWC2000.Message: The %1 cable or interconnect is connected.

SRV004.Description: The SupportAssist collection data cannot be exported because of an issue while connecting to the network share using the provided credentials or other network share parameters.
SRV004.Resolution: Make sure the entered share type, share name, IP address, user name and password are valid and retry the operation.
SRV004.Message: Unable to access network share for exporting SupportAssist Collection data.

RAC0743.Description: Unable to perform storage configuration operations because no storage controllers are detected on the server.
RAC0743.Message: Unable to perform storage configuration operations because no storage controllers are detected on the server.

RAC0642.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'day' of a month while scheduling a job.
RAC0642.Resolution: Enter a correct numerical value in the following format: Day [1 to 31] of every [1 to 12] month(s). For example, Day 4 of every 11 months. Retry the operation.
RAC0642.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid value is entered for the 'day' of a month.

SYS096.Description: The required Dell Diagnostics firmware package is not installed or cannot be found in the iDRAC internal storage.
SYS096.Resolution: Install the Dell 64bit uEFI Diagnostics firmware package, and then retry the operation. The Dell Diagnostics can be installed using the Dell 64bit uEFI Diagnostics Dell Update Package (DUP).
SYS096.Message: Unable to complete the diagnostics operation because the required Dell Diagnostics firmware package is not installed.

SWC0134.Message: The RAC log was cleared successfully

SWU8554.Description: Local CMC firmware update process is initiated.
SWU8554.Message: Local CMC firmware update has been initiated.

UEFI0074.Description: The system BIOS logs this message after detecting a change in Secure Boot policy settings. Such a change may result from user configuration or a system BIOS update. Changes to the following settings trigger this message: 1) Secure Boot (Enable/Disable) 2) Secure Boot Policy (Standard/Custom) 3) Platform Key 4) Key Exchange Keys 5) Authorized Signature Database (db) 6) Forbidden Signature Database (dbx).
UEFI0074.Resolution: Review the Secure Boot policy settings in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. If policy changes were expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise, modify the Secure Boot policy settings as needed.
UEFI0074.Message: The Secure Boot policy has been modified since the last time the system was started.

CMC8554.Description: An internal network error occurred. If none of the external sources have an issue, the CMC may have a hardware issue. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8554.Resolution: Reseat the network cable and check the connectivity to the outbound switch.

PWR2005.Message: The OS run-time software initiated a hard reset.

RAC0760.Description: Unable to perform storage configuration operations on physical disk drive(s) as there are no disk drive(s) available with Ready/RAID/NON-RAID state or the selected controller is in HBA mode.
RAC0760.Resolution: Check the following: 1) If there are no physical disk drive(s) in either Ready state or in RAID/NON-RAID state, insert additional disk drive(s). 2) If the Controller(s) are in HBA mode, switch the controller(s) to RAID mode. To switch controller(s) to RAID mode using the F2 System Setup utility, go to Device Settings > RAID Controller > Controller Management > Advanced Controller Management > Switch to RAID mode.
RAC0760.Message: Unable to perform physical disk(s) storage configuration operations for the selected controller.

GMGR0013.Description: The iDRAC local group identified in the message cannot be deleted because of an internal issue in the Primary Group Controller.
GMGR0013.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC.
GMGR0013.Message: Unable to delete the iDRAC local group %1 because of an internal issue in the Primary Group Controller.

RAC0232.Description: This is a specific error message used only on the default prompt login page when the user fails to enter the secure default password.
RAC0232.Resolution: Enter valid credentials and retry the operation.
RAC0232.Message: Login failed. Verify username and password is correct. The secure default password is on the pull-out Information Tag located on the front of the chassis.

IOID006.Description: The Storage Target Persistence Policy setting is changed to the restart type identified in the message.
IOID006.Message: Storage Target Persistence Policy setting is changed to %1.

RAC0724.Description: Quick Sync Firmware is successfully updated.
RAC0724.Message: Quick Sync Firmware is successfully updated.

MEM1012.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM1012.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in a degraded state.

RAC0152.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about power supplies.
RAC0152.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0152.Message: Unable to retrieve the power supply information. The system is powered off.

VDR11.Description: This message is generated after initialization of a virtual disk starts.

UEFI0298.Description: The BIOS Recovery process is started.
UEFI0298.Message: The BIOS Recovery process is started.

SWC9002.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate Reset operation cannot be completed either because of insufficient space in certificate store, an internal error or an invalid Certificate type is entered.
SWC9002.Resolution: Enter a valid Certificate type and retry the operation. If the issue persists, free some space in the certificate store by deleting few certificates, restart iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SWC9002.Message: Unable to complete the SecureBoot Certificate Reset operation either because of insufficient space in certificate store, an internal error or an invalid Certificate type is entered.

SYS234.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported port number value.
SYS234.Resolution: Make sure that the correct port number value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS234.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported port number value, %2.

VFL0708.Message: SD card is busy with another operation and could not be initialized.

SWC0120.Description: The syntax of the sslcertview command is invalid.
SWC0120.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertview subcommand.
SWC0120.Message: Invalid syntax. Certificate type (-t) must be specified.

CTL92.Description: The controller identified in the message licensed features do not match its peer.
CTL92.Resolution: Update the license on the peer controller.
CTL92.Message: %1 is not operating in Fault Tolerant Mode because of an incompatible license setting on its peer controller.

PWR8509.Description: Unable to change the server power priority because Server Based Power Management mode is enabled.
PWR8509.Resolution: The server power priority can be changed once Server Based Power Management mode is disabled. Using the CMC Web UI, navigate to the Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration page, then uncheck the Enable Server Based Power Management checkbox. Retry the operation.
PWR8509.Message: Unable to change the server power priority because Server Based Power Management mode is enabled.

UEFI0182.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Early Vref Centering error was detected.
UEFI0182.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0182.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

UEFI0183.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Early Vref Centering initialization.
UEFI0183.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0183.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

PDR32.Description: The controller cannot to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a global hot spare. The disk either failed or was removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.
PDR32.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and installed. Check the cables. Refer to the product documentation and see the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the global hot spare.

RAC014.Description: The method cannot be run because an invalid attribute name is entered.
RAC014.Resolution: Enter a valid attribute name and retry the operation.
RAC014.Message: Unable to run the method because an invalid attribute name is entered.

SYS159.Description: The vFlash SD Card erase operation was unsuccessful. This may be because the SD card is not enable, not licensed or not initialized.
SYS159.Resolution: Make sure the vFlash SD Card is enabled, licensed and initialized, and then retry the System Erase operation with only the vFlash option selected.

BAR023.Description: The process is entering the component update phase of the restore operation.

CTL28.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL28.Message: The Background Initialization (BGI) rate has changed for %1.

SRV127.Description: The SupportAssist registration contact and shipping information cannot be retrieved because data is either missing or corrupted.
SRV127.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, Reset the iDRAC configuration and re-register the server for SupportAssist and then retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC configuration using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm racresetcfg". After resetting the iDRAC configuration, to re-register the server for SupportAssist using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm supportassist register".
SRV127.Message: Unable to retrieve the SupportAssist registration contact and shipping information in iDRAC because data is either missing or corrupted.

ASR0101.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. System was reset. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset 01 - event 3:0 - 3h if booting 4h if running).
ASR0101.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0101.Message: The OS watchdog timer reset the system.

BAT1013.Description: The battery cannot be recharged further.
BAT1013.Message: Recharge count has exceeded the maximum limit for battery on %1.

SRV046.Description: Unable to start the operation because the server is turned off.
SRV046.Resolution: Retry the operation after the server has been turned on and POST has completed.
SRV046.Message: Unable to start the operation because the server is turned off.

SRV094.Description: The SupportAssist Auto Collection could not be uploaded to SupportAssist server because iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service is not running in the server operating system (OS).
SRV094.Resolution: 1) Make sure that compatible iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service is installed and running in server host operating system (OS). 2) Retry the operation. 3) If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and server OS.
SRV094.Message: Unable to upload the SupportAssist Auto Collection to SupportAssist server because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running in the server operating system (OS).

SWC0128.Description: The Common Name field is necessary for generating a CSR. It is not generated if Common Name is empty.
SWC0128.Resolution: Configure the Common Name field by using config command.
SWC0128.Message: The Common Name (CN) field of the CSR Security group must be configured before a CSR can be generated.

HWC6000.Description: Information and status from the controller is unavailable.
HWC6000.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

VF042.Description: The remote file could not be found.

PWR1006.Resolution: Review system configuration, upgrade power supplies or reduce system power consumption.
PWR1006.Message: The system halted because system power exceeds capacity.

RAC1067.Description: The minimum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is lesser than, or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.
RAC1067.Resolution: Check the minimum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the minimum threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1067.Message: Unable to set the minimum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is lesser than, or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.

FAN8500.Description: Enabling Enhanced Cooling Mode will provide increased airflow capability to the blades by increasing the maximum allowable blower speed at the cost of increased power consumption.

SUP0525.Description: Unable to verify the digital signature of the Update Package.
SUP0525.Resolution: Download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0525.Message: Unable to verify the digital signature of the Update Package.

PFM0001.Description: The utilization value of the sensor identified in the message is higher than the upper critical threshold.
PFM0001.Resolution: Check the work load of the server and reduce the workload if necessary to bring the system performance into required ranges. For more information about the specified values, see the relevant product documentation available at the support site.
PFM0001.Message: The value of %1 is greater than the upper critical threshold.

UEFI0177.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.
UEFI0177.Resolution: Only a single Quad Rank DIMM module can be installed on a channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0177.Message: A DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Quad Rank DIMM module.

SWC8531.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to set the administrator role for the iDRAC root user. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or iDRAC is rebooting.
SWC8531.Resolution: If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8531.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to set iDRAC administrator role for root user account.

HWC9004.Description: The BOSS device identified in the message does not have a fan installed in it.
HWC9004.Message: The BOSS-S1 device does not have a fan installed in it.

RAC0763.Description: Unable to configure the port number that is entered because the port number is already in use.
RAC0763.Resolution: Enter a port number that is not already in use and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0763.Message: Unable to configure the port number that is entered because the port number is already in use.

GMGR0050.Description: There are no jobs present in the current group.
GMGR0050.Message: There are no jobs present in the current group.

SRV071.Description: The SupportAssist operation to update registration information is started.
SRV071.Message: The SupportAssist operation to update registration information is started.

SRV052.Description: The Debug Logs collection operation for SupportAssist is cancelled by user.
SRV052.Message: The Debug Logs collection operation for SupportAssist is cancelled by user.

PCI1310.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1310.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1310.Message: A PCI system error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

GMGR0028.Description: The configuration clone operation cannot be completed either because of a firmware mismatch between Primary Group Controller and Group Member or because of network issues.
GMGR0028.Resolution: See iDRAC Group Manager job view for information about recommended correction action. In case of a firmware mismatch, ensure the firmware versions match each other by performing a firmware update.
GMGR0028.Message: Unable to complete the configuration clone operation either because of a firmware mismatch between Primary Group Controller and Group Member or because of network issues.

SWC0243.Description: SSL Certificate is regenerated successfully and the Web server is restarted.
SWC0243.Message: Certificate regenerated successfully and webserver restarted

RAC0639.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'minute' while scheduling a job.
RAC0639.Resolution: Enter a correct value from 0 to 59, and then retry the operation.
RAC0639.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid 'minute' value is entered.

SYS421.Description: The Active Directory object DCLookupByUserDomain cannot be disabled, because the DCLookupDomainName object of Active Directory is not configured.
SYS421.Resolution: Configure the DCLookupDomainName object by using the PATCH operation on the Redfish OemAttributes URL, and then retry the operation.
SYS421.Message: The Active Directory object DCLookupByUserDomain cannot be disabled, because the DCLookupDomainName object of Active Directory is not configured.

PR5.Description: Some or all configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to the current device. This may be due to firmware version or other differences in the part.
PR5.Resolution: Check the device's configuration and ensure that the new configuration is correct for the system.
PR5.Message: The configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to device: %1

USR0151.Description: The VNC client from the IP address identified in the message is logged off.
USR0151.Message: The remote VNC session from the IP address %1 is logging off.

UEFI0086.Description: Unsupported Small Outline Dual In-line Memory Module (SODIMM) memory is installed on the RDIMM memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0086.Resolution: Remove the unsupported SODIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0086.Message: Unsupported Small Outline Dual In-line Memory Module (SODIMM) memory is installed on RDIMM memory slot: %1.

RED079.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the parameter identified in the message.
RED079.Resolution: Verify the value for the parameter identified in the message is valid and retry the operation.
RED079.Message: The input value entered for the parameter %1 is invalid.

LIC907.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of an unknown error in the iDRAC.
LIC907.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
LIC907.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

JCP030.Description: Unable to schedule jobs for execution while an iDRAC firmware update job is running.
JCP030.Resolution: Wait for the running job to complete, and then retry the operation.
JCP030.Message: Unable to schedule jobs while an iDRAC firmware update or configuration job is running.

JCP027.Description: The (installation or configuration) job identified in the message is successfully created on iDRAC.
JCP027.Message: The (installation or configuration) job %1 is successfully created on iDRAC.

PDR70.Description: A copyback operation began to copy data from one physical disk to another physical disk. This may be due to a user initiated operation or a predictive failure.

LC085.Description: The Export Video Log operation is successfully completed and the files are exported to iDRAC Local folder.
LC085.Message: The Export Video Log operation is successfully completed and the files are exported to iDRAC Local folder.

SYS195.Description: The OEM ID Module installation process completed with no errors.
SYS195.Message: The OEM ID module is successfully installed.

UEFI0198.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Read Level Fine Training phase.
UEFI0198.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0198.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

SUP0109.Description: The firmware update cannot proceed without the TFTP IP address.
SUP0109.Message: A TFTP IP address has not been specified but is required.

SYS425.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the value entered for the property identified in the message is not supported.
SYS425.Resolution: Enter a valid value for the property in the request body and retry the operation.For information about valid values, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS425.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the value %1 entered for the property %2 is invalid.

SWC0044.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation. For more information, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0044.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0044.Message: Unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation.

LC082.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) attribute setting is disabled on the system.
LC082.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) attribute setting and then retry the operation. To enable the CSIOR setting using the RACADM command line utility, type "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart Enabled".
LC082.Message: Unable to complete the requested operation because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) attribute setting is disabled on the system.

LC050.Description: The value provided to set the attribute identified in the message is invalid.
LC050.Resolution: For more information on the valid values, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation. Retry the operation with a valid value for the SystemServicesState attribute.

RAC1146.Description: The SNMPv3 username cannot be set because SNMPv3 is not enabled for the specified user on iDRAC.
RAC1146.Resolution: Enable SNMPv3 for the specified user by running the command "racadm set iDRAC.Users.<user index>.SNMPv3Enable 1", and then retry the operation.
RAC1146.Message: Unable to set the SNMPv3 username because SNMPv3 is not enabled for the specified user on iDRAC.

AMP0304.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0304.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0304.Message: The system board %1 current is outside of range.

SWC9007.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate DeleteAll operation is successfully scheduled.
SWC9007.Resolution: Restart the host server for the changes to take effect.
SWC9007.Message: The SecureBoot Certificate DeleteAll operation is successfully scheduled. Restart the host server for the changes to take effect.

GMGR0004.Description: The iDRAC local group is successfully renamed to new name identified in the message.
GMGR0004.Message: The iDRAC local group is successfully renamed to %1.

SYS437.Description: The job cannot be created because the EndTime value entered is less than 5 minutes of StartTime value.
SYS437.Resolution: Enter an EndTime value that is greater than 5 minutes of the StartTime value.
SYS437.Message: Unable to create the job because the EndTime value entered is less than 5 minutes of StartTime value.

LNK2700.Resolution: Check network cable and network connections.

MEM1214.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed.
MEM1214.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>.

FAN900.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully enabled.
FAN900.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully enabled.

OSD42.Description: There was an error while copying the ISO image from the network share to the vFlash.
OSD42.Resolution: 1) Make sure the network connection is working. 2) Make sure the Dell vFlash does not have any hardware issues by accessing it through the iDRAC GUI.
OSD42.Message: Downloading ISO File to VFlash failed.

USR0020.Description: The specified session id does not exist and is invalid.

SWC0264.Description: The resources required for the execution are in use by another process.
SWC0264.Resolution: Wait for the process to release the resources and try again.
SWC0264.Message: Resource currently in use by another process. Please retry again later.

STOR060.Description: The requested operation is not supported on the specified storage controller.
STOR060.Resolution: For more information about supported operations, see the documentation specific for the targeted storage controller.
STOR060.Message: Configuration operations are not supported on the specified storage controller.

RED026.Description: An internal error occurred while processing the current update. The update did not complete successfully.
RED026.Message: An internal error occurred while processing updates.

VLT0234.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0234.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions. 2) Reseat the mezzanine card. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0234.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is outside of range.

RAC047.Description: The event action selected is not supported for the event filter specified.
RAC047.Resolution: Refer to the iDRAC User Guide and Lifecycle Controller documentation and retry the operation with a valid event action selection on the specified filter.
RAC047.Message: Unsupported event action for the specified event filter.

FAN0017.Description: The RPM of the fan identified in the message is functioning correctly.
FAN0017.Message: %1 RPM is within normal operating range.

PSU1001.Description: The enclosure detected that a power supply unit has failed.
PSU1001.Resolution: Check for other messages related to the state of the power supply unit/enclosure. These may help determine the cause of this event. Contact technical support if the issue still persists.

ISM0035.Description: The operating system (OS) collector service is successfully closed on the server OS.
ISM0035.Message: The operating system (OS) collector service is successfully closed on the server OS.

SWC0048.Description: The backup server profile operation did not complete because:1) The backup server configuration profile image file present on the vFlash SD card is invalid for this system.2) The passphrase entered does not match the passphrase used to secure the backup server configuration profile image file.
SWC0048.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation:1) Reinsert the vFlash SD card with correct backup image file.2) Enter the passphrase that was used to secure the backup server configuration profile image file.
SWC0048.Message: Unable to validate the backup server configuration Profile image file for this system.

STOR079.Description: The requested operation cannot be performed because it is either not supported by the device or the device was not in the right state to perform the operation.
STOR079.Resolution: Make sure the device supports the requested operation. If the operation is supported, then make sure the server is turned on and retry the operation.
STOR079.Message: The device does not support this operation or is in a state that does not allow this operation.

PWR2271.Description: The Intel Management Engine has encountered a Exception Event.
PWR2271.Resolution: Perform an AC Cycle operation on the host server, and then update the BIOS firmware to the latest version. If the issue persists, contact your service provider. For information about recommended BIOS versions, see the BIOS documentation on the support site.
PWR2271.Message: The Intel Management Engine has encountered a Exception Event.

SWC0296.Description: Either the password field or the username field is empty.
SWC0296.Resolution: Enter the command with the username and password.
SWC0296.Message: The specified value is not allowed to be configured if the user name \nor password is blank.

SEL1509.Message: Member %1 has joined the Chassis Group.

MEM8502.Description: An ECC memory condition was detected on the primary CMC and a failover was initiated.
MEM8502.Resolution: Reseat the primary CMC and initiate a failover back to the primary CMC. If the problem persists and multiple failovers occur, contact your service provider.
MEM8502.Message: ECC Memory error rate failover condition detected.

MEM9070.Description: The memory module is in its factory default state because the BIOS sent the Factory Default command to the module controller. This command erases all data in the module, disables all event notifications, and resets all module registers to their default values. The Factory Default command does not affect the firmware version of the module.
MEM9070.Message: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) with serial number %1 is reconfigured to its factory default state.

NIC012.Description: No changes to BIOS attribute data are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration.

SWC0255.Description: Unable to open the specified file.

CMC004.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the parameter identified in the message is invalid.
CMC004.Resolution: Enter a valid parameter and retry the operation. For information about valid parameters, see the CMC Profile document available on the support site.
CMC004.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the parameter %1 is invalid.

JCP013.Description: One or more required input parameters needed for the operation are missing.
JCP013.Resolution: Refer to the documentation for the operation being attempted and provide valid values for the identified parameters.

SYS043.Description: The current configuration of the system components (BIOS, RAID, NIC, iDRAC, and so on) was written to a Server Configuration Profile and successfully copied to the specified location.

STOR046.Description: Unable to complete the create virtual disk operation because the StartingLBA and Size value combination results in an overlapping virtual disk.
STOR046.Resolution: Refer to the users guide to provide the correct StartingLBA and Size combination values.
STOR046.Message: The specified StartingLBA and Size values combination result in an overlapping virtual disk.

PCI3007.Message: Link Tuning or FlexAddress data successfully obtained.

SEC0607.Message: The network boot password violation was corrected.

SYS254.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of one or more of the following: 1) remote host cannot be reached. 2) remote share name is not present. 3) incorrect credentials were entered.
SYS254.Resolution: Make sure that the file transfer parameters are correct, and then retry the operation.
SYS254.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of one or more of the following: 1) remote host cannot be reached. 2) remote share name is not present. 3) incorrect credentials are entered.

OSD71.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'Password' is missing.
OSD71.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "Password" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD71.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'Password' is missing.

SWC0152.Message: RAC configuration from file completed successfully

POW001.Description: Host failed to power up because chassis cover is open. This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2251.
POW001.Message: Power on permission error, chassis cover open.

RAC1038.Description: Unable to clear pending values for the specified component. This may be because there is an existing configuration job for the component.
RAC1038.Resolution: Make sure that a config job is not scheduled for this component. For more information, view the help command by running the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue help delete".
RAC1038.Message: Unable to clear pending values for the specified component.

USR0019.Description: The specified username exceeds the prescribed limit (255).
USR0019.Message: Specified user name is too long.

VFL0713.Resolution: Detach the partitions and try again.
VFL0713.Message: One or more partitions are currently attached; the SD card could not be initialized.

SWU8551.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC was not successful, because of a firmware image checksum error.
SWU8551.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8551.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Active CMC. The checksum process was not successful.

CTL78.Description: This alert message occurs if controller firmware is flashed.

SUP0530.Description: The catalog repository path entered is not accessible.
SUP0530.Resolution: Retry the operation with the correct catalog repository path.

RAC0697.Description: Choose to create a job from the existing successful pending operations.
RAC0697.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Click Pending Operations button to view pending operations. 2) Click Create Job button to create a configuration job. 3) Click Cancel button to quit job creation.
RAC0697.Message: Choose to create a job from the existing successful pending operations.

SYS202.Description: The disk erase operation cannot be completed on the drive identified in the message.
SYS202.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the System Erase operation. To retry the System Erase operation by using the Lifecycle Controller utility, restart the server. When the company logo is displayed, press F10. Select Hardware Configuration > Retire or Repurpose System, Select the appropriate options under Storage & Physical Disks, and then retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, erase the drive manually.
SYS202.Message: Unable to complete the disk erase operation on the drive %1.

LC032.Description: This method is not supported in the current version of iDRAC firmware.
LC032.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware to a version that supports this method.
LC032.Message: The Hardware Inventory Export method not supported.

PWR8556.Description: The Server identified in the message was shutdown due to insufficient power.
PWR8556.Message: Server %1 was shutdown due to insufficient power.

RAC0907.Description: The System ID LED was successfully set to on.

LC054.Description: The network share may be read-only or it may not have sufficient space for the export operation.
LC054.Resolution: Verify the network share is not read-only and has sufficient space for exporting, then retry the operation.
LC054.Message: Unable to write to the network share.

RAC1013.Description: For any iDRAC user, SNMPv3 authentication protocol can be changed to "None" only if the SNMPv3 privacy protocol state is set to "None".
RAC1013.Resolution: Change the SNMPv3 privacy protocol state to 'None' using "racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.SNMPv3PrivacyType none", and retry the operation.
RAC1013.Message: The SNMPv3 authentication protocol state cannot be set to None if the SNMPv3 privacy protocol state is set to None.

SUP0516.Description: Do not turn off the system while firmware update is in progress.

SWU8520.Description: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC identified in the message is not successful.
SWU8520.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the original source, and then retry the operation.
SWU8520.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is not successful.

ENC29.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

LC006.Description: The Auto-Discovery action selected is invalid.
