LC006.Resolution: Verify that the selected Auto-Discovery action is supported. The supported commands are documented in the Lifecycle Controller User Guide.

MEM9004.Description: A link degradation was detected in propagation of signals between processors through the Intel QPI interconnect interconnect identified in the message. The system will continue to operate at reduced performance.
MEM9004.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the server and check whether the issue persists. 2) If the issue is not resolved by the preceding action, reseat the processors and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

SYS121.Description: The operation to collect OS and Application Data was cancelled using iDRAC Web UI.
SYS121.Message: The operation to collect OS and Application Data was cancelled using iDRAC Web UI.

RFL2000.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is present.

CMC8612.Description: The Link Tuning Table is successfully updated by using iDRAC on the slot identified in the message.
CMC8612.Message: The Link Tuning Table is successfully updated by using iDRAC on slot %1.

BAR091.Description: A System Profile Backup request made by the user of the Unified Server Configurator interface has completed.

SWC8540.Description: The Public Key (PK) SSH Authentication key file is successfully uploaded to the Chassis Management Controller.
SWC8540.Message: The add key operation successfully completed for slot %1 of service account.

UEFI0145.Description: The Trusted Platform Module (TPM) installed on this system is not supported.
UEFI0145.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the BIOS firmware. 2) Replace the TPM with a supported one. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0145.Message: The Trusted Platform Module (TPM) installed on this system is not supported.

DIS006.Description: Auto Discovery operation was successful in establishing connection and getting certificate. Auto Discovery feature is no longer needed and has been disabled.
DIS006.Message: Auto Discovery operation successful. Disabling Auto Discovery feature.

PR19.Description: The specified job has completed successfully.

OSD27.Description: Copying drivers for selected operating system failed. The Driver Pack may be unusable.
OSD27.Resolution: Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and then rerun the command.
OSD27.Message: Copying drivers for selected operating system failed.

RAC1188.Description: Unable to configure the Upper Non-Critical value for the System Performance sensor because the value provided is not in valid range.
RAC1188.Resolution: Specify a value in the range of 0 to 100 to set the upper non-critical value.
RAC1188.Message: Unable to configure the Upper Non-Critical value for the System Performance sensor.

SWC8504.Description: The Profile identified in the message was renamed and the description for the Profile was edited.
SWC8504.Message: %1 Profile renamed to %2 and description edited.

MEM0004.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.
MEM0004.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. Review product documentation for supported memory configurations. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM0004.Message: Memory device at location %1 is disabled.

STOR0503.Description: Existing RAID configuration was successfully erased.

CTL110.Description: The Patrol ReadRate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL110.Message: The Patrol Read Rate of %1 is set to %2.

CTL56.Description: The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation. This text is from events in the controller event log that were generated while Storage Management was not running.
CTL56.Resolution: See the hardware documentation for more information.

PWR8572.Description: The server identified in the message can be shutdown only if the server is turned on.
PWR8572.Message: Unable to shutdown the server %1 because the server is off.

UEFI0012.Description: A CPU page fault (type 0x0E) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment. A program accessed a page mapped in the virtual address space, but not loaded in physical memory.
UEFI0012.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

UEFI0160.Description: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit.
UEFI0160.Resolution: Check the total number of ranks in the channel to make sure it does not exceed the maximum allowed limit. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0160.Message: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit on memory slots: %1.

SUP0104.Description: The source path needs to be lesser than 64 characters.

SWC0057.Description: Unable to copy the file to the network share because it does not have the specified folder, the specified folder name has space between the characters, does not have enough free space, or is read-only.
SWC0057.Resolution: Make sure that the network share has the specified folder, the specified folder name has no space between the characters, has enough free space, or is not read-only. If the problem persists, perform an AC power cycle and retry the operation.
SWC0057.Message: Unable to export the file to the network share.

SRV095.Description: The SupportAssist End User License Agreement (EULA) is already accepted by the iDRAC user <user name> by using the iDRAC interface <interface name>.
SRV095.Message: The SupportAssist End User License Agreement (EULA) is already accepted by the iDRAC user %1 by using the iDRAC interface %2.

PDR46.Description: The Patrol Read task has encountered an error that cannot be corrected. There may be a bad disk block that cannot be remapped.
PDR46.Resolution: Backup your data from the disk. Start disk initialization and wait for it to complete, then restore the data from the backup to the disk.
PDR46.Message: Patrol Read found an uncorrectable media error on %1.

UEFI0272.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the BIOS cannot obtain the initiator information from DHCPv4 server.
UEFI0272.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Check the configuration of DHCPv4 server. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable DHCP and configure the initiator information manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0272.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the BIOS cannot obtain the initiator information from DHCPv4 server.

CTL64.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL64.Message: Attempted to import Unsupported Virtual Disk type RAID%1 on %2.

CMC8516.Description: The I/O module may have taken more time to boot than was expected or the I/O module did not boot.
CMC8516.Resolution: Verify the I/O Module is turned on using CMC Web Interface or RACADM CLI and retry the operation. Otherwise, reinsert the I/O Module and retry the operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support.
CMC8516.Message: The I/O Module %1 did not boot within the expected time.

PSU0035.Resolution: Check input power, replace or re-install the power supply. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0035.Message: An over voltage fault detected on power supply %1.

LIC019.Description: A leased license may not be imported prior to the actual start date of the license.
LIC019.Resolution: Import the license on or after the license start date.
LIC019.Message: A leased license may not be imported prior to its start date.

BAT1026.Description: The controller has retrieved cached data.
BAT1026.Message: The %1 has recovered cached data from the Battery Backup Unit (BBU).

HWC2011.Description: The riser blade cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC2011.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC2011.Message: The riser board cable or interconnect is not connected, or is improperly connected.

UEFI0100.Description: The Memory Mirroring feature cannot be enabled because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.
UEFI0100.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0100.Message: Unable to enable the Memory Mirroring feature because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.

FC007.Description: Configuration job already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job succeeded or the job is cancelled.
FC007.Resolution: Wait for the existing job to complete or cancel the existing job and retry the operation.
FC007.Message: A configuration job already exists. Unable to create another configuration job on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled.

PDR16.Description: The physical disk is predicted to fail. Many physical disks contain Self Monitoring Analysis and Reporting Technology (SMART). When enabled, SMART monitors the disk health based on indications such as the number of write operations that were performed on the disk.
PDR16.Resolution: Replace the physical disk. Even though the disk may not have failed yet, it is strongly recommended that the disk be replaced. Review other messages for additional information.

JCP042.Description: The (installation or configuration) job identified in the message cannot be run. For more information, see the Job Queue.
JCP042.Resolution: Review the LC Log for related update, configuration, or collection job errors. Retry the operation. If the problem persists, contact your service provider.
JCP042.Message: Unable to run the (installation or configuration) job %1 because %2.

RAC0727.Description: Auto-throttling is enabled for the server based on a request from the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) because the CMC has restarted.
RAC0727.Message: Auto-throttling is enabled for the server.

RFM1035.Message: Media is present for Removable Flash Media.

PDR44.Description: A Clear task was being performed on a physical disk but the task was interrupted and did not complete successfully. The controller may have lost communication with the disk, the disk was removed, or the cables may be loose or defective.
PDR44.Resolution: Verify that the disk is present and not in a Failed state. Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables. Restart the Clear task.

SWC0105.Description: The command does not take in the -m option.
SWC0105.Resolution: Refer the help text for getraclog command.
SWC0105.Message: Invalid -m option. Try --more or refer help for proper usage.

SWU8530.Description: The process for iKVM firmware update was not successful.
SWU8530.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8530.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware.

LIC008.Description: All bound perpetual licenses contain the unique identifier of a specific device. The unique identifier binds a license to the device. For example, iDRAC's unique identifier is the service tag.
LIC008.Resolution: Obtain a new license file with the correct unique identifier for the device. To use this license, import to the device with the correct unique identifier.
LIC008.Message: The license binding ID does not match the device unique identifier.

UEFI0112.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during the LRDIMM interface initialization.
UEFI0112.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0112.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

USR0182.Description: Server information has been accessed by using the iDRAC Quick Sync feature.
USR0182.Message: Server information has been accessed by using the iDRAC Quick Sync feature.

GMGR0009.Description: The server having the Service Tag identified in the message is assigned as the Primary Controller of the group identified in the message. Hereafter, all group tasks can be done from the Primary Controller.
GMGR0009.Message: The server %1 is successfully assigned as the Primary Controller of the group %2.

SWC8511.Description: The user name identified in the message was added successfully.

PST0192.Description: System BIOS shutdown test failed during POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code C0).
PST0192.Resolution: Check system event log for CMOS battery exceptions. Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

GMGR0051.Description: The operation cannot be completed because Grouped Servers are not detected in the group.
GMGR0051.Resolution: Wait for some time, because the group initialization may take time. If the issue persists, do the following: 1) Verify that the group was not deleted by reviewing lifecycle logs. 2) Disable, and then enable the Group Manager by using the iDRAC home page. 3) Make sure that network connections are correct. 4)If the iDRAC was already part of group, logged into the group manager and if the group deletion job is successful, log out and log in to the iDRAC Group Manager. 5) Log out, and then log in to the iDRAC Group Manager. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
GMGR0051.Message: Unable to complete the operation because Grouped Servers are not detected in the group.

RDU8513.Description: The firmware version of Active CMC and Standby CMC are the same.

RAC0223.Description: The Subject line in the email contains invalid characters.
RAC0223.Resolution: Invalid character. Enter a valid value as mentioned in the online help.
RAC0223.Message: Enter an alphanumeric value or a valid symbol for the following (see the online help for more information).

PWR207.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.
PWR207.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR207.Message: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.

BAR078.Description: The collection and export of Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC)firmware was not successful.
BAR078.Resolution: Apply the integrated remote access controller firmware, manually set the configuration attributes, and try the operation again.
BAR078.Message: Unable to collect the Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

LIC201.Description: This license is going to expire. An expired license could result in the loss of functionality that is specific to the features supported by the license.
LIC201.Resolution: Purchase a new license to prevent interruption of licensed features.
LIC201.Message: License %1 assigned to device %2 expires in %3 days.

CMC8564.Description: The KVM is not mapped to any of the server slots.
CMC8564.Message: The KVM mapping feature is disabled.

RED068.Description: Unable to successfully complete the job identified in the message.
RED068.Resolution: For more information about the job, view the job queue.

SYS184.Description: The checksum cannot be computed because OS Collector files are not readable.
SYS184.Resolution: Reinstall the OS Collector in the iDRAC and retry the operation. To install the OS Collector using the iDRAC Web UI, get the latest OC Collector update package and then select the Update and Rollback link from the iDRAC Web UI home page and upload the install package. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SYS184.Message: Unable to compute the checksum because OS Collector files are not readable.

SYS054.Description: The current configuration for components that require staged configuration already match the configuration specified by the input file. A system restart to apply staged configuration is not required.
SYS054.Message: No configuration changes requiring a system restart need to be applied.

RAC1168.Description: The RACADM "getconfig" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.
RAC1168.Resolution: Run the RACADM "racadm get" command to retrieve the iDRAC configuration parameters. For more information on the get command, run the RACADM command "racadm help get".
RAC1168.Message: The RACADM "getconfig" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.

SYS268.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the proxy operation is taking longer time than the set time limit of the proxy configuration. The other possible reasons are: 1) issue in the network 2) remote host server may not be turned on 1) remote host server is turned on but not functioning 4) an issue in protocol negotiation.
SYS268.Resolution: Check the file transfer parameters, health of the remote host, the proxy time limit configuration and then retry the operation.
SYS268.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the proxy operation is taking longer time than the set time limit.

NIC008.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. To create a Configuration job, at least one attribute should be changed.
NIC008.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes and then create a configuration job.
NIC008.Message: No pending data present to create a Configuration job

RAC938.Description: The configuration XML file export operation was successfully initiated after it was invoked by the user specified in the message.
RAC938.Message: Successfully initiated configuration XML file export operation invoked by the %1.

SYS419.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because the Redfish attribute is disabled.
SYS419.Resolution: Make sure that the Redfish.1.Enable attribute is set to Enabled by running the HTTP PATCH method on "Managers OemAttributes" Redfish API, and then retry the operation.
SYS419.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the Redfish attribute is disabled.

SUP0519.Description: The update firmware image operation is unable to process the firmware image provided. The image is invalid or incompatible with the installed component.
SUP0519.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0519.Message: Unable to validate firmware image for %1.

PSU0004.Description: The operating requirements for the power supply may be found in product documentation or on the power supply itself.
PSU0004.Resolution: Verify the input source is attached to the power supply. Verify the input power is within the operating requirements for the power supply.
PSU0004.Message: The power input for power supply %1 is outside of range.

JCP028.Description: An install or configuration job status is successfully updated on iDRAC.

ENC8.Description: You have disabled the enclosure alarm.

PDR31.Description: The controller cannot to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a global hot spare. The disk either failed or was removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.
PDR31.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and installed. Check the cables. Refer to the product documentation and see the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the global hot spare.
PDR31.Message: A global hot spare has been removed.%1

BAT0003.Message: The system board battery is present.

PDR114.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message is between 90% and 100% of reaching read-only mode.

VLT0206.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0206.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0206.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

OSD36.Description: User has cancelled system services by using the CTRL+E option (iDRAC configuration utility) or F2 option during POST. This action cancels the WSMAN request to boot to ISO.
OSD36.Resolution: To resolve the issue rerun the command. Do not cancel system services using CTRL+E or F2 during POST when system is rebooting to the ISO.
OSD36.Message: Boot to ISO Image has been cancelled by using CTRL+E or F2 option on the server.

CMC8547.Description: A firmware error occurred causing the failover. If this condition continues, a failover will result. If multiple failovers occur, contact Service.
CMC8547.Resolution: No response action is required. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8547.Message: Missing kernel module %1. Failover condition detected.

BOOT015.Description: The boot partition configuration request was successful. An unattached vFlash partition was configured for one-time boot using the ChangeBootOrderByInstanceID method. The method creates a job (to attach the vFlash partition and set the partition for one-time boot.
BOOT015.Message: Set operation successful for the boot partition.

ASR0001.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC) within the timeout period. The system was reset per the configured setting.
ASR0001.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0001.Message: The watchdog timer reset the system.

PST0130.Description: During memory configuration system BIOS encountered device failures or speed configurations that resulted in unused memory. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 82).
PST0130.Resolution: Remove input power. Reseat memory devices or reduce system to minimum supported memory configuration.
PST0130.Message: Memory is configured, but not usable.

STOR064.Description: Unable to create the requested virtual disk because the physical disks specified did not have the same block size.
STOR064.Resolution: Verify that the physical disks selected for creating the virtual disk have the same block size and retry the operation. The block size can be determined by reviewing the physical disk inventory and checking the BlockSize property for each physical disk.
STOR064.Message: One or more physical disks specified for creating a virtual disk do not have the same block size.

SYS420.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the Redfish URI version identified in the message is not supported.
SYS420.Resolution: Enter a valid URI version and retry the operation. For information about valid URI versions, see the Redfish User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS420.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the Redfish URI version %1 is not supported.

VFL1003.Description: The removable flash media is installed but improperly configured or failed to initialize.
VFL1003.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media and module.
VFL1003.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is not IPMI-function ready.

OSD66.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'OSName' is missing.
OSD66.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "OSName" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD66.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'OSName' is missing.

PR14.Description: The device identified in the message could not apply the configuration settings. This may indicate configuration changes since the last system inventory.
PR14.Resolution: Check the current system configuration and retry the operation.
PR14.Message: The configuration could not be applied to device: %1

PCI5008.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) could not successfully connect to the PCIe switch board.
PCI5008.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Perform an AC Power Cycle operation on the Chassis by disconnecting the chassis from AC power, waiting for 30 seconds, and then reconnecting AC power. 2) Power on at least one server. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Server Overview->Power->Control and then click the Operation field and select the Power On Server operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PCI5008.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to communicate with the PCIe switch board.

PWR2401.Description: The iDRAC controller detected that the power management firmware did not initialize properly. The system may operate in a performance degraded state.
PWR2401.Resolution: 1) Disconnect system input power, wait one minute, reconnect system input power.2) Re-flash system BIOS.3) Upgrade system BIOS to the latest revision.

CTL82.Description: The controller identified in the message is functioning normally.

RAC1215.Description: The certificate cannot be imported because the certificate being imported already exists in the database.
RAC1215.Resolution: Delete the existing certificate, restart the host server, and then retry the operation.To know how to Delete, run sub-command help "racadm bioscert help delete". For further information, see the RACADM CLI Reference Guide available on the support site.
RAC1215.Message: Unable to import the certificate because the certificate being imported already exists in the database.

RAC1143.Description: The job identified in the message is not a configuration job, a configuration XML import or preview type job that generates configuration results.
RAC1143.Message: Configuration results are not applicable for the job type for Job: %1.

RAC065.Description: The iDRAC reset operation was not successful. This may be due to IPMI communications issues.
RAC065.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, remove AC input power from the server and re-apply AC power to the server and retry the operation. 3) If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
RAC065.Message: iDRAC reset operation was not successful.

SYS135.Description: The user context the OS Collector is being run in does not have the necessary privileges for running the application successfully.
SYS135.Resolution: Run the OS Collector application as administrator or as a user added to admin group or domain administrator or Local administrator.
SYS135.Message: OS Collector: The user context the OS Collector is being run in does not have the necessary privileges for running the application successfully.

CMC8517.Description: A double height server is detected in slot specified in the message, however the server is not detected in the bottom slot. This occurs if the server is not correctly inserted into the chassis.
CMC8517.Resolution: Remove the server from the chassis, check for any broken or bent pins at the rear of the server. If there is no damage, reinsert the server into the chassis.
CMC8517.Message: A double height server is detected in slot %1, however the server is not detected in the bottom slot.

SWC8613.Description: The selected profile does not contain setting information for the boot list identified in the message in a usable format.
SWC8613.Resolution: Recreate the profile or use a different profile.
SWC8613.Message: Unable to fully extract %1 boot list settings from the profile.

PWR206.Description: The Server Based Power Management (SBPM) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.
PWR206.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR206.Message: The Server Based Power Management (SBPM) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.

UEFI0278.Description: The Post Package Repair (PPR) operation cannot be completed because of an issue in the DIMM memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0278.Resolution: Replace the DIMM and retry the operation. For more information, see the platform Owners Manual. .
UEFI0278.Message: Unable to complete the Post Package Repair (PPR) operation because of an issue in the DIMM memory slot %1.

PSU0042.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0042.Message: An output over current fault detected on power supply %1.

GMGR0064.Description: The group job cannot be stopped because it is not in the active state. Only a job in running state can be stopped. Scheduled and completed group jobs cannot be stopped.
GMGR0064.Message: Unable to stop the group job because it is not an actively running job.

SWC0318.Description: The value for -s must be greater than zero.
SWC0318.Resolution: Enter a value greater than zero, for the option -s.
SWC0318.Message: The starting record must be greater than zero.

VFL0007.Description: The operations could not be completed because a vFlash SD Card is not detected.
VFL0007.Resolution: Confirm an SD Card is present in the vFlash SD Card reader slot. Otherwise, insert an SD Card and retry the operation.
VFL0007.Message: No vFlash SD card is present.

VDR9.Description: A consistency check operation on a virtual disk has started.

PSU0911.Message: Soft power control restored on power unit %1.

RAC928.Description: Racadm unable to set the recurrence value. This occurs if the underlying instrumentation do not set the value.
RAC928.Resolution: Wait for a few minutes and retry the command. If the problem persists, contact the service provider.
RAC928.Message: Unable to modify the recurrence value.

UEFI0223.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Receive Buffer Per Bit Deskew Training phase.
UEFI0223.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0223.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SYS431.Description: The import or export configuration changes cannot be applied because an import or export operation is currently in progress.
SYS431.Resolution: Wait for the current import or export operation to complete and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SYS431.Message: Unable to apply the configuration changes because an import or export operation is currently in progress.

CTL107.Description: The Rebuild Rate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL107.Message: The Rebuild Rate of %1 is set to %2.

UEFI0245.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization failed to configure all installed processors to the maximum common frequency.
UEFI0245.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0245.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) link initialization error detected.

UEFI0254.Description: Unable to enable NUMA Fault Resilient Memory operating mode because of channel configuration mismatches.
UEFI0254.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0254.Message: Unable to enable NUMA Fault Resilient Memory operating mode because of channel configuration mismatches.

SRV105.Description: Unable to detect the host network connection because the network connection in the host operating system is not available.
SRV105.Resolution: Make sure the network connection in host operating system is available. If network connection requires proxy settings, enter the proxy settings in the iDRAC and retry the operation.
SRV105.Message: Unable to detect the host network connection because the network connection in the host operating system is not available.

UEFI0195.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Read Training phase.
UEFI0195.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0195.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RAC0645.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'recurrence frequency' while scheduling a job.
RAC0645.Resolution: Enter a correct value, and then retry the operation.
RAC0645.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid value is entered for the recurrence frequency.

RAC0747.Description: Unable to perform reset configuration on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0747.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes.
RAC0747.Message: Unable to perform reset configuration on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

PR23.Description: The specified job is ready to start. It is waiting for scheduling from job control. This message is no longer in use in Lifecycle Controller 2.0 as the job control functionality handles this operation.

RSI0003.Description: The Remote Service database is being updated.
RSI0003.Message: The remote service is reloading data

RED032.Description: The rollback firmware images previously stored were deleted to provide space for storing the firmware images for the requested operation. All the rollback firmware images are deleted.
RED032.Message: Reached maximum size limit allowed for storing firmware images. Deleted all rollback firmware images.

SWC0052.Description: An error occurred while retrieving the operating system drivers.
SWC0052.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and update the system with the latest operating system driver packs available from the service provider and retry the operation. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller user's guide.
SWC0052.Message: Unable to continue with OS Deployment operation.

PDR11.Description: A user has cancelled the rebuild operation.

RAC1212.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the Secure Boot policy is set to Standard.
RAC1212.Resolution: Reset the Secure Boot policy to Custom by running the following RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation:"racadm set bios.syssecurity.securebootpolicy Custom". For more information, see the RACADM CLI Reference Guide available on the support site.
RAC1212.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the Secure Boot policy is set to Standard.

HWC0009.Description: The vFlash SD card is missing or not inserted correctly. iDRAC is not able to enable vFlash SD card.
HWC0009.Resolution: Reinsert the vFlash SD card and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
HWC0009.Message: Unable to enable vFlash SD card.

LOG008.Description: The complete Lifecycle Log was successfully created for a requested export operation.
LOG008.Message: The complete Lifecycle Log was successfully created for an export operation.

NIC011.Description: Configuration job already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job is completed.
NIC011.Resolution: Cancel the configuration job or wait for the job to complete. Refer to documentation on job cancellation.
NIC011.Message: Configuration job already created, pending data cannot be deleted

STOR043.Description: One or more physical disk drives selected for the operation are part of a virtual disk that is not Secondary RAID Level 0.
STOR043.Resolution: This operation is not supported unless the previous virtual disk on the selected physical disk drives are deleted first. To perform the operation, delete any virtual disk on the selected physical disks drives and retry the operation.
STOR043.Message: One or more selected physical disk drives are part of virtual disk that is not Secondary RAID Level 0.

PDR23.Description: A disk is degraded and has received a SMART alert (predictive failure). The disk is likely to fail in the near future.
PDR23.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk will cause the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.

BAT1021.Description: The controller battery cannot maintain sufficient charge level to function properly or the battery is discharging.
BAT1021.Resolution: Check for other events related to the state of the battery. These may help determine the cause of this event.
BAT1021.Message: The charge level for the battery on %1 is below the normal threshold.

LNK8501.Description: The network connection of the identified server to the external network is restored.
LNK8501.Message: The network connection of server in slot %1 IOM in slot %2 port %3 is restarted.

LC073.Description: An SSL Certificate cannot be generated because of internal firmware issues.
LC073.Resolution: Make sure that the security attributes are valid and retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC by invoking the WS-Man iDRACReset method which is defined in the DCIM_iDRACCardService class , and then retry the operation.
LC073.Message: Unable to generate an SSL Certificate because of internal firmware issues.

PSU8520.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature is supported and fully operational.
PSU8520.Message: Enhanced Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is fully supported.

HWC0004.Description: The vFlash SD card is incorrectly inserted, the vFlash SD card is faulty, or there is an iDRAC communication failure.
HWC0004.Resolution: Reinsert or replace the vFlash SD card, or reset iDRAC, and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
HWC0004.Message: Unable to initialize vFlash SD card.

STOR0104.Description: No virtual disk data to display. The system is powered off, physical disks are not present on the system, or virtual disks are not created.
STOR0104.Resolution: Check if the server has power, physical disks are available, and virtual disks are created.

SWC0223.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0223.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0223.Message: Invalid syntax. The -d option is not valid with -p.

SWC0054.Description: There was an internal error while saving the settings.
SWC0054.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system or update the Lifecycle Controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.

AMP0302.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0302.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0302.Message: The system board %1 current is greater than the upper warning threshold.

SRV072.Description: The partition containing the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer is detached from Host operating system (OS).
SRV072.Message: The partition containing the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer is detached from Host operating system (OS).

MEM1003.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM1003.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to transition to in test.

SRV030.Description: The OS Collector Application is unable to collect data about OS and application because the OS installed on the server is not supported by OS Collector.
SRV030.Message: The OS Collector Application is unable to collect data about OS and application because the OS installed on the server is not supported by OS Collector.

SWU8500.Description: This message is displayed when:1. A reboot job is unable to provide a valid reboot ID.2. The WSMAN command to set up a job queue on Lifecycle Controller was not successful.
SWU8500.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the error persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8500.Message: The %1 request to Lifecycle Controller on server %2 was not successful.

SYS260.Description: Unable to transfer a file because the destination file system does not have sufficient free space or does not have sufficient free user quota.
SYS260.Resolution: Make sure that the following are correct and retry the operation: a) file transfer parameters b) remote host file system free space.
SYS260.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the destination file system does not have sufficient free space or does not have sufficient free user quota.

PWR204.Description: Object value is successfully modified. Max Power Conservation Mode will deactivate the Extended Power Performance feature.
PWR204.Message: Object value is successfully modified. Max Power Conservation Mode will deactivate the Extended Power Performance feature.

CMC8548.Description: The active Chassis Management Controller is not connected to an external network for more than 25 seconds. A failover is performed if the standby CMC is connected to the external network.
CMC8548.Resolution: Make sure that the external network cable is connected to the active CMC and the network switch. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8548.Message: The active Chassis Management Controller is no longer connected to an external network.

MEM1015.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in a power active state.

SWC8529.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to enable the iDRAC root user. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or iDRAC is rebooting.
SWC8529.Resolution: If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8529.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to enable the iDRAC root user.

SWC1917.Description: HTTP to HTTPS redirection is disabled. Any iDRAC connection made over the HTTP port (default port number 80) will no longer be redirected to the secure HTTPS port (default port number 443). This will make the connections insecure as the data transmitted over the port is no longer encrypted.

SWC5008.Description: The <name> cannot be accessed because of a hardware error condition.
SWC5008.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation available on the support site to choose a convenient contact method.
SWC5008.Message: Unable to access %1 because of a hardware error condition.

RAC0770.Description: The network connection to the remote system cannot be started because incorrect network information is entered.
RAC0770.Resolution: Enter correct network data and retry the operation. To reset the network properties, on the graphical user interface (GUI), in the left pane, click Network. On the Network page, type appropriate data in the fields, and then click Save. For more information about description of data to be entered in the fields, press F1 on the GUI to read the online help information.To reset network properties by using RACADM command run "racadm set iDRAC.RFS" at the command line(CLI). If the issue persists contact your service provider.
RAC0770.Message: Unable to connect to the remote system because incorrect network information is entered.

RAC1119.Description: The command could not be successfully run because of one or more of the following reasons:1. The command does not have "--verifycatalog" in it.2. The updates available on the repository are not applicable for the operation that is requested.
RAC1119.Resolution: To generate a comparison report, type "--verifycatalog" in the racadm command, and then retry the operation.
RAC1119.Message: Unable to generate a comparison report for the specified repository.

SEC0100.Description: The Storage disk tray identified in the message is open. The tray should be closed as soon as any service action is completed. Leaving the tray open for an extended period may result in drives over heating.
SEC0100.Resolution: Close the Storage disk tray identified in the message.

SWU8516.Description: iDRAC firmware update operation was not successful. The firmware Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8516.Resolution: Make sure the iDRAC firmware Image file is available in the given path and retry the operation.
SWU8516.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware on the server in slot %1. Transfer is not successful. ErrorCode=0x%2.

UEFI0266.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 subnet mask address is invalid.
UEFI0266.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the Initiator Subnet Mask field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0266.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 subnet mask address is invalid.

SWC1914.Description: Network Time Protocol configuration is disabled.
SWC1914.Message: Network Time Protocol configuration is disabled.

RAC1195.Description: User requested state / configuration change using specified interface.
RAC1195.Message: User %1 via IP %2 requested state / configuration change to %3 using %4.

LOG508.Description: The network share may be read-only or it may not have sufficient space for the export operation.
LOG508.Resolution: Verify the network share is not read-only and has sufficient space for exporting, then retry the operation.
LOG508.Message: Unable to write to the network share.

SYS131.Description: Unable to communicate with the OS IPMI service because the service is not running.
SYS131.Resolution: For more information about checking whether the IPMI service is running, see the iDRAC8 User's Guide.
SYS131.Message: OS Collector: Unable to communicate with the OS IPMI service.

RAC1018.Description: This occurs when an incorrect syntax is used or an incorrect object is specified during the command invocation.
RAC1018.Resolution: Make sure to use the correct syntax and correct object names, and retry the operation. For information related to the corresponding group, see RACADM help or the RACADM User's Guide.
RAC1018.Message: The specified object or syntax is invalid.

RED031.Description: The internal space available for storing firmware images is almost full. Normal operations will continue until the critical limit is reached. When the critical limit is reached, all the rollback firmware images will be deleted.
RED031.Message: Approaching maximum size limit allowed for storing firmware images.

UEFI0017.Description: Unable to locate a file required to run Lifecycle Controller. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0017.Resolution: Repair Lifecycle Controller firmware using the Lifecycle Controller Dell Update Package (DUP) or Lifecycle Controller Repair Package via iDRAC. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
UEFI0017.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible and is therefore in Recovery mode.

SWC0304.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0304.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0304.Message: The -g option requires -u to also be specified.

PCI3019.Description: A low-severity issue was detected in the SSD bay identified in the message.
PCI3019.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the component identified in the message, and then monitor the log for a re-occurrence of the issue. If the issue persists, and occurs during server startup, update the component firmware. If the issue persists and occurs during OS runtime, restart the server and update the OS drivers for the component identified in the message.
PCI3019.Message: A low-severity issue is detected in the SSD bay %1, Slot %2.

FAN8503.Description: The Chassis was turned off because more than two Chassis internal fans stopped functioning. The fans with issues are identified in the CMC Hardware (System Event Log) and Chassis Logs.
FAN8503.Resolution: Make sure that the Chassis internal fans are functioning. At the command line interface (CLI), enter the following command to identify fans that are not functioning: "racadm getsel". Using the CMC Web GUI, select the chassis, click the Logs tab, and then select Hardware Log. Reinsert or replace fans that are not functioning correctly.
FAN8503.Message: The Chassis was turned off because more than two internal fans stopped functioning.

SWC0140.Message: RAC reset operation initiated successfully. It may take up to a minute for the RAC to come back online again.

SRV077.Description: The SupportAssist operation to present iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer to Host operating system (OS) did not complete successfully.
SRV077.Resolution: Make sure the Host OS allows access to USB devices and then retry the action.
SRV077.Message: The SupportAssist operation to present iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer to Host operating system (OS) did not complete successfully.

CTL24.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL24.Message: Abort CC on Error and Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.

PWR8670.Description: The server identified in the message cannot be turned on if the Connector Limit for the subsystems identified in the message is exceeded .
PWR8670.Resolution: Make sure the system operates within the subsystem Connector Limit for the components specified. To review power budget information select Chassis Overview -> Power -> Budget Status. Turn off unused components within the subsystem to make power available for the server to turn on or turn off low priority servers and try the operation again.
PWR8670.Message: Unable to turn on server%1 because the required power %2 AC Watts exceeds the subsystem Connector Limit %3 AC Watts for IO modules, Blowers and Servers.

RAC032.Description: The DNS RAC name specified is not valid.
RAC032.Resolution: Retry operation with valid DNS RAC name.
RAC032.Message: Invalid value specified for DNS RAC name.

MEM1006.Message: Memory device at location %1 is online.

SWC8516.Description: Unable to modify privileges of the User identified in the message.
SWC8516.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8516.Message: Unable to modify privileges of User %1: %2-%3

SWC5002.Resolution: Check system logs for minor errors.
SWC5002.Message: %1 upgrade was successful but encountered minor errors.

RAC0500.Description: Batteries cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off or there is a bad or disconnected cable for batteries connected to the controller.
RAC0500.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Verify that the batteries are connected properly.
RAC0500.Message: There are no batteries to be displayed.

STOR0510.Description: Unable to apply the RAID controller encryption because RAID controller is not responding.
STOR0510.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system or update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.

UEFI0233.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - FIFO Reset phase.
UEFI0233.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0233.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC0690.Description: The iDRAC Service Module is not installed on the operating system of the server.
RAC0690.Resolution: Install the iDRAC Service Module and retry the operation.
RAC0690.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is not installed on the operating system of the server.

VDR37.Description: Disk space that was formerly "dead" or inaccessible to a redundant virtual disk has been restored. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR37.Message: Dead disk segments are restored on %1.

SRV126.Description: The SupportAssist data cannot be retrieved from SupportAssist server because of an issue between iDRAC and SupportAssist server.
SRV126.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and server OS. 3) If the issue persists, retry the operation after some time as SupportAssist back-end server might be under maintenance.
SRV126.Message: Unable to retrieve the data from SupportAssist server because of an issue between iDRAC and SupportAssist server.

PDR117.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message has turned off because the critical temperature threshold of the device was exceeded.
PDR117.Resolution: Contact your service provider for further instructions.
PDR117.Message: The %1 has turned off because the critical temperature threshold is exceeded.

LOG501.Description: The command cannot be run because a general issue occurred.
LOG501.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the CMC, and then retry the operation.
LOG501.Message: Unable to run the command because of a general issue.

RAC1061.Description: The requested SystemErase operation was initiated successfully.
RAC1061.Resolution: Check the job status by running the RACADM command: "racadm jobqueue view -i <JobID>".

PDR218.Description: The Patrol Read operation detected a media error (bad block) on the disk drive identified in the message and automatically corrected the error. The Patrol Read automatically remapped data to correct the error.
PDR218.Message: The Patrol Read operation detected a media error on the disk drive %1 and automatically corrected the error.

RED092.Description: The firmware for the component identified in the message was updated successfully to the firmware version identified in the message.
RED092.Message: The %1 firmware updated successfully. Previous version: %2, Current version: %3

SRV065.Description: The SupportAssist Enclosure Controller logs collection operation is successfully completed .
SRV065.Message: The SupportAssist Enclosure Controller logs collection operation is successfully completed .

SYS179.Description: Unable to export TTY log data because the storage controller present in the server does not support the feature.
SYS179.Resolution: Make sure that at least one storage controller is present in the server that supports the TTY log feature, and then retry the operation.
SYS179.Message: Unable to export TTY log data because the storage controller present in the server does not support the feature.

SWC9000.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate Delete operation cannot be completed either because an invalid thumbprint, hash, certificate type, subtype is entered or due to insufficient space in certificate store.
SWC9000.Resolution: Enter correct thumbprint, hash, certificate type, subtype, free some space in the certificate store by deleting few certificates and then retry the operation. For more information, see iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SWC9000.Message: Unable to complete the SecureBoot Certificate Delete operation either because an invalid thumbprint, hash, certificate type, subtype is entered or due to insufficient space in certificate store.

PCI1362.Description: System performance may be degraded. The bus is not operating at maximum speed or width.
PCI1362.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next scheduled service time.
PCI1362.Message: Bus performance degraded for a component at slot %1.

ISM0022.Description: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the application encountered an error.
ISM0022.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the OS Collector on the iDRAC to the most recent version available, and then retry the operation.
ISM0022.Message: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the application encountered an error.

UEFI0072.Description: When the Secure Boot feature is enabled, the system BIOS authenticates each UEFI driver against the Secure Boot policy. If a UEFI driver does not meet the policy criteria, the system BIOS does not load or execute the UEFI driver and displays this message at the end of POST. The Secure Boot policy consists of authorized and unauthorized X.509 certificates; signed drivers must chain to an authorized certificate. The policy may also authorize hash values of individual UEFI driver images. Users can configure the Secure Boot feature and the Secure Boot policy in F2 System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page.
UEFI0072.Resolution: If the Secure Boot feature is not desired, disable it in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. Otherwise, do the following: 1) Make sure the firmware on the failing device is up-to-date. 2) If subsequent failures occur, review the Secure Boot Policy Summary in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. The device firmware must be authorized by a public key or hash value in the Authorized Signature Database. The public key or hash value must not be present in the Forbidden Signature Database.
UEFI0072.Message: Unable to load the firmware from %1 because of the Secure Boot policy.

SRV067.Description: The SupportAssist Chassis Controller logs collection operation did not complete successfully.
SRV067.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and then retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm racreset". To reset the CMC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm chassisaction reset".
SRV067.Message: The SupportAssist Chassis Controller logs collection operation did not complete successfully.

PDR113.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message has either reached or exceeded the warranted wear-out limit.
PDR113.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.
PDR113.Message: The %1 has reached or exceeded its warranted wear-out limit.

CMC8568.Description: The DVD drive is disabled and is not mapped to any of the server slots.
CMC8568.Message: The DVD drive mapping feature is disabled.

CTL48.Description: The controller has physical disks that were moved from another controller or have been removed and replaced on the current configuration. These physical disks contain virtual disks that were created on the current or other controller. See the storage hardware documentation for Import Foreign Configuration and Clear Foreign Configuration for more information. Foreign configuration is seen when a controller is replaced.
CTL48.Resolution: Import or clear the detected foreign configuration using a configuration tool or utility.
CTL48.Message: A foreign configuration was detected on %1.

SYS009.Description: Length of string for specified attribute exceeded the maximum length allowed.
SYS009.Resolution: Check Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and retry the command with string value length less than maximum length allowed.
SYS009.Message: String exceeds maximum length for attribute: %1

UEFI0297.Description: A BIOS corruption is detected. A BIOS Recovery process is automatically started. This process would take a few minutes.
UEFI0297.Message: A BIOS corruption is detected. A BIOS Recovery process is requested by the BIOS. This process would take a few minutes.

RED075.Description: The Automatic Backup schedule operation could not be successfully created because the Automatic Backup schedule configuration already exists.
RED075.Resolution: Check the Automatic Backup schedule to verify if it is accurate or delete the existing schedule and retry the operation.
RED075.Message: An Automatic Backup schedule already exists.

TMP5.Description: You have changed the value for the maximum temperature probe warning threshold. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
TMP5.Message: The temperature probe maximum warning value was changed on %1.

SWC8602.Description: The system is busy with other operations. The feature was unable to get mutex.
SWC8602.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, make sure any other operations have completed and then retry the operation.
SWC8602.Message: Quick Deploy Profile for server %1 was not successful.

IOV003.Description: A PCIe device error was detected that does not allow the assignment, unassignment, or the turning off of the device. The errors can be caused by incorrect PCIe device installation or installation of an unsupported PCIe adapter card. For a list of supported PCIe adapter cards contact your service provider.
IOV003.Resolution: Make sure that supported adapters are used and installed correctly in the PCIe slots.
IOV003.Message: Unable to manage the device located in the PCIe slot specified in the operation.

SRV051.Description: The Debug Logs collection operation is successfully completed for SupportAssist.
SRV051.Message: The Debug Logs collection operation is successfully completed for SupportAssist.

GMGR0037.Description: The group job identified in the message cannot be deleted because the job is running.
GMGR0037.Resolution: Wait for the job to complete and retry the operation. Else, stop the job if running and retry the operation.
GMGR0037.Message: Unable to reschedule the group job %1 of type %2 because the job is actively running.

JCP012.Description: The requested operation requires memory or file space allocation. The operation failed due to lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC.
JCP012.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
JCP012.Message: The operation failed due to an internal iDRAC error.

VLT0219.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0219.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0219.Message: The %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

NIC004.Description: The value for the specified parameter is invalid.
NIC004.Resolution: Verify that parameter values passed to the method are entered as they appear in the enumeration and parameter data type matches the documentation.

RAC0277.Description: This warning message appears when IPv4 is disabled.
RAC0277.Resolution: Use IPv6 network to access iDRAC remotely.
RAC0277.Message: Disabling IPv4 prevents access to iDRAC using an IPv4 address.

PSU8518.Description: The operation to read the FRU data from the PSU identified in the message did not complete successfully due to internal communication errors.
PSU8518.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the condition persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8518.Message: Unable to access the PSU %1 FRU data.

GMGR0020.Description: The group job identified in the message is successfully cancelled.
GMGR0020.Message: The group job %1 of type %2 is cancelled.

UEFI0038.Description: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because an expected interrupt(s) from the iDRAC SMA (Shared Memory Architecture) interface did not happen. Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as active power management, thermal management.
UEFI0038.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0038.Message: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of missing interrupts on the Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) interface.

ENC21.Description: A device has been removed and the system is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

RAC922.Description: The specified path (specified with the l parameter) for the remote share is too long. This path should be less than 256 characters in length.
RAC922.Resolution: Try the same command with a different remote share location, which is less than 256 characters in length.

CMC8513.Description: The Extended Storage feature activation on the secondary CMC timed out. If the media on Standby CMC does not respond within 90 seconds of confirming activation the feature returns to single CMC mode.
CMC8513.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration, and verify if the SD card on secondary CMC displays errors. 2) If errors are displayed, execute the following racadm command: "racadm cmcchangeover". 3) Repair the removable flash media SD Card by selecting the Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration > Repair Active Controller Media in the CMC Web interface. Repairing is only allowed on the SD card of the primary CMC. If the problem persists, replace the card.
CMC8513.Message: The Extended Storage feature activation on the secondary CMC timed out. The feature is being returned to single CMC mode.

SUP1908.Resolution: Reacquire the image from the original source and retry the operation.

JCP008.Description: Multiple attributes were set in the operation but some set attribute actions were not successful. For example, setting an attribute that is not valid for the component being configured.
JCP008.Resolution: Examine the results of the configuration job in the Lifecycle Log for the source of the errors. Modify the settings as necessary and resubmit the job.

RDU0012.Description: The current power operational mode is non-redundant because of a power supply exception, a power supply inventory change, or a system power inventory change. The system was previously operating in a power redundant mode.
RDU0012.Resolution: Check the event log for power supply failures. Review system configuration and power consumption.

ISM0007.Description: The iDRAC Service Module ended communication with iDRAC over the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel. This is because either iDRAC is being restarted or the OS to iDRAC Pass-through configuration is being changed. The iDRAC Service Module will continue to try connecting to iDRAC.
ISM0007.Message: The iDRAC Service Module communication with iDRAC has ended.

PWR8516.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action requested.
PWR8516.Resolution: Check the tracelog for more information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8516.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action requested.

RAC0219.Description: Requested power state change has failed.
RAC0219.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.

SWC0005.Description: The view current hardware inventory operation encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0005.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0005.Message: Unable to display the current hardware inventory.

CTL125.Description: The firmware version of the RAID controller identified in the message cannot be updated because of an issue detected in the firmware image file during the verification process.
CTL125.Resolution: Download the correct firmware image file and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CTL125.Message: Unable to update the RAID controller %1 firmware version because the firmware image file is not supported.

SYS258.Description: The remote host server certificate was validated against the uploaded certificate and the validation did not succeed. The remote host server certificate does not correspond to the uploaded verification certificate. The certificate subject name, CN part, may not match the domain name used. If the uploaded certificate is correct, the IP address of the remote host server may be incorrect, the certificate may be expired or this error could indicate a Man-In-The-Middle attack in progress.
SYS258.Resolution: Make sure that the following are correct and retry the operation: a) the file transfer parameters b) the uploaded certificate corresponds to the remote host server c) the certificate subject name, CN part, matches the domain name used.
SYS258.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because there is a problem with the remote host server's security certificate.

RAC946.Description: The "Auto Dedicated NIC" mode cannot be set for a NIC if the NIC selection mode is set to "Dedicated NIC".
RAC946.Resolution: To set the NIC to Auto Dedicated NIC mode, set NIC selection mode to "Shared NIC", and retry the operation.
RAC946.Message: Unable to set the NIC to Auto Dedicated NIC mode.

RAC1029.Description: The certificate cannot be deleted if the certificate type specified is not "3".
RAC1029.Resolution: Make sure to specify "3" for the certificate type (-t) option, and retry the operation.
RAC1029.Message: Unable to delete the specified certificate type.

UEFI0250.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. The Legacy VGA range processor target is not populated. Decode was forced to the Legacy CPU socket.
UEFI0250.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0250.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

RAC1064.Description: Unable to initiate the requested SystemErase operation because another SystemErase job is already in progress.
RAC1064.Resolution: To check the job status, run the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view" and retry the operation after the current SystemErase operation has completed.
RAC1064.Message: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation because another instance of SystemErase job is already in progress.

UEFI0257.Description: Cannot boot to Service Partition because the target Service Partition was not found in the boot list.
UEFI0257.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Update the system BIOS. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0257.Message: Unable to boot to Service Partition because the target Service Partition was not found in the boot list.

SRV132.Description: The SupportAssist operation did not complete within the allocated time.
SRV132.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm racreset".
SRV132.Message: Unable to complete the SupportAssist operation within the allocated time.

VF025.Resolution: To perform a write operation on this partition, change its access type to read-write and try this operation again.

STOR078.Description: The requested operation cannot be performed because it involves server reboot type which is different than the reboot type of pending operations. Combining operations with different reboot types for the same RAID controller is not supported by iDRAC.
STOR078.Resolution: Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller and then retry the operation.
STOR078.Message: The requested operation requires a reboot type that does not match the reboot type required for pending operations.

VDR13.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

UEFI0286.Description: A management console requested changes to Secure Boot policy objects, and the BIOS saved the changes successfully. Secure Boot policy objects consist of the Platform Key (PK), Key Exchange Key (KEK) database, Authorized Signature Database (db), and Forbidden Signature Database (dbx).
UEFI0286.Message: The changes to Secure Boot policy objects are successfully saved by BIOS.

PCI3010.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next service window.
PCI3010.Message: A non-fatal IO error detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

SUP0517.Description: The firmware image specified in the operation did not apply successfully. An internal error may have occurred.
SUP0517.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, download the latest update package from your service provider, and retry the operation.
SUP0517.Message: Unable to update the %1 firmware to version %2.

RAC1121.Description: The command could not be successfully run, because one or more values about the proxy server was not entered.
RAC1121.Resolution: Make sure that you enter the following data, and then retry the operation:- proxy server address- proxy user name- proxy password.
RAC1121.Message: Unable to run the command, because the data entered for connecting to the Proxy server is insufficient.

RAC1147.Description: The SNMPv3 user cannot be set because the user with the entered username for the SNMPv3 group is not present or enabled on iDRAC.
RAC1147.Resolution: Make sure the specified username is present on iDRAC and enabled, and retry the operation.
RAC1147.Message: Unable to set the SNMPv3 username entered in the command because the username is not present or enabled on iDRAC.

LC042.Description: Configure Console name while Virtual Address Management is in FlexAddress mode.
LC042.Resolution: Configure the Virtual Address Management to Console mode, and then configure the name of a console.
LC042.Message: Configure Console name in FlexAddress mode

RED016.Description: The remote share location that has the file(s) or ISO image did not mount correctly.
RED016.Resolution: 1. Verify that the path to the share is correct and that the parameters to the call are correct. 2. Verify that there are no network connectivity issues. 3. Verify that the mount point exists.

SYS237.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an incorrect password value.
SYS237.Resolution: Make sure that the correct password value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS237.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an incorrect password value.

HWC4016.Description: The system has detected a mezzanine card that is not supported on this system.
HWC4016.Resolution: 1) Review system documentation for supported mezzanine cards. 2) Replace mezzanine card with a supported mezzanine card.
HWC4016.Message: Hardware incompatibility detected with mezzanine card %1.

FC014.Description: The AttributeValue parameter is invalid due to one of the following: 1) The length of new AttributeValue is not within the minimum length and maximum length range or does not comply with the governing regular expression 2) Value of new AttributeValue is not within the lower bound and upper bound range limits 3) The value is not one of the possible values.
FC014.Resolution: For valid attribute values, see the FC HBA Profile specification.
FC014.Message: Invalid AttributeValue parameter content for corresponding AttributeName %1.

RED086.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because the Chassis Management at Server (CMAS) attribute is incorrectly set. The CMAS attribute must be set to Monitor and Configure on the CMC in order to update CMC firmware from and iDRAC.
RED086.Resolution: Make sure that the Chassis Management at Server attribute is set to Monitor and Configure, and then retry the operation. To set the correct attribute using Chassis Management Controller (CMC) GUI, navigate to Chassis Overview, then Setup, then General, and then click on the Chassis management at Server attribute to select the correct value.
RED086.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware, Chassis Management at Server is not set to Monitor and Configure.

RAC1211.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the Hash value is not accepted for certificates of Public Key (PK) or Key Encrypting Key (KEK) type.
RAC1211.Resolution: Enter a Thumbprint value for certificates of Public Key (PK) or Key Encrypting Key (KEK) type. For DB, DBX certificate types, enter a valid Hash value. To view a list of valid types, see the RACADM CLI Reference Guide available on the support site.
RAC1211.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the Hash value is not accepted for certificates of Public Key (PK) or Key Encrypting Key (KEK) type.

PDR15.Description: This message is generated after a rebuild completes on a physical disk.

DIS113.Description: The AutoConfig configuration import operation could not be started, because no options were specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS113.Resolution: Make sure that the following are correctly entered in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC, and then retry the operation: 1) Filename -f <filename>). 2) The IP address of the network share folder (-i <ip-address>). 3) Network share name (-n <share-name>). 4) The share type (-s <0 or 2>) where 0 = NFS, 2 = CIFS. 5) The username and password (-u <username> & -p <password>) 6) Shutdown type (-d <0 or 1>) where 0 = Graceful shutdown and 1 = Forced shutdown. 7) Time to wait (-t <value>) where value is more than 300 seconds and less than 3600 seconds.
DIS113.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because no options were specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

IOV118.Description: The Fabric identified in the message is not up and a chassis power cycle is required.
IOV118.Resolution: Power cycle the chassis. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM command line interface, run the command "racadm chassisaction powercycle".

STOR033.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because an invalid value is specified for Start/Until Time.
STOR033.Resolution: Enter a valid Start/Until Time and retry the operation. For more information about the Start/Until Time, see the RAID Profile specification.
