STOR033.Message: Invalid parameter value for Start/Until Time.

SRV053.Description: The Debug Logs cannot be collected for SupportAssist collection because of insufficient storage space on iDRAC.
SRV053.Resolution: Retry the action. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and then retry the operation.
SRV053.Message: Unable to collect the Debug Logs data for SupportAssist because of insufficient storage space on iDRAC.

SWC8623.Description: The current configuration details of IOA in the slot identified in the message could not be saved to its startup configuration.
SWC8623.Resolution: Power-cycle the IOA and retry the operation.
SWC8623.Message: Unable to save the I/O Aggregator configuration in %1.

OSD6.Description: Unable to dynamically allocate memory to perform the task.
OSD6.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and run the command.

RSI0001.Description: The Lifecycle Controller Remote Services instrumentation is available.
RSI0001.Message: The Lifecycle Controller Remote Services is available.

HWC0005.Description: Internal error while retrieving firmware version for the currently installed components. For more information about the failure, see Lifecycle Log.
HWC0005.Resolution: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
HWC0005.Message: Internal error while retrieving update information.

SUP0533.Description: The file cannot be downloaded from FTP share due to network issues.
SUP0533.Resolution: Check network connection and retry download. If the issue persists, reconfigure the network settings and retry.
SUP0533.Message: Unable to download the update package files from the FTP server.

CMC8701.Description: The Member Chassis could not join the chassis group identified in the message because either the Member Chassis is already a part of the other chassis group; or, the Member Chassis could not be reached.
CMC8701.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) If the Member Chassis is a part of other chassis groups, remove the Member Chassis from the other groups by using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) graphical user interface (GUI): Log in to the Member Chassis. Click Chassis Overview > Setup > Group Administration. From the drop-down menu, select None. 2) Restart the Member Chassis by clicking Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components > Reset/Failover CMC. To reset by running RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), enter racadm chassisaction reset.
CMC8701.Message: The Member Chassis could not join the chassis group %1 because either the Member Chassis is already a part of the other chassis group; or, the Member Chassis could not be reached.

RAC1110.Description: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Proxy port number was entered. The Proxy port value must be a positive integer.
RAC1110.Resolution: Enter only numbers for a Proxy port value.
RAC1110.Message: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Proxy port number was entered.

PDR49.Description: The dedicated hot spare is not large enough to protect all virtual disks that reside on the disk group.
PDR49.Resolution: Assign a larger disk as the dedicated hot spare.
PDR49.Message: The dedicated hot spare %1 is too small.

ISM0033.Description: The user identified in the message, without necessary privileges, tried to perform a Full Power Cycle operation from the operating system (OS).
ISM0033.Message: The user %1, without necessary privileges, tried to perform a Full Power Cycle operation from the operating system (OS).

BAT0015.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0015.Resolution: Check the battery at the next service window.

SYS014.Description: The value provided for the identified attribute is invalid.
SYS014.Resolution: For more information, refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and provide a valid value for the identified attribute.

UEFI0008.Description: A CPU invalid task segment state (TSS) exception (type 0x0A) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0008.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0008.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x0A: Invalid Task Segment State Segment (TSS) (Software).

RAC067.Description: iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation was not successful. This may be due to IPMI communications issues.
RAC067.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, remove AC input power from the server and re-apply AC power to the server and retry the operation. 3) If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
RAC067.Message: iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation was not successful.

CTL119.Description: The firmware version of the RAID controller identified in the message cannot be updated because of an error in erasing the previous RAID controller firmware version (Flash Erase Error). The previous image file was not correctly erased.
CTL119.Resolution: Do not reset, restart, or turn off the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). However, retry the operation by using a correct firmware image file. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CTL119.Message: Unable to update the RAID controller %1 firmware version because of an error in erasing the previous RAID controller firmware version (Flash Erase Error).

SRV098.Description: The SupportAssist Collection operation is completed and the export operation is started.
SRV098.Message: The SupportAssist Collection operation is completed and the export operation is started.

UEFI0065.Description: One or more attributes are successfully configured. The system is automatically turned off in 5 seconds.
UEFI0065.Message: One or more attributes are successfully configured. The system will be automatically turned off in 5 seconds.

LC064.Description: The maximum number of characters allowed for the parameter is displayed.
LC064.Resolution: Reduce the number of characters to the maximum length allowed for this parameter.
LC064.Message: The value exceeds the maximum length of %1 characters for %2.

BAT1031.Description: The room temperature may be too hot. In addition, the system fan may be degraded or failed.
BAT1031.Resolution: Verify that the room temperature is normal and that fans are functioning properly. See the storage hardware documentation for acceptable operating temperatures.
BAT1031.Message: The battery temperature on %1 is above normal.

PDR22.Description: A disk has reached an unacceptable temperature and received a SMART alert (predictive failure). The disk is likely to fail in the near future.
PDR22.Resolution: Do the following:1) Determine why the physical disk reached an unacceptable temperature. For example, a fan failure, incorrect thermostat settings, or the room temperature may be too hot or cold. 2) Verify that the fans in the server or enclosure are working. 3) If the physical disk is in an enclosure, check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source. Verify the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information. 4) If you cannot identify why the disk has reached an unacceptable temperature, then replace the disk. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk causes the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.

SRV041.Description: The OS Collector application cannot be successfully started because the user context in which the OS Collector is run does not have necessary privileges for successfully running the application.
SRV041.Resolution: Restart the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service as an administrator.
SRV041.Message: Unable to successfully start the OS Collector application because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) does not have necessary privileges for successfully running the application.

LC040.Description: Unable to allocate required memory to perform the operation.
LC040.Resolution: Power cycle system and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.

MEM9034.Description: The NVDIMM device in the slot identified in the message is not responding.
MEM9034.Resolution: Remove and reinstall the Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device. If the issue persists, contact your service provider. For information about removing and reinstalling the NVDIMM, see the system Owner's Manual on the support site.
MEM9034.Message: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device in the slot %1 is not responding.

SWU001.Description: The expander or storage enclosure processor firmware is successfully updated.
SWU001.Message: The expander or storage enclosure processor firmware is successfully updated.

HWC9003.Description: The BOSS device identified in the message is not functioning because of a Watchdog failure.
HWC9003.Resolution: Make sure that the inlet temperature, fan health, or total power associated with the BOSS device is within specified limits. For information about specified values, see the iDRAC 9.0 and later User's Guide available on the support site.
HWC9003.Message: The %1 device is not functioning because of a Watchdog failure.

HWC4003.Message: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and other hardware.

CTL71.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL71.Message: Attempted to import an incompatible Physical Disk on %1.

LOG505.Description: The network share access cannot be accessed.
LOG505.Resolution: Make sure that correct network share access credentials are entered (such as IP address, username, password, and share type). For more information, see the Chassis Record Log Profile.
LOG505.Message: Unable to access the network share.

RAC0180.Description: Certificate upload failed. Unable to get local issuer certificate. The local issuer certificate is the certificate for the Certificate Authority (CA) that has signed the certificate for the Active Directory (AD) server, unless it is self signed. The iDRAC needs to verify that the CA is legitimate.
RAC0180.Resolution: Certificate has expired. Try creating a new CSR and then upload the certificate.
RAC0180.Message: Certificate upload failed: Unable to get local issuer certificate from the Certification Authority (CA) for confirming the CA is legitimate.

SWC1942.Description: The Quick Sync Wifi feature is enabled.
SWC1942.Message: The Quick Sync Wifi feature is enabled.

STOR071.Description: The configuration operation could not be performed because the specified span count is not valid.
STOR071.Resolution: Enter a valid span count, and then retry the operation.
STOR071.Message: The Span Count is not valid for creating a RAID 10. Valid Span counts are %1.

UEFI0067.Description: A PCIe link failure is observed in the PCIe device identified in the message and device link is disabled.
UEFI0067.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Turn off the input power to the system and turn on again. 2) Update the PCIe device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0067.Message: A PCIe link training failure is observed in %1 and device link is disabled.

STOR0514.Description: The physical disk drive(s) cannot be initialized because the selected RAID controller does not support this operation while in non-RAID mode.
STOR0514.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Select a controller that is in RAID mode and retry the operation. 2) Update the controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
STOR0514.Message: Unable to initialize the selected physical disk drive(s).

STOR056.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because the specified physical disk does not support data encryption.
STOR056.Resolution: Specify a physical disk that is security capable and retry the operation.
STOR056.Message: Physical disk is not security capable.

SUP1909.Resolution: Check that the image is available and retry the operation.

USR8511.Description: Successful login from IP address by Username identified in the message.
USR8511.Message: Login was successful %1 from %2 (username=%3, type=%4, sid=%5)

UEFI0120.Description: Both of the Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card media are missing, or not responding.
UEFI0120.Resolution: Make sure both the SD card media are properly installed and retry the system start up. If the issue persists, replace the SD card media.
UEFI0120.Message: Both of the Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card media are missing, or not responding.

BAR030.Description: The import system profile is complete. iDRAC restarts to complete restore.
BAR030.Message: Import System Profile Complete, restarting Integrated Remote Access Controller.

PDR78.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR78.Message: %1 state changed from Non-RAID to READY.

SWC0037.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to export the file to the network share because the destination folder is not present or inaccessible.
SWC0037.Resolution: Make sure that the destination folder is present and accessible, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, check network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0037.Message: Unable to export the file to the network share.

CMC8561.Description: Unable to send the email alerts to the destination.
CMC8561.Resolution: Make sure to use a valid email address.
CMC8561.Message: Unable to send the email to %1 after trying %2 times.

UEFI0115.Description: The BIOS has recovered the Management Engine after it became unresponsive via the HECI interface. There is no performance degradation and the Management Engine is functioning normally now.
UEFI0115.Resolution: The Management Engine is functioning normally now. No response action is required.
UEFI0115.Message: The Management Engine firmware has recovered from one or more correctable errors.

LOG201.Description: Lifecycle Controller Log corruption was detected during iDRAC boot. The Lifecycle Controller Log was truncated at the point of corruption.
LOG201.Message: Recovered from Lifecycle Controller Log corruption.

SEL1501.Description: An action or failure has taken place that breaks CMC redundancy. This includes loss of network connection, hardware failures, firmware update, firmware mismatch between CMC's, CMC reset, and unplugging a CMC.
SEL1501.Resolution: Check CMC network cables and network connections. Check that CMC firmware versions match.
SEL1501.Message: Chassis management controller (CMC) redundancy is lost.

SYS137.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
SYS137.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller by pressing F2 during server startup and select iDRAC Settings > Lifecycle Controller and then enable the Lifecycle Controller. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
SYS137.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

SWC8554.Description: The Virtual MAC Address Pool identified in the message is not valid. This can occur because the XML syntax is not correct or because of invalid configuration values.
SWC8554.Resolution: Edit the Virtual MAC Address Pool and correct any XML schema or configuration errors present, and then retry the operation.
SWC8554.Message: The Virtual MAC Address Pool %1 is invalid for Boot Identity profile operations.

STOR306.Description: Controller mode cannot be changed as the controller currently has the security key assigned.
STOR306.Resolution: Delete the security key and retry the operation.
STOR306.Message: Unable to change controller mode while security key is assigned to the controller.

MEM9007.Description: A non-recoverable link issue was detected in propagation of signals between processor and memory through the Intel SMI 2 memory interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9007.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9007.Message: Intel SMI 2 Memory interconnect %1 has a non-recoverable issue.

IOV005.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is not ready to run commands because the chassis must be turned on.
IOV005.Resolution: Turn on chassis and retry the command.
IOV005.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is not ready to run commands.

JCP023.Description: One of the job ID values specified as input to the operation is a duplicate. The duplicated Job ID is indicated in the message.
JCP023.Resolution: Use the correct job ID and retry. Use the GetAllJobs method to retrieve all open jobs.

RAC1006.Description: The update was not applied because of one of the following reasons: 1) The Update Package is invalid. 2) Lifecycle Controller is corrupted. 3) Another update is in progress.
RAC1006.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Download the correct Update Package from your service provider. 2) Use the Lifecycle Controller repair package to repair Lifecycle Controller. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide. 3) Wait until the current update operation is complete.
RAC1006.Message: Unable to process the %1, and the update was not applied.

STOR314.Description: Only one pending Reconfiguration operation is possible on a Virtual Disk at a time.
STOR314.Resolution: There are two possible response actions. 1)Commit and execute the pending reconfiguration operation. Once complete, retry the new Reconfiguration operation. 2)Cancel the pending Reconfiguration operation and then retry the new reconfiguration operation.
STOR314.Message: Unable to start the reconfiguration operation on a Virtual Disk because a reconfiguration request for that Virtual Disk already exists.

LC052.Description: There can only be one Server Profile Import job at a time.
LC052.Resolution: Wait for the existing Server Profile Import job to run and complete or cancel it, before retrying the operation.
LC052.Message: Cannot create multiple Server Profile Import jobs.

SWC8565.Description: The Boot Identity profile identified in the message is created with number of templates as identified in the message.
SWC8565.Message: The Boot Identity profile %1 is created with %2 templates.

VLT0300.Description: Low voltages may be the result of a problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. The low voltage may cause the processor to fail to operate.
VLT0300.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0300.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

SWC0126.Description: Racadm tool was unable to download the generated CSR file.

UEFI0146.Description: Unable to verify the chassis type via iDRAC and CMC. System configuration may be incorrect as a result.
UEFI0146.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware and then restart the system. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0146.Message: Unable to verify the chassis type via iDRAC and CMC. System configuration may be incorrect as a result.

CTL45.Description: The Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) is beginning to malfunction.
CTL45.Resolution: Replace the Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) to avoid data loss or data corruption. The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM.

SWC0030.Description: iDRAC is unable to complete the backup Server Profile operation.
SWC0030.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0030.Message: Unable to complete the backup Server Profile backup operation.

SYS089.Description: The Preview operation of Server Configuration Profile is complete.
SYS089.Message: Preview of Server Configuration Profile is complete.

UEFI0007.Description: A CPU coprocessor segment overrun exception (type 0x09) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0007.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0007.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x09: Coprocessor Segment Overrun (Software).

UEFI0005.Description: A CPU math coprocessor not available (type 0x07) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0005.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0005.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x07: Math Coprocessor Not Available (Hardware).

SWC0001.Description: The network cable may not be connected or an internal error occurred. For more information about the failure, see Lifecycle Log.
SWC0001.Resolution: Verify the network cable is connected and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0001.Message: Unable to save the network settings.

LC080.Description: The Export Server Screen Shot operation successfully exported the server screen shot file.
LC080.Resolution: Download the encoded Base64 format server screen shot file, decode the Base64 file and then save it as a *.png file.
LC080.Message: The Export Server Screen Shot operation successfully exported the server screen shot file.

RAC978.Description: The Lifecycle Controller firmware version on the target system does not support the configuration XML file import or export operations.
RAC978.Resolution: Update to the latest Lifecycle Controller firmware and retry the operation.
RAC978.Message: Unsupported Lifecycle Controller firmware version detected.

ISM0019.Description: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS), because checksum verification did not succeed for some files.
ISM0019.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the OS Collector on the iDRAC to the most recent version available, and then retry the operation.
ISM0019.Message: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because checksum verification did not succeed for some files.

UEFI0073.Description: When the Secure Boot feature is enabled, the system BIOS authenticates each boot option against the Secure Boot policy. If a boot option does not meet the policy criteria, the system BIOS does not boot to the boot option and displays this message. The Secure Boot policy consists of authorized and unauthorized X.509 certificates; signed boot images must chain to an authorized certificate. The policy may also authorize hash values of individual boot images. Users can configure the Secure Boot feature and the Secure Boot policy in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page.
UEFI0073.Resolution: If the Secure Boot feature is not desired, disable it in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. Otherwise, do the following: 1) review the Secure Boot Policy Summary in F2 System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. The boot option must be authorized by a public key or hash value in the Authorized Signature Database. 2) If the boot option is not authorized but it can be trusted, enter System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page, set Secure Boot Policy to Custom, and add a entry for the boot option in the Authorized Signature Database (System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings > Custom Policy Settings > Authorized Signature Database > Import Database Entry).
UEFI0073.Message: Unable to boot %1 because of the Secure Boot policy.

RDU8521.Description: The active CMC has been removed from the chassis. If standby CMC is present, it will become active.
RDU8521.Resolution: Reinstall the CMC that was removed.
RDU8521.Message: CMC%1: active CMC has been removed

STOR315.Description: Certain RAID levels require a Virtual Disk to have more than one span. Reconfiguration operation on these Virtual Disks is not supported by the storage controller.
STOR315.Resolution: Make sure that the Virtual Disk has a single span and retry the reconfiguration operation. For information about the RAID levels that have a single span, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide available at the support site.
STOR315.Message: Unable to perform the reconfiguration operation because the storage controller does not support reconfiguring a Virtual Disk that has more than one span.

SWU8542.Description: The firmware update operation for the CMC was not successful. The Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8542.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware Image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8542.Message: Unable to update the Active CMC firmware. The Image file transfer process was not successful.

UEFI0285.Description: The BIOS cannot send Secure Boot policy data (certificates and hash values) to iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI). This means management consoles will not display the latest Secure Boot policy data because BIOS is not synchronized with iDRAC. Synchronization must occur before using management consoles to configure Secure Boot policy data.
UEFI0285.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0285.Message: Unable to send Secure Boot policy data to iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).

VFL0012.Description: The vFlash media is not enabled.
VFL0012.Resolution: Enable the vFlash media by running the command 'racadm set idrac.vFlashSD.Enable 1'.

CTL42.Description: An attempt to hot plug an Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has been detected.
CTL42.Resolution: If the new enclosure and its device are not detected by the operating system, try restarting your system to verify the newly attached enclosure and its sub-components are detected. See the hardware documentation for more information.
CTL42.Message: Enclosure Management Module (EMM) hot plug is not supported on %1.

RAC1041.Description: Successfully configured the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings.
RAC1041.Message: Successfully configured the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings.

RFL2007.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is writable.

JCP037.Description: The (installation or configuration) job identified in the message is successfully completed on iDRAC.
JCP037.Message: The (installation or configuration) job %1 is successfully completed.

SRV014.Description: Unable to export Storage Controller Log because the storage controller identified in the message does not support the feature.
SRV014.Message: Unable to export Storage Controller Log because the storage controller %1 present in the server does not support the feature.

SYS090.Description: The configuration profile contains DOCTYPE tags which may contain injection security threats. The DOCTYPE tag is not supported in configuration profiles.
SYS090.Resolution: Check the input XML file for DOCTYPE XML tags and remove them before retrying the operation.
SYS090.Message: The configuration profile contains unsupported DOCTYPE tags.

BIOS032.Description: The network share cannot be accessed because incorrect network share identify information is entered.
BIOS032.Resolution: Enter correct network share identify information and retry the operation.
BIOS032.Message: Unable to access the network share because incorrect network share identify information is entered.

USR8509.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.
USR8509.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct. Retry the operation with valid credentials.
USR8509.Message: Login was not successful (username=%1, ip=%2, error=0x%3, type=%4)

GMGR0065.Description: The group job cannot be retried because it is not in an error state. Only failed or errored group job shall be retried.
GMGR0065.Message: Unable to retry completing the group job because it is not in an error state.

SEC0002.Description: The I/O card area is open. I/O cards may be added or removed. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0002.Resolution: Close the I/O card area. Check system logs.
SEC0002.Message: The I/O card area is open.

STOR070.Description: The method name identified in the message could not be successfully completed, because the number of elements entered for VDPropNameArray and VDPropValueArray is not equal.
STOR070.Resolution: Enter a valid parameter, and then retry the operation. For more information about a valid parameter, refer to the SimpleRAIDProfile document available at DellTechCenter http://en.community.dell.com/techcenter/extras/m/white_papers/20263535.aspx.
STOR070.Message: Unable to run the WS-MAN method %1, because an invalid parameter %2 is entered.

RAC0680.Description: The USB Configuration XML feature is not available if the iDRAC user credentials and BIOS passwords are not set to default values.
RAC0680.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC user credentials and BIOS passwords to default and retry the operation.
RAC0680.Message: Server iDRAC user credentials and/or BIOS passwords are not currently set to default credentials. The USB Configuration XML feature is not available unless default credentials are set.

RAC973.Description: The configuration XML file which was specified for import, had the same configuration as the current system configuration.
RAC973.Resolution: Make any desired system configuration changes to the configuration XML file and retry the operation.
RAC973.Message: The imported configuration XML file matches the current system configuration.

FAN1000.Description: The enclosure detected that a fan was removed and the enclosure is no longer functioning in optimal condition.
FAN1000.Resolution: Re-insert the fan into the enclosure. Contact technical support if the issue persists.

HWC7000.Message: Server %1 health changed to a normal state.

SWC1946.Description: The Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-only mode.
SWC1946.Message: The Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-only mode.

UEFI0267.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the IPv4 initiator gateway address is invalid.
UEFI0267.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the Initiator Gateway field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0267.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the IPv4 initiator gateway address is invalid.

STOR3.Description: Storage Management has lost communication with a controller. This may occur if the connectivity between the controller and iDRAC is disrupted or any underlying hardware problems are encountered.
STOR3.Resolution: Reboot the system or iDRAC. If the problem is not resolved, contact technical support.
STOR3.Message: CEM Storage Management has lost communication with the %1.

SWC8541.Description: The Profile identified in the message is imported.

SYS1003.Description: System is performing a CPU reset because of system power off, power on or a warm reset like CTRL-ALT-DEL.

RAC016.Description: The method cannot be run because an invalid attribute name is entered.
RAC016.Resolution: Enter a valid attribute name and retry the operation.
RAC016.Message: Unable to run the method because an invalid attribute name is entered.

SWC8519.Description: The user name identified in the message was successfully modified.
SWC8519.Message: Successfully modified user name from %1 to %2.

RAC0126.Description: The label field is empty. A label is required to create an empty partition.
RAC0126.Resolution: Enter a label that contains one to six alphanumeric characters.
RAC0126.Message: The label value is invalid. Expected range: 1-6 alphanumeric characters.

HWC5037.Description: The firmware on the I/O module did not boot. The problem may be because the I/O module is not inserted correctly.
HWC5037.Resolution: Reseat I/O module. If problem persists, contact the service provider.

HWC4001.Message: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and CPU.

LIC010.Description: A license is not imported to the iDRAC when one of the following conditions exists:1) The license is not for the iDRAC.2) The target system may not be upgraded to the product class specified by the license (for example, user may not upgrade from an express product class to an enterprise product class).
LIC010.Resolution: Verify this system may be upgraded to the product class specified by the license. If this system cannot be upgraded to the product class specified, obtain a new license file.
LIC010.Message: Import failed: This license is not for the specified device.

RAC1054.Description: Successfully cleared the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.
RAC1054.Message: Successfully cleared the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.

GMGR0043.Description: The group job identified in the message cannot be scheduled because the maximum number of group jobs are already created. A maximum of 50 group jobs of all states are maintained by the group manager.
GMGR0043.Resolution: Delete any completed group job and retry the operation.
GMGR0043.Message: Unable to schedule a group job of type %1 because maximum number of group jobs are already created.

SYS409.Description: The object properties cannot be set because an incorrect object value is entered.
SYS409.Resolution: Enter a valid object value and retry the operation. For information about recommended values, see the schema or the attribute registry based on the type of resource.
SYS409.Message: Unable to set the object properties because an incorrect object value is entered.

VDR29.Description: A mirrored virtual disk is un-mirrored. When a virtual disk is mirrored, its data is copied to another virtual disk to maintain redundancy. After being un-mirrored, the disk formerly used as the mirror returns to being a physical disk and becomes available for inclusion in another virtual disk.
VDR29.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR29.Message: A mirrored virtual disk has been un-mirrored.

SUP011.Description: The specified Job ID was not found in the job queue.
SUP011.Resolution: Verify the job ID and retry the action. Retrieve all open jobs by issuing the GetAllJobs command.

PSU8513.Description: Unable to update the PSU firmware due to PMBus communication errors.
PSU8513.Resolution: Retry the firmware update operation. If the problem persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8513.Message: Unable to complete the PSU slot %1 firmware update. Error=0x%2.

SYS021.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of incorrect parameters or internal firmware issues.
SYS021.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following: 1) verify the value being set is correct, 2) reset the iDRAC.
SYS021.Message: Unable to set the value for %1

RAC0216.Description: Login failed because of an unknown reason.
RAC0216.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.

RAC0604.Description: The system inventory may not be up-to-date because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled. The CSIOR feature retrieves detailed system inventory information during system startup and stores this information on iDRAC.
RAC0604.Resolution: Enable CSIOR, restart the system and retry the operation. To enable CSIOR, press F2 (System Setup) during system startup, navigate to iDRAC Settings >Lifecycle Controller, and select the Enabled option for Collect System Inventory on Restart.
RAC0604.Message: System inventory may not be up-to-date because Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) is disabled.

HWC7008.Description: Server <number> health changed to a warning state from more severe state.
HWC7008.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7008.Message: Server %1 health changed to a warning state from more severe state.

RAC0648.Description: The request cannot be processed, because the length of string entered for one of the input parameter is more than the specified length.
RAC0648.Resolution: Enter a string not more than 4095 characters in length, and then retry the operation.

PSU8515.Description: Unable to set the Enable Dynamic Power Supply Engagement attribute.
PSU8515.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, review the tracelog for more details. To retrieve the tracelog, in the CMC Web interface, go to Troubleshooting > Diagnostics page and enter the "gettracelog" command, or use RACADM "gettracelog" command. If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider and provide the tracelog.
PSU8515.Message: Unable to set the Enable Dynamic Power Supply Engagement attribute.

SWC9008.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate Reset operation is successfully scheduled.
SWC9008.Resolution: Restart the host server for the changes to take effect.
SWC9008.Message: The SecureBoot Certificate Reset operation is successfully scheduled. Restart the host server for the changes to take effect.

PST0005.Description: System BIOS has started copying image from flash to system memory.

PDR88.Description: When physical drives in spun down power state are configured, the drives should transition to spun up power state. If the drive is not functioning properly, this transition could fail.
PDR88.Resolution: Replace the physical disk and try again. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
PDR88.Message: Power state change failed on %1. (from %2 to %2)

SEL9900.Description: The current software version cannot decode this event. The source of the event may come from a source that is not compatible with this software or the event may have been added after the release of this software. You may need to review this event using a tool which displays raw data such as Ipmitool with the -vvv option or Racadm with the -E option.

PDR1020.Message: Consistency check for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 completed.

PDR1005.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is in the critical array.

RAC0106.Description: Communication with the Smart Card reader is established and a Smart Card is inserted, but there are problems reading the Smart Card.
RAC0106.Resolution: This error may occur because:1. Make sure the Smart Card is seated correctly.2. Smart Card is invalid. Insert a valid Smart Card and try again. 3. Check connection between reader and system.4. There may be an issue with the Smart Card reader. Try reinstalling the reader driver or use a different reader.
RAC0106.Message: The Smart Card cannot be detected. Insert the Smart Card correctly.

PSU0077.Description: Power supplies should be of the same input type and power rating.
PSU0077.Resolution: Install matched power supplies and review product documentation for proper configuration.
PSU0077.Message: Power supply %1 vendor type mismatch detected.

SWC0032.Description: Exporting the Server Configuration Profile image file to the USB drive was successful.
SWC0032.Message: Successfully exported the Server Configuration Profile image file to the USB drive.

CTL51.Description: The text for this message is generated by the controller during runtime and can vary depending on the situation.
CTL51.Resolution: Make sure the SAS cables attached to the enclosure/backplane are attached securely. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables. Contact technical support if the issue persists.

UEFI0015.Description: The BIOS is unable to access the Lifecycle Controller firmware. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0015.Resolution: Perform the following actions: 1)Reboot the system. 2) Press F2 during boot to enter System Setup. 3) Select iDRAC Settings then Lifecycle Controller. 4) Change Lifecycle Controller back to Enabled. If subsequent failures occur, press and hold the system ID button down for 15 seconds to reset the iDRAC. For more information on how to reset iDRAC, see iDRAC User's Guide.
UEFI0015.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible and is therefore in Recovery mode.

ENC15.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
ENC15.Message: An enclosure blink operation has initiated on %1.

PFM0004.Description: The value of the sensor identified in the message is within specified limits.
PFM0004.Message: The value of %1 is within specified limits.

SWC0212.Message: Perform POST Virtual Console disable from local system

VDR5.Description: The controller removed a virtual disk. This is due to a delete virtual disk operation, a reset configuration operation, or the removal of every physical disk that was a member of the virtual disk.

STOR006.Description: The operation could not be completed because of an issue with the management controller (either the iDRAC or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC)) that is managing the storage.
STOR006.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

RAC0649.Description: Unable to process the request, because data is not entered or not selected in one or more mandatory fields.
RAC0649.Resolution: Make sure to enter or select data in all the mandatory fields, and then retry the operation.

UEFI0186.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the DC Detection phase.
UEFI0186.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0186.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

BAR072.Description: The vFlash backup partition format operation was not successful.
BAR072.Resolution: Enable and initialize the vFlash media and retry the export. If the issue persists, try a new vFlash media or use the network share option(s).
BAR072.Message: Format of vFlash Backup partition unsuccessful.

PWR8504.Description: The chassis power button press is detected but the button has been disabled.
PWR8504.Resolution: The chassis power button is disabled. To enable the chassis power button use the CMC RACADM command line interface, CMC Web interface. Using the command line, enter "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerButtonEnable 1". Using the Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration. Clear the Disable Chassis Power Button check box.
PWR8504.Message: Chassis power button is pressed, but the button is disabled.

DIS007.Description: Unable to connect to Provisioning Server to notify about new iDRAC IP .
DIS007.Resolution: Check Provisioning Server connectivity and retry.
DIS007.Message: Unable to notify Provisioning Server of iDRAC IP address change.

RAC028.Description: The attributes "DNS Domain Name From DHCP" and "DNS From DHCP" are dependent on the attribute DHCP being Enabled. Currently DHCP is configured as Disabled.
RAC028.Resolution: Set DHCP attribute to Enable to be able to Enable DNS Domain Name From DHCP or DNS From DHCP.
RAC028.Message: Unable to Enable "DNS Domain Name From DHCP" or "DNS From DHCP" because DHCP is Disabled.

SYS429.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the property is not in the list of valid properties for the resource.
SYS429.Resolution: Remove the unknown property from the request body and retry the operation.
SYS429.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the property %1 is not in the list of valid properties for the resource.

STOR0513.Description: Unable to encrypt unsecure virtual disks due to an internal error.
STOR0513.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.

RED063.Description: The iDRAC firmware updated successfully to the firmware version identified in the message.
RED063.Message: The iDRAC firmware updated successfully. Previous version: %1, Current version: %2

UEFI0275.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the TCP connection timed out when connecting to the iSCSI target.
UEFI0275.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure the iSCSI target system is online with the firewall configured to allow TCP access. 2) Make sure the server network infrastructure is configured to allow access to the iSCSI target. 3) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, make sure the iSCSI initiator settings (iSCSI, DHCP, VLAN, initiator/target IP addresses) are configured correctly. 4) Retry the operation.
UEFI0275.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the TCP connection timed out when connecting to the iSCSI target.

RAC1220.Description: The Secure Boot certificate data cannot be exported because the size of exported file is greater than 25 MB.
RAC1220.Resolution: Export the certificate to a network file share (NFS) folder that has a storage space of 25 MB and greater.
RAC1220.Message: Unable to export the Secure Boot certificate data because the size of exported file is greater than 25 MB.

RAC040.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the method invoked in the operation are missing.
RAC040.Resolution: Verify that all required parameters are provided. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

LC017.Description: A parameter value provided when the method was invoked is not valid.
LC017.Resolution: Verify that parameter values provided to the method are typed as they appear in the enumeration and that the parameter data type matches the Lifecycle Controller Profile documentation.

PWR203.Description: The System Input Power Cap value cannot be set to less than or equal to 13300 W, because the Extended Power Performance feature is enabled.
PWR203.Resolution: Enter a Power cap value greater than 13300 W, and then retry the operation.
PWR203.Message: Unable to set the System Input Power Cap value to less than or equal to 13300 W (45381 BTU/h), because the Extended Power Performance feature is enabled.

VLT0302.Description: High voltages may be the result of problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. Elevated voltages may result in damage to the processor or other electronic components inside the system.
VLT0302.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0302.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

RAC0208.Description: Upload failed possibly due to invalid key data.
RAC0208.Resolution: Upload a certificate with a valid key.
RAC0208.Message: Upload failed: May be due to invalid key data.

RED039.Description: Settings for an Automatic Server Profile Backup, Automatic Update, or other recurring operations identified in the message were cleared. The recurring operation identified in the message is deleted.
RED039.Message: Settings for a recurring operation of type %1 were cleared.

UEFI0114.Description: The Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) operating mode cannot be enabled because of mismatches in DIMM channel configurations.
UEFI0114.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0114.Message: Unable to enable the Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) operating mode because of mismatches in DIMM channel configurations.

VF046.Description: File transfer was not successful. This could be because of network problems or an operational problem with the file server.
VF046.Resolution: Try the download again. If the issue persists, validate that the network share is operational.
VF046.Message: HTTP download operation was not successful.

RAC1023.Description: Configuration jobs are created only if at least one object on the device or component (for example, NIC.Slot.1 or BIOS) has a pending value to be applied.
RAC1023.Resolution: Make sure that there is at least one object on the specified device or component that has a pending value, and retry the operation.
RAC1023.Message: Unable to create the configuration job.

UEFI0180.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Write Leveling error was detected.
UEFI0180.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0180.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

RAC0766.Description: The USB NIC IP address identified in the message cannot be assigned to the OSBMC device because only Link Local IP address can be allowed.
RAC0766.Resolution: Enter appropriate Link Local IP address, and then retry the operation. For information about supported IP addresses, refer to the iDRAC Users Guide available at the support site.
RAC0766.Message: Unable to assign USB NIC IP address %1 to the OSBMC device because only Link Local IP address can be allowed.

UEFI0123.Description: The secondary SD card has now become the primary SD card.
UEFI0123.Resolution: Check the screen display or the Lifecycle Log for prior messages. If the switch is expected, then no response action is required.
UEFI0123.Message: The secondary SD card has now become the primary SD card.

PCI1346.Resolution: Reboot the system and update the component drivers.
PCI1346.Message: A software error was detected on a component at slot %1.

PSU0019.Message: The input power for power supply %1 has been restored.

BAR049.Description: The automatic Host System power up request has erred and the system will not power up after the Integrated Remote Access Controller has restarted.
BAR049.Resolution: As indicated by the job status, wait for restore to complete. After the status displays Complete or Failed, wait for a few minutes for the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) to restart. After restart, power on the Host System using iDRAC.
BAR049.Message: Automatic Host System power up setup failed.

VLT0216.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0216.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0216.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is outside of range.

SUP007.Description: The iDRAC communication channel is open and being used by another process; this can be caused by an open session of USC locally on the server.
SUP007.Resolution: If USC is in use, wait until USC has exited and retry the action. Otherwise retry after 30 seconds to check if network connectivity caused this error.

AMP0323.Message: Chassis power level current is within range.

BAR108.Description: The license required for Server Profile Import and Export operations to function is not present.
BAR108.Resolution: Obtain the license for Server Profile Export and Import, install the license and retry the operation.
BAR108.Message: License to Export and Import Server Profile not present.

CTL105.Description: The Patrol Read attribute identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message for the controller identified in the message.
CTL105.Message: The Patrol Read attribute %1 is set to %2 for %3.

LC081.Description: The Server Screen Shot export operation cannot be completed because of internal firmware issues.
LC081.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart iDRAC by invoking the WS-Man iDRACReset method which is defined in the DCIM_iDRACCardService class (input parameters are not required for this method), and then retry the operation.
LC081.Message: Unable to complete the Server Screen Shot export operation because of internal firmware issues.

VDR91.Description: This message occurs if there are medium errors in the physical drives.
VDR91.Message: Consistency check for %1 has detected multiple uncorrectable medium errors.

UEFI0242.Description: The Partial Memory Mirroring feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the requested size.
UEFI0242.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure the requested Partial Mirror size can be supported. For more information, see platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0242.Message: Unable to enable the requested Partial Mirror size of %1GB due to the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the requested size. %2GB was allocated instead.

HWC9000.Description: The inlet temperature, fan health, and total power associated with the BOSS device identified in the message are restored to normal.
HWC9000.Message: The inlet temperature, fan health properties, and total power associated with the %1 device are restored to normal.

UEFI0133.Description: Unable to perform PXE boot because the VLAN settings conflict with that of the iSCSI device settings.
UEFI0133.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Go to System Setup and change the VLAN configuration for the PXE device to match that of the iSCSI device. Either both devices must be configured with VLAN enabled or both devices must be configured with VLAN disabled. 2) Change the PXE device interface setting to use a different NIC interface than the NIC interface used by the iSCSI device.
UEFI0133.Message: Unable to perform PXE boot because the VLAN settings conflict with that of the iSCSI device settings.

SRV029.Description: The Operating System (OS) Application Data is not included in the SupportAssist Collection because of an unknown issue in iDRAC.
SRV029.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
SRV029.Message: Unable to include the Operating System (OS) Application Data in the SupportAssist Collection because of an unknown issue in iDRAC.

BOOT006.Description: One or more of the Boot Source instance ID's does not contain valid data.
BOOT006.Resolution: Verify that all of the Boot Source instance IDs being entered are as they appear in the DCIM_BootSourceSetting enumeration.

RAC0758.Description: The Tech Support Report generation will take the time identified in the message to complete.
RAC0758.Resolution: To cancel the reports collection click Cancel.
RAC0758.Message: Tech Support Report (TSR) data is being collected. This operation will take less than %1 minutes.

CMC8546.Description: A firmware error has occurred in the internal firmware process identified in the message. This condition will cause a CMC failover to occur. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8546.Resolution: No response action is required. A failover may result from this condition. If multiple failovers occur, contact your service provider.
CMC8546.Message: Issues identified with Process %1. Failover condition detected.

RAC0677.Description: No physical disk drives in ready state, virtual disks, or PCIe SSD drives are available to perform operations on.
RAC0677.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1. If there are no disk drives available in ready state, insert additional disk drives and make sure the drives are in ready state. 2. If no virtual disks are present, click <create virtualdisk link> and create at least one virtual disk. 3. If PCIe SSD drives are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane.
RAC0677.Message: No physical disk drives in ready state, no virtual disks are created, and no PCIe SSD drives are available to perform operations on.

SWC0278.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0278.Resolution: Enter the values for the group name and object name correctly.

VF002.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an internal issue with the firmware.
VF002.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.

CMC8521.Description: The Mezz card 1 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8521.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8521.Message: The Mezz card 1 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.

SWC0074.Description: The export operation of SupportAssist collection cannot be started because the current version of iDRAC firmware does not support the operation.
SWC0074.Resolution: Update iDRAC firmware to the latest version and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC0074.Message: Unable to start operation with the current iDRAC version.

PWR2263.Description: User continued after receiving power supply oversubscription warning (F1/F2).
PWR2263.Message: User ignored Power Supply Oversubscription Warning.

RAC0400.Description: iDRAC is running low on memory.

STOR088.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the enclosure FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) specified in the input is not valid.
STOR088.Resolution: Enter a valid enclosure FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
STOR088.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the enclosure FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) specified in the input is not valid.

RED067.Description: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were staged. The system will now restart to apply the staged updates.
RED067.Message: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were staged. The system will now restart to apply the staged updates.

RAC027.Description: Unable to set static values for Speed or Duplex when the Auto Negotiation attribute is enabled.
RAC027.Resolution: Disable Auto Negotiation in order to set values for Speed or Duplex.
RAC027.Message: Unable to set values for Speed or Duplex because Auto Negotiation is Enabled.

USR0031.Description: Unsuccessful login for the username, IP address, and interface identified in the message.
USR0031.Resolution: Make sure the login credentials are valid and retry the operation.
USR0031.Message: Unable to log in for %1 from %2 using %3.

LOG302.Description: The Chassis Log file header is corrupted. The Chassis Log will be recreated and all current log entries will not be preserved.
LOG302.Message: The Chassis Log file header is corrupted.

VFL0013.Description: The request could not be successfully completed, because the vFlash SD Card is in read-only mode. Write operations cannot be performed on the card.
VFL0013.Resolution: Change the access mode on the vFlash SD Card to read-write.
VFL0013.Message: The vFlash SD Card is in read-only mode.

STOR099.Description: The FQDD cannot be found because an invalid FQDD is entered or an operation is pending on the FQDD identified in the message.
STOR099.Resolution: Do the following and then retry the operation: 1) Make sure the FQDD entered is valid. 2) Make sure an operation is not pending on the FQDD identified in the message. For more information refer to the RACADM Command Line Reference Guide.
STOR099.Message: Unable to find the FQDD %1 because an invalid FQDD is entered or an operation is pending on the specified FQDD.

SUP027.Description: The required parameter identified in the message is missing.
SUP027.Resolution: Verify the required parameter value for the method is specified and retry the operation.

UEFI0075.Description: The Network Daughter Card 1 is not detected.
UEFI0075.Resolution: Install a Network Daughter Card in the system.
UEFI0075.Message: Network Daughter Card 1 is not detected.

RAC0248.Description: This message is displayed when trying to delete a vFlash partition.
RAC0248.Resolution: Press OK to delete this partition of the SD Card. This action will erase all the data in this partition. If undesired press Cancel.
RAC0248.Message: This operation deletes the partition permanently. Do you want to continue?

PWR8563.Description: The Server identified in the message did not turn on due to a fabric mismatch between the I/O Module and the Mezzanine card on the Server.
PWR8563.Resolution: Make sure that the hardware compatibility between the I/O Module (IOM) and the Mezzanine (Mezz) card is correct. Check the M1000e Hardware Manual for correct component compatibility.
PWR8563.Message: Unable to turn on Server %1 due to I/O fabric inconsistency.

RAC0708.Description: Previous reboot was due to a firmware watchdog timeout.
RAC0708.Message: Previous reboot was due to a firmware watchdog timeout.

SRV087.Description: The job identified in the message is successfully created.

RED047.Description: An Automatic Server Profile Backup or Automatic Update operation is already configured.
RED047.Resolution: Clear the existing configuration settings for the operation identified in the message and retry the operation.
RED047.Message: A recurring operation %1 was not created because the operation is already configured.

RAC924.Description: The inlet temperature history was successfully exported to the specified file.

SWC0078.Description: The server has been successfully removed from Integrated Data Center. All configurations will be restored to Factory defaults.
SWC0078.Message: The server has been successfully removed from Integrated Data Center.

USR0180.Description: The Quick Sync feature is enabled because the activate button on the bezel was pressed.
USR0180.Message: The Quick Sync feature is enabled because the activate button on the bezel was pressed.

JCP021.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of an unknown error in the iDRAC.
JCP021.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
JCP021.Message: The operation failed due to an internal iDRAC error.

RAC062.Description: The attribute can not be set if the IPMI Watchdog state is disabled.
RAC062.Resolution: Enable the IPMI Watchdog state and retry the operation.
RAC062.Message: Unable to set the attribute because the IPMI Watchdog state is disabled.

HWC2014.Resolution: Make sure the hardware is installed correctly. Refer to the product documentation for correct configuration and installation procedures.

SWC8507.Description: A new Profile identified in the message has been created.

SWC0122.Description: The syntax of the sslcertupload command is invalid.
SWC0122.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertupload subcommand.
SWC0122.Message: Invalid syntax. SSL key type (-t) must be specified.

LOG005.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in iDRAC.
LOG005.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
LOG005.Message: Cannot perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

RAC1115.Description: The command could not be successfully run, because of insufficient privileges for the username supplied.
RAC1115.Resolution: Make sure that you have appropriate privileges, and then retry the operation.
RAC1115.Message: Unable to run the command, because of insufficient user privileges.

RAC0725.Description: Unable to update the Quick Sync Firmware.
RAC0725.Message: Unable to update the Quick Sync Firmware.

RAC986.Description: The "vmkey" sub-command is deprecated, and the functionality is available using "vflashsd" sub-command.
RAC986.Resolution: Use "vflashsd" sub-command instead of "vmkey". For more information about the sub-command, use "racadm help vflashsd" command.

VLT0230.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0230.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the mezzanine card.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0230.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

UEFI0027.Description: A license change for the system or a component in the system requires a system reset in order for the new license to take effect.
UEFI0027.Resolution: Wait for the BIOS to reset the system.
UEFI0027.Message: The system must be restarted for the new license to become effective.

RAC1065.Description: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation because iDRAC encountered an internal issue.
RAC1065.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and then retry the operation after the iDRAC has finished restarting.
RAC1065.Message: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation because iDRAC encountered an internal issue.

RAC043.Description: Some event filter settings were not updated due to problems encountered processing the input parameters.
RAC043.Resolution: Verify the input parameters provided and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC043.Message: Unable to update some event filter settings.

MEM0702.Description: The memory may not be operational. This an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0702.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM0702.Message: Correctable memory error rate exceeded for %1.

SRV005.Description: The SupportAssist job identified in the message is cancelled by user request.
SRV005.Resolution: To start another SupportAssist job, wait until the current job that is being cancelled completes and then retry the operation.

UEFI0216.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Late Command Training phase.
UEFI0216.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0216.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SWC0310.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0310.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0310.Message: Invalid syntax. The -f is not valid with the option specified.

RAC1069.Description: The minimum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.
RAC1069.Resolution: Check the maximum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the maximum critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1069.Message: Unable to set minimum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.

RAC1050.Description: One or more required options to configure the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature are missing.
RAC1050.Resolution: For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help systemconfig backup".
RAC1050.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings. The required options are either invalid or not provided.

LC089.Description: The job cannot be set to run on monthly or quarterly recurrence basis because required parameters are not entered in the command.
LC089.Resolution: For setting monthly or quarterly recurrence, enter either the DayofMonth parameter, or the WeekofMonth and DayofWeek parameters. For information about correct syntax and parameters, see the Profile Documents on the TechCenter website.
LC089.Message: Unable to set the job to run on monthly or quarterly recurrence basis because necessary parameters are not entered in the command.

SYS226.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of the reason described by the code identified in the message. For every unsuccessful file transfer, the HTTP remote host server returns an error code, where each code has a description about the reason for failure.
SYS226.Resolution: View the HTTP remote host server documentation to resolve the issue. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SYS226.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of the reason described by the code %2 sent by the HTTP remote host server.

RAC1071.Description: The maximum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is less than or equal to the minimum non critical threshold value.
RAC1071.Resolution: Check the minimum non critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the minimum non critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1071.Message: Unable to set maximum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is less than, or equal to the minimum non critical threshold value.

RAC921.Description: The file type specified (with the t parameter) is invalid. The temperature history can be exported in XML or CSV.
RAC921.Resolution: Change the requested export file type to either XML or CSV. To do this, change the argument given to the t parameter. The argument given to the parameter is case-insensitive.
RAC921.Message: The temperature history can be exported in XML or CSV format only.

SUP006.Description: The DUP is being downloaded and the update cannot be deleted while the download is in progress.
SUP006.Resolution: Wait until the update package is downloaded and retry the action. The download can take more than 5 minutes depending on network speed and size of the update package.

IOV121.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has changed the PCIe ride-through timeout to the value identified in the message. PCIe adapters will remain turned on for the number of seconds specified by the ride-through timeout value after the server they are assigned to is turned off. Note: A value of zero equals infinite number of seconds.
IOV121.Message: PCIe ride-through time out has changed from %1 to %1 seconds.

PSU0002.Description: System performance and power redundancy may be degraded or lost.
PSU0002.Resolution: Remove and re-install the power supply at the next service window. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0002.Message: A predictive failure detected on power supply %1.

SYS052.Description: Configuration changes that do not require a system restart are currently being applied.
SYS052.Message: Analyzing iDRAC, System, or Lifecycle Controller configuration for changes to be applied.

VLT0202.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0202.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0202.Message: The system board %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

SWC8524.Description: A Chassis Group member already exists with the same hostname or IP address information as the target identified in the message.
SWC8524.Message: Unable to add %1 to Chassis Group because a member already exists with the same addressing information.

RAC034.Resolution: Wait for existing jobs to run to completion or delete some jobs from the job queue.
RAC034.Message: Unable to create a job because the job queue is full.

SWC0301.Description: The IP address provided is not valid.
SWC0301.Message: The specified IP address is not valid.

PCI5006.Description: The power related issue of the PCIe device in the slot identified in the message is resolved.
PCI5006.Message: The power-related issue of the PCIe adapter in slot%1 is resolved.

IOV012.Description: By default, the non-licensed system assigns virtual adapters (VA) 1-4 to servers 1-4 respectively.
IOV012.Resolution: Import a license which enables the assignment of a PERC virtual adapter (VA) to any server. For more information about licenses, contact your service provider.
IOV012.Message: Unable to assign a virtual adapter (VA) to a non-default server because a license is required.

PDR36.Description: The only physical disk available to be assigned as a hot spare is using SAS technology. The physical disks in the virtual disk are using SATA technology. Because of this difference in technology, the hot spare cannot rebuild data if one of the physical disks in the virtual disk fails.
PDR36.Resolution: Add a SATA disk that is large enough to be used as the hot spare and assign the new disk as a hot spare.
PDR36.Message: The only hot spare available is a SAS disk %1.

RAC975.Description: The share type specified using the l parameter is invalid. Only CIFS or NFS share types are supported for this operation.
RAC975.Resolution: See the subcommand help text for supported share types.

OSD4.Description: Driver Pack partition in Lifecycle Controller is not accessible. The Lifecycle Controller or the iDRAC might be unresponsive.
OSD4.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and rerun the command. If the command fails again, check if the iDRAC is functional and accessible on the system.
OSD4.Message: Cannot access Lifecycle Controller Driver Pack partition.

RAC1014.Description: The SNMPv3 privacy protocol cannot be configured to AES or DES mode if SNMPv3 authentication protocol state is set to "None".
RAC1014.Resolution: To configure the SNMPv3 Privacy Protocol for a specified iDRAC user, change the SNMPv3 Authentication Protocol to either MD5 or SHA state using "racadm set idrac.users.<index>.SNMPv3AuthenticationType <value>".
RAC1014.Message: The SNMPv3 privacy protocol cannot be configured to AES or DES mode if SNMPv3 authentication protocol state is set to "None".

SWC0233.Description: Indexed groups in the configuration file is more than the indexed groups in iDRAC.
SWC0233.Resolution: Verify if the number of indexed groups available in iDRAC match the indexed groups in the configuration file. If it does not match, either reset the unnecessary indexes on iDRAC or remove the extra groups from the configuration file.
SWC0233.Message: No indexes are available to configure additional groups.

SWC0071.Description: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully exported to the network share folder.
SWC0071.Message: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully exported to the network share folder.

LC026.Description: This method is not supported in this version of the iDRAC firmware.
LC026.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware to a version that supports the log export.
LC026.Message: Lifecycle Controller Log Export method is not supported.

PCI1358.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1358.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1358.Message: A fatal error was detected on a component at slot %1.

MEM0701.Description: The memory may not be operational. This an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0701.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM0701.Message: Correctable memory error rate exceeded for %1.

UEFI0092.Description: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit.
UEFI0092.Resolution: Check the total number of ranks in each channel to make sure it does not exceed the maximum allowed limit. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0092.Message: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit.

CTL95.Description: The controller identified in the message has stopped operating in a fault tolerant mode.
CTL95.Resolution: This situation may resolve itself in a few minutes. If the situation does not resolve itself or this message is repeated, contact your service provider.
CTL95.Message: %1 has left the fault tolerant pair.

PR26.Description: The configuration data associated with the specified job could not be located.
PR26.Resolution: Retry the operation. If this issue persists, contact technical support.

RAC918.Description: Racadm unable to obtain the inlet temperature data. This happens if there is no data populated in the temperature tables or if the underlying instrumentation does not return valid values.
RAC918.Resolution: Wait for the underlying instrumentation to populate the thermal tables. Retry the operation.
RAC918.Message: Unable to get the inlet temperature data.

SWC0269.Description: Local Configuration using RACADM may be disabled.
SWC0269.Resolution: Check if the Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled and enable it through GUI.
SWC0269.Message: Unable to clear the RAC log. Possible reason may be that Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled.

VFL1013.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 has finished booting.

UEFI0304.Description: The Save operation cannot be completed because of an issue identified in the message. All NVDIMM-N modules will be set to read-only mode.
UEFI0304.Resolution: Install NVDIMM-N battery and retry the operation.
UEFI0304.Message: Unable to complete the NVDIMM-N Save operation because %1. All NVDIMM-N modules will be set to read only mode.

LC044.Description: The Lifecycle Controller system configuration wipe operation is currently running. The operation deletes user information from system hardware and resets BIOS, iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller to default settings. The current operation and system restart must complete before the operation can be attempted again.
