LC044.Resolution: Wait for the Lifecycle Controller system configuration wipe operation that is currently running to complete before requesting another operation.
LC044.Message: An instance of Lifecycle Controller system configuration wipe is already running.

UEFI0192.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Clock Alignment phase.
UEFI0192.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0192.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

HWC2010.Message: The riser board cable or interconnect is connected.

RED019.Description: Reinstall or Rollback cannot be performed since no applicable firmware was found on the Lifecycle Controller.
RED019.Resolution: Directly update to the desired version.
RED019.Message: Reinstall or Rollback cannot be performed since no applicable firmware was found on the Lifecycle Controller.

MEM1000.Message: Memory device at location %1 transition to a running state.

LOG001.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the method invoked in the operation are missing.
LOG001.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
LOG001.Message: Missing required InstanceID or JobID parameter.

HWC2016.Description: A fabric type mismatch is detected between the server in slot and I/O module as identified in the message.
HWC2016.Resolution: Check the chassis fabric type by using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) graphic user interface (GUI) and compare against the type of fabric used in the I/O or mezzanine card. To check chassis type on the CMC home page, select the server, and then view the I/O module properties. For more information about the compatible fabric types, see the CMC User's Guide available on the support site.
HWC2016.Message: A fabric type %1 mismatch is detected between the server in slot %2 and I/O module.

UEFI0184.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Load Reduced DIMM (LR-DIMM) buffer initialization.
UEFI0184.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0184.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

PCI3020.Description: A low-severity issue is detected in the component identified in the message.
PCI3020.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the component identified in the message, and then monitor the log for a re-occurrence of the issue. If the issue persists, and occurs during server startup, update the component firmware. If the issue persists and occurs during OS runtime, restart the server and update the OS drivers for the component identified in the message.
PCI3020.Message: A low-severity issue is detected in a component of the bus %1, device 0, function %2.

UEFI0022.Description: The Management Engine firmware cannot be initialized because the Management Engine is not responding.
UEFI0022.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0022.Message: Unable to initialize Management Engine because the Management Engine is not responding.

STOR0105.Description: No enclosure data to display. The system is powered off, enclosures are not present on the system, or enclosures are not connected to the RAID controllers.
STOR0105.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosures are available, and enclosures are connected to the RAID controllers.

TST102.Description: The destination address of the email is not configured.
TST102.Resolution: Configure the email alert destination address and retry the operation.
TST102.Message: Email alert destination address not configured.

BIOS013.Description: An unknown AttributeName was specified in the operation.
BIOS013.Resolution: Enter the correct AttributeName available in the system. Refer to the enumeration response for desired attribute.

RAC1131.Description: The iDRAC was reset and is successfully restarted.

ISM0030.Description: Unable to complete iDRAC Hard Reset operation because this feature is not supported on this platform.
ISM0030.Resolution: Refer to the platform User's Guide documentation for information about whether the iDRAC Hard Reset feature is available.
ISM0030.Message: Unable to complete the iDRAC Hard Reset operation because this feature is not supported on this platform.

PWR2258.Description: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) hotspare thresholds were modified to the Wake Threshold and Sleep Threshold identified in the message.
PWR2258.Message: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) hotspare thresholds were modified. Wake Threshold: %1 %, Sleep Threshold: %2 %.

VF019.Resolution: Check all the partitions, delete the ones that are not necessary and try this operation again.
VF019.Message: Not enough space on SD card

PWR2253.Description: The server did not turn on because a PCIe card or Mezzanine card is not installed.
PWR2253.Resolution: Install a PCI or Mezzanine card in the appropriate slot and retry the operation.
PWR2253.Message: Unable to turn on the server because a PCIe card or Mezzanine card is not installed.

VDR101.Description: Indicates the Virtual Disk to Virtual Adapter Mapping for audit purposes.
VDR101.Message: Virtual Adapter mapping reported for %1. Virtual Adapter 1 is now %2. Virtual Adapter 2 is now %3. Virtual Adapter 3 is now %4. Virtual Adapter 4 is now %5

SWC0027.Description: The backup Server Profile operation successfully completed.
SWC0027.Message: Successfully backed up a Server Profile by using the Lifecycle Controller GUI.

VDR94.Description: This message occurs if the controller pinned cache is recovered.
VDR94.Message: Controller preserved cache was recovered for %1.

PWR8560.Description: Unable to turn on the I/O Module identified in the message due to insufficient chassis power.
PWR8560.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface to check available power and I/O Module power requirements. If sufficient power is available, restart the CMC and retry the operation. If sufficient power is not available due to an insufficient number of PSUs, add additional PSU(s) and reinsert the I/O Module.
PWR8560.Message: Unable to turn on I/O Module %1 due to insufficient chassis power.

HWC7002.Description: Server health changed to a warning state from a normal state.
HWC7002.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7002.Message: Server %1 health changed to a warning state from a normal state.

BAR028.Description: The component restoration on the host system has completed, but there were errors. The Host System will shutdown.
BAR028.Resolution: View configuration data and request attributes update for the components or retry system profile import.
BAR028.Message: Host System Component Restore completed with errors, shutting down Host System.

UEFI0308.Description: The Baseboard UPI A cable connection is misconfigured.
UEFI0308.Resolution: Connect the Baseboard UPI A cable. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0308.Message: The Baseboard UPI A cable connection is misconfigured.

BAR101.Description: Importing license data from the backup Server Profile.

UEFI0226.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the DDR4 LR-DIMM Transmit Buffer Training phase.
UEFI0226.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0226.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

PCI5002.Description: A PCIe card carrier that does not contain a PCIe card is inserted in the PCIe slot identified in the message.
PCI5002.Message: A PCIe card carrier that does not contain a PCIe card is inserted in the PCIe slot%1 .

SUP028.Description: The GetRepoBasedUpdateList method was not successfully executed because the InstallFromRepo method was not executed first.
SUP028.Resolution: Execute InstallFromRepo method, and then retry the operation.
SUP028.Message: The GetRepoBasedUpdateList method did not complete successfully.

PWR8672.Description: The server identified in the message does not have a card in the Mezzanine slot as identified in the message. A mezzanine card position is identified with the following numbers: For quarter-width server, the position number is 1. For half-width server mezzanine C & B maps to position numbers 1 & 2 respectively. For full-width server, mezzanine C & B on the upper- or left part of the server maps to position numbers 1 & 2 respectively. Mezzanine C & B on the lower- or right part of the server maps to position numbers 3 & 4 respectively.
PWR8672.Resolution: Insert a mezzanine card in the slot identified in the message.
PWR8672.Message: The server in slot %1 does not have a %2 mezzanine card in slot %3.

MEM0020.Message: Memory device at location %1 is enabled.

CMC8607.Description: Information about the firmware on server in slot identified in the message cannot be retrieved because there is no communication between Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and iDRAC.
CMC8607.Resolution: 1.Reset iDRAC by using the graphical user interface (GUI): Click Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components. In the Reset Server section, from the Reset drop-down menu, select iDRAC Reset corresponding to the server iDRAC to be reset, and then click Apply Selection. Or, reset iDRAC by running the following command at the command line interface (CLI): racadm racreset -m server-n.2.Reset Chassis Management Controller (CMC) by using the GUI: Click Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components, and then click Reset/Failover CMC. Or, reset CMC by running the following command at the CLI: racadm racreset.For more information about the syntax and parameters used, see the iDRAC 8/7 v2.30.30.30 RACADM CLI Guide and the Chassis Management Controller Version 5.0 for Dell PowerEdge M1000e RACADM Command Line Reference Guide available on the support site.
CMC8607.Message: Unable to retrieve information about the firmware on server in slot %1, because there is no communication between Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and iDRAC.

USR102.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.
USR102.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

UEFI0255.Description: Network Daughter Card 1 and Network Daughter Card 2 in the system do not match.
UEFI0255.Resolution: Check the Network Daughter Cards and make sure they are the same type.
UEFI0255.Message: Network Daughter Card 1 and Network Daughter Card 2 in the system do not match.

SWC0225.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0225.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0225.Message: Invalid syntax. The -d option is not valid with -l.

RAC004.Description: The parameter value for the given parameter is invalid.
RAC004.Resolution: Provide a valid parameter value for specified parameter.

UEFI0200.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Write Level Coarse Training phase.
UEFI0200.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0200.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

BAR009.Description: The vFlash media is not present on the system.
BAR009.Resolution: Insert the appropriate vFlash media in the designated vFlash portal, enable and initialize it, and retry.

SWC0216.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0216.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0216.Message: The -c option requires -l to also be specified.

RAC1176.Description: The Certificate Signing Request (CSR) message cannot be generated because all the attributes in the iDRAC.Security group are not configured.
RAC1176.Resolution: Make sure that all the attributes in the iDRAC.Security group are configured. To get the list of attributes, run the following command "racadm get iDRAC.Security".
RAC1176.Message: Unable to generate the Certificate Signing Request (CSR) message because all the attributes in the iDRAC.Security group are not configured.

AMP0303.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0303.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0303.Message: The system board %1 current is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PST0127.Description: System BIOS gave control to the operating system.

VLT0207.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0207.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0207.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

VRM0020.Description: Racadm tool failed to obtain the data.
VRM0020.Message: Unable to determine current Remote Image state.

TMP0121.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm.
TMP0121.Message: The system inlet temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

RAC0225.Description: Sending the test mail failed. This will prevent alert messages from being sent to this email address.
RAC0225.Resolution: Confirm that:1. A valid SMTP server address is configured in the iDRAC. 2. The remote email server is configured properly to send and receive emails.

UEFI0163.Description: Unsupported DIMM module with technology less than 2Gb is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0163.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0163.Message: Unsupported DIMM module with less than 2Gb technology is installed on memory slot: %1.

RED090.Description: A Chassis firmware update operation is no longer in progress. This is not an indication of success or failure.
RED090.Message: A Chassis firmware update operation is no longer in progress.

SUP0511.Description: The Diagnostic application (Embedded Preboot System Assessment - Enterprise UEFI Diagnostics) is not installed or is corrupt.
SUP0511.Resolution: Update the Diagnostics application using the Firmware Update feature in Lifecycle Controller. For the latest Update Packages, contact your service provider.

JCP011.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid and must be corrected for the invoked method to complete successfully.
JCP011.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation. Retry the operation requested with corrected value.

SWC0260.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0260.Resolution: Refer the list of objects in the corresponding group.

VDR45.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

CMC8702.Description: The Member Chassis exited from the Chassis group <GroupName> because of manual changes made on the member chassis.
CMC8702.Message: The Member Chassis exited from the chassis group %1 because of manual changes made on the member chassis.

CMC005.Description: The operation cannot be completed because of a mismatch between AttributeName and AttributeValue count.
CMC005.Resolution: Enter a valid AttributeName and AttributeValue count, and then retry the operation.
CMC005.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of a mismatch between AttributeName and AttributeValue count.

TMP0127.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0127.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0127.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PDR208.Description: The Cryptographic Erase operation is successfully completed on the physical disk drive identified in the message.
PDR208.Message: The Cryptographic Erase operation is successfully completed on the physical disk drive %1.

JCP035.Description: New jobs cannot be created because a backup job is currently running.
JCP035.Resolution: Wait for the running job to complete, and then retry the operation. To view a list of the jobs currently running, use the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view" or using the WSMAN API, enumerate DCIM_LifeCycleJob to view the list of jobs that are currently scheduled.
JCP035.Message: Unable to create new jobs because a backup job is currently running.

ASR0104.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was powered cycled. (IPMI sensor 23h offset - 03h event 3:0 - 4h).
ASR0104.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0104.Message: The OS watchdog timer powered cycle the system.

MEM1010.Message: Memory device at location %1 is off-duty.

SYS269.Description: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) attribute cannot be changed because the feature is not supported by using Server Configuration Profile (SCP), and the attribute setting is not applied.
SYS269.Resolution: To set Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) attribute to enabled using the RACADM command line utility, type "racadm set idrac.security.fipsmode enabled".
SYS269.Message: Unable to change the Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) attribute because the feature is not supported by using Server Configuration Profile (SCP), and the attribute setting is not applied.

SWC0144.Message: Certificate successfully uploaded to the RAC. The RAC will now reset to enable the new certificate and may be offline temporarily.

SYS230.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported protocol value.
SYS230.Resolution: Make sure that the correct protocol value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS230.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported protocol value, %2.

SYS041.Description: The configuration update is complete, however all of the values were not correctly applied.
SYS041.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log for the values that were not set. Resolve the issues in the XML configuration input file and retry the operation. Alternatively, configure each of the attributes using the component service methods. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
SYS041.Message: Unable to apply some component configuration values.

SEC0612.Description: The default username and password is currently in use and unauthorized access to the iDRAC may occur because the default values are widely known. This is a severe security risk.
SEC0612.Resolution: To change the credentials using RACADM command, run the following at the command line interface (CLI): "racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.Password <new password string>". Alternately, to disable the default credential in use message, run "racadm config -g cfgractuning -o cfgRacTuneDefCredentialWarningEnable 0".
SEC0612.Message: The default username and password is currently in use. It is recommended to immediately change the default credentials.

USR8512.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.
USR8512.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct. Retry the operation with valid credentials.

PDR56.Description: The bad block table is the table used for remapping bad disk blocks. This table fills as bad disk blocks are remapped. When the table is full, bad disk blocks are no longer remapped, which means that disk errors are no longer corrected. At this point, data loss can occur. The bad block table is now 80 percent full.
PDR56.Resolution: Replace the disk generating this message.
PDR56.Message: Bad block table on %1 is 80% full.

MEM1005.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to power off.

SRV008.Description: The SupportAssist System information collection operation is cancelled.
SRV008.Message: The SupportAssist System information collection operation is cancelled.

UEFI0059.Description: The Power Supply Units (PSUs) in the system do not match.
UEFI0059.Resolution: Check the PSU types and make sure they are appropriately matched, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0059.Message: The Power Supply Units (PSUs) in the system do not match.

RAC803.Description: The System Configuration Lockdown mode is enabled.
RAC803.Message: The System Configuration Lockdown mode is enabled.

VFL1014.Description: The card is write-protected by the physical latch on the SD card. IDSDM cannot use a write-protected card.
VFL1014.Resolution: If unintended, remove the media and disable write protection.
VFL1014.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is write protected.

HWC5010.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

USR0207.Description: The Quick Sync feature is disabled because the activate/deactivate button on the panel was pressed.
USR0207.Message: The Quick Sync feature is disabled because the activate/deactivate button on the panel was pressed.

RAC956.Description: The allocated size for the Lifecycle Log entries has reached its maximum limit, and no further comments can be added to the Lifecycle Log.
RAC956.Message: There is no free space to add new comments to the Lifecycle Log.

SWC0149.Description: The requested SNMP test trap alert was successfully sent.

FAN905.Description: Applying fan configuration settings. This may take several seconds.
FAN905.Message: Applying fan configuration settings. This may take several seconds.

PDR29.Description: See A Rebuild Completes with Errors for more information.
PDR29.Resolution: See A Rebuild Completes with Errors for more information.

IOV101.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected the insertion of an adapter in the slot identified in the message.
IOV101.Resolution: If the adapter in slot identified in the message is mapped to a server, the server must be turned off then back on before server can access adapter. If the adapter in slot is a shared adapter and any server is on then the entire chassis must be turned off and turned on for the server(s) to gain access to the installed shared adapter.
IOV101.Message: A PCIe adapter %1 is inserted in %2 %3.

LC063.Description: All jobs must be completed before creating a new job.
LC063.Resolution: Retry after all the existing jobs are completed or deleted.
LC063.Message: Cannot create new jobs until the existing running jobs are completed or deleted.

VDR96.Description: This message occurs if the virtual disk has bad blocks.
VDR96.Resolution: Replace the disk in the Virtual disk, generating this message.
VDR96.Message: Bad block table on %1 is 80 percent full.

SEL0012.Description: If the system event log failed to initialize platform status and failure events are not captured. Some management software will not report platform exceptions.
SEL0012.Resolution: Reboot the management controller or iDRAC. Cycle system input power. If problem persists call support.
SEL0012.Message: Could not create or initialize the system event log.

FAN0029.Description: The fan identified in the message is either removed, incorrectly installed, or not present.
FAN0029.Resolution: Install the fan at the next scheduled service.
FAN0029.Message: The fan %1 is either removed, incorrectly installed, or not present.

JCP041.Description: The job cannot be run because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.
JCP041.Resolution: Disable the System Lockdown mode and retry the operation.
JCP041.Message: Unable to successfully run the job because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.

PWR2269.Description: The properties of Power Cap setting mode is changed.
PWR2269.Message: The properties of Power Cap setting mode is changed.

SYS411.Description: The file cannot be uploaded because the file size is greater than specified limit.
SYS411.Resolution: Make sure that the file size is less than the specified limit. For information about specified limit, see the Redfish User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS411.Message: Unable to upload the file because the file size is greater than specified limit.

LC019.Description: The PKCS12 string could not be decoded from the Base64 encoding into a PKCS12 binary file.
LC019.Resolution: Validate that the contents of the PKCS12 parameter is base64 encoded. OpenSSL can be used to validate the encoding.
LC019.Message: Base64 decode of PKCS12 content was not successful.

RAC959.Description: The content of the configuration XML file used for import is invalid because of incorrect modifications or content.
RAC959.Resolution: Correct the modifications to the configuration XML file to be imported or specify the correct file, and retry the operation. Check the Lifecycle Log for more details.
RAC959.Message: Invalid file used for configuration XML file import operation.

RAC1132.Description: The firmware could not be successfully updated, because one or all of the following values are incorrect:A) logon ID.B) IP address of TFTP or FTP server.C) Full path of the firmware file.
RAC1132.Resolution: Run the racadm command "racadm help <subcommand>" to get more details about the various options applicable for this command and the values accepted by the command.
RAC1132.Message: Unable to update the firmware. The value entered for an option is invalid.

MEM1209.Message: Memory spare redundancy is degraded. Check memory device at location %1.

SWC0070.Description: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully copied to the USB drive.
SWC0070.Message: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully copied to the USB drive.

RAC0240.Description: vFlash needs to be enabled before attempting this operation.
RAC0240.Resolution: Enable vFlash before trying the operation.

STOR053.Description: The system could not obtain a controller key from the Dell Key Management Server.
STOR053.Resolution: For more information about obtaining a key, see Dell Key Manager or Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Guide available at dell.com/support/manuals.
STOR053.Message: The controller key is not present. The key must be retrieved from the Dell Key Management Server.

STOR300.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because at least one other pending operation was found on the RAID controller. This operation needs exclusivity because it requires a server reboot for changes to apply.
STOR300.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending operations, allow the job to complete, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR300.Message: Unable to change the controller mode because there are already pending operations.

RAC1155.Description: The operation was not completed because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.
RAC1155.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. To enable Lifecycle Controller, run the command 'racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1'.
RAC1155.Message: Unable to complete the operation because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.

RAC078.Description: The Import File operation cannot be completed because invalid parameters are entered.
RAC078.Resolution: Make sure that valid parameters are entered, and then retry the operation. For more information about valid parameters, see the iDRAC Card Profile Documents or iDRAC Card Service MOF files.
RAC078.Message: Unable to complete the Import File operation because invalid parameters are entered.

STOR0107.Description: No EMMs data to display. The system is powered off, no enclosure EMMs are present, or the EMMs are not connected to the enclosures.
STOR0107.Resolution: Check if the server has power, EMMs are available, and EMMs are connected to the enclosure.
STOR0107.Message: EMMs are not connected to enclosures or data about EMMs is unavailable.

RAC0146.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.

OSD39.Description: Unable to get vFlash information from internal instrumentation.
OSD39.Resolution: 1) Make sure the Dell vFlash is seated correctly. 2) Make sure a Dell licensed vFlash card is inserted 3) Make sure the Dell vFlash does not have any hardware issues by accessing it through the iDRAC GUI.

RAC949.Description: The specified work note was added to the Lifecycle Log.
RAC949.Resolution: View the work notes using the racadm lclog view c worknotes command.
RAC949.Message: Successfully added a work note to the Lifecycle Log.

SYS171.Description: The import operation cannot be completed successfully because the SHA1v3Key and the MD5V3Key values must both be supplied.
SYS171.Resolution: The SHA1v3Key and the MD5V3Key values must be entered together for an import operation.
SYS171.Message: Unable to successfully complete the import operation because not all hash password values have been entered.

RAC0273.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0273.Resolution: Enable remote access to access iDRAC remotely.
RAC0273.Message: iDRAC access will be limited to running the Racadm utility on the local server or using the serial interface.

PSU0037.Resolution: Check for fan blockage. If not replace the power supply.
PSU0037.Message: Fan failure detected on power supply %1.

RAC0696.Description: The iDRAC is unable to retrieve hardware overview related information while the server is turned off.
RAC0696.Resolution: Turn the server on to view the hardware overview information.
RAC0696.Message: Unable to retrieve the hardware overview information because the server is turned off.

ISM0000.Description: The iDRAC Service Module is started on the OS of server.
ISM0000.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is started on the operating system (OS) of server.

GMGR0019.Description: The group job identified in the message is successfully stopped. The job details can be viewed in the Group Manager job view.
GMGR0019.Message: The group job %1 of type %2 is stopped.

RAC1060.Description: The system inventory information may not be current because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.
RAC1060.Resolution: To enable the CSIOR feature, run the RACADM command "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart 1". Then restart the server to cause system inventory information to be collected.
RAC1060.Message: System inventory may not be current because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

OSD7.Description: Unable to connect to Lifecycle Controller because of an existing open connection or an internal error.
OSD7.Resolution: Reset iDRAC, and rerun the command to correct the problem.
OSD7.Message: Unable to retrieve Lifecycle Controller handle.

PDR1001.Description: The controller detected a failure on the disk and has taken the disk offline.
PDR1001.Resolution: Remove and reseat the failed drive. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PDR1001.Message: Fault detected on drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

SWC0289.Description: The specified object value is invalid.
SWC0289.Resolution: Configure the specified object and assign a valid value.
SWC0289.Message: Invalid value in config file. Group: %1, Object: %2, Value: \"%3\", Line [%4}

SRV006.Description: The SupportAssist System information collection operation is started.
SRV006.Message: The SupportAssist System information collection operation is started.

USR8503.Description: The Active Directory authentication was not successful for the specified username.
USR8503.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used in the operation are correct.
USR8503.Message: Domain user authentication was not successful. Reason code = %1

SWU8513.Description: The firmware update operation of IOM infrastructure is successful.
SWU8513.Message: Successfully updated the IOM infrastructure firmware of slot %1.

PDR111.Description: The volatile memory backup device on the PCIe solid state device identified in the message is no longer functional. Data loss is possible.
PDR111.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.
PDR111.Message: The volatile memory backup device on %1 is no longer functional.

VLT0203.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0203.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0203.Message: The system board %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

UEFI0104.Description: The DIMM module on memory slot identified in the message is populated out of order in the channel.
UEFI0104.Resolution: Install DIMM modules in sequential order without skipping any slots in the channel. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0104.Message: The DIMM module on memory slot %1 is populated out of order in the DIMM channel.

OSD14.Description: iDRAC was unable to expose the drivers as a USB device for the OS installation to proceed.
OSD14.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD14.Message: Unable to expose the USB device that contains the operating system drivers to host system.

USR0208.Description: The Quick Sync feature is deactivated because the inactivity timeout limit was reached.
USR0208.Resolution: Press the activate/deactivate button on the panel to activate the Quick Sync feature.
USR0208.Message: The Quick Sync feature is deactivated because the inactivity timeout limit was reached.

HWC4011.Resolution: Check presence, re-install or reconnect, then re-attempt the update. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC4011.Message: Hardware unsuccessfully updated for mezzanine card %1.

LOG300.Description: The system recovered from Chassis Log file corruption. Some log entries may not be recovered.
LOG300.Message: The system recovered from Chassis Log file corruption.

RDU0003.Description: One of more fans have failed or have been removed or a configuration change occurred which requires additional fans.
RDU0003.Resolution: Remove and re-install failed fans or install additional fans.

BAT1033.Description: The controller cannot communicate with the battery. Either the battery was removed, or the contact point between the controller and the battery is degraded.
BAT1033.Resolution: Make sure that the battery is present and properly connected. If the battery is present, wait for a few minutes and re-check if the battery is detected. If the contact point between the battery and the controller is degraded, you must replace the battery, the controller, or both. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on how to safely access, or remove. Contact technical support if the issue persists.

RAC1186.Description: Only possible configurations for the DRAC NIC are 10Mbps and 100 Mbps. For documentation with respect to this setting, refer to the racadm User Guide under cfgNetTuning group.
RAC1186.Message: 1000Mbps speed setting is Read Only and cannot be configured for the iDRAC NIC.

UEFI0206.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Command Clock Training - Group 1 phase.
UEFI0206.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0206.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC0290.Description: The user name value does not accept spaces.
RAC0290.Resolution: Do not enter spaces in the user name. If desired, use underscores.
RAC0290.Message: The user name cannot have spaces.

CTL86.Description: The controller is operating in conjunction with another controller to service the same set of virtual and physical disks, providing better redundancy.
CTL86.Message: %1 is operating in Fault Tolerant Mode.

LIC503.Description: The currently installed license does not support the feature for the requested operation. The operation requires a valid license to enable specific features in the system. Since the required license is missing or expired, the features that are being accessed during the operation are disabled.
LIC503.Resolution: Acquire and install the license to enable the required feature, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support or see product documentation for more information.
LIC503.Message: Unable to complete the current operation. The currently installed license does not support the following features: %1.

RED052.Description: Processing of update packages is starting. Attempting a manual update will not be possible until current update package processing is completed.
RED052.Message: Processing of update packages is starting.

CTL104.Description: The Enhanced Auto Import Foreign Config status of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL104.Message: The Enhanced Auto Import Foreign Config value of %1 is set to %2.

RAC0614.Description: The specified password was incorrect for the PKCS#12 file.
RAC0614.Resolution: Make sure to use the correct password for the PKCS#12 file. If the PKCS#12 file is encrypted with a password, add it in required password box. Leave the password box empty if the file was not encrypted with a password.

RAC1062.Description: Unable to initiate the requested SystemErase operation. The component identifier specified is not valid.
RAC1062.Resolution: Run the RACADM command "racadm help systemerase" to see the list of supported components.
RAC1062.Message: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation. The component identifier specified is not valid.

CMC8533.Description: Unable to read the header of the extended FRU information. This can occur if there is a problem in the communication between the CMC and the server.
CMC8533.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the server. The CMC will retry the read operation of the FRU information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8533.Message: Unable to read the FRU information, status = %1

SWC0031.Description: iDRAC is unable to initiate the backup Server Profile operation because an unrecoverable error occurred.
SWC0031.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0031.Message: Unable to initiate the backup Server Profile backup operation.

LC060.Description: Lifecycle controller is currently performing tasks and another task cannot be scheduled until the previous task finishes.
LC060.Resolution: Wait until Lifecycle controller finishes performing current tasks and host system to finish POST.
LC060.Message: Lifecycle controller is currently not ready to take provisioning requests

OSE1004.Description: The system OS has successfully booted from the PXE server.

SYS435.Description: The BIOS configuration data cannot be retrieved either because the system inventory is not collected, Lifecycle Controller Wipe operation is performed, or because of a system error.
SYS435.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) feature, collect the system inventory, and then retry the operation. To enable CSIOR and Lifecycle Controller respectively perform the PATCH operation for these attributes on the Redfish OemAttributes URL.
SYS435.Message: Unable to retrieve the BIOS configuration data either because the system inventory is not collected, Lifecycle Controller Wipe operation is performed, or because of a system error.

SEL0002.Description: This message appears when event logging of a specific type is disabled by the user. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 01h).

RAC0149.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about the fans.
RAC0149.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0149.Message: Unable to retrieve the fan information. The system is powered off.

USR108.Description: The Quick Sync InactivityTimeout feature cannot be set because the InactivityTimerEnable attribute is disabled.
USR108.Resolution: Enable the Quick Sync InactivityTimerEnable option before configuring the InactivityTimeout feature.
USR108.Message: Unable to set the Quick Sync InactivityTimeout feature because the InactivityTimerEnable attribute is disabled.

STOR318.Description: Expansion of storage capacity of a Virtual Disk is limited by the disk space of its physical disks and the Virtual Disk RAID level. Based on these two values there is a maximum limit on the capacity expansion size of a Virtual Disk.
STOR318.Resolution: Make sure that the Virtual Disk size specified for the reconfiguration operation is less than or equal to the maximum possible value. For information about the maximum possible value, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide available at the support site.
STOR318.Message: Unable to perform the reconfiguration operation because the Virtual Disk size specified is invalid.

VF053.Description: CreatePartitionUsingImage method cannot be completed because the URI and Share Type entered do not match.
VF053.Resolution: Make sure that the URI and Share Type match, and then retry the operation.
VF053.Message: Unable to CreatePartition because the URI and Share Type entered do not match.

OSD67.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'IPAddress' is missing.
OSD67.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "IPAddress" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD67.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'IPAddress' is missing.

RAC1200.Description: The SupportAssist Registration operation did not complete successfully because either the values are not entered or are invalid.
RAC1200.Resolution: Retry the operation by entering correct values. For information about the correct values, run the RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI): "racadm supportassist help register".
RAC1200.Message: Unable to complete the SupportAssist register operation because either the values are not entered or are invalid.

PCI2000.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI2000.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device.
PCI2000.Message: A fatal IO error detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

SYS134.Description: The report size is more than the 30MB allowed size which will cause a truncated, partial report to be generated.
SYS134.Resolution: Remove older log entries so that the final zip archive size can be reduced.
SYS134.Message: OS Collector: Zip archive size exceeded the limit.

RAC1030.Description: The custom signing certificate present on iDRAC was deleted.
RAC1030.Message: The custom signing certificate was deleted.

TMPS0100.Description: Inlet temperature has been above the warning threshold for duration of 8% or more for the operational time during the last one year.
TMPS0100.Resolution: This condition will occur if the ambient temperature is high. Make sure the ambient temperature of the environment is in normal range.
TMPS0100.Message: Inlet temperature is above warning level for extended duration.

UEFI0293.Description: DDR memory initialization of the Dual In-line Memory Modules (DIMMs) installed in the system cannot be completed because the DIMMs are installed in an unsupported, asymmetrical configuration between the Integrated Memory Controllers (iMCs).
UEFI0293.Resolution: Remove the Dual Inline Memory Module's (DIMMs) and install in a supported, symmetric configuration between the Integrated Memory Controllers (iMCs). For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual available on the support site.
UEFI0293.Message: Unable to initialize all Dual Inline Memory Modules (DIMMs) in the system because DIMMs are installed in an unsupported, asymmetric configuration between the Integrated Memory Controllers (iMCs).

UEFI0276.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the initiator information from DHCPv6 server cannot be obtained.
UEFI0276.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Check the configuration of DHCPv6 server. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable DHCP and configure the initiator information manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0276.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the initiator information from DHCPv6 server cannot be obtained.

UEFI0029.Description: iDRAC could not be initialized because of some critical issues. Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as remote out of band access, active power management, thermal management, inventory collection, LCD, or system error reporting.
UEFI0029.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. 3) Continue to boot. Note: This may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as remote out of band access, active power management, thermal management, inventory collection, LCD, or system error reporting.
UEFI0029.Message: Unable to initialize iDRAC because of some critical issues.

SRV039.Description: The OS Collector Application is unable to create an Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI) session.
SRV039.Resolution: Restart the Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) service and then retry the operation. For restarting WMI service, see the iDRAC9 User's Guide.
SRV039.Message: The OS Collector Application is unable to create an Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI) session.

SWU8560.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful because of a unrecognized image error.
SWU8560.Resolution: Obtain a valid firmware image from your service provider and retry the operation.
SWU8560.Message: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful because of a unrecognized image error.

SYS126.Description: Application data source was not found. An issue occurred while collecting Application Data because of an unknown exception.
SYS126.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS126.Message: OS Collector: Unable to collect Application Data.

CBL0004.Description: The cable identified in the message is incorrectly connected to the backplane connector.
CBL0004.Resolution: Make sure the cable identified in the message is cabled correctly. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0004.Message: The %1 cable is incorrectly connected to backplane %2 connector %3.

PSU0044.Description: The power supply is operating but the system cannot get status information.
PSU0044.Resolution: If problem persist, remove and re-install power supply.
PSU0044.Message: Cannot obtain status information from power supply %1.

RAC0764.Description: Selecting a higher SSL encryption enhances the security. However, the cryptography settings for your virtual machine environment (JVM, IcedTea) may require installing the Unlimited Strength Java Cryptography Extension Policy Files to permit usage of iDRAC plugins such as vConsole with this higher level of encryption.NOTE: Using this level of encryption may have import or export implications. For more guidance, contact your legal department.
RAC0764.Message: Selecting a higher SSL encryption enhances the security. However, the cryptography settings for your virtual machine environment (JVM, IcedTea) may require installing the Unlimited Strength Java Cryptography Extension Policy Files to permit usage of iDRAC plugins such as vConsole with this higher level of encryption. NOTE: Using this level of encryption may have import or export implications. For more guidance, contact your legal department.

OSD12.Description: iDRAC was unable to create and expose the drivers as a USB device for the OS installation to proceed.
OSD12.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD12.Message: Cannot create the USB device needed to copy drivers for the selected operating system.

CTL44.Description: A diagnostics test failed. The text for this message is generated by the tool that ran the diagnostics and can vary depending on the situation.
CTL44.Resolution: Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information on the diagnostic test.

PWR2201.Message: The system is sleeping with system hardware and processor context maintained.

JCP034.Description: A new configuration or update job has been created.
JCP034.Message: %1 job is successfully created on iDRAC with %2.

RAC0207.Description: Certificate upload failed possibly due to poor network connection.
RAC0207.Resolution: Try the operation again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, issue a new Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and try again.

SWC9012.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate Delete operation is successfully scheduled.
SWC9012.Resolution: Restart the host server for the changes to take effect.
SWC9012.Message: The SecureBoot Certificate Delete operation is successfully scheduled. Restart the host server for the changes to take effect.

CPU0003.Resolution: 1) Turn off the server and disconnect input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Reduce system configuration to minimum memory and remove all PCI devices. If system completes POST, update system BIOS. Re-install memory and PCI one component at a time to meet the original configuration. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

BAR062.Description: Collecting the Lifecycle Controller configuration database and copying it into the server profile backup file.

BAR113.Description: The Automatic Backup job that was earlier schedule was not successfully created. This could be due to an invalid parameter entered to create the job.
BAR113.Resolution: Using the iDRAC Web UI, select Server Profile from the navigation panel, and then the Automatic Backup tab. Clear Settings and reenter appropriate data, the select Schedule Backup to restart the Automatic Backup jobs. Using the RACADM CLI or WSMAN API, clear the scheduled backup settings and retry the Automatic Backup scheduling operation.
BAR113.Message: Unable to create an Automatic Backup job.

VFL1008.Description: An error is reported during a SD card read or write.
VFL1008.Resolution: Re-install the flash media, if the issue persists replace the media.
VFL1008.Message: Failure detected on Removable Flash Media %1.

SYS418.Description: The test event cannot be sent because the Alert service is disabled.
SYS418.Resolution: Enable the attribute IPMILan.1.AlertEnable by using the PATCH operation on the Redfish OemAttributes URL, and then retry the operation.
SYS418.Message: Unable to send the test event because the Alert service is disabled.

PR22.Description: This is the initial job status value when a job is created. This message is no longer in use in Lifecycle Controller 2.0 as the job control functionality handles this operation.

PR35.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference for the power supply and will start the firmware update process upon system reboot.
PR35.Message: Power Supply slot %1 firmware update will be performed during next system reboot.

UEFI0136.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This issue is caused by missing LC partitions.
UEFI0136.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0136.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

RAC0212.Description: This is a generic error message used on all the login pages.
RAC0212.Message: Login failed. Verify that username and password is correct.

SWC0087.Description: The Public IP access feature in iDRAC is disabled by the Integrated Data Center solution. The iDRAC can no longer be accessed via the public IP interface.
SWC0087.Message: The Integrated Data Center Public IP mode is disabled.

RAC948.Description: A test event notification for the specified message ID was not sent to the configured destination.
RAC948.Resolution: Make sure to the use a valid message ID, set the required notification filter, and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC948.Message: Unable to send the notification for the specified event to the configured destination.

PWR219.Description: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because PSU in the slot identified in the message is not a 3000 W PSU.
PWR219.Resolution: In order to use the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature, replace the PSU identified in the message with a 3000 W PSU.
PWR219.Message: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because the PSU in slot %1 is not a 3000 W PSU.

PWR2402.Description: The iDRAC controller cannot communicate with the power management firmware due to an problem with the interface to the power management engine or with the power management engine itself. The system may operate in a performance degraded state.
PWR2402.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Controller Log (LC Log) and make sure that there are no subsequent log entries indicating that Communication with power management firmware has been restored. If this log entry is not present then do one of the following: 1) Disconnect system input power, wait one minute, reconnect system input power. 2) Re-flash system BIOS. 3) Upgrade system BIOS to the latest revision.
PWR2402.Message: iDRAC is unable to communicate with power management firmware.

RRDU0005.Description: The current operating configuration cannot maintain redundancy. The unit may operate in a degraded state.
RRDU0005.Resolution: Review product documentation and SD card configuration.
RRDU0005.Message: Internal Dual SD Module is not redundant. Insufficient resources to maintain normal operations.

LC020.Description: The contents of the PKCS12 parameter was not valid because: 1) not a valid PKCS12 file 2) not a valid pfx file 3) did not contain a certificate that matched the private key in the file.
LC020.Resolution: Validate that the PKCS12 content was Base64 encoded. OpenSSL can be used to create or validate a PKCS12 encoding.
LC020.Message: PKCS12 decrypt of the certificate could not complete.

SUP0120.Message: Preparing for firmware update. Please wait.

SWC0230.Description: vFlash is not enabled. This may be because the user does not have enough privileges.

BAR039.Description: The license required for operation is not present.
BAR039.Resolution: Use supported vFlash media and licensing for this feature, and try the operation again.

PDR13.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk has failed or is corrupted. In addition, you may have cancelled the rebuild.
PDR13.Resolution: Replace the failed or corrupt disk, and then start the rebuild operation.

PCI5004.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected an issue in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in the slot identified in the message.
PCI5004.Resolution: Make sure that: 1) The PCIe adapter used is supported by the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). For a list of supported adapters, contact your service provider. 2) The adapter is not damaged. 3) The power requirement of adapter is not more than the power allocated to the slot. 4) The adapter is properly inserted in the slot.
PCI5004.Message: A power fault issue is detected in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in PCIe slot%1.

SWC0018.Description: The BIOS boot mode settings could not be applied due to an internal error.
SWC0018.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit the Lifecycle Controller and perform an AC power cycle.
SWC0018.Message: Unable to apply the boot mode settings for BIOS.

SWC0156.Message: CSR file downloaded from RAC successfully

ISM0026.Description: The iDRAC Hard Reset operation is performed by system OS user identified in the message from the operating system (OS) on the day-date-time-year identified in the message.
ISM0026.Resolution: The iDRAC may take up to 2 minutes to fully restart. Wait until the iDRAC is fully restarted before performing further operations with the iDRAC.
ISM0026.Message: The iDRAC Hard Reset operation is performed by system OS user %1 from the operating system (OS) on date %2.

OSE1007.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. See system video for additional information.

SWC0132.Description: Either the destination Ip address is not reachable or the required values are not configured.
SWC0132.Resolution: Check for the connectivity to the configured Ip address.
SWC0132.Message: Unable to send test trap. Please make sure that your trap has been configured correctly and connectivity to the destination endpoint exists.

PWR8557.Description: The current Power Cap setting cannot be enforced. This may be the result of changing the redundancy mode or by changing the PSUs. The power cap setting must be increased to be usable.
PWR8557.Resolution: Increase the Power Cap value. To increase the Power Cap do one of the following: 1) Using CMC Web interface: Select "Chassis Overview" -> Power -> Configuration and then adjust System Input Power Cap values. 2) Run the following RACADM command at the command line interface: "config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerCap <value>".Try setting the power cap above the lower bound displayed on the power configuration page.
PWR8557.Message: The System Input Power Cap is too low to be enforced using the current Power Supply configuration.

PWR200.Description: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature will disable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature. MPCM forces servers in to a low-power and limited-performance mode, and then disables the ability to turn on additional servers.
PWR200.Message: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature will disable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature.

SRV001.Description: The SupportAssist Collection operation is started by the interface identified in the message.
SRV001.Message: The SupportAssist Collection operation is started by %1.

AMP0301.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0301.Message: The system board %1 current is less than the lower critical threshold.

BOOT8500.Description: Unable to change the BIOS boot order for the server because of a broken communication between the CMC and iDRAC, or iDRAC is rebooting.
BOOT8500.Resolution: Reset iDRAC or wait until iDRAC reboots, and retry the operation.
BOOT8500.Message: Unable to change the BIOS boot order for the Server %1

POW003.Description: Host failed to power up because PCI/Mezz cards not installed in Fabric1/Fabric2.This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2253.
POW003.Message: Power on permission error, no PCI/Mezz card installed in Fabric1/Fabric2.

NIC016.Description: A set attribute operation was attempted on a disabled attribute.
NIC016.Message: AttributeValue cannot be changed for disabled AttributeName %1.

VLT0201.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0201.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0201.Message: The system board %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

SRV021.Description: The SupportAssist OS and Application data collection operation is started.
SRV021.Message: The SupportAssist OS and Application data collection operation is started.

UEFI0212.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Early Command Training phase.
UEFI0212.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0212.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC0700.Description: An email page was successfully sent.

PWR8507.Description: The system Input Power Cap was changed from the value to the value indicated in the message.
PWR8507.Message: System Input Power Cap changed from %1W AC to %2W AC.

STOR089.Description: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.
STOR089.Resolution: To apply the configuration operation immediately, create a configuration job using the --realtime option. To create the necessary real-time job, run the jobqueue command. For more information about jobqueue command, run the racadm help jobqueue command.
STOR089.Message: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.

RED022.Description: The version compatibility check of the firmware update package was not successful for the device specified.
RED022.Resolution: The version compatibility check was not successful for the device specified. Verify that the firmware version pre-requisites specified in the release notes are satisfied.
RED022.Message: Version compatibility check was not successful.

RAC0501.Description: Physical disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off or the physical disks are removed. This may result in communication loss while retrieving controller data.
RAC0501.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Check if the physical disks are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane. 3. There are no out-of-band capable controllers detected.
RAC0501.Message: There are no physical disks to be displayed.

OSD54.Description: vFlash allows only 16 partitions to be created.
OSD54.Resolution: Make sure that there are less than 16 partitions before creating another partition on vFlash.

RAC0246.Description: The contents of a read-only partition cannot be modified.
RAC0246.Resolution: Make sure the partition is writable before attempting to change its contents.

GMGR0017.Description: The group member identified in the message cannot be removed from group identified in the message because a group job is in progress with in the group. Retry the operation after the group job is complete.
GMGR0017.Resolution: Log in to the group manager and track the progress of the group task. Retry the operation once the group task is completed.
GMGR0017.Message: Unable to remove the group member %1 from group %2 because a group job is in progress with in the group.

IOID117.Description: The iDRAC has applied I/O Identity settings on NIC and FC HBA devices. All the device configuration related to virtual addresses, initiator and target settings have been configured successfully according to the current persistence policy settings.
IOID117.Message: The operation to apply I/O Identity settings based on current persistence policy settings has completed successfully.

RFL2003.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is online.

OSD63.Description: The DetachDrivers invoke method cannot be run because the driver files are not attached.
OSD63.Message: Unable to run the DetachDrivers invoke method because the driver files are not attached.

PCI2003.Message: The component at slot %1 recovered from a fatal IO error.

IPA0100.Description: The iDRAC IP Address changed from the earlier IP Address identified in the message to the new IP Address identified in the message. This notification will be generated when the iDRAC network card selection is changed, if the DHCP lease expires and the DHCP server assigns another address, or if iDRAC IP address is manually changed.
IPA0100.Resolution: Remote management consoles that have cached or stored the iDRAC IP address may have to be updated with the new IP address either through a re-discovery or manual reconfiguration. A response action may not be required if the console receives this SNMP notification and updates the iDRAC IP address accordingly.
IPA0100.Message: The iDRAC IP Address changed from %1 to %2.

BAT1030.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1030.Message: The %1 battery charge level is normal.

JCP009.Description: Scheduled jobs were deleted as a result of a cancel job request. The job cancellation request is manually or programmatically initiated. Lifecycle Controller enters Recovery mode when unrecoverable and persistent errors occur.
JCP009.Resolution: If the job was not cancelled manually, then Lifecycle Controller may be in Recovery mode. To verify or change Recovery mode, use F2 Setup to select iDRAC Configuration then Lifecycle Controller Settings.

GMGR0029.Description: The iDRAC identified in the message is successfully ignored from the Group Manager's autodiscovery, and then added to the Ignore list.
GMGR0029.Message: The iDRAC %1 is successfully ignored from the Group Manager's autodiscovery.

RFL2008.Description: The Internal Dual SD Card redundancy feature was disabled. The SD card identified in the message is disabled.
RFL2008.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is disabled.

RAC0504.Description: Enclosures cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, there is no enclosure connected to the controller, or there is a bad or disconnected adapter cable for the enclosure.
RAC0504.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is ON. 2. Check if the Storage Enclosure is ON. 3. Verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0504.Message: There are no enclosures to be displayed.

SWC0024.Description: The Test Network Connection ping test timed-out. The network cable is disconnected or the network is not configured correctly.
SWC0024.Resolution: Check the network cable connection and network configuration settings, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, reconfigure the network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0024.Message: The Test Network Connection ping test timed-out.

LC070.Description: The configuration XML file used for the import operation does not exist on the specified network share.
LC070.Resolution: Make sure the input configuration XML file for the operation exists on the network share.
LC070.Message: Unable to find the configuration XML import file.

BAT1007.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1007.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle will start in %2 hours.

JCP017.Description: The current job count has reached the maximum value supported. No more jobs are created until the number of jobs on the system is reduced. Completed jobs are automatically deleted if they are older than the DeleteOnCompletionTimeout setting.
JCP017.Resolution: Do one of the following to reduce the job count: 1) Delete one or more jobs and retry the operation. 2) Wait until existing jobs have an elapsed time since completion that is greater than the delete on completion timeout setting and are automatically deleted. 3) change the DeleteOnCompletionTimeout setting using the WSMAN API to a smaller value so that completed jobs are automatically deleted sooner.
JCP017.Message: Job creation request unsuccessful. Maximum number of jobs reached.

PSU8519.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) feature is suspended due to the configuration or the type of PSU present. The feature is enabled, but suspended until a supported PSU configuration is in place.
PSU8519.Resolution: Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is not supported by the current power supply configuration. Verify the PSUs are supported. Replace the unsupported PSUs.
PSU8519.Message: Enhanced Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is not supported by the current power supply configuration and is suspended.

PSU8501.Description: Unable to retrieve input voltage information for the PSU specified in the message.
PSU8501.Resolution: Remove the PSU from the chassis, wait for two minutes, and reinsert it. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8501.Message: Unable to retrieve PSU %1 input voltage information.

VFL0009.Description: Unable to access the vFlash media, because another operation is currently using the vFlash media.
VFL0009.Resolution: Wait until the vFlash media is available for the requested operation, and then retry the operation.
VFL0009.Message: vFlash media is currently in use by another operation.

OSD31.Description: Copying drivers for the selected operating system to network share failed. The share may be read-only or the Driver Pack present in Lifecycle Controller may be unusable.
OSD31.Resolution: 1) Make sure that the network share has write permission. 2) Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and then rerun the command.
OSD31.Message: Copying operating system drivers to network share failed

PWR8554.Description: This situation occurs if the iDRAC is found to be turned off after power allocation information is sent by the CMC or if the communications between the CMC and iDRAC is non functional.
PWR8554.Resolution: Perform a Virtual Reseat of the component identified in the message. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components, and then select slot for the component identified in the message and apply the Virtual Reseat.
PWR8554.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to send power allocation information to %1-%2 at priority %3.

SWC0234.Description: The remote host specified for the ftp update is not reachable.
SWC0234.Resolution: Check the connectivity between iDRAC and the remote host used for the ftp update.
SWC0234.Message: Remote host is not reachable or connection is interrupted.

PR28.Description: The device that the job was intended for is no longer detected. This could be due to the device being removed, disabled, or a failure.
PR28.Resolution: If the device was removed, reinsert the device and retry the operation. If the device was disabled, re-enable the device and retry the operation.
PR28.Message: Unable to locate device in current configuration.

STOR0702.Description: The value entered for the option name identified in the message is invalid.
STOR0702.Resolution: For more information, run the RACADM command "racadm raid help createvd".
STOR0702.Message: The value entered for the %1 option is invalid

RAC0774.Description: The BIOS attributes cannot be displayed either because attributes are not present in the registry, a Lifecycle Controller Wipe operation has been performed, or there is an internal error.
RAC0774.Resolution: Retry the operation after doing the following: 1) Start the server. 2) Press F2 (System Setup) when the company logo is displayed. 3) On the System Setup page, click iDRAC Settings; Lifecycle Controller. Select Enabled corresponding to Lifecycle Controller and CSIOR. 4) After Lifecycle Controller and CSIOR are enabled, restart the system and make sure that the inventory collection operation completes successfully.
RAC0774.Message: Unable to display the BIOS attributes either because attributes are not present in the registry, a Lifecycle Controller Wipe operation has been performed, or there is an internal error.

UEFI0156.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license in three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor and the Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup options are being reverted to default because of the absent license.
UEFI0156.Resolution: If the absence of license is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0156.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license in three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor and the Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup options are being reverted to default because of the absent license.

SWC0089.Description: One or more iDRAC configurations cannot be saved by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.
SWC0089.Resolution: Make sure that the network cable is connected, DHCP server is turned on, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform the following steps: 1) Turn off the server and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the server, and then retry the operation.
SWC0089.Message: Unable to save one or more iDRAC configurations by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.

SWC0224.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0224.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0224.Message: Invalid syntax. The -d option is not valid with -u.

PST0084.Description: System started the Automated Task application.

RAC0243.Description: There was a conflict with a concurrent session. Another user may have logged in using a separate browser or RACADM.
RAC0243.Resolution: There was a conflict with a concurrent session. Refresh the page to see the currently available options.
RAC0243.Message: Partition failed: A partitioning conflict has occurred with another session.

RAC0514.Description: Virtual disk(s) cannot be created because of one or more reasons identified in the Recommended Response Action.
RAC0514.Resolution: Check the following: 1) If no physical disk drives are available for virtual disk (VD) creation, install additional physical disk drives. 2) If the maximum number of VDs that can be created on the controller has been reached, a new VD cannot be created until an existing VD is deleted. 3) If the maximum number of VDs supported by drive group has been created, a new VD cannot be created until an existing VD is deleted from the selected drive group. 4) If the physical disk drive(s) are in non-RAID mode, convert them to RAID mode by pressing Ctrl+R while restarting the server, and then select the required controller. Press F2 and select the Convert to RAID capable option, and then complete the operation. 5) If a job is currently running or scheduled on the selected controller, the job must be completed or deleted before attempting a new operation. Status of the scheduled job can be viewed and managed on the Job Queue page on iDRAC. Click Job Queue link to view the status of the scheduled jobs.
RAC0514.Message: Unable to create virtual disk(s) on the selected controller.

SYS400.Description: The precondition check operation such as Open Data Protocol (OData) Version, If-Match request-header, and If-Not-Modified request-headers cannot be completed.
SYS400.Resolution: Make sure that the prerequisites specified for the request are satisfied. For more information about the prerequisites, see the Redfish Specification and Redfish Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS400.Message: Unable to successfully complete the precondition check operations such as Open Data Protocol (OData) Version, If-Match request-header, and If-Not-Modified request-headers.

PST0012.Description: System extended memory test in progress.

BOOT008.Description: More source arguments were provided than are available for the impacted Boot Configuration.
BOOT008.Resolution: Verify that all of the Boot Source instance IDs being entered are as they appear in the DCIM_BootSourceSetting enumeration.
BOOT008.Message: Source argument contains more devices than are present on the system

SUP0518.Description: The specified firmware for the component was successfully updated.
SUP0518.Message: Successfully updated the %1 firmware to version %2.

SRV032.Description: The OS Collector Application is unable to collect the application data because of an unknown exception.
SRV032.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SRV032.Message: The OS Collector Application is unable to collect the application data because of an unknown exception.

VDR92.Description: This message occurs if there are medium errors in the physical drives.
VDR92.Message: Consistency check for %1 has completed with uncorrectable errors.

BAR080.Description: Importing the Lifecycle Controller configuration database from the system profile backup file.

VME0004.Description: Virtual Media session fails to start.
VME0004.Resolution: Retry the Virtual Media session initiation.
VME0004.Message: Virtual Media session fails to start.

SWC5005.Description: The System Controller (SC) firmware cannot be updated. For information about the causes, see SEL Event Data Byte 2.
SWC5005.Resolution: Retry the SC firmware update operation. If the issue persists, try updating by using a different firmware update file.
SWC5005.Message: Unable to update the System Controller (SC) firmware.

RAC011.Description: A Job has already been scheduled to apply pending iDRAC attribute values. Additional configuration operations are not allowed while there is a configuration Job pending execution.
RAC011.Resolution: Wait for the scheduled Job to complete before setting more attributes.
RAC011.Message: A configuration Job already exists, cannot process more set operations.

RED018.Description: Reinstall or Rollback not supported for this device.
