RED018.Resolution: 1. Update the device directly using the update methods since rollback is not supported for this device. 2. Verify that the target specified in the command is correct.
RED018.Message: Reinstall or Rollback not supported for this device.

SYS143.Description: ePSA Diagnostics are deleted because of a System Erase operation.

RAC0640.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'hour' while scheduling a job.
RAC0640.Resolution: Enter a correct value from 0 to 23, and then retry the operation.
RAC0640.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid 'hour' value is entered.

RAC0628.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested recurrent Automatic Update job is already scheduled.
RAC0628.Resolution: Delete the current scheduled job, and then retry to create a new Automatic Update job with a new schedule.
RAC0628.Message: Unable to schedule, because the requested recurrent Automatic Update job is already scheduled.

NIC018.Description: The input BIOS password used in the operation is invalid.
NIC018.Resolution: Use a valid BIOS password and retry.

ISM0023.Description: The feature WMI Information is disabled. It will be enabled when a compatible iDRAC firmware is installed.
ISM0023.Resolution: WMI Information feature requires iDRAC 8 firmware version 2.00.00 or later. Update the iDRAC firmware to the appropriate version to activate the WMI Information feature.
ISM0023.Message: The feature WMI Information is deactivated because the iDRAC firmware version installed is not compatible. It will be activated when the compatible iDRAC firmware is installed.

BIOS037.Description: The import operation cannot be started either because the file name identified in the message is invalid, file is corrupted, or the file encoding format is incorrect.
BIOS037.Resolution: Make sure that a valid file is used and retry the operation.
BIOS037.Message: Unable to start the import operation either because the file name entered : %1 is invalid, file is corrupted, or the file encoding format is incorrect.

PDR30.Description: The controller cannot to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a global hot spare. The disk either failed or was removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.
PDR30.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and installed. Check the cables. Refer to the product documentation and see the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the global hot spare.

UEFI0197.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Read Level Coarse Training phase.
UEFI0197.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0197.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

BIOS005.Description: The number of AttributeName and AttributeValue parameters do not match.
BIOS005.Resolution: Enter the same number of parameters for AttributeName and AttributeValue. Refer to documentation for method input parameter details.
BIOS005.Message: Mismatch in AttributeName and AttributeValue count

BAR037.Description: Adjustments to Lifecycle and Integrated Remote Access Controller environments are complete.
BAR037.Message: System Reset or Lifecycle Controller Actions Canceled, System Profile Failure Recovery completed.

RAC0666.Description: A RAID Controller Log is created.
RAC0666.Resolution: To export the Log report, click OK. To delete the report, click Cancel.
RAC0666.Message: A RAID Controller Log is created.

RAC052.Description: Unable to create a configuration job because an existing configuration job is already in progress. Only one configuration job for a component can run or can be processed at any time.
RAC052.Resolution: Retry the operation after the existing configuration job is complete, or cancel the existing configuration job and retry the operation.
RAC052.Message: Unable to create a configuration job because an existing configuration job is already in progress.

VF017.Description: The SD card is not initialized.
VF017.Resolution: In order to perform this operation, first initialize the SD Card.

PCI1360.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1360.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1360.Message: A bus fatal error was detected on a component at slot %1.

RED073.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the parameter identified in the message.
RED073.Resolution: Verify the value for the parameter identified in the message is valid and retry the operation.
RED073.Message: The input value entered for the parameter %1 is invalid.

SRV042.Description: An issue was encountered while communicating with iDRAC Service Module (iSM) present on the operating system.
SRV042.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Restart the iDRAC Service Module on the OS and retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest iDRAC Service Module Service on the OS and retry the operation .
SRV042.Message: An issue was encountered while communicating with iDRAC Service Module (iSM) present on the operating system.

VDR35.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk completed.

LIC004.Description: This error condition is reported when one of the following conditions occur: 1) Operating system detected a file error (for example, bad CRC, bad sector) when reading/writing a license manager file. The error could indicate bad or corrupt FLASH device. 2) License Manager detected an internal memory data corruption.3) The command or command parameters passed to License Manager is invalid. This is an internal error showing memory corruption. Under normal circumstances this error should not occur.4) When exporting a license file, License Manager was unable to allocate the temporary space required for the transfer of the file.
LIC004.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC004.Message: An internal system error has occurred.

LIC213.Description: This error can occur when:1) License Manager fails to load due to lack of system resources.
LIC213.Message: A system error was detected during License Manager startup.

PSU0078.Description: This power supply revision is not supported for this system.
PSU0078.Resolution: Review product documentation, change power supply with correct revision.

BOOT007.Description: One or more of the Boot Source instance IDs does not belong to the affected Boot Configuration.
BOOT007.Resolution: ChangeBootOrderByInstanceID only accepts Boot Sources from the impacted Boot Configuration. Verify that all source arguments belong to the desired Boot Configuration.
BOOT007.Message: Boot Source does not belong to specified Boot Configuration

SYS166.Description: The collection of OS and Application Data did not start within the allocated time.
SYS166.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) Make sure the OS does not have any firewall setting to block USB device enumeration, and then retry the operation. 3) Make sure the OS is not configured to attach USB devices as read-only, and then retry the operation. 4) Make sure the OS is supported by the OS Collector application. 5) Reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation. 6) For more information about the collection of OS and application data, see the iDRAC8 User's Guide.
SYS166.Message: The collection of OS and Application Data did not start within the allocated time.

USR0202.Description: The mobile device with the MAC Address identified in the message is no longer connected to Quick Sync.
USR0202.Message: Mobile device has disconnected from Quick Sync %1.

MEM0024.Message: Memory device at location %1 is no longer spare memory.

PCI1300.Description: The front panel diagnostic was pressed, and the system may be halted as a result. The interrupt was user induced.
PCI1300.Resolution: Reset the system to continue operation.
PCI1300.Message: A front panel diagnostic interrupt was detected.

SEL0013.Message: The system event log was created or initialized successfully.

RAC1182.Description: The server instrumentation can not provide any information related to power because PMBus capability is not present or the PSU(s) with PMBus capability have been removed.
RAC1182.Message: Unable to retrieve information for the Power group or attribute because the server is not PMBus capable.

UEFI0009.Description: A CPU segment not present exception (type 0x0B) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0009.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0009.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x0B: Segment Not Present (Software).

USR0172.Description: The Front Panel USB Management Port Mode setting is changed as identified in the message.
USR0172.Message: The Front Panel USB Management Port Mode setting is changed from %1 to %2.

FAN8502.Description: The current CMC firmware did not detect the blower identified in the message.
FAN8502.Resolution: Make sure that CMC is using the latest firmware, and then retry the operation.
FAN8502.Message: Unable to detect the blower %1 because the blower may not be optimally operating.

RAC092.Description: The file cannot be imported because the size of importing payload is greater than the file size specified in the start of packet.
RAC092.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Make sure that the size of file packet and file being imported is same. 2) Clear the partially imported file in iDRAC by using the WS-Man method "ClearTransferSession".
RAC092.Message: Unable to import the file because the size of importing payload is greater than the file size specified in the start of packet.

SYS002.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in iDRAC.
SYS002.Resolution: Retry the action. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC.
SYS002.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

RAC937.Description: The configuration XML file import operation was successfully initiated after it was invoked by the user specified in the message.
RAC937.Message: Successfully initiated configuration XML file import operation that was invoked by the %1.

ASR0002.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC). The system powered off per the configured setting.
ASR0002.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0002.Message: The watchdog timer powered off the system.

VLT0235.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is within range.

OSD5.Description: A Driver Pack was not found on the Lifecycle Controller.
OSD5.Resolution: Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and then run the command again.
OSD5.Message: Lifecycle Controller Driver Pack not found.

PWR8505.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature was not successfully enabled.
PWR8505.Resolution: Restart the Chassis Management Controller and retry the operation. To restart the Chassis Management Controller, using the WEB UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Control, select the Reset CMC option, and then click Apply.
PWR8505.Message: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature was not successfully enabled.

RAC033.Description: The specified attribute cannot be enabled since it depends on IPv4 to be enabled.
RAC033.Resolution: Enable IPv4 and retry the operation.
RAC033.Message: Unable to enable attribute because IPv4 is Disabled.

CMC8608.Description: The operation cannot be started on the server identified in the message because of insufficient user privileges.
CMC8608.Resolution: Retry the operation by using user credential that has Server Debug privileges. For more information about recommended user privileges, contact your system administrator or service provider.
CMC8608.Message: Unable to start the operation on server in slot %1, because of insufficient user privileges.

RED074.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because the required parameters were not present in the method invocation.
RED074.Resolution: Verify that all required parameters for the method are present and retry the operation.
RED074.Message: A required parameter is not present.

SYS241.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported proxy type value.
SYS241.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy type value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS241.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported proxy type value, %2.

RAC0509.Description: The server is currently unable to handle the request due to temporary overloading or server maintenance.
RAC0509.Resolution: Wait for few minutes and refresh the page. If the issue persists, contact service provider.
RAC0509.Message: The server is temporarily unavailable. Try again after sometime.

VRM0018.Message: Virtual Media image server operation successful

SRV047.Description: The collection of OS and Application Data did not start within the allocated time.
SRV047.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure that the OS Collector application supports the OS installed on the server. If the OS is not supported, the OS Collector may not function correctly. 2) Reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation. To install the OS Collector using the iDRAC Web UI, get the latest OC Collector update package and then select the Update and Rollback link from the iDRAC Web UI home page and upload the install package. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SRV047.Message: The collection of OS and Application Data did not start within the allocated time.

STOR027.Description: Setting the Virtual disk name is not a valid operation on the specified controller.
STOR027.Resolution: Do not specify the virtual disk name and retry the operation.
STOR027.Message: Virtual Disk name is not supported.

SWC8562.Description: All of the specified MAC addresses are deactivated from the Virtual MAC Address Pool.
SWC8562.Message: All of the specified MAC addresses are deactivated from the Virtual MAC Address Pool of Boot Identity profile operations.

HWC9001.Description: The BOSS device identified in the message may stop functioning because either the inlet temperature, fan health, or total power associated with the BOSS device is reaching the threshold value.
HWC9001.Resolution: Make sure that the inlet temperature, fan health, or total power associated with the BOSS device is within specified limits. For information about specified values, see the iDRAC 9.0 and later User's Guide available on the support site.
HWC9001.Message: The %1 device may stop functioning because either the inlet temperature, fan health, or total power associated with the %1 device is reaching the threshold value.

IOID116.Description: The iDRAC has started to apply I/O Identity settings on NIC and FC HBA devices based on the current persistence policy settings.
IOID116.Message: Applying I/O Identity settings based on current persistence policy settings.

SUP0101.Description: Unable to get the update status.
SUP0101.Message: Unable to get firmware update status.

SWC8533.Description: The delete all keys for service accounts for all slots operation did not complete successfully due to problems encountered while saving the key file.
SWC8533.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8533.Message: Unable to complete delete all keys operation for service accounts for all slots due to problem saving key file.

CTL21.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL21.Message: Abort CC on Error and Load Balance has changed for %1.

RAC1021.Description: NIC objects are not available if NIC devices are not installed in the system, or if some iDRAC services are busy.
RAC1021.Resolution: Make sure the NIC devices are correctly installed in the system and retry the operation after the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature has updated the system inventory. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC1021.Message: NIC objects are not available in the current system configuration.

RAC0767.Description: The USB NIC IP address identified in the message cannot be assigned to the OSBMC device because IP address setting conflicts with existing network interface IP.
RAC0767.Resolution: Enter an unique IP address for OSBMC USB NIC that is not the same as another NICs IP address, and then retry the operation. For information about supported IP addresses, refer to the iDRAC Users Guide available at the support site.
RAC0767.Message: Unable to assign USB NIC IP address %1 to the OSBMC device because IP address setting conflicts with existing network interface IP.

MEM1201.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM1201.Message: Memory RAID redundancy is lost. Check memory device at location(s) %1.

PDR61.Description: It is not possible to rebuild data that resides on a defective disk.
PDR61.Resolution: Replace the source disk and restore data from backup.
PDR61.Message: The rebuild of %1 failed due to errors on the source physical disk.

AMP0314.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0314.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0314.Message: System level current is greater than the upper warning threshold.

CMC8577.Description: The Remote Access Controller (RAC) Kerberos Keytab is changed.
CMC8577.Message: The Remote Access Controller (RAC) Kerberos Keytab is changed.

PDR51.Description: The controller firmware attempted to do SMART polling on the hot spare but could not complete the SMART polling. The controller may have lost communication with the hot spare.
PDR51.Resolution: Verify the health of the disk assigned as a hot spare. Replace the disk and reassign the hot spare. Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables.
PDR51.Message: Hot spare %1 SMART polling has failed.%2

BAR032.Description: The system profile backup file validation did not complete successfully.
BAR032.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) An incorrect passphrase may have been entered, correct the input and retry the operation. 2) Download a valid backup image of the host system and retry. 3) Reboot the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) and retry. 4) Download a new firmware image for the iDRAC and retry.

ENC1.Description: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has failed is inserted into the enclosure.

STOR092.Description: The requested configuration operation cannot be run because a foreign configuration import operation on the controller is already in progress.
STOR092.Resolution: Wait for the import process to complete before running any configuration operation.
STOR092.Message: Unable to run the configuration operation on the controller because foreign configuration import operation is in progress.

SWC0019.Description: The Test Network Connection ping test timed-out. The network cable is disconnected or the network is not configured correctly.
SWC0019.Resolution: Check the network cable connection and network configuration settings, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, reconfigure the network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0019.Message: The Test Network Connection operation completed with errors.

UEFI0176.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slots.
UEFI0176.Resolution: Only a single Quad Rank DIMM module can be installed on a channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0176.Message: Multiple Quad Rank DIMM modules are installed on a DDR channel. Refer to DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

BAT0014.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may report absent due to disconnect or thermal exceptions.
BAT0014.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation for the associated bay. 2) If installed, reseat or reconnect the battery and cables. 3) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.
BAT0014.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is absent.

SYS417.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because the value entered for the query parameter is out of range as identified in the message.
SYS417.Resolution: Enter a query parameter value within range and retry the operation.
SYS417.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the value %1 entered for the query parameter %2 is out of range %3.

RAC0271.Description: Locking the user account prevents them from gaining access to iDRAC.
RAC0271.Resolution: Press OK to lock this user account. This action will prevent future access for this user. If undesired press Cancel.

PDR68.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR68.Message: Dedicated spare %1 imported as global due to missing disk groups.

SWC0103.Description: The specified log does not take in the -e option.
SWC0103.Message: The -E option is not valid for the specified log.

NIC009.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage because it is use by another application or operation.
NIC009.Resolution: Wait for the current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator utility 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
NIC009.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

RAC1025.Description: Some objects have dependencies on other objects that are required to perform a task. However, some of the objects are read-only because of the current system configuration and the values of the dependent objects.
RAC1025.Resolution: Verify the object dependency using "racadm help <device class>.<group name>.<object name>", and retry the operation.
RAC1025.Message: The specified object is read-only and cannot be modified due to an object dependency.

USR0175.Description: The USB device attached to the port identified in the message is drawing more current than is supported by the port.
USR0175.Resolution: Reinsert the USB device in the Front Panel USB Port and retry the operation. If the issue persists, use a different USB device.
USR0175.Message: The Front Panel USB Port Over Current is detected for the attached device on Disk.USBFront.%1.

SWC0112.Description: A network time-out occurred while trying to perform the power action.
SWC0112.Message: Timeout while waiting for server to perform requested power action.

CTL25.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL25.Message: Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.

SWC8514.Description: Unable to delete the user name identified in the message.
SWC8514.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.

BAR051.Description: The configuration import for the specified device is in progress.
BAR051.Message: Performing Component Configuration Restore for Device : %1

RAC1010.Description: The power cap cannot be set if the object Power.Cap is disabled.
RAC1010.Resolution: Enable Power Cap setting using "racadm set System.Power.Cap.Enable < 1 | Enabled >", and retry the operation.
RAC1010.Message: Unable to set the power cap value.

RFM1026.Description: An error is reported during a SD card read or write.
RFM1026.Resolution: Re-install the flash media, if the issue persists replace the media.
RFM1026.Message: Failure detected on Removable Flash Media.

SWC0277.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0277.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0277.Message: Invalid syntax. The -i option is only valid with -g and -o.

FC004.Description: The value for the specified parameter is invalid.
FC004.Resolution: Make sure that the input parameter values that are provided to the method match the parameter data type and possible values defined in the FC HBA Profile specification.

RAC070.Description: The SSL Web-Server certificate was successfully restored to factory defaults.
RAC070.Message: The SSL Web-Server certificate was successfully restored to factory defaults.

SYS133.Description: An issue was encountered while creating an IPMI session.
SYS133.Resolution: Restart the WMI service and retry the operation.

PWR2266.Description: The power supply unit (PSU) identified in the message is disabled because of a generation mismatch and therefore the PSU is not supported on the server.
PWR2266.Resolution: Install a supported power supply unit (PSU). For information about PSUs of supported generations, see the product documentation available on the support site.
PWR2266.Message: The power supply unit (PSU) %1 is disabled because of a generation mismatch and therefore the PSU is not supported on the server.

PST0082.Description: System is at the BIOS Setup Menu.

VF003.Description: The required input parameter identified in the message is missing.
VF003.Resolution: Refer the iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller User Guides for the required input parameters for this method.

SWC8552.Description: The server in slot identified in the message does not have a profile associated with it.
SWC8552.Message: The server in slot %1 does not have a profile associated with it.

SYS015.Description: The requested job has been created.

VLT0100.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0100.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0100.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

RAC0511.Description: Physical disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, physical disks are removed, or incorrect filters are applied.
RAC0511.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Check if the physical disks are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane. 3. Check if correct filters are applied. 4. Check that the Storage Enclosure is on. 5. verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0511.Message: There are no physical disks to be displayed.

BAR043.Description: A timeout occurred waiting for the Unified Server Configurator (USC) to exit.
BAR043.Message: Timeout waiting for Unified Server Configurator to exit.

RAC1223.Description: The Client trust certificate cannot be deleted.
RAC1223.Resolution: Ensure a client trust certificate is already uploaded by running the following RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI)and then retry the operation."racadm sslcertdownload -f <filename> -t 4" If the issue persists contact service provider.
RAC1223.Message: Unable to delete the Client trust certificate.

MEM8500.Description: A low memory condition was detected. If this condition continues, a failover or a reset may occur. If multiple resets occur, contact your service provider.
MEM8500.Resolution: If multiple resets occur, contact Service.

PCI3000.Description: Either the BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, or LOM firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3000.Resolution: Update BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, and LOM firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3000.Message: Device option ROM on embedded NIC failed to support Link Tuning or FlexAddress.

HWC8510.Description: The heat sinks of the PCIe switches are properly attached.
HWC8510.Message: The heat sinks of the PCIe switches are properly attached.

SWC0056.Description: Unable to export the file to the USB drive because it does not have the specified folder, does not have enough free space, or is read-only.
SWC0056.Resolution: Make sure that the USB drive contains the folder specified, has enough free space, or is not read-only. If the problem persists, reboot the system and retry the operation.
SWC0056.Message: Unable to export the file to the USB drive.

UEFI0039.Description: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Keyboard Controller Style (KCS) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI). Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as remote out of band access, active power management, thermal management, inventory collection, LCD, or system error reporting.
UEFI0039.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0039.Message: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Keyboard Controller Style (KCS) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).

RAC0674.Description: Export Report will create a zip file of XML and text-based logs intended for Dell Technical Support assistance with troubleshooting system issues. Choose Advanced Export Options to specify optional report settings and actions.
RAC0674.Message: Export Report will create a zip file of XML and text-based logs intended for Dell Technical Support assistance with troubleshooting system issues. Choose Advanced Export Options to specify optional report settings and actions.

ISM0014.Description: The feature identified in the message is disabled by using one of the iDRAC interfaces.

USR101.Description: Unable to allocate the resource because of the lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC firmware.
USR101.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.

SYS180.Description: The TTY log data of the storage controller identified in the message cannot be exported because an issue was encountered while communicating with the controller.
SYS180.Resolution: While exporting the TTY log, make sure that the server is not in BIOS POST, and then retry the operation. Use GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus() invoke method and check for output parameter RTStatus and ensure it shows 0 (ready status) and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC, and retry the operation.
SYS180.Message: There was an issue encountered when attempted to export TTY Log data for the storage controller %1.

PDR1019.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is no longer the hot-spare drive.

SWC0722.Description: iDRAC is processing a previous reset to default command.
SWC0722.Message: Error occurred while resetting to defaults. The reset command was not accepted.

SRV059.Description: Unable to detect the host network connection because the host proxy authentication did not complete successfully.
SRV059.Resolution: Make sure the host proxy information entered in iDRAC is correct and retry the operation.
SRV059.Message: Unable to detect the host network connection because the host proxy authentication did not complete successfully.

BIOS008.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. To create a configuration job, at least one attribute should be changed.
BIOS008.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes and then create a configuration job.
BIOS008.Message: No pending data present to create a Configuration job.

RAC967.Description: The configuration XML file can only be exported to a remote share while using Firmware RACADM.
RAC967.Resolution: When using Firmware RACADM, make sure to export the configuration XML file to a remote share only.
RAC967.Message: Exporting the configuration XML file to a local share is not supported when using Firmware RACADM.

SYS047.Description: The input file is not compliant with the system configuration schema.
SYS047.Resolution: Make sure that the input file is compliant with the system configuration schema published on delltechcenter.com/lc in the LC profile Schema Guide.
SYS047.Message: Input file for import configuration is not compliant with the configuration schema.

VDR12.Description: This message is generated after reconfiguration of a virtual disk starts.

TMP0133.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0133.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0133.Message: The control panel temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PR10.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference and would apply firmware based on user settings for the system. However, the previous device's firmware update package is not present on the Lifecycle Controller.
PR10.Resolution: Use Unified Server Configurator or Dell update package to update device.
PR10.Message: Firmware update will not be performed. Firmware package is not present for %1

PWR8583.Description: To enable 110V operation, the Allow 110VAC Operation feature must be enabled. If the feature is not enabled, the server turn-on operation will not be processed.
PWR8583.Resolution: On the Power Configuration page, in the Web UI, select the Allow 110VAC Operation for power supplies and retry the operation. Using the RACADM utility, run the following command, "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisAllow110VACOperation 1".
PWR8583.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because unacknowledged 110V PSUs are present.

VLT0227.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0227.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0227.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

RAC940.Description: If an existing system profile import or export job is running, then a system configuration profile backup or restore operation cannot be started.
RAC940.Resolution: Wait until the existing system profile export or import job is completed or cancel the job before retrying the operation.
RAC940.Message: Unable to start the system configuration profile export or import operation.

RAC0664.Description: Exporting the RAID Controller Log will take less than the number of minutes identified in the message. The job identified in the message is created for the RAID Controller Log Export operation.
RAC0664.Resolution: To check the progress of the job click the Job Queue button.
RAC0664.Message: Exporting the RAID Controller Log will take less than %1 minutes. Job ID: #{jobID} is created for the RAID Controller Log Export operation.

DKM1002.Message: Key management server certificate problem detected.

SWC4008.Description: FlexAddress is not implemented in one of the versions of firmware. Please update the firmware.
SWC4008.Resolution: Check firmware versions. Update CMC 1 and CMC 2 firmware to match.
SWC4008.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility detected between CMC 1 and CMC 2.

SYS407.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the value entered for the query parameter identified in the message is invalid.
SYS407.Resolution: Enter a valid value and retry the operation. The minimum value that can entered for top query parameter is 1.
SYS407.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the value %1 entered for the query parameter %2 is invalid.

BAR056.Description: The configuration import was successful for the specified device.

ISM0027.Description: An unprivileged user identified in the message tried to perform an iDRAC Hard Reset operation from the operating system (OS).
ISM0027.Message: An unprivileged user %1 tried to perform an iDRAC Hard Reset operation from the operating system (OS).

RAC0676.Description: Unable to assign physical disk drives as global hotspare(s). This may be because there are no disk drives available in a ready state or there are no virtual disks present.
RAC0676.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) If there are no disk drives available in ready state, insert additional disk drives and make sure the drives are in ready state. 2) If no virtual disks are present, click <create virtualdisk link> and create at least one virtual disk. 3) If the physical disk drive(s) are in non-RAID mode, convert them to RAID mode by pressing Ctrl+R while restarting the server, and then select the required controller. Press F2 and select the Convert to RAID capable option, and then complete the operation.
RAC0676.Message: Unable to assign physical disk drives as global hotspare(s).

STOR013.Description: One or more storage device(s) are in a state that prevents the operation from completing.
STOR013.Resolution: Make sure the specified storage devices are in a state appropriate for the requested operation and retry the operation.
STOR013.Message: One or more storage device(s) are not in a state where the operation can be completed.

RAC1198.Description: The LCD panel firmware cannot be updated either because of connection issues or the LCD bezel is damaged.
RAC1198.Resolution: Remove the LCD bezel and reinstall. If the issue persists, replace the LCD bezel.
RAC1198.Message: Unable to update the LCD panel firmware either because of connection issues or the LCD bezel is damaged.

VFL0002.Description: The status of vFlash SD Card or the vFlash media partition cannot be obtained, because some of the iDRAC services are busy.
VFL0002.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation. If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
VFL0002.Message: Unable to query the vFlash media status.

PWR8562.Description: Unable to power on the server before the power on timer has expired. This happens if the server did not show power on status change within 30 seconds after the power on operation was initiated. This issue may also occur when iDRAC is rebooting.
PWR8562.Resolution: The Server may need more time to power on. Wait for ten seconds and check the power status. If the server was not powered on, retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the server, wait for the iDRAC to complete startup, and retry the operation.
PWR8562.Message: Unable to power on the server %1 before power on timer expired.

JCP026.Description: Update packages are being downloaded for other jobs initiated on this system. This job resumes when the downloads complete.
JCP026.Message: Update packages are being downloaded. This job resumes when the downloads are completed.

LOG003.Description: The log entry with the specified InstanceID does not have any associated configuration results.
LOG003.Resolution: Verify the ConfigResults availability for the InstanceID through enumeration of the LogEntry class and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
LOG003.Message: ConfigResults not available for log entry specified.

SWC0236.Description: The specified public key was deleted from iDRAC.

SRV036.Description: Unable to create the final zip archive name because the Service Tag and time stamp could not be retrieved from OS interfaces.
SRV036.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SRV036.Message: The OS Collector application is unable to create the filename for zip archive.

SUP029.Description: The catalog in the repository specified in the operation has the same firmware versions as currently present on the server. Firmware updates in the specified repository are not applicable to the server.
SUP029.Message: Firmware versions on server match catalog, applicable updates are not present in the repository.

CTL47.Description: The Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) is malfunctioning. Data loss or data corruption may occur. The DIMM must be replaced immediately.
CTL47.Resolution: Replace the DIMM immediately. The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to your hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM.

BOOT002.Description: Unable to allocate required memory to perform the operation.
BOOT002.Resolution: Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.

MEM9013.Description: BIOS logged location information of a Memory Reference Code (MRC) warning. This information can be reviewed by using a tool which displays raw IPMI SEL data such as IPMItool with the -vvv option or RACADM with the -E option.
MEM9013.Message: Memory Reference Code (MRC) warning location information is logged.

VDR18.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk has failed or was removed.
VDR18.Resolution: If a physical disk has failed, replace the physical disk. Restart the virtual disk initialization.

VLT0104.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0104.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0104.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is outside of range.

BAT1009.Description: The controller battery health has returned to normal.
BAT1009.Message: Write policy on %1 was changed to Write Back.

LC028.Description: Hardware Inventory information is not retrievable due to an internal error.
LC028.Resolution: Try one of the following: 1) Try the operation again 2) AC power cycle system 3) apply the latest firmware update packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
LC028.Message: Unable to retrieve Hardware Inventory information.

PDR1016.Description: The controller detected that the drive was removed.
PDR1016.Resolution: Verify drive installation. Remove and reseat the failed drive. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PDR1016.Message: Drive %1 is removed from disk drive bay %2.

RAC0241.Description: SD Card does not have enough free space available.
RAC0241.Resolution: Delete existing data or insert a SD card of greater size and retry.
RAC0241.Message: The specified size exceeds the maximum size of %1 MB.

LC077.Description: The new certificate will not be in-use until iDRAC has been restarted.
LC077.Message: Certificate imported successfully. Reset iDRAC to apply new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset old certificate will be active

MEM9037.Description: The NVDIMM device in the slot identified in the message has reached the end of supported life duration and is placed in write-protect mode.
MEM9037.Resolution: Replace the Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device. For information about removing and reinstalling the NVDIMM, see the system Owner's Manual on the support site.
MEM9037.Message: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device in the slot %1 has reached the end of supported life duration and is placed in write-protect mode.

IOV119.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has disabled PCIe ride-through mode. PCIe adapters that are turned on and in "ride-through" mode are immediately turned off.

BAR036.Description: A system profile import did not complete successfully and has left the system in an unusable state. Attempting to setup the environment for normal operation.
BAR036.Message: System Reset or Lifecycle Controller Actions Canceled, System Profile Failure Recovery initiated.

BAR109.Description: The OEMDRV partition is mounted for performing operating system deployment use. This situation prevents the Export and Import Server Profile operation from continuing.
BAR109.Resolution: Dismount the OEMDRV partition by selecting F10 during boot and retry the operation.

SWC0036.Description: Unable to launch hardware diagnostics because the Enterprise UEFI Diagnostics application is corrupt or iDRAC is not responding.
SWC0036.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the Enterprise UEFI Diagnostics using one of the following methods: 1) Use the Firmware Update feature in Lifecycle Controller. 2) Use the Server Update Utility. 3) Run the Update Package from the operating system. If the problem continues to persist, reset the iDRAC. For more information, contact your service provider.

LIC021.Description: All the features in the evaluation license are currently licensed in the system. The license is not imported as it would duplicate existing and active licensed features.
LIC021.Resolution: Remove the license(s) that contain the license set from the evaluation license.
LIC021.Message: Import failed: The features contained in the evaluation license are already licensed.

CTL127.Description: The firmware version of the RAID controller identified in the message cannot be updated because the signed and certified firmware image file is not authenticated.
CTL127.Resolution: Download the correct firmware image file and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CTL127.Message: Unable to update the RAID controller %1 firmware version because the signed and certified firmware image file is not authenticated.

SRV075.Description: The partition containing the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer is presented to Host operating system (OS).
SRV075.Message: The partition containing the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer is presented to Host operating system (OS).

VLT0105.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is within range.

PST0009.Description: System BIOS has started PCI bus enumeration and video initialization.

SUP0503.Description: Unable to retrieve the system ID from BIOS.
SUP0503.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do one of the following: 1) Reboot the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the BIOS firmware to the latest version and retry the operation. If the problem continues to persist contact the service provider.
SUP0503.Message: Unable to retrieve the system ID.

VLT0102.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0102.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0102.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

PST0131.Description: Memory errors occurred copying BIOS image into system memory. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception Code 83).
PST0131.Resolution: Remove input power. Reduce system memory to minimum configuration and apply input power.

RAC0228.Description: SD Card needs to be formatted to make it usable. The card must be initialized.
RAC0228.Resolution: Click Initialize to initialize the card and make it usable.
RAC0228.Message: SD Card is detected with an unrecognized format. Click Initialize to initialize the card.

PWR8683.Description: A Virtual Reseat for the peripheral sled identified in the message is initiated. A Virtual Reseat is the same as removing and inserting a peripheral sled.
PWR8683.Message: Initiated the Virtual Reseat of peripheral %1.

OSD2.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and run the command.

SEL1507.Message: Communications restored with Chassis Group Member %1.

CTL30.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL30.Message: The Check Consistency rate has changed for %1.

RAC022.Description: Unable to set values for User Password, IPMILan, IPMISerial or User Admin Privilege because the User Name is not configured.
RAC022.Resolution: Set User Name before attempting to set values of other identified attributes.
RAC022.Message: Unable to set values for User Password, IPMILan, IPMISerial or User Admin Privilege because the User Name is not configured.

CMC8535.Description: Unable to turn on the server specified in the message because of an internal CMC error.
CMC8535.Resolution: Reboot CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, reseat the server and retry the operation.
CMC8535.Message: Unable to turn on High Power Management for the server %1

RED045.Description: The necessary user access rights for performing the operation identified in the message were removed or the username was removed and the iDRAC is unable to create the next job in the sequence.
RED045.Resolution: Use a username that has the necessary access rights and retry the operation.
RED045.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was unable to create a job because the necessary user access rights are not available now.

RAC0695.Description: Unable to perform security key operations on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0695.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0695.Message: Unable to perform security key operations on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

PDR28.Description: A physical disk that was assigned as a hot spare has been unassigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically unassigned by Storage Management. Storage Management unassigns hot spares that have been used to rebuild data. Once data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, the hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. Assign a new hot spare to maintain data protection in this situation.
PDR28.Resolution: Although this alert is provided for informational purposes, you may need to assign a new hot spare to the virtual disk. Refer to product documentation and see the section Protecting Your Virtual Disk with a Hot Spare for more information.

PWR8521.Description: The chassis reset operation was completed.

SWC0700.Description: iDRAC7 is not ready or is busy and is not responding to iDRAC7 Settings IPMI requests.
SWC0700.Resolution: Turn off the system, Remove AC. Wait for 5 seconds. Connect AC. Turn it on.
SWC0700.Message: iDRAC is not ready. The configuration values cannot be accessed. Please retry after a few minutes.

RAC0670.Description: Deleting the virtual disk will remove the virtual disk from the controller's configuration. If the specified virtual disk is a boot device, the server will not boot unless another boot device is selected in BIOS.
RAC0670.Resolution: If the specified virtual disk is a boot device, the server will not boot. Press OK to continue.
RAC0670.Message: Deleting the virtual disk will remove the virtual disk from the controller's configuration.

SWC0063.Description: The share name and login credentials provided are incorrect.
SWC0063.Resolution: Enter the correct share name and login credentials, and retry the operation.
SWC0063.Message: Unable to authenticate the login credentials and share name.

PCI3017.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card was successfully updated.

LC035.Description: This method is not supported in this version of Firmware.
LC035.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware to a version that supports this method.
LC035.Message: As-Shipped Hardware Inventory Export method is not supported.

PWR8574.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is not able to communicate with the iDRAC on the server identified in the message. Therefore the server could not be hard reset. This situation may occur when iDRAC is restarting.
PWR8574.Resolution: Wait for three minutes, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the server and wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting before retying the operation.
PWR8574.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate to the iDRAC, when trying to hard reset the server %1.

UEFI0043.Description: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the processor does not support TXT.
UEFI0043.Resolution: Install a TXT-capable processor and retry the operation.
UEFI0043.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the processor does not support TXT.

LC083.Description: The Redfish Event service cannot deliver notifications to the IP Address identified in the message because of network communication issues.
LC083.Resolution: Make sure that the server is connected to the network and retry the operation. If the issue persists, delete the subscription and then subscribe by using an IP that is connected to the network.
LC083.Message: The Redfish Event service cannot deliver notifications to %1 because of network communication issues.

NIC508.Message: NIC teaming info is not currently available.

VFL1005.Description: The media is being prepared or is under maintenance. If the problem persists, reinstall the card.
VFL1005.Resolution: Please wait for the media to be ready.
VFL1005.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is not ready.

PDR76.Description: Copyback not possible as SAS or SATA mixing is not supported in the same virtual disk. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR76.Message: Copyback not possible as SAS or SATA mixing is not supported.

DIS010.Description: The Auto Discovery process has encountered a problem. One of the following messages will be displayed on the LCD display and entered in the LC log: 1) No credentials returned, 2) Blocked Because Admin Account Enabled, 3) Blocked Because IPv6 Enabled, 4) No IP on NIC, 5) No provisioning server found, 6) Provisioning server is unreachable/invalid address, 7) SSL connection failed no service at IP/port, 8) SSL connection refused, 9) SSL connection failed (Server authentication), 10) SSL connection failed (client authentication), 11) SSL connection failed other, 12) SOAP failure, 13) Failed to create account, 14) Blocked Because Active Directory Enabled, 15) No Service Tag, and 16) Unknown.
DIS010.Resolution: Refer to Lifecycle Controller Remote Services User's Guide for additional information for LCD messages.

OSD44.Description: The ISO on vFlash is not currently attached, so the DetachISOFromVFlash command could not be executed.
OSD44.Resolution: Since the ISO image is not attached, the DetachISOFromVFlash command does not have to be run.
OSD44.Message: Unable to detach ISO image on VFlash.

ASR0003.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC). The system powered cycled per the configured setting.
ASR0003.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0003.Message: The watchdog timer power cycled the system.

UEFI0213.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Basic Read DQ/DQS Training phase.
UEFI0213.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0213.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

BAT0019.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0019.Resolution: Check the battery to confirm presence.

SWC0323.Description: The number of records specified to be displayed should be lesser than number of records available.
SWC0323.Resolution: Get the number of records available, and then run the command.
SWC0323.Message: Number of records specified exceeds number of records available.

LOG506.Description: The requested operation cannot be started because the ExportChassisLog operation is already running.
LOG506.Resolution: Wait for the current ExportChassisLog operation to complete and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
LOG506.Message: Unable to start the requested operation because the ExportChassisLog operation is already running.

VF041.Description: The remote share could not be mounted.
VF041.Resolution: Try the operation again. If this problem persists, check your login credentials and network.

SYS120.Description: The OS Collector application did not complete its task within the maximum allowed time and the operation is cancelled. This may be because the server OS is not supported by the OS Collector application and the application is unable to function correctly.
SYS120.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure that the OS Collector application supports the OS installed on the server. If the OS is not supported, the OS Collector may not function correctly. 2) Reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation. To install the OS Collector using the iDRAC Web UI, get the latest OC Collector update package and then select the Update and Rollback link from the iDRAC Web UI home page and upload the install package. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SYS120.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the OS Collector is taking too much time. The operation is cancelled.

PDR1105.Message: Drive %1 is in the critical array.

HWC1013.Description: The USB cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC1013.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

CMC8540.Description: The CMC specified in the message is turned on because of a CMC insertion or due to chassis AC power on.

NIC002.Description: Unable to allocate required memory to perform the operation.
NIC002.Resolution: Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.

NIC516.Message: Static IP configuration enabled and modified successfully

BAR004.Description: Hardware Inventory data is being collected and copied into the backup file.

RAC1206.Description: The Secure Boot Certificate DeleteAll operation is successfully scheduled. For the changes to become effective, restart the host server.
RAC1206.Message: The Secure Boot Certificate DeleteAll operation is successfully scheduled.

USR0201.Description: The user identified in the message is unable to access Quick Sync because invalid credentials are entered.
USR0201.Resolution: Make sure that correct user name and password are entered, and then retry the operation.
USR0201.Message: User %1 has unsuccessfully attempted to log in to Quick Sync.

MEM0021.Message: Persistent correctable memory error limit reset for a memory device at location %1.

SUP0112.Description: The requested option is not available for remote racadm/operating system.
SUP0112.Message: The -p option is not currently supported for remote RACADM and the operating system being used.

RAC0719.Description: Not able to connect to remote file share. Virtual media devices are already in use.
RAC0719.Resolution: Stop existing Virtual Media sessions and retry the operation.
RAC0719.Message: Not able to connect to remote file share. Virtual media devices are already in use.

USR0022.Description: The username specified already exists and cannot be assigned.
USR0022.Message: The specified user already exists. Duplicate user names are not allowed.

SYS168.Description: The requested System Erase job cannot complete because there was another job or System Services task already in progress.
SYS168.Resolution: Wait for the job or System Services task in progress to complete before initiating a System Erase job.
SYS168.Message: Unable to complete the System Erase job because another operation is in progress.

SWC0055.Description: Unable to load the View Current Version page due to an internal error.
SWC0055.Resolution: Retry the operation. If problem persists, update the iDRAC firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
SWC0055.Message: Unable to load the View Current Version page.

PCI1320.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1320.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1320.Message: A bus fatal error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

PDR58.Description: A user attempted to replace a disk with another disk that is using an incompatible technology. For example, replaced one side of a mirror with a SAS disk when the other side of the mirror is using SATA technology.
PDR58.Resolution: Refer to the hardware documentation for information on replacing disks.

VFL0716.Description: An error has occurred while initializing SD Card because the SD card is not an approved vFlash SD card.
VFL0716.Resolution: Insert a vFlash SD card and try again.
VFL0716.Message: SD Card is not a vFlash SD Card; the SD card could not be initialized.

ENC30.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

ASR0100.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the system board within the timeout period. The system was reset per the configured setting. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset 01h event 3:0 - 2h).
ASR0100.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0100.Message: The BIOS watchdog timer reset the system.

VF023.Description: Partition with this label exists. Duplicate labels are not supported.

RDU8517.Description: No failover or other action can occur while a CMC firmware update is in progress.
RDU8517.Resolution: No response action is required. Wait until the firmware update is complete and retry the operation.
RDU8517.Message: CMC%1: no action allowed while firmware update is in progress

IOID110.Description: The virtual address of NIC port identified in the message is configured.
IOID110.Message: The virtual address of %1 Port %2 is configured.

SWC0257.Description: Invalid number of arguments were passed to the command.
SWC0257.Resolution: Refer the help text for the command.
SWC0257.Message: Invalid syntax. Too many options specified.

FAN911.Description: The attempt to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode (ECM) was not successful because ECM is already enabled or Gen3 fans are not present in the Chassis.
FAN911.Resolution: Check whether or not the Enhanced Cooling Mode (ECM) is already enabled. Make sure there are Gen3 fans in the Chassis and retry the operation.
FAN911.Message: The attempt to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode was not successful.

RSI0002.Description: The Remote Service database is currently not available.
RSI0002.Message: The remote service is currently not available

LIC013.Description: The license includes features not supported in this firmware release.
LIC013.Resolution: Update the firmware to the latest version.
LIC013.Message: These license features are not supported by this firmware version.

SWC8503.Description: The Profile identified in the message has been renamed.

PDR21.Description: A disk has received a SMART alert (predictive failure). The disk is likely to fail in the near future.
PDR21.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk will cause the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.

LC088.Description: Unable to export the server screen shot because there is no file in source folder.
LC088.Message: Unable to export the server screen shot because there is no file in source folder.

SWC0161.Message: PK SSH Authentication operation completed successfully.

BAR047.Description: The System Profile operation was canceled as part of a clean up operation performed during a restart of the Integrated Remote Access Controller.
BAR047.Message: System Profile operation canceled by user.

UEFI0173.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.
UEFI0173.Resolution: Quad Rank DIMM modules must be installed before Dual Rank DIMM modules on the channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0173.Message: A Quad Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Dual Rank DIMM module.

SWC0040.Description: The location of the backup Server Configuration Profile image file provided is incorrect.
SWC0040.Resolution: Enter the correct location of the backup Server Configuration Profile image file and retry the operation.
SWC0040.Message: Unable to complete the Import operation.

RAC0754.Description: Reset iDRAC to complete custom SSL certificate deletion action. A manual reset of iDRAC is needed for the action to take effect.
RAC0754.Resolution: Click the Reset iDRAC link to reset iDRAC.
RAC0754.Message: Reset iDRAC to complete the deletion action of the certificate.

RAC960.Description: The configuration XML file specified for import cannot be located in the specified repository.
RAC960.Resolution: Make sure the specified file name is correct and is located in the specified repository, and retry the operation. For more information about the syntax, run "racadm help set" to view RACADM help.
RAC960.Message: Unable to find the specified configuration XML file for import.

BIOS009.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage because of use by another application or operation.
BIOS009.Resolution: Wait for the current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator utility 2) Waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
BIOS009.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

CTL108.Description: The Check Consistency Rate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL108.Message: The Check Consistency Rate of %1 is set to %2.

SRV048.Description: The iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installed on the operating system is not up to date and does not support the SupportAssist feature.
SRV048.Resolution: Make sure the operating system (OS) is a supported OS for the SupportAssist feature and the latest iDRAC Service Module (iSM) software is installed on the OS.
SRV048.Message: The iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installed on the operating system is not up to date and does not support the SupportAssist feature.

JCP014.Description: The number of jobs specified in the SetupJobQueue request combined with the existing job count contains more jobs IDs than the maximum number of jobs supported by the system (256). Completed jobs are automatically deleted if they are older than the delete on completion timeout setting.
JCP014.Resolution: Reduce the number of jobs specified in the operation or reduce the existing job count before retrying the operation. Perform one of the following to reduce the job count: 1) Delete one or more jobs and retry the operation. 2) Wait until existing jobs have an elapsed time since completion that is greater than the delete on completion timeout setting and are automatically deleted. 3) Change the delete on completion timeout setting to a smaller value so that completed jobs are automatically deleted sooner.

RAC0756.Description: Fan information cannot be displayed. This situation may occur if the server is powered off.
RAC0756.Resolution: Power on the server. If the server is already powered on, wait for a few minutes and refresh the page. If the problem persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0756.Message: Unable to retrieve the fan information.

STOR055.Description: The BIOS on the server is not Dell Key Management capable.
STOR055.Resolution: For more information about key management capabilities, see Dell Key Manager or Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Guide available at dell.com/support/manuals.
STOR055.Message: BIOS does not support Dell Key Manager capabilities.

RAC088.Description: The Clear Transfer Session operation cannot be completed because the file entered is not available for deletion.
RAC088.Resolution: Make sure that FileType and FileOperation parameters are valid, and they retry the operation.
RAC088.Message: Unable to complete the Clear Transfer Session operation because the file entered is not available for deletion.

UEFI0036.Description: The iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) interface cannot be initialized. The BIOS will use the Keyboard Controller Style (KCS) interface.
UEFI0036.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0036.Message: Unable to initialize the iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) interface.

SUP0115.Description: The rac cannot be reset, while the firmware update is in progress.
SUP0115.Resolution: Wait for the firmware update to finish.
SUP0115.Message: A firmware update is currently in progress. Unable to reset the RAC at this time.

SEC0043.Description: TXT POST cannot be completed because system configuration may have changed.
SEC0043.Resolution: Check system hardware inventory for TPM presence, clear and reconfigure TPM and TXT in BIOS setup menu.
SEC0043.Message: BIOS Authenticated Code Module detected an Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) problem during POST.

OSD064.Description: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is abruptly stopped either by the user or the installation infrastructure.
OSD064.Message: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is abruptly stopped either by the user or the installation infrastructure.

SWU8517.Description: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware. The firmware Image file is not accessible.
SWU8517.Resolution: Make sure the iDRAC firmware Image file is available in the given path and retry the operation.
SWU8517.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware on the server in slot %1. The Image file is not accessible. ErrorCode=0x%2.

DH003.Resolution: Try again. If the error persists, use RACADM command racreset to clear the issue.
DH003.Message: Service tag could not be read.

PWR8671.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature cannot be enabled because the requested power exceeds the Chassis subsystem power limit for IO Modules, Blowers and Servers.
PWR8671.Resolution: Make sure the system operates within the subsystem Connector Limit for the components specified. To review power budget information select Chassis Overview -> Power -> Budget Status. Turn off unused components within the subsystem to make power available to set Enhanced Cooling Mode.
PWR8671.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to set the Enhanced Cooling Mode because the requested power %1 AC Watts exceeds the subsystem power limit %2 AC Watts for IO Modules, Blowers and Servers.

PDR1119.Message: Drive %1 is no longer the hot-spare drive.

CMC8543.Description: The CMC specified in the message has reset because of thermal issues.
CMC8543.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Review the Hardware Log and check if there are fans that are not functioning properly. 2) Replace the fans that are not functioning properly. 3) If all the fans are functioning, check the chassis temperature in the CMC Web Interface or by using RACADM. When the fans are functioning properly and the chassis temperature is too high, the ambient air temperature is too high or the air inlets are not receiving sufficient air.
CMC8543.Message: The CMC %1 has reset because the thermal threshold was exceeded.

HWC5008.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
HWC5008.Message: Console is not available for the %1.

VDR25.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PDR98.Description: An error occurred while performing an action on the disk.
PDR98.Resolution: Check the disk is present or replace the disk.

PWR8501.Description: Power allocation succeeded for Virtual infrastructure.
PWR8501.Message: Successfully set Virtual Infrastructure Device power to %1 WDC.

AMP0318.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0318.Message: Chassis power level current is less than the lower warning threshold.

UEFI0151.Description: A PERC storage adapter is installed in a slot identified by this message but the internal storage slot is empty This configuration is not supported.
UEFI0151.Resolution: Install a compatible storage adapter in the internal storage slot. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0151.Message: A PERC storage adapter is installed in %1 but the internal storage slot is empty. This configuration is not supported.

CMC8579.Description: The security certificate cannot be uploaded because of an Unexpected Event issue in the Remote Access Controller.
CMC8579.Resolution: Upload the certificate again and retry operation.
CMC8579.Message: Unable to upload the security certificate because of an Unexpected Event issue in the Remote Access Controller (RAC).

DH002.Resolution: Try again. If the error persists, use RACADM command racreset to clear the issue.

SEL1400.Message: The platform generated a page alert.

GMGR0038.Description: The iDRAC local group could not identify a Secondary Controller either because of firmware incompatibility between master and members, or because the local group does not have a second member to select a master.
GMGR0038.Resolution: To enable redundancy, make sure that there is at least one more member that has the supported firmware version for the Controller capability.
GMGR0038.Message: The iDRAC local group could not identify a Secondary Controller either because of firmware incompatibility between master and members, or because the local group does not have a second member to select a master.

RED097.Description: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is for a component that is not in the target system inventory.
RED097.Resolution: Identify and download the firmware version that corresponds to the component being updated in the target system inventory, and retry the operation. For a list of supported firmware versions, refer to the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
RED097.Message: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is for a component that is not in the target system inventory.

STOR6.Description: A comparison of storage inventory collected before and after the host re-boot/re-set. reports differences. There could have been some storage components added or removed when the host was powered down.
STOR6.Message: CEM Storage Management detected inventory change(s) after host re-boot.

BAR081.Description: Importing the Lifecycle Controller firmware image data is from the system profile backup file.

VDR55.Description: The controller cannot communicate with attached devices. A disk may be removed or contain errors. Cables may also be loose or defective.
VDR55.Resolution: Verify the health of attached devices. Review the Alert Log for significant events. Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables.

PWR2268.Description: The power supply unit (PSU) identified in the message is disabled because of a mismatch in the input voltage and therefore the PSU is not supported on the server.
PWR2268.Resolution: Install a power supply unit (PSU) that has similar input voltage. For information about supported PSUs, see the product documentation available on the support site.
PWR2268.Message: The power supply unit (PSU) %1 is disabled because of a mismatch in the input voltage and therefore the PSU is not supported on the server.

GMGR0018.Description: The group job identified in the message is successfully rescheduled.
GMGR0018.Message: The group job %1 of type %2 is rescheduled.

NIC005.Description: The number of AttributeName and AttributeValue parameters do not match.
NIC005.Resolution: Pass the same number of parameters for AttributeName and AttributeValue. Refer to documentation for method input parameter details.
NIC005.Message: Mismatch in AttributeName and AttributeValue count

UEFI0172.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.
UEFI0172.Resolution: Quad Rank DIMM modules must be installed before Single Rank DIMM modules on the channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0172.Message: A Quad Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Single Rank DIMM module.

MEM0016.Message: Memory device at location(s) %1 is operating correctly.

FC016.Description: A set attribute operation was not successful because the attribute is disabled.
FC016.Message: Unable to change the attribute value of the disabled attribute %1.

SWC0239.Description: The requested object is auto-assigned if IPv6 AutoConfig is enabled, and hence cannot be configured.
SWC0239.Resolution: Disable IPv6 AutoConfig and re-try the command.
SWC0239.Message: The requested object is not allowed to be configured if IPv6 AutoConfig is enabled.

SYS088.Description: Applying the changes defined in the configuration XML file will take approximately the estimated time identified in the message.
SYS088.Message: Estimated time for applying configuration changes is %1 seconds.

STOR059.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because there are no virtual disks (VD) available on the specified controller.
STOR059.Resolution: Create a virtual disk and retry the operation.
STOR059.Message: The requested operation is not currently valid because there are no virtual disks on the controller.

SWC0067.Description: The location of the operating system configuration file specified in the operation is not valid.
SWC0067.Resolution: Make sure that the specified source file path is correct and retry the operation.
SWC0067.Message: Unable to import operating system configuration file.

LC022.Description: The Lifecycle Controller Log was successfully exported to the destination specified.
LC022.Message: Lifecycle Controller Log Export was successful.

RAC0297.Description: The Domain Controller Address be specified for Active Directory configuration.
RAC0297.Resolution: Enter a valid Domain Controller Address.
