RAC0297.Message: Specify a Domain Controller Address must be configured.

PST0136.Description: System BIOS detected an failure with the programmable interval timer during POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.(BIOS POST Exception code 88).
PST0136.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PDR99.Description: This message is generated after the secure erase operation completion on a Self-Encryption Disk.
PDR99.Message: The secure erase operation on Self Encryption Disk %1 has completed.

UEFI0259.Description: The BIOS operation cannot be completed because the R920 baseboard does not support the R930 BIOS firmware.
UEFI0259.Resolution: Update the BIOS firmware to a supported R920 BIOS version. For a list of supported firmware versions, see the Owners Manual available at the support site.
UEFI0259.Message: Unable to complete the BIOS operation because the R920 baseboard does not support the R930 BIOS firmware.

RAC1180.Description: A USB Device inserted in the front panel USB Management port and is in use by the server operating system. The device needs to not be in use in order to change the port mode settings.
RAC1180.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the USB device and retry the operation.
RAC1180.Message: A USB device is inserted in the front panel USB Management port and is in use by the server operating system.

FAN1001.Description: The enclosure detected that a fan was inserted.

RAC1207.Description: The Secure Boot Certificate RestoreAll operation is successfully scheduled. For the changes to become effective, restart the host server.
RAC1207.Message: The Secure Boot Certificate RestoreAll operation is successfully scheduled.

DH007.Resolution: Check that the private key parameter is correct. The passphrase can be validated against the private key, passphrase, and certificate can be validated using OpenSSL tools.
DH007.Message: The password unlocked the private key but it was the wrong private key.

SWC9003.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate ResetAll operation cannot be completed either because of an internal error or due to insufficient space in certificate store.
SWC9003.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, free some space in the certificate store by deleting few certificates, restart iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SWC9003.Message: Unable to complete the SecureBoot Certificate ResetAll operation because of an internal error or due to insufficient space in certificate store.

IOV009.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) runs this function only when the chassis is turned off.
IOV009.Resolution: Turn off the chassis and retry the operation.
IOV009.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to reset to factory default or pre-factory default settings.

SYS132.Description: An issue occurred while loading the OS Collector IPMI library. This may be because the OS collector binary images are not valid and need to be re-installed.
SYS132.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS132.Message: OS Collector: Unable to communicate with OS Collector IPMI library.

CTL106.Description: The Background Initialization Rate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL106.Message: The Background Initialization Rate of %1 is set to %2.

SWC0059.Description: The vFlash partitions are being used by other applications such as Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services or RACADM.
SWC0059.Resolution: Wait until the current operations are complete and retry the operation. For information, see the FAQs section of the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services or RACADM User Guide.

SWC0029.Description: Status of backup Server Profile operation could not be retrieved because an unrecoverable error occurred while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0029.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0029.Message: Unable to retrieve status of backup Server Profile operation.

RAC0902.Description: The syntax of the specified command is invalid. In this case, the usage of the -f option is invalid.
RAC0902.Resolution: See the help text/documentation for the valid syntax of the subcommand.
RAC0902.Message: The -f option requires -d to also be specified.

SYS439.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the Secure Boot policy is set to Standard.
SYS439.Resolution: Reset the Secure Boot policy to Custom by performing the PATCH operation for the SecureBootPolicy attribute on the Redfish Bios URL.
SYS439.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the Secure Boot policy is set to Standard.

CTL20.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL20.Message: Copyback and Load Balance has changed for %1.

SWC5007.Description: The <name> cannot be accessed because of a degraded functionality.
SWC5007.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation available on the support site to choose a convenient contact method.
SWC5007.Message: Unable to access %1 because of a degraded functionality.

RAC950.Description: The work note cannot be added to the Lifecycle Log if iDRAC is archiving the older records in the Lifecycle Log.
RAC950.Resolution: Wait for several minutes while iDRAC archives the older records, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC950.Message: Unable to add the work note to the Lifecycle Log.

HWC8506.Description: During a Chassis Management Controller (CMC) firmware update, the control panel firmware synchronization failed. The control panel may be inoperable.
HWC8506.Resolution: Remove and reapply chassis input power. If problem persists, contact your service provider.
HWC8506.Message: Unable to synchronize control panel firmware due to internal error.

RAC0260.Description: The specified IPv6 address prefix length is invalid.
RAC0260.Resolution: Enter a valid IPv6 prefix length. Expected range: 0-128.
RAC0260.Message: Invalid IPv6 prefix length. Expected range: 0-128.

PWR8685.Description: The firmware identified in the message supports the storage sled.
PWR8685.Message: The %1 firmware in the server slot %2 supports the storage sled.

STOR0502.Description: No RAID controller is installed on the system.
STOR0502.Resolution: Install the RAID controller and do the following: 1) Reboot the system.2) Press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller.3) Retry RAID configuration.
STOR0502.Message: Unable to launch RAID Configuration wizard.

GMGR0023.Description: The group job identified in the message is completed but with errors. The job details can be viewed in the Group Manager job view.
GMGR0023.Resolution: Review the error details in Group Manager job view and rerun the operation if required.
GMGR0023.Message: The group job %1 of type %2 is completed but with errors.

CMC8539.Description: CMC cannot log new events to Hardware Log if Hardware Log is full. Therefore, new events are not written to the log unless older events are cleared. This issue also occurs if event logging is disabled.
CMC8539.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Save the Hardware Log if required. 2) Clear the Hardware Log.
CMC8539.Message: The CMC %1 is unable to log %2 event to the Hardware Log.

PDR10.Description: This message is generated after a rebuild starts on a physical disk.

RAC919.Description: Racadm could not export the inlet temperature history file to the specified remote share. This is because the specified share may be write- protected.
RAC919.Resolution: To export the file, change the permissions on the remote share. Else, create another share with write permissions.
RAC919.Message: Copy to remote share unsuccessful. Remote share might be write protected.

DKM1006.Resolution: Review server error logs for additional information.

RAC0516.Description: Converting physical disk drives to RAID-compatible will overwrite any OS-created RAID arrays.
RAC0516.Resolution: Make sure that there are no OS-configured RAID arrays, and then click OK.
RAC0516.Message: Converting physical disk drives to RAID-compatible will overwrite any OS-created RAID arrays.

PDR1106.Message: Drive %1 is in the failed array.

RDU0030.Description: The storage voltage of the device identified in the message is redundant.
RDU0030.Message: The storage voltage of %1 is redundant.

CTL36.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL36.Message: The Patrol Read mode has changed for %1.

VF021.Description: The size specified is greater than the maximum allowed for a partition.
VF021.Resolution: Try a partition size that is smaller than 4GB and the available space on the card.

SUP0540.Description: The update packages cannot be installed because of insufficient space in the iDRAC even after deleting firmware installation files stored in the Rollback feature.
SUP0540.Resolution: Delete Lifecycle Controller related data by using the Repurpose or Retire System features, and then retry the operation.
SUP0540.Message: Unable to install update packages because of insufficient space in the iDRAC.

BAR111.Description: The Import or Export job did not complete successfully. The Import or Export operation timed-out while validating or transferring Server Profile data. Possible causes are loss of network connectivity, vFlash SD card access issues, or problems encountered with system power off and on.
BAR111.Resolution: If the managed system does not turn off during Import, turn off the system and retry the operation. If the managed system turned off, restart the Remote Access Controller and retry the operation. If the export was to a network share verify the connection and try the operation again. If the export destination was the vFlash media, insert a new SD card and try the operation again.

PCI3008.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next service window.
PCI3008.Message: A non-fatal PCIe error detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

LOG507.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in the CMC.
LOG507.Resolution: Reset the CMC and retry the operation.
LOG507.Message: Unable to allocated required CMC resources.

VFL0710.Message: vFlash is not enabled; the SD card could not be initialized.

BOOT009.Description: No Boot Sources could be found for the desired Boot Configuration.
BOOT009.Resolution: Verify that Boot Sources for the indicated Boot Configuration are displaying when enumerating DCIM_BootSourceSetting. Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
BOOT009.Message: Boot Sources cannot be found for this Boot Configuration

MEM9016.Description: The memory device identified in the message may not be operational. This an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM9016.Resolution: Re-install the memory component identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM9016.Message: Correctable memory error rate exceeded for Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM)%1.

SWC1931.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout configuration is disabled. The iDRAC Quick Sync feature will remain available after pressing the activate button.
SWC1931.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout configuration is disabled.

IOV122.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter (VA) identified in the message has been assigned to the extension of the server slot identified in the message.
IOV122.Message: %1 %2 is mapped/assigned to extension of server slot %3.

IOV123.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter(VA) identified in the message has been unassigned/unmapped from the extension of the server slot identified in the message.
IOV123.Message: %1 %2 is unassigned/unmapped from extended server slot %3.

VF032.Description: The specified partition type is not a valid type.
VF032.Resolution: Try a partition type that is supported.

UEFI0084.Description: One or more PCI Parity errors (PERR) have occurred.
UEFI0084.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCI device that caused the PERR. Update the identified device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0084.Message: One or more PCI Parity errors (PERR) have occurred.

SRV060.Description: The SupportAssist Registration operation did not complete successfully.
SRV060.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Make sure the registration information is valid. 2) Make sure that the communication between iDRAC and iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is working. If the issue persists, restart the iSM service on the host OS.
SRV060.Message: The SupportAssist Registration operation did not complete successfully.

RAC0768.Description: iDRAC firmware is recently updated and iDRAC is still in the process of initializing. It is recommended to wait a few minutes before logging in so that the iDRAC initialization process can fully complete.
RAC0768.Resolution: Wait a few minutes to log in to iDRAC. Some iDRAC features may not be available for use if log in is continued at this time.
RAC0768.Message: iDRAC is currently initializing. Try logging in to iDRAC after few minutes because iDRAC is initializing after a recent firmware update process.

BAR076.Description: The collection and export of Lifecycle Controller Configuration Database failed.
BAR076.Resolution: Enter System Services in USC, and select Exit and Reboot to reset and update the database. If the error continues repair the Lifecycle Controller, apply the Dell Update Packages for USC, diagnostics, device firmware and driver pack and retry the operation.
BAR076.Message: Unable to collect the Configuration database.

STOR10.Description: The RAID controller was detected, however it is unable to turn on. Access to shared storage will not be available.
STOR10.Message: Access to shared storage will not be available, because the RAID controller is unable to turn on.

HWC4010.Message: Hardware successfully updated for mezzanine card %1.

RAC0247.Description: This message is displayed when trying to format or download to an attached vFlash partition.
RAC0247.Resolution: Detach this partition and try again.

FAN0019.Description: An incompatibility between operating mode and fan type was corrected for the fan identified in the message.
FAN0019.Message: An incompatibility between operating mode and fan type was corrected for fan %1.

UEFI0210.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Receive Buffer Vref Training phase.
UEFI0210.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0210.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SRV112.Description: The Auto Collection schedule is not set for SupportAssist.
SRV112.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Make sure that the iDRAC is registered for SupportAssist. 2) Make sure that the Lifecyclecontroller is enabled on iDRAC. 3) Make sure that the SupportAssist feature is enabled on iDRAC, and Auto Collection schedule is set.
SRV112.Message: The Auto Collection schedule is not set for SupportAssist.

PST0090.Description: A problem was detected related to the previous server boot. The next logged message contains more specific details for the detected issue.
PST0090.Resolution: Review the next logged message for the recommended response action to resolve the problem.
PST0090.Message: A problem was detected related to the previous server boot.

SYS164.Description: The System Erase operation attempted to access Lifecycle Controller internal storage that is already being accessed by another function. Exclusive access to the internal storage is required for the System Erase operation. The System Erase operation attempts Lifecycle Controller internal storage access for 10 minutes. After the timeout the current job completes with an unsuccessful status.
SYS164.Resolution: Check the server and make sure that it is not in BIOS POST startup processing or stopped in the POST phase of startup. The server can also be stopped during POST because the <F2> is pressed or Option ROM setup utilities are being used. After the BIOS startup has completed, retry the operation.
SYS164.Message: Access to Lifecycle Controller internal storage was not acquired.

PSU0045.Message: Power supply %1 status information successfully obtained.

PST0142.Description: BIOS Memory testing failed. Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce system configuration to minimum memory configuration. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.
PST0142.Resolution: Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce system configuration to minimum memory configuration.

PWR2262.Description: The Intel Management Engine is unable to utilize the PECI over DMI facility.
PWR2262.Resolution: Look for the PWR2264 "normal system operation" message in the Lifecycle Log after the PWR2262 entry. It may take 30 seconds for the message to be logged. If the PWR2264 message does not appear, do the following: Disconnect power from the server and reconnect power. Turn on the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR2262.Message: The Intel Management Engine has reported an internal system error.

SWC0316.Description: The value for index must be greater than zero.
SWC0316.Resolution: Enter a positive value for index.
SWC0316.Message: The index must be greater than 0.

SEC0006.Description: The fan area is open. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0006.Resolution: Close the fan area. Check system logs.

SYS412.Description: The file cannot be uploaded because of unknown internal issues.
SYS412.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC, and then retry the operation. Reset the iDRAC by using the "Manager Reset Actions" Redfish API.
SYS412.Message: Unable to upload the file because of unknown internal issues.

RAC1035.Description: The command is unable to clear the pending state for attributes of the specified component because there are no pending values.
RAC1035.Resolution: Make sure that there is at least one attribute on the specified device has a pending value, and retry the operation.
RAC1035.Message: There are no pending values to be cleared.

USR8508.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.
USR8508.Resolution: Maximum sessions already in use, so close any of existing session and retry the operation.
USR8508.Message: %1 login was not successful (username=%2, ip=%3, reason=%4)

RAC0217.Description: Client did not receive a response for the login request.
RAC0217.Resolution: Try pinging the iDRAC and then try again.

SYS198.Description: An internal iDRAC memory component is unresponsive.
SYS198.Resolution: The iDRAC requires an AC power cycle. Do the following: 1) Determine a time that the AC power can be removed and then reapplied to the server. 2) Save data and perform an AC power cycle.
SYS198.Message: Unable to communicate with internal iDRAC memory.

SWC0300.Description: There is no coredump available to display.
SWC0300.Message: There is no coredump currently available.

SWC0058.Resolution: Reboot the system and retry the operation.

PWR8558.Description: A configuration change has occurred such that the current power cap is now supported.
PWR8558.Message: The System Input Power Cap is being enforced with the current Power Supply configuration.

PSU8507.Description: The PSU identified in the message has been disengaged or removed. Insufficient power is available.
PSU8507.Resolution: Insert a PSU in the slot identified in the message.
PSU8507.Message: Insufficient power available because PSU in the slot %1 is not present.

SWC8607.Description: The Quick Deploy of Profile process has started for the server identified in the message.
SWC8607.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Starting to apply profile %1 to server %2.

LC067.Description: The Export Certification operation successfully exported the SSL Certificate.

RAC972.Description: Configuration XML import and export operations require the specified username to have administrator role privileges.
RAC972.Resolution: Run the same command with a username that has an administrator role privileges.
RAC972.Message: Insufficient privileges to run the configuration XML file import or export operations.

OSE1010.Description: The system has successfully booted to ROM.

VDR23.Description: This message is generated after initialization completes on a virtual disk.

BAT1006.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1006.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle will start in %2 days.

UEFI0159.Description: Unsupported 4Gb technology DIMM module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0159.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0159.Message: Unsupported Unregistered Dual In-line Memory Module (UDIMM) memory is installed on memory slot: %1.

VLT0217.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is within range.

BAR003.Description: The Backup partition is being created for storing the backup file.

BAR052.Description: The required device firmware was not found, and the update cannot continue. The device firmware is either not present on the firmware storage partition or does not match the version stored in the configuration information database. No response action is required, however obtaining and installing the update package for the device indicated will update the firmware storage partition. A backup of the server profile is recommended after updating.
BAR052.Message: Firmware update cannot be performed for Device: %1

SRV025.Description: The iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer cannot be presented to the host operating system because another Lifecycle Controller operation is currently in progress.
SRV025.Resolution: Make sure all other Lifecycle Controller operations are finished and retry the operation. Using the iDRAC Web UI, select Server > Job Queue, check the job queue for unfinished jobs and wait for the jobs to finish before retrying the operation. Also, check whether there are update packages being executed in the server OS and wait for these operations to finish before retrying the operation. For remote web services API access, make sure that the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status, and then retry the operation.
SRV025.Message: Unable to present the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer to the host operating system because another Lifecycle Controller operation is currently in progress.

PDR1021.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is no longer in the critical array.

SYS252.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the file is not available at the remote host location.
SYS252.Resolution: Make sure that the file is available at the remote host location and retry the operation.
SYS252.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the file is not available at the remote host location.

LOG502.Description: The command cannot be run because the method parameter identified in the message is missing.
LOG502.Resolution: Enter all the parameters required in the command, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the Chassis Record Log Profile.
LOG502.Message: Unable to run the command because the method parameter %1 is missing.

OSE1013.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. See system video for additional information.

IOV120.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has enabled PCIe ride-through mode. PCIe adapters will remain turned on for the number of seconds specified by the ride-through timeout value after the server they are assigned to is turned off.

PST0194.Description: System BIOS could not configure the Remote Access controller This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code C2).
PST0194.Resolution: Cycle input power and power on the system. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

CPU0702.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.
CPU0702.Resolution: Check system and operating system logs for exceptions. If no exceptions found, remove input power, reinstall the processor, then apply input power.

UEFI0116.Description: One or more boot drivers have reported issue(s) via the UEFI Driver Health Protocol.
UEFI0116.Resolution: Check the Driver Health Menu in Boot Manager for details.
UEFI0116.Message: One or more boot drivers have reported issue(s).

TMP0102.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0102.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0102.Message: The system board %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

CTL65.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL65.Message: Attempted to import Unsupported Virtual Disk type RAID%1 on %2.

PSU8521.Description: The power supply unit (PSU) identified in the message was turned off because the temperature exceeded the high temperature threshold in the unit.
PSU8521.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the PSU or remove AC power and reapply power to the PSU to get it functional again.
PSU8521.Message: PSU %1 exceeded upper temperature threshold and has been turned off.

AMP0305.Message: The system board %1 current is within range.

RAC0744.Description: Unable to perform storage configuration operations because neither Storage controllers nor PCIe Extenders detected on the system.
RAC0744.Message: Unable to perform storage configuration operations because neither Storage controllers nor PCIe Extenders detected on the system.

RAC0684.Description: Unable to perform split mode configuration on the selected enclosures, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0684.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0684.Message: Unable to perform split mode configuration on the selected enclosures, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

PR24.Description: The specified job was cancelled. This could be due to user action or system error. This message is no longer in use in Lifecycle Controller 2.0 as the job control functionality handles this operation.

RAC0261.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv6 gateway address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0261.Resolution: Enter a valid IPv6 gateway address.

OSD063.Description: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is successfully completed.
OSD063.Message: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is successfully completed.

DIS114.Description: The AutoConfig feature timed out while waiting for Remote Services to be ready.
DIS114.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC. To reset iDRAC by using RACADM command, run the racadm racreset command at the command line interface (CLI). For more information about resetting iDRAC, see iDRAC Users Guide available at the support site.
DIS114.Message: The AutoConfig feature timed out while waiting for Remote Services to be ready.

UEFI0299.Description: The BIOS Recovery process is completed.
UEFI0299.Message: The BIOS Recovery process is completed.

SEL1508.Description: The indicated member may be a member of another chassis group or may be incompatible with membership.
SEL1508.Resolution: 1)Check that the Name or IP address, User Name, and Password of the member are correct. 2)Check that the member is not a leader or member of another group. 3)Check that the member can be reached by the leader.
SEL1508.Message: Member %1 could not join the Chassis Group.

RAC029.Description: The operation cannot be completed because necessary dependency values are not found in the input.
RAC029.Resolution: Refer to the Dell Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide and Profile Documents available at the support site, and then retry the operation.
RAC029.Message: Unable to complete the operation because necessary dependency values are not found in the input.

PDR115.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message is in read-only mode.
PDR115.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.

BAR098.Description: The Service Tag installed on the system is invalid. The Backup and Restore feature will not operate without a valid Service Tag.

SWC0701.Description: Power capping is enabled and sets user-defined power capping limits for the system.

RAC1113.Description: The configuration XML preview operation cannot be executed because the -b, -s, and -w options must not be used with the --preview option.
RAC1113.Resolution: Remove the -b, -w, and -s options when using the --preview option and retry the operation.
RAC1113.Message: Unable to perform the preview operation because the options -b, -c, -w, and -s must not be used with the --preview option.

STOR022.Description: The operation cannot be completed because controller is not security capable.
STOR022.Message: The controller is not security capable.

STOR009.Description: Physical disk did not identify valid physical disk for the operation.
STOR009.Resolution: Provide compatible physical disk with the operation.
STOR009.Message: Physical disk FQDD did not identify a valid physical disk for the operation.

UEFI0194.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Fine Command Training phase.
UEFI0194.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0194.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

UEFI0263.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the network cable is not connected.
UEFI0263.Resolution: Check the network cable connection of the system and retry the operation.
UEFI0263.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the network cable is not connected.

UEFI0277.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection number identified in the message because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv6 server is invalid.
UEFI0277.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reconfigure the DHCPv6 server boot file URL option, and note that server name must be specified. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable Target Info via DHCP and configure the parameters manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0277.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv6 server is invalid.

SRV061.Description: The SupportAssist Chassis controller logs collection operation is started.
SRV061.Message: The SupportAssist Chassis controller logs collection operation is started.

VDR1.Description: A storage component such as a physical disk or an enclosure has failed. The failed component may have been identified by the controller while performing a task such as a rescan or a check consistency.
VDR1.Resolution: Replace the failed component. You can identify which component has failed by locating the component that has a red "X" for its status. Perform a rescan after replacing the failed component.

USR0013.Description: The user does not have sufficient privileges to execute the command.
USR0013.Message: Insufficient user privileges to perform operation.

AMP0310.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0310.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0310.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is outside of range.

RAC0609.Description: The import or export system configuration operation with the job ID indicated in the message was successfully added to the Job Queue.
RAC0609.Resolution: No response action is required. The status of jobs can be viewed on the Job Queue page.
RAC0609.Message: The job %1 has been successfully added to the job queue.

PCI1354.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next scheduled service time.
PCI1354.Message: A bus correctable error was detected on a component at slot %1.

LC007.Description: One of the parameters specified in the method is invalid.
LC007.Resolution: Verify that the parameters specified are correct. For a list of parameters for this method refer to the Lifecycle Controller User Guide.

FC013.Description: An incorrect AttributeName parameter name was provided.
FC013.Resolution: Enter the correct AttributeName available for the component in the system. Identify the correct AttributeName from the attribute enumeration response for the component or refer to the FC HBA Profile specification.

SWC0151.Message: RAC configuration saved to file successfully

OSD24.Description: Unable to continue with DetachDrivers - UnPackAndAttach is in progress.
OSD24.Resolution: Wait until UnpackAndAttach finishes and then run DetachDrivers. This can take more than 5 minutes.
OSD24.Message: Unable to continue with DetachDrivers - UnPackAndAttach is in progress.

PCI3009.Message: PCIe is operating normally on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

RAC0742.Description: A Secure Erase operation on a PCIe SSD overwrites all blocks in an encrypted way and all the data on the PCIe SSD device will be permanently lost. The changes will happen after reboot of the system or loss of power to the drive.
RAC0742.Message: The Secure Erase command will be executed on the selected PCIe SSD disk drives(s) only after the reboot of the system or loss of power to the disk drives(s).

VDR41.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PWR8552.Description: There is insufficient power for the component identified in the message to turn on.
PWR8552.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis. Contact your service provider for information on the power required for the component identified in the message.
PWR8552.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on %1-%2 because of insufficient power.

PR13.Description: The Part Replacement feature detected a firmware difference and cannot apply the configuration changes. After the device firmware is updated, configuration changes can be applied.
PR13.Message: Firmware mismatch detected. Configuration changes not applied.

UEFI0318.Description: The PWD_EN jumper is not installed. The BIOS Initial Boot Block code has detected an unauthenticated Pre-EFI (PEI) module.
UEFI0318.Resolution: No response action is required, if the issue is observed in the development phase. However, in production environment, recover the BIOS by doing the following: 1) Turn off the server and disconnect the input power. 2) Install the PWD_EN jumper on the motherboard. 3) Reconnect to the power source and restart the server.
UEFI0318.Message: The PWD_EN jumper is not installed. The BIOS Initial Boot Block code has detected an unauthenticated Pre-EFI (PEI) module.

RED096.Description: The maximum iDRAC storage space allocated for storing firmware image files is reached. The firmware image of the earlier version that was stored for a rollback operation is now deleted.
RED096.Message: The maximum iDRAC storage space allocated for storing firmware image files is reached. The firmware image of the earlier version that was stored for a rollback operation is now deleted.

VF040.Description: The downloaded image did not successfully complete the hash verification.
VF040.Resolution: Try the download again. If this issue persists, check the network connectivity.
VF040.Message: Image hash verification was not successful.

PWR2400.Description: The power management firmware cannot reduce power consumption to meet configuration or user defined settings.
PWR2400.Resolution: 1) Review system power policy.2) Check system event logs for thermal or power related exceptions.
PWR2400.Message: Power management firmware unable to maintain power limit.

RAC0629.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested job type is not supported.
RAC0629.Resolution: Enter a correct job type, and then retry the operation.
RAC0629.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid job type is entered.

SYS227.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of the reason described by the code identified in the message. For every unsuccessful file transfer, the proxy server returns an error code, where each code has a description about the reason for failure.
SYS227.Resolution: View the proxy server documentation to resolve the issue. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SYS227.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of the reason described by the code %2 sent by the proxy server.

FAN0002.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.
FAN0002.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan at the next scheduled service window. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0002.Message: Fan %1 RPM is greater than the upper warning threshold.

SYS406.Description: The configuration operation cannot be started because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.
SYS406.Resolution: Make sure that the Lockdown.1.SystemLockdown attribute is set to Disabled by running the HTTP PATCH method on "Managers OemAttributes" Redfish API, and then retry the operation.
SYS406.Message: Unable to start the configuration operation because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.

SRV022.Description: The SupportAssist OS and Application data collection operation is successfully completed.
SRV022.Message: The SupportAssist OS and Application data collection operation is successfully completed.

UEFI0199.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Write Level Fine Training phase.
UEFI0199.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0199.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

LIC905.Description: The LicenseName value is greater than the allowed max length of 64.
LIC905.Resolution: Correct the length of the LicenseName value and retry the operation.
LIC905.Message: The LicenseName value cannot exceed 64 characters.

RED024.Description: Lifecycle Controller is in use or currently processing another job. The specified job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.
RED024.Resolution: Wait for current Lifecycle Controller task to complete.
RED024.Message: The specified job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.

SYS225.Description: The job identified in the message cannot be successfully completed because of the issues listed in the Lifecycle Controller log files.
SYS225.Resolution: Verify the reason for the unsuccessful completion of the job by inspecting the Lifecycle Log entries related to the job. Correct the underlying cause of the unsuccessful completion and retry the operation.
SYS225.Message: Unable to complete the job %1 successfully because of the issues listed in the Lifecycle Controller log files.

SRV066.Description: The SupportAssist Enclosure Controller logs collection operation is cancelled.
SRV066.Message: The SupportAssist Enclosure Controller logs collection operation is cancelled.

IOV113.Description: Chassis Infrastructure firmware re-installation is successful.
IOV113.Message: Chassis Infrastructure firmware re-installation is successful.

LC078.Description: The Message Registry was successfully exported to the specified destination file folder.
LC078.Message: The Export Message Registry operation was successfully completed.

PWR8602.Description: The power buttons for all multinode sleds in the chassis are enabled. The operation to enable the power button is only applicable to the multinode sleds available, and does not affect other servers in the chassis.
PWR8602.Resolution: To disable the chassis power button use the CMC RACADM command line interface (CLI) or CMC Web interface. At the CLI, enter "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisSledPowerButtonEnable 0". Using the Web interface, click Server Overview > Power > Control. Select the "Disable power button for all multinode sleds in the chassis" check box.
PWR8602.Message: The multinode sled power button is enabled.

SWC9006.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate View operation cannot be completed because SecureBoot policies are not found in the server.
SWC9006.Resolution: Configure Secureboot policies and retry the operation.
SWC9006.Message: Unable to complete the SecureBoot Certificate View operation because SecureBoot policies are not found in the server.

BAR097.Description: The current Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator software installed on the system does not have Backup and Restore feature support.
BAR097.Resolution: Obtain the Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator update package with Backup and Restore support, update the software and try the operation again.
BAR097.Message: Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator incompatibility detected.

SRV083.Description: The operation cannot be started because iDRAC Service Module (iSM) running on the server operating system (OS) is not compatible with iDRAC firmware version installed on the server.
SRV083.Resolution: Install the compatible version of iDRAC Service Module (iSM) on the server operating system (OS) and then retry the operation. Refer to the iSM Installation Guide for details on the compatible versions.
SRV083.Message: Unable to start the operation because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service running on the server operating system (OS) is not compatible with iDRAC firmware version installed on the server.

ISM0009.Description: iDRAC Service Module detected that OpenManage Server Administrator is not running on the OS of this server. Therefore, one or more features of iDRAC Service Module that were earlier disabled are now enabled on this server.
ISM0009.Message: The features of iDRAC Service Module that were disabled will be enabled on this server, because OpenManage Server Administrator is not running on the operating system (OS) of this server.

STOR309.Description: The command cannot be run because multiple targets must not be entered as input in the Blink/Unblink Target method.
STOR309.Resolution: Enter only one target FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor), and then retry the operation.
STOR309.Message: Unable to run the command because multiple targets must not be entered as input in the Blink/Unblink Target method.

PWR2211.Message: The system is in legacy ON state.

OSD41.Description: vFlash does not contain the ISO Image because either the image was deleted, or it was never copied.
OSD41.Resolution: Download the ISO Image to the vFlash again using the DownloadISOToVFlash method.
OSD41.Message: ISO Image not found on VFlash.

RAC1179.Description: Unable to complete requested operation because a Type A/A USB cable is connected to the front panel USB port and the iDRAC is emulating a NIC device.
RAC1179.Resolution: To change the USB Management Port mode setting, remove the Type A/A USB cable from the front panel USB port and change the port mode settings.
RAC1179.Message: Unable to complete requested operation because an Type A/A USB cable is connected to the front panel USB port and the iDRAC is emulating a NIC device.

ENC40.Description: The controller detected a new enclosure. This is due either to a hot plug of an enclosure, or a power state change of an enclosure. In addition, this message is generated if the daisy chain order of the enclosures changes.
ENC40.Message: A new enclosure was detected on %1.

VDR2.Description: The virtual disk has returned to a healthy state and is working properly.

SWC4013.Description: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between the components identified in the message.
SWC4013.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between %1%2 and %3%4.

MEM9038.Description: The NVDIMM device in the slot identified in the message has lost persistency and is placed in write-protect mode.
MEM9038.Resolution: Remove and reinstall the Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device. If the issue persists, contact the service provider. For information about removing and reinstalling the NVDIMM, see the system Owner's Manual on the support site.
MEM9038.Message: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device in the slot %1 has lost persistency and is placed in write-protect mode.

CMC002.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because of an unknown issue.
CMC002.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) Reset CMC and retry the operation.
CMC002.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of an unknown issue.

TMP0112.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0112.Message: The %1 temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

RAC0510.Description: This error occurs if Lifecycle log events have not occurred recently.
RAC0510.Message: There are no events to be displayed.

SRV082.Description: The operation cannot be started because iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running on the server operating system (OS).
SRV082.Resolution: Enable and start the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service from within the server operating system (OS) and then retry the operation.
SRV082.Message: Unable to start the operation because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service is not running on the server operating system (OS).

GMGR0048.Description: The group job at the member level is completed but with errors. Review the job execution details at member iDRAC lifecycle log.
GMGR0048.Resolution: Review the job execution details at member iDRAC lifecycle log. Rerun the job if required after addressing any action items.
GMGR0048.Message: The group job is completed, but with errors.

PDR1104.Message: Consistency check is in progress for drive %1.

LOG305.Description: The Chassis Log file was cleared as a result of clear log operation.
LOG305.Message: The Chassis Log file was cleared.

PWR8601.Description: The power buttons for all multinode sleds in the chassis are disabled. The operation to disable the power button is only applicable to the multinode sleds available, and does not affect other servers in the chassis.
PWR8601.Resolution: To enable the chassis power button use the CMC RACADM command line interface (CLI) or CMC Web interface. At the CLI, enter "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisSledPowerButtonEnable 1". Using the Web interface, click Server Overview > Power > Control. Clear the Disable power button for all multinode sleds in the chassis" check box.
PWR8601.Message: The multinode sled power button is disabled.

PWR8561.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate with the Server iDRAC service processor and the server could not be powered on. This situation may occur when iDRAC is rebooting.
PWR8561.Resolution: Wait for three minutes and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the server and wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting.
PWR8561.Message: Unable to power on server %1 because of iDRAC communication issue.

OSD69.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is missing.
OSD69.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ShareType" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD69.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is missing.

VLT0103.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0103.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0103.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

VLT0228.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0228.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0228.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is outside of range.

RAC0250.Description: The vFlash partitions are read-only. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0250.Resolution: Make sure the partitions are writable before attempting to change their contents.
RAC0250.Message: One or more partitions are read-only.

BAR105.Description: Importing system branding data from the Server Profile backup file.

RAC0904.Description: The iDRAC cannot access the remote file location. The credentials or path to the remote file location is incorrect or iDRAC cannot connect to the network address.
RAC0904.Resolution: Confirm that the path and credentials to remote file are correct, and check that the iDRAC can connect to the network address.
RAC0904.Message: The remote file location is not accessible or reachable.

RDU0005.Description: One of more fans have failed or have been removed or a configuration change occurred which requires additional fans.
RDU0005.Resolution: Remove and re-install failed fans or install additional fans.
RDU0005.Message: The fans are not redundant. Insufficient resources to maintain normal operations.

SWC8600.Description: The profile version must be compatible with the server generation and Lifecycle Controller firmware version.
SWC8600.Resolution: Make sure that profile versions are compatible with target servers when attempting application of profiles to servers.
SWC8600.Message: The selected profile was not applied to %1.

ISM0004.Description: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully started communication with iDRAC.
ISM0004.Message: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully started communication with iDRAC.

SWC0205.Message: Upload an SSL key to the RAC

UEFI0056.Description: The PCIe error is logged during Power-on-Self-Test (POST). The error could have occurred during either the current or the previous POST.
UEFI0056.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCIe device that is not functioning correctly, and then update the device firmware.

ENC23.Description: There is a problem with a physical connection or PHY in the enclosure identified in the message.

MEM9036.Description: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) devices are placed in write-protect mode because the server may not provide sufficient power or the battery is not sufficiently charged to save data in case of power loss.
MEM9036.Resolution: Review any preceding power or battery entries in the log and resolve the issues. Refer to your documentation for details on how to view the log.
MEM9036.Message: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) devices are placed in write-protect mode because the system may not provide sufficient power to save data in case of power loss.

RAC993.Description: The job ID specified in the message was deleted.

PWR8586.Description: The Chassis does not support the server identified in the message.
PWR8586.Resolution: The server inserted is not supported in the Chassis. Remove the server from the Chassis.
PWR8586.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because it is not supported in the VRTX chassis.

UEFI0306.Description: The BIOS firmware cannot be updated because the BIOS image file used is corrupted.
UEFI0306.Resolution: Make sure that the BIOS firmware is downloaded from the correct support site. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0306.Message: Unable to update BIOS firmware because the new BIOS image file used is corrupted.

PDR110.Description: The reliability of the PCIe solid state device identified in the message degraded. Data loss is possible.
PDR110.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.

TMP0115.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0115.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0115.Message: The %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SEC0032.Message: The chassis is closed while the power is on.

MEM0022.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.
MEM0022.Resolution: If unexpected, check presence, then re-install.
MEM0022.Message: Memory device at location %1 is absent.

RAC0740.Description: The Prepare to Remove operation will stop any activity on the PCIe SSD device so that it can be removed safely. The device is safe to remove when the disk shows the safe to remove LED pattern.
RAC0740.Message: The Prepare to Remove operation will stop any activity on the PCIe SSD device so that it can be removed safely. The device is safe to remove when the disk shows the safe to remove LED pattern.

SRV100.Description: The iDRAC event identified in the message is forwarded to the SupportAssist back-end server.
SRV100.Message: The iDRAC event %1 is forwarded to the SupportAssist back-end server.

SYS029.Description: The parameter name is not supported.
SYS029.Resolution: Remove the unsupported parameter and retry the operation.

DIS004.Description: The Auto Discovery process has timed out and stopped. The Auto Discovery process runs for 24 hours from the initial system power on or re-initialization request. Every 90 seconds the Auto Discovery client will attempt to identify and contact the Provisioning Server during this period.
DIS004.Resolution: Check for previous messages in the Lifecycle Controller Log that provide more specific information why the timeout occurred.
DIS004.Message: Auto Discovery 24-hour timeout occurred. Stopping Auto Discovery process.

FC012.Description: No changes to component attribute data are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration.

RAC0262.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the Preferred IPv6 DNS Server address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0262.Resolution: Enter a valid Preferred IPv6 DNS server address.
RAC0262.Message: The Preferred IPv6 DNS Server Address is invalid.

PDR107.Description: The physical disk drive identified in the message is assigned as a global hot-spare.
PDR107.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is assigned as a global hot-spare.

BAR068.Description: The system profile export destination is not supported.
BAR068.Resolution: Insert, enable and initialize supported vFlash media and retry the operation.

CTL9.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL9.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL9.Message: Bad block extended medium error on %1.

GMGR0041.Description: The group job identified in the message cannot be retried because the group job is not in an error state. Only failed or errored group job shall be retried.
GMGR0041.Message: Unable to retry the group job %1 of type %2 because the group job is not in an error state.

ENC18.Description: The controller has lost communication with an Enclosure Management Module (EMM). The cables may be loose or defective.
ENC18.Resolution: Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables. Reboot the system.

RAC0673.Description: To export operating system (OS) and application data, the OS Collector utility must be run on the server OS. A virtual USB device labeled DRACRW has appeared in the server OS. After the OS Collector utility execution has completed, return to this page to complete exporting the Tech Support Report (TSR).
RAC0673.Resolution: Invoke the OS Collector utility in the OS and wait for execution completion. Then return to this page to complete exporting the Technical Support Report (TSR).
RAC0673.Message: OS Collector must be run on the server OS in order to export OS and Application Data. A virtual USB device labeled DRACRW has appeared in the server OS. This device contains the OS Collector utility, go to the Server OS and run the version of the utility appropriate to the OS type. After the OS Collector utility execution has completed, return to this page to finish exporting the Technical Support Report (TSR).

PWR8585.Description: Chassis Management Controller granted the power required to turn on the server identified in the message.
PWR8585.Message: Chassis Management Controller granted the power required to turn on server-%1.

VLT0215.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0215.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0215.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

LC023.Description: Credentials or network share identity information provided did not result in a network connection being established.
LC023.Resolution: Check network share access credentials (IP address, user name, password, share type, and so on). Refer to Lifecycle Controller Profile documentation for more details.

RAC0136.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while attaching the vFlash partition.
RAC0136.Message: An error has occurred while attaching a partition.

RAC1123.Description: Fibre Channel (FC) objects are not available if Fibre Channel devices are not installed in the server, or if some iDRAC services are busy.
RAC1123.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Power off and remove AC or DC power from the server. 2) Make sure the Fibre Channel devices are correctly installed in the server. 3) Restart the server to allow the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature to update the server inventory. 4) Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC1123.Message: Unable to perform the operation because Fibre Channel (FC) attributes are not available in the current server configuration.

SRV012.Description: The SupportAssist Storage Controller Logs collection operation is cancelled.
SRV012.Message: The SupportAssist Storage Controller Logs collection operation is cancelled.

TMP0135.Message: The control panel temperature is within range.

CMC8573.Description: The chassis health is critical or non-recoverable.
CMC8573.Resolution: Review the Chassis log or the Chassis Management Controller(CMC) SEL log for the failure or Export chassis log and SEL log and contact technical support .

SWC0069.Description: The new boot mode settings for BIOS were successfully applied.
SWC0069.Message: Successfully applied the new boot mode settings for BIOS.

UEFI0099.Description: The Memory Mirroring feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.
UEFI0099.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure the Memory Mirroring feature can be supported. For more information, see platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0099.Message: Unable to enable the Memory Mirroring feature because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.

USR0024.Description: Cannot log in to iDRAC from the user name and IP address identified in the message by using Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI) because an incorrect user name or password is entered.
USR0024.Resolution: Enter the correct user name and password and retry the operation.
USR0024.Message: Unable to log in to iDRAC from %1:%2 using Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI) because an incorrect user name or password is entered.

RAC1214.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the Secure Boot policy is of unknown type.
RAC1214.Resolution: Set the Secure Boot policy to Standard or Custom mode. For example to set the policy to Custom mode use command "racadm set bios.syssecurity.securebootpolicy Custom". For more information, see the RACADM CLI Reference Guide available on the support site.
RAC1214.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the Secure Boot policy is of unknown type.

CTL109.Description: The Reconstruct Rate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL109.Message: The Reconstruct Rate of %1 is set to %2.

PDR1003.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is the hot-spare drive.

BAR112.Description: Server Profile backup file validation failed because the target system identifier information does not match the value stored in the file. The Server Profile file may be from another system or the iDRAC may need to be restarted to acquire the system identifier information accurately.
BAR112.Resolution: Obtain a valid Server Profile file for the target system and try the operation again. If the problem reoccurs, restart the iDRAC and try the operation again.
BAR112.Message: The system identifier in the Server Profile file does not match the target system.

GMGR0007.Description: The server having the Service Tag identified in the message has successfully joined the local iDRAC group identified in the message. The server can now be managed from the local group.
GMGR0007.Message: The server %1 has successfully joined the local iDRAC group %2.

RED100.Description: iDRAC initiated the download update package files operation. Wait for a few minutes.
RED100.Message: iDRAC initiated the download update package files operation. Wait for a few minutes.

SRV057.Description: The SupportAssist Registration operation is started.
SRV057.Message: The SupportAssist Registration operation is started.

RAC045.Description: The combination of input parameters provided did not match any event filters.
RAC045.Resolution: Verify the combination of input parameters and retry the operation.
RAC045.Message: Event filter does not exist for input parameter combination.

SUP018.Description: The specified until time is invalid.
SUP018.Resolution: Until Time should be in the form YYYYMMDDHHMMSS. Verify the specified until time and retry the action.

STOR312.Description: The firmware package being used to update the physical disk drive is not valid for the drive model identified in the message. The firmware package contains the drive component id in the list of supported drives, but the firmware image is not valid for the drive model identified in the message.
STOR312.Resolution: Acquire the correct firmware image file for the drive model identified in the message, and then retry the operation. The correct image file can be found by using the drive model information and searching the support site for related firmware.
STOR312.Message: Unable to update the firmware of the physical disk drive %1 because an incorrect firmware image file is used.

PDR1101.Description: The controller detected a failure on the disk and has taken the disk offline.
PDR1101.Resolution: Remove and reseat the failed disk. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

RAC1009.Description: The Active Directory objects DCLookupEnable or GCLookupEnable cannot be enabled, because IPv4.DNS1, IPv4.DNS2, IPv6.DNS1, or IPv6.DNS2 is not configured.
RAC1009.Resolution: Configure IPv4.DNS1, IPv4.DNS2, IPv6.DNS1, or IPv6.DNS2 using racadm set command, and retry the operation. For example, "racadm set iDRAC.IPv4.DNS1 <address>".
RAC1009.Message: The Active Directory objects DCLookupEnable or GCLookupEnable cannot be enabled.

RAC0718.Description: Remote File Share service is busy with the previous connection.
RAC0718.Resolution: Stop the Remote File Share session and retry the operation.
RAC0718.Message: Remote File Share service is busy with the previous connection.

SWC8509.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required. The Lifecycle log in the server identified in the message may have additional information about the inability of the iDRAC to apply Profile settings.
SWC8509.Message: Unable to apply %1 Profile to server in slot %2

BIOS015.Description: A set attribute operation was attempted on a read only attribute.
BIOS015.Message: AttributeValue cannot be changed to read only AttributeName %1.

VDR30.Description: A user changed the write policy for a virtual disk.
VDR30.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

VDR19.Description: The reconfiguration operation was not completed. This may be due to a user action or a physical disk failure.
VDR19.Resolution: Recreate the virtual disk and restore data from a backup copy.

SWC0079.Description: iDRAC entered into Dell Integrated Data Center Troubleshooting Mode.
SWC0079.Message: iDRAC entered into Integrated Data Center Troubleshooting Mode.

UEFI0175.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.
UEFI0175.Resolution: Quad Rank and Octal Rank DIMM modules cannot be mixed on a channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0175.Message: A Octal Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Quad Rank DIMM module.

HWC3000.Description: The removed device may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC3000.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

ASR0008.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC) within the timeout period. The BMC invoked a system interrupt. (IPMI sensor type code 23h - offset 00h).
ASR0008.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0008.Message: The watchdog timer interrupt was initiated.

RAC0663.Description: Resetting the selected PERC controller's configuration will delete all the virtual disks (VDs) and unassign hot-spares from the associated controller.
RAC0663.Message: Resetting the selected PERC controller's configuration will delete all the virtual disks (VDs) and unassign hot-spares from the associated controller.

SUP0116.Message: The RAC configuration has initiated restoration to factory defaults. Please wait up to a minute for this process to complete before accessing the RAC again.

BAR077.Description: The collection and export of host system firmware images was not successful.
BAR077.Resolution: Apply Dell Update Packages for all devices and software, and try the operation again. If the error continues, repair the Lifecycle Controller and apply the packages again, and retry the operation.
BAR077.Message: Unable to collect the Firmware images.

LOG203.Description: This message is generated while archiving Lifecycle Log. All the older messages are archived and can be retrieved using the export Lifecycle Log feature.
LOG203.Message: Lifecycle Log archived up to Log Sequence number %1.

RAC082.Description: The file cannot be transferred because either the file name entered as input is incorrect or the file is not available.
RAC082.Resolution: Enter a valid file name and retry the operation.
RAC082.Message: Unable to transfer the file because either the file type entered as input is incorrect or the file is not available.

PWR2205.Message: The system is in a soft-off state.

SEL1402.Message: The platform generated a LAN alert.

STOR0102.Description: No battery data to display. The system is powered off, batteries are not present on the system, batteries are not connected to the RAID controller, or the batteries are depleted.
STOR0102.Resolution: Check if the server has power, batteries are available, and batteries are connected to the RAID controller.

UEFI0209.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Transmit Buffer Per Bit Deskew Training phase.
UEFI0209.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0209.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

TST104.Description: The SNMP trap being tested is not properly configured.
TST104.Resolution: Configure the SNMP trap and retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC.

PWR2273.Description: The power required by server is within the power supplied by the power supply units (PSUs).
PWR2273.Message: The power required by server is within the power supplied by the power supply units (PSUs).

RAC0154.Description: Displayed when a group of redundant power supplies has one or more individual power supplies with bad status.
RAC0154.Resolution: Replace the degraded power supply unit. Check the Power Supplies page for more information.
RAC0154.Message: Non-redundant power mode: Secondary power supply has degraded.

RAC1175.Description: The user configuration cannot be modified, because modification is not allowed at index 1.
RAC1175.Message: Unable to change the user configuration because modifying the user configuration at index 1 is not allowed.

HWC0008.Description: An internal error occurred while communicating with iDRAC.
HWC0008.Resolution: Exit the wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.

RAC1047.Description: Successfully cleared the Automatic Update(autoupdate) feature settings.
RAC1047.Message: Successfully cleared the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings.

RAC0647.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'week of the month' while scheduling a job.
RAC0647.Resolution: Enter a correct value from 1 to 4, and then retry the operation.
RAC0647.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid value is entered for the 'week of the month'.

SYS024.Description: Unable to complete the operation because attribute dependency checking did not complete successfully. This attribute is dependent on a related attribute that has an incorrect value. The related attribute is the parent in a parent-child value dependency relationship and has an affect on what values the child attribute can have.
SYS024.Resolution: Make sure the dependency related attribute has the correct value and retry the operation. For more information on attribute dependency, Refer to the Dell Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide and Profile Documents available at the support site.
SYS024.Message: Unable to complete the operation because attribute dependency checking did not complete successfully.

VLT0222.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition. If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0222.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions 2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0222.Message: The %1 voltage is outside of range.

STOR0508.Description: Unable to configure RAID as the supported RAID controller is not present.
STOR0508.Resolution: Install a supported RAID controller and the required number of physical disks for the RAID configuration, and retry the operation.
STOR0508.Message: No supported controllers present for RAID configuration.

RAC0746.Description: Unable to perform virtual disk(VD) operations, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0746.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. To enable Lifecycle Controller, restart the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes.
RAC0746.Message: Unable to perform virtual disk (VD) operations, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

CPU0006.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.
CPU0006.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0006.Message: Unrecoverable CPU complex error detected on CPU %1.

UEFI0229.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Receive Enable Training - Calibration phase.
UEFI0229.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0229.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

PWR211.Description: The Fresh Air (FA) mode cannot be set because the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is enabled.
PWR211.Message: Unable to set the Fresh Air (FA) mode because the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is enabled.

PDR42.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC0657.Description: The file name cannot be blank when performing the Backup Server Profile operation.
RAC0657.Resolution: Enter an appropriate file name, and then retry the operation.
RAC0657.Message: The file name field must not be blank.

RAC1158.Description: The requested number of Lifecycle log entries exceed the limit and cannot be displayed. The remote RACADM operation may time out before retrieving all the log entries.
RAC1158.Resolution: Retrieve a smaller number of log entries using remote RACADM or use firmware or local RACADM to view all the log entries. To retrieve a limited number of log entries, use the -n option. For example, to view the last 10 log entries, run the command 'racadm lclog view -n 10'.
RAC1158.Message: The requested number of log entries exceeds the limit.

IOV006.Description: The Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard firmware is not at the correct version.
IOV006.Resolution: Run the command "racadm fwupdate -g -u -a <TFTP server IP Address> -d mainboard.bin -m main_board" to upload the latest firmware version to the Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard.
IOV006.Message: Incorrect Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard firmware version.

SEC0700.Description: If the property name is configured without changing the default password, iDRAC may be accessible on the Internet. This causes a severe security risk for iDRAC.
SEC0700.Resolution: To change the password, run the following racadm command: racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.Password <new password string>.Alternatively, to avoid this warning message, run the following racadm command: racadm set iDRAC.Tuning.DefaultCredentialWarning Disable.
SEC0700.Message: Warning: Default username and password are currently in use. It is strongly recommended to change the default password before configuring the property. Else, it causes a severe security risk for iDRAC.

RDU8515.Description: A CMC failover was initiated by the CMC health monitoring process. There should be a reason listed in the chassis log.
RDU8515.Message: CMC%1: failover was initiated by internal health monitoring process.

CMC8534.Description: Unable to turn on the server specified in the message, because the available power is lesser than the requested power.
CMC8534.Resolution: In the CMC Web interface, verify the available power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, retry the operation. Otherwise, increase the power cap value.
CMC8534.Message: Unable to turn on the server %1 because the power requirement request exceeds the power cap value.

RAC0117.Description: The SD card is not present, or communication with the SD card is lost. This could result in reduced functionality and capabilities.
RAC0117.Resolution: This error may occur because: 1. Make sure the SD card is seated correctly. 2. The SD card is invalid. Insert a valid SD card of size greater than 256MB and try again.

RAC066.Description: iDRAC was successfully reset to factory-default properties.
RAC066.Message: iDRAC is successfully reset to factory-default properties.

LIC024.Description: The License can not be installed, deleted or replaced when the device is on.
LIC024.Resolution: Turn off the respective device and retry the License operation.
LIC024.Message: License operation did not complete successfully because the device is turned on.

PWR8682.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the storage sled controller identified in the message. The Chassis storage sled controller is unable to turn on due to a configuration or hardware issue.
PWR8682.Resolution: Remove the storage sled identified in the message, re-insert it and observe whether the issue is resolved. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
