PWR8682.Message: Unable to turn on the storage sled controller %1 in slot %2 because the %3 module is not functioning.

RFLA2001.Description: The SD card module is not detected or not installed.
RFLA2001.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the SD module.
RFLA2001.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is absent.

SWC0127.Description: The file may be write protected and hence could not be edited.
SWC0127.Resolution: Check if the file is write protected.
SWC0127.Message: Unable to open file for writing.

OSE0000.Description: The system halted due to an exception during operating system load or operating system initialization.
OSE0000.Resolution: Review operating system logs and system video for additional information.
OSE0000.Message: A critical stop occurred during OS load.

RDU8516.Description: A failover has been requested from the RACADM command line interface.
RDU8516.Message: CMC%1: failover initiated by RACADM interface.

SYS256.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an out-of-memory condition. The issue is not because of network conditions, proxy status, or remote host status.
SYS256.Resolution: Check the iDRAC health and retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation after the iDRAC has fully restarted.
SYS256.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an out-of-memory condition.

SWC8500.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required.
SWC8500.Message: Unable to generate Profile with [ %1 ] settings.

RAC0503.Description: Out-of-band controllers cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, or controllers are removed or disconnected.
RAC0503.Resolution: Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown.
RAC0503.Message: There are no out-of-band capable controllers to be displayed.

CTL33.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL33.Message: The %1 debug log file has been exported.

SYS141.Description: The Lifecycle Controller data is deleted because of a System Erase operation.

UEFI0281.Description: The system BIOS is not fully secured because the PWD_EN jumper is not installed on the motherboard. Some BIOS security features such as signed BIOS update are enforced based on the PWD_EN jumper presence.
UEFI0281.Resolution: Disconnect the input AC power to the system, install the PWD_EN jumper, connect the AC power, and then turn on the system. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0281.Message: The system BIOS is not fully secured because the PWD_EN jumper is not installed on the motherboard.

SWC0302.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0302.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0302.Message: The -s option is not valid with any other option.

PST0126.Description: System is currently booting to an UEFI compatible operating system. No more POST codes will be generated in this boot sequence.
PST0126.Message: Giving control to UEFI aware OS.

CMC8504.Description: The NIC is disabled on the server identified in the message, and the CMC is unable to display the link to launch the iDRAC web interface.
CMC8504.Resolution: Enable the NIC on the server identified in the message using the CMC command line or CMC Web interface, so that the link to launch iDRAC is displayed on the CMC Web interface. To enable the NIC for DHCP using RACADM, enter "racadm setniccfg -m server-<slot number> -d" where <slot number> is the server identified in the message. To enable the NIC using the Web interface, click Server Overview > select the identified server, go to Setup > select the Enable LAN check box.
CMC8504.Message: Unable to access server: %1, because the NIC is disabled on the identified server.

LC037.Description: Lifecycle Controller is locked by another instance of Lifecycle Controller Log Export operation. Wait for that operation to complete before attempting to run another command.
LC037.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Wait approximately 2 minutes and retry the operation. 2) Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
LC037.Message: An instance of Lifecycle Controller Log Export is already running.

UEFI0271.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the network connection to DHCPv6 server is not established.
UEFI0271.Resolution: Check the network cable connection of the initiator or the DHCPv6 server and retry the operation.
UEFI0271.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the network connection to DHCPv6 server is not established.

RAC1004.Description: The smart card login cannot be enabled, because the Active Directory Single Sign On is enabled.
RAC1004.Resolution: Disable Active Directory Single Sign On (SSO) using "racadm set iDRAC.ActiveDirectory.SSOEnable <0 | Disabled>", and retry the operation.
RAC1004.Message: The smart card login cannot be enabled.

RAC063.Description: The string length of the entered value for the attribute identified in the message may be less than the minimum length or greater than the maximum length allowed.
RAC063.Resolution: Make sure that the string length is correct and retry the operation.
RAC063.Message: The string length of the provided value for %1 is inappropriate.

UEFI0294.Description: DDR memory initialization of the Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) in the specified memory slot cannot be completed because of a mismatch in the number of ranks between the DIMMs installed in the server.
UEFI0294.Resolution: Remove the mismatched Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) and replace it with a DIMM with the same rank count as the other installed DIMMs in the Integrated Memory Controllers (iMCs). For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual available on the support site.
UEFI0294.Message: Unable to initialize the Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) in memory slot %1 because of a mismatch in the number of ranks.

USR0171.Description: The device identified in the message is connected to the Front Panel USB port and detached from the iDRAC.
USR0171.Message: The Front Panel USB port is detached from the iDRAC Disk.USBFront.%1. Device Details: Device Class %2, Vendor ID %3, Product ID %4.

BOOT012.Description: A job was created to configure a OneTime boot to the specified vFlash SD card partition. If this partition was not attached to the system, the job attaches it as well.
BOOT012.Message: Job started to attach and set vFlash SD card partition for OneTime boot.

SEC0608.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0608.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

SWC0246.Description: The specified value is outside of the valid range.
SWC0246.Resolution: Verify that a valid value is specified. See the help text or documentation for valid values.
SWC0246.Message: Value specified is invalid: Valid range is %1.

PWR2207.Message: The system is in a mechanical off state.

USR0034.Description: The account identified in the message is temporarily disabled because of consecutive unsuccessful Login attempts to iDRAC from the IP address identified in the message.
USR0034.Resolution: Contact the iDRAC administrator and make sure the username and password credentials used are correct. Check the Lifecycle Controller Log (LC Log) to see if more unauthorized iDRAC access attempts are occurring than would be expected due to forgotten account names or passwords.
USR0034.Message: Login attempt alert for %1 from %2 using %3, IP will be blocked for %4 seconds.

SYS191.Description: The provided Server Configuration Profile is being applied to the system. The host may reboot to apply all changes.
SYS191.Resolution: No response action is required. Use the GetConfigResults() method to get the configuration job results or export the Lifecycle Log to review the configuration job results.

HWC2004.Message: The system board %1 cable or interconnect is connected.

PST0002.Description: System BIOS has started loading the processor microcode.

SUP0105.Description: The firmware image provided by the user is not valid.

VDR6.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

CMC8529.Description: The user account does not have sufficient privileges to perform the requested operation. Server Administrator privilege is required to perform the requested action.
CMC8529.Resolution: Use a different user account that has Server Administrator privilege, and retry the operation. For more information, contact your system administrator or service provider.
CMC8529.Message: Unable to perform the requested action on the server-%1, because of insufficient privileges.

RAC0658.Description: The iDRAC Service Module service can now be started on the server operating system. This service needs to be started manually on the server operating system.
RAC0658.Message: The iDRAC Service Module service can now be manually started on the server operating system.

SYS251.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the file is not available at the source file path.
SYS251.Resolution: Check the file transfer parameters and retry the operation.
SYS251.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the file is not available at the source file path.

AMP0320.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0320.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0320.Message: Chassis power level current is greater than the upper warning threshold.

UEFI0051.Description: Brand information is successfully collected. The system is being restarted. The rebranding process is completed.
UEFI0051.Message: Brand information is successfully collected. The system is being restarted.

PWR8573.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is not able to communicate with the iDRAC on the server identified in the message. Therefore the server could not be turned off. This situation may occur when iDRAC is restarting.
PWR8573.Resolution: Wait for three minutes, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the server and wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting before retying the operation.
PWR8573.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate to the iDRAC, when trying to turn off the server %1.

SEC0102.Description: The module or Storage tray identified in the message is closed.

STOR049.Description: The controller is in Local Key Management mode.
STOR049.Message: Controller is in Local Key Management mode.

BAR063.Description: Collecting the Lifecycle Controller firmware images and copying them in the server profile backup file.

SWC0242.Description: The license is missing or expired. This will result in the loss of functionality that is specific to the features supported by the license.
SWC0242.Resolution: Import an appropriate license to iDRAC. If you do not know which license to install, contact your service provider.
SWC0242.Message: A required license is missing or expired. Obtain an appropriate license and try again, or contact your service provider for additional details.

UEFI0314.Description: The Baseboard UPI D cable connection is misconfigured.
UEFI0314.Resolution: Connect the Baseboard UPI D cable. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0314.Message: The Baseboard UPI D cable connection is misconfigured.

RAC989.Description: Only Windows-based Update Package (.exe extension), iDRAC Firmware (.d7 extension), Personality Module Firmware (.pm extension), Lifecycle Controller firmware repair package (.usc) are supported for the firmware update operation.
RAC989.Resolution: The file used for the operation is invalid. For the list of supported files, use "racadm help update". For the correct version of the file specific to the system, contact the service provider.
RAC989.Message: Unable to apply the %1 firmware update.

UEFI0284.Description: The BIOS cannot accept the Secure Boot policy data from the management console because the format of the data is incompatible with the BIOS Secure Boot databases. Secure Boot policy data consists of a Platform Key (PK), Key Exchange Key (KEK) database, Authorized Signature Database (db), and Forbidden Signature Database (dbx). The contents of PK and KEK must follow the Distinguished Encoding Rules (DER) X.509 certificate format. Each entry in db and dbx must follow the DER X.509 certificate format or consist of a hash value generated by a Secure Hash Algorithm (SHA-256, SHA-384, or SHA-512).
UEFI0284.Resolution: Make sure certificates follow the Distinguished Encoding Rules (DER) X.509 certificate format. Hash values in the Secure Boot policy must be 32 bytes, 48 bytes, or 64 bytes in size. Also make sure the data for the Platform Key (PK) and Key Exchange Key (KEK) database contain only certificates, not hash values. If the import operation includes multiple policy objects (certificates or hash values), determine the failing object by retrying the operation with one object at a time.
UEFI0284.Message: Unable to import Secure Boot policy data because the format of the data is incompatible with the Secure Boot databases.

SRV102.Description: The iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer cannot be presented to the host operating system because the Lifecycle Controller iSM update package is not installed.
SRV102.Resolution: Install the Lifecycle Controller for iDRAC Service Module (iSM) and retry the operation.
SRV102.Message: Unable to present the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer to the host operating system because the Lifecycle Controller iSM update package is not installed.

HWC0015.Description: iDRAC has encountered a hardware error.
HWC0015.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.

PWR8598.Description: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) identified in the message is turned off because it is not compatible with the other PSUs in the Chassis.
PWR8598.Resolution: Replace the PSU with an appropriate unit, and then retry the operation. For a list of PSUs that are compatible, consult the system Owner's Manual or contact your service provider.
PWR8598.Message: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) %1 is turned off because it is not compatible with the other PSUs used in the Chassis.

ISM0006.Description: The iDRAC Service Module could not successfully communicate with iDRAC, because the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel is not configured in the USB-NIC mode.
ISM0006.Resolution: Make sure that the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel is configured only in the USB-NIC mode, and then retry the operation. To enable the OS-to-iDRAC Pass-through channel, run the following command in the order they are listed: 1) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.PTMode usb-p2p 2) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.UsbNicIpAddress <ip address> 3) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.adminstate enabled.
ISM0006.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is unable to communicate with iDRAC using the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel.

PWR8669.Description: The server identified in the message could not be successfully turned on because of incompatibility between the chassis PCIe components and mezzanine card.
PWR8669.Resolution: Make sure that the chassis PCIe components and mezzanine card are compatible. For information about compatibility of hardware components, see the Modular System Chassis Hardware Manual available at the support site.
PWR8669.Message: Unable to turn on the server %1 because of an inconsistency between the chassis and server components.

UEFI0253.Description: Unable to enable NUMA Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) feature due to the current configuration does not support it.
UEFI0253.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure NUMA FRM feature can be supported. For more information, see platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0253.Message: Unable to enable NUMA Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) feature due to the current configuration does not support it.

TMP0114.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0114.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0114.Message: The %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

OSD62.Description: The command cannot be run because an invalid firmware image file name is entered.
OSD62.Resolution: Make sure that a valid firmware image file is entered. The file must not contain any file path components such as forward slash (/) or period (.).
OSD62.Message: Unable to run the command because an invalid firmware image file name is entered.

RAC1213.Description: The Public Key (PK) cannot be deleted because a PK already exists.
RAC1213.Resolution: Delete the existing Public Key, restart the host server, and then retry the operation.To know how to Delete, run sub-command help "racadm bioscert help delete". For further information, see the RACADM CLI Reference Guide available on the support site.
RAC1213.Message: Unable to import the Public Key (PK) because a PK already exists.

RED095.Description: An item named rSPI that is dependent on the Diagnostics package was not updated successfully when the Diagnostics package was updated.
RED095.Message: Update of rSPI was not successful after the Diagnostics package was updated.

SUP0125.Message: Current firmware update status is unknown

SRV115.Description: The SupportAssist Collection was not uploaded because upload to SupportAssist server failed.
SRV115.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and server OS.
SRV115.Message: Unable to upload the SupportAssist Collection because upload to SupportAssist server failed.

RAC951.Description: Up to 256 characters are allowed for a work note.
RAC951.Resolution: Do not exceed 256 characters in the work note, and retry the operation.
RAC951.Message: The number of characters entered for the work note exceeds the supported limit.

PSU0034.Description: This failure may be the result of an electrical issue with cables or subsystem components in the system.
PSU0034.Resolution: 1) Remove and re-install the power supply.2) Check cables and subsystem components in the system for damage. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0034.Message: An under voltage fault detected on power supply %1.

USR0030.Description: Successful login for the username, IP address, and interface identified in the message.
USR0030.Message: Successfully logged in using %1, from %2 and %3.

JCP000.Description: A new job with the ID identified in the message is created.
JCP000.Message: A new job with ID %1 is created.

PWR8680.Description: The firmware identified in the message does not support the storage sled.
PWR8680.Resolution: Update the firmware identified in the message to the supported latest available version. See the latest iDRAC User Guide for information on the versions that support the storage sled.
PWR8680.Message: The %1 firmware in the server slot %2 does not support the storage sled.

RAC0655.Description: The Replicate Lifecycle Controller Log in OS Log and Auto System Recovery Action features are disabled in the iDRAC Service Module because the OpenManage Server Administrator is installed on the server operating system.
RAC0655.Message: The Replicate Lifecycle Controller Log in OS Log and Auto System Recovery Action features are disabled in the iDRAC Service Module because the OpenManage Server Administrator is installed on the server operating system.

BIOS011.Description: Configuration job already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job is completed.
BIOS011.Resolution: Cancel the configuration job or wait for the job to complete. Refer to documentation on job cancellation.
BIOS011.Message: Configuration job already created, pending data cannot be deleted.

SRV016.Description: The Storage Controller Log data export did not complete within the allocated time. Currently, the maximum allocated time is 20 minutes.
SRV016.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm racreset".
SRV016.Message: Unable to export Storage Controller Log information for controller %1 because the export did not complete within the allocated time.

SYS201.Description: The disk erase operation is successfully completed on the drive identified in the message.
SYS201.Message: The disk erase operation on the drive %1 successfully completed.

HWC1001.Description: The absent device may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

CMC8601.Description: The Chassis group identified in the message is created. This chassis is the leader of the group.

SYS181.Description: The collect OS and Application Data operation cannot be completed because the OS Collector is not installed on the iDRAC.
SYS181.Resolution: Install OS Collector on the iDRAC and retry the operation. To install the OS Collector using the iDRAC Web UI, get the latest OC Collector update package and then select the Update and Rollback link from the iDRAC Web UI home page and upload the install package.
SYS181.Message: Unable to collect OS and Application Data because the OS Collector is not installed on the iDRAC.

UEFI0016.Description: Unable to find a Lifecycle Controller partition. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0016.Resolution: Perform the following actions: 1)Reboot the system. 2) Press F2 during boot to enter System Setup. 3) Select iDRAC Settings then Lifecycle Controller. 4) Change Lifecycle Controller back to Enabled. If subsequent failures occur, press and hold the system ID button down for 15 seconds to reset the iDRAC. For more information on how to reset iDRAC, see iDRAC User's Guide.
UEFI0016.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible and is therefore in Recovery mode.

LOG202.Description: Unable to access part of Lifecycle Controller Log comments file during iDRAC boot. The file was truncated at the point of corruption.
LOG202.Message: Recovered from Lifecycle Controller Log comments file corruption.

PWR2208.Message: The system is in a sleep state.

SYS072.Description: The import of Server Configuration Profile did not complete as the operation took too long.
SYS072.Resolution: Delete all jobs, reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and retry the operation.
SYS072.Message: Server Configuration Profile import operation timed-out.

STOR9.Description: No supported RAID controllers have been detected. Access to shared storage will not be available.
STOR9.Resolution: Ensure supported RAID controllers are installed.
STOR9.Message: No RAID controllers have been detected. Access to shared storage will not be available.

PSU0803.Description: Insufficient power in chassis to power on server.
PSU0803.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller web interface to check available power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, retry the operation.
PSU0803.Message: Insufficient power in chassis to power on server.

RAC1138.Description: Unable to export the remote diagnostics results because the remote diagnostics results have not been generated.
RAC1138.Resolution: Using the RACADM command line interface, run the "racadm diagnostics run" command to make sure that the diagnostics results are available, and then retry the operation.
RAC1138.Message: Unable to export the diagnostics results because the results do not exist.

LC058.Description: The attribute value specified in the AttributeValue array is not valid for the corresponding specified attribute.
LC058.Resolution: Retry the operation with a valid attribute value for the corresponding specified attribute.
LC058.Message: Invalid AttributeValue parameter value for corresponding AttributeName value, %1.

CTL3.Description: You have enabled the controller alarm. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

HWC0006.Description: If a vFlash SD card is not present in the system or if the card is locked, Lifecycle Controller cannot save the settings.
HWC0006.Resolution: Insert the vFlash SD card or unlock the vFlash SD card and retry the operation.
HWC0006.Message: Unable to save vFlash SD card settings.

SWC0146.Message: Last ASR screen was cleared successfully

TST101.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC firmware.
TST101.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.

RAC1056.Description: The requested firmware Rollback operation was initiated successfully.

RAC0507.Description: The requested information cannot be displayed, because the system did not find any matching resource. This occurs because the system is turned off, resource is not present, or the resource is removed or deleted. For example, resources such as physicals disks, vFlash SD card, SSL certificate or custom signing certificate.
RAC0507.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Turn on the system. 2) Make the resource available.
RAC0507.Message: Unable to find the requested resource.

SWC0245.Description: Local configuration using RACADM is disabled. This limits local configuration privileges such as resetting object values.
SWC0245.Resolution: Within group cfgRacTuning set the property cfgRacTuneLocalConfigDisable to 0.
SWC0245.Message: Failed to set object value because local configuration using RACADM is disabled.

USR0183.Description: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature is detected.
USR0183.Message: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature is detected.

VDR15.Description: The initialization operation could not be completed. This may be due to a user action or a physical disk failure.
VDR15.Resolution: If a physical disk failed, then replace the physical disk. Restart the virtual disk initialization.

RAC1120.Description: The command could not be successfully run, because an incorrect Proxy type value was entered for the -pt option.
RAC1120.Resolution: Make sure that you entered either "http" or "https" as the proxy type. Enter the correct type, and then retry the operation.
RAC1120.Message: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Proxy type is entered.

SRV040.Description: The report size is more than the 30MB allowed size which will cause a truncated, partial report to be generated.
SRV040.Resolution: Delete older OS system log entries so that the final zip archive size can be reduced.
SRV040.Message: The OS Collector log file was truncated because the size of zip archive created by OS collector has exceeded the 30MB limit.

UEFI0154.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.
UEFI0154.Resolution: If the absence of license is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0154.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.

RAC0694.Description: Unable to configure the attributes of the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0694.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0694.Message: Unable to configure the attributes of the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

BAT1020.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1020.Message: The %1 battery is executing a learn cycle.

RAC1019.Description: Some objects have dependencies on other objects that are required to perform a task. The specified object is not available because of such dependencies.
RAC1019.Resolution: Verify the object dependency using "racadm help <device class>.<group name>.<object name>", and retry the operation. For example, racadm help NIC.VndrConfigGroup.1.VirtWWPN.
RAC1019.Message: The specified object is not supported for the current system configuration.

SWC8550.Description: An insufficient number of unused MAC addresses are available in the Virtual MAC Address database to capture the requested number of profiles.
SWC8550.Resolution: Add more MAC addresses to the Virtual MAC Address Pool and retry the capture Boot Identity profile operation. Using the CMC GUI, navigate to the Boot Identity page. More MAC addresses are added using "Add MAC Address" option provided in "Manage Virtual MAC Address Pool" section.
SWC8550.Message: Unable to capture the server profile because an insufficient number of unused Media Access Control (MAC) addresses in the Virtual MAC Address Pool.

PSU8508.Description: Unable to set the Power configuration because the PSU firmware update is in progress.
PSU8508.Resolution: Retry the operation after the PSU firmware update is completed.
PSU8508.Message: %1, PSU%2 firmware update is in progress.

SWC0213.Message: Disable the Virtual Console from a local Console

SWC0724.Description: Resetting to defaults did not complete within the maximum process allotted time.
SWC0724.Message: Error occurred while Resetting to defaults due to a timeout.

SYS278.Description: The factory-assigned MAC address of iDRAC is restored which may cause the iDRAC to restart in some situations. iDRAC is restarted by using a factory default MAC address that can potentially change the DHCP assigned iDRAC IP address.
SYS278.Resolution: No response action is required. However, if this message is displayed multiple times indicating that the MAC address of iDRAC is restored to factory default, contact your service provider.
SYS278.Message: The factory assigned MAC address of iDRAC is restored which may cause the iDRAC to restart in some situations.

RAC981.Description: A passphrase is required only for passphrase protected certificate, which is specified using the value of 3 for the -t option.
RAC981.Resolution: If the file being uploaded is passphrase protected, specify the file type as 3 using the -t option. If the file is not passphrase protected, retry the command, without specifying the -p option.
RAC981.Message: The type of certificate specified does not require a passphrase.

SWC8542.Description: The Profile identified in the message is exported.

VDR43.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR43.Message: Dedicated hot spare unassigned physical disk %1.

LC010.Description: The communications encryption certificate was imported successfully.

SRV130.Description: The iDRAC Service Module (iSM) running in Host Operating System (OS) is unable to allocate memory because of insufficient storage space in Host OS.
SRV130.Resolution: Make sure that there is storage space available in Host Operating System (OS) and then retry the operation.
SRV130.Message: The iDRAC Service Module (iSM) running in Host Operating System (OS) is unable to allocate memory because of insufficient storage space in Host OS.

DH006.Resolution: Validate that the certificate parameter matches the certificate contents; the certificate can be validated using OpenSSL tools.
DH006.Message: Not the right passphrase for the private key (need to re-write).

NIC023.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in iDRAC.
NIC023.Resolution: Retry the action. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
NIC023.Message: Cannot perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

RED042.Description: The necessary user access rights for performing the operation identified in the message are not available for the username used to access the iDRAC.
RED042.Resolution: Use a username that has the necessary access rights and retry the operation.
RED042.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was not created because the necessary user access rights are not available.

SRV011.Description: The SupportAssist Storage Controller Logs collection operation is completed.
SRV011.Message: The SupportAssist Storage Controller Logs collection operation is completed.

SYS074.Description: Unable to apply configuration changes because another configuration job is in progress.
SYS074.Resolution: Wait until the current configuration job is complete and retry the operation.
SYS074.Message: Unable to apply configuration changes because another configuration job is in progress.

PDR105.Description: The physical disk drive identified in the message is assigned as a dedicated hot-spare.
PDR105.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is assigned as a dedicated hot-spare.

RED102.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be downgraded because the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) does not allow the downgrade operation when the Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) mode is enabled.
RED102.Resolution: Disable the Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) mode, and then retry the operation. To downgrade by using Chassis Management Controller (CMC) graphical user interface (GUI), click Chassis Overview > Network > Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS), select "Disabled", and then click "Apply Changes". To downgrade by running RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), enter "racadm racresetcfg".
RED102.Message: Unable to downgrade the Chassis firmware because the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) does not allow the downgrade operation when the Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) mode is enabled.

OSD45.Description: The ISO Image present in vFlash is attached to the host system. The ISO Image cannot be deleted from vFlash.
OSD45.Message: Cannot delete ISO image from VFlash.

UEFI0289.Description: DDR memory initialization cannot be completed because no Dual Inline Memory Module's (DIMM's) are installed. Only processor embedded memory is available.
UEFI0289.Resolution: Populate Dual Inline Memory Module's (DIMM's) in a supported memory configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual available on the support site.
UEFI0289.Message: Unable to initialize DDR memory because no Dual Inline Memory Module's (DIMM's) are installed.

SWC8530.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to set the server administrator access to the iDRAC root user. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or the iDRAC is rebooting.
SWC8530.Resolution: If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8530.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to set administrator access to the iDRAC root user.

PWR8535.Description: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to disable.
PWR8535.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8535.Message: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to disable.

STOR102.Description: The operation cannot be performed because the HDDs have the RAID controller in mixed RAID mode.
STOR102.Resolution: Do the following to separate the mixed RAID mode and retry the operation. 1) Group the hard disk drives (HDDs) into to Windows and Linux metadata categories by observing the RAIDType property on the Physical Disk page of iDRAC graphical user interface (GUI). 2) Convert a group of selected HDDs to non-RAID mode by running the ConvertToNonRAID method or RACADM command, or by setting the RAIDPDState to NonRAID in the Server Configuration Profile.
STOR102.Message: Unable to start the operation because the hard disk drives (HDDs) have the RAID controller in mixed RAID mode.

PSU0041.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0041.Message: An output over voltage fault detected on power supply %1.

UEFI0019.Description: The system boot process did not complete repeatedly due to problems encountered while performing a Lifecycle Controller task for function. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0019.Resolution: Repair Lifecycle Controller firmware using the Lifecycle Controller Dell Update Package (DUP) or Lifecycle Controller Repair Package via iDRAC. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
UEFI0019.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) is unable to complete a requested task or function and prevented the boot process from completing on multiple attempts. LC is in Recovery Mode.

RAC0600.Description: Temperature information cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the server is powered off.
RAC0600.Resolution: Power on the server. If the server is already powered on, wait for a few minutes and refresh the page. If the problem persists, contact service provider.
RAC0600.Message: Unable to retrieve the temperature information.

SYS244.Description: The file cannot be transferred because a proxy workgroup value is not entered, or the entered value is not supported.
SYS244.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy workgroup value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS244.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported proxy workgroup value.

GMGR0039.Description: The operation cannot be completed because of an internal error or timeout connecting with the master.
GMGR0039.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC by using RACADM command line interface (CLI), enter "racadm racreset". To reset by using iDRAC graphical user interface (GUI), on the iDRAC homepage, click Maintenance > Diagnostics > Reset iDRAC.
GMGR0039.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of an internal error or timeout to connect with the group master.

UEFI0256.Description: Unable to allocate legacy I/O resources for one of more PCIe devices because the legacy I/O space limit was reached. The legacy I/O space limit is 64K.
UEFI0256.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Remove unused PCIe cards to free up legacy I/O space. 2) Go to System Setup and disable unused PCIe cards to free up legacy I/O space.
UEFI0256.Message: Unable to allocate legacy I/O resources for one of more PCIe devices because the legacy I/O space limit was reached.

RDU0018.Description: The storage system has multiple redundant power lines. One or more of these power lines is no longer available.
RDU0018.Resolution: Turn system off and remove AC input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. If the issue still persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
RDU0018.Message: The storage power redundancy is degraded.

CTL74.Description: The controller has preserved data in the cache from a virtual disk, which it can no longer locate. No data loss has occurred as the controller is saving these operations in its cache.
CTL74.Resolution: Check for the existence of a foreign configuration and import if any. Check that enclosures are cabled correctly.

RAC038.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in the iDRAC.
RAC038.Resolution: Retry the action. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
RAC038.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

SYS064.Description: The input file for the import configuration operation contains invalid XML data at the line specified.
SYS064.Resolution: Open the input file in any Web browser to check for invalid content before the expected root element. Correct the invalid content and make sure that the XML file is compliant to the system configuration schema before retrying the operation.
SYS064.Message: Input file for import configuration operation is invalid at line %1.

SWC0299.Description: The Email Address provided is invalid.
SWC0299.Message: The Destination Email Address is invalid.

UEFI0211.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Transmit Buffer Vref Training phase.
UEFI0211.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0211.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

FAN0030.Description: The configuration of fan identified in the message is not matching with the other fans in the server.
FAN0030.Resolution: Replace the fan with one that has similar configuration during the next scheduled service. For more information about recommended fan configurations, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
FAN0030.Message: The configuration of fan %1 is not matching with the other fans in the server.

UEFI0222.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Round Trip Training phase.
UEFI0222.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0222.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SYS266.Description: Unable to transfer a file because either an unsupported access type value is set or the value is not set at all.
SYS266.Resolution: Make sure that correct access type value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS266.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because either an unsupported access type value is set or the value is not set at all.

RED087.Description: Unable to update the Chassis firmware because the Allow CMC Updates Through OS and Lifecycle Controller setting is set to Disabled.
RED087.Resolution: Make sure that the Allow CHC Updates Through OS and Lifecycle Controller setting is set to Enabled, and then retry the operation. Using the iDRAC Web UI, select iDRAC > Update, click on the Settings tab, select Enabled for the setting and then click Apply button.
RED087.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware, Allow CMC Updates Through OS and Lifecycle Controller is set to Disabled.

PR11.Description: A valid license for this feature is not present.
PR11.Message: A required license for the Part Replacement feature is not present, replacement action(s) will not be performed.

SYS145.Description: vFlash SD Card data is deleted because of a System Erase operation.
SYS145.Message: vFlash SD Card data is deleted.

SEL1510.Description: Group master CMC could not log into the group member CMC.
SEL1510.Message: An authentication error detected for Chassis Group Member %1.

VDR7.Description: One or more physical disks included in the virtual disk have failed. If the virtual disk is non-redundant (does not use mirrored or parity data), then the failure of a single physical disk can cause the virtual disk to fail. If the virtual disk is redundant, then more physical disks have failed than you can rebuild using mirrored or parity information.
VDR7.Resolution: Create a new virtual disk and restore from a backup.

AMP0300.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0300.Message: The system board %1 current is less than the lower warning threshold.

JCP038.Description: The (installation or configuration) job identified in the message cannot be run. For more information, see the Job Queue.
JCP038.Resolution: Navigate to the Maintenance->overview->Lifecycle Log page in the iDRAC GUI. Look for logs with the prefix "RED" within the timeframe. Perform the recommended response action for these messages by referring to the error message guide.
JCP038.Message: Unable to run the (installation or configuration) job %1 because %2.

SWC0291.Description: Another object of the same value exists. Typically in the case of username.
SWC0291.Resolution: Change the specified value and re-try.
SWC0291.Message: Another object exists with the specified value. Duplicate values are not allowed for the requested object.

CPU0704.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.
CPU0704.Resolution: 1) Check system and operating system logs for exceptions. If no exceptions are found continue. 2) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 3) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 4) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

DIS011.Description: Customer provided client certificate is being used. Auto Discovery client is using this certificate for the SSL connection with the Provisioning Server.
DIS011.Message: Auto Discovery client using customer signed client certificate.

RED056.Description: An internal error occurred because of insufficient memory available on iDRAC.
RED056.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
RED056.Message: An internal error occurred. Unable to complete the specified operation.

PDR8.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

CPU0804.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0804.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0804.Message: The power input for CPU %1 voltage regulator module is outside of range.

SYS152.Description: Some of the requested storage component erase tasks were not successful. Retrying the System Erase operation may be required. The vFlash SD Card must be initialized and licensed to be erased successfully.
SYS152.Resolution: Retry the System Erase operation. To retry the System Erase operation using the Lifecycle Controller utility, restart the server and when the company logo is displayed, press <F10>. Select Hardware Configuration > Retire or Repurpose System, check appropriate storage options, and then retry the operation.
SYS152.Message: Erase operations for some System Erase tasks did not complete successfully.

VLT0213.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0213.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0213.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

RAC983.Description: The Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file is passphrase protected, and the passphrase provided is invalid.
RAC983.Resolution: Specify the correct passphrase for the file using -p option.
RAC983.Message: Invalid passphrase provided for the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file.

PWR2261.Description: The iDRAC experienced an issue initializing the Current Monitor. The system motherboard may need replacement.
PWR2261.Message: Current Monitor initialization issue observed, IMON Revision %1, CPLD IMON MFR Revision %2.

RAC0160.Description: Certificate upload failed because the certificate could not be validated.
RAC0160.Resolution: Certificate may be corrupt. Try creating a new Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and then upload the certificate.
RAC0160.Message: Certificate upload failed: Cannot validate the certificate.

SUP0118.Message: iDRAC reset failed. Please reset the iDRAC manually to complete the firmware rollback operation.

RAC1144.Description: No configuration results information is available for the job ID identified in the message because the job ID is invalid or is not present in the job queue and a related Lifecycle Log entry is not found.
RAC1144.Resolution: Check the job ID identified in the message and retry the operation with a valid job ID. To check valid job IDs in the current job queue, using RACADM, run the command "racadm jobqueue view".
RAC1144.Message: The Job: %1 is invalid or is not present in the job queue and a related Lifecycle Log entry is not found.

STOR054.Description: The controller or the firmware on the controller does not support the CacheCade feature.
STOR054.Resolution: Refer to the specific controller users guide for more information.

PDR87.Description: The physical device was reset. This is a normal part of operations and is not a cause for concern.

IOID005.Description: The Storage Initiator Persistence Policy setting is changed to the restart type identified in the message.
IOID005.Message: Storage Initiator Persistence Policy setting is changed to %1.

GMGR0032.Description: The iDRAC identified in the message is successfully removed from the Ignore list.
GMGR0032.Message: The iDRAC %1 is successfully removed from the Ignore list.

STOR311.Description: A drive firmware update was applied but requires a DC power cycle (cold boot) to activate. If the drive is internal to the system performing the update, no further action is required. If the drive is in an external enclosure, the enclosure must be turned off and then turned on in order for the updated drive firmware to activate.
STOR311.Resolution: If the drive is internal to the system performing the update, no further action is required. If the drive is in an external enclosure, the enclosure must be turned off and then turned on in order for the updated drive firmware to activate. After turning off the external enclosure, wait for drives to spin down before turning the enclosure back on. The drive firmware will activate after the enclosure is turned back on.
STOR311.Message: A firmware update was applied to a drive that requires a DC power cycle (cold boot). If the drive is in an external enclosure, the updated firmware will only be activated after a DC power cycle of the enclosure.

PCI2002.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI2002.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device.
PCI2002.Message: A fatal IO error detected on a component at slot %1.

SWC1924.Description: The server configuration cannot be modified by using Quick Sync because issues were found with the configuration information.
SWC1924.Resolution: Review the server configuration operation results and correct any issues detected, then retry the operation.
SWC1924.Message: Unable to modify the server configuration by using Quick Sync.

VFL0003.Description: The partition number identified in the message cannot be queried, because identified partition does not exist.
VFL0003.Resolution: Use a partition number of an existing partition for the requested operation.

SYS085.Message: Successfully exported the ePSA Diagnostics results.

VFL0705.Description: An error has occurred while initializing the SD card. The SD card is not present or vFlash is not enabled, or the SD card is write-protected.
VFL0705.Resolution: Re-insert the SD card, enable the SD card, or disable write-protection on the SD card. Then try to initialize the SD card again.
VFL0705.Message: Error occurred and SD card could not be initialized.

PWR8588.Description: The server identified in the message cannot be turned on while a chassis infrastructure firmware update operation is in progress.
PWR8588.Resolution: The chassis infrastructure firmware update is in progress. Retry the operation after the firmware update is complete.
PWR8588.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because a chassis infrastructure firmware update is in progress.

GMGR0011.Description: The Group Manager identified a Secondary Controller for the local group.
GMGR0011.Message: The Group Manager identified a Secondary Controller for the local group.

SWC0060.Description: One or more vFlash partitions are attached.
SWC0060.Resolution: Use iDRAC Web interface to detach the vFlash partitions and retry the operation.

RAC0748.Description: The BIOS watchdog must be disabled if Automatic System Recovery option is enabled.
RAC0748.Resolution: Make sure the BIOS watchdog timer is disabled before enabling the Automatic System Recovery option.
RAC0748.Message: The BIOS watchdog timer must be disabled if the Automatic System Recovery option is enabled.

STOR021.Description: Operation cannot be completed because a controller key is not present.
STOR021.Resolution: Set an appropriate controller key and retry the operation.
STOR021.Message: The controller key is not present.

IOV111.Description: Unable to successfully update Chassis Infrastructure firmware.
IOV111.Resolution: Refer to the release notes of the Mainboard update package for recommended action. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
IOV111.Message: Unable to update Chassis Infrastructure firmware.

RAC1118.Description: Successfully initiated the update operation specified in the command.
RAC1118.Resolution: To know about the status of a command that is initiated, run the following command:racadm jobqueue view -I <job ID>.
RAC1118.Message: Successfully initiated the update operation specified in the command.

PWR2252.Description: The server did not turn on because an NDC or Mezzanine card is incompatible with the I/O Module or PCIe subsystem.
PWR2252.Resolution: Check the release notes for the product and make sure to install compatible components in the server.
PWR2252.Message: Unable to turn on the server because an NDC or Mezzanine card is incompatible with the I/O Module or PCIe subsystem.

RAC0630.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested network file share type is not supported.
RAC0630.Resolution: Enter a correct network file share type, and then retry the operation.
RAC0630.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid network file share type is entered.

CTL100.Description: The Patrol Read operation running on the controller was stopped by user request or an issue was detected by the controller.
CTL100.Message: The Patrol Read operation was stopped and did not complete for %1.

GMGR0021.Description: The group job identified in the message is rerunning a failed operation on the basis of a user request.
GMGR0021.Message: The group job %1 of type %2 is rerunning a failed operation per user request.

SWC0220.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0220.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0220.Message: The -u option requires -c to also be specified.

MEM9006.Description: A non-recoverable link issue was detected in propagation of signals between processors through the Intel QPI interconnect interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9006.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the server and check whether the issue persists. 2) If the issue is not resolved by the preceding action, reseat the processors and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9006.Message: Intel QPI interconnect %1 has a non-recoverable issue.

SYS077.Description: Unable to perform the preview operation because the specified system configuration XML file does not exist on the remote share.
SYS077.Resolution: Make sure the configuration XML file to be previewed exists on the remote share before retrying the operation.
SYS077.Message: Unable to perform the preview operation because the specified file does not exist on the remote share.

SYS273.Description: The firmware version cannot be updated because of one or more missing firmware update prerequisites.
SYS273.Resolution: Make sure that the prerequisite firmwares are installed, and then retry updating the firmware. For information about prerequisite firmware, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS273.Message: Unable to update the firmware version because of one or more missing firmware update prerequisites.

SUP0504.Description: The catalog file in the update repository is not digitally signed.
SUP0504.Resolution: Use a repository that has the catalog file from a trusted source and retry the operation. If the catalog is from a trusted source, click OK to proceed without digital signature verification.
SUP0504.Message: Unable to authenticate the catalog file in the update repository.

PCI1348.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1348.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1348.Message: A PCI parity error was detected on a component at slot %1.

RAC1221.Description: The switch connection details cannot be retrieved because the switch connection view is disabled.
RAC1221.Resolution: Enable the switch connection view by running the following RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation: racadm set idrac.switchconnectionview.enable 1.
RAC1221.Message: Unable to retrieve the switch connection details because the switch connection view is disabled.

PWR8567.Description: Unable to turn off the Server on a power cycle operation. This happens if the Server did not show a "power off" status change within the expected time.
PWR8567.Resolution: The Server could have taken more time to turn off than expected. If the Server is turned off, turn on to complete the power cycle. If the Server has not completed a power cycle, retry the operation.
PWR8567.Message: Unable to turn off Server %1 on a power cycle action.

PWR2260.Description: The iDRAC experienced an IPMB communication issue with the Intel Management Engine and was not able to recover IPMB communications. The server thermal failsafe state is activated.
PWR2260.Resolution: Disconnect power from the server and reconnect power. Turn on the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR2260.Message: The Intel Management Engine is unresponsive and the server thermal failsafe state is activated.

SUP0513.Description: The specified filename path to the Update Package is incorrect.
SUP0513.Resolution: Enter the correct file path where the Update Package is located and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system and retry the operation.
SUP0513.Message: Unable to access the Update Package.

SWC0241.Description: To modify this property, set the Power Cap Enable option.
SWC0241.Resolution: Set the Power Cap Enable object and modify the required property.
SWC0241.Message: Power Cap Enable not set. Unable to modify this property.

STOR081.Description: The job could not be created because the reboot type selected for the job creation and the reboot type required for pending operations do not match.
STOR081.Resolution: Change the reboot type for job creation and retry the operation.
STOR081.Message: The job could not be created because the reboot type selected for the job creation and the reboot type required for pending operations do not match.

RAC920.Description: From firmware racadm, the inlet temperature history can be exported only to a remote file share.
RAC920.Resolution: Create a remote file share to export the inlet temperature history. Else, use remote/local racadm to export to the file system accessible by the racadm executable.
RAC920.Message: This interface does not support the specified option.

RAC006.Description: The attribute value cannot be changed because it is of read-only type.
RAC006.Message: The attribute value cannot be changed because it is of read-only type.

SYS003.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the operation are missing.
SYS003.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation and retry the operation with the required parameters.

RAC023.Description: Unable to enable the User or set values for IPMILan, IPMISerial, or User Admin Privilege because the User Password is not configured.
RAC023.Resolution: Set User Password before attempting to enable the other identified attributes.
RAC023.Message: Unable to enable the User or set values for IPMILan, IPMISerial, or User Admin Privilege because the User Password is not configured.

SSD0002.Description: The Available Spare of solid state drive identified in the message is less than the threshold value of 'Available Spare Alert'.
SSD0002.Resolution: Back up the data on the solid state drive (SSD), and then contact your service provider for more assistance.
SSD0002.Message: The Available Spare of solid state drive (SSD) %1 is less than the threshold value of 'Available Spare Alert'.

RAC961.Description: Another import operation cannot be started if an import operation that was performed earlier has some pending or committed configuration changes.
RAC961.Resolution: Wait until the configuration changes are applied before starting another import operation. Use the racadm jobqueue view command to check the status of the current import operation.
RAC961.Message: A pending or committed system configuration change exists.

STOR075.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because there is an operation pending to change the enclosure configuration mode (Split or Unified). This operation is exclusive because it involves changing the RAID backplane topology.
STOR075.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending enclosure mode change request operation, allow the job to complete, restart the server, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR075.Message: The operation cannot be performed because the enclosure configuration mode (Split or Unified) change request is pending.

PWR8534.Description: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to enable.
PWR8534.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8534.Message: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to enable.

AMP0315.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0315.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0315.Message: System level current is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PSU8511.Description: The firmware for the PSU identified in the message was successfully updated.
PSU8511.Message: Successfully updated the firmware for the PSU in slot %1.

SUP0121.Message: Firmware update in progress [%1 percent complete]

SWC0320.Description: Racadm tool failed to get the total number of records.
SWC0320.Message: Unable to get the number of records available.

MEM9033.Description: An unsupported Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device is of unsupported configuration and unable to operate as currently configured.
MEM9033.Resolution: Review the memory configuration and make sure the configuration is as per memory rules defined in the system Owner's Manual on the support site.
MEM9033.Message: An unsupported Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device is of unsupported configuration and unable to operate as currently configured.

TMP0130.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0130.Message: The control panel temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

SWC0253.Description: Unable to allocate memory to perform the operation, see the inserted comment.
SWC0253.Resolution: Power Cycle the system and re-enter the command.
SWC0253.Message: Unable to allocate memory needed to perform operation.

PWR8519.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned off.
PWR8519.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned off.

UEFI0264.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot because the iSCSI initiator name is invalid.
UEFI0264.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the iSCSI Initiator Name field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0264.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot because the iSCSI initiator name is invalid.

PST0013.Description: System extended memory test in progress.

RAC974.Description: The value specified for the wait time (w) option is invalid. The valid range is 300 to 3600 seconds.
RAC974.Resolution: Make sure to specify a valid wait time (-w) option and retry the command. The range of supported values are 300 to 3600 seconds.

USR0018.Description: There are no active sessions on the iDRAC which can be displayed.

JCP001.Description: The UEFI automated task related to the job was successfully scheduled.

PWR2404.Description: Power supply capacity alert disabled due to user configuration.

PDR59.Description: The disk has a bad block. Data was remapped to another disk block. No data loss has occurred.
PDR59.Resolution: Monitor the disk for other messages or indications of poor health.
PDR59.Message: A bad disk block was reassigned on %1.

LC005.Description: The value provided for the update mode parameter is invalid.
LC005.Resolution: Verify that the correct firmware update mode was entered. The choices are: 1) Disable (default) 2)Allow version upgrade only 3) Match firmware of replaced part.

STOR069.Description: The method name identified in the message could not be successfully completed, because the number of elements entered for VDPropNameArray and VDPropValueArray is not equal.
STOR069.Resolution: Enter equal number of elements (pair value), and then retry the operation.
STOR069.Message: Unable to run the %1 method, because the number of elements entered for VDPropNameArray and VDPropValueArray is unequal.

RAC0257.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the Alternate DNS IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0257.Resolution: Enter a valid Alternate DNS Server Address. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0257.Message: The Alternate DNS Server Address is invalid. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].

PSU0007.Description: A power supply that is designed to operate at 220V, but is connected to a 110V power source requires additional current for operation. The additional current may trip circuit-breakers or cause other electrical issues with the input source.
PSU0007.Resolution: Check input power source and cabling. Use recommended input power. Review the product documentation. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0007.Message: Power supply %1 is operating at 110 volts, and could cause a circuit breaker fault.

RAC1150.Description: The export operation did not be complete successfully.
RAC1150.Resolution: Retry the export operation after five minutes.
RAC1150.Message: Unable to complete the export operation.

VFL0016.Description: The requested vFlash media partition is already attached to the host operating system.
VFL0016.Message: vFlash media partition is already in attached state.

RAC1012.Description: Unable to change the auto-negotiation state for the current NIC selection mode, because the iDRAC NIC is in dedicated mode.
RAC1012.Resolution: Change the iDRAC NIC mode to shared mode using "racadm set idrac.nic.selection <value>", and retry the operation.
RAC1012.Message: Unable to change the auto-negotiation state for the current NIC selection mode.

BAR033.Description: A Lifecycle Controller internal data import operation did not complete successfully.
BAR033.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Download and apply the Dell Update Package for the Unified Server Configurator (USC). 2) Run System Services to update the database if CSIOR is not enabled. 3) Reboot the system and retry the operation. If these response actions do not resolve the issue, download the Field Service Repair software and repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download and install all the DUPs for USC, diagnostics, driver packs, and device firmware of all the devices of the host system.
BAR033.Message: Unable to Restore Lifecycle Controller data.

LC036.Description: The Lifecycle Controller has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E or F2 on boot up or through a remote command.
LC036.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations : Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

VFL0005.Description: There are no vFlash partitions available currently for the display.

SWC0262.Description: The IPMI drivers or the RAC controller may not be installed.
SWC0262.Resolution: Check if the required modules are installed.
SWC0262.Message: Unable to perform operation. Please make sure RAC controller and appropriate IPMI drivers are installed.

SEL1404.Message: A platform event trap (PET) was generated.

UEFI0033.Description: The NVRAM_CLR jumper is installed to clear the BIOS configuration. After clearing the BIOS configuration, remove the NVRAM_CLR jumper so that the system can function normally and any non-default BIOS system setting changes can be persistently saved.
UEFI0033.Resolution: To change the system BIOS settings and persistently save the settings, remove the NVRAM_CLR jumper and then go to the System Setup to configure system settings.
UEFI0033.Message: Default system BIOS settings are in use because NVRAM_CLR jumper is installed on the system board.

UEFI0130.Description: The system time and data are invalid.
UEFI0130.Resolution: Go to the System Setup to set the current time and date.
UEFI0130.Message: The system time and date are invalid.

SYS035.Description: The component configuration operation was completed, however some of the configuration values were not successfully applied.
SYS035.Resolution: Retrieve and view configuration operation results in the Lifecycle Log. For more information to retrieve the configuration results see the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services User's Guide. Identify the unsuccessful configuration operations. Modify the input data as appropriate for the component and retry the configuration operation.
SYS035.Message: Some configuration values were not applied to: %1

USR0033.Description: The IPMI over LAN login attempt was ended by the IPMI client before success or failure.
USR0033.Message: Login for %1 from %2 using %3 was incomplete.

BAR035.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) Configuration import did not complete successfully.
BAR035.Resolution: Manually reset the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) configuration.
BAR035.Message: Unable to Restore Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration.

RAC0689.Description: Unable to create a virtual disk on the selected disk drives, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0689.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0689.Message: Unable to create a virtual disk on the selected disk drives, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

PDR48.Description: This message is generated after rebuild resumes on a physical disk.

RAC0709.Resolution: Acquire the latest Chassis Management Controller (CMC) firmware that supports the server indicated and update the CMC to at least that version.

SWC4012.Description: The system has detected a firmware or software incompatibility between the components identified in the message. A mismatch between component versions may cause the system to not function appropriately.
SWC4012.Resolution: Update the firmware or software of the components identified in the message. For information about the identified components, see the product documentation available at the service provider support site.
SWC4012.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility is detected between %1%2 and %3%4.

SWC8537.Description: The add key operation did not complete successfully for the slot identified in the message due to the key being too long.
SWC8537.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8537.Message: Unable to add key for slot %1 of service account, due to the key being too long.

PDR86.Description: The number of blocks on the disk that exhibit an error has exceeded the capacity of the drive to remap. Any future writes to bad sectors will be unrecoverable.
PDR86.Message: Bad block table on %1 is full.

SWU8553.Description: The firmware update operation of Active CMC was not successful. The firmware Image file could not be accessed.
SWU8553.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware Image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8553.Message: Unable to update the Active CMC firmware. The Image file was not accessible.

PWR8591.Description: Before inserting hard disk drives, always make sure the Chassis has enough available power. Otherwise operating servers may be turned off.
PWR8591.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Go to, the Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field, view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis.
PWR8591.Message: Servers are turned off to allocate power to the newly inserted hard disk drives.

PSU8517.Description: The operation to change the PSU redundancy policy is complete.

RRDU0003.Description: Either one of the SD card or both the SD cards are not functioning properly.
RRDU0003.Message: Internal Dual SD Module redundancy is degraded.

MEM0003.Description: The memory is operational. This is an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0003.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0003.Message: Stuck bit memory error detected on a memory device at location %1.

BAT1018.Description: The temperature of the battery is high. This may be due to the battery being charged.
BAT1018.Resolution: If the battery is being charged, then charging the battery should be stopped until the battery cools down and charging should be resumed. If this is not case, then some other condition exists and should be investigated.

SWC0124.Description: The syntax of the sslcsrgen command is invalid.
SWC0124.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcsrgen subcommand.
SWC0124.Message: The -u option requires -f to be specified.

PCI3002.Description: Either the BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, LOM, or NIC firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3002.Resolution: Update BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, LOM, and mezzanine card firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3002.Message: Failed to program virtual MAC address on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

OSD19.Description: Failed to execute fork() system call to perform the task in a child process. iDRAC may be unresponsive.
OSD19.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD19.Message: The fork() command for a child process to perform the task failed.

TMP0202.Resolution: Check system operating environment, fans, and heatsinks.
TMP0202.Message: CPU %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

NIC501.Description: Autoconfig assigns values to the network components.
NIC501.Resolution: Disable Autoconfig and then modify the value.
NIC501.Message: The requested object is not allowed to be configured if Auto Config is enabled.

TMP0200.Message: CPU %1 temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

CTL80.Description: The controller identified in the message has an issue as displayed in the message.
CTL80.Resolution: To resolve this issue, see Troubleshooting section in the Dell Shared PowerEdge RAID Controller (SPERC8) documentation.
CTL80.Message: %1 experienced the following warning during startup: %2.

SRV050.Description: The Debug Logs collection operation is started for SupportAssist.
SRV050.Message: The Debug Logs collection operation is started for SupportAssist.

PDR63.Description: A write operation cannot complete because the disk contains bad disk blocks that could not be reassigned. Data loss may have occurred. Data redundancy may be lost.
PDR63.Message: A bad disk block on %1 cannot be reassigned during a write operation.

PWR8511.Description: Unable to set the CHASSIS_POWER_button_disable chassis power property.
PWR8511.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8511.Message: Unable to set the CHASSIS_POWER_button_disable chassis power property.

RAC0707.Description: Primary Firmware image is invalid. Currently booted from backup image. To restore primary image, update the firmware.
RAC0707.Resolution: Acquire an iDRAC firmware image of the version desired. Using the latest version available is recommended. Update the iDRAC firmware.
RAC0707.Message: Primary Firmware image is invalid. Currently booted from backup image. To restore primary image, update the firmware.

RAC1218.Description: The remote share cannot be mounted because incorrect remote share credentials are entered.
RAC1218.Resolution: Enter the correct remote share name, user name, and password. For more information, see the RACADM CLI Reference Guide available on the support site.
RAC1218.Message: Unable to mount the remote share because incorrect remote share credentials are entered.

SWC0267.Description: Unable to edit the SD card, since it is write protected.
SWC0267.Resolution: Check if the SD card is write protected. If yes, disable the write protection.
SWC0267.Message: Unable to perform the requested operation. Make sure a non write protected SD card is inserted.

PWR2265.Description: The power supply unit (PSU) identified in the message is disabled because of a configuration mismatch and therefore the PSU is not supported on the server.
