PWR2265.Resolution: Install a supported power supply unit (PSU). For information about supported PSUs, see the product documentation available on the support site.
PWR2265.Message: The power supply unit (PSU) %1 is disabled because of a configuration mismatch and therefore the PSU is not supported on the server.

UEFI0224.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Transmit Buffer Per Bit Deskew Training phase.
UEFI0224.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0224.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC0654.Description: Unable to perform operations on the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) because the iSM is not installed on the server operating system. All fields in the iDRAC GUI iSM page are disabled.
RAC0654.Resolution: Make sure that the iDRAC Service Module is installed on the server operating system, and then retry the operation.
RAC0654.Message: No operations can be performed on the iDRAC Service Module.

RAC0107.Description: Communication with the Smart Card reader is established and a Smart Card is inserted, but there are problems accessing the Smart Card. The appropriate Cryptographic Service Provider (CSP) drivers are not installed.
RAC0107.Resolution: There may be an issue with the Smart Card Cryptographic Service Provider (CSP) drivers. Use the client OS to install CSP driver. If the OS has problem with Smart Card, then there will have problem using the Smart Card. So make sure Smart Card can login with Windows OS.
RAC0107.Message: The inserted Smart Card cannot be recognized. Ensure that the correct Smart Card CSP drivers are installed.

UEFI0034.Description: A CMOS battery loss is detected resulting in an invalid BIOS configuration.
UEFI0034.Resolution: Go to the System Setup to configure system settings, system time and date.
UEFI0034.Message: A CMOS battery loss is detected resulting in an invalid BIOS configuration.

RDU0002.Description: One of more fans have failed or have been removed or a configuration change occurred which requires additional fans.
RDU0002.Resolution: Remove and re-install failed fans or install additional fans.

MEM1008.Message: Memory device at location %1 is offline.

OSD16.Description: Unable to mount the network share using the parameters specified in the command because either the IP address or share name is incorrect.
OSD16.Resolution: Rerun the command with the correct IP address and share name.
OSD16.Message: Mount network share failed - incorrect IP address or share name.

PCI5003.Description: A PCIe card carrier is removed from the PCIe slot identified in the message.
PCI5003.Message: A PCIe card carrier is removed from the PCIe slot%1 .

RAC0135.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while detaching the vFlash partition.
RAC0135.Message: An error has occurred while detaching a partition.

SYS044.Description: Unable to collect the configuration information for one or more components. An internal error occurred while processing component information.
SYS044.Resolution: Enable Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) using Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. Make sure that inventory collection is complete before retrying the operation. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
SYS044.Message: Unable to export one or more component configurations.

PWR8580.Description: The power on request for the server identified in the message was not successful because the Chassis is turned off.
PWR8580.Resolution: Turn on the Chassis, and then retry the operation. To turn on the Chassis using the Chassis Management Controller Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Control, select the Power On System option, and then click Apply.
PWR8580.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because the Chassis is not turned on.

VDR60.Description: There are two modes of virtual disk initialization, full and fast. This initialization type identified in the message is running on the virtual disk identified in the message.

PWR8664.Description: The power configuration property dynamic power supply engagement feature is disabled or enabled as identified in the message.
PWR8664.Message: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature is %1.

CBL8501.Description: The SAS cable identified in the message is not connected to the correct expander.
CBL8501.Resolution: Reconnect the SAS cable to the correct expander and retry the operation.
CBL8501.Message: SAS cable %1 is connected to the incorrect expander.

BIOS030.Description: The BIOS password cannot be configured because an Import Server Profile operation is already running.
BIOS030.Resolution: Wait until the current import operation is completed, and then retry the operation.
BIOS030.Message: Unable to change the BIOS password because an Import Server Profile operation is already running.

SWC8624.Description: The network communication session between CMC and I/O Aggregator (IOA) cannot be started because the IOA did not respond.
SWC8624.Resolution: Power-cycle the IOA and retry the operation.
SWC8624.Message: The network communication session between CMC and I/O Aggregator cannot be started on %1.

SYS022.Description: The operation could not complete because of an internal resource allocation issue with the firmware.
SYS022.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.

RAC0912.Description: The management system could not connect to the iDRAC.
RAC0912.Resolution: Verify whether the IP address of the remote iDRAC is correct. Verify whether connectivity exists between the management system and the iDRAC.
RAC0912.Message: Unable to connect to RAC at specified IP address.

UEFI0236.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - FIFO Reset phase.
UEFI0236.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0236.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

BAR027.Description: The component restoration on the host system is complete. The Host System will shutdown.
BAR027.Message: Host System Component Restore complete, shutting down Host System.

UEFI0178.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Read DQ/DQS error was detected.
UEFI0178.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0178.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

RAC0103.Description: Smart Card login is only supported in newer versions of Internet Explorer.
RAC0103.Resolution: See the iDRAC help text or documentation for a list of supported browsers.
RAC0103.Message: This browser does not support Smart Card logon on iDRAC. Use Internet Explorer version 7.0 or later to use this feature.

PWR8543.Description: Invalid power inventory reported by the iDRAC of the server identified in the message to the CMC.
PWR8543.Resolution: Turn on the server identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8543.Message: Server %1 power inventory is not valid. Power inventory reading is Max Power=%2 AC Watt, Min Power=%3 AC Watt, Allocated Power=%4 AC Watt.

SRV093.Description: The SupportAssist Collection identified in the message is successfully uploaded to SupportAssist server.
SRV093.Message: The SupportAssist Collection %1 is successfully uploaded to SupportAssist server.

HWC5036.Description: The IOM module performance may be impact.
HWC5036.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
HWC5036.Message: A failure is detected on IO module %1.

LIC015.Description: This error occurs when the Lifecycle Controller restore operation is interrupted before it completes. This can occur due to a power outage or when a system is rebooted before the operation is completed.
LIC015.Resolution: Repeat the Lifecycle Controller restore operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC015.Message: The License Manager database restore operation failed.

STOR305.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the preserved cache is present on the controller.
STOR305.Resolution: To recover the data preserved in pinned cache do one of the following 1) Try importing foreign drives, if any. 2) Make sure that the enclosure containing the virtual drive is connected to the controller. 3) Install any drives that are reported as missed or failed. Pinned cache can be discarded if data saved in controller pinned cache is not required. For more information about managing preserve cache, refer to the PERC User's Guide available on the support site.
STOR305.Message: Unable to complete the operation because preserved cache is present on the controller.

RAC0513.Description: There are no virtual disks to be displayed. There may be no virtual disks created, the controller(s) may not be in RAID mode, or there may be pending creation or deletion jobs that have not completed.
RAC0513.Resolution: Check the following: 1) Check if the server is turned off. If the server is turned off, turn it on and wait until POST completes. 2) If no virtual disks are created, to start the virtual disk creation process, click #{create_virtualdisk_link}. 3) If create virtual disk operation(s) are in a pending state, complete the creation process. To complete the virtual disk(s) creation, go to the Pending Operations page and create a configuration job on the appropriate controller. 4) If delete virtual disk operation(s) are in pending state, then cancel the operation. To cancel delete virtual disk pending operation(s), go to the Pending Operations page and delete all pending operation(s) on the appropriate controller. 5) If the Controller(s) are in HBA mode, switch the controller(s) to RAID mode. To switch controller(s) to RAID mode using the F2 System Setup utility, go to Device Settings > RAID Controller > Controller Management > Advanced Controller Management > Switch to RAID mode.
RAC0513.Message: There are no virtual disks to be displayed.

BAR020.Description: The Lifecycle Controller data is being imported from the backup file.

BAT1004.Description: The controller battery must be fully charged before the learn cycle can begin. The battery may be unable to maintain a full charge causing the learn cycle to timeout. In addition, the battery must be able to maintain cached data for a specified period of time in the event of a power loss. For example, some batteries maintain cached data for 24 hours. If the battery is unable to maintain cached data for the required period of time, then the Learn cycle will timeout.
BAT1004.Resolution: Replace the battery pack. The battery is unable to maintain a full charge.
BAT1004.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has timed out.

TMP1004.Description: The enclosure temperature sensor identified in the message is operating within the upper and lower configured temperature thresholds.
TMP1004.Message: The temperature sensor %1 is now within configured threshold values.

PDR53.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR53.Message: A redundant path has been restored for %1.

SWC8508.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required.
SWC8508.Message: Unable to capture Profile from server in slot %1

SUP0102.Description: The TFTP IP Address specified is invalid.
SUP0102.Resolution: Specify a valid TFTP IP Address.

UEFI0105.Description: The Cluster on Die (COD) feature cannot be enabled because of an unsupported memory configuration.
UEFI0105.Resolution: Make sure to populate all memory channels in the system with a minimum of one DIMM per channel. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0105.Message: Unable to enable the Cluster on Die (COD) feature because of an unsupported memory configuration.

SEC0613.Description: The default username and password is changed.
SEC0613.Message: The default username and password is changed.

SRV107.Description: The Storage Logs are excluded from the SupportAssist collection because the Collection data is being filtered for personally identifiable information.
SRV107.Message: The Storage Logs are excluded from the SupportAssist collection because the Collection data is being filtered for personally identifiable information.

RAC0120.Description: Requested partition size exceeds the available space.
RAC0120.Resolution: Enter a partition size smaller than the unused space on the vFlash SD card.
RAC0120.Message: The selected partition size exceeds the available space.

SWC8618.Description: The request for the WS-Man method identified in the message for server in slot identified slot is unsuccessful.
SWC8618.Resolution: Make sure that iDRAC is ready and system is functioning correctly. run the RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure that the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required.
SWC8618.Message: Server Profiles: request %1 for server in slot %2 was unsuccessful. Message ID %3. Returned fault: %4.

RAC0211.Description: Firmware update has failed. This may be due to a corrupt firmware image, poor network connection, or another issue.
RAC0211.Resolution: Download a new firmware image and try loading the firmware again.

GMGR0008.Description: The iDRAC having the Service Tag identified in the message has been successfully removed from the local iDRAC group identified in the message.
GMGR0008.Message: The server %1 is successfully removed from the group %2 by the Group Manager administrator.

SYS426.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the value entered for the property identified in the message is not in the enumeration list.
SYS426.Resolution: Enter a valid value from the enumeration list that Redfish service supports and retry the operation.For information about valid values, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS426.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the value %1 entered for the property %2 is not in the list of acceptable values.

RAC0209.Description: Certificate upload failed because iDRAC unable to upload at this time.
RAC0209.Resolution: Try the operation again in a few minutes.
RAC0209.Message: Certificate upload failed: iDRAC unable to upload at this time.

RAC1183.Description: The IP addresses 169.254.0.3 and 169.254.0.4 cannot be assigned to the device identified in the message because the IP addresses entered are reserved for the iDRAC Direct feature.
RAC1183.Resolution: Enter another appropriate IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC1183.Message: Unable to assign IP addresses 169.254.0.3 and 169.254.0.4 to the device OSBMC USBNIC because the IP addresses entered are reserved for the iDRAC Direct feature.

SWC0322.Description: The starting record value has to be lesser than the number of records available.
SWC0322.Resolution: Get the number of records available, and then run the command. If the command is gettracelog, try executing the command again.
SWC0322.Message: Starting record specified exceeds number of records available.

RED058.Description: A repository update job with the job ID identified in the message was created.
RED058.Message: A repository update job %1 was created.

SWC0075.Description: Unable to perform RAID operations because the selected controller is in HBA mode.
SWC0075.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation using other controllers that support RAID operations and are not in HBA mode. 2) Change the mode of the controller from HBA mode to RAID mode and retry the operation.
SWC0075.Message: Unable to perform RAID operations because the selected controller is in HBA mode.

PSU0033.Resolution: Check the system operating environment, including airflow and inlet temperature. Check system logs for temperature and thermal component failures.
PSU0033.Message: The temperature for power supply %1 is outside of range.

RAC965.Description: Any operation involving remote share (CIFS) cannot continue if the location (-l) is not specified. The u and p options represent the user name and password for the remote share, and -l represents the location of the remote share.
RAC965.Resolution: Make sure to specify the location (-l) of the remote share along with the user name and password, and retry the operation. To view the list of options that can used for the required subcommand, use the racadm help <subcommand> command.
RAC965.Message: The -l option must be specified if -u and -p are used.

LIC016.Description: The license includes features that are dependent upon additional licensed features not included in this license. These licensed features are not activated until license(s) with the dependent licensed features are imported to the system.
LIC016.Resolution: Import the license(s) that meet the license features dependencies.
LIC016.Message: The feature dependencies of the license are not met.

RAC1001.Description: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 DNS1 or DNS2, because the object DNSFromDHCP6 is enabled.
RAC1001.Resolution: Disable the object DNSFromDHCP6 using "racadm set iDRAC.IPv6.DNSFromDHCP6 <0 | Disabled>", and retry the operation.
RAC1001.Message: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 DNS1 or DNS2.

DIS120.Description: The AutoConfig import operation cannot be started because the AutoConfig import file is not available in the sharename or location specified in DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS120.Resolution: Update the sharename or location in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC, make sure the AutoConfig import file is available, and then retry the operation.
DIS120.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig import operation because the AutoConfig import file, %1, is not available.

DIS001.Description: Auto Discovery starts automatically, but was unable to find a valid license. Once you have obtained a valid license and installed it, restart.
DIS001.Resolution: Follow service providers instructions to enable the license.

USR0210.Description: Server information has been accessed by using the Quick Sync feature.
USR0210.Message: Server information has been accessed by using the Quick Sync feature.

PDR79.Description: A user aborted an ongoing copyback operation. The operation did not complete.
PDR79.Message: A user terminated Copyback from %1 to %1.

SWC9013.Description: The Secure Boot Certificate Import operation cannot be completed because the file size being imported is greater than the maximum file size allowed for importing.
SWC9013.Resolution: Import the file by using the BIOS System Setup page by pressing F2 when the company logo is displayed while booting the server. For information about the maximum file size allowed, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SWC9013.Message: Unable to complete the Secure Boot Certificate Import operation because the file size being imported is greater than the maximum file size allowed for importing.

RAC968.Description: The configuration XML file cannot be imported from a client location when using Firmware RACADM.
RAC968.Resolution: When using Firmware RACADM, make sure to import the configuration XML file from a remote share only.
RAC968.Message: Importing the configuration XML file from a local share is not supported when using Firmware RACADM.

SEC0701.Description: This warning message is displayed when using the default username and password (root and calvin). Using the default password causes a severe security risk for iDRAC.
SEC0701.Resolution: To change the password, run the following racadm commands: racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.Password <new password string>.Alternatively, to avoid this warning message run the following racadm command: racadm set iDRAC.Tuning.DefaultCredentialWarning Disable.
SEC0701.Message: Warning: Default username and password are currently in use. It is strongly recommended to change the default password immediately.

SWC0133.Resolution: Specify either the connect or the disconnect option with the subcommand.

BAT0002.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0002.Message: The system board battery has failed.

CTL126.Description: The firmware version of the RAID controller identified in the message cannot be updated because the firmware image file is not signed and certified by an authorized source.
CTL126.Resolution: Download the correct firmware image file and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CTL126.Message: Unable to update the RAID controller %1 firmware version because the firmware image file is not signed and certified by an authorized source.

SWC0270.Description: Local Configuration using RACADM may be disabled.
SWC0270.Resolution: Check if the Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled and enable it through GUI.
SWC0270.Message: Unable to clear the SEL. Possible reason may be that Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled.

PSU0802.Description: The power supply redundancy policy on the system has been set.
PSU0802.Message: The power supply redundancy policy on the system has been set to %1.

VLT0204.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0204.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0204.Message: The system board %1 voltage is outside of range.

LIC005.Description: The maximum number of installed licenses has been reached.
LIC005.Resolution: Delete one of the currently installed licenses and retry the import.
LIC005.Message: Import failed: The maximum number of licenses are installed.

RAC1202.Description: The Secure Boot Certificate is successfully exported.
RAC1202.Message: The Secure Boot Certificate is successfully exported.

SWU8538.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation was not successful.
SWU8538.Resolution: Retry the Update operation. If the issue persists, reinsert the iKVM and retry the operation.
SWU8538.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware. Reason = 0x%1.

MEM1205.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed.
MEM1205.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>.
MEM1205.Message: Memory mirror redundancy is lost. Check memory device at location(s) %1.

SYS017.Description: The job did not complete successfully.
SYS017.Resolution: Verify the reason for the unsuccessful completion of the job by inspecting the Lifecycle Log entries related to the job. Correct the underlying cause of the unsuccessful completion and retry the operation.

PSU0040.Description: The power supply output voltage is insufficient to keep system operating at a normal levels.
PSU0040.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0040.Message: An output under voltage fault detected on power supply %1.

PST0088.Description: System BIOS is preparing to boot the system.

HWC6002.Description: Information and status from the controller is unavailable.
HWC6002.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
HWC6002.Message: The %1 controller is stuck in boot mode.

SEL9902.Description: Software on the system has logged an event that cannot be determined. You may need to review this event using a tool which displays raw data such as Ipmitool with the -vvv option or Racadm with the -E option.

UEFI0122.Description: The secondary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.
UEFI0122.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Install a SD card media in the secondary SD card slot. 2) Reseat or replace the SD card media. 3) If the secondary SD card is intentionally not installed or write-protected mode is expected, then no response action is required.
UEFI0122.Message: The secondary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.

POW005.Description: Host failed to power up because CMC MPCM mode is enabled. This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2255.
POW005.Resolution: Disable MPCM mode to power up.
POW005.Message: Power on permission error, CMC is in MPCM mode.

RAC0608.Description: The message appears in Job Queue page when the iDRAC firmware update job status is downloading. Communication to the iDRAC will be lost when the iDRAC restarts to complete the firmware update.
RAC0608.Resolution: Reconnect iDRAC communications session after iDRAC is restarted. The iDRAC will be ready for login once the restart is complete.
RAC0608.Message: The iDRAC will restart when the iDRAC firmware update is complete. All current user sessions will be closed.

PDR20.Description: A disk has received a SMART alert (predictive failure) after a configuration change. The disk is likely to fail in the near future.
PDR20.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk will cause the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.

MEM1009.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to transition to offline.

STOR007.Description: The operation could not be completed because of insufficient memory space on the management controller (either the iDRAC or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC)) managing the storage.
STOR007.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

VDR40.Description: This message is generated after the reconfiguration of a virtual disk resumes.

RAC0230.Description: This message is displayed when a confirmation is required to initialize the vFlash SD Card.
RAC0230.Resolution: Press OK to initialize the SD Card. This will erase all data. If undesired press Cancel.
RAC0230.Message: This operation erases all data in the SD Card. Do you want to continue?

SWC0229.Description: Insufficient arguments passed to the command.
SWC0229.Resolution: Refer the help text for vflashpartition command.
SWC0229.Message: Some Necessary tag(s) are missing: -i -o -e -t -f & -s must be specified for create partition.

RAC0661.Description: Various storage configuration operations can be performed on different devices such as physical disks, virtual disks, controllers, or enclosures. The operations are applied to the device by creating a configuration job on the associated controller.
RAC0661.Resolution: To complete the storage configuration operation, create a storage configuration job with the necessary scheduling.
RAC0661.Message: Storage configuration operation - #(operation) is pending on the selected #{devicetype} : #{devicename}.

SWC0046.Description: Unable to initiate Import operation since another Import operation is already in progress.
SWC0046.Resolution: Wait until current Import operation is complete before initiating a new Import operation.

PWR8533.Message: Power cap changed from %1 W AC to %1 W AC.

UEFI0062.Description: One or more attributes were successfully changed.
UEFI0062.Message: One or more attributes are successfully changed.

RAC0130.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while creating the vFlash partition.
RAC0130.Message: An error has occurred while creating a partition.

PDR1.Description: This message is generated after a copyback stops on a physical disk during a rebuild operation.
PDR1.Resolution: Wait for rebuild to finish, then copyback should resume.

STOR0501.Description: Unable to create a virtual disk due to unknown reasons.
STOR0501.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation:1) Exit the RAID Configuration wizard.2) Update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version.3) Reboot the system and press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.

PWR8530.Description: Max Power Conservation Mode is disabled.
PWR8530.Message: Max Power Conservation Mode is disabled.

RAC1157.Resolution: Verify whether or not the entered FQDD is valid. Run the command 'racadm gethostnetworkinterfaces' for the list of valid FQDDs.
RAC1157.Message: Unable to find the specified FQDD.

LC090.Description: The iDRAC cannot be registered to SupportAssist because the length of parameter entered is less than the stipulated length as identified in the message.
LC090.Resolution: Make sure that the parameter length is more than or equal to minimum allowed length and retry the operation. For information about specified parameter length, see the SupportAssist documentation on DellTechCenter.
LC090.Message: Unable to register iDRAC to SupportAssist because the length of parameter %1 entered is less than the stipulated length %2.

RAC1130.Description: The requested operation could not be successfully completed because of an unsupported version of BIOS, USC, and/or iDRAC firmware.
RAC1130.Resolution: Verify whether or not a correct version of BIOS, Lifecycle Controller, and/or iDRAC firmware is installed. For more information on the appropriate firmware version required, refer to the RACADM Command Line Reference Guide. Also check if there is a limitation in terms of platforms such as monolithic or modular, and then retry the operation.
RAC1130.Message: Unable to complete the operation. This feature is not supported on the currently-used platform.

PWR8584.Description: If power redundancy is lost and the server Performance Over Power Redundancy feature is disabled, the server turn-on will not be allowed.
PWR8584.Resolution: To enable the server to be turned-on, on the Power Configuration page in the Web UI, enable the server Performance Over Power Redundancy option . Using the RACADM utility, run the following command "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPerformanceOverRedundancy 1". Then retry the operation.
PWR8584.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because the power supply redundancy is lost and Performance Over Power Redundancy feature is disabled and the power required is less than the available power.

PWR8596.Description: The Chassis Management Controller cannot turn on the server identified in the message, because PSU redundancy is lost or PSUs are removed. Sufficient power is not available for the operation.
PWR8596.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Go to, the Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field, view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis. When enough power is available, retry the operation.
PWR8596.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because PSU redundancy is lost and the available power is insufficient.

SYS023.Description: There are no pending values to change.
SYS023.Resolution: Ensure there are pending values for the attributes that need to be set and retry the operation.

UEFI0143.Resolution: Replace the processor(s) with supported ones. For more information about supported processors, contact your service provider.

BAR050.Description: The firmware update for the specified device in progress.

SYS189.Description: There is no cached copy of OS and Application data in the iDRAC flash storage.
SYS189.Resolution: Collect the OS and Application Data either manually or automatically using the iDRAC Services Module (ISM) tools and then retry the operation.
SYS189.Message: Cached OS and Application Data is not available in the iDRAC.

RAC0772.Description: The BIOS configuration settings cannot be modified because the Lifecycle Controller or Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR), or both the features are disabled.
RAC0772.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller and Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) features, and then retry the operation. To enable these features: Press F2(System Setup) when the company logo is displayed. On the System Setup page, click iDRAC Settings > Lifecycle Controller. Select Enabled corresponding to Lifecycle Controller and CSIOR.
RAC0772.Message: Unable to modify the BIOS configuration settings because the Lifecycle Controller or Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR), or both the features are disabled.

RAC017.Description: The requested job has been created.
RAC017.Message: Job created to apply the attribute value.

UEFI0127.Description: The secondary SD card is write-protected mode.
UEFI0127.Resolution: No response action is required if this is intentional.
UEFI0127.Message: The secondary SD card is in write-protected mode.

UEFI0288.Description: The Memory Multi-rank Sparing feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.
UEFI0288.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure Memory Multi-rank Sparing feature can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0288.Message: Unable to enable the Memory Multi-rank Sparing feature because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.

SYS144.Description: Starting controller hardware cache data erase operations because of a System Erase operation request.
SYS144.Message: Starting controller hardware cache data erase operations.

SRV007.Description: The SupportAssist System information collection operation is successfully completed.
SRV007.Message: The SupportAssist System information collection operation is successfully completed.

SYS261.Description: The file cannot be transferred because initial network connection to the remote host server is not successfully started. The other probable reasons are: 1) issue in the network 2) remote host server is not turned on 3) remote host server is turned on but not functioning 4) issue in protocol negotiation.
SYS261.Resolution: Check the file transfer parameters, health of the remote host, and then retry the operation.
SYS261.Message: Unable to transfer the file, %1, because initial network connection to the remote host server is not successfully started.

CMC8519.Description: FRU of the LOM riser specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8519.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8519.Message: The LOM riser FRU for slot %1 FRU ID %2 is not functioning.

SUP025.Description: Generic message to show that last command was successful.

PCI1302.Description: System performance may be degraded. The device has failed to respond to a transaction (master/target abort or completion timeout).
PCI1302.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1302.Message: A bus time-out was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

PDR85.Description: Errors were detected with security related operations on the disk. The data on the disk might not be retrieved or stored successfully. In addition, the security of the stored data might be at risk.
PDR85.Resolution: Verify the disk is a Secure Encrypted Disk and is not locked. If it is not, replace the disk with a Secure Encrypted Disk. See the storage hardware documentation for more information.

LC012.Description: Lifecycle Controller is in use by another process. Wait for other process to complete before attempting to run another command.
LC012.Resolution: Try one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes. 2) Make sure that Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator or an Update Package is not currently running on the server 3) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
LC012.Message: Another process is using Lifecycle Controller.

PSU0043.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0043.Message: An output under current fault detected on power supply %1.

BAT0006.Message: The storage battery is operating normally.

UEFI0310.Description: The Baseboard UPI B cable connection is misconfigured.
UEFI0310.Resolution: Connect the Baseboard UPI B cable. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0310.Message: The Baseboard UPI B cable connection is misconfigured.

UEFI0081.Description: Memory size has changed from the last time the system was started. No action is required if memory was added or removed.
UEFI0081.Resolution: If the change is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise, check the DIMM population inside the system and memory settings in System Setup for configuration changes. For more information, see the platform Owners Manual.
UEFI0081.Message: Memory size has changed from the last time the system was started.

RAC0263.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the Alternate IPv6 DNS Server address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0263.Resolution: Enter a valid Alternate IPv6 DNS server address.
RAC0263.Message: The Alternate IPv6 DNS Server Address is invalid.

SYS427.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the property identified in the message is a read only property.
SYS427.Resolution: Remove the property from the request body and retry the operation.
SYS427.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the property %1 is a read only property and cannot be assigned a value.

PST0083.Description: System is at the BIOS Boot Menu.

USR103.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the operation are missing.
USR103.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation and provide the required parameters.

SYS243.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported proxy port number value.
SYS243.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy port number value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS243.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported proxy port number value, %2.

RAC083.Description: The file cannot be imported because the chunk size value entered is greater than the import file size.
RAC083.Resolution: Make sure that chunk size entered is less than import file size, and then retry the operation.
RAC083.Message: Unable to import the file because the chunk size value entered is greater than the import file size.

PWR8537.Description: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is disabled.
PWR8537.Message: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is disabled.

VME0003.Description: Virtual Console session fails to start.
VME0003.Resolution: Retry the Virtual Console session initiation.
VME0003.Message: Virtual Console session fails to start.

DIS118.Description: The AutoConfig operation cannot be completed because the flag identified in the message is not recognized, which is causing a syntax error.
DIS118.Resolution: Enter an appropriate flag and retry the operation. For example, -u is a flag indicating the username that has access to network share of CIFS type. For a list of recommended flags, see the Zero-Touch Bare Metal Server Provisioning using Dell iDRAC with Lifecycle Controller Auto Config white paper available at Dell TechCenter.
DIS118.Message: Unable to complete the AutoConfig operation because the flag %1 is not recognized, which is causing a syntax error.

GMGR0042.Description: The group job identified in the message cannot be started because the operation is not supported.
GMGR0042.Message: Unable to start the requested operation on the group job %1 of type %2 because the operation is not supported.

RAC060.Description: The attribute identified in the message could not be set, because certain features cannot be enabled when OMSA is installed on the server.
RAC060.Resolution: Uninstall OMSA, and then retry the operation.
RAC060.Message: Unable to set the attribute because OpenManage Server Administrator (OMSA) is installed on the server %1

GMGR0063.Description: The iDRAC Group Manager feature is disabled. iDRAC will no longer be able to create or join or maintain iDRAC local groups. However, all the earlier settings of Group Manager are preserved. To enable the Group Manager, log in to iDRAC. On the Dashboard page, click Enable Group Manager.
GMGR0063.Resolution: Enable the iDRAC Group Manager feature and retry the operation. To enable the Group Manager, log in to iDRAC. On the Dashboard page, click Enable Group Manager.
GMGR0063.Message: Unable to complete the requested operation because the iDRAC Group Manager feature is disabled.

CTL38.Message: The Patrol Read operation completed for %1.

RED003.Resolution: Schedule the job if it is not already scheduled.

BAR070.Description: Access to the NFS export/import destination is not possible or has been denied.
BAR070.Resolution: Verify that the input parameters are correct, connectivity exists to the destination end point, and retry the operation.

PSU0039.Description: Insufficient amount of current to keep power supply operating at a normal levels.
PSU0039.Resolution: 1) Remove and re-install the power supply input cord. 2) Check power distribution or PSU input source for anomalies. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0039.Message: An under current fault detected on power supply %1.

BAR066.Description: The system profile export destination is not enabled.
BAR066.Resolution: Enable the vFlash media and retry the operation.

GMGR0070.Description: The server with the Service Tag identified in the message is unable to leave the local group either because the iDRAC is not part of the group or there are issues in the network connection.
GMGR0070.Resolution: Do any one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Enter the correct group name. 2) Verify the network cabling connections.
GMGR0070.Message: The server with the Service Tag %1 is unable to leave the local group %2 either because the iDRAC is not part of the group or there are issues in the network connection.

SRV085.Description: The operation cannot be started because the SupportAssist end user license agreement (EULA) is not accepted.
SRV085.Resolution: Accept the SupportAssist End User License Agreement (EULA) by navigating to the SupportAssist page on the iDRAC GUI.
SRV085.Message: Unable to start the operation because the SupportAssist End User License Agreement (EULA) is not accepted.

PWR8559.Description: Power cycle initiated for the I/O module in the slot identified in the message.
PWR8559.Message: Power cycle initiated for I/O Module %1.

TMP0302.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature cannot be enabled because the necessary power or fan configuration is not available.
TMP0302.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the available power and the fan configuration. 2) If the required power for Enhanced Cooling mode is not available, remove other chassis components which are not being used in order to obtain sufficient power. 3) If the fan configuration does not support Enhanced Cooling Mode, replace unsupported fans with supported ones. 4) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
TMP0302.Message: Unable to set Enhanced Cooling Mode because the required power or fan configuration is not available.

RAC0181.Description: The iDRAC recovered from a firmware Bootloader error that occurred because of the reason identified in the message.
RAC0181.Message: The iDRAC recovered from a firmware boot loader error with the following reason : %1.

SYS163.Description: The iDRAC environment has changed and the iDRAC must be restarted to apply the changes requested. Normal operation will return after the restart has completed. One exception is, the iDRAC has been reset to its default settings. In this case additional setup is required to use the iDRAC. For more information, see the iDRAC User's Guide.
SYS163.Message: The iDRAC is restarting to complete the System Erase operation. Do not restart server until the iDRAC restarts.

RRDU0001.Message: Internal Dual SD Module is redundant.

RAC0631.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid network file share name is entered.
RAC0631.Resolution: Enter a valid network file share name, and then retry the operation.
RAC0631.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid network file share name is entered.

ENC32.Description: The SEP has been rebooted as part of the firmware download operation and will be unavailable until the operation completes.
ENC32.Message: Storage Enclosure Processor (SEP) for %1 has been rebooted.

OSD52.Resolution: Enable the vFlash from the iDRAC GUI or RACADM, and then proceed.

TMP1000.Description: The enclosure is too hot. A variety of factors can cause the excessive temperature. For example, a fan may have failed, the thermostat may be set too high, or the room temperature may be too hot.
TMP1000.Resolution: Check for factors that may cause overheating. For example, verify that the enclosure fan is working. You should check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source. Make sure the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information.

BAR117.Description: The firmware version for the iDRAC contained in the hardware Server Profile image is not compatible with this system hardware. Continue to use the installed firmware version or update to later versions if necessary.
BAR117.Message: The iDRAC firmware cannot be restored due to hardware compatibility restraints.

BIOS016.Description: A set attribute operation was attempted on a disabled attribute.
BIOS016.Message: AttributeValue cannot be changed for disabled AttributeName %1.

USR0181.Description: The Quick Sync feature is deactivated because the inactivity timeout limit was reached.
USR0181.Resolution: Press the activate button on the bezel to activate the iDRAC Quick Sync feature.
USR0181.Message: The Quick Sync feature is deactivated because the inactivity timeout limit was reached.

RAC0171.Description: Certificate upload failed because the certificate has expired.
RAC0171.Resolution: Certificate has expired. Try creating a new Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and then upload the certificate.
RAC0171.Message: Certificate upload failed: Certificate has expired.

RDU8511.Description: For failover, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same firmware version as the primary CMC and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC does not meet this criteria.
RDU8511.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8511.Message: Unable to failover, CMC%1 in unknown state.

STOR11.Description: The current hardware configuration is setup correctly for High Availability. However, the current firmware does not provide this functionality and one of the cards will be kept in a powered down state until High Availability capable firmware is installed.
STOR11.Message: The currently detected hardware configuration is High Availability Ready. However, the current software solution does not yet support high availability.

IOID112.Description: The initiator properties of the NIC port identified in the message are successfully configured.
IOID112.Message: The initiator properties of the %1 Port %2 are successfully configured.

BAR096.Description: The current BIOS firmware installed on the system does not have Backup and Restore feature support.
BAR096.Resolution: Obtain the System BIOS firmware with Backup and Restore support, update the system and try the operation again.

RAC0286.Description: When creating a user account, the New Password and Confirm New Password fields cannot be empty.
RAC0286.Resolution: Enter valid passwords for New Password and Confirm New Password.
RAC0286.Message: New Password and Confirm New Password fields cannot be empty.

PST0007.Description: System BIOS has started power on self test.

SWC0314.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0314.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0314.Message: Invalid syntax. The -o option requires -g to be specified also.

VFL0010.Description: Another operation is currently in progress on the SD card.
VFL0010.Resolution: Wait until the current operation is completed, and then retry the requested operation.
VFL0010.Message: An operation is in progress on the SD card.

MEM0000.Description: The memory is operational. This is an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0000.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0000.Message: Persistent correctable memory errors detected on a memory device at location(s) %1.

FAN904.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode cannot be enabled because the Maximum Power Conservation Mode is enabled.
FAN904.Resolution: Disable the Maximum Power Conservation Mode, and then retry the operation. To disable the mode by using CMC Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration. To disable the mode using the RACADM utility, run the command "racadm config -g cfgThermal -o cfgThermalEnhancedCoolingMode 0".
FAN904.Message: Cannot enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode because the Maximum Power Conservation Mode is enabled.

SYS045.Description: An error occurred while copying the Server Configuration Profile to the network share.
SYS045.Resolution: If the file is being exported to an NFS share, make sure that it is accessible from iDRAC. If the file is being exported to a CIFS share, make sure that it is accessible from iDRAC by using share access credentials with the appropriate privileges. If the share is by using http or https protocol, make sure that you have correctly configured the share and it can be accessible by using iDRAC.
SYS045.Message: Unable to copy the Server Configuration Profile to the network share.

USR105.Description: The user account used as credentials to access iDRAC is not enabled or configured to perform the operation.
USR105.Resolution: Retry the operation after creating the user account.

RAC077.Description: The Import File operation is successfully completed.
RAC077.Message: The Import File operation is successfully completed.

PDR97.Description: The controller detected drives that require security keys for access. Without providing security keys, the drives are unstable.
PDR97.Resolution: Provide the security key required to unlock the secure encrypted drives.

SRV015.Description: The Storage Controller Log information of the controller identified in the message cannot be exported because of an issue in communicating with the controller.
SRV015.Resolution: Make sure that server is not in BIOS POST mode, and then retry the operation. Use the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus() invoke method and check for output parameter RTStatus and make sure it shows 0 (ready status), and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
SRV015.Message: Unable to export Storage Controller Log information of %1 because of an issue in communicating with the controller.

SUP0124.Message: Firmware update is not currently in progress

SUP0113.Description: The cfgRhostsFwUpdateTftpEnable object must be set.
SUP0113.Resolution: Set the cfgRhostsFwUpdateTftpEnable object in cfgRemoteHosts group using config subcommand.
SUP0113.Message: TFTP firmware update is currently disabled.

CTL37.Description: A patrol read operation was initiated by the controller or the user.
CTL37.Message: A Patrol Read operation started for %1.

RAC0244.Description: This message is displayed when a duplicate vFlash partition name is entered.
RAC0244.Resolution: Enter a unique label name for the partition.
RAC0244.Message: The partition label must be unique.

SYS086.Description: Unable to copy the ePSA Diagnostics results file to the specified network share.
SYS086.Resolution: If the results are being exported to an NFS share, make sure that the network share is accessible from iDRAC. If the results are being exported to a CIFS share, make sure that the network share is accessible from iDRAC using the specified share access credentials.
SYS086.Message: Unable to copy the ePSA Diagnostics results file to the network share.

UEFI0063.Description: An attribute cannot be successfully configured because of an issue in the ACI data block.
UEFI0063.Resolution: Check the ACI data block for any invalid configuration data and settings, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0063.Message: Unable to change an attribute because of issues in the Attribute Configuration Interface (ACI) data block.

SYS036.Description: The configuration settings could not be applied to the component. This may indicate configuration changes since the last system inventory collection was completed.
SYS036.Resolution: Retry the operation or try the attribute set operation for the component.
SYS036.Message: Unable to apply the configuration to the component.

CMC8566.Description: The KVM mapping is disabled for the server slot specified in the message. The KVM cannot be mapped to this server slot.
CMC8566.Message: KVM mapping is disabled for the server slot %1.

RED085.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because communication between iDRAC and CMC took more time than expected.
RED085.Resolution: Verify the status of CMC by accessing the CMC and making sure it is functioning and responding and then retry the operation. For more information about troubleshooting a CMC issue, see the CMC User Manual. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RED085.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware, communication with Chassis Management Controller took more time than expected.

SWC8564.Description: The Boot Identity profile from the server identified in the message cannot be cleared because there is no response from the server iDRAC. A MAC Address conflict is possible if the server retains virtual MAC Address values and they are also allocated to another server.
SWC8564.Resolution: Make sure that the server is not used until the Persistence Policy settings are returned to default values and the Virtual MAC Address settings have been cleared. Persistence Policy settings can be reset to default values by resetting the server iDRAC to factory default settings. If the iDRAC cannot be reset to default values, contact your service provider before attempting to use the server.
SWC8564.Message: Unable to clear the Boot Identity profile from the server in slot %1 because there is no response from the server iDRAC.

RED094.Description: The firmware for the component identified in the message is being updated to the firmware version identified in the message.
RED094.Message: Updating firmware for %1 from version %2 to version %3.

PWR8522.Description: The chassis power cycle operation was initiated.

PR6.Description: The configuration values stored for the previous device were applied to the current device.
PR6.Message: Configuration changes successfully applied to device: %1

SWC0250.Resolution: Enter the subcommand without any options.
SWC0250.Message: Invalid syntax. The specified subcommand does not require any options.

PWR2204.Message: The system is in a non-volatile sleep state.

SYS8500.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) sent messages to delay power throttling to all capable servers in the chassis. This was done because the CMC firmware was updated or a failover was initiated. If specific server errors are shown in the message, verify that the iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller firmware versions on those servers is updated to the most current version available.
SYS8500.Resolution: If no errors are shown, no response is required. If errors are listed in the message, navigate to the named servers and make sure that IDRAC and Lifecycle Controller firmware versions are the latest available.

STOR1.Description: The controller cannot communicate with a device. The state of the device cannot be determined. There may be a bad or loose cable, or a missing device, or a problem with the driver or firmware.
STOR1.Resolution: See the storage hardware documentation for information on checking the cables. Check for problems with any enclosures attached to the system. Verify that the controller has a supported version of the driver and firmware. Rebooting the system may resolve this problem.
STOR1.Message: A device %1 is in an unknown state.

PWR201.Description: Selecting the Server Based Power Management Mode option sets your power cap to a maximum value, server priorities to a default priority, and then disables the Max Power Conservation Mode.
PWR201.Message: Selecting the Server Based Power Management Mode option sets your power cap to a maximum value, server priorities to a default priority, and then disables the Max Power Conservation Mode. Do you want to continue?

RED053.Description: Processing of update packages has completed.
RED053.Message: Processing of update packages has completed.

UEFI0050.Message: The process of collecting Brand information is started.

ISM0010.Description: The iDRAC Service Module received a request from a source identified in the message to stop the Service Module services. For example, a requesting source can be an OS or iDRAC.
ISM0010.Resolution: If the requesting source is iDRAC, enable the iDRAC Service Module on the iDRAC before starting this service on the server OS. To enable the Service Module by using iDRAC GUI: Click Network, click OS to iDRAC Pass-through, and then click the USB NIC option. In the OS IP Address box , type an IP address, and then click Apply. To enable the module by using RACADM command, run the following command at the command line interface: racadm set idrac.servicemodule.ServiceModuleEnable enabled.
ISM0010.Message: The iDRAC Service Module received a request from the %1 to stop the services of Service Module.

RDU8519.Description: The communication between the primary and standby CMCs was lost. This may occur when the CMC identified in the message is restarting, or a firmware update operation is in progress. If the issue persists, a failover will occur.
RDU8519.Resolution: Wait for 10 minutes for: 1)Firmware update operations to complete and 2) The CMC to finish restarting. If the communication is not reestablished, remove and reinsert the CMC.
RDU8519.Message: Unable to communicate with peer CMC %1.

RAC979.Description: The custom signing certificate was extracted from the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file and applied to the system configuration.
RAC979.Message: Successfully uploaded the custom signing certificate to iDRAC.

CTL11.Description: A user operation to reset the controller configuration was performed.

PSU0091.Description: The rating of the power supply unit identified in the message should not exceed system power distribution limits.
PSU0091.Resolution: Remove the power supply unit identified in the message and review server product documentation for appropriate configuration.
PSU0091.Message: Power supply unit %1 rating exceeds the system power distribution limits.

SRV084.Description: The operation cannot be started because iDRAC is not registered for the SupportAssist features.
SRV084.Resolution: Register iDRAC for SupportAssist via one of the iDRAC interfaces (iDRAC GUI, WSMAN, RACADM) and then retry the operation. From the iDRAC GUI, navigate to SupportAssist page and register the iDRAC.
SRV084.Message: Unable to start the operation because iDRAC is not registered for the SupportAssist features.

RAC1128.Description: Any operation involving remote share (CIFS) cannot continue if the location (-l option) is not specified. The -u and -p options represent the user name and password for the remote share, and -l represents the location of the remote share.
RAC1128.Resolution: Make sure to specify the location (-l option) of the remote share along with the user name and password, and retry the operation. To view the list of options that can used for the required subcommand, run the RACADM command "racadm help <subcommand>".
RAC1128.Message: The -l option must be specified if -u and -p options are used.

AMP0309.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0309.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0309.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is greater than the upper critical threshold.

OSD58.Description: The connect ISO operation using Remote File Share (RFS) did not complete successfully.
OSD58.Resolution: Verify all the parameters are correct. If the problem persists. then reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
OSD58.Message: Unable to connect an ISO using Remote File Share (RFS).

PDR5.Description: A physical disk has been removed from the disk group. This alert can also be caused by loose or defective cables or by problems with the enclosure.
PDR5.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) If a physical disk was removed from the disk group, either replace the disk or restore the original disk. Identify the disk that was removed by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. 2) Perform a rescan after replacing or restoring the disk. 3) If a disk was not removed from the disk group, then check for cable problems. Refer to product documentation for more information on checking the cables. 4) Make sure that the enclosure is powered on. 5) If the problem persists, check the enclosure documentation for further diagnostic information.

MEM9060.Description: The Post-Package Repair operation is successfully completed on the Dual in-line Memory Module (DIMM) device that was failing earlier.
MEM9060.Message: The Post-Package Repair operation is successfully completed on the Dual in-line Memory Module (DIMM) device that was failing earlier.

SWC0038.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to export the file to the network share because the destination folder is read-only or inaccessible.
SWC0038.Resolution: Remove the write protection on the destination folder and verify the folder is accessible, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, check network settings and retry.
SWC0038.Message: Unable to export the file to the network share.

RAC1165.Description: Unable to configure the port number that is entered for either http or https ports of the iDRAC Web server, because the port number is already in use.
RAC1165.Resolution: Enter a port number that is not already in use and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC1165.Message: Unable to configure the port number that is entered for either http or https ports of the iDRAC Web server, because the port number is already in use.

LC039.Description: Lifecycle Controller is locked by another instance of the As-Shipped Inventory export process. Allow the process to complete before attempting another export operation.
LC039.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
LC039.Message: An instance of As-Shipped Inventory export is already in progress.

RAC1170.Description: Unable to find the SSL library. This can be because, the library is not installed in the default path or no SSL library is installed.
RAC1170.Resolution: If a SSL library is not installed, install one and retry the operation. If a SSL library is installed, create a soft-link of the installed SSL library to "libssl.so" using the linux "ln" command and retry the operation.
RAC1170.Message: Unable to find the SSL library in the default path.

MEM1016.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.
MEM1016.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM1016.Message: Memory device at location %1 is not installed correctly.

STOR14.Description: Peripheral sled initialization is not successful with following possible reasons: 1) FRU is not functioning. 2) Sled internal components are not responding. 3) Component power state is not good. 4) Hardware configuration errors.
STOR14.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check system log for further information about the issue, 2) Remove and re-insert the peripheral sled identified in the message or virtual reseat the sled, 3) Reset the CMC and wait for a few minutes for the CMC to finish restarting. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
STOR14.Message: The peripheral sled in slot %1 initialization is not complete.

SWC8525.Description: Unable to add member because the maximum number of Chassis Group members indicated in the message has been reached.
SWC8525.Resolution: Try removing an existing member and retry the operation.
SWC8525.Message: Unable to add member to Chassis Group. Maximum members supported is %1.

RAC1055.Description: The Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings must already exist in order to be cleared.
RAC1055.Message: Unable to clear the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings because there is currently no configuration.

MEM0008.Message: Memory device at location %1 is spare memory.

RDU8514.Description: A failover operation has been requested, but a failover operation cannot be completed while CMC firmware update is in progress.
RDU8514.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover, firmware update is in progress.

CTL49.Description: The NVRAM has corrupted data. This may occur after a power surge, a battery failure, or for other reasons. The controller is reinitializing the NVRAM.
CTL49.Resolution: No response action is required as the controller is taking the required corrective action. However, If this message is generated often (such as during each reboot), then replace the controller.
CTL49.Message: The NVRAM has corrupted data on %1.

CTL96.Description: The controller identified in the message has an issue as displayed in the message.
CTL96.Resolution: To resolve this issue, see Troubleshooting section in the Dell Shared PowerEdge RAID Controller (SPERC8) documentation.
CTL96.Message: %1 has entered safe mode with limited functionality due to %2

SWC1930.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync feature is set to automatically disable after a specified inactivity time.
SWC1930.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout feature is enabled.

USR8504.Description: The IP range filter feature is enabled in CMC. The IP address from where the login attempt was made is not in the specified range of IP address that can access the CMC.
USR8504.Resolution: If access needs to be given to this specified IP address, change the IP range address and IP range mask accordingly and retry the operation.
USR8504.Message: The IP address specified is out of range.

SYS188.Description: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file has a file size of zero, which is not valid.
SYS188.Resolution: Make sure the import configuration file is valid before retrying the operation.
SYS188.Message: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file has a file size of zero, which is not valid.

RDU0014.Description: The current power supply configuration does not meet the platform requirements to enable redundancy. If a power supply fails the system may shut down.
RDU0014.Resolution: If unintended, review system configuration and power consumption and install power supplies accordingly. Check power supply status for failures.
RDU0014.Message: The power supplies are not redundant.

MEM1002.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in test.

RED038.Description: An Automatic Server Profile Export or Automatic Update task identified in the message has been added.
RED038.Message: A recurring task of type %1 is added.

CPU0025.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.
CPU0025.Resolution: Check presence and reinstall the terminator.

VLT0210.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0210.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0210.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is outside of range.

SWC8609.Description: The CMC was unable to perform the operation described in the message because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller of the server is disabled.
SWC8609.Resolution: Make sure that iDRAC on the server identified in the message is operating and that Lifecycle Controller is enabled, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform a virtual reseat of the server and retry the operation. To perform a virtual reseat of the server, on CMC Web interface, select Chassis Overview -> Troubleshooting -> Reset Components. On the Reset Components page, select Virtual Reseat from the drop-down menu for the server identified in the message.
SWC8609.Message: Server Profiles: unknown response received from server: %1 for operation [%2] because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller of the server is disabled.

PWR8677.Description: Dynamic Power Supply Engagement configuration is changed.
PWR8677.Message: Dynamic Power Supply Engagement configuration is changed.

OSD47.Description: Unable to access the network share using the credentials specified or the firewall might be enabled and is preventing access to the share.
OSD47.Resolution: Make sure that the firewall is disabled, and that the credentials (username, password) are correct.

PSU8510.Description: The firmware for the PSU identified in the message is successfully updated to the version displayed in the message.
PSU8510.Message: PSU in slot %1 FW updated successfully to version %2

PSU0912.Description: Status from the power supply indicates a power supply exception occurred. The power supply will try to operate in a degraded state. System Performance and power redundancy may be degraded or lost.
PSU0912.Resolution: Check input power. Re-install the power supply. If problem persists contact support.
PSU0912.Message: A failure detected on power unit %1.

IOV008.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) was unable to reset the PCIe subsystem into factory default mode.
IOV008.Resolution: Turn off the chassis, turn on the chassis, and then retry the operation.
IOV008.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to put PCIe subsystem into factory default mode.

IOV109.Description: An error condition associated with the PCIe slot is cleared.
IOV109.Message: An error condition associated with the PCIe slot is cleared.

RAC1053.Description: Unable to view the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.
RAC1053.Resolution: Configure the Automatic Backup feature by running the RACADM command "racadm systemconfig backup" with the desired option settings.
RAC1053.Message: Unable to view the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.

VDR27.Description: The check consistency on a virtual disk has resumed processing after a pause.
VDR27.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR27.Message: The consistency check on a %1 has been resumed.

PR15.Description: The configuration changes requested have not passed the device specific verification check and will not be applied.
PR15.Message: Unable to verify configuration changes for device: %1

PDR3.Description: The RAID Controller may not be able to read/write data to the physical disk drive indicated in the message. This may be due to a failure with the physical disk drive or because the physical disk drive was removed from the system.
PDR3.Resolution: Remove and re-insert the physical disk drive identified in the message and make sure the physical disk drive is inserted properly. If the issue persists, replace the physical disk drive.

SWC0129.Description: Racadm tool was not able to send a test email for the configuration.
SWC0129.Resolution: Check for the parameters mentioned in the message.
SWC0129.Message: Unable to send test email. Please make sure that your email alerts have been configured correctly and connectivity to the SMTP server exists.

RAC071.Description: The iDRAC reset operation cannot be completed because a firmware upgrade operation is in progress.
RAC071.Resolution: Wait for the current update process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC071.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset operation because the firmware upgrade operation is in progress.

LC025.Resolution: Make more space available on the network share and try the operation again.

SYS053.Description: Configuration changes specified in the Server Configuration Profile were successfully applied.
SYS053.Message: Successfully imported and applied Server Configuration Profile.

RAC999.Description: DNSFromDHCP6 cannot be enabled if iDRAC IPv6 AutoConfig is disabled.
RAC999.Resolution: Enable IPv6 AutoConfig using "racadm set iDRAC.IPv6.AutoConfig < 1 | Enabled >" command, and retry the operation.
RAC999.Message: The object DNSFromDHCP6 cannot be enabled.

UEFI0202.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Health Check phase.
UEFI0202.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0202.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RED083.Description: The Chassis firmware is not updated because the firmware version currently on the Chassis is same as the requested version.
RED083.Message: The Chassis firmware is not updated because the version currently on the Chassis is same as the requested version.

LC091.Description: The SSL Certificate cannot be generated because a certificate generation process is currently in progress.
LC091.Resolution: Wait for the current Certificate generation process to complete and retry the operation.
LC091.Message: Unable to generate the SSL Certificate because a certificate generation process is currently in progress.

VFL0712.Resolution: Retry the task after a few minutes.
VFL0712.Message: One or more partitions are busy with another operation; the SD card could not be initialized.

SWU8519.Description: The iDRAC firmware update operation was stopped, because the Image file is corrupted.
SWU8519.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the original source, and then retry the operation.
SWU8519.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is stopped. The Image file is corrupted.

SEL1513.Description: The iDRAC communication link to Chassis Controller is restored. Any issues related to network communication between Chassis Controller and iDRAC, incorrectly seated Chassis Controller, or unavailability of Chassis Controller is now resolved successfully.
SEL1513.Message: The status of Chassis Controller has changed from critical to OK.

USR8501.Description: The operation to close a user session using the process ID identified in the message was successful.
USR8501.Message: Successfully closed Session process: pid=%1 sid=%2

RAC0765.Description: The OS IP address cannot be accessed by using the Ping process because an incorrect IP address is entered.
RAC0765.Resolution: Enter a correct IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC0765.Message: Unable to access the operating system (OS) IP address by using the Ping process because an incorrect IP address is entered.

IOV1004.Description: The parameters for the method identified in the message are not passed correctly.
IOV1004.Resolution: Refer to the DCIM Chassis PCI Management Profile document and provide the required parameters.
IOV1004.Message: Too many slots provided as parameters to Assign and UnAssign Servers methods.

STOR072.Description: The configuration operation could not be performed because it requires iDRAC Service Module (ISM) service to be present and running in the server Operating System.
STOR072.Resolution: Make sure the iDRAC Service Module (ISM) service is running on the server Operating System and then retry the operation. Refer to the iDRAC User Guide for installing and starting ISM.
STOR072.Message: iDRAC Service Module (ISM) is either not present or not running on the server OS.

JCP005.Description: System services was cancelled by selecting CTRL+E or F2 on boot up and cancelling it through the iDRAC configuration utility. This prevents jobs from executing further.
JCP005.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

SWU002.Description: The expander or storage enclosure processor firmware update did not complete successfully.
SWU002.Resolution: Check the Storage Enclosure Backplane type and the Firmware version and make sure they are appropriately matched, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
SWU002.Message: The backplane firmware update did not complete successfully.
