TMP1001.Resolution: Check whether the thermostat setting is too low and whether the room temperature is too cool.
TMP1001.Message: %1 has crossed the minimum warning threshold.

UEFI0106.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0106.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0106.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

UEFI0235.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Calibration phase.
UEFI0235.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0235.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SUP0538.Description: Unable to update firmware due to one the following:1) Update Package is not supported. 2) Trusted Platform Module feature is enabled in BIOS settings.
SUP0538.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Download the latest Update Package from your service provider. 2) Disable the Trusted Platform Module feature in BIOS settings. 3) Update the Lifecycle Controller firmware to the latest version.

SRV063.Description: The SupportAssist Chassis Controller logs collection operation is cancelled.
SRV063.Message: The SupportAssist Chassis Controller logs collection operation is cancelled.

LC057.Description: The attribute name provided is not valid for the current method.
LC057.Resolution: Retry the operation with a valid AttributeName parameter value.

SEL1511.Message: Member %1 removed from the Chassis Group.

OSD17.Description: Unable to expose the ISO image as an internal CD device to the host system because the ISO file is no longer present, network errors are preventing access to the ISO file, or iDRAC may not be responsive.
OSD17.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD17.Message: Exposing ISO image as internal device to the server failed.

SWC8532.Description: The starting IP address specified cannot accommodate all the servers. The starting iDRAC IPv4 Address specifies the static IPv4 address of the iDRAC located in the first slot. The static IPv4 address of each subsequent iDRAC is calculated as a slot number increment of this IPv4 address.
SWC8532.Resolution: Make sure there are enough IPv4 addresses for all the iDRACs and then retry the operation.
SWC8532.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to set chassis assigned QuickDeploy IP addresses because the starting IP address cannot accommodate all iDRACs.

ENC12.Description: Communication with an enclosure has been restored. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PST0003.Description: System BIOS has started chipset initialization.

UEFI0076.Description: A Corrected Machine Check error(s) has occurred.
UEFI0076.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the Corrected Machine Check (CMC) errors. Resolve the issue identified in the SEL that caused the CMC.
UEFI0076.Message: One or more Corrected Machine Check(CMC) errors have occurred.

VLT0231.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0231.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the mezzanine card.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0231.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

BAT0001.Message: The system board battery is operating normally.

RAC1044.Description: The Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature is not enabled.
RAC1044.Resolution: To enable, run the RACADM command "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.lcattributes.autoupdate 1".
RAC1044.Message: The Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature is not enabled.

BAR012.Description: Lifecycle Controller data collection and export has failed.
BAR012.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Download and apply the Dell Update Package (DUP) for USC. 2) Run System Services to update the database if CSIOR is not enabled. 3) Reboot the system and retry. If the issue persists after performing these operations, download the Field Service Repair software and repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download and install all the DUPs for USC, diagnostics, driver packs, and device firmware of all the devices of the host system.
BAR012.Message: Unable to collect Lifecycle Controller data.

UEFI0109.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during write leveling initialization.
UEFI0109.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0109.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

USR0016.Description: Unable to obtain the session info from RAC.
USR0016.Message: Unable to get session info from the RAC.

UEFI0239.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - Calculation phase.
UEFI0239.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0239.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

STOR011.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the stripe size entered is not supported by the controller.
STOR011.Resolution: Enter a valid stripe size and retry the operation.
STOR011.Message: Stripe size not supported on controller.

CTL91.Description: The controller identified in the message is unable to communicate with its peer. This can be because of a cabling issue.
CTL91.Resolution: Check the cabling between the PERC cards and the expanders. If this does not resolve the issue then contact your service provider.
CTL91.Message: %1 is unable to communicate with its peer.

RAC0621.Description: The message appears in Job Queue page when the iDRAC firmware update job status is completed. Communication to the iDRAC will be lost .
RAC0621.Resolution: The iDRAC will be ready for login once the restart is complete.
RAC0621.Message: Successfully completed the iDRAC firmware update. All current user sessions will be closed.

BAT1027.Description: The battery successfully completed a charge cycle.
BAT1027.Message: The battery on %1 completed a charge cycle.

RAC926.Description: The value given for the recurrence interval is invalid. It has to be a value from 0 to 365.
RAC926.Resolution: Change the argument of r to a value from 0 to 365 and then run the same command.
RAC926.Message: The recurrence interval needs to be an integer from 0 to 365.

SWC0061.Description: Write-protection is enabled on the vFlash SD card.
SWC0061.Resolution: Remove the write-protection on the vFlash SD card and retry the operation.

RAC0632.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid hostname or IP address is entered.
RAC0632.Resolution: Enter a valid network file share hostname or IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC0632.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid network file share hostname or IP address is entered.

RAC0692.Description: Unable to assign and un-assign physical disk drives as global hotspare(s), because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0692.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0692.Message: Unable to assign and un-assign physical disk drives as global hotspare(s), because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

DKM1000.Resolution: Check for network connectivity. Review network, server, and client configuration.
DKM1000.Message: A network problem detected. Cannot contact key management server.

SWC0017.Description: An unrecoverable error occurred while retrieving the drivers.
SWC0017.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit Lifecycle Controller and perform an AC power cycle.
SWC0017.Message: Unable to retrieve the drivers for the selected operating system.

SWC0116.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0116.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0116.Message: The -s option requires IP address, subnet mask, and gateway.

NIC015.Description: A set attribute operation was attempted on a read only attribute.
NIC015.Message: AttributeValue cannot be changed to read only AttributeName %1.

RAC015.Description: The input attribute value is not valid for the attribute identified in the message.
RAC015.Resolution: Provide valid attribute value for the attribute identified in the message and retry the operation.
RAC015.Message: Unable to run the method because the input value is not one of the possible values for AttributeName %1.

UEFI0131.Description: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient shadow memory. The option ROM shadow memory is located between C0000h and F0000h.
UEFI0131.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove unused PCIe card(s) to free up option ROM space. 2) Disable unused boot protocol instances (such as PXE, iSCSI, etc.) from applicable PCIe card(s) option ROM configurations. 3) If possible, install and run the Operating System in UEFI boot mode.
UEFI0131.Message: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient shadow memory.

JCP036.Description: The job identified in the message is successfully deleted on iDRAC.

RAC0133.Description: A non-specific error has been detected when downloading the partition.
RAC0133.Resolution: Try downloading the partition again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC before trying the operation again.
RAC0133.Message: An error has occurred while downloading a partition.

RAC1005.Description: The hardware inventory was successfully exported.

GMGR0068.Description: The group job cannot be completed because a group job is in progress.
GMGR0068.Resolution: Wait for the existing group job to get completed and retry the operation.
GMGR0068.Message: Unable to complete a system configuration job because a group job is in progress.

MEM9011.Description: BIOS logged location information of a QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) warning. This information can be reviewed by using a tool which displays raw IPMI SEL data such as IPMItool with the -vvv option or RACADM with the -E option.
MEM9011.Message: QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) Reference Code warning location information is logged.

PSU1007.Description: A device has been failed and the system is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

SYS154.Description: Initiating secure erase operation on secure erase-capable drives for the controller identified in the message.
SYS154.Message: Initiating secure erase operation on secure erase-capable drives for controller: %1.

UEFI0240.Description: An error occurred during Memory Voltage Regulator initialization during the VR0 SVID Ramp phase.
UEFI0240.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0240.Message: An error occurred during Voltage Regulator (VR) initialization on memory riser %1.

SUP0520.Description: The firmware update operation for the component did not complete due to an internal error.
SUP0520.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0520.Message: Unable to update the %1 firmware to version %2.

SWC0256.Description: Unable to read the specified file.

STOR093.Description: The configuration operation cannot be performed because the controller is not available for import process.
STOR093.Resolution: Make sure an operation is not pending on the controller. If an operation is pending, wait for the operation to complete or cancel the pending operation and then retry the operation. Refer to the storage controller documentation for compatibility information.
STOR093.Message: Unable to run the configuration operation because the controller is not available for the import process.

CTL50.Description: The NVRAM has corrupt data. The controller is unable to correct the situation.

GMGR0024.Description: The group passcode is successfully changed.
GMGR0024.Message: The group passcode is successfully changed.

OSD062.Description: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is started and is in progress.
OSD062.Message: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is started and is in progress.

SWC0051.Description: Unable to retrieve license information due to an iDRAC communication error.
SWC0051.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0051.Message: Unable to retrieve iDRAC license information.

RED064.Description: A scheduled Update from Repository completed and no applicable updates were found.
RED064.Message: The scheduled Update from Repository job completed successfully. Applicable updates were not found.

SYS037.Description: Operation validation is unsuccessful. The command, target and operation data are all validated before an update is performed. If any of them are missing or incorrect the operation does not complete successfully.
SYS037.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory on Restart attribute using Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. Retry the operation after the system restarts.

STOR074.Description: The requested RAID configuration operation will not be allowed because the RAID controller is currently in HBA mode.
STOR074.Resolution: In order to perform a RAID configuration operation, change the controller mode to RAID and retry the operation. For switching to RAID mode using the F2 System Setup utility, go to Device Settings > "RAID Controller "> Controller Management > Advanced Controller Management > Switch to RAID mode.
STOR074.Message: The requested RAID configuration operation is not allowed because the controller is currently in HBA mode.

RAC1193.Description: A RAC system configuration change has been requested. Please check logs for more details on the configuration change and the origin of the configuration change request.
RAC1193.Message: A RAC system configuration change has been requested.

VDR53.Description: The consistency check can no longer report errors in the parity data.
VDR53.Resolution: See the storage hardware documentation for more information on consistency check operation. Contact technical support.
VDR53.Message: The consistency check logging of inconsistent parity data is disabled for %1.

PCI3018.Description: New PCI card(s) have been detected in the system that may require additional airflow. Fan speeds may have changed to add additional cooling to the cards.
PCI3018.Resolution: Changing default fan response to PCIe cards should be done with appropriate understanding of the PCIe cooling needs of the cards present in the system. If the automatic cooling response is insufficient, additional cooling can be added by one of the following methods. 1) From iDRAC Web GUI, click Hardware -> Fans -> Setup, then from the fan speed offset drop-down list appropriately select the cooling level needed or set the minimum fan speed to a custom value. 2) From F2 System Setup, select iDRAC Settings -> Thermal, and set a higher fan speed from the fan speed offset or minimum fan speed. 3) For RACADM commands run "racadm help system.thermalsettings". If a lower fan speed is required, contact your service provider for the appropriate IPMI commands to reduce the default fan speed response for new PCIe cards.
PCI3018.Message: New PCI card(s) have been detected in the system. Fan speeds may have changed to add additional cooling to the cards.

DIS100.Description: The AutoConfig operation is successfully completed by the iDRAC using the AutoConfig import file specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

SYS050.Description: The Server Configuration Profile for the import configuration operation is not compliant with schema nesting checks. Only RAID controllers can have nested Component nodes up to a maximum nesting depth of three.
SYS050.Resolution: Make sure that the Server Configuration Profile is compliant with the system configuration schema published on delltechcenter.com/lc in the LC profile Schema Guide. Only RAID controllers can have nested Component nodes.
SYS050.Message: The Server Configuration Profile for import configuration is not compliant with schema nesting checks.

LOG509.Description: The command cannot be run because the value of the parameter identified in the message exceeds the maximum length identified in the message.
LOG509.Resolution: Enter a value for the parameter identified in the message that is equal to or less than the maximum allowed characters.
LOG509.Message: Unable to run the command because the parameter value of %1 exceeds the maximum allowed number of %2 characters.

BAR094.Description: The request to create a System Profile Backup file did not complete successfully because there is already a request in progress.
BAR094.Resolution: If possible monitor the in progress job for completion and then retry the request. If that is not possible try clearing all jobs and try the request again. If the issue persists, restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) and try the request again.
BAR094.Message: Another Backup operation already in progress.

UEFI0261.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the R920 I/O riser is not supported in R930.
UEFI0261.Resolution: Replace the R920 I/O riser with an R930 I/O riser. For information about the supported I/O risers, see the product documentation available at the support site.
UEFI0261.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the R920 I/O riser is not supported.

RAC049.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC.
RAC049.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.

VF008.Description: Creating a partition with an image did not complete successfully.
VF008.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes, 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
VF008.Message: Image partition creation did not complete successfully.

SYS190.Description: The OS-related data cannot be collected because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installed on the server does not support this feature on the version of Operating System installed.
SYS190.Resolution: Install a iDRAC Service Module (ISM) supported OS, and then retry the operation.
SYS190.Message: Unable to collect the operating system (OS)-related data because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installed on the server does not support this feature on the version of Operating System installed.

SWC0271.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0271.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0271.Message: Invalid syntax. The -f option is only valid with -p and -c.

UEFI0089.Description: Incompatible x16 data bus width DIMM is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0089.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0089.Message: Incompatible x16 data bus width DIMM is installed on memory slot: %1.

BAT1024.Description: The battery or the battery charger is not functioning properly. The battery may have an inadequate charge.

SYS294.Description: Some configuration changes for the component identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) in the configuration job results were not successfully previewed.
SYS294.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Export the Lifecycle Log report and check the configuration changes that did not complete. 2) Retrieve the configuration results by running the GetConfigResults method at the command line interface (CLI). 3) Retry importing the changes that are not successfully completed.
SYS294.Message: Component configuration preview was completed with errors.

PDR9.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

VDR51.Description: The consistency check completed on the virtual disk after making corrections.
VDR51.Message: The consistency check process made corrections and completed on %1.

BAT1015.Description: Diagnostic event for service to determine if there is an ambient temperature problem.

GMGR0016.Description: The Service Tag identified in the message could not join the iDRAC local group identified in the message either because the Group passcode entered is incorrect, local group already has the max allowed iDRACs, or issues in network connection.
GMGR0016.Resolution: Do any one of the following and retry the operation: a) Enter correct Group Passcode. b) Remove existing iDRAC(s) from the local group. Consider upgrading to a supported console if there are more than the maximum iDRACs. c) Verify the network cabling connections.
GMGR0016.Message: %1 is unable to join the iDRAC local group %2 either because the Group passcode is incorrect, group already has the max allowed iDRACs, iDRAC already part of another group, group name does not exist, or issues in network connection.

RRDU0006.Description: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild initiated.
RRDU0006.Message: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild initiated.

UEFI0292.Description: DDR memory initialization of the Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) in the specified memory slot cannot be completed because of a mismatch in the size of the DIMM installed in the server.
UEFI0292.Resolution: Remove the mismatched Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) module and replace it with a DIMM of the same size as other DIMMs installed on the Integrated Memory Controller (iMC). For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual available on the support site.
UEFI0292.Message: Unable to initialize the Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) in memory slot %1 because of a mismatch in the size of the DIMM installed in the server.

STOR094.Description: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.
STOR094.Resolution: To apply the configuration operation immediately, create a configuration job using the --realTime option. To apply the configuration after restarting the server, create a configuration job using the -r option. To create the necessary real-time and restart jobs, run the jobqueue command. For more information about jobqueue command, run the racadm help jobqueue command.
STOR094.Message: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.

STOR4.Description: There was a software problem in initializing the CEM storage management components. Storage inventory and monitoring will be affected.
STOR4.Resolution: Reboot the system or iDRAC. If the problem is not resolved, contact technical support.
STOR4.Message: CEM Storage Management encountered internal error.

SWC8555.Description: The Boot Identity operation cannot be started because a Boot Identity operation is already in progress.
SWC8555.Resolution: Wait for the current operation to complete, and then retry. Only one Boot Identity operation can be performed at a time.
SWC8555.Message: Unable to start the Boot Identity profile operation because a Boot Identity operation is already in progress.

SYS098.Description: A Remote Diagnostic (ePSA) job already exists and only one job of this type can exist at a time.
SYS098.Resolution: A response action is not required if the scheduled start time of the existing Remote Diagnostic (ePSA) job is ok. Else, delete the existing Diagnostics (ePSA) job and recreate another with an appropriate start time.
SYS098.Message: A Remote Diagnostic (ePSA) job already exists.

MEM1007.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to transition to online.

RAC1177.Description: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC and accessible from the iDRAC.
RAC1177.Resolution: No response action is required. To attach the USB device to the server instead of the iDRAC, remove the USB device from the front panel USB port, change the USB Management Port mode settings and then reinsert the USB device.
RAC1177.Message: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC.

JCP040.Description: User created configuration / update Job with specified Job Name using specified interface.
JCP040.Message: User %1 via IP %2 created configuration / update Job ID %3 with Job Name %4 using %5.

HWC0003.Description: The vFlash SD card was successfully initialized.

BAR059.Description: The system profile import or export network destination is being tested for access.

RAC1058.Description: The requested firmware Rollback operation did not complete successfully because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.
RAC1058.Resolution: Run the RACADM command "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1" to enable Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.
RAC1058.Message: Rollback operation did not complete successfully because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.

NIC017.Description: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration.
NIC017.Resolution: Remove AC power from system and after restoring AC power, retry the operation.
NIC017.Message: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration

IOV002.Description: CMC could not successfully allocate resources because of the following reasons: 1) The chassis manager is unable to allocate required resources. 2) The chassis manager or chassis infrastructure firmware is rolled back to an earlier version. 3) There is an issue with the internal communications between chassis components.
IOV002.Resolution: Make sure the firmware for the various chassis components are compatible with each other. If this is the case, do the following: 1) Turn off the chassis, by pressing the chassis Power Button, 2) run the following CMC RACADM command "racadm racresetcfg". If the problem persists, contact your technical service provider.
IOV002.Message: Unable to create or allocate the required resources.

IOV103.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected the replacement of an adapter in the slot identified in the message.
IOV103.Message: A PCIe adapter %1 in %2%3 is replaced by PCIe adapter %1.

PWR1003.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1003.Resolution: If unintended, review system configuration changes and thermal policy.
PWR1003.Message: The system performance degraded because cooling capacity has changed.

STOR084.Description: The requested job cannot be run because another job is currently running. Two options for running jobs on multiple storage controllers are: 1) Run the jobs on each controller individually. Wait for each job to complete before starting the configuration and job creation on the next controller. 2) Schedule multiple jobs to run at a later time using the scheduling options.
STOR084.Resolution: Make sure that the currently running job is completed, and then retry the operation. If necessary, recreate the configuration and the job. For information about running jobs on multiple storage controllers, see the iDRAC Online Help or iDRAC Users Guide.
STOR084.Message: Unable to create the job because another job is currently running

BOOT013.Description: The boot list is currently not active. Changes cannot be made to boot list that is not active.
BOOT013.Resolution: Alter boot mode to set the boot list active and retry the operation.
BOOT013.Message: Cannot make changes to non-active boot list.

STOR0509.Description: The controller does not have the minimum number of initialized disks to create a virtual disk.
STOR0509.Resolution: Connect required number of initialized physical disks to the RAID controller and retry the operation.

UEFI0058.Description: Uncorrectable Memory Error has occurred because a Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) is not functioning.
UEFI0058.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the non-functioning DIMM, and then replace it.
UEFI0058.Message: An uncorrectable Memory Error has occurred because a Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) is not functioning.

ISM0002.Description: The OS to iDRAC Pass-through mode is disabled. The iDRAC Service Module is currently enabling the OS to iDRAC Pass-through mode in the USB NIC mode. This operation is done only for the first run of iDRAC Service Module. If OS to iDRAC Pass-through is disabled after this point of time, iDRAC Service Module will not be able to connect to iDRAC until user enables the OS-iDRAC Pass-through in the USB mode.
ISM0002.Message: The OS to iDRAC Pass-through is disabled. The iDRAC Service Module is currently enabling the OS to iDRAC Pass-through in the USB NIC mode.

BAR093.Description: The attempt to disconnect from the specified CIFS location was not successful.
BAR093.Resolution: If this happens on a backup request, restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller and try the operation again. If this is a restore request the Integrated Remote Access will be restarted during the execution of the request. Only restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller if it does not restart on its own.

RAC0910.Description: The specified command is missing group and object name syntax.
RAC0910.Resolution: Specify the correct subcommand group and object name syntax. See the help text or documentation for the valid syntax.
RAC0910.Message: Invalid subcommand syntax: Specify group and object name.

BAR104.Description: Unable to collect system branding data to copy to backup Server Profile.
BAR104.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
BAR104.Message: Unable to collect system branding data.

STOR304.Description: Controller mode cannot be changed as the controller has virtual disk or hotspare associated with it.
STOR304.Resolution: Delete the Virtual Disks and/or Hotspares and retry the operation.
STOR304.Message: Unable to change controller mode while Virtual Disks and/or Hotspares are present on the controller.

PSU0038.Message: Power supply %1 fan is operating normally.

AMP0322.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0322.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0322.Message: Chassis power level current is outside of range.

CTL6.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL6.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.

RAC002.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.

SRV091.Description: The SupportAssist job identified in the message cannot be created.
SRV091.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and then retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC using RACADM command line utility, type "racadm racreset".
SRV091.Message: Unable to create the SupportAssist job for %1.

SRV088.Description: The SupportAssist operation identified in the message is successfully completed.
SRV088.Message: The SupportAssist %1 operation is successfully completed.

PWR8545.Description: Incorrect power inventory information reported by the iDRAC for the server identified in the message.
PWR8545.Resolution: Invalid power inventory information could be due to outdated iDRAC firmware or server BIOS firmware versions. Update the components to their latest versions.
PWR8545.Message: Chassis Management Controller turned off the server %1 because of incorrect power data retrieved from iDRAC at inventory.

TMP0124.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0124.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

SYS157.Description: Unable to successfully complete requested options of the System Erase operation. Retrying the System Erase operation may be required.
SYS157.Resolution: Retry the System Erase operation. To retry the System Erase operation using the Lifecycle Controller utility, restart the server and when the company logo is displayed, press <F10>. Select Hardware Configuration > Retire or Repurpose System, check appropriate options, and then retry the operation. Also disable "F1/F2 Prompt on Error" in BIOS settings for System Erase operation to continue without intervention.
SYS157.Message: Unable to successfully complete requested System Erase tasks.

SWC0232.Description: Remote RACADM commands are not supported on the current iDRAC.
SWC0232.Resolution: If remote RACADM is a necessity, upgrade the iDRAC version.
SWC0232.Message: Remote RACADM commands are not supported on this iDRAC. To upgrade your iDRAC version, contact your service provider.

VLT0220.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0220.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0220.Message: The %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

PCI3005.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card %1 was successfully updated.

UEFI0269.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI target IP address is invalid.
UEFI0269.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, do the following: 1) Make sure the Target IP Address is set corresponding to the mode enabled (IPv4/IPv6). 2) Make sure there is no typographical error in the Target IP Address field. 3) Retry the operation.
UEFI0269.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI target IP address is invalid.

CTL93.Description: The controller identified in the message has been changed to operate as part of a fault tolerant pair.
CTL93.Message: %1 has been successfully changed to operate in Fault Tolerant mode.

SUP022.Description: JobStore file has exceeded the size limit. Delete all unneeded JobIDs from the job store.
SUP022.Resolution: New JobID cannot be stored. Manually delete the failed jobs and retry the operation.
SUP022.Message: Job store has reached the maximum storage limit.

IOV115.Description: The discovery process for PCIE adapters was unable to allocate the power required to power on the PCIE adapters.
IOV115.Resolution: Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM command line interface, run the command "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerCap <Power cap>" to increase the power cap or add an additional power supply.
IOV115.Message: Unable to allocate %1 WATTS for discovery of PCIE adapters.

SWC0221.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0221.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0221.Message: The -l option requires -c to also be specified.

HWC0007.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to retrieve vFlash SD card information from iDRAC.
HWC0007.Resolution: Reinsert the vFlash SD card and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
HWC0007.Message: Unable to load vFlash SD card settings.

HWC8512.Description: The Coin Cell battery in the front panel was detected low and a new battery is installed.
HWC8512.Message: The Coin Cell battery in the front panel is properly installed.

BIOS018.Description: The BIOS password specified in the operation is not valid. A valid BIOS password must be made from the following: 0 to 32 characters in length, numbers 0 to 9, lowercase letters a to z, special characters <>|-,+./;[\]'.
BIOS018.Resolution: Retry the operation with a BIOS password that conforms with system BIOS password requirements.

RAC954.Description: Up to 128 characters are allowed for a comment.
RAC954.Resolution: Do not exceed 128 characters for the comment, and retry the operation.
RAC954.Message: The number of characters entered for the comment exceeds the supported limit.

LNK0004.Description: Unable to connect to FTP server due to a network error.
LNK0004.Resolution: Check the network connection, network configuration settings, and retry. If the problem persists, restart the FTP server.
LNK0004.Message: Unable to connect to FTP server.

UEFI0307.Description: The Baseboard UPI A cable is not connected.
UEFI0307.Resolution: Connect the Baseboard UPI A cable. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0307.Message: The Baseboard UPI A cable is not connected.

CPU0802.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0802.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0802.Message: A predictive failure detected on CPU %1 voltage regulator module.

PDR43.Description: This message is generated after a clear operation completes on a physical disk.
PDR43.Message: The clear operation on %1 has completed.

ISM0012.Description: The iDRAC Service Module is successfully ended on the server OS.
ISM0012.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is successfully ended on the server operating system (OS).

PR3.Description: The current component firmware version is higher than the replaced component firmware version.
PR3.Message: Newer version of firmware found on device: %1

UEFI0311.Description: The Baseboard UPI C cable is not connected.
UEFI0311.Resolution: Connect the Baseboard UPI C cable. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0311.Message: The Baseboard UPI C cable is not connected.

RAC0506.Description: This error occurs when the user tries to access a program or function that is beyond user granted privileges.
RAC0506.Resolution: Contact the system administrator to perform the operation or grant the required privileges.
RAC0506.Message: You do not have privileges to perform this operation.

BAR042.Description: Lifecycle Controller/System services are not available. There is another operation using the resources at this time.
BAR042.Resolution: Wait for the other operation to release the resources, as indicated by the System Services option presence and retry the operation.

GMGR0066.Description: The group job cannot be started because an invalid operation is requested.
GMGR0066.Message: Unable to start the requested operation on the group job because the operation is not supported.

SWU8543.Description: The firmware update operation of CMC was not successful. The Image file was not accessible.
SWU8543.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8543.Message: Unable to update the Active CMC firmware. The Image file was not accessible.

PSU0080.Description: The system does not support mixed voltage power supplies.
PSU0080.Resolution: Review product documentation, change power supply with correct voltage rating.
PSU0080.Message: Power supply %1 voltage rating does not match the system's requirements.

IOID002.Description: After the I/O Identity optimization feature is disabled, the time during boot to configure I/O Identity attributes using the Server Configuration Profile (Configuration XML) import feature will increase.
IOID002.Message: The Input/Output Identity (I/O Identity) optimization feature is disabled.

UEFI0193.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Coarse Command Training phase.
UEFI0193.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0193.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

OSD15.Description: Unable to mount the network share using the credentials specified in the command because either the username or password is incorrect.
OSD15.Resolution: Rerun the command with the correct username and password.
OSD15.Message: Mount network share failed - incorrect username or password.

PR30.Description: Operation validation was unsuccessful. The command, target and operation data are all validated before proceeding. If any of them are missing or incorrect the request is failed.
PR30.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory on Restart attribute of the Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. After the system has restarted, retry the operation.

CMC8613.Description: The reset process of iDRAC Non Maskable Interrupt (NMI) on sled identified in the message is initiated.
CMC8613.Message: The reset process of iDRAC Non Maskable Interrupt (NMI) on sled %1 is initiated.

IOID114.Description: The target setting properties of the NIC port identified in the message are successfully configured.
IOID114.Message: The target settings properties of the %1 Port %2 are successfully configured.

SRV069.Description: Unable to collect Chassis Management Controller (CMC) logs because iDRAC is not able to communicate to the CMC.
SRV069.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and then retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm racreset". To reset the CMC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm chassisaction reset". If racadm command fails, cold reset CMC and iDRAC manually and retry the operation.
SRV069.Message: Unable to collect Chassis Management Controller (CMC) logs because iDRAC is not able to communicate to the CMC.

SYS200.Description: The job identified in the message is successfully run and completed.
SYS200.Message: The job with %1 is successfully run and completed.

OSD20.Description: Unable to get the size or label for selected operating system from the Driver Pack present in Lifecycle Controller. The driver pack may be corrupt.
OSD20.Resolution: Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and rerun the command.
OSD20.Message: Unable to get size or label from Driver Pack for selected operating system.

USR8502.Description: The operation to close a user session using the session ID identified in the message was successful.

TMP0123.Message: The system inlet temperature is within range.

SRV109.Description: The SupportAssist Collection data cannot be exported because the network share information is not available.
SRV109.Resolution: Make sure that either the default network share attributes are set, or enter the network share type, share name, IP address, user name, and password, and retry the operation.
SRV109.Message: Unable to export the SupportAssist Collection data because the network share information is not available.

UEFI0227.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Receive Enable Training - Configuration Read phase.
UEFI0227.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0227.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

VDR4.Description: This message is generated after a virtual disk was created on a controller.

HWC7012.Description: Server <number> health changed to a non-recoverable state.
HWC7012.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7012.Message: Server %1 health changed to a non-recoverable state.

SWU8534.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation is not successful.
SWU8534.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8534.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware.

RAC998.Description: IPv6 cannot be enabled if iDRAC NIC is disabled.
RAC998.Resolution: Enable iDRAC NIC using "racadm set iDRAC.NIC.Enable < 1 | Enabled >" command and retry the operation.

UEFI0052.Description: The rebranding process cannot be completed because of the reasons identified on the computer screen.
UEFI0052.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Update the iDRAC firmware. 2) Update the system BIOS. 3) Update the OEM ID module.
UEFI0052.Message: Unable to complete the rebranding operation because of the issue(s) displayed earlier.

HWC9002.Description: The BOSS device identified in the message is not functioning because either the inlet temperature, fan health properties, or total power associated with the BOSS device has exceeded the threshold values.
HWC9002.Resolution: Make sure that the inlet temperature, fan health, or total power associated with the BOSS device are within specified limits.For information about specified values, see the iDRAC 9.0 and later User's Guide available on the support site.
HWC9002.Message: The %1 device is not functioning because either the inlet temperature, fan health properties, or total power associated with the %1 device has exceeded the threshold values.

IOV114.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter (VA) identified in the message has been assigned to the server identified in the message.

CMC8571.Description: The coin cell battery in the primary CMC is not working. The battery needs to be replaced.
CMC8571.Resolution: Replace the coin cell battery in the primary CMC.
CMC8571.Message: The coin cell battery in the primary CMC is not working.

GMGR0058.Description: Unable to complete the configuration operation because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.
GMGR0058.Resolution: Disable the System Lockdown mode and retry the operation. To disable System Lockdown mode, Go to iDRAC home page > Dashboard > More Actions > Turn off the System Lockdown Mode (or) on iDRAC secure shell, use the command racadm set iDRAC.Lockdown.SystemLockdownMode Disabled.
GMGR0058.Message: Unable to complete the configuration operation because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.

FAN0004.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.
FAN0004.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0004.Message: Fan %1 RPM is outside of range.

SWC0121.Description: The syntax of the sslcertview command is invalid.
SWC0121.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertview subcommand.
SWC0121.Message: Invalid syntax. User index (-i) must be specified.

CTL13.Description: The controller has flushed the cache and all data in the cache has been lost. This may occur when the system has memory or battery problems that cause the controller to distrust the cache. Although user data may have been lost, this alert does not always indicate that relevant or user data has been lost.
CTL13.Resolution: Verify that the battery and memory are functioning properly.

UEFI0080.Description: The PCIe link speed is not optimal for the identified PCIe device.
UEFI0080.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Turn off the input power to the system and turn on again. 2) Update the PCIe device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0080.Message: PCIe link speed is not optimal for %1. Expected link speed: Gen %2 and actual link speed: Gen %2.

USR0007.Description: UserID closing session from IP Address.

TMP0129.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is within range.

SWC0084.Description: The iDRAC has successfully joined Integrated Data Center network. This iDRAC will now be managed by the Integrated Data Center solution.
SWC0084.Message: The iDRAC successfully joined Integrated Data Center network.

VRM0011.Description: The Virtual Media server is already disconnected.
VRM0011.Message: The Virtual Media image server is not currently connected.

LC074.Description: The Certificate export operation did not complete successfully.
LC074.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation.
LC074.Message: The Certificate export operation did not complete successfully.

CTL68.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL68.Message: Attempted to import Virtual Disk with missing Physical Disk on %1.

USR0015.Description: The specified user does not exist.
USR0015.Resolution: Verify the existing users and enter a valid username.
USR0015.Message: The specified user does not exist.

RAC982.Description: The PKCS12 file provided is invalid, because it may not be in the correct format.
RAC982.Resolution: For more details, contact the Certificate Authority.
RAC982.Message: Invalid Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file detected.

HWC0002.Description: The vFlash SD Card is either not present or not correctly inserted.
HWC0002.Resolution: Insert the vFlash SD card or reinsert the vFlash SD card, and retry the operation.
HWC0002.Message: Unable to detect vFlash SD card.

UEFI0230.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Receive Enable Training - Calculation phase.
UEFI0230.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0230.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

FC010.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G and above generations: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
FC010.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.
FC010.Message: Unable to create Configuration job because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

MEM1208.Description: The assigned spare is no longer available.
MEM1208.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>.
MEM1208.Message: Memory spare redundancy is lost. Check memory device at location %1.

VLT0301.Description: Low voltages may be the result of a problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. When the critical threshold is crossed, the processor will fail to operate. The system may power down.
VLT0301.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0301.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

BAR010.Description: The Backup partition creation operation did no complete successfully.
BAR010.Resolution: Make sure that the vFlash media is not write-protected. Enable and initialize the vFlash media, retry backup. If that fails Try new vFlash media or use the Network Share option(s).
BAR010.Message: Unable to create Backup partition on vFlash media.

SWC0317.Description: The value for -c must be greater than zero.
SWC0317.Resolution: Enter a value greater than zero, for the option -c.
SWC0317.Message: The number of records to display must be greater than zero.

BAR025.Description: For each component with firmware, an update is in progress.

SUP013.Description: The update process is underway and cannot be deleted.
SUP013.Resolution: Do not try to delete the job when the update process is underway. To revert to the previous version of the update, download and update the firmware to the version desired or run the rollback command to go back to the previous version.

CTL66.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL66.Message: Attempted to import Unsupported Virtual Disk type RAID%1 on %2.

SYS062.Description: The input file for the import configuration operation does not contain a valid profile root element.
SYS062.Resolution: Open the input file in any Web browser to check for invalid content before the expected root element. Correct the invalid content and make sure that the profile is compliant to the system configuration schema before retrying the operation.
SYS062.Message: Input file for import configuration operation is invalid. The expected profile root element was not found.

OSE1008.Description: The system OS has successfully booted from the CD-ROM.

PSU0031.Description: The power supply may operate, however power supply monitoring will be degraded. System performance may be degraded.
PSU0031.Resolution: Remove and re-install the power supply. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

DIS005.Description: Message was sent successfully from Auto Discovery to Provisioning Server to request certificate.
DIS005.Message: Auto Discovery communicated successfully with Provisioning Server %1.

IPA0004.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.

PWR2212.Message: The system is in legacy OFF state.

GMGR0047.Description: The group job is either stopped by a user action or failed at the member level.
GMGR0047.Resolution: Do the following and rerun the job: 1) Check the group job rollup status to see if the job is stopped by the user. If yes, rerun the job if required. 2) If not, review the job execution details in the Lifecycle Log details of the member iDRAC. By using the iDRAC graphical user interface (GUI), on the home page, click Maintenance > Lifecycle Log. By using command line interface (CLI), enter the RACADM command "racadm lclog view".
GMGR0047.Message: The group job is either stopped by a user action or failed at the member level.

UEFI0164.Description: The Advanced ECC memory operating mode cannot be enabled because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.
UEFI0164.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0164.Message: Unable to enable the Advanced ECC memory operating mode because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations on memory slots: %1.

PWR1004.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1004.Resolution: If unintended, review system configuration changes and power policy.
PWR1004.Message: The system performance degraded because power capacity has changed.

FCD8504.Description: The card was installed and activated on another chassis. To use this card, it must be deactivated (uninstalled) on the other chassis.
FCD8504.Resolution: Remove the card and install it on the chassis where the feature is activated.
FCD8504.Message: The feature was previously activated on another chassis.

STOR073.Description: The iDRAC Service Module version present on the server OS does not support the requested PCIe SSD (NVMe) device operation.
STOR073.Resolution: Update the Dell iDRAC Service Module (ISM) to the version that supports the requested operation on the PCIe SSD (NVMe) device.
STOR073.Message: The iDRAC Service Module version present on the server OS does not support the requested PCIe SSD (NVMe) device operation.

SWU8525.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful. The update process was not completed within the firmware update timeout duration.
SWU8525.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8525.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware on the server in slot %1. The firmware update timeout limit is exceeded.

RED015.Description: The download protocol specified is not supported.
RED015.Resolution: The supported protocols include NFS, CIFS, HTTP, FTP, TFTP.
RED015.Message: The download protocol specified is not supported.

VLT0214.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0214.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0214.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

SYS405.Description: The request cannot be successfully completed because the JSON data format entered is invalid.
SYS405.Resolution: Do the following and the retry the operation: 1) Enter the correct JSON data format and retry the operation. 2) Make sure that no syntax error is present in JSON data format. 3) Make sure that a duplicate key is not present in JSON data format.
SYS405.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the JSON data format entered in invalid.

NIC504.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC504.Message: The IPv6 DNS Server IP address is not allowed to be configured if IPv6 DNS Server DHCP (cfgIPv6DNSServersFromDHCP6) is enabled.

STOR035.Description: Unable to perform operation because either the number of storage objects specified is insufficient or the storage objects are not in a required state to perform this operation.
STOR035.Resolution: Check the number and state of storage objects and retry the operation.
STOR035.Message: Unable to perform operation because either the number of storage objects specified is insufficient or the storage objects are not in a required state to perform this operation.

SYS069.Description: The settings specified in the system configuration XML file match the current configuration for all components.
SYS069.Message: No changes were applied since the current component configuration matched the requested configuration.

STOR7.Description: The storage monitoring instrumentation detected a burst of events from underlying storage controllers. To overcome this overload condition, all the outstanding events have been purged and a fresh inventory will be performed automatically.
STOR7.Message: The storage management instrumentation is performing an inventory refresh operation.

MEM1212.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed.
MEM1212.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>.

TMP0204.Resolution: Check system operating environment, fans, and heatsinks.
TMP0204.Message: CPU %1 temperature is outside of range.

RAC0150.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about system intrusion.
RAC0150.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0150.Message: Unable to retrieve the intrusion sensor information. The system is powered off.

RAC1145.Description: The value entered for the -t option is invalid.
RAC1145.Resolution: Check help text for the list of valid log types and retry the operation by entering a valid log type.
RAC1145.Message: The entered log type is invalid.

ASR0102.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was shutdown. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset - 02h event 3:0 - 4h).
ASR0102.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0102.Message: The OS watchdog timer shutdown the system.

SRV090.Description: The SupportAssist operation identified in the message did not complete successfully.
SRV090.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Logs for related errors and perform the recommended response actions for these error messages and then retry the operation.
SRV090.Message: The SupportAssist %1 operation did not complete successfully.

STOR061.Description: The initializing virtual disk operation is not supported on the target device.
STOR061.Resolution: For more information about supported operations, see the documentation specific for the targeted RAID controller or the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide.
STOR061.Message: Initializing virtual disk is not supported on the RAID controller.

RAC0671.Description: Going out of this page will not save the operations or configuration settings that were selected.
RAC0671.Resolution: Press OK to continue. Press Cancel to continue working on the page.
RAC0671.Message: Going out of this page will not save the operations or configuration settings that were selected.

USR0203.Description: The mobile device with the specified mac address did not enter proper authentication credentials within the required duration of time.
USR0203.Resolution: Press the activate button on the panel. Make sure that correct user name and password are entered, and then retry the operation.
USR0203.Message: Mobile device with MAC Address %1 was disconnected from Quick Sync interface because of authentication timeout.

CPU9001.Description: A correctable error was detected in propagation of signals between processors.
CPU9001.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Restart the server and verify whether or not the issue persists. 2) If yes, reseat the processors, and then restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your server provider.
CPU9001.Message: CPU interconnect %1 has a correctable error.

GMGR0067.Description: The group job cannot be scheduled for the requested operation because the maximum number of group jobs are already created. A maximum of 50 group jobs of all states are maintained by the Group Manager.
GMGR0067.Resolution: Delete the completed group jobs and retry the operation.
GMGR0067.Message: Unable to schedule a group job for the requested operation because the maximum number of group jobs are already created.

SEL1211.Description: The time stamp on system event log events may not correlate to the system time. (IPMI sensor type code 12h - offset 05h).
SEL1211.Resolution: Cycle system input power, if problem persists call support.
SEL1211.Message: The time-stamp clock could not be synchronized.

FCD8505.Description: Features cannot be deactivated when the chassis is turned on.
FCD8505.Resolution: Turn off the chassis via the Web interface or RACADM command line interface before deactivating the feature. To turn off the chassis using Racadm type "racadm chassisaction -m chassis powerdown". To deactivate the feature using RACADM, type "racadm <feature> -d" where <feature> is the name of the feature to be deactivated.
FCD8505.Message: The features cannot be deactivated when the chassis is turned on.

UEFI0107.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Read DQ/DQS initialization.
UEFI0107.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0107.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

RAC0138.Description: The retrieved certificate came back as a null or empty document.
RAC0138.Message: A valid certificate is not loaded.

BAR034.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller(iDRAC) firmware import did not complete successfully.
BAR034.Resolution: Download the firmware for the Integrated Remote Access Controller(iDRAC) and apply it.
BAR034.Message: Unable to Restore Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

SWC0002.Description: The Part Replacement policy configuration operation encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0002.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0002.Message: Unable to set Part Replacement policies.

TMP0103.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0103.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0103.Message: The system board %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SRV055.Description: All the Debug Logs cannot be collected because the log file size exceeds 30 MB. Only the latest debug logs up to 30 MB is collected.
SRV055.Message: Unable to collect all the Debug Logs because the log file size is more than 30 MB.

RED072.Description: Unable to delete the Automatic Backup schedule information because the schedule is not configured.
RED072.Message: Unable to delete the Automatic Backup schedule.

PWR8579.Description: A request to reset the CMC identified in the message is initiated. If a second CMC is present, a failover to the other CMC will occur as a result.
PWR8579.Message: Request to reset the CMC %1 is initiated.

SWU8536.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8536.Resolution: Make sure that the iKVM firmware image file is available at the specified location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8536.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because the Image file could not be accessed. ErrorCode=0x%1.

OSD57.Description: Remote File Share (RFS) is currently configured to be in auto-attach mode. For Web services to attach an ISO, RFS should be changed to attach mode.
OSD57.Resolution: Change the Remote File Share (RFS) mode to Attach using iDRAC GUI or Remote Services API and retry.
OSD57.Message: Remote File Share (RFS) is in Auto-Attach mode.

VLT0205.Message: The system board %1 voltage is within range.

BAT1010.Description: Battery is in warn only mode and requires reconditioning.
BAT1010.Resolution: Start a learn cycle on the battery.
BAT1010.Message: Battery on %1 requires reconditioning. Initiate a learn cycle.

OSD68.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareName' is missing.
OSD68.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ShareName" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD68.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareName' is missing.

SYS267.Description: Unable to transfer a file because the network connection from the proxy server to the remote host server is unsuccessful.
SYS267.Resolution: Make sure that correct file transfer parameters are set, the health of remote host is good, and then retry the operation.
SYS267.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the network connection from the proxy server to the remote host server is unsuccessful.

RDU0013.Description: The current power operational mode is non-redundant because of a power supply exception, a power supply inventory change, or a system power inventory change. The system was previously operating in a power redundant mode.
RDU0013.Resolution: Check the event log for power supply failures. Review system configuration and power consumption.

UEFI0190.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Clock DCC Training phase.
UEFI0190.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0190.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RAC1197.Description: The LCD panel firmware is successfully updated.
RAC1197.Message: The LCD panel firmware is successfully updated.

PWR2255.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is configured in Max Power Conservation Mode and is unable to grant power on permission to the server.
PWR2255.Resolution: Disable the Max Power Conservation Mode on the chassis and retry the operation. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Chassis Overview>Power>Configuration and then uncheck the Max Power Conservation Mode field.
PWR2255.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is configured in Max Power Conservation Mode and is unable to grant power on permission to the server.

RAC089.Description: The Server Port Connection data refresh operation is successfully completed.
RAC089.Message: The refresh operation of switch connection and switch port connection information of all network ports is completed successfully.

SYS005.Description: The AttributeName input array and AttributeValue input array do not have the same number of elements.
SYS005.Resolution: Verify AttributeName and AttributeValue pairs match and are valid. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation.
SYS005.Message: AttributeName array and AttributeValue array element count mismatch.

BIOS035.Description: The operation cannot be started because invalid hash signature parameter is entered.
BIOS035.Resolution: Make sure that correct parameters are entered and retry the operation.
BIOS035.Message: Unable to start the operation because invalid hash signature parameter is entered.

DIS015.Description: Auto Discovery client is using the default Certificate Authority certificate to authenticate the Provisioning Server for the SSL connection.
DIS015.Message: Auto Discovery client using default CA certificate to authenticate Provisioning Server.

SYS1002.Description: System is performing a power cycle.
SYS1002.Message: System is performing a power cycle.

SRV028.Description: The Operating System (OS) on the server did not complete the native OS Application Data Collection within the maximum allowed time.
SRV028.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the server Operating System (OS) and retry the operation.
SRV028.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the native Operating System (OS) Application Data Collection is taking more time than allocated.

SYS055.Description: The configuration specified in the Server Configuration Profile was applied, but there were some errors. The Lifecycle Controller Log contains the details of the component configurations that did not complete successfully.
SYS055.Resolution: Review the Lifecycle Controller Log and identify the configuration changes that did not complete successfully. Retry those changes in a separate operation.
SYS055.Message: Import of Server Configuration Profile operation completed with errors.

SYS147.Description: Starting non-secure erase-capable drives erase operations because of a System Erase operation request.
SYS147.Message: Starting non-secure erase-capable drive erase operations.

SWC0026.Description: Status of backup Server Profile operation could not be retrieved because an unrecoverable error occurred while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0026.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0026.Message: Unable to retrieve status of backup Server Profile operation.

LOG004.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in iDRAC firmware.
LOG004.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.

BAT1032.Description: The battery temperature is within the normal operating range.
BAT1032.Message: The battery temperature on %1 is normal.

SWC8560.Description: New Media Access Control (MAC) addresses are added to the Virtual MAC Address Pool.
SWC8560.Message: %1 New Media Access Control (MAC) addresses are added to the Virtual MAC Address Pool for Boot Identity profile operations.

LC016.Description: A required method argument was missing.
LC016.Resolution: Include all the parameters required for the command. Check Lifecycle Controller Profile documentation and try again.

UEFI0225.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the DDR4 LR-DIMM Receive Buffer Training phase.
UEFI0225.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0225.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC0675.Description: Results are not available for the search criterion entered.
RAC0675.Resolution: Enter another criterion and retry the operation.
RAC0675.Message: Results are not available for the search criterion entered.

SYS079.Description: The Preview operation indicates the input file for Server Configuration Profile is not compliant with the configuration profile schema.
SYS079.Resolution: Make sure that the input file is compliant with the system configuration XML schema published on www.delltechcenter.com/lc.
SYS079.Message: The Preview operation indicates the input file for Server Configuration Profile is not compliant with the configuration profile schema.

PCI3011.Message: The component at bus %1 device %2 function %3 recovered from a non-fatal IO error.

SYS408.Description: Only one task ID is displayed. By default, the location response header displays information about only one task ID.
SYS408.Resolution: To view all task IDs, run the "Tasks" Redfish API.
SYS408.Message: Only one task ID is displayed in the response.

RAC1008.Description: The Active Directory object DCLookupByUserDomain cannot be disabled, because the Active Directory object DCLookupDomainName is not configured.
RAC1008.Resolution: Configure the Active Directory object DCLookupDomainName using "racadm set iDRAC.ActiveDirectory.DCLookupDomainName <Name>", and retry the operation.
RAC1008.Message: The Active Directory object DCLookupByUserDomain cannot be disabled.

UEFI0103.Description: One or more memory initialization error have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0103.Resolution: Replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0103.Message: One or more memory initialization errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

RAC0266.Resolution: Enter a valid VLan ID. Expected range: 1-4094.

UEFI0290.Description: The Sub-NUMA Cluster (SNC) mode cannot be enabled because of mismatches in the memory configuration.
UEFI0290.Resolution: Check the Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) population to make sure that the Sub-NUMA Cluster (SNC) mode can be enabled. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0290.Message: Unable to configure the Sub-NUMA Cluster (SNC) mode because of mismatches in the memory configuration.

OSD60.Description: Connecting ISO using Remote File Share (RFS) was unsuccessful.
OSD60.Resolution: Verify ISO is connected using Remote File Share (RFS) and retry the operation.
OSD60.Message: Unable to connect to ISO using Remote File Share (RFS).

SWC0725.Description: iDRAC is busy and does not respond to iDRAC configurator IPMI requests.
SWC0725.Resolution: Try AC power cycling the server or upgrade the iDRAC firmware.

RAC0255.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv4 Subnet Mask does not conform to the required format.
RAC0255.Resolution: Enter a valid Subnet Mask. Expected ranges are: 255.XXX.0.0 [Class A], 255.255.XXX.0 [Class B], 255.255.255.XXX [Class C], and XXX.0.0.0 [others], where XXX must be valid (0,128,192,224,240,248,252,254).
RAC0255.Message: The Subnet Mask is invalid. Expected ranges are: 255.XXX.0.0 [Class A], 255.255.XXX.0 [Class B], 255.255.255.XXX [Class C], and XXX.0.0.0 [others], where XXX must be valid (0,128,192,224,240,248,252,254).

SYS124.Description: The OS and Application data collection by the OS Collector application is unable to execute on the OS installed on the server because the OS is not supported.
SYS124.Message: OS Collector: The OS Collector application does not support execution in the OS installed on the server.

VLT0101.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0101.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0101.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

DIS109.Description: The server could not be configured because the End Host Power State value specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC is incorrect.
DIS109.Resolution: In the DHCP scope option field where VendorID=iDRAC, enter a end-host-power-state (-e <0 or 1>) where 0 = Powered Off and = Powered On, and then retry the operation.
DIS109.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because an invalid End Host Power State value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

GMGR0053.Resolution: Do any one of the following: 1) Change the current group name. 2) Log in to the other group and change the other group's name. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

SWC0287.Description: The value of a parameter in the config file is invalid.

SEC0001.Description: The drive bay is open. A drive may be added or removed. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0001.Resolution: Close the drive bay. Check system logs.

SWC0064.Description: The details provided to access the network share are incorrect.
SWC0064.Resolution: Enter the correct network share details, and retry the operation.
SWC0064.Message: Unable to mount the network share.

LC041.Description: The length of the Console name exceeds the maximum length allowed or the file operation error encountered.
LC041.Resolution: Change the name of a console to a name less than 32 characters.

SWC8549.Description: The status of Media Access Control (MAC) address identified in the message is not valid. Possible MAC address status values are unassign, assign and active.
