The value is "unassigned" if the MAC address is not used in any profile. The value is "assigned" if the MAC address used in a profile. The value is "active" if used in a profile applied to a server. The status must be same for all Virtual MAC addresses if assigned to a profile.
SWC8549.Resolution: Edit the Virtual MAC Address Pool to correct the MAC address status. Possible MAC address status values are unassign, assign and active. The value is "unassigned" if the MAC address is not used in any profile. The value is "assigned" if the MAC address used in a profile. The value is "active" if used in a profile applied to a server. The status must be same for all Virtual MAC addresses if assigned to a profile.
SWC8549.Message: The status of Media Access Control (MAC) address %1 is not valid for Boot Identity profile operations.

SYS245.Description: The file cannot be transferred because a proxy username value is not entered, or the entered value is not supported.
SYS245.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy username value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS245.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported proxy username value.

UEFI0121.Description: The primary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.
UEFI0121.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Install a SD card media in the primary SD card slot. 2) Reseat or replace the SD card media. 3) If write-protected mode is expected, then no response action is required.
UEFI0121.Message: The primary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.

RAC0221.Description: The Destination E-mail Address can contain up to 64 characters.
RAC0221.Resolution: Enter an email address that contains up to 64 characters.
RAC0221.Message: The Destination E-mail Address is too long. The maximum length is 64 characters.

STOR317.Description: A disk drive group has a limit on the minimum and maximum number of disk drives it can have on the basis of its Virtual Disk RAID level. When a reconfiguration operation is specified with additional physical disks the total number of physical disks should be in the disk group's permissible range.
STOR317.Resolution: Enter the correct number of physical disks for the reconfiguration operation and retry the operation. The number of physical disks in a disk group must be within the disk group's permissible range. For information about the minimum and maximum possible physical disks in a disk group, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide available at the support site.
STOR317.Message: Unable to perform the reconfiguration operation because the number of physical disks specified in the disk group is not as per the permitted range.

SWC8553.Description: The profile identified in the message is not valid.
SWC8553.Resolution: Edit the profile and make sure no XML schema or configuration errors are present and then retry the operation.

RAC1154.Description: The requested techsupreport collect or export operation is initiated.
RAC1154.Resolution: Run the RACADM jobqueue sub-command, using the job id to check the status of the requested operation.

JCP033.Description: This job is newly created. This is the default message in a job when it has just been created.

MEM1001.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM1001.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to transition to a running state.

SWU8550.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful.
SWU8550.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8550.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Standby CMC and Active CMC.

USR0184.Description: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature has been disconnected and the feature is not available.
USR0184.Resolution: Connect a bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature. Press the activate button to enable the Quick Sync feature.
USR0184.Message: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature has been disconnected and the feature is not available.

CMC8575.Description: The RAC SSL Certificate is changed.
CMC8575.Message: The RAC SSL Certificate is changed.

UEFI0124.Description: The size and speed of the primary SD card do not match those of the secondary SD card. The secondary SD card needs to have equal or greater capacity and speed than the primary SD card.
UEFI0124.Resolution: Replace the secondary SD card with one that has equal or greater capacity and speed than the primary SD card.
UEFI0124.Message: The size and speed of the secondary SD card do not match those of the primary SD card.

RAC0502.Description: Virtual disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off or there are no virtual disks created.
RAC0502.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Check if virtual disks are created.
RAC0502.Message: There are no virtual disks to be displayed.

RAC927.Description: The recurrence value was successfully modified to the specified value.

SWC0068.Description: The BIOS boot mode settings could not be retrieved because of an internal issue.
SWC0068.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit Lifecycle Controller and perform an AC power cycle.
SWC0068.Message: Unable to retrieve the boot mode settings from BIOS.

NIC502.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC502.Resolution: Enable DHCP on the NIC before enabling it for DNS.
NIC502.Message: DHCP is required to be enabled on the NIC before DHCP can be enabled for DNS server or domain name objects.

BAT0009.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may report absent due to disconnect or thermal exceptions.
BAT0009.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation.2) If installed, reseat or reconnect the battery and cables. 3) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.

PST0193.Description: System BIOS POST memory test failed. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code C1).
PST0193.Resolution: Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce system configuration to minimum memory configuration.

FAN0018.Description: Enhanced Cooling Mode is not supported by the type of fan identified in the message.
FAN0018.Resolution: Replace the fan identified in the message with another fan which supports Enhanced Cooling Mode.
FAN0018.Message: Enhanced Cooling Mode is not supported for fan %1.

RAC0759.Description: A running Tech Support Report job has been cancelled.
RAC0759.Resolution: Click Job Queue button to view the status of the cancelled job.
RAC0759.Message: A running Tech Support Report job has been cancelled.

SWU8514.Description: The IOM infrastructure firmware update operation is not successful.
SWU8514.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source folder, and then retry the operation.
SWU8514.Message: Unable to update the IOM infrastructure firmware of slot %1. ErrorCode=0x%2.

USR0014.Description: The user session which is currently in use is invalid.
USR0014.Message: The current user session is invalid.

HWC2003.Description: The cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC2003.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC2003.Message: The storage %1 cable is not connected, or is improperly connected.

VDR42.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR42.Message: Dedicated hot spare assigned physical disk %1.

OSD23.Description: Cannot continue with DetachISOImage because another command is in the process of exposing the ISO image and booting to it.
OSD23.Resolution: See the ConcreteJob status to make sure that the current running process is complete and then run DetachISOImage.
OSD23.Message: Unable to continue with DetachISOImage - another command is in the process of exposing the ISO Image and booting to it.

RAC977.Description: The configuration XML file import operation was initiated.
RAC977.Resolution: Use the racadm jobqueue view i <Job ID> command to view the status of the operation.
RAC977.Message: Import configuration XML file operation initiated.

RAC069.Description: Unable to complete the operation because the string length is less than the minimum supported length.
RAC069.Resolution: Enter a string value that is greater than the minimum supported length and retry the operation.
RAC069.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the string length is less than the minimum supported length.

LC030.Description: The file path specified for the operation is a read-only file system.
LC030.Resolution: Enable write access to the file path and try again.
LC030.Message: The file path is to a read-only file system.

FAN8501.Description: Disabling Enhanced Cooling Mode allows for reduced power consumption by reducing the maximum speed of the blowers while still providing sufficient blade airflow.

STOR0511.Description: Unable to change the encryption key due to an internal error.
STOR0511.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
STOR0511.Message: Unable to change the encryption key.

SWC0288.Description: The object specified in the message in the group specified in the message is not configured.
SWC0288.Resolution: Configure the object specified in the message in specified group, before performing a config to file action.
SWC0288.Message: Object %1 in %2 group must be specified. Line: %3

SWC0226.Description: The Remote/Firmware racadm did not find any AD/LDAP certificate at specified path.
SWC0226.Message: No valid directory service certificate exists

PCI5009.Description: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected that a PCIe adapter was removed from a server which was turned-on. This may cause the server operating system to stop responding or to function in an improper manner.
PCI5009.Resolution: Perform a 'Power Cycle' operation on the associated server. Restarting the operating system will not resolve this issue. Only remove PCIe adapters when the associated server is turned-off.
PCI5009.Message: The PCIe adapter in the PCIe slot%1 was removed from the slot while the server%2 was turned-on.

UEFI0312.Description: The Baseboard UPI C cable connection is misconfigured.
UEFI0312.Resolution: Connect the Baseboard UPI C cable. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0312.Message: The Baseboard UPI C cable connection is misconfigured.

SWC0047.Description: The passphrase specified is not correct.
SWC0047.Resolution: Enter the valid passphrase and retry the operation.
SWC0047.Message: Incorrect backup Server Configuration Profile file passphrase provided.

CMC8532.Description: The user account does not have sufficient privileges to perform the requested operation. Server Administrator privilege is required to perform the requested action.
CMC8532.Resolution: Use a different user account that has Server Administrator privilege, and retry the operation. For more information, contact your system administrator or service provider.
CMC8532.Message: Unable to perform the requested action on the peripheral sled %1, because of insufficient privileges.

RAC0231.Description: This message is displayed when a confirmation is required to format the vFlash SD Card partition.
RAC0231.Resolution: Press OK to initialize this partition of the SD Card. This action will erase all the data in this partition. If undesired press Cancel.
RAC0231.Message: This operation erases all data in the partition. Do you want to continue?

PDR82.Description: Security on a secure encrypted disk was activated.

RAC0688.Description: Applying this configuration operation will also apply all existing pending operations on the controller identified in the message.
RAC0688.Resolution: Click Create Job button to create the configuration job. Click Cancel to quit job creation.
RAC0688.Message: Applying this configuration operation will also apply all existing pending operations on the %1.

RAC943.Description: The Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is currently disabled. If the system inventory is not up-to-date, the system configuration profile that is being copied will not have the latest inventory information.
RAC943.Resolution: To get latest inventory information, cancel the current export job, run "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart 1" to enable CSIOR, and re-initiate the export operation.
RAC943.Message: Warning: Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

RAC1011.Description: The OS to iDRAC pass-through cannot be enabled, because the NIC is in Dedicated mode.
RAC1011.Resolution: Change the iDRAC NIC mode to shared mode using "racadm set idrac.nic.selection <value>", and retry the operation.
RAC1011.Message: The OS to iDRAC pass-through cannot be enabled.

SYS410.Description: The attribute cannot be modified because the attribute is read-only and depends on other attributes. Some attributes have dependencies on other attributes that are required to perform a task. However, some of the attributes are read-only because of the current system configuration and the values of the dependent attributes.
SYS410.Resolution: Verify if the attribute has dependency on other attributes and retry the operation. To verify, view the attribute registry based on the type of resource.
SYS410.Message: Unable to modify the attribute because the attribute is read-only and depends on other attributes.

LC0100.Description: A persistent error has occurred while carrying out a Lifecycle Controller operation. This situation causes Lifecycle Controller to enter Recovery mode. Any remote jobs pending execution were cancelled.
LC0100.Resolution: To verify or change Recovery mode, use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings. Updating Lifecycle Controller clears the Recovery mode.
LC0100.Message: Lifecycle Controller has entered Recovery mode.

SRV125.Description: The SupportAssist operation cannot be started because the Lifecycle Controller is in use.
SRV125.Resolution: Make sure all other Lifecycle Controller operations are finished and retry the operation. Using the iDRAC Web UI, select Server > Job Queue, check the job queue for unfinished jobs and wait for the jobs to finish before retrying the operation. Also, check whether there are update packages being executed in the server OS and wait for these operations to finish before retrying the operation. For remote web services API access, make sure that the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status, and then retry the operation.
SRV125.Message: Unable to start the SupportAssist operation because the Lifecycle Controller is in use.

FAN0015.Description: The cooling device is not performing optimally. The cooling device may be installed improperly.
FAN0015.Resolution: Remove and re-install the cooling device. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0015.Message: %1 RPM is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SYS232.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported destination file path value.
SYS232.Resolution: Make sure that the correct destination file path value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS232.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported destination file path value.

CPU0008.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.
CPU0008.Resolution: If unexpected, check presence, and system setup (BIOS) configuration.

LNK8500.Description: The server identified in the message could not be successfully connected to the external network, because the network connection is not functional.
LNK8500.Resolution: Do one of the following, and then retry the operation: 1) Check whether or not the external network cable is functioning. 2) Reinstall or replace network cable of the IOM and port identified in the message.
LNK8500.Message: Unable to connect the server in slot %1 to the IOM in slot %2 port %3, because the IOM port is down.

UEFI0078.Description: One or more Machine Check errors occurred in the previous boot.
UEFI0078.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the source of the Machine Check error and resolve the issues.
UEFI0078.Message: One or more Machine Check errors occurred in the previous boot.

LIC023.Description: An unauthorized iDRAC license version is being used.
LIC023.Resolution: Obtain an authorized iDRAC license version. For more information, contact your service provider. Also, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
LIC023.Message: An unauthorized iDRAC license version is being used.

RAC0239.Description: The contents of a write protected SD Card cannot be modified.
RAC0239.Resolution: Make sure the SD Card is not write-protected before attempting to change its contents.

BOOT016.Description: The input source argument value referring to the boot device is incorrect or empty. The boot device identifier must match the InstanceID for the Boot Source Setting instance that represents the boot device.
BOOT016.Resolution: Use the correct source argument value for the boot device and retry the operation.
BOOT016.Message: Input source argument value for the boot device is incorrect or not found among the boot devices on the system.

SWC0157.Message: User certificate successfully uploaded to the RAC.

SUP0515.Description: Lifecycle Controller was unable to authenticate the Update Package digital signature. The Update Package will not be applied unless it has a valid digital signature.
SUP0515.Resolution: Download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0515.Message: Unable to authenticate the Update Package signature.

RAC802.Description: iDRAC time has been set through Network Time Protocol (NTP).
RAC802.Message: iDRAC time is set using Network Time Protocol.

GMGR0002.Description: The iDRAC local group with a name identified in the message is successfully created. Current iDRAC continues to be the Primary Controller of iDRAC local group.
GMGR0002.Message: The iDRAC local group %1 is successfully created.

SYS274.Description: The file identified in the message cannot be applied because of one or more missing firmware update prerequisites.
SYS274.Resolution: Make sure that the prerequisite firmware updates are installed, and then retry updating the firmware. For information about prerequisite firmware, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS274.Message: Unable to apply the firmware file %1 because one or more missing firmware update prerequisites.

SWC1921.Description: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is disabled.
SWC1921.Message: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is disabled.

UEFI0070.Description: One or more correctable PCIe errors have occurred. Data about the errors are logged into SEL during the POST operation.
UEFI0070.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCIe device, and then update its firmware.
UEFI0070.Message: One or more correctable PCIe errors have occurred.

AMP0317.Message: System level current is within range.

PDR41.Description: The clear command did not complete on the physical disk. This means that some data was not cleared and may be recoverable.
PDR41.Message: The clear operation on %1 was cancelled.

GMGR0035.Description: The group job identified in the message is successfully cancelled.
GMGR0035.Message: The group job %1 is successfully cancelled.

RAC1133.Description: The BIOSRTDRequested attribute was modified successfully. The BIOS reset to default values operation is pending a server restart.
RAC1133.Resolution: To apply the BIOS default values, restart the server. After the server has restarted, the default BIOS values will be accessible from the iDRAC.
RAC1133.Message: BIOSRTDRequested value is modified successfully. The BIOS reset to default values operation is pending a server restart.

VDR49.Description: A redundant virtual disk has lost redundancy. This may occur when the virtual disk suffers the failure of more than one physical disk. In this case, both the source physical disk and the target disk with redundant data have failed. A rebuild is not possible because there is no longer redundancy.
VDR49.Resolution: Replace the failed disks and restore from backup.

SEL1306.Description: The disk in the drive is not formatted correctly or does not contain the necessary operating system files (IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 03h).

SWU8556.Description: The sled network uplink on the sled identified in the message could not be configured. The servers on the sled may not have expected network connectivity.
SWU8556.Resolution: Perform a Virtual Reseat operation, and then retry the operation. To virtually reseat a server 1) Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components, and then select slot for the component identified in the message and apply the Virtual Reseat or 2) Run the following RACADM command at the command line interface: "racadm serveraction -f -m sled-<slot number> reseat".
SWU8556.Message: Unable to configure the sled network uplink on sled %1.

RAC970.Description: The import operation cannot continue if the value specified for the end power state of the system option (-s) is incorrect. The supported values are "On" and "Off".
RAC970.Resolution: Make sure to specify either "On" or "Off" for the end power state (-s) option.
RAC970.Message: Incorrect value specified for the end power state option.

VF029.Description: The user account credentials provided for this vFlash operation do not have the correct privileges. Virtual Media Access privilege is required to perform vFlash SD Card media operations.
VF029.Resolution: Use a different user account the has Virtual Media Access privilege.

PCI1306.Resolution: Reboot the system and update the component drivers.
PCI1306.Message: A software error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

SEC0610.Description: This may apply to a remote access attempt.
SEC0610.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

IOV001.Description: The operation or operation parameter sent to the Chassis Manager is invalid or not supported.
IOV001.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to Chassis Manager product documentation to determine the contact method for the service provider.
IOV001.Message: The operation contains an invalid request or argument.

SUP0123.Resolution: Re-connect to the iDRAC after a minute.
SUP0123.Message: Firmware update completed successfully. The RAC is in the process of resetting. Your connection will be lost. Please wait up to a minute before starting a new session.

PWR8597.Description: The identified Power Supply Unit (PSU) is turned off because it is not supported by the Chassis.
PWR8597.Resolution: Replace the PSU identified in the message with an appropriate unit, and then retry the operation. For a list of PSUs that are compatible, consult the system Owner's Manual or contact your service provider.
PWR8597.Message: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) %1 is turned off because it is not supported by the Chassis.

SWU8541.Description: The PSU firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8541.Resolution: Make sure that the PSU firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8541.Message: Unable to update the PSU firmware, because the Image file is not accessible. ErrorCode=0x%1.

RAC1203.Description: The Secure Boot Certificate Import operation is successfully scheduled. For the changes to become effective, restart the host server.
RAC1203.Message: The Secure Boot Certificate Import operation is successfully scheduled.

PCI1342.Description: System performance may be degraded. The device has failed to respond to a transaction (master/target abort or completion timeout).
PCI1342.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1342.Message: A bus time-out was detected on a component at slot %1.

RAC0235.Description: When uploading an image to the vFlash partition, the operation is unresponsive, and has timed out.
RAC0235.Resolution: Try uploading the vFlash image again.

PDR81.Description: The physical disk firmware update operation has started.

UEFI0247.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. The requested Memory Mapped IO (MMIOH) size is not supported. MMIOH allocation was forced instead.
UEFI0247.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0247.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

MEM9009.Description: A correctable error was detected in the propagation of signals on the Intel DDR memory interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9009.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reseat all DIMMs on the memory riser, 2) Reseat the memory riser, and 3) Restart the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9009.Message: Intel DDR Memory interconnect %1 has a correctable error.

CTL97.Description: The controller identified in the message has been changed to a new personality mode (HBA or RAID).

STOR062.Description: One or more physical disks specified are full and cannot be used to create additional virtual disks.
STOR062.Resolution: Make sure all physical disks specified to create a virtual disk have the required amount of free space and retry the operation.
STOR062.Message: One or more physical disks specified are full and cannot be used to create additional virtual disks.

RAC1137.Description: Remote unattended diagnostic results export operation initiated.
RAC1137.Resolution: Using the RACADM command line interface, run the "racadm jobqueue view -i <job id>" command to view the status of the operation.
RAC1137.Message: Remote unattended diagnostic results export operation initiated.

STOR0701.Description: There are no RAID controllers, physical disks or virtual disks discovered by instrumentation that can be configured.
STOR0701.Resolution: Storage objects are unavailable in the current system configuration. Make sure that the storage devices are installed in the system, and then retry the operation after the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature has updated the system inventory. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
STOR0701.Message: Storage objects are unavailable in the current system configuration.

RAC073.Description: The iDRAC reset operation cannot be completed because a vFlash partition creation operation is in progress.
RAC073.Resolution: Wait for the vFlash partition creation process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC073.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset operation because a vFlash partition creation operation is in progress.

IOID113.Description: The initiator properties of the NIC port could not be configured because either iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is not enabled, or the network controller is not functioning.
IOID113.Resolution: Make sure that the iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is enabled. Check whether or not the network controller is working and then retry the operation.
IOID113.Message: Unable to configure the initiator properties of %1 Port %2.

SWC0207.Message: Display the version info of RACADM

PST0135.Description: System BIOS detected a timer refresh failure during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 87).
PST0135.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

VDR32.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk has started. This is an automated process that writes the parity or mirror data on newly created virtual disks.

LC034.Description: The As-Shipped from the factory Hardware Inventory information is not present on the system.
LC034.Message: Unable to retrieve As-Shipped Hardware Inventory from the system.

UEFI0047.Description: One or more keys in the keyboard is stuck and not functional.
UEFI0047.Resolution: Make sure that the key is not stuck in the keyboard and retry the operation.
UEFI0047.Message: One or more keys in the keyboard is stuck and not functional.

SYS415.Description: The operation cannot be completed because an invalid username and/or password is entered, and therefore authentication failed.
SYS415.Resolution: Enter valid user name and password and retry the operation.
SYS415.Message: Unable to complete the operation because an invalid username and/or password is entered, and therefore authentication failed.

RAC1181.Description: USB Management Port state cannot be changed because of an unknown hardware or firmware issue.
RAC1181.Resolution: To change the Management Port mode settings do the following: If a device is present, remove and reinsert the USB device from the front panel USB Management port and retry the operation. If the issue persists restart the iDRAC and retry the operation.
RAC1181.Message: Unable to change USB Management Port mode.

SYS013.Description: The attribute name provided for the requested operation does not exist on the target system or is invalid.
SYS013.Resolution: For more information, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

RAC0115.Description: The IPv4 address does not conform to the addressing standard or the supported IPv4 address range.
RAC0115.Resolution: Enter the Destination IP Address value between [1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0115.Message: The Destination IP Address value is invalid.

SWC1918.Description: HTTP to HTTPS redirection is enabled. Any iDRAC connection made over the HTTP port (default port number 80) will be redirected to the secure HTTPS port (default port number 443).

MEM9032.Description: The NVDIMM device in the slot identified in the message is unable to restore the data that was saved in the previous 'save' operation. The NVDIMM is placed in write-protect mode.
MEM9032.Resolution: Remove and reinstall the Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device. If the issue persists, contact your service provider. For information about removing and reinstalling the NVDIMM, see the system Owner's Manual on the support site.
MEM9032.Message: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device in the slot %1 is unable to restore the data that was saved in the previous 'save' operation.

PDR37.Description: The physical device may not have a supported version of the firmware or the physical device may not be supported.
PDR37.Resolution: If the physical device is supported, then update the firmware to a supported version. If the physical device is not supported, then replace the physical device with one that is supported.

RAC1072.Description: The maximum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is less than or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.
RAC1072.Resolution: Check the minimum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the minimum critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1072.Message: Unable to set maximum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is less than, or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.

CMC8503.Description: CMC is unable to access the IPv4 information for the specified server. Unable to display the specified server's Launch iDRAC link on the CMC Web interface.
CMC8503.Resolution: Enable IPv4 on the specified slot's iDRAC via the CMC command line or Web GUI interface, for the iDRAC's launch point to show up on the CMC web GUI. For the command line options or navigation for Web interface, see the Troubleshooting section in the CMC User's Guide.
CMC8503.Message: Unable to access the IPv4 information of the server.

HWC2012.Description: The fabric type on the server does not match that of the IO module.
HWC2012.Resolution: Check chassis fabric type in CMC GUI and compare to the type of IOM or mezzanine card.
HWC2012.Message: A fabric mismatch detected on fabric %1 with server in slot %2.

SEL1207.Message: An entry was removed from auxiliary log.

TMP0300.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is enabled.
TMP0300.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is enabled.

RAC0745.Description: There are no pending operations on the selected component group.
RAC0745.Message: There are no pending operations present on the selected component group.

SYS033.Description: The staged component configuration update performed in the UEFI environment on the host system has completed, but there were errors.
SYS033.Message: Staged component configuration completed with errors.

CTL18.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL18.Message: Load Balance and Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.

MEM1013.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in a full state.

UEFI0158.Description: The iDRAC request to reset BIOS to default settings cannot be completed.
UEFI0158.Resolution: Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0158.Message: Unable to complete the iDRAC request to reset BIOS to default settings.

PWR2272.Description: The power required by server exceeds the power supplied by the PSUs.
PWR2272.Resolution: Check the power supply unit (PSUs) configuration, and then upgrade the PSU, if necessary.
PWR2272.Message: The power required by server exceeds the power supplied by the power supply units (PSUs).

SYS032.Description: The staged component configuration update performed in the UEFI environment on the host system is complete.

CTL34.Description: This is the result of a user operation.
CTL34.Message: A foreign configuration was cleared on %1.

BAT0012.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may have failed because of thermal exceptions.
BAT0012.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation for the associated bay.2) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.
BAT0012.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 has failed.

STOR16.Description: The configuration of the storage sled in the slot identified in the message is normal.
STOR16.Message: The storage sled %1 configuration is normal.

UEFI0260.Description: The R930 baseboard does not support R920 memory risers.
UEFI0260.Resolution: Replace R920 memory risers with R930 memory risers. For information about the supported memory riser types, see the Owners Manual available at the support site.
UEFI0260.Message: The R930 baseboard does not support R920 memory risers.

UEFI0252.Description: The watchdog timer is armed before the BIOS boot manager invokes an UEFI boot option. The watchdog is set to a period of 5 minutes. The Operating System boot loader from the boot option is required to disable the watchdog timer after it is successfully loaded, otherwise the system will reset if the timer expires.
UEFI0252.Resolution: Check the boot option image and boot loader. Update them to the latest version if possible.
UEFI0252.Message: Unable to boot a boot option because the watchdog timer has expired. System will reset.

RDU8509.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.
RDU8509.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8509.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover, chassis is in non-redundant state

USR0008.Description: The Default Login Warning feature is disabled. No warning is provided if any local user is configured with default credentials.
USR0008.Message: The Default Login Warning feature is disabled.

TMP8503.Description: The NIC adapter in the slot identified in the message may have temperature related issues. The device temperature suggests degraded cooling or possibly a fan not functioning correctly on the adapter card (if adapter card has a fan).
TMP8503.Resolution: The cooling system may have issues. Contact your authorized Customer Service representative for further assistance.
TMP8503.Message: Temperature of NIC adapter in slot %1 is greater than normal operating range possibly due to an issue in the cooling system or a fan that is no longer functioning correctly.

RAC1142.Description: The Remote diagnostic operation cannot be performed because the difference between "Start Time" and "Expiration Time" is less than 5 minutes.
RAC1142.Resolution: Make sure that the Expiration Time is greater than five minutes, and then retry the operation.
RAC1142.Message: Unable to start the Remote Diagnostics operation because the Expiration Time entered (difference between Start Time and Expiration Time) is less than five minutes.

RRDU0007.Description: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild completed successfully.
RRDU0007.Message: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild completed successfully.

SYS083.Description: Unable to export ePSA Diagnostics results because iDRAC internal storage could not be accessed.
SYS083.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Delete all jobs, 2) Reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and 3) Retry the operation.
SYS083.Message: Unable to export ePSA Diagnostics results because iDRAC internal storage could not be accessed.

PWR1007.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1007.Resolution: Review system configuration, upgrade power supplies or reduce system power consumption.
PWR1007.Message: The system performance degraded because power exceeds capacity.

RAC955.Description: The specified record does not exist in the Lifecycle Log.
RAC955.Resolution: Run the racadm lclog view -i command to get the sequence number of the records logged in the Lifecycle Log, and retry the command with a valid sequence number.
RAC955.Message: Unable to retrieve the information related to the specified record in the Lifecycle Log.

ISM0013.Description: The feature identified in the message is enabled by using the one of the iDRAC interfaces.

BAR110.Description: All the existing jobs are canceled during the Import Server Profile operation or if the Import operation fails.
BAR110.Resolution: Resubmit any jobs that were cancelled by the Import operation after the Import Server Profile operation completes.
BAR110.Message: All existing jobs cancelled because of Import Server Profile request processing.

USR0190.Description: The peak value of the sensor identified in the message is reset.
USR0190.Message: Peak value is reset for %1 sensor.

SWC8526.Description: Unable to delete Chassis Group member identified in the message. Another user may have deleted the member before the operation or the group may have been disbanded.
SWC8526.Resolution: Make sure the member identified in the message exists as a member of the Chassis Group. Use the CMC web interface to select the lead chassis, select the setup tab, and then select the group administration sub tab and check if the member exists. If the member exists, restart the group leader and retry the operation.
SWC8526.Message: Unable to delete Chassis Group member %1 (%2)

GMGR0012.Description: The new iDRAC local group cannot be created in Group Manager either because a group with the same name already exists, Service tag not setup for the system or there is an error in network connection.
GMGR0012.Resolution: Do any one of the following and retry the operation: a) Check if another group with the same name appears in the Group Manager Discovered Groups view. b) Verify the system has a servicetag setup c) Verify your network settings. d) Restart iDRAC.
GMGR0012.Message: Unable to create new iDRAC local group either because a group with the same name already exists, Service tag not setup for the server or there is an error in network connection.

CBL0006.Description: Each server model only supports a certain set of backplane configurations. For unified backplanes or split mode capable backplanes that are in unified mode, multiple controllers cannot be connected to the same backplane. In unified backplane situations any controller besides the first will not be operational.
CBL0006.Resolution: Make sure that only one RAID controller is connected to the backplane. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0006.Message: Unsupported backplane %1 configuration: Multiple RAID controllers cannot be connected to the same backplane.

UEFI0079.Description: One or more Uncorrectable Memory errors occurred in the previous boot.
UEFI0079.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the non-functional DIMM, and then replace the DIMM.
UEFI0079.Message: One or more Uncorrectable Memory errors occurred in the previous boot.

RAC0685.Description: A pending operation has been created for this operation identified in the message.
RAC0685.Resolution: To view the pending operations click the Pending Operations button.
RAC0685.Message: A pending operation has been created for this %1 operation.

PDR39.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR39.Message: A blink operation has initiated on %1.

SUP0532.Description: The repository contains corrupt Update Packages.
SUP0532.Resolution: Enter another repository location that contains the desired Update Packages and retry the operation.
SUP0532.Message: The repository contains corrupt Update Packages.

SEL9901.Description: The current software version cannot decode this event. The source of the event may come from a source that is not compatible with this software or the event may have been added after the release of this software. You may need to review this event using a tool which displays raw data such as Ipmitool with the -vvv option or Racadm with the -E option.
SEL9901.Resolution: See product documentation for additional information.

SWC0045.Description: The Import operation did not successfully complete. For more information, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0045.Resolution: Exit the Import Server Profile wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0045.Message: Unable to complete the Import operation.

FC015.Description: A set attribute operation was not successful because the attribute is read-only.

SWC4007.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between system BIOS in slot %1 and CMC.

UEFI0014.Description: A CPU alignment check exception (type 0x11) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0014.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

SWC8539.Description: The Public Key (PK) SSH Authentication key file delete operation is successfully completed for the slot identified in the message.
SWC8539.Message: The key delete operation successfully completed for slot %1 of service account.

OSE0005.Description: Graceful shutdown request to an agent via the BMC did not occur due to a system hardware or software exception.
OSE0005.Resolution: Review operating system logs and system video for additional information.

PDR26.Description: A drive has entered the online state. This may be because the system just started or could be because a problem with the drive has been corrected.

SUP0111.Message: Timeout waiting for firmware update process to complete.

SUP005.Description: Reboot value specified is not supported.
SUP005.Resolution: Verify the reboot value and retry the action. Current options available are 1)Power Cycle 2) Graceful shutdown without forced shutdown 3) Graceful shutdown with forced shutdown (~10 minutes wait time).

SYS279.Description: iDRAC is not ready for processing ISM requests. Retry after 1 minute.
SYS279.Message: iDRAC is not ready for processing ISM requests. Retry after 1 minute.

RAC0683.Description: Unable to perform split mode configuration on enclosure(s).
RAC0683.Resolution: Check the following: 1) The controller must have Real Time Configuration Capability and the associated enclosure(s) must have Split Mode Capability in order to perform the operation. 2)The controller(s) associated with the enclosure(s) support real time configuration. To verify the controller real time configuration support, go to the Controller Properties page, select the required controller and verify the Real Time Configuration Capability value.3)The enclosure(s) supports split mode configuration. To verify the enclosure, go to the Enclosure Properties page, select the required enclosure, and verify the Enclosure Split Mode Capability property value.
RAC0683.Message: Unable to perform split mode configuration on enclosure(s).

FC002.Description: Unable to allocate memory required to perform the operation.
FC002.Resolution: Perform an AC power cycle and retry Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC firmware update.

PFM0002.Description: The utilization value of the sensor identified in the message is higher than the upper warning threshold.
PFM0002.Resolution: Check the work load of the server and reduce the workload if necessary to bring the system performance into required ranges. For more information about the specified values, see the relevant product documentation available at the support site.
PFM0002.Message: The value of %1 is greater than the upper warning threshold.

SWC9001.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate DeleteAll operation cannot be completed because of an internal error or insufficient space in certificate store.
SWC9001.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, free some space in the certificate store by deleting few certificates, restart iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SWC9001.Message: Unable to complete the SecureBoot Certificate DeleteAll operation because of an internal error or insufficient space in certificate store.

SRV038.Description: An issue occurred while loading the OS Collector IPMI library. This may be because the OS collector binary images are not valid and need to be re-installed.
SRV038.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SRV038.Message: The OS Collector application is unable to communicate with IPMI library.

PWR8555.Description: The request to turn on the component identified in the message was not successful because insufficient power is available at the identified priority for the component.
PWR8555.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis.
PWR8555.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to turn on %1-%2 at priority %3 because of insufficient power. Minimum power needed is %4 AC Watt, but only %5 AC Watt is available.

RAC091.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of internal firmware issues.
RAC091.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart iDRAC by invoking the WS-Man iDRACReset method which is defined in the DCIM_iDRACCardService class and then retry the operation.
RAC091.Message: Unable to transfer the file because of internal firmware issues.

RAC0749.Description: SNMPv3 User cannot be set to None.
RAC0749.Resolution: Set the SNMPv3 User to a value other than None and retry the operation.
RAC0749.Message: SNMPv3 User cannot be set to None.

SUP0126.Message: Firmware update in progress. Please wait.

SRV081.Description: The operation cannot be started because iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not installed on the server operating system (OS).
SRV081.Resolution: Install the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) in the server operating system (OS) and then retry the operation. Refer to the iSM Installation Guide on the support site for details.
SRV081.Message: Unable to start the operation because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not installed on the server operating system (OS).

BAT1003.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1003.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has completed.

ISM0016.Description: The BMC watchdog reset time is changed to a value identified in the message.
ISM0016.Message: The BMC watchdog reset time is changed to %1 seconds.

SEC0004.Description: The LAN is disconnected. Network performance may be degraded.

PSU0906.Description: In order to meet service requirements the supply must be shut down.
PSU0906.Resolution: Remove input power at the power supply.
PSU0906.Message: An interlock power down error detected on power unit %1.

GMGR0027.Description: The group passcode could not be modified.
GMGR0027.Resolution: Log in to the iDRAC as administrator, exit the local group, and then rejoin by using the new passcode. If the issue persists, restart iDRAC and retry the operation.
GMGR0027.Message: Unable to modify the local group passcode.

ISM0018.Description: The OS Collector application is started on the server Operating System.
ISM0018.Message: The OS Collector application is successfully started on the server operating system (OS).

PSU8504.Description: Selecting the Allow 110 VAC Operation involves potential risk that an overload can occur. The overload risk was not acknowledged in the CMC Web interface when the selection was made.
PSU8504.Resolution: Select the Allow 110 VAC Operation and accept the subsequent dialog that acknowledges the overload risk.
PSU8504.Message: The Allow 110 VAC Operation overload risk is not acknowledged.

HWC2002.Message: The storage %1 cable or interconnect is connected.

LC093.Description: The Client Trust Certificate is successfully deleted.
LC093.Message: The Client Trust Certificate is successfully deleted.

UEFI0096.Description: The Advanced ECC memory operating mode cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or system configuration does not support Advanced ECC mode.
UEFI0096.Resolution: Check DIMM population and system configuration to make sure Advanced ECC memory operating mode can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0096.Message: Unable to enable the Advanced ECC memory operating mode because the current DIMM population or system configuration does not support Advanced ECC mode.

PR27.Description: The system ran out of memory while attempting to perform an operation. This has been deprecated.
PR27.Resolution: Retry the operation. If more than one operation was attempted retry them one at a time.

STOR12.Description: One or more RAID controllers is disabled. This prevents Fault Tolerant mode from operating.
STOR12.Message: Chassis is operating with a disabled RAID controller.

RAC0678.Description: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on the PCIe SSD disk drives.
RAC0678.Resolution: Make sure PCIe SSD disk drives are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0678.Message: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on PCIe SSD disk drives.

NIC013.Description: An unknown AttributeName was entered for the operation.
NIC013.Resolution: Enter the correct AttributeName available in the system. Refer to the enumeration response for desired attribute.

PWR8536.Description: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is enabled.
PWR8536.Message: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is enabled.

GMGR0077.Description: The iDRAC cannot be added to group because the maximum possible iDRACs are already added to group.
GMGR0077.Resolution: Remove existing iDRAC(s) from group to free up slots. If available iDRACs are more than allowed number of iDRACs, upgrade to OpenManage Consoles.
GMGR0077.Message: Unable to add the iDRAC to group because the maximum possible iDRACs are already added to group.

PDR50.Description: The global hot spare is not large enough to protect all virtual disks that reside on the controller.
PDR50.Resolution: Assign a larger disk as the global hot spare.
PDR50.Message: Insufficient space on the global hot spare %1.

RAC0224.Description: A partial string used to construct a complete error message.

VDR56.Description: This message occurs when a physical disk in the disk group was removed or when a physical disk included in a redundant virtual disk fails. Because the virtual disk is redundant (uses mirrored or parity information) and only one physical disk has failed, the virtual disk can be rebuilt. Typically, the virtual disk (E.g. RAID 6) has multiple redundant disks and there is a problem with one of them.
VDR56.Resolution: Replace the missing or failed physical disk.

USR0173.Description: The Front Panel USB port switched automatically from iDRAC to operating system.
USR0173.Message: The Front Panel USB port switched automatically from iDRAC to operating system.

MEM1017.Message: Memory device at location %1 is installed correctly.

HWC3006.Description: There are not enough IPv4 addresses reserved for the servers in this chassis. Therefore the newly inserted server could not be configured with the QuickDeploy feature.
HWC3006.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the number of reserved IPv4 addresses for QuickDeploy. 2) Modify it such that the newly inserted blade will obtain an IP address for QuickDeploy. 3) Reseat the server to retry the QuickDeploy operation or manually configure the network parameters for the server. (Note that some chassis models may require a response at the LCD panel).
HWC3006.Message: Unable to QuickDeploy server in slot %1.

UEFI0179.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Read Receive Enable error was detected.
UEFI0179.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0179.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

SYS297.Description: The compressed file cannot be expanded because because the password entered for ZipPassword attribute in the iDRAC does not match with the password used for protecting the compressed file. Or, the encryption type used is not supported by the iDRAC.
SYS297.Resolution: Make sure that the password entered for ZipPassword attribute on the iDRAC is same as the password used to encrypt the compressed file and use the default (ZipCrypto) encryption.
SYS297.Message: Unable to expand the compressed file because the password entered for ZipPassword attribute in the iDRAC does not match with the password used for protecting the compressed file. Or, the encryption type used is not supported by the iDRAC.

PWR8528.Description: The Max Power Conservation Mode can be enabled only when Server Based Power Management Mode is disabled.
PWR8528.Resolution: The Max Power Conservation Mode can be changed when Server Based Power Management mode is disabled. Using the CMC Web UI, navigate to the Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration page, then uncheck the Enable Server Based Power Management checkbox. Retry the operation.
PWR8528.Message: Unable to set Max Power Conservation Mode because the Server Based Power Management mode is enabled.

RAC0741.Description: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on the selected PCIe SSD disk drive(s), because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0741.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0741.Message: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on the selected PCIe SSD disk drive(s), because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

PDR1000.Message: Drive %1 is installed in disk drive bay %2.

RAC0627.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested recurrent Automatic Backup job is already scheduled.
RAC0627.Resolution: Delete the current scheduled job, and then retry to create a new Automatic Backup job with a new schedule.
RAC0627.Message: Unable to schedule, because the requested recurrent Automatic Backup job is already scheduled.

ISM0032.Description: The Full Power Cycle operation is successfully cancelled by the server operating system (OS) user from the OS on date as identified in the message.
ISM0032.Resolution: No response action is required. For information about Virtual AC powercycle, see the platform User's Guide available on the support site.
ISM0032.Message: The Full Power Cycle operation is successfully cancelled by the server operating system (OS) user %1 from the OS on date %2.

VFL0711.Description: An error occurred while initializing the SD card because the SD card write-protection feature is enabled.
VFL0711.Resolution: Move the SD card write-protection tab to the disabled position and try again.
VFL0711.Message: SD card is write-protected and could not be initialized.

FSD001.Description: Dell has authorized the specified debug capabilities. Each debug capability represents a certain action Dell engineers can perform to debug iDRAC.
FSD001.Message: Debug authorized by Dell; debugcaps: %1, at %2, was authorized by Dell employee: %3, for the time period %4 to %5.

PR4.Description: The current component firmware version is lower than the previous component firmware version.
PR4.Message: Older version of firmware found on device: %1

RED0101.Description: The firmware was rolled back to the previous version.

UEFI0102.Description: The Memory Sparing feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.
UEFI0102.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure Memory Sparing feature can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0102.Message: Unable to enable the Memory Sparing feature because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.

CPU0000.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate the source of the error.
CPU0000.Resolution: Review System Event Log and Operating System Logs. These logs can help the user identify the possible issue that is producing the problem.
CPU0000.Message: Internal error has occurred check for additional logs.

BAR008.Resolution: Verify the request parameters and retry. Check passphrase for rule validity. NOTE: A valid passphrase contains 8 to 32 characters. It must include a combination of uppercase and lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols without spaces.

BAR069.Description: The system profile export did not complete successfully because there is insufficient space on the vFlash media.
BAR069.Resolution: Delete partitions and free up 384 MB of space on the current vFlash media, or use new vFlash media.

USR0209.Description: A panel with the Quick Sync feature has been disconnected and the feature is not available.
USR0209.Resolution: Connect a panel with the Quick Sync feature. Press the activate/deactivate button to enable the Quick Sync.
USR0209.Message: A panel with the Quick Sync feature is not available.

PCI1304.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1304.Message: An I/O channel check error was detected.

PST0128.Description: System BIOS was unable to detect memory in the system . This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video (BIOS Post Exception 80).

SYS413.Description: The operation successfully completed as all conditions have been met.

POW002.Description: Host failed to power up because unsupported components installed in Fabric1/fabric2.This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2252.
POW002.Resolution: Check for unsupported components installed in Fabric1/Fabric2.
POW002.Message: Power on permission error, unknown component installed in Fabric1/Fabric2.

UEFI0040.Description: The TXT has been disabled due to an unexpected issue. Check the SEL (System Event Log) for details of the issue.
UEFI0040.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the BIOS firmware on the system. For information about the issue, see System Event Log (SEL).
UEFI0040.Message: The TXT feature is disabled because of an unexpected issue.

STOR023.Description: Unable to perform configuration operations because a configuration job for the device already exists.
STOR023.Resolution: Wait for the current job for the device to complete or cancel the current job before attempting more configuration operations on the device.
STOR023.Message: Unable to perform configuration operations because a configuration job for the device already exists.

PR20.Description: The specified job is in progress.

RFL2005.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is operating normally.

LNK0003.Description: Cannot connect to the DNS server because of network issues or there is no response from the DNS server.
LNK0003.Resolution: Verify that the server is connected to the network and retry the operation.
LNK0003.Message: Unable to connect to the DNS server.

UEFI0087.Description: Unsupported 4Gb technology DIMM module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0087.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0087.Message: Unsupported 4Gb technology DIMM module is installed on memory slot: %1.

DIS002.Description: Use the Lifecycle Controller or other service to enable Auto Discovery and restart.
DIS002.Resolution: If you want AutoDiscovery to locate a Provisioning Server, enable this feature.

MEM9014.Description: The memory device identified in the message has encountered a correctable memory error. This may be an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM9014.Resolution: This is a correctable error. Review log information and if multiple correctable errors have occurred on the DIMM identified in the message, re-install the memory device. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9014.Message: A correctable memory error has occurred in Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) device %1.

HWC0011.Description: The USB drive does not have sufficient free space to copy the file.
HWC0011.Resolution: Make sure the USB drive has sufficient free space before retrying the operation.
HWC0011.Message: Insufficient space to copy the file to the USB drive.

PST0065.Description: System BIOS is configuring PCI devices.

NIC025.Description: The configuration operation cannot be started because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.
NIC025.Resolution: Make sure that the Lockdown.1#SystemLockdown attribute is set to Disabled in the DCIM_iDracCardEnumeration class by running the WS-Man get command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation.
NIC025.Message: Unable to start the configuration operation because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.

BIOS012.Description: No changes to BIOS attribute data are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration.

UEFI0026.Description: iDRAC is not responding to BIOS commands. The BIOS will reset the system to retry the initialization process.
UEFI0026.Resolution: Wait for the BIOS to reset the system and reinitialize the iDRAC. If the issue persists, remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.

PFM0003.Description: The utilization value of the sensor identified in the message is lower than the lower warning threshold value.
PFM0003.Resolution: The workload on server is almost zero. Consider assigning additional workloads to the server.
PFM0003.Message: The value of %1 is less than the lower warning threshold.

SUP0505.Description: The catalog file in the selected repository is corrupt.
SUP0505.Resolution: Select a repository with a valid catalog file, and retry the operation.

CTL122.Description: The firmware version of the RAID controller identified in the message cannot be updated because of an issue during the update process (programming timeout error).
CTL122.Resolution: Do not reset, restart, or turn off the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). However, retry the operation by using a correct firmware image file. If the issue persists, contact the service provider.
CTL122.Message: Unable to update the RAID controller %1 firmware version because of an issue during the update process (programming timeout error).

PR25.Description: The system's configuration database is missing or is unreadable. This may be due to a user action such as Lifecycle Controller Wipe or a replaced motherboard.
PR25.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory on Restart attribute of the Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. Alternatively, use the Unified Server Configurator utility.

SYS100.Description: A FQDD equivalent for the token name identified in the message cannot be found.
SYS100.Resolution: Make sure that only valid FQDDs are entered as input to the Target parameter, and then retry the operation.
SYS100.Message: Unable to find an FQDD equivalent for the token %1

SYS012.Description: The user credentials provided do not have appropriate privileges to perform the operation requested.
SYS012.Resolution: Retry operation using user credentials that have appropriate privileges to perform the operation.
SYS012.Message: User privileges are not sufficient to perform operation.

STOR024.Description: Configuration changes for the specified device are already scheduled.
STOR024.Message: Unable to create a configuration job because a configuration job for the device already exists.

SWC0286.Description: Objects in the cfgUserAdmin group corresponding to index 1 cannot be modified.
SWC0286.Message: Modifying the user configuration at index 1 is not allowed.

OSE0001.Description: The system halted due to an exception while the operating system was running. This is a kernel panic or bug check event.
OSE0001.Resolution: Review operating system logs and system video for additional information.

PDR1121.Message: Drive %1 is no longer in the critical array.

PSU8505.Description: Unable to set the chassis redundancy policy to AC Redundancy.
PSU8505.Resolution: Retry the operation using the CMC command line interface or CMC Web interface. To set the chassis redundancy policy using the command line, enter "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisRedundancyPolicy 1". To configure the chassis redundancy policy using the Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration. From the Redundancy drop-down menu, select AC Redundancy.
PSU8505.Message: Unable to set the chassis redundancy policy to AC Redundancy.

ISM0024.Description: The NVMe Device identified in the message is successfully prepared for removal from the PCIe slot identified in the message.
ISM0024.Resolution: No further response action is required before removing the NVMe Device identified in the message. To enable the NVMe Device for use, remove and re-insert the device or restart the system with the device inserted.
ISM0024.Message: The NVMe Device %1 is successfully prepared for removal from PCIe slot %2.

SWC0306.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0306.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0306.Message: The -a option requires -g and -u to also be specified.

LC059.Description: The attribute specified is read only and the value cannot be changed.
LC059.Message: Cannot set read only attribute specified in AttributeName %1.

OSE1000.Description: The system OS has successfully booted from A:.

UEFI0119.Description: Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) RAID redundancy was lost. The system BIOS should have prompted the user for the rebuild process.
UEFI0119.Resolution: No additional response action is required if you have followed the instructions on the screen to start the rebuild process.
UEFI0119.Message: The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) RAID redundancy was lost.

SWC0155.Message: CSR generated and downloaded from RAC successfully

SRV120.Description: The SupportAssist Collection cannot be uploaded to the SupportAssist server because the host network connection is unavailable.
SRV120.Resolution: Make sure that the host has network connection and retry the operation.
SRV120.Message: Unable to upload the SupportAssist Collection to the SupportAssist server because the host network connection is not available.

VFL0021.Description: The requested operation cannot be performed if one of the vFlash SD cards is in an 'attached' state.
VFL0021.Resolution: Detach the vFlash SD Card partitions by running the racadm command "racadm set iDRAC.vflashpartition.<partition number>.attachstate 0". and retry the operation.
VFL0021.Message: One of the vFlash SD Card partitions is already attached to the host operating system.

RAC0298.Description: A Root Domain Name must be specified for Active Directory configuration.
RAC0298.Resolution: Root Domain Name must be configured.
RAC0298.Message: Root Domain Name must be configured.

UEFI0185.Description: A Load-Reduced DIMM (LR-DIMM) buffer initialization failure was detected during memory initialization.
UEFI0185.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0185.Message: Load Reduced DIMM (LR-DIMM) training errors have occurred on memory riser %1.

SWC0240.Description: The requested object is auto-assigned if DNS Server DHCP is enabled, and hence cannot be configured.
SWC0240.Resolution: Disable DNS Server DHCP and re-try the command.
SWC0240.Message: The IPv6 DNS Server IP address is not allowed to be configured if IPv6 DNS Server DHCP (cfgIPv6DNSServersFromDHCP6) is enabled.

SWC8506.Description: The Profile identified in the message has been deleted.

IOV007.Description: For each adapter assigned to a server, power is allocated when the server is turned on. If the available power is less than the required power, the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) will not power on the adapters associated with the server.
IOV007.Resolution: To release the required power, turn off one or more servers by pressing the Power Button on the individual server units.
IOV007.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to allocate power to one or more PCIe adapters in the Chassis Infrastructure component.

LIC011.Description: License Manager does not allow the replacement of a non-evaluation license with an evaluation license.
LIC011.Resolution: To replace a non-evaluation license, first delete the non-evaluation license, then import the evaluation license.
LIC011.Message: A non-evaluation license cannot be replaced with an evaluation license.

MEM0601.Message: Memory device is removed from location %1.

VDR16.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk failed or there is an error in the parity information. A failed physical disk causes errors in parity information.
VDR16.Resolution: Check that all the physical disks of the virtual disk are in a healthy condition. Replace any disks that are not healthy and restart the operation. If this is not the problem, delete the virtual disk and restore the data to the disk from a backup copy.

PWR8687.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the storage sled controller installed on the server in the slot identified in the message because the server does not have a Mezzanine card. A Mezzanine card position is identified with the following numbers: For quarter-width server, the position number is 1. For half-width server mezzanine C & B maps to position numbers 1 & 2 respectively. For full-width server, Mezzanine C & B on the upper- or left part of the server maps to position numbers 1 & 2 respectively. Mezzanine C & B on the lower- or right part of the server maps to position numbers 3 & 4 respectively.
PWR8687.Resolution: Install a Mezzanine card in the Mezzanine card slot of the server identified in the message, and then retry the operation.
PWR8687.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the storage sled controller installed on server in slot %1 because the server does not have a Mezzanine card.

SWC0248.Description: The specified command has invalid syntax.
SWC0248.Resolution: Verify that the correct command syntax is specified. See the help text or documentation for valid commands.

SYS436.Description: The job cannot be created because the Start Time entered is invalid.
SYS436.Resolution: Enter the Start Time in the String format, and then retry the operation For example, YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS. For more information about recommened Start Time format, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS436.Message: Unable to create the job because the Start Time entered is invalid.

NIC505.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC505.Message: The DNS domain name is not allowed to be configured if domain name DHCP (cfgDNSDomainNameFromDHCP) is enabled.

RAC044.Description: Some event filter settings were not updated due to problems encountered processing the input parameters.
RAC044.Resolution: Verify the input parameters provided and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC044.Message: Unable to update some event filter settings.

RED070.Description: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup schedule due to invalid input parameters.
RED070.Resolution: Verify the input parameters to the set Automatic Backup schedule method are correct and retry the operation.
RED070.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup schedule.

SWC8543.Description: The Boot Identity operation cannot be performed because server in the slot identified in the message does not have a Service Tag.
SWC8543.Resolution: Set the Service Tag value using the F2 System Setup boot utility. Follow the Server BIOS menu instructions for setting an absent Service Tag or contact your service provider.
SWC8543.Message: Unable to perform the Boot Identity profile operation because the server in slot %1 does not have a Service Tag.

LC075.Description: Deleting the custom signed certificate should regenerate a new unique certificate . Reset iDRAC to apply new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset old certificate will be active.
LC075.Message: The Custom Signed Certificate (CSC) is deleted successfully. Reset iDRAC to complete the delete action of the certificate.

PR9.Description: The Part Replacement feature started the firmware update process based on Part Firmware Update attribute settings.

PWR8529.Description: The Max Power Conservation Mode is enabled.
PWR8529.Message: Max Power Conservation Mode is enabled.

TMP0120.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm.
TMP0120.Message: The system inlet temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

CBL0007.Description: The backplane cables identified in the message need to be connected to the correct backplane bays.
CBL0007.Resolution: Make sure the cables identified in the message are cabled correctly. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0007.Message: Backplane %1 %2 cable and backplane %1 %2 cable are swapped.

SWC0115.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0115.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0115.Message: The -s option cannot be used with any other options.

JCP002.Description: The Lifecycle Controller is not able to schedule a job at this time because of an internal error.
JCP002.Resolution: Wait up to three minutes and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system and enumerate DCIM_Lifeycle Job to view the list of jobs that are currently scheduled.

PWR2270.Description: The Intel Management Engine has encountered a Health Event.
PWR2270.Resolution: Perform an AC Cycle operation on the host server, and then update the BIOS firmware to the latest version. For information about recommended BIOS versions, see the BIOS documentation on the support site.
PWR2270.Message: The Intel Management Engine has encountered a Health Event.

TMP1003.Resolution: Check whether the thermostat setting is too low and whether the room temperature is too cool.
TMP1003.Message: %1 has crossed the minimum failure threshold.

SRV128.Description: The SupportAssist operation cannot be started because system is in Lockdown mode.
SRV128.Resolution: Disable the Lockdown mode on the system and retry the operation. To disable the Lockdown mode on the system using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm set idrac.lockdown.SystemLockdownMode Enabled".
SRV128.Message: Unable to start the SupportAssist operation because system is in Lockdown mode.

RED057.Description: An internal error occurred because of insufficient memory available on iDRAC.
RED057.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
RED057.Message: An internal error occurred. Unable to complete the specified operation.

STOR016.Description: The physical disk drive cannot be assigned as the hot-spare of this virtual disk because the capacity of the physical disk is not sufficient.
STOR016.Resolution: Specify a physical disk with a larger capacity or replace the specified physical disk with one with more capacity, and then retry the operation.
STOR016.Message: The physical disk specified is not large enough to be a hot spare for this virtual disk.

SUP023.Description: Duplicate/Invalid JobID was provided as input for scheduling.
SUP023.Resolution: Verify the job ID and retry the action. Retrieve all open jobs by issuing the GetAllJobs command.
SUP023.Message: Duplicate JobID provided as inputs for scheduling.

STOR082.Description: The operation cannot be stopped or canceled because the operation is not currently running.
STOR082.Resolution: Make sure the operation is running before attempting to cancel or stop the operation.
STOR082.Message: The operation cannot be stopped or cancelled because the operation is not currently running.

GMGR0040.Description: The group job identified in the message cannot be stopped because it is not in the active state. Scheduled and completed group jobs cannot be stopped.
