GMGR0040.Message: Unable to stop the group job %1 of type %2 because the group job is not an actively running task.

CTL70.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL70.Message: Attempted to import an orphan drive on %1.

TST106.Description: The email alert being tested is not properly configured.
TST106.Resolution: Configure the email alert and retry the operation. If the failure persists, reset iDRAC.
TST106.Message: Email alert destination address not configured.

SEL1515.Description: An I2C sensor is not responding either because it is damaged, or because of damaged circuit lines for I2C bus, or a faulty sensor state.
SEL1515.Resolution: To find the sensor number that is not responding, type "racadm getsel -E" and check the Event Data Byte 1. To recover the sensor from the faulty state, do one of the following: 1) Reset iDRAC: a) By using graphical user interface (GUI), click Overview > Server > Quick Launch Tasks > Reset iDRAC. b) by running RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), enter racadm racreset. 2) Change the corresponding I2C sensor by contacting your service provider.
SEL1515.Message: An I2C sensor is not responding either because it is damaged, or because of damaged circuit lines for I2C bus, or a faulty sensor state.

ISM0036.Description: The operating system (OS) collector service cannot be successfully closed on the server OS because either the service is not responding or the service has already closed.
ISM0036.Message: Unable to successfully close the operating system (OS) collector service on the server OS because either the service is not responding or the service has already closed.

SEC0604.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0604.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

SRV074.Description: The SupportAssist End User License Agreement (EULA) is accepted by iDRAC user via iDRAC interface identified in the message.
SRV074.Message: The SupportAssist End User License Agreement (EULA) is accepted by iDRAC user %1 via iDRAC interface %2.

RAC1217.Description: The properties of Secure Boot Certificate cannot be displayed because the certificate data entered does not exist.
RAC1217.Resolution: Make sure that valid certificate data exists and retry the operation. For more information, see the RACADM CLI Reference Guide available on the support site.
RAC1217.Message: Unable to display the properties of Secure Boot Certificate because the certificate data entered does not exist.

BAR017.Description: A system profile backup file validation has been requested.

SWC0086.Description: The Public IP access feature has been enabled in iDRAC by the Integrated Data Center solution. The iDRAC can now be managed via the Public IP interface.
SWC0086.Message: The Integrated Data Center Public IP mode is enabled.

STOR104.Description: The operation cannot be started because the operation is not supported on the NVMe RAID drives. The RAIDMode may not match the RAIDType or the SoftwareRAIDMode requested.
STOR104.Resolution: Set the NVMeMode attribute of BIOS to NonRAID and retry the operation. To set the NonRAID mode, see the staged objects example of setting Single-Object in the SET command section of the iDRAC RACADM CLI Reference guide available on the support site. To verify the setting by using iDRAC graphical user interface (GUI), click Configuration > BIOS Settings > NVMe Settings.
STOR104.Message: Unable to start the operation because the operation is not supported on the NVMe RAID drives.

PCI5005.Description: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected an issue in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in the slot identified in the message.
PCI5005.Resolution: Make sure that: 1) The PCIe adapter used is supported by the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). For a list of supported adapters, contact your service provider. 2) The adapter is not damaged. 3) The adapter is properly inserted in the slot.
PCI5005.Message: An auxiliary power fault issue is detected in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in PCIe slot%1.

RAC0251.Description: The vFlash partitions are attached. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0251.Resolution: Detach the partitions and try again.
RAC0251.Message: One or more partitions are currently attached.

RAC013.Description: The method cannot be run because an invalid FQDD is entered.
RAC013.Resolution: Enter a valid FQDD and retry the operation.
RAC013.Message: Unable to run the method because an invalid FQDD is entered.

STOR057.Description: The instrumentation for the specified RAID controller is not in state where the requested operation can be performed because system inventory collection (the CSIOR feature) has not been executed.
STOR057.Resolution: Enable the CSIOR (Collect System Inventory On Restart) feature and restart the server to cause CSIOR execution. Make sure the Remote Services status is Ready and retry the operation. To get the Remote Services status, invoke the GetRSStatus method. For more information about this method, see Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Guide.
STOR057.Message: The specified RAID controller is not currently available for configuration.

SYS172.Description: A Remote Diagnostic operation has been interrupted because the server was restarted during the operation.
SYS172.Resolution: Make sure that there are no diagnostic operations in progress before restarting the server or wait for the Remote Diagnostic operation to complete.
SYS172.Message: A Remote Diagnostic operation has been interrupted.

PWR8681.Description: The firmware identified in the message does not support the PCIe reassignment operation.
PWR8681.Resolution: Update the firmware identified in the message to the supported latest available version. See the latest iDRAC User Guide for information on the versions that support the PCIe reassignment.
PWR8681.Message: The %1 firmware in the server slot %2 does not support additional PCIe slots.

TMPS0102.Description: Inlet temperature has been above the warning threshold for duration of 10% or more for the operational time during the last one year.
TMPS0102.Resolution: This condition will occur if the ambient temperature is high. Make sure the ambient temperature of the environment is in normal range.
TMPS0102.Message: Inlet temperature is above warning level for extended duration.

RAC0660.Description: The file server cannot be accessed because of incorrect credentials.
RAC0660.Resolution: Check the file server credentials and retry the operation.
RAC0660.Message: Unable to access the specified file server location.

SYS304.Description: The import operation cannot be performed because the RepositoryUpdate feature is not supported for local imports.
SYS304.Resolution: Remove the value from the RepositoryUpdate attribute under the System.Embedded.1 component.
SYS304.Message: The import operation cannot be performed because the RepositoryUpdate feature is not supported for local imports.

OSD53.Resolution: Remove the write protect from the SD card and then proceed.

OSD32.Description: Cannot continue with DetachISOImage because the system does not have an attached ISO image.
OSD32.Resolution: The call to DetachISOImage is unnecessary since the ISO image is not currently attached.

RAC1135.Description: The RACADM command could not be run because the internal instrumentation components are either busy or have stopped functioning.
RAC1135.Resolution: Wait for a minute for the internal instrumentation component to respond, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for 15 seconds, wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting, and then retry the operation. If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
RAC1135.Message: Unable to run the RACADM command because an internal instrumentation component has stopped functioning.

VF011.Description: The specified password was not correct.

GMGR0045.Description: The group job cannot be canceled because it is not in the scheduled state. Active and completed group jobs cannot be canceled.
GMGR0045.Message: Unable to cancel the group job %1 of type %2 because it is not a job in scheduled state.

UEFI0129.Description: The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) has encountered an unknown issue. This may be because new error codes are coming from the IDSDM firmware and the system BIOS or the iDRAC firmware need to be updated to process correctly.
UEFI0129.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the system BIOS. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. 3) Reseat or replace the SD card media. Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0129.Message: The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) has encountered an unknown issue.

LIC501.Description: The attempted action requires a valid license for certain advanced features installed in the system but the required license is missing or expired.
LIC501.Resolution: Obtain an appropriate license then try again. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC501.Message: A required license is missing or expired.

LC094.Description: The Export SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics) file operation is successfully completed and the files are exported to iDRAC Local folder.
LC094.Message: The Export SVG file operation is successfully completed and the files are exported to iDRAC Local folder.

MEM8501.Description: A low memory condition was detected. If this condition continues, a failover or a reset may occur.
MEM8501.Resolution: If multiple resets occur, contact your service provider.

SYS095.Description: Unable to unmount an iDRAC internal storage partition.
SYS095.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issues persists, reset the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and then retry the operation after the iDRAC has finished restarting.
SYS095.Message: Unable to unmount an iDRAC internal storage partition.

BIOS041.Description: The operation cannot be completed because hash signature is not supported in Platform Key (PK) and Key Exchange Key (KEK).
BIOS041.Resolution: Make sure that hash signature is not used in the input parameter and retry the operation.
BIOS041.Message: Operation not allowed because hash signature is not supported in Platform Key (PK) and Key Exchange (KEK).

RED014.Description: A job for this update already exists in the queue and prevents the new job from being scheduled.
RED014.Resolution: Delete the existing job before scheduling a new update job. For Remote Services API consumers, enumerate all the jobs to find and identify the duplicate job. Then invoke the DeleteJob() method to delete this job and enable the new update job to be scheduled.
RED014.Message: Job for this device is already present.

SRV123.Description: The operation cannot be started because the SupportAssist schedule based auto collections are not enabled in iDRAC.
SRV123.Resolution: Enable the SupportAssist schedule based auto collections in iDRAC and then retry the operation. To enable the SupportAssist schedule based auto collections using the RACADM command line interface, enter "racadm supportassist autocollectscheduler create" with desired schedule.
SRV123.Message: Unable to start the operation because the SupportAssist schedule based auto collections are not enabled in iDRAC.

SYS253.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the remote host server or remote host file system is set to read-only mode.
SYS253.Resolution: Make sure that the file transfer parameters and the remote host file system properties are correct, and then retry the operation.
SYS253.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the remote host server or remote host file system is set to read-only mode.

RED077.Description: Unable to get the Automatic Update schedule information because the schedule is not configured.
RED077.Message: Unable to get the Automatic Update schedule information.

IOID003.Description: The Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Auxiliary powered devices is changed to the restart type identified in the message.
IOID003.Message: The Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Auxiliary powered devices is changed to %1.

OSD26.Description: Unable to continue with BootToPXE command because another process is using Lifecycle Controller.
OSD26.Resolution: See ConcreteJob status to make sure that the running process is complete, and then run BootToPXE.
OSD26.Message: Unable to continue with BootToPXE - another command is running.

SWC0272.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0272.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0272.Message: Invalid syntax. The -g option is only valid with -o, -i, and -c.

SWC0285.Description: The value given for the object is not valid.
SWC0285.Resolution: Enter a valid value for the corresponding object.

HWC8504.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) cannot communicate with the control panel identified in the message because of internal issues.
HWC8504.Resolution: Disconnect the input power supplied to the chassis and reconnect. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
HWC8504.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) cannot communicate with the %1 control panel because of internal issues.

SWU8535.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8535.Resolution: Make sure that the iKVM firmware image file is available at the specified location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8535.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because the Image file transfer is not successful. ErrorCode=0x%1.

RFM1027.Message: Removable Flash Media is operating normally.

SRV062.Description: The SupportAssist Chassis Controller logs collection operation is successfully completed .
SRV062.Message: The SupportAssist Chassis Controller logs collection operation is successfully completed .

RAC923.Description: The specified file path (specified with the f parameter) is too long. This path should be less than 64 characters in length.
RAC923.Resolution: Try the same command with a shorter file path (specified with the f parameter) which is less than 64 characters in length.
RAC923.Message: The file path is too long.

ENC28.Description: The firmware on the EMM modules is not the same version. Both modules must have the same firmware version. This message is caused when you attempt to insert an EMM module that has a different firmware version than an existing module.
ENC28.Resolution: Upgrade to the same version of the firmware on both EMM modules and then powercycle the system and attached enclosures.
ENC28.Message: Enclosure Management Module (EMM) firmware version mismatch detected in %1.%2 %3.

SRV023.Description: The SupportAssist OS and Application data collection operation is cancelled.
SRV023.Message: The SupportAssist OS and Application data collection operation is cancelled.

DH001.Resolution: Try again. If the error persists, use RACADM command racreset to clear the issue.
DH001.Message: Resource needed to perform the operation is unavailable.

LC053.Description: Lifecycle Controller Remote Service is either not ready or currently reloading server information.
LC053.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, refer to Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation for more information.
LC053.Message: Lifecycle Controller Remote Services is currently unavailable.

BIOS0001.Description: BIOS logged a Trusted Compute Module (TPM) Physical Presence Operation.
BIOS0001.Message: Trusted Compute Module (TPM) Physical Presence Operation %1 logged.

UEFI0125.Description: Unable to finish The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) image rebuild process because of issues.
UEFI0125.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat or replace the SD card media. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0125.Message: Unable to finish The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) image rebuild process because of issues.

SYS039.Description: The requested configuration changes have not passed the component specific verification checks, and therefore the changes will not be applied.
SYS039.Resolution: Check the scripts or related documentation and retry the operation.
SYS039.Message: Verification of requested configuration changes failed.

SWC0114.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0114.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0114.Message: The -o option cannot be used with any other options.

BAT1019.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PWR2254.Description: The use of 110V is unacknowledged for the chassis and the chassis cannot grant power on permission to the server.
PWR2254.Resolution: Check for unacknowledged use of 110V and change to acknowledged. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Chassis Overview>Power>Configuration and then check the 110V Acknowledge field. Retry the operation to turn on the server.
PWR2254.Message: The use of 110V is unacknowledged and the chassis cannot grant power on permission to the server.

SWU8523.Description: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC identified in the message is successful.
SWU8523.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is successfully completed.

CTL101.Description: The controller identified in the message is disabled by a user action.

RAC0611.Description: The IP address cannot be blank for import or export of system configuration profile operation.
RAC0611.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Address for network location.

CTL123.Description: The firmware version of the RAID controller identified in the message cannot be updated because the memory chip on which the firmware image is saved in is of an unknown type.
CTL123.Resolution: Download the correct firmware image file and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CTL123.Message: Unable to update the RAID controller %1 firmware version because the memory chip on which the firmware image is saved in is of an unknown type.

STOR041.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because an invalid value for the attribute identified in the message is specified.
STOR041.Resolution: Specify a valid value for the attribute identified in the message and retry the operation.

RAC1134.Description: Unable to export the Lifecycle log data, because the export file size larger than 25MB and cannot be processed locally.
RAC1134.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log to a network file share. Using the RACADM command line utility, run the lclog export command with --complete option and related network file share parameters, and then retry the operation. For more information about the --complete option, run the "racadm help lclog export" command at the command line interface.
RAC1134.Message: Unable to export the Lifecycle log data, because the export file size larger than 25MB and cannot be processed locally.

GMGR0046.Description: The group job at the member level cannot be started either because the group member is unavailable or turned off.
GMGR0046.Resolution: Wait for the group member to be available and rerun the job.
GMGR0046.Message: The group member is unavailable or turned off.

CMC8567.Description: The DVD drive is mapped to the server slot specified in the message.
CMC8567.Message: The DVD drive is mapped to the server slot %1.

STOR039.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because of a mismatch in the number of AttributeName and AttributeValue values specified.
STOR039.Resolution: Specify a valid number of AttributeName and AttributeValue pair values and retry the operation.
STOR039.Message: Mismatch in AttributeName and AttributeValue count.

AMP0312.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0312.Message: System level current is less than the lower warning threshold.

ENC26.Description: The enclosure or an enclosure component is in a Failed or Degraded state. It is not responding to storage management commands or there is a connectivity problem between the controller and enclosure.
ENC26.Resolution: Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. See the hardware documentation to for more information. Contact technical support.

SYS262.Description: The file cannot be transferred because either the proxy may not allow file transfer operations or incorrect proxy credentials are entered.
SYS262.Resolution: Make sure that correct proxy settings are enabled and correct proxy credentials are entered and retry the operation.
SYS262.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because either the proxy may not allow file transfer operations or incorrect proxy credentials are entered.

CMC8509.Description: The extended storage feature is not activated if the media on the secondary CMC is no longer functional.
CMC8509.Resolution: Do one of the following, and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration and verify if the card on the secondary CMC displays errors. 2) Do a failover and then reprovision the card from the same GUI page. Reprovisioning is only allowed on the card of primary CMC. However, if both the options 1 and 2 fail, the card may be no longer functional.
CMC8509.Message: Unable to activate the extended storage feature on the secondary CMC: %1. The feature will be deactivated.

USR107.Description: The identified user has performed the identified set operation or invoke method operation. The operation is either set on an instance of the class identified or an invocation of the identified method.
USR107.Message: The operation %1 of the %2 was performed by %3

SWC0228.Description: Invalid values passed to the function.
SWC0228.Message: Partition label must be an alphanumeric character string.

STOR303.Description: Controller mode cannot be changed as the controller has foreign configuration associated with it.
STOR303.Resolution: Clear the foreign configuration and retry the operation.
STOR303.Message: Unable to change controller mode while foreign configuration is present on the controller.

SYS287.Description: The Repository Update operation cannot be performed because the specified catalog file does not exist on the remote share.
SYS287.Resolution: Make sure that the specified catalog file is available on the remote share, and then retry the operation.
SYS287.Message: Unable to perform the Repository Update operation because the specified catalog file does not exist on the remote share.

MEM9005.Description: A link degradation was detected in propagation of signals between processor and memory through the Intel SMI 2 memory interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9005.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9005.Message: Intel SMI 2 Memory interconnect %1 has degraded.

STOR0106.Description: No fan data to display. The system is powered off, no fan enclosures are present in the system, or the fans are not connected to the enclosures.
STOR0106.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosure fan is available, and fan is connected to the enclosure.
STOR0106.Message: Fans are not connected to enclosures or data about fans is unavailable.

SEL0014.Description: The System Event Log (SEL) was cleared by the username identified in the message from the IP address identified in the message.
SEL0014.Message: The System Event Log (SEL) was cleared by %1 from %2.

PDR12.Description: The physical disk has failed or is corrupt.
PDR12.Resolution: Replace the failed or corrupt disk. Identify a disk that has failed by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. Restart the initialization.

SYS155.Description: Initiating clear operation on non-secure erase-capable drives for the controller identified in the message.
SYS155.Message: Initiating clear operation on non-secure erase-capable drives for controller: %1.

MEM9030.Description: The NVDIMM device in the slot identified in the message is not responding and is disabled.
MEM9030.Resolution: Remove and reinstall the Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device. If the issue persists, contact your service provider. For information about removing and reinstalling the NVDIMM, see the system Owner's Manual on the support site.
MEM9030.Message: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device in the slot %1 is not responding and is disabled.

UEFI0214.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Basic Receive Enable Training phase.
UEFI0214.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0214.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC0607.Description: The integrated NICs in the system do not support OS to iDRAC Pass-Through.
RAC0607.Resolution: Make sure the integrated NICs are enabled from BIOS setup and support OS to iDRAC Pass-Through, then retry the operation. To access BIOS setup, press F2 during system startup. For more information about OS to iDRAC Pass-Through, see iDRAC7 Users Guide.
RAC0607.Message: Unable to perform OS to iDRAC Pass-Through with the current system configuration.

HWC8513.Description: The control panel identified in the message is not installed, or the cable is not connected to the Chassis Management Controller (CMC).
HWC8513.Resolution: Turn off the chassis and check if the control panel identified in the message is properly installed.
HWC8513.Message: The %1 control panel is not installed, or the cable is not connected to the Chassis Management Controller (CMC).

STOR045.Description: The specified physical disks have fragmented disk space, therefore StartingLBA and Size parameters are required to be specified in order to create a virtual disk.
STOR045.Resolution: Specify StartingLBA and Size parameters and retry the operation.
STOR045.Message: StartingLBA and Size parameters are required to create a virtual disk.

PSU0006.Description: The power supply identified in the message must be supported by the platform. Generally, multiple power supplies in the server should have the same feature set and power rating.
PSU0006.Resolution: Review server product documentation for supported power supplies and power supply configurations.

RAC0213.Description: Login page is missing a username.

GMGR0022.Description: The group job identified in the message is successfully completed.
GMGR0022.Message: The group job %1 of type %2 is successfully completed.

VLT0232.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0232.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the mezzanine card.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0232.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

HWC5032.Description: The fabric type for IOM's on the same chassis fabric must match.
HWC5032.Resolution: Check chassis fabric type in CMC GUI and compare to the type of both IOM's.
HWC5032.Message: A fabric mismatch detected on IO module %1.

SRV043.Description: Unable to start the SupportAssist operation because the Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
SRV043.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller by pressing F2 during server startup and select iDRAC Settings > Lifecycle Controller and then enable the Lifecycle Controller. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
SRV043.Message: Unable to start the SupportAssist operation because the Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

PDR52.Description: The controller has two connectors that are connected to the same enclosure. The communication path on one connector has lost connection with the enclosure. The communication path on the other connector is reporting this loss.
PDR52.Resolution: Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. Make sure both Enclosure Management Modules (EMMs) are healthy.

BOOT014.Description: The system's SD card has been removed or is in use.
BOOT014.Resolution: Verify that the SD card is inserted and that another operation is not in progress, and try again.

SRV033.Description: The native Operating System (OS) Application Data Collection is unable to collect data because of an unknown exception.
SRV033.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the server Operating System (OS) and retry the operation.
SRV033.Message: The native Operating System (OS) Application Data Collection is unable to collect data because of an unknown exception.

UEFI0077.Description: One or more PCIe device errors occurred in the previous boot.
UEFI0077.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCIe device with errors, and then update its firmware.
UEFI0077.Message: One or more PCIe device errors occurred in the previous boot.

TMP1002.Description: The enclosure is too hot. A variety of factors can cause the excessive temperature. For example, a fan may have failed, the thermostat may be set too high, or the room temperature may be too hot.
TMP1002.Resolution: Check for factors that may cause overheating. For example, verify that the enclosure fan is working. You should also check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source. Make sure the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information.
TMP1002.Message: %1 has exceeded the maximum failure threshold.

STOR048.Description: Either the controller or the firmware on the controller does not support the Dell Key Management feature.
STOR048.Message: Controller is not Dell Key Management capable.

GMGR0010.Description: iDRAC is unable to communicate within the server group because either the service tag is not configured, group passcode has changed, group was deleted and does not exist or network cable is disconnected from the Primary Controller.
GMGR0010.Resolution: Make sure that the group was not deleted prior or cabling of all iDRAC servers is correct or server has a configured service tag. If the issue persists, try disabling and reenabling the group manager or reset the IDRAC.
GMGR0010.Message: Unable to complete the operation as iDRAC is unable to communicate within the server group either because service tag is not configured, group passcode has changed, group was deleted and does not exist or network is disconnected from the master server.

VF007.Description: A partition with an image was created.

RAC0911.Resolution: Try again later. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
RAC0911.Message: Data about version details is unavailable.

LC066.Description: The Export Certificate operation is already running and may take a few minutes to complete.
LC066.Resolution: Wait until the current operation is complete and then retry the operation.
LC066.Message: The Export Certificate operation is currently running.

RAC0278.Description: This warning message appears when IPv6 is disabled.
RAC0278.Resolution: Use IPv4 network to access iDRAC remotely.
RAC0278.Message: Disabling IPv6 prevents access to iDRAC using an IPv6 address.

ENC16.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
ENC16.Message: An enclosure blink has ceased on %1.

PSU501.Description: The server was already up, when the user gave a power on request.

MEM0700.Message: The persistent correctable memory error rate is at normal levels for a memory device at location %1.

CPU0816.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0816.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence and re-install .
CPU0816.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is absent.

LIC901.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.
LIC901.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

HWC1005.Description: The storage adapter may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

ASR0105.Description: The operating system or an application failed to failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was powered off. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset - 02h event 3:0 - 4h).
ASR0105.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0105.Message: The OS watchdog timer powered off the system.

SYS231.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported source file path value.
SYS231.Resolution: Make sure that the correct source file path is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS231.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported source file path value.

DIS116.Description: The AutoConfig operation cannot be completed because the parameter name identified in the message is not of flag type which is causing a syntax error. The parameter name must always be of flag type.
DIS116.Resolution: Enter an appropriate parameter of flag type and retry the operation. For example, -u is a flag indicating the username that has access to network share of CIFS type. For a list of recommended flags, see the Zero-Touch Bare Metal Server Provisioning using Dell iDRAC with Lifecycle Controller Auto Config white paper available at Dell TechCenter website.
DIS116.Message: Unable to complete the AutoConfig operation because the parameter %1 is not of flag type, which is causing a syntax error.

RED065.Description: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were applied. A system restart was not required.
RED065.Message: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were applied. A system restart was not required.

BAT0010.Description: To charge the battery, the system has to remain powered on.
BAT0010.Resolution: Allow the PERC RAID controller battery for the associated bay to charge. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
BAT0010.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is low.

SEL1204.Description: The operating system or BIOS detected an unknown event. (IPMI sensor type code 12h - offset 02h).
SEL1204.Resolution: Reduce system to minimum supported configuration. If issues persists, contact support.
SEL1204.Message: An unknown system hardware failure detected.

SEL1503.Message: The chassis management controller (CMC) is not redundant.

SWC0077.Description: iDRAC is unable to initiate the Repurpose or Retire System operation because the iDRAC is not responding or another operation is in progress.
SWC0077.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do one the following: 1) Check if there are other operations running on the iDRAC and wait for the operations to complete, and retry the operation. 2) Restart the server, and retry the operation.
SWC0077.Message: Unable to initiate the Repurpose or Retire System operation.

LC087.Description: The configuration operation cannot be started because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.
LC087.Resolution: Make sure that the Lockdown.1#SystemLockdown attribute is set to Disabled in the DCIM_iDracCardEnumeration class by running the WS-Man get command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation.
LC087.Message: Unable to start the configuration operation because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.

HWC5034.Description: Link tuning table not supported for this IO modular.
HWC5034.Resolution: Update the CMC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC5034.Message: A link tuning failure detected on IO module %1.

ISM0031.Description: The Full Power Cycle operation is triggered by the server operating system (OS) user from the OS on date as identified in the message. However, the server components will be AC power cycled when the server is shut down.
ISM0031.Resolution: No response action is required. For information about Full powercycle, see the platform User's Guide available on the support site.
ISM0031.Message: The Full Power Cycle operation is triggered by the server operating system (OS) user %1 from the OS on date %2. However, the server components will be AC power cycled when the server is shut down.

UEFI0090.Description: A DIMM with an incompatible number of ranks is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0090.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0090.Message: A DIMM with an incompatible number of ranks is installed on memory slot: %1.

STOR034.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because an invalid value is specified for RebootJobType.
STOR034.Resolution: Enter a valid RebootJobType value and retry the operation. For more information about the RebootJobType parameter, see the RAID Profile specification.

SYS150.Description: A System Erase job with the job ID identified in the message is initiated.
SYS150.Message: Starting System Erase operation. Job ID: %1

RED091.Description: Unable to install Lifecycle Controller firmware.
RED091.Resolution: Reinstall the iDRAC7 firmware (DUP) to repair Lifecycle Controller. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
RED091.Message: Unable to install Lifecycle Controller firmware.

VF016.Description: The SD card is not writable.
VF016.Resolution: Check the write-protection tab of the SD card.

BAR088.Description: The maximum number of partitions are already in use.
BAR088.Resolution: Delete partitions and free up 384MB of space on the current vFlash media or obtain new vFlash media.
BAR088.Message: No partitions available on vFlash media.

SWC0039.Description: The backup Server Configuration Profile image partition is not present in the vFlash SD card.
SWC0039.Resolution: A backup Server Configuration Profile is required to import or export a Server Profile. Perform the backup operation and retry import or export operation.
SWC0039.Message: Unable to find the backup Server Configuration Profile image.

BAR054.Description: The attempt to clean up after an unsuccessful Backup/Restore of a system profile operation has not been successful. The Lifecycle Controller/System Services related operations may not execute as expected until the system is properly restored to a functional configuration.
BAR054.Resolution: Enter the iDRAC configuration utility. Select the System Services option in the main selection screen. Choose the Cancel Lifecycle Controller Actions / Cancel System Services operation and follow the directions to ensure this operation is performed. If Cancel Lifecycle Controller Actions / Cancel System Services is not available, remove power from the system, wait 1 minute and reapply power. If the issue persists, contact your technical service provider.
BAR054.Message: System Reset or Lifecycle Controller Actions Canceled, System Profile Failure Recovery unsuccessful.

RAC0253.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0253.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Address. Expected range: [1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0253.Message: The IP Address is invalid. Expected range: [1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].

MEM0009.Resolution: If unexpected, review system logs for power or thermal exceptions.
MEM0009.Message: Memory device at location %1 is throttled.

SWC8559.Description: A new Virtual MAC Address Pool is created with the number of addresses identified in the message starting from the MAC address identified in the message.
SWC8559.Message: A new Virtual MAC Address Pool is created with %1 addresses from %2 for Boot Identity profile operations.

UEFI0319.Description: The system is booting from the recovery BIOS image file. The recovery BIOS did not receive a request from iDRAC to update the primary BIOS, and therefore the system stopped responding.
UEFI0319.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Turn off the server and disconnect the input power. 2) Wait for 30 seconds and reconnect to the power source and retry the operation. 3) Make sure that the iDRAC firmware version on the system is up to date and retry the operation.
UEFI0319.Message: The system is booting from the recovery BIOS image. The recovery BIOS did not receive a request from iDRAC to update the primary BIOS, and therefore system stopped responding.

STOR058.Description: Unable to complete the operation either because the operation is not supported on the target device, or the RAIDType of "MD Software RAID" does not allow the operation.
STOR058.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Make sure that the target device supports the operation. 2) Make sure that the if the RAIDType is set to "MD Software RAID" ensure that is the desired value. . For more information, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
STOR058.Message: The operation cannot be completed either because the operation is not supported on the target device, or the RAIDType of "MD Software RAID" does not allow the operation.

PST0195.Description: The current processor configuration is unsupported or encountered a fatal exception during POST. Check the processor configuration. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code C3).
PST0195.Resolution: Review system processor configuration and reduce the system to the minimum configuration.

FAN0016.Description: The cooling device is not performing optimally. The cooling device may be installed improperly.
FAN0016.Resolution: Remove and re-install the cooling device. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0016.Message: %1 RPM is outside of normal operating range.

LNK0002.Description: The DNS query did not complete successfully. This may be because the connection timed out due to an incorrect host name or a DNS server configuration issue.
LNK0002.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Verify host name entered is valid and retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, verify the DNS server settings are configured properly to resolve the host name.

BIOS003.Description: An invalid number of arguments was passed to the method.
BIOS003.Resolution: Enter all the required command parameters. Check documentation and try again.
BIOS003.Message: Missing required parameter. Refer to the inserted comment.

CTL39.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

TMP0109.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0109.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0109.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

FAN0012.Description: The device is not performing optimally. The device may be installed improperly.
FAN0012.Resolution: Remove and re-install the device at the next scheduled service. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0012.Message: %1 RPM is less than the lower warning threshold.

CPU0010.Description: The CPU is throttled due to thermal or power conditions.
CPU0010.Resolution: Review system logs for power or thermal exceptions.

CMC8563.Description: The KVM is mapped to the server slot number specified in the message.
CMC8563.Message: The KVM is mapped to the server slot %1.

SEL1506.Description: The primary CMC has lost communication with the indicated member CMC.
SEL1506.Resolution: Check network cable and network connections.
SEL1506.Message: Lost communications with Chassis Group Member %1.

LC047.Description: The DownloadClientCerts operation is in progress. The operation may take a few minutes to compete before the operation can be attempted again.
LC047.Resolution: Wait a few minutes before retrying retry the operation.
LC047.Message: An instance of DownloadClientCerts is already running.

UEFI0258.Description: An issue is observed on the Hard-drive/SSD backplane.
UEFI0258.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Make sure the correct type of Hard-drive/SSD backplane is installed. 2) Check the configuration of Hard-drive/SSD backplane and make sure its power cable is connected. Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0258.Message: An issue is observed on the Hard-drive/SSD backplane.

RDU8508.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.
RDU8508.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8508.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover since the other CMC is non-functional.

SWC0088.Description: The DHCP IP address of iDRAC cannot be retrieved because a network cable is not connected or a DHCP server is not functioning.
SWC0088.Resolution: Make sure that the network cable is connected, DHCP server is turned on, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform the following steps: 1) Turn off the server and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the server, and then retry the operation.
SWC0088.Message: Unable to retrieve the iDRAC DHCP IP address.

SEC0045.Message: Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) is operating correctly.

SYS097.Description: The Lifecycle Controller State has been set to disabled by the configuration profile import operation. Further changes to the system configuration require the Lifecycle Controller State to be enabled before the changes are processed.
SYS097.Resolution: If further configuration changes are required for the system, the Lifecycle Controller State must be enabled prior to attempting the configuration change. To enable the Lifecycle Controller State, run the racadm command "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState Enabled".
SYS097.Message: The state of Lifecycle Controller is disabled by the configuration profile import operation.

LC051.Description: There can only be one Server Profile Export job at a time.
LC051.Resolution: Wait for the existing Server Profile Export job to run and complete or cancel it, before retrying the operation.
LC051.Message: Cannot create multiple Server Profile Export jobs.

RAC0121.Description: SD card not readable. The card must be initialized.
RAC0121.Resolution: Initialize the SD card before it can be used.

VFL0001.Description: The requested operation for the vFlash SD Card completed successfully.
VFL0001.Message: The vFlash SD Card operation is successful.

VF012.Description: There is no SD card detected.

HWC1105.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message is removed from the unsupported slot identified in the message.
HWC1105.Message: The %1 is removed from the slot %2.

CPU0703.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.
CPU0703.Resolution: 1) Check system and operating system logs for exceptions. If no exceptions are found continue. 2) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 3) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 4) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

UEFI0207.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Command Clock Training - Group 2 phase.
UEFI0207.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0207.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

MEM9002.Description: A correctable error was detected in propagation of signals between processors through the Intel QPI interconnect interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9002.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the server and check whether the issue persists. 2) If the issue is not resolved by the preceding action, reseat the processors and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9002.Message: Intel QPI interconnect %1 has a correctable error.

RAC962.Description: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to run the operation.
RAC962.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle controller using the racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1 command, and retry the operation.
RAC962.Message: Unable to continue with the operation because Lifecycle Controller is in recovery state.

BIOS031.Description: The configuration operation cannot be started because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.
BIOS031.Resolution: Make sure that the Lockdown.1#SystemLockdown attribute is set to Disabled in the DCIM_iDracCardEnumeration class by running the WS-Man get command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation.
BIOS031.Message: Unable to start the configuration operation because the System Lockdown mode is enabled.

FAN901.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully disabled.
FAN901.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully disabled.

SWC0118.Description: The syntax of the sslcertupload command is invalid.
SWC0118.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertupload subcommand.

HWC4012.Message: Hardware successfully updated for embedded NIC.

UEFI0279.Description: The Post Package Repair (PPR) operation in the DIMM memory slot identified in the message is successfully completed.
UEFI0279.Message: The Post Package Repair (PPR) operation in the DIMM memory slot %1 is successfully completed.

PDR14.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

LOG504.Description: The Chassis Log was successfully exported to the destination specified.

BAR061.Description: Collecting system information and copying it into the backup file. The operation collects system information that includes System Model and Service Tag.

LIC904.Description: The network share is not accessible from the iDRAC.
LIC904.Resolution: Verify the network share connection and retry the operation.
LIC904.Message: Could not connect to network share.

RAC1192.Description: The Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is currently disabled. If the system inventory is not up-to-date, the system configuration profile that is being copied will not have the latest inventory information.
RAC1192.Resolution: To get latest inventory information, cancel the current job, run "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart 1" to enable CSIOR, and re-initiate the operation.
RAC1192.Message: The Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

JCP8501.Description: This job information message occurs if some configuration stored in the profile are not applicable to the target server.
JCP8501.Message: Job ID: %1. CMC sent %2 properties from %3 profile to the server (Service Tag: %4 ) in the slot %5.

SRV113.Description: The export or upload operation cannot be started because the SupportAssist Collection is not available on the iDRAC.
SRV113.Resolution: Make sure that the SupportAssist Collection is available on iDRAC and retry the operation. To generate a SupportAssist Collection by using RACADM command line interface (CLI), enter "racadm supportassist collect".
SRV113.Message: Unable to start the export or upload operation because the SupportAssist Collection is not available on the iDRAC.

VF033.Description: The specified format type is not a valid type.
VF033.Resolution: Try a format type that is supported.

BOOT018.Description: The Boot Control List specified in the operation is read-only and cannot be modified.
BOOT018.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on validity of operation for the Boot Control List specified. For more information on the operation, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
BOOT018.Message: Specified Boot Control List is read-only

HWC5031.Description: The CMC has powered off the IOM.
HWC5031.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

SYS151.Description: A System Erase job with the job ID identified in the message is completed.

BAR116.Description: Unable to create a recurring export Server Profile job because an existing scheduled Backup Image job is scheduled within the next 24 hours.
BAR116.Message: Unable to create a recurring export Server Profile job because an existing scheduled Backup Image job is scheduled within the next 24 hours.

RAC1136.Description: The remote unattended diagnostic execution operation is initiated.
RAC1136.Resolution: Using the RACADM command line interface, run the "racadm jobqueue view -i <job id>" command to view the status of the operation.
RAC1136.Message: Remote unattended diagnostic execution operation initiated.

UEFI0024.Description: The Management Engine firmware is not responding to the BIOS via the HECI interface.
UEFI0024.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0024.Message: The Management Engine is not responding.

IOV011.Description: All servers that PCIe slots or virtual adapter (VA) will be assigned-to and unassigned-from must be turned off before an assign or unassign operation can be performed.
IOV011.Resolution: Turn off all servers that the PCIe slots or virtual adapter (VA) will be assigned-to and unassigned-from, and then retry the operation.
IOV011.Message: Unable to assign or unassign PCIe slot(s) or virtual adapter (VA) because all affected servers must be turned off.

RAC1205.Description: The Secure Boot Certificate Restore operation is successfully scheduled. For the changes to become effective, restart the host server.
RAC1205.Message: The Secure Boot Certificate Restore operation is successfully scheduled.

RFM1032.Description: The card is write-protected by the physical latch on the SD card. IDSDM cannot use a write-protected card.
RFM1032.Resolution: If unintended, remove the media and disable write protection.
RFM1032.Message: Removable Flash Media is write protected.

SYS004.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.
SYS004.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation and retry the operation with a valid value for the identified parameter.

SWC1950.Description: The Quick Sync inactivity timeout configuration is disabled. The iDRAC Quick Sync feature will remain available after pressing the activate/deactivate button.
SWC1950.Message: The Quick Sync inactivity timeout configuration is disabled.

RAC0237.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while uploading the vFlash image.
RAC0237.Resolution: Try uploading the vFlash image again.
RAC0237.Message: An error occurred while uploading the vFlash image.

VF028.Description: This partition is detached and attempts to detach it will fail.

PWR1001.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1001.Resolution: Review system configuration and power consumption.

RAC0606.Description: The selected network connection test operation was successful.
RAC0606.Message: The network connection test operation was successful.

OSD30.Description: The value specified for ExposeDuration is out of range. It must be between 60 and 65535 seconds.
OSD30.Resolution: Rerun the command with a ExposeDuration value between 60 and 65535 seconds.
OSD30.Message: Invalid value for ExposeDuration - must be 60 - 65535 seconds

RED101.Description: The firmware version cannot be updated because the license version of the currently installed firmware does not allow the update process.
RED101.Resolution: Make sure that the recommended license is installed, and then retry updating the firmware. For information about compatible license versions, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
RED101.Message: Unable to update the firmware version because the license version of the currently installed firmware does not allow the update process.

IOID004.Description: The Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Non-Auxiliary powered devices is changed to the restart type identified in the message.
IOID004.Message: Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Non-Auxiliary powered devices is changed to %1.

GMGR0059.Description: The configuration clone operation is successfully completed to clone the group email alert settings while the server is joined to the group. The job status is as identified in the message.
GMGR0059.Message: The configuration clone operation is successfully completed to clone the group email alert settings while the server is joined to the group. The job status is %1.

UEFI0251.Description: A memory riser was detected behind an empty processor socket. Memory must be installed behind a populated processor socket in order to be recognized by the system and available for usage. Check to make sure processors and memory are installed in a supported configuration.
UEFI0251.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Populate processors and memory in a supported configuration and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0251.Message: Memory riser %1 is populated behind an empty processor socket.

FCD8500.Description: The server specified in the message must be turned off or the server slot must be empty before changing the FlexAddress configuration.
FCD8500.Resolution: Turn off the server and retry the operation.
FCD8500.Message: Unable to apply the %1 configuration. The affected servers (slot %2) are not turned off.

VDR14.Description: A user cancelled the consistency check operation for a virtual disk.
VDR14.Message: The consistency check on %1 was cancelled.

SYS016.Description: All the operations in the Job were attempted, but some did not complete successfully.
SYS016.Resolution: Review the Job content and verify the values are correct. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation.

BAR058.Description: The system profile import or export network destination is being tested for access.

SWC0218.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0218.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0218.Message: The -c option requires -p to also be specified.

CTL7.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL7.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.

PWR8564.Description: The server identified in the message was not turned on because the available power is less than the requested power.
PWR8564.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller web interface to check the System Input Max Power Capacity Power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, retry the operation. Otherwise, increase the System Input Power Cap value.
PWR8564.Message: Unable to turn on the Server %1 because the power request exceeded the System Input Power Cap.

UEFI0246.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. Link option mismatch detected.
UEFI0246.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0246.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

SEC0000.Description: The chassis is open. System performance may be degraded, and security may be compromised.
SEC0000.Resolution: Close the chassis. Check system logs.

LC056.Description: The name value pairs in the input parameter arrays do not match in the input.
LC056.Resolution: Retry the operation with a valid (AttributeName, AttributeValue) pair.

RAC1042.Description: One or more required options to configure the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature are missing.
RAC1042.Resolution: For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help autoupdatescheduler".
RAC1042.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings. The required options are either invalid or not provided.

RAC0633.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid password is entered.
RAC0633.Resolution: Enter a valid network file share password, and then retry the operation.
RAC0633.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid network share password is entered.

CMC8578.Description: The Remote Access Controller (RAC) SSL Certificate and key is changed.
CMC8578.Message: The Remote Access Controller (RAC) SSL Certificate and key is changed.

RAC1225.Description: The Secure Boot Certificate cannot be imported because the size of the file being imported is greater than the maximum size supported.
RAC1225.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Restart the server and press F2 when the company logo is displayed. 2) On the System Setup page, click System BIOS. 3) On the System BIOS page, click System Security. 4) In the Secure Boot section, click Custom corresponding to Secure Boot Policy, and then import the file. For more information about the importing process, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
RAC1225.Message: Unable to import the Secure Boot Certificate because the size of the file being imported is greater than the maximum size supported.

OSD37.Description: ISO Image size is bigger than the available size in vFlash.
OSD37.Resolution: 1) Use a smaller size ISO Image. 2) Format the vFlash using the iDRAC GUI, RACADM, or iDRAC configuration utility and then retry this command.

SWC8603.Description: The selected profile cannot be applied to the server identified in the message, because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature on the server is disabled.
SWC8603.Resolution: Make sure that CSIOR on the server identified in the messages is enabled and retry the operation. For 11th generation servers, to enable CSIOR, restart the server, and select the Ctrl-E setup. Select System Services, and enable CSIOR. For 12th generation and above, to enable CSIOR using Lifecycle Controller GUI, restart the server, click <F2> when the company's logo is displayed. On the iDRAC Settings page, click Lifecycle Controller, and enable CSIOR.
SWC8603.Message: Unable to apply profile to server %1 using Quick Deploy feature, because the CSIOR feature on Server %1 is disabled.

RFM1020.Message: Removable Flash Media is IPMI-function ready.

RAC0274.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0274.Resolution: See iDRAC user documentation for more information on using racadm.
RAC0274.Message: See the iDRAC user documentation for more information on using the Racadm utility or the serial interface.

BAR067.Description: The system profile export destination is not initialized.
BAR067.Resolution: Initialize the vFlash media and retry the operation.

RAC1178.Description: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC and a configuration XML import operation is in progress.
RAC1178.Resolution: Wait until the configuration XML import operation has completed before attempting another operation. Verify the status of the configuration XML import operation by running the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view".
RAC1178.Message: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC and a configuration XML import operation is in progress.

RED093.Description: Lifecycle Controller is not enabled and must be enabled in order for scheduled jobs to be created.
RED093.Resolution: Enable Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. Lifecycle Controller can be enabled by using the F2 System Setup by pressing F2 during server startup, then select iDRAC Settings > Lifecycle Controller and enable the Lifecycle Controller feature. Retry the operation after the server restarts.
RED093.Message: The requested job cannot be scheduled because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

MEM0002.Description: The memory is operational. This is an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0002.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0002.Message: Parity memory errors detected on a memory device at location %1.

SWC1927.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-only mode.
SWC1927.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-only mode.

TMP0104.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0104.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0104.Message: The system board %1 temperature is outside of range.

SEL1500.Message: The chassis management controller (CMC) is redundant.

STOR0109.Description: No power supply unit data to display. The system is powered off, no power supply unit is present in the system, or the power supply unit is not connected to the enclosure.
STOR0109.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosure power supply unit is available, and power supply unit is connected to the enclosure.
STOR0109.Message: Power supply unit is not connected to the enclosure or data about power supply unit is unavailable.

RAC054.Description: The user account attributes cannot be reset to default values due to an internal error.
RAC054.Resolution: Make sure the configuration XML file contains valid values for user account attributes and retry the operation.
RAC054.Message: User account attributes cannot be reset to default values due to an internal error.

FAN1002.Description: The enclosure detected that a fan has failed and the enclosure is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

SWC0325.Message: The specified object is WRITE-ONLY and cannot be displayed.

BAT1011.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1011.Message: Battery on %1 is in warn only mode and requires reconditioning.

SUP021.Description: Diagnostics and USC updates are direct updates and cannot be scheduled.
SUP021.Resolution: Do not schedule USC or Diagnostics Jobs.
SUP021.Message: Diagnostics, Driver Pack or Lifecycle Controller update is a direct update and cannot be scheduled.

RAC0108.Description: A non-specific error is detected when accessing the Smart Card.
RAC0108.Resolution: Review the error message preceding or following this message.
RAC0108.Message: An internal error is encountered. Insert a valid Smart Card and try again.

SWC0297.Description: After the Groups are downloaded to a file, the passwords are to be deleted.
SWC0297.Message: Unable to remove passwords because file could not be saved.

SYS438.Description: The Secure Boot keys cannot be reset because the installed BIOS version does not support the operation.
SYS438.Resolution: Update the BIOS to the latest version and retry the operation. For information about updating BIOS, see the iDRAC Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS438.Message: Unable to reset the Secure Boot keys because the installed BIOS version does not support the operation.

BIOS014.Description: AttributeValue may be invalid because of the following causes: 1) Length of new AttributeValue is not within required minimum length and maximum length 2) Value of new AttributeValue is not within required LowerBound and UpperBound 3) Value of new AttributeValue is not one of the possible values.
BIOS014.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on valid Attribute values.

SYS236.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported username value.
SYS236.Resolution: Make sure that the correct username value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS236.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported username value.

RAC0508.Description: The server encountered an unexpected condition. This may be due to invalid JavaScript Object Notation.
RAC0508.Resolution: Wait for few minutes and refresh the page. If the problem persists, contact service provider.

LC038.Description: Lifecycle Controller is locked by another instance of the Hardware Inventory export process. Allow the process to complete before attempting another export operation.
LC038.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset the iDRAC and rerun the command.
LC038.Message: An instance of Hardware Inventory export is already in progress.

CMC8531.Description: The user account does not have sufficient privileges to perform the virtual reseat operation on the Sleeve or Sled specified in the message. The server administration privilege is required to perform a virtual reseat operation. This applies to Sleeve or Sled components.
CMC8531.Resolution: Use a different user account that has server administration privileges, and retry the operation. For more information, contact your system administrator about necessary privileges.
CMC8531.Message: Unable to perform the requested action on the Sleeve or Sled %1 because of insufficient user privileges.

JCP043.Description: The update operation cannot be started because the Export or Server Profile Import operation is already in progress.
JCP043.Resolution: Wait for the Export or Server Profile Import operation to complete, and then retry the operation.
JCP043.Message: Unable to start the update operation because the Export or Server Profile Import operation is already in progress.

JCP020.Description: Existing jobs cannot be scheduled while an Export Server Profile or Import Server Profile job is running.
JCP020.Resolution: Retry the job scheduling operation after the export or import operation is completed.
JCP020.Message: Cannot schedule jobs while export or import operations are running.

RAC037.Description: There are no pending configurations to delete.

SEC0605.Message: A setup password violation was corrected.

VLT0303.Description: High voltages may be the result of problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. Elevated voltages may result in damage to the processor or other system electrical components. The system may power down.
VLT0303.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0303.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

RED059.Description: Unable to create an update job for the component identified in the message.
RED059.Resolution: Retry the operation for the component identified in the message.
RED059.Message: Unable to create an update job for %1.

SUP0542.Description: The firmware cannot be updated because the file identified in the message is not authentic. The firmware image file may be corrupted.
SUP0542.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, download the latest Update Package from the support site and retry the operation. Else, contact your service provider.
SUP0542.Message: Unable to update the firmware because the firmware image file %1 is not authentic.

PR2.Description: The specified device configuration is different from the previous device configuration.

CTL90.Description: The peer controller is not compatible with the controller identified in the message because of a hardware mismatch.
CTL90.Resolution: Replace the peer controller with the same model controller as the controller identified in the message.
CTL90.Message: %1 is not operating in Fault Tolerant Mode because of an incompatible peer controller.

SYS240.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported mount-point path value.
SYS240.Resolution: Make sure that the correct mount-point path value is entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS240.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported mount-point path value.

RAC0711.Description: Unknown power on response from the CMC.
RAC0711.Resolution: Try resetting the CMC. Also try resetting the server.
RAC0711.Message: Unknown power on response from the CMC.

GMGR0069.Description: The group job cannot be cancelled because it is not in the scheduled state. Active and completed group jobs cannot be cancelled.
GMGR0069.Message: Unable to cancel the group job because it is not in the scheduled state.

RAC0801.Description: iDRAC closes all the existing sessions and all configuration settings are set to default values. The iDRAC IP address is set to the default static IP address.
RAC0801.Message: iDRAC has reset to default settings.

STOR090.Description: Unable to create a virtual disk because an invalid combination of span count or disks passed was entered for the RAID level selected.
STOR090.Resolution: Enter a span count value (-sc option) or number of disks (-pdkey option) that is appropriate for the RAID level selected. See the PERC Controller Users Guide for valid span count and number of disks required for a raid level. Retry the operation by running the RACADM storage createvd command with the appropriate options.
STOR090.Message: Unable to create a virtual disk because an invalid combination of span count or number of disks was entered for the RAID level selected.

SRV118.Description: The SupportAssist operation cannot be started because the Lifecycle Controller is not ready.
SRV118.Resolution: Wait for the current operation to complete and Lifecycle Controller to be in ready state, and then retry the operation.
SRV118.Message: Unable to start the SupportAssist operation because the Lifecycle Controller is not ready.

PST0137.Description: System BIOS detected a parity error during post This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code 89).
PST0137.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

UEFI0270.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the network connection to DHCPv4 server is not established.
UEFI0270.Resolution: Check the network cable connection of the initiator or the DHCPv4 server and retry the operation.
UEFI0270.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the network connection to DHCPv4 server is not established.

PWR8575.Description: A Virtual Reseat for the server identified in the message is initiated. A Virtual Reseat is the same as removing and inserting a server.
PWR8575.Message: Initiated the Virtual Reseat of server %1.

NIC022.Description: The current BIOS password jumper setting prevents the BIOS password from being changed.
NIC022.Resolution: Change the jumper setting to enable setting the BIOS password.
NIC022.Message: Unable to set the BIOS password because of a jumper setting on the motherboard.

SRV068.Description: The SupportAssist Enclosure Controller logs collection operation did not complete successfully.
SRV068.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and Enclosure Controller (EC) and then retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm racreset". To reset the EC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm chassisaction reset".
SRV068.Message: The SupportAssist Enclosure Controller logs collection operation did not complete successfully.

RRDU0008.Description: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild failed because read/write to one of the SD cards failed.
RRDU0008.Resolution: Replace the failed SD card and retry rebuild.
RRDU0008.Message: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild did not complete successfully.

UEFI0316.Description: Unable to allocate Memory Mapped Input Output (MMIO) resources for one or more PCIe cards either because of insufficient MMIO memory space, or because the NVRAM_CLR jumper is already installed.
UEFI0316.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Remove the NVRAM_CLR jumper. 2) Remove the unused PCIe cards to provide more Memory Mapped Input Output (MMIO) memory space.
UEFI0316.Message: Unable to allocate Memory Mapped Input Output (MMIO) resources for one or more PCIe cards either because of insufficient MMIO memory space, or because the NVRAM_CLR jumper is already installed.

LC043.Description: Work notes cannot include non-printable or reserved characters, such as &, <, >, /.
LC043.Resolution: Do not use non-printable characters or reserved characters such as &, <, >, and /.
LC043.Message: Work note contains non-printable or reserved characters.

IOV1001.Description: The requested operation was successfully executed.
IOV1001.Message: The requested operation was successfully executed.

PWR8665.Description: The property chassis power button is either enabled or disabled as identified in the message.

MEM1014.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in a power save state.

RDU0015.Description: The system may power down or operate in a performance degraded state.
RDU0015.Resolution: Check the event log for power supply failures. Review system configuration and power consumption and upgrade or install power supplies accordingly.
RDU0015.Message: The power supplies are not redundant. Insufficient resources to maintain normal operations.

STOR068.Description: The requested RAID configuration operation did not succeed because the Lifecycle Controller version on the target server does not have the necessary capabilities.
STOR068.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Controller version on the target server and update it with the latest version available.
STOR068.Message: Unable to perform the requested RAID configuration because the Lifecycle Controller version on the server does not have the necessary capabilities.

TMP7.Description: A device has been failed and the system is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

RED098.Description: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is not compatible with the target system.
