RED098.Resolution: Identify and download the firmware version that corresponds to the system model being updated, and retry the operation. For a list of supported firmware versions, refer to the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
RED098.Message: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is not compatible with the target system model.

UEFI0055.Description: The debranding process cannot be completed because of the reasons identified on the computer screen.
UEFI0055.Resolution: Check the screen display for details of the failure. Retry the debrand process again, or update the system BIOS and then retry.
UEFI0055.Message: Unable to complete the debranding operation because of the issue(s) displayed earlier.

SUP0534.Description: The catalog file cannot be found in the specified location.
SUP0534.Resolution: Specify the correct repository location and retry the operation.
SUP0534.Message: Unable to locate the catalog file.

SWC0072.Description: SupportAssist collection cannot be exported to the destination folder.
SWC0072.Resolution: Verify the following and retry the operation: 1) Destination folder is present. 2) Destination folder has sufficient free disk space. 3) Destination folder is not write-protected. If the issue persists, perform an AC power cycle operation, and then retry the operation.
SWC0072.Message: Unable to export the SupportAssist collection to destination folder.

SWC0283.Description: The value given for the object is not valid.
SWC0283.Resolution: Enter a valid value for the corresponding object.
SWC0283.Message: The specified object value is not valid.

SEC0703.Description: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is disabled.
SEC0703.Message: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is disabled.

RAC010.Description: The input value for the attribute being set contains characters that are not allowed.
RAC010.Resolution: Retry the operation using valid input characters. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

VF049.Description: The initializing SD card operation did not complete successfully.
VF049.Message: Initialize media operation did not complete successfully.

UEFI0118.Description: Card identification signature is not present on Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card 2.
UEFI0118.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Check the IDSDM or the SD card media. 2) Try reseat or replace the SD card media. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0118.Message: Card identification signature is not present on Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card 2.

MEM0010.Resolution: If unexpected, review system logs for power or thermal exceptions.
MEM0010.Message: Memory device at location %1 is overheating.

VLT0209.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0209.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0209.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PDR95.Description: The attempt to update the physical disk has failed. This is due to too much activity on the bus, a bad update package, or a bad disk.
PDR95.Resolution: Retry the update. If the update fails a second time, verify the update package is valid. If the update package is valid, replace the failing disk. Contact technical support if the problem persists.

SYS160.Description: The Lifecycle Controller log data deleted as part of a System Erase operation. All previously stored information is no longer available.
SYS160.Message: The Lifecycle Controller logs are cleared.

UEFI0205.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Command Clock Training - Group 0 phase.
UEFI0205.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0205.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC046.Description: The event notification selected is not supported for the event filter specified.
RAC046.Resolution: Refer to the iDRAC User Guide and Lifecycle Controller documentation and retry the operation with a valid event notification selection on the specified filter.
RAC046.Message: Unsupported event notification for the event filter specified.

CPU0800.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is present.

SEL0010.Description: When the event log is full, additional events are not written to the log or older events will be overwritten and lost. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 05h).
SEL0010.Resolution: Backup and clear log at the next maintained time.
SEL0010.Message: System event log (SEL) is almost full.

VFL0719.Description: The SD card is in use by another process. Initialization requires exclusive access to the SD card to complete the initialization.
VFL0719.Resolution: The SD card is in use by another process. Retry after a few minutes.
VFL0719.Message: One or more partitions are in use; the SD card could not be initialized.

SWC8512.Description: Unable to add user name identified in the message. The reason for this issue is described with the error code in the message.
SWC8512.Resolution: Correct the error described in the message and retry the operation after a few minutes.

SYS276.Description: The file identified in the message will be applied, but only limited features are made available for use until the firmware update prerequisite identified in the message is fully installed.
SYS276.Resolution: No response action is required for using base features. However, to use all features, make sure that the firmware prerequisite identified in the message is installed, and then retry updating the firmware. For information about prerequisite firmware, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
SYS276.Message: The firmware file %1 will be successfully applied, but only limited features are made available for use until the firmware update prerequisite %2 is fully installed.

PST0001.Description: System BIOS detected the system is turned on.

OSE1003.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. Verify the media in C: is bootable. See system video for additional information.

JCP019.Description: A new job cannot be created until the existing Import Server Profile job is complete or deleted. Only one Import Server Profile job can be running at any given time.
JCP019.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation after the Import Server Profile job is complete. 2) Delete the scheduled Import Server Profile job and retry the operation.
JCP019.Message: Cannot create new jobs until the existing Import System Profile job is completed or cancelled.

SWU8545.Description: The firmware update operation of the Standby CMC was not successful.
SWU8545.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware.

SWC0028.Description: iDRAC is unable to complete the backup Server Profile operation because an unrecoverable error occurred.
SWC0028.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0028.Message: The backup Server Profile operation did not successfully complete.

LC031.Description: An internal error occurred while exporting the Hardware Inventory XML file.
LC031.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the command.
LC031.Message: Internal error occurred while exporting inventory.

HWC5006.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

SUP014.Description: An unknown error was encountered while trying to delete the job.
SUP014.Resolution: Retry the action. If this fails, reboot the iDRAC.

MEM0001.Description: The memory has encountered a uncorrectable error. System performance may be degraded. The operating system and/or applications may fail as a result.
MEM0001.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0001.Message: Multi-bit memory errors detected on a memory device at location(s) %1.

FAN908.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already disabled.
FAN908.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already disabled.

RAC1033.Description: The server component software inventory cannot be retrieved because of an internal error.
RAC1033.Resolution: Make sure to enable Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature, reboot the server, and retry the operation. If CSIOR is already enabled, restart iDRAC using "racadm racreset" command, and retry the operation.
RAC1033.Message: Unable to retrieve the server component software inventory.

LC072.Description: An SSL Certificate is successfully generated in response to the requested operation.
LC072.Resolution: Download the SSL Certificate and get it signed by an authority.
LC072.Message: An SSL Certificate is successfully generated.

SWC1926.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync interface is enabled.
SWC1926.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync interface is enabled.

BAT0000.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0000.Resolution: Check the system board battery at the next service window.
BAT0000.Message: The system board battery is low.

SRV104.Description: The SupportAssist End User License Agreement (EULA) is not accepted.
SRV104.Resolution: Accept the SupportAssist End User License Agreement (EULA). To accept the SupportAssist EULA using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm supportassist accepteula".
SRV104.Message: The SupportAssist End User License Agreement (EULA) is not accepted.

UEFI0221.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Read Voltage Training phase.
UEFI0221.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0221.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

PST0139.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the Keyboard Controller. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code 8B).
PST0139.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

BAT1017.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1017.Message: The %1 battery learn mode has changed to Warn.

SWC8556.Description: The Boot Identity profile identified in the message is in use by the server that has the Service Tag identified in the message.
SWC8556.Message: The Boot Identity profile %1 is in use by the server that has the Service Tag %2.

RAC1129.Description: The BootOnce object could not be modified, because the FirstBootDevice object is set to either F10, F11, or BIOS.
RAC1129.Resolution: Configure the FirstBootDevice object to values other than F10, F11, or BIOS and retry the set operation for the BootOnce object. For more information about possible FirstBootDevice values, run the RACADM command "racadm help idrac.serverboot.firstbootdevice".
RAC1129.Message: Unable to modify the BootOnce object.

PDR72.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC1073.Description: The threshold value of the sensor identified in the message cannot be successfully set because the capability reset the sensor threshold value is not supported.
RAC1073.Resolution: No response action is required. For more information about resetting the threshold level of a sensor, run the "racadm getsensorinfo" command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation.
RAC1073.Message: Unable to reset the threshold value of sensor %1 because the capability to reset this sensor threshold value is not supported.

CMC8524.Description: The Mezz card 4 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8524.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8524.Message: The Mezz card 4 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.

TMP0125.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0125.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

PWR8566.Description: Unable to turn off the Server before the Power Off timer has expired. This happens if the Server did not show "power off" status change within 30 seconds after the operation was initiated. This situation may also occur when iDRAC is rebooting.
PWR8566.Resolution: The Server may need more time to turn off. Wait for ten seconds and check the power status. If the Server was not turned off, retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the Server, wait for the iDRAC to complete startup, and retry the operation.
PWR8566.Message: Unable to turn off the Server %1 before the Power Off timer expired.

SYS239.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported share name value.
SYS239.Resolution: Make sure that the correct share name value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS239.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported share name value, %2.

SWC8520.Description: Unable to modify the user name specified in the message.
SWC8520.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8520.Message: Unable to modify user name from %1 to %2: %3-%4

IPA0001.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.
IPA0001.Message: Invalid NIC IP address parameter specified.

BAR083.Description: System profile backup file validation failed because the host system model information does not match the value stored in the file.
BAR083.Resolution: Obtain a valid host system backup image and try the operation again. Reboot the remote access controller and try the operation again. If the error continues, download a new remote access controller firmware image and try the operation again.
BAR083.Message: Host System Model does not match the Backup file System Model information.

PSU1003.Description: The power supply is not providing any power. This may be because the power supply switch is in the off position or the power supply has failed.
PSU1003.Resolution: Check whether the power switch on the power supply unit is turned off or on. If it is turned off, turn it on. If the problem is not corrected, verify that the power cord is attached and functional. See the storage hardware documentation for more information.

PWR8654.Description: CMC could not successfully send the power allocation information to the component identified in the message, because either iDRAC is stopped after the power allocation was sent by CMC or the communication between CMC and iDRAC has ended.
PWR8654.Resolution: Perform a Virtual Reseat operation of the component, and then retry the operation. To virtually reseat a component, log in to the CMC Web interface, select Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components > select the option corresponding to the component, and then click Virtual Reseat.
PWR8654.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to send power allocation information to the component %1-%2.

RAC0656.Description: The iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service cannot be started by just enabling in iDRAC web interface because the service has to also be manually restarted on the server operating system.
RAC0656.Resolution: To re-enable the iDRAC Service Module (iSM), do the following: 1) Enable the iSM in the iDRAC web interface, 2) Start the iSM service on the server operating system.
RAC0656.Message: Are you sure you want to disable the iDRAC Service Module on the server operating system?

SEL1206.Message: An entry was added to auxiliary log.

PDR1122.Message: Drive %1 is no longer in the failed array.

SWC0266.Description: The SD card may not be inserted/inserted properly.
SWC0266.Resolution: Ensure that the SD card is inserted in the server.
SWC0266.Message: Unable to perform the requested operation. Make sure SD card is inserted.

HWC5035.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure fans are installed and working correctly. 2) Check the temperature sensor status for the chassis and make sure it is within the chassis operating temperature range. 3) Reseat the I/O module to clear the over-temperature condition. If the problem persists, contact the service provider.
HWC5035.Message: An over-temperature event detected on I/O module %1.

RRDU0004.Resolution: Install additional SD card and configure for redundancy if redundancy is desired.
RRDU0004.Message: Internal Dual SD Module is not redundant.

RFL2006.Description: The module is write-protected. Changes may not be written to the media.
RFL2006.Resolution: If unintended, remove the media and disable write protection.
RFL2006.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is write protected.

BAT1002.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1002.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has started.

IOV010.Description: Unable to assign the PCIe slots because a license is required to assign more than two PCIe slots to a server. Non-licensed systems are allowed only two slots per server.
IOV010.Resolution: Import a license that allows assignments of more than two PCIe slots per server. For more information about licenses, contact your service provider.
IOV010.Message: Unable to assign the PCIe slot(s) because a license is required to assign more than two PCIe slots to a server.

OSD77.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is missing.
OSD77.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ResetType" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD77.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is missing.

LIC203.Description: Signature verification failed due to an error in the saved license file.
LIC203.Resolution: Delete and re-import the license file.
LIC203.Message: The license %1 has encountered an error.

RAC1208.Description: The operation cannot be completed because an invalid Certificate or Key Type is entered.
RAC1208.Resolution: Enter a valid Certificate or Key Type and retry the operation. To view a list of valid types, enter the following RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI): "racadm help <subcommand>". Also, see the RACADM CLI Reference Guide available on the support site.
RAC1208.Message: Unable to complete the operation because an invalid Certificate or Key Type is entered.

RSI0004.Description: The Remote Service database is unavailable.

BAR085.Description: The validation of the system profile backup file has failed. The retrieval of system information to validate the backup file has failed.
BAR085.Resolution: Restart the remote access controller, and retry the operation. If the error continues, use the remote access controller firmware to try the operation again.
BAR085.Message: Unable to collect System Information for Import Backup file validation.

BIOS026.Description: The status of the Password cannot be set to locked, because currently there is a System Password change is pending.
BIOS026.Resolution: Wait until the pending System Password change is applied or delete the pending System Password change and retry the operation.
BIOS026.Message: Password status cannot be set to locked when a System Password change is pending.

SUP0110.Description: The firmware update is being uninitialized.
SUP0110.Message: Uninitializing firmware update services. Please wait.

PSU0032.Resolution: Check the system operating environment, including airflow and inlet temperature. Check system logs for temperature and thermal component failures.

VDR39.Description: The virtual disk check consistency has identified issues and made corrections. For example, the check consistency may have encountered a bad disk block and remapped the disk block to restore data consistency. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR39.Resolution: No response action is required. As a precaution, monitor the Log for other errors related to this virtual disk. If problems persist, contact technical support.
VDR39.Message: The check consistency has made corrections and completed for %1.

SYS156.Description: The requested component erase tasks of the System Erase operation is successfully completed.
SYS156.Message: Erase operations for System Erase tasks successfully completed.

ASR0107.Description: The operating system or an application failed to respond to a pre-notification with-in the timeout period. (IPMI sensor type code 11h - offset 07h).
ASR0107.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0107.Message: The OS watchdog timer pre-timeout interrupt was initiated.

CTL75.Description: The controller cache was discarded by the user. Data may have been lost or corrupted.
CTL75.Resolution: If data was corrupted or lost, restore the data to the disk from a backup copy.

SEC0031.Description: The chassis is open. System performance may be degraded, and security may be compromised.
SEC0031.Resolution: Close the chassis. Check system logs.
SEC0031.Message: The chassis is open while the power is on.

TMP0301.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is disabled.
TMP0301.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is disabled.

LIC022.Description: License Manager database is locked while a backup and restore operation is in progress. License import/export/delete operations are not allowed but a user can view license information.
LIC022.Resolution: Wait until the backup or restore operation completes and try again.
LIC022.Message: License Manager database locked due to ongoing backup and restore operation.

CTL17.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

HWC1201.Description: The sled identified in the message is removed from the slot identified in the message.
HWC1201.Message: The sled %1 is removed from slot %2.

SYS1004.Description: This message is for debugging purposes only.

SYS428.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the property identified in the message is not supplied as part of the request.
SYS428.Resolution: Make sure that the property is in the request body and has a valid value, and retry the operation.
SYS428.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the property %1 is a required property and must be included in the request.

PST0138.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the SIO. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST code exception code 8A).
PST0138.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PR32.Description: The configuration changes requested, for the indicated job, have not passed the device specific verification check and will not be applied.
PR32.Resolution: Check the scripts or company documentation and try again.

SRV010.Description: The SupportAssist Storage Controller Logs collection operation is started.
SRV010.Message: The SupportAssist Storage Controller Logs collection operation is started.

LC027.Description: The Hardware Inventory XML file export operation was successful.
LC027.Message: The Hardware Inventory file export was successful.

HWC2005.Description: The cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC2005.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

SWC8561.Description: Some or all or the specified MAC addresses are removed from the Virtual MAC Address Pool. Some MAC addresses could not be removed because they were not present.
SWC8561.Message: Some or all or the specified MAC addresses are removed from the Virtual MAC Address Pool of Boot Identity profile operations.

PWR8510.Description: Unable to set the chassis power identified in the message.
PWR8510.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8510.Message: Unable to set chassis power property %1.

DIS115.Description: The AutoConfig configuration import operation could not be started, because no options were specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS115.Resolution: Make sure that the following are correctly entered in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC, and then retry the operation: 1) Filename -f <filename>). 2) The IP address of the server containing the filename (-i <ip-address>). 3) The share type (-s <0, 2, 4 or 5>) where 0 = NFS, 2 = CIFS, 4 = HTTP, 5 = HTTPS. 4) For share type CIFS and NFS, provide the network share name (-n <share-name>). 5) For share type CIFS, provide the username and password (-u <username> & -p <password>).
DIS115.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because no options were specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

SWC1912.Description: User ID Access Right has been changed.
SWC1912.Message: User ID %1 User Access Right has been changed.

SWC1913.Description: Network Time Protocol configuration is enabled.
SWC1913.Message: Network Time Protocol configuration is enabled.

TST103.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the operation are missing.
TST103.Resolution: To provide the correct parameters, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

SYS138.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server OS is turned off.
SYS138.Resolution: Turn on the server and wait until the OS finishes booting, and then retry the operation.
SYS138.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server is turned off.

USR0021.Description: The session could not be closed. A possible reason is that the session does not exist.
USR0021.Message: Unable to close session with the specified ID

VRM0014.Description: Racadm tool was unable to get the status of the USB interface.
VRM0014.Message: Unable to determine current state of Virtual Media USB interface.

SYS293.Description: The configuration changes for the component identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) was successfully previewed.
SYS293.Resolution: No response action is required. For more information, see the Lifecycle Log data.

SUP0117.Message: Firmware rollback initiated successfully. The iDRAC will now reset to complete the firmware rollback operation.

CMC8522.Description: The Mezz card 2 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8522.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8522.Message: The Mezz card 2 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.

AMP0311.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is within range.

UEFI0113.Description: The Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.
UEFI0113.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure the Memory Mirroring feature can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0113.Message: Unable to enable the Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) feature because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.

BAR016.Description: A system profile import operation has been requested.

OSE1002.Description: The system OS has successfully booted from C:.

PDR1008.Message: Rebuild was aborted for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

SWU8531.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful, because the Update process was not completed within the firmware update timeout duration.
SWU8531.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware. The firmware update timeout limit is exceeded.

SWC8535.Description: Public Key (PK) SSH Authentication key file upload did not complete successfully because Chassis Management Controller is unable to access the configuration database.
SWC8535.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8535.Message: Unable to add key for slot %1 of service account, due to problem saving key file.

RAC0182.Description: The iDRAC was reset for the reason identified in the message. The reasons may include: AC Power Cycle, Watchdog timer expiry, or a reset initiated via user interface or ID Button.
RAC0182.Message: The iDRAC firmware was rebooted with the following reason: %1.

FSD002.Description: A RACADM Debug command failed. If the RACADM Debug command was executed under the direction of Dell tech support then further assistance from tech support should be requested. Otherwise this command is not intended for customer use.
FSD002.Resolution: Verify all of the following 1) ensure that the unblock, grant, and invoke/start/stop/resume commands are all executed against the same iDRAC. 2) ensure dat.ini file has not been changed in any way. 3) ensure that current date falls between the start and end times. Note that Dell can further restrict both the set of debugCaps that is authorized and the start and stop times. If an authorized person did not enter a RACADM debug command then an attacker may have entered the command.
FSD002.Message: Debug authorization failed; for debugCaps: %1, authorized by iDRAC user: %2, and Dell employee: %3, at %4 for the period: %5 to %6.

USR0023.Description: The user privilege is invalid. This may be due to invalid combinations of privileges given to the user.
USR0023.Resolution: Request the administrator to assign appropriate user privileges to the specific user.
USR0023.Message: The current user privilege is not valid.

SWC0254.Description: Local Configuration using RACADM may be disabled.
SWC0254.Resolution: Check if the Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled and enable it through GUI.
SWC0254.Message: Unable to perform requested operation. If the operation attempted was to configure DRAC, possible reason may be that Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled.

TMP0118.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0118.Message: The system inlet temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

CPUA0023.Resolution: Verify processor installation. If present, reseat the processor.

RAC0252.Description: The vFlash partitions are detached Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0252.Resolution: Attach the partitions and try again.
RAC0252.Message: One or more partitions are currently detached.

CBL0005.Description: The backplane connector identified in the message is incorrectly connected to the motherboard SATA controller.
CBL0005.Resolution: Make sure the cable identified in the message is cabled correctly. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0005.Message: Backplane %1 %2 connector incorrectly connected to the motherboard SATA controller.

MEM9035.Description: The NVDIMM device in the slot identified in the message cannot be configured to save data during a power loss because of an issue in the NVDIMM.
MEM9035.Resolution: Remove and reinstall the Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device. If the issue persists, contact your service provider. For information about removing and reinstalling the NVDIMM, see the system Owner's Manual on the support site.
MEM9035.Message: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device in the slot %1 cannot be configured to save data during a power loss because of an issue in the NVDIMM.

RAC0129.Description: No status response was returned after completing the initialization request.
RAC0129.Resolution: Try reinitializing the card again in a few minutes.
RAC0129.Message: An error has occurred while initializing the SD card.

RAC0679.Description: Unable to process the request because a job operation is already running.
RAC0679.Resolution: Wait until the running job is completed or delete the scheduled job and retry the operation.
RAC0679.Message: A job operation is already running. Retry the operation after the existing job is completed.

RAC913.Description: The management system could not login to the iDRAC.
RAC913.Resolution: Verify whether the username and password given for the iDRAC are correct.
RAC913.Message: Unable to login to RAC using the specified address

RAC992.Description: The job ID specified in the message is invalid or was already deleted.
RAC992.Resolution: To monitor the current set of the jobs, use the "racadm jobqueue view" command.

RAC0615.Description: The contents of the PKCS12 file was not valid because one of the following: 1) Not a valid PKCS#12 file, 2) Not a valid pfx file or 3) Did not contain a valid key.
RAC0615.Resolution: Make sure to upload the file in PKCS#12 format. OpenSSL can be used to validate a PKCS#12 file.

VFL1016.Description: The SD card is not detected or not installed.
VFL1016.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
VFL1016.Message: Media not present for Removable Flash Media %1.

PDR1116.Description: The controller detected a drive removal.
PDR1116.Resolution: If unintended, verify drive installation. Remove and reseat the indicated disk. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SWU8559.Description: The firmware downgrade operation is unsuccessful. A downgrade to the firmware version uploaded is not supported.
SWU8559.Resolution: Refer to the platform Owner's Manual for more information or contact your service provider.
SWU8559.Message: The firmware downgrade operation is unsuccessful. A downgrade to the firmware version uploaded is not supported.

VRM0019.Description: The Remote Image is now configured and ready to use.

CMC8526.Description: CMC is unable to obtain the CPU information from the server specified in the message. This occurs if there is no communication between CMC and iDRAC.
CMC8526.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC. 2) Reset CMC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8526.Message: Unable to retrieve the server-%1 CPU information.

HWC2001.Description: The cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC2001.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC2001.Message: The %1 cable or interconnect is not connected or is improperly connected.

UEFI0049.Description: The NMI button cannot be enabled because either the NMI button is stuck or iDRAC firmware is not updated.
UEFI0049.Resolution: Correct the NMI button if stuck or update iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0049.Message: Unable to enable the Non-maskable Interrupt (NMI) button because either the NMI button is stuck or iDRAC firmware is not updated.

BAT1014.Description: Diagnostic event for service to determine if there is an ambient temperature problem.

SYS235.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an unsupported port number value.
SYS235.Resolution: Make sure that the correct workgroup value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS235.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an unsupported workgroup value.

SYS087.Description: When the configuration XML file specified in the Preview operation is imported to the system, a system reboot will occur to apply the configuration changes.
SYS087.Message: A system reboot will occur when the previewed configuration XML file is imported to the system.

PDR25.Description: Portions of the physical disk that were formerly inaccessible have been recovered. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

USR0152.Description: Could not successfully connect to the remote VNC session, because an incorrect VNC password was entered from the IP address identified in the message.
USR0152.Resolution: Enter the correct VNC password and retry the operation.
USR0152.Message: Unable to connect the remote VNC session, because an incorrect VNC password was entered from the IP %1.

ENC11.Description: An enclosure service tag was changed. In most circumstances, this service tag should only be changed by the service provider.
ENC11.Resolution: Make sure that the service tag was changed under authorized circumstances.

PDR33.Description: The controller cannot to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a dedicated hot spare. The disk either failed or was removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.
PDR33.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and installed. Check the cables. Refer to the product documentation and see the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the dedicated hot spare.
PDR33.Message: A dedicated hot spare has been removed. %1

SYS129.Description: Unable to complete XML transform on the data collected because the collected data is in an unexpected format.
SYS129.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS129.Message: OS Collector: Unable to complete XML transform on the data collected.

PDR18.Description: A physical disk assigned as a hot spare was unassigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically unassigned by Storage Management. Storage Management unassigns hot spares were used to rebuild data. Once the data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, the hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. Assign a new hot spare to maintain data protection in this situation.
PDR18.Resolution: Although this alert is provided for informational purposes, you may need to assign a new hot spare to the virtual disk. See Protecting Your Virtual Disk with a Hot Spare for more information.

SRV017.Description: The Storage Controller Log cannot be retrieved because another operation is in progress on the storage controller identified in the message.
SRV017.Resolution: View the job queue, make sure that all jobs are in completed state, and then retry the operation. To view the job queue using RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm jobqueue view".
SRV017.Message: Unable to retrieve the Storage Controller Log because another operation is in progress on the storage controller %1.

VF031.Description: The specified partition label is not a valid label.
VF031.Resolution: Try a label that complies with the standards for an OS volume label.

PWR209.Description: The redundancy policy cannot be changed to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.
PWR209.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR209.Message: Unable to change the redundancy policy to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.

CMC8614.Description: The reset process of iDRAC Non Maskable Interrupt (NMI) on server identified in the message is initiated.
CMC8614.Message: The reset process of iDRAC Non Maskable Interrupt (NMI) on server %1 is initiated.

SRV070.Description: Unable to collect Enclosure Controller (EC) logs because iDRAC is not able to communicate to the EC.
SRV070.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and Enclosure Controller (EC) and then retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm racreset". To reset the EC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm chassisaction reset". If racadm command fails, cold reset EC and iDRAC manually and retry the operation.
SRV070.Message: Unable to collect Enclosure Controller (EC) logs because iDRAC is not able to communicate to the EC.

BAR044.Description: Waiting for the host system to successfully get turned off.
BAR044.Message: Waiting for the host system to successfully get turned off.

RAC0635.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid domain name is entered.
RAC0635.Resolution: Enter a valid domain name, and then retry the operation.
RAC0635.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid domain name is entered.

UEFI0020.Description: The Lifecycle Controller feature is enabled.
UEFI0020.Message: The Lifecycle Controller feature is enabled.

USR8514.Description: A bezel that has the iDRAC LCD panel feature is detected.
USR8514.Message: A bezel that has the iDRAC LCD panel feature is detected.

PWR214.Description: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is enabled.
PWR214.Resolution: Disable Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) and retry the operation.
PWR214.Message: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is enabled.

CMC8551.Description: The message is displayed if the chassis health is not OK (non-critical or critical). The message after this message in the log indicates cause for the issue.

VLT0218.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0218.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0218.Message: The %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

RAC1199.Description: The Support Assist Automatic Collection scheduler settings cannot be configured because either the values are not entered or invalid.
RAC1199.Resolution: Retry the operation by entering correct values. For information about the correct values, run the RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI): racadm supportassist help autocollectscheduler.
RAC1199.Message: Unable to configure the Support Assist Automatic Collection scheduler settings because either the values are not entered or invalid.

SYS153.Description: The non-volatile cache of the controller identified in the message is being erased.
SYS153.Message: Deleting hardware cache data for controller: %1.

UEFI0215.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Basic Write Level Training phase.
UEFI0215.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0215.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

BAR064.Description: Collecting the Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware and copying it in the server profile backup file.
BAR064.Message: Collecting Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

PWR8673.Description: Displays voltage change with power configuration change.

CTL116.Description: The secure foreign locked drives cannot be unlocked because already unlocked drives are detected which have secure locked configuration that are neither imported nor erased.
CTL116.Resolution: The unlock command should be followed by an import config command to import a secure foreign locked configuration or by a cryptographic erase command. If the unlocked drives are not imported or erased, then further unlock operations on locked drives will be blocked. To import already unlocked drives on a controller, run the RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI): "racadm raid importconfig:<Controller FQDD>" where <Controller FQDD> is the FQDD identifier of the target controller. In order to erase the data on the unlocked drive, run the command: "racadm raid cryptographicerase:<Drive FQDD>" where <Drive FQDD> is the FQDD identifier of the target drive.
CTL116.Message: Unable to unlock secure foreign locked drives because already unlocked drives are detected that are neither imported nor deleted.

PSU1004.Description: The enclosure detected that AC power supply was restored to the power supply unit.
PSU1004.Message: Power supply cable has been inserted into %1.

SWU8532.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation is not successful, because an invalid parameter is entered.
SWU8532.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because an invalid parameter is entered. ErrorCode=0x%1.

JCP022.Description: An invalid Job ID was provided as input for a scheduling or deletion operation. The Job ID indicated in the message does not match an existing Job on the target system.
JCP022.Resolution: Verify the job ID value by enumerating job instances and validating that the Job ID value is correct for the job being scheduled or deleted. Retry the operation with the correct Job ID value.
JCP022.Message: Invalid Job ID %1 for scheduling or deletion operation.

SYS127.Description: OS log data was not collected. An issue occurred while collecting OS log data because of an unknown exception.
SYS127.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS127.Message: OS Collector: Unable to collect OS log data

LC015.Resolution: Check for correct parameter values: 1) Disabled 2) Apply always 3) Apply only if firmware match.

HWC4015.Description: CMC has old firmware and does not recognize the new device which has requested link tuning information. After updating the firmware the CMC will recognize the device.
HWC4015.Resolution: Update the CMC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.

RAC098.Description: The System Lockdown mode cannot be set because it is not supported by the ApplyAttribute method.
RAC098.Resolution: Use the ApplyAttribute, SetAttribute, or SetAttributes method, and retry the operation.
RAC098.Message: Unable to set the System Lockdown mode because it is not supported by the ApplyAttributes method.

RAC1059.Description: The requested firmware rollback operation could not be performed because another firmware update job is running or being scheduled.
RAC1059.Resolution: Wait until the existing firmware update jobs are completed or scheduled before retrying the operation. To monitor the status of the existing jobs, run the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view". If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and then retry the operation after the iDRAC has finished restarting.
RAC1059.Message: Rollback operation could not be performed because another firmware update job is running.

SYS076.Description: The configuration profile contains a component node that is not supported.
SYS076.Resolution: Make sure the input configuration profile only specifies supported component. Check the import operation job configuration results for the unsupported profile node.
SYS076.Message: Invalid or unsupported component specified in the input configuration profile.

SYS007.Description: The input value for the attribute being set is not within the acceptable range for the attribute.
SYS007.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation for the specific attribute and retry the operation with valid value within the range of the attribute.

RAC0562.Description: iDRAC automatically restored connection with CMC proxy component. Agent free Monitoring will now be supported for Chassis PCIe slots.
RAC0562.Message: iDRAC-CMC communication restored for agent free monitoring of chassis PCIe slots.

SEC0602.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0602.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

PCI3003.Message: Virtual MAC address for component at bus %1 device %2 function %3 was successfully programed.

PDR1006.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is in the failed array.

CTL84.Description: The firmware on the controller identified in the message is not supported by this version of the CMC. This may result in degraded functionality.
CTL84.Resolution: Update the CMC Firmware to the latest version available or revert the controller firmware to a previous version.
CTL84.Message: %1 is running an unsupported firmware version.

BIOS023.Description: An unrecoverable error occurred in the operation while communicating with iDRAC.
BIOS023.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue continues, reset the iDRAC.
BIOS023.Message: Cannot perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

RAC0646.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'day of the week' while scheduling a job.
RAC0646.Resolution: Enter a correct value, and then retry the operation.
RAC0646.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid value is entered for the day of the week.

VFL0704.Resolution: Insert the SD card and try again.
VFL0704.Message: SD card is not present and could not be initialized.

UEFI0171.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.
UEFI0171.Resolution: Dual Rank DIMM modules must be installed before Single Rank DIMM modules on the channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0171.Message: A Dual Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Single Rank DIMM module.

PDR116.Description: The PCIe Solid-State Drive is predicted to fail. Many physical disks contain Self Monitoring Analysis and Reporting Technology (SMART). When enabled, SMART monitors the disk health based on indications such as the number of write operations that were performed on the disk.
PDR116.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.

RDU0019.Message: The storage voltage is not redundant.

VLT0233.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0233.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the mezzanine card.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0233.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

NIC506.Description: The requested operation requires the DNS registration to be enabled.
NIC506.Message: The requested object requires DNS registration to be enabled.

SYS073.Description: The import of Server Configuration Profile operation completed with errors because the Lifecycle Controller State was disabled in the input profile. Configuration changes requiring a system reboot were not applied.
SYS073.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller State setting and retry the operation.
SYS073.Message: Unable to apply changes that require system reboot because the Lifecycle Controller State setting is disabled in the Server Configuration Profile.

PSU8503.Description: The input voltage of the PSU specified in the message does not match the input voltage of the PSUs already present in the chassis.
PSU8503.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check if the input voltage of all the PSUs are the same. 2) If the input voltage of the PSU specified in the message is not the same, then remove the unmatched PSU.
PSU8503.Message: The PSU in slot %1 detected 220 VAC input voltage and does not match chassis configuration.

BIOS002.Description: Unable to allocate required memory to perform the requested operation; see the inserted comment.
BIOS002.Resolution: Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.

FCD8503.Description: Chassis already has the feature identified in the message activated. Only one instance of a feature can be activated at a time. If the feature must be activated on the new card, it must be deactivated before activating.
FCD8503.Message: The feature is activated in the chassis: %1

PWR8547.Description: The chassis was already turned off, when the power off request was received.

CPU0817.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is operating normally.

SUP017.Description: The specified start time is invalid.
SUP017.Resolution: Start Time should be in the form YYYYMMDDHHMMSS. Or it should be TIME_NOW to specify an immediate update or reboot. Verify the specified start time and retry the action.

SRV086.Description: The operation cannot be started because the SupportAssist feature is disabled on iDRAC.
SRV086.Resolution: Enable the SupportAssist feature on the iDRAC by navigating to the SupportAssist page on the iDRAC GUI and retry the operation.
SRV086.Message: Unable to start the operation because the SupportAssist feature is disabled on iDRAC.

PSU0046.Message: Communication has been restored to power supply %1.

IOV104.Description: For each adapter assigned to a server, power is allocated when the server is turned on. If the available power is less than the required power, the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) will not power on the adapters associated with the server.
IOV104.Resolution: Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM command line interface, run the command "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerCap <Power cap>" to increase the power cap or add an additional power supply.
IOV104.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to allocate %1 Watt for server-%2 PCIe adapters.

RAC042.Description: The number of input parameters provided is not valid to perform the operation.
RAC042.Resolution: Verify that all required parameters are provided. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

LIC001.Description: The command or command parameters passed to License Manager is invalid. This is an internal error indicative of memory corruption. Under normal circumstances this error should not occur.
LIC001.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC001.Message: The License Manager command parameter used is invalid.

BAR045.Description: The host system is powering down to facilitate the import of the Integrated Remote Access Controller system profile.
BAR045.Message: Powering down the Host System for Integrated Remote Access Controller Restore.

IOID001.Description: After the I/O Identity optimization feature is enabled, the time during boot to configure I/O Identity attributes using the Server Configuration Profile (Configuration XML) import feature will be significantly reduced.
IOID001.Message: The Input/Output Identity (I/O Identity) optimization feature is enabled.

RAC094.Description: The license cannot be replaced by running the ReplaceLicense method because it is not supported on the 14th generation and later servers.
RAC094.Resolution: Run the DeleteLicense method, and then run the ImportLicense or ImportLicensefromNetworkShare method to import the license. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC094.Message: Unable to replace the license by running the ReplaceLicense method because it is not supported on the 14th generation and later servers.

BIOS043.Description: The maximum number of characters allowed for the parameter is displayed.
BIOS043.Resolution: Make sure that the parameter length is equal to or less than the maximum allowed, and then retry the operation.
BIOS043.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the length of input parameter %1 is more than the maximum allowed length %2.

CMC8527.Description: CMC is unable to obtain the memory information from the server specified in the message. This occurs if there is no communication between CMC and iDRAC.
CMC8527.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC. 2) Reset CMC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8527.Message: Unable to retrieve the server-%1 memory information.

VFL0011.Description: The vFlash media is not disabled.
VFL0011.Resolution: Disable the vFlash media by running the command 'racadm set idrac.vFlashSD.Enable 0'.

RAC086.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the chunk size value entered is more than the maximum chunk size limit (512 KB).
RAC086.Resolution: Make sure that the chunk size value is less than the maximum limit and retry the operation.
RAC086.Message: Unable to transfer the file because the chunk size value entered is more than the maximum chunk size limit (512 KB).

SYS178.Description: Unable to retrieve TTY log data because no storage controllers are detected in the server.
SYS178.Resolution: Make sure that at least one storage controller is present in the server, and then retry the operation.
SYS178.Message: Unable to retrieve TTY log data because no storage controllers are detected in the server.

HWC0001.Description: The error is caused due to iDRAC failure.
HWC0001.Resolution: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord and turn on the system.
HWC0001.Message: Unable to complete the operation as there is no response from iDRAC.

SWC0298.Description: The specified object value cannot be configured if local configuration is disabled or smart card logon is enabled. If smart card logon is enabled, serial, SSH, telnet and IPMI over LAN is disabled by force and cannot be enabled.
SWC0298.Resolution: Enable Local Configuration (through GUI) or Disable Smart Card Logon to change the value.
SWC0298.Message: The specified object value cannot be configured if local configuration is disabled or smart card logon is enabled. If smart card logon is enabled, serial, SSH, telnet and IPMI over LAN is disabled by force and cannot be enabled.

UEFI0244.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) links failed to come up to full operating frequency.
UEFI0244.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0244.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) links are operating in slow speed mode.

ENC10.Description: You have changed the enclosure asset name. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RED066.Description: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates are staged to run after the next system restart.
RED066.Resolution: A system restart is required to apply the staged updates.
RED066.Message: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates are staged to run after the next system restart.

UEFI0162.Description: An incompatibility has been detected between an installed memory buffer and the downstream DDR channel design.
UEFI0162.Message: A 3 DIMM Per Channel (DPC) configuration has been detected on a 2 DPC memory buffer.

CPU0806.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0806.Resolution: Review product documentation for proper configuration and installation procedures.
CPU0806.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is incorrectly configure.

RAC080.Description: The Export File operation is successfully completed.
RAC080.Message: The Export File operation is successfully completed.

RAC1051.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the option identified in the message.
RAC1051.Resolution: Retry with a correct value for the option identified in the message. For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help systemconfig backup".
RAC1051.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings. The option %1 is either invalid or not provided.

SYS082.Description: The request to preview the Server Configuration Profile import operation completed. Some changes specified in the configuration profile will not be successfully applied in an import configuration profile operation.
SYS082.Resolution: Identify the configuration changes that cannot be completed successfully by 1) Export the Lifecycle Log review the configuration results in the entries for the preview job or 2) Retrieve the preview operation configuration results using the GetConfigResults() method. Retry those changes that did not complete in a separate import operation.
SYS082.Message: Completed the preview of Server Configuration Profile import operation. Some changes specified in the configuration profile will not be successfully applied in an import operation.

SWC8622.Description: The remote network share settings are accessible on the CMC web interface at Server Overview/Setup/Remote Network Share tab. These settings must be correct for the CMC to connect to the remote network share and perform the application of the profile as specified in the Quick Deploy tab on the Profiles page.
SWC8622.Resolution: Make sure that the remote network share settings in the CMC are correct and that the remote share NFS/CIFS server is functioning correctly. Use the "Test Network" button in the CMC Web interface to make sure that the CMC can access the remote share.
SWC8622.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Unable to access remote network share and apply assigned profile to the server in slot %1.

LC062.Description: Export or Import server profile operation is already running. The operation may take a few minutes to compete.
LC062.Resolution: To retry the operation, wait for a few minutes.
LC062.Message: Export or Import server profile operation is already running.

VDR57.Description: A disk media error was detected while the controller was completing a background task. A bad disk block was identified. The disk block has been remapped.
VDR57.Resolution: Consider replacing the disk. If you receive this alert frequently, ensure to replace the disk. It is recommended to routinely back up your data.
VDR57.Message: Background Initialization in %1 corrected medium error.

PWR8570.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is not able to communicate with the iDRAC on the server identified in the message. Therefore, the server could not be power cycled. This situation may occur when iDRAC is rebooting.
PWR8570.Resolution: Wait for few minutes, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following: 1) Reset the iDRAC, 2) Perform a Virtual Reseat of the server, 3) Remove and re-insert the server.
PWR8570.Message: Unable to communicate to the iDRAC, when trying to power cycle the server %1.

JCP016.Description: The UntilTime input parameter for the job or job queue creation must be at least 5 minutes after the value specified in the StartTime parameter.
JCP016.Resolution: Set the UntilTime at least 5 minutes after StartTime and retry the operation.
JCP016.Message: Invalid UntilTime value. A minimum of 5 minutes is required.

VDR3.Description: Data redundancy has been restored to a virtual disk that previously suffered a loss of redundancy.
VDR3.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC0153.Description: Power redundancy is typically used to protect equipment from unexpected power disruption that could cause data loss or hardware damage.
RAC0153.Resolution: It is recommended to use power redundancy.
RAC0153.Message: Non-redundant power mode: Check the system hardware manual for implications.

SYS229.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of some unknown reasons.
SYS229.Resolution: Make sure that correct file transfer parameters are set, and then retry the operation.
SYS229.Message: Unable to transfer file, %1, because of some unknown reasons.

SWU8526.Description: The firmware update operation of iDRAC identified in the message is initiated.
SWU8526.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is initiated.

VDR52.Description: The data on physical disk members of the virtual disk does not match. Redundancy may be lost.
VDR52.Resolution: Rerun the consistency check task. If you receive this message again, verify the health of the physical disks included in the virtual disk. See the storage hardware documentation for more information. Review messages for significant messages related to the physical disks. If a physical disk has a problem, replace it and restore from a backup copy. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
VDR52.Message: The consistency check found inconsistent parity data on %1.

RAC1210.Description: The operation cannot be completed because an invalid Hash Value is entered.
RAC1210.Resolution: Enter a valid Hash value and retry the operation. To view a list of valid types, enter the following RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI): "racadm help <subcommand>". Also, see the RACADM CLI Reference Guide available on the support site.
RAC1210.Message: Unable to complete the operation because an invalid Hash value is entered.

TST105.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.
TST105.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

VDR33.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk was cancelled. This may be due to user action. This operation may automatically restart.

DIS117.Description: The AutoConfig operation cannot be completed because an argument is not entered for the flag identified in the message, which is causing a syntax error.
DIS117.Resolution: Enter an appropriate argument for the flag and retry the operation. For example, -s 0 indicates argument 0 is entered to indicate a share type of NFS. For a list of recommended flags and arguments, see the Zero-Touch Bare Metal Server Provisioning using Dell iDRAC with Lifecycle Controller Auto Config white paper available at Dell TechCenter.
DIS117.Message: Unable to complete the AutoConfig operation because an argument is not entered for the flag %1, which is causing a syntax error.

BAT0011.Resolution: Verify the battery installation, check the system logs for thermal related issues.
BAT0011.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is operating normally.

CMC8507.Description: The Extended Storage feature synchronizes data from the primary CMC removable flash media SD Card is synchronized with the secondary CMC removable flash media SD Card.
CMC8507.Message: Extended Storage for primary CMC and secondary CMC synchronization is complete.

UEFI0282.Description: One or more graphics processing unit (GPU) adapters are not operating correctly because the power cables between graphics processing unit (GPU) adapters and motherboard are not correctly connected.
UEFI0282.Resolution: Make sure that the cable connections between GPU adapters and motherboard are correct and retry the operation.
UEFI0282.Message: One or more graphics processing unit (GPU) adapters are not operating correctly because the power cables between the GPU adapters and motherboard are not correctly connected.

VLT0200.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0200.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0200.Message: The system board %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

SWC8502.Description: A Profile is successfully generated with the number of settings identified in the message.
SWC8502.Message: A Profile is successfully generated with [ %1 ] settings.

RAC0681.Description: Shared component updates through the Server OS or Lifecycle controller cannot be applied because the CMC setting for Chassis Management at Server Mode is not set to 'Manage and Monitor'.
RAC0681.Resolution: To enable this feature do the following: 1) Launch CMC Web UI. 2) Navigate to Chassis Overview -> Setup -> General, and select 'Manage and Monitor' option for the Chassis Management at Server Mode. 3) Click Apply to save changes in CMC. 4) Retry the operation in iDRAC. For more information, refer to the CMC User Guide.
RAC0681.Message: Shared component updates through the Server OS or Lifecycle controller cannot be applied because the CMC setting for Chassis Management at Server Mode is not set to 'Manage and Monitor'.

CTL69.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL69.Message: Attempted to import virtual disk with outdated physical disk information on %1.

RAC969.Description: The import operation cannot continue if the value specified for the shutdown option (-b) is incorrect. The supported values are "Graceful" and "Forced".
RAC969.Resolution: Make sure to specify either "Graceful" or "Forced" for the shutdown (-b) option.
RAC969.Message: Incorrect value specified for the shutdown option.

RED034.Description: A firmware update operation is currently in progress.
RED034.Resolution: Check the firmware update job status. Wait for the current job to complete.

PCI1356.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1356.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1356.Message: A bus uncorrectable error was detected on a component at slot %1.

SYS402.Description: The method cannot be run because the requested HTTP method is not allowed.
SYS402.Resolution: Enter a valid HTTP method and retry the operation. For information about valid methods, see the Redfish Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS402.Message: Unable to run the method because the requested HTTP method is not allowed.

STOR0506.Description: The physical disk is unreadable or the RAID controller is not responding.
STOR0506.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, replace the physical disk or update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version, and retry the operation.

UEFI0234.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Memory Test phase.
UEFI0234.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0234.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SWC0109.Description: There is no RAC diagnostic information available.
SWC0109.Message: No process information is currently available.

PDR73.Description: The physical disk participating in the copyback operation failed.
PDR73.Resolution: Replace the disk and retry the operation.

VDR10.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC0901.Description: The syntax of the specified command is invalid. In this case, the usage of the -t option is invalid.
RAC0901.Resolution: See the help text/documentation for the valid syntax of the subcommand.
RAC0901.Message: Invalid syntax. The -t option value must set to 1.

PSU0908.Description: The power supply is installed correctly but an input source is not connected or is not functional.
PSU0908.Resolution: Verify the input source is attached to the power supply. Verify the input power is within the operating requirements for the power supply.

RAC0512.Description: Virtual disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, no virtual disks were created, or incorrect filters are applied.
RAC0512.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is ON. 2. Check if virtual disks are created. 3. Check if correct filters are applied. 4. Check if the Storage Enclosure is ON. 5. Verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0512.Message: There are no virtual disks to be displayed.

NIC503.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC503.Message: The DNS server IP address is not allowed to be configured if DNS server DHCP (cfgDNSServersFromDHCP) is enabled.

SYS263.Description: The file cannot be transferred because the operation is taking longer time than the set time limit. The other probable reasons are: 1) issue in the network 2) remote host server is not turned on 3) remote host server is turned on but not functioning 4) issue in protocol negotiation.
SYS263.Resolution: Check the file transfer parameters, health of the remote host, and then retry the operation.
SYS263.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the operation is taking longer time than the set time limit.

USR8507.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.
USR8507.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct. Retry the operation with valid credentials.
USR8507.Message: %1 login was not successful (username=%2, ip=%3, error=0x%4)

CMC8611.Description: The version number of Complex Programmable Logical Device (CPLD) on the sled identified in the message cannot be read because the CPLD version is very old, or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to identify the version.
CMC8611.Resolution: Update the CPLD version of sled and retry the operation. For more information about the recommended CPLD versions, see the Chassis Management Controller User's Guide available at the support site.
CMC8611.Message: Unable to read the Complex Programmable Logical Device (CPLD) version number of sled %1 because the CPLD version is very old, or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to identify the version.

DIS103.Description: The network share folder cannot be accessed by using the credentials specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS103.Resolution: Verify whether or not the following are correctly entered in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC, and then retry the operation: 1) Network share name. 2) The IP address of the network share folder. 3) The username and password (-u <username> & -p <password>).
DIS103.Message: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access a network share folder, because incorrect credentials are specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

SEL1208.Message: A platform event filter action was executed.

CPU0012.Resolution: Review System Event Log and Operating System Logs. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0012.Message: Correctable Machine Check Exception detected on CPU %1.

VDR34.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk failed.
VDR34.Resolution: Run a consistency check on the virtual disk. If that fails, check the health of the member drives of the virtual disk and then recreate.

PWR8503.Description: This Information is provided to enable checking whether the powercap is lower than the maximum supported powercap limit.
PWR8503.Message: The current value of System Input Power Cap (%1W AC) is less than the upper limit (%1W AC).

RED035.Description: The firmware for the component identified in the message was updated successfully by the firmware rollback operation. The component firmware was updated from the earlier version to the current version identified in the message.
RED035.Message: %1 Rollback successful. Earlier version:%2, Current version:%2.

SYS006.Description: The attribute being set is currently read-only and cannot be changed.
SYS006.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation for the specific attribute behavior.
SYS006.Message: Unable to set read only attribute: %1

FSD000.Description: The customer has authorized the specified debug capabilities on this iDRAC. (This should occur in response to a request from Dell tech support.) Each debug capability represents a certain action Dell engineers can perform to debug iDRAC.
FSD000.Message: Debug authorized by customer; debugcaps: %1, was authorized by: %2, at %3 for the period: %4 to %5.

RDU0032.Description: The system has multiple redundant voltage lines. One or more of these voltage lines is no longer available.
RDU0032.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

VDR17.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk failed.
VDR17.Resolution: Replace the failed physical disk. Identify the failed physical disk by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. Rebuild the physical disk. When finished, restart the virtual disk format operation.

UEFI0141.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This situation is caused by missing LC files.
UEFI0141.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0141.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

SWC8610.Description: All settings of the selected profile were sent to the server identified in the message and the operation is captured in the job identified in the message.
SWC8610.Message: Job ID: %1. CMC sent all settings of profile %2 to Server (Service Tag: %3) in Slot %4.

OSD25.Description: Detaching the USB device (that contains drivers for the operating system installation) from the host has failed. The device may be detached, or iDRAC may not be operating normally.
OSD25.Resolution: Reset iDRAC to detach this device automatically.
OSD25.Message: Unable to detach USB device containing operating system drivers.

RAC0613.Description: An internal error occurred because of an invalid file.
RAC0613.Resolution: Make sure to upload the required file in the correct format and retry the operation.

SWC8557.Description: The profile identified in the message cannot be deleted because it is currently in use.
SWC8557.Message: Unable to delete the profile %1 because the profile is in use.

UEFI0108.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Read Receiving Enable initialization.
UEFI0108.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0108.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

UEFI0302.Description: The NVDIMM-N module in slot identified in the message has issue because of the reasons described in the message. The NVDIMM-N module identified will be set to read-only mode.
