UEFI0302.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the NVDIMM-N module and restart the system. If the issue persists, replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0302.Message: %1 on NVDIMM-N located at %2. The identified NVDIMM-N module will be set to read only mode.

RAC0623.Description: A firmware update is not required for the components on the server, because current firmware versions are the latest available in the repository.
RAC0623.Message: The firmware versions on all the components of this server are up-to-date.

RAC0626.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because all or some of the schedule parameters entered are incorrect.
RAC0626.Resolution: Enter correct input schedule parameters and retry the operation.
RAC0626.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid schedule parameter is entered.

RAC1153.Description: The time stamp was not recorded for the previous techsupreport collect operation.
RAC1153.Resolution: Run the RACADM techsupreport collect command. After the techsupreport collect operation completes, run the RACADM getupdatetime command.
RAC1153.Message: The time stamp is not available to display.

CTL40.Description: An error involving multiple bits has been encountered during a read or write operation. The error correction algorithm recalculates parity data during read and write operations. If an error involves only a single bit, it may be possible for the error correction algorithm to correct the error and maintain parity data. An error involving multiple bits, however, generally indicates data loss. In some cases, if the multi-bit error occurs during a read operation, then the data on the disk may be ok. If the multi-bit error occurs during a write operation, then data loss has occurred.
CTL40.Resolution: Replace the Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM). The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM. You may need to restore data from backup.

RAC1122.Description: One or more of the group or component attributes specified in the operation do not exist on the targeted server.
RAC1122.Message: The specified group or object is not supported on the server.

PR1.Description: The specified device has been replaced.
PR1.Message: A replacement part was detected for device: %1

STOR313.Description: The storage controller does not support reconfiguration operations.
STOR313.Resolution: Make sure of the following and retry the operation: 1) The latest version of Lifecycle Controller firmware is installed, 2) The storage controller supports reconfiguration process. For information about the supported storage controller versions, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide available on the support site.
STOR313.Message: Unable to run the command to reconfigure the Virtual Disk because the storage controller does not support reconfiguration operations.

IOV116.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected a power fault in an PCIE AUX power cable after the adapter was powered on. A power fault may be caused by a loose cable connection to the adapter or between the cable and the AUX cable harness.
IOV116.Resolution: Make sure AUX power cable identified in the message is fully plugged into the adapter and the AUX cable harness.
IOV116.Message: PCIE AUX power cable %1.was disconnected while powered on.

FC009.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage due to use by another application or operation.
FC009.Resolution: Wait for Lifecycle Controller to complete the current operation. Make sure that the system is: 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
FC009.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

UEFI0128.Description: Both the primary and secondary SD cards are in write-protected mode.
UEFI0128.Resolution: No response action is required if this is intentional.
UEFI0128.Message: Both the primary and secondary SD cards are in write-protected mode.

LC097.Description: The Diagnostics report cannot be exported because the proxy port number entered is invalid.
LC097.Resolution: Enter a valid proxy port number and retry the operation. The valid range is 0-65535. For more information, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
LC097.Message: Unable to export the Diagnostics report because the proxy port number entered is invalid.

STOR010.Description: The operation cannot be completed either because the RAID level entered is not supported by the controller, or the current RAIDType of "MD Software RAID" does not allow the operation.
STOR010.Resolution: Enter a valid RAID level and retry the operation.
STOR010.Message: Unable to complete the operation either because the RAID level entered is not supported by the controller, or the current RAIDType of "MD Software RAID" does not allow the operation.

SWU8515.Description: The IOM firmware update operation was not successful. Unable to initiate the Update process.
SWU8515.Message: Unable to update the IOM firmware. Update Initiation was not successful. ErrorCode=0x%1.

PDR1002.Description: The controller received a SMART error from the drive. The drive is operational but needs replacement.
PDR1002.Resolution: The drive will need replacement at the next service window.
PDR1002.Message: A predictive failure detected on drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

UEFI0054.Description: Debranding process is completed. The system is being restarted.
UEFI0054.Message: Debranding process is completed. The system is being restarted.

SRV124.Description: The cached operating system (OS) and application data available in the iDRAC is included in the SupportAssist collection.
SRV124.Message: The cached operating system (OS) and application data available in the iDRAC is included in the SupportAssist collection.

CTL120.Description: The firmware version of the RAID controller identified in the message cannot be updated because of a timeout while erasing the previous RAID controller firmware version.
CTL120.Resolution: Do not reset, restart, or turn off the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). However, retry the operation by using a correct firmware image file. If the issue persists, contact the service provider.
CTL120.Message: Unable to update the RAID controller %1 firmware version because of a timeout while erasing the previous RAID controller firmware version.

SWC0295.Description: The object name specified is incorrect.
SWC0295.Resolution: Refer to the list of objects in the group and choose the correct one.

RAC093.Description: The Base64 payload cannot be decoded because either a newline character (\n) is not located at the end of the payload, payload is not divisible by 4, or the payload is invalid.
RAC093.Resolution: Make sure that a newline character (\n) is located at the end of the payload (if the payload is less than or equal to 64 bytes), the payload size (excluding the new lines) is divisible by 4, or the payload is base64-encoded.
RAC093.Message: Unable to decode the Base64 payload because either a newline character (\n) is not located at the end of the payload, payload is not divisible by 4, or the payload is invalid.

OSD70.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'Username' is missing.
OSD70.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "Username" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD70.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'Username' is missing.

RAC994.Description: The jobs cannot be deleted if they are in one of these states: "Scheduled" or "Running". However, all jobs in one of these states: "Completed" or "Failed" will be deleted.
RAC994.Resolution: To monitor the job status, use the "racadm jobqueue view -i <job ID>", and delete the jobs one at a time using the "racadm jobqueue delete -i <job ID>" command.
RAC994.Message: Unable to run the "jobqueue delete --all" command.

GMGR0003.Description: The iDRAC local group with a name identified in the message is successfully deleted. The deleted iDRAC will be shown as available in other groups' views for forming a group.
GMGR0003.Message: The iDRAC local group %1 is successfully deleted.

MEM7002.Resolution: Review product documentation for proper memory riser installation and configuration.
MEM7002.Message: A hardware mismatch detected for memory riser.

PST0254.Description: System BIOS detected a functional or configuration issue during system POST. Check the system video screen for more information. The system event log may contain additional details. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code FE).
PST0254.Resolution: Check system video and review event log for additional information.

PSU0001.Resolution: Remove and re-install the power supply. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SYS149.Description: Initiating iDRAC reset to defaults operation because of a System Erase operation. The iDRAC will restart after firmware default values are restored.
SYS149.Message: The process of resetting iDRAC to default settings is initiated.

TMP0106.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0106.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

PWR8523.Description: The chassis power cycle operation was completed.

SRV092.Description: The SupportAssist Collection identified in the message is successfully exported to the network share.
SRV092.Message: The SupportAssist Collection %1 is successfully exported to the %2 network share.

BOOT004.Description: An invalid number of source arguments was passed to the method.
BOOT004.Message: Invalid number of Boot Source arguments

RAC1112.Description: Unable to clear the pending state from the attributes for a RAID object. A job is currently running and iDRAC internal storage is in use.
RAC1112.Resolution: Retry the operation after any currently running jobs have completed. Jobs can be monitored by running the racadm command "racadm jobqueue view".
RAC1112.Message: Unable to delete the pending values for the specified device because the iDRAC internal storage is in use by a currently running job.

SWC4011.Description: A firmware or software incompatibility was automatically corrected between the network device in the Server identified in the message and the Chassis Management Controller (CMC).
SWC4011.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility is automatically corrected between the %1%2 in Server-%3 and the Chassis Management Controller (CMC).

BAR120.Description: The Backup operation is currently validating the ability to access the HTTPs destination.
BAR120.Message: The Backup operation is currently validating the ability to access the HTTPs destination.

HWC4019.Description: The fan speed cannot be controlled because a sled mismatch or hardware incompatibility is detected. This results in fans rotating at the maximum allowed speed (RPM).
HWC4019.Resolution: Remove the sled in which a hardware incompatibility is detected and replace with a compatible working sled. For more information about hardware compatibility, see the platform Owners Manual available on the support site.
HWC4019.Message: Unable to control the fan speed because a sled mismatch or hardware incompatibility is detected.

STOR040.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because an invalid AttributeName value is specified.
STOR040.Resolution: Specify a valid AttributeName value for the attribute identified in the message and retry the operation.

SWC0012.Description: The operation to retrieve the front panel security settings encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0012.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0012.Message: Unable to retrieve the front panel security settings.

HWC4000.Description: A hardware incompatibility was detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and Processor(s). An iDRAC or BMC firmware update is needed.
HWC4000.Resolution: Update the BMC/iDRAC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC4000.Message: A hardware incompatibility detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and CPU.

SWC0237.Description: The key text in the public key specified is corrupt.
SWC0237.Resolution: Request for a valid public key from the system and re-try the command.
SWC0237.Message: Key text appears to be corrupted.

UEFI0191.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the VCK Reference Clock phase.
UEFI0191.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0191.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RED076.Description: Unable to create the Automatic Update schedule because an input parameter is invalid.
RED076.Resolution: Verify the values for all the input parameters are correct and retry the operation.
RED076.Message: Unable to create an Automatic Update schedule, because an invalid parameter is entered.

AMP0308.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0308.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0308.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is greater than the upper warning threshold.

ENC19.Description: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has failed. The failure may be caused by a loss of power to the EMM. The EMM self-test may also have identified a failure. There may also be a firmware problem or a multi-bit error.
ENC19.Resolution: Reset the Enclosure Management Module (EMM). See the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the EMM. Replace the EMM. Contact technical support if the issue persists.

PDR57.Description: The bad block table is the table used for remapping bad disk blocks. This table fills as bad disk blocks are remapped. When the table is full, bad disk blocks are no longer remapped, which means that disk errors are no longer corrected. At this point, data loss can occur.
PDR57.Resolution: Replace the disk generating this message and restore from a backup copy. You may have lost data.
PDR57.Message: Bad block table on %1 is full. Unable to log block %2.

SWC0231.Description: The partition image type specified is not available on local racadm.
SWC0231.Message: Partition of type \"image\" not supported on local racadm.

SYS061.Description: Some configuration changes for the component identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) in the configuration job results were not successfully applied.
SYS061.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log and identify the configuration changes that did not complete or retrieve the configuration results using the GetConfigResults() method. Retry those changes that did not complete in a separate import operation.

NIC003.Description: An invalid number of arguments was passed to the method.
NIC003.Resolution: Enter all the required command parameters. Check documentation and try again.

BAR122.Description: The Backup operation cannot be completed because access to the HTTPs destination is denied.
BAR122.Resolution: Make sure that the input parameters are correct, network connection exists to the destination, and then retry the operation.
BAR122.Message: Unable to continue with Backup operation because access to the HTTPs destination is denied.

SYS038.Description: Unable to locate the configuration data associated with the job.
SYS038.Resolution: Retry the operation. If this issue persists, contact your service provider.

RED010.Resolution: Correct the target information and retry the operation.

BAR053.Description: Restoring device firmware on the device identified in the message.

IOV1002.Description: The operation did not complete successfully due to an exception from the instrumentation layer.
IOV1002.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset CMC and retry the operation when the CMC has completed restarting. The CMC may take 2 to 3 minutes to complete restarting.

PWR8506.Description: Resetting the power computation reading causes the log to report time at which it is reset.
PWR8506.Message: Cumulative power computation (KWH) time is reset on %1.

SWC5006.Description: System Controller (SC) reported a successful Firmware Update.

UEFI0111.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during memory test.
UEFI0111.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0111.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

BIOS006.Description: A configuration job is already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job succeeds or the job is cancelled.
BIOS006.Resolution: Wait for the job to complete. To continue with more set operations on the specified target, cancel the job and proceed.
BIOS006.Message: Configuration job already created, cannot set attribute on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled.

PSU0003.Description: The power supply is installed correctly but an input source is not connected or is not functional.
PSU0003.Resolution: Verify the input source is attached to the power supply. Verify the input power is within the operating requirements for the power supply.
PSU0003.Message: The power input for power supply %1 is lost.

SWC0282.Description: The value being modified is READ only.
SWC0282.Message: The specified object is READ ONLY for this index and cannot be modified.

UEFI0066.Description: A PCIe Link failure is observed in the device identified in the message and device link is disabled. The system will be halted.
UEFI0066.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Turn off the input power to the system and turn on again. 2) Update the PCIe device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0066.Message: A PCIe link training failure is observed in %1 and the link is disabled. The system has halted.

VLT0221.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0221.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0221.Message: The %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SUP0535.Description: Component firmware update is in progress.
SUP0535.Resolution: No response action is required. Do not turn off the system while the update is in progress.

RAC0270.Description: This is a warning message that continuing this operation does not allow subsequent GUI interactions to this NIC.
RAC0270.Resolution: Enable IPv4 or IPv6 before continuing the operation.

SWU8533.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation is not successful, because the target is not ready.
SWU8533.Resolution: Wait for the target to become ready. This may take a few minutes. After the target is ready, then retry the operation.
SWU8533.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because the target is not ready. ErrorCode=0x%1.

SRV111.Description: The iDRAC is already registered with SupportAssist.
SRV111.Message: The iDRAC is already registered with SupportAssist.

SEC0601.Message: A secure mode violation was corrected.

SWC0111.Description: The serveraction subcommand requires an option to be specified.
SWC0111.Resolution: Refer the help for serveraction subcommand, and enter a valid option.
SWC0111.Message: A server action command must be specified.

HWC8511.Description: The Coin Cell battery in the front panel is not working.
HWC8511.Resolution: Replace the Coin Cell battery. For more information about replacing, see the Chassis Management Controller User's Guide available on the support site.
HWC8511.Message: The Coin Cell battery in the front panel is not working.

LC024.Description: Unable to retrieve Lifecycle Controller Log records because of an issue internal to the firmware.
LC024.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Try the operation again 2) AC power cycle the system 3) apply the latest firmware update packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
LC024.Message: Unable to retrieve Lifecycle Controller Log records.

SYS250.Description: The file cannot be transferred because of an internal issue. This is not related to any issue in network, proxy status, or remote host status.
SYS250.Resolution: Check the system health and retry the operation.
SYS250.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because of an internal error.

RED062.Description: Unable to successfully authenticate. The username or password entered is incorrect, or HTTP server does not support BASIC or Digest authentication types.
RED062.Resolution: Verify username, password and server authentication type. To manually update, retry the operation.
RED062.Message: Unable to successfully authenticate user credentials to the specified repository.

SWC0158.Message: User CA certificate successfully uploaded to the RAC.

RAC0687.Description: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.
RAC0687.Resolution: Choose to create a job for the successful operations. View successful pending operations using the Pending Operations button or click Cancel to quit job creation.
RAC0687.Message: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.

OSD65.Description: The ISO file is successfully attached. The next host reboot is scheduled to boot to the ISO file.
OSD65.Message: The ISO file is successfully attached. The next host reboot is scheduled to boot to the ISO file.

TMP8501.Description: System was unable to read planar board or control panel temperature sensors. The fan speed was increased to protect system hardware.
TMP8501.Resolution: Remove AC power from the system and reapply AC power. Check to see if the issue is resolved. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
TMP8501.Message: Unable to read planar board temperature sensors. The cooling has been increased to safeguard the system.

RAC074.Description: The iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation cannot be completed because a vflash partition creation operation is in progress.
RAC074.Resolution: Wait for the vFlash partition creation process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC074.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation because a vFlash partition creation operation is in progress.

STOR0103.Description: No physical disk data to display. The system is powered off, physical disks are not present on the system, or physical disks are not connected to the enclosure or backplane.
STOR0103.Resolution: Check if the server has power, physical disks are available, and physical disks are connected to the enclosure or backplane.

PCI3014.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next scheduled service time.
PCI3014.Message: A non-fatal PCIe error detected on a component at slot %1.

PWR8515.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is not turned on.
PWR8515.Resolution: Turn the chassis on and retry the operation.
PWR8515.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is not turned on.

IOV102.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected the removal of an adapter card from the slot identified in the message.
IOV102.Message: A PCIe adapter %1 is removed from %2 %3.

PR31.Description: All the tasks in the Job were attempted, but some did not complete successfully.
PR31.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log for more details associated with this warning then retry the operation if appropriate.

VDR31.Description: The controller is getting disconnected from its virtual disk, while Input Output (IO) is in-progress.
VDR31.Resolution: Try importing foreign disks, if any. Check if the enclosure containing the Virtual Disk is disconnected from the controller. Insert any disks that are reported missing or failed. If the enclosure or disks were removed intentionally, the preserved cache can be discarded. See storage hardware documentation for more information on performing these steps.
VDR31.Message: Controller cache is preserved for missing or offline %1.

SWC0085.Description: Integrated Data Center Mode is disabled because of one of the following reasons: 1) The feature was disabled 2) The server is not supported for the Integrated Data Center solution 3) The default user credentials on the iDRAC were changed 4) Suppression of the default credentials warning was selected.
SWC0085.Message: The Integrated Data Center mode is disabled.

AMP0306.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0306.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is less than the lower warning threshold.

RAC988.Description: A new firmware update job cannot be initiated while an existing firmware update job is still in one of these states: "New", "Downloading", or "Running".
RAC988.Resolution: Wait until the existing firmware update jobs are completed or scheduled before retrying the operation. To monitor the status of the existing jobs, use the "racadm jobqueue view" command.
RAC988.Message: Unable to initiate the %1 firmware update.

LC096.Description: The SSL Certificate is successfully imported.
LC096.Message: The SSL Certificate is successfully imported.

RAC1032.Description: The job specified in the message were cancelled.
RAC1032.Message: %1 jobs was cancelled by the user.

SEL1300.Description: System setup displays the system boot order. The local video screen may also show additional information. (IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 00h).
SEL1300.Resolution: Check system boot settings. Check mass storage controller configuration settings is applicable.

UEFI0093.Description: The DIMM installed on the memory slot identified in the message does not meet the minimum supported frequency.
UEFI0093.Resolution: Remove all unsupported DIMM modules from the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0093.Message: The DIMM installed on the memory slot: %1 does not meet the minimum supported frequency.

UEFI0088.Description: Unsupported 8Gb technology DIMM module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0088.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0088.Message: Unsupported 8Gb technology DIMM module is installed on memory slot: %1.

PWR216.Description: Unable to enable Extended Power Performance, because redundancy policy is set to Grid Redundancy or No Redundancy.
PWR216.Resolution: Configure Redundancy Policy to Power Supply Redundancy and retry the operation. Using the CMC Web GUI, click Power > Configuration. From the Redundancy Policy drop-down menu, select Power Supply Redundancy.
PWR216.Message: Unable to enable Extended Power Performance, because Redundancy Policy is set to Grid Redundancy or No Redundancy.

BAR074.Description: The collection and export of firmware inventory data did not complete successfully.
BAR074.Resolution: Apply the Dell Update Package for Unified Server Configurator (USC). If collect system inventory on reboot (CSIOR) is not enabled, enter and exit System Services in USC to update the database, reboot the system and try the operation again. If the error continues, use the field service repair software to repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download all Dell Update Packages for USC, Diagnostics Driver Packs, and device firmware for all host system devices, install all packages and retry the operation.
BAR074.Message: Unable to collect Firmware Inventory information.

OSD40.Description: This is not a Dell-licensed vFlash.
OSD40.Resolution: Insert a Dell vFlash and then retry this command.

UEFI0031.Description: The PCIe device identified in the message was not trained at the expected link width.
UEFI0031.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the firmware on the PCIe device. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0031.Message: PCIe downtrain is detected on %1. Expected link width: %2 Actual link width: %2.

PSU0914.Description: Status from the power supply indicates a power supply exception occurred. The power supply will try to operate. System Performance and power redundancy may be degraded or lost.
PSU0914.Resolution: Remove input power and re-install supply at the next service window.
PSU0914.Message: A predictive failure detected on power unit %1.

BAR007.Description: System profile export operation is successfully completed.

RDU8520.Description: The standby CMC is recovered from unhealthy state by the monitoring daemon.

SWC0305.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0305.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0305.Message: The -p option requires -u to also be specified.

RED020.Description: The feature invoked is not supported by the current version of the Unified Server Configurator.
RED020.Resolution: Upgrade Unified Server Configurator to the latest available version before using this feature.
RED020.Message: Feature not supported on current version of USC.

RDU8500.Description: The CMC is identified in the message is active.

OSD3.Description: Lifecycle Controller is currently locked by another process. Make sure that the process completes before attempting to run another command.
OSD3.Resolution: 1) After two minutes, rerun the command. 2) Make sure that USC or DUP is not currently running on the server. 3) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD3.Message: Lifecycle Controller is being used by another process.

RAC0722.Description: Failed to program the Chassis assigned MAC address for the NIC.Integrated in the specified slot number.
RAC0722.Message: Failed to program the Chassis assigned MAC address for the NIC.Integrated.%1.

ENC5.Description: One or more of the enclosure components has failed. For example, a fan or power supply may have failed. Although the enclosure is currently operational, the failure of additional components could cause the enclosure to fail.
ENC5.Resolution: Identify and replace the failed component. To identify the failed component, select the enclosure in the tree view and click the Health subtab. Any failed component will be identified with a red X on the enclosure's Health subtab. Alternatively, you can select the Storage object and click the Health subtab. The controller status displayed on the Health subtab indicates whether a controller has a failed or degraded component. See the enclosure documentation for information on replacing enclosure components and for other diagnostic information.

SWC0219.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0219.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0219.Message: The -p option requires -c to also be specified.

RDU8502.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.
RDU8502.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8502.Message: CMC%1 cannot go standby since the other CMC is not present or healthy.

RAC1162.Description: The requested techsupreport collect operation cannot be initiated because another techsupreport collect operation for the Tech Support Report (TSR) is in progress.
RAC1162.Resolution: Wait for the current collect operation to complete before initiating another collect operation. To view the status of the techsupreport collect operation, run the command 'racadm jobqueue view'.
RAC1162.Message: Unable to initiate the techsupreport collect operation for the Tech Support Report (TSR) because another collect operation is in progress.

VLT0208.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0208.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0208.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

RAC1224.Description: The Client trust certificate cannot be deleted because the certificate does not exist.
RAC1224.Message: Unable to delete the Client trust certificate because the certificate does not exist.

RAC1036.Description: Successfully cleared pending values for attributes in the group specified.
RAC1036.Resolution: To verify, run the RACADM command "racadm get group".
RAC1036.Message: Successfully cleared pending attribute(s) for the group specified.

USR8515.Description: A bezel that has the iDRAC LCD panel feature is disconnected, and therefore the feature is not available.
USR8515.Resolution: Connect a bezel that has the iDRAC LCD panel feature.
USR8515.Message: A bezel that has the iDRAC LCD panel feature is disconnected.

SWC5001.Resolution: Reboot the system and attempt the upgrade again.

VRM0009.Description: No virtual media was found to disconnect.
VRM0009.Message: No Virtual Media devices are currently connected.

SYS075.Description: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file does not exist on the remote share.
SYS075.Resolution: Make sure the import configuration file exists on the remote share before retrying the operation.
SYS075.Message: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file does not exist on the remote share.

SWC0717.Description: For security reasons, the local configuration is disabled. Enable local configuration from the iDRAC Web interface.
SWC0717.Resolution: Enable iDRAC local configuration from iDRAC Web interface.
SWC0717.Message: iDRAC Local Configuration is disabled. iDRAC Settings are accessed in read-only mode.

MEM9050.Description: The NVDIMM device in the slot identified in the message has regained persistency and is available for use.
MEM9050.Message: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device in the slot %1 has regained persistency and is available for use.

SRV073.Description: The SupportAssist operation to update registration information did not complete successfully.
SRV073.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Make sure the registration information is valid. 2) Make sure that the communication between iDRAC and iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is working. If the issue persists, restart the iSM service on the host OS.
SRV073.Message: The SupportAssist operation to update registration information did not complete successfully.

SRV121.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the Operating System-Baseboard Management Controller Pass Through (OS-BMC PT) required for communication with iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not enabled.
SRV121.Resolution: Enable the Operating System-Baseboard Management Controller Pass Through (OS-BMC PT) and then retry the operation. To enable the OS-BMC PT using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm set idrac.os-bmc.AdminState Enabled".
SRV121.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the Operating System-Baseboard Management Controller Pass Through (OS-BMC PT) required for communication with iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not enabled.

SWC8528.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to update the IDRAC "root" user password. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or if the password entered is not valid.
SWC8528.Resolution: Make sure the password is valid. If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8528.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to update the iDRAC root password.

PDR65.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

UEFI0313.Description: The Baseboard UPI D cable is not connected.
UEFI0313.Resolution: Connect the Baseboard UPI D cable. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0313.Message: The Baseboard UPI D cable is not connected.

RAC990.Description: If Lifecycle Controller is disabled, the firmware update operation cannot continue.
RAC990.Resolution: Enable Lifecycle Controller using the "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.lcattributes.lifecyclecontrollerstate 1" command, and retry the operation.

AMP0313.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0313.Message: System level current is less than the lower critical threshold.

TMPS0103.Description: Inlet temperature has been above the critical threshold for duration of 1% or more for the operational time during the last one year.
TMPS0103.Resolution: This condition will occur if the ambient temperature is high. Make sure the ambient temperature of the environment is in normal range.
TMPS0103.Message: Inlet temperature is above critical level for extended duration.

SYS130.Description: Unable to create the final zip archive name because the Service Tag and time stamp could not be retrieved from OS interfaces.
SYS130.Resolution: Do the following: 1) On Windows, restart the WMI service and retry the operation, 2) Restart the OS and retry the operation.
SYS130.Message: OS Collector: Unable to create filename for zip archive.

PDR1007.Message: Rebuild is in progress for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

GMGR0033.Description: The new group job identified in the message is successfully created.
GMGR0033.Message: A new group job %1 is successfully created for %2. The job progress can be viewed in the Group Manager job view.

BAR114.Description: The Automatic Backup job identified in the message is created per the Server Profile automatic export schedule previously configured.
BAR114.Message: An Automatic Backup job %1 is created.

STOR051.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the specified StartingLBA and Size value combination is greater than allowed by the physical disk size.
STOR051.Resolution: Specify the Size value only and allow the instrumentation to calculate the StartingLBA value then retry the operation.
STOR051.Message: StartingLBA and Size value combination is greater than allowed by the physical disk size.

SRV101.Description: The SupportAssist Collection data is requested for iDRAC event identified in the message.
SRV101.Message: The SupportAssist Collection data is requested for iDRAC event %1.

RAC1141.Description: The iDRAC firmware rollback operation was initiated.
RAC1141.Message: The iDRAC firmware rollback operation was initiated.

UEFI0139.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This situation is caused by LC partition attach issues.
UEFI0139.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0139.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

ISM0028.Description: The iDRAC Hard Reset operation cannot be performed either because of an unsupported CPLD firmware version or the iDRAC Hard reset feature is currently disabled on iDRAC.
ISM0028.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the CPLD version by using iDRAC graphical user interface (GUI). 2) To enable the iDRAC Hard Reset feature by running RACADM command, enter the following at the command line interface (CLI): "racadm set idrac.servicemodule.idrachardreset enabled".
ISM0028.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC Hard Reset operation either because of an unsupported CPLD firmware version or the iDRAC Hard Reset feature is currently disabled on iDRAC.

SWC8617.Description: The request by the WS-Man method identified in the message for the server in slot identified slot is unsuccessful.
SWC8617.Resolution: Make sure that iDRAC is ready and system is functioning properly. Run the RACADM command "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until iDRAC is ready for use. A Virtual Reseat may be required.
SWC8617.Message: Server Profiles: request %1 for server in slot %2 was unsuccessful. Returned fault: %3.

RED028.Description: Update files were not selected, therefore the installation did not proceed.
RED028.Resolution: Select one or more update files to install.

HWC4017.Description: The system has detected an unsupported hardware component. A hardware incompatibility is detected between the components identified in the message.
HWC4017.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Review system documentation for the hardware components identified in the message. 2) Replace unsupported components with supported components.
HWC4017.Message: A hardware incompatibility is detected between %1%2 and %3%4.

OSD065.Description: The Operating System/Hypervisor installation did not complete successfully. The system may be unable to boot into the operating system/hypervisor because of the incomplete installation.
OSD065.Resolution: Check the installation logs of operating system or hypervisor, resolve any issues identified, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
OSD065.Message: Operating System/Hypervisor Installation did not complete successfully.

UEFI0283.Description: The command cannot be written to Mailbox Interface CSR register during Memory Reference Code (MRC) initialization because the Power Control Unit (PCU) Mailbox is not responding.
UEFI0283.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Disconnect the input power supply to the server. 2) Reseat all processors. 3) Restart the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0283.Message: Unable to write the command to Mailbox Interface CSR register during Memory Reference Code (MRC) initialization because the Power Control Unit (PCU) Mailbox is not responding.

SWC0276.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0276.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0276.Message: Invalid syntax. The -p option is only valid with -f.

CMC8545.Description: A firmware error has occurred causing a CMC failover. The process identified in the message was not detected. The CMC will restart automatically.
CMC8545.Resolution: No response action is required. If multiple failovers occur, contact your service provider.
CMC8545.Message: Detected a missing process failover condition detected. Process = %1.

RAC0236.Description: vFlash image upload failed because the image is not valid.
RAC0236.Resolution: Image may be corrupt. Try uploading a valid vFlash image.

UEFI0169.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because low memory (i.e. memory below the 4GB boundary) cannot be split evenly across processor sockets during memory initialization.
UEFI0169.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0169.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

PWR8656.Description: CMC could not successfully turn on the component identified in the message, because of insufficient power available.
PWR8656.Resolution: Make sure there is sufficient power available, and then retry the operation. To increase available power, add more PSUs, use PSUs with higher voltage inputs or a higher power rating, remove unused components from the Chassis, or change the redundancy policy to Redundancy Alerting Only or Non-redundant.
PWR8656.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the component %1-%2 because of insufficient power.

USR8506.Description: The operation to invalidate the Session identified in the message was successful.

STOR13.Description: The operation mode of the newly inserted storage sled in the slot identified in the message cannot be set because the storage sled has only one PERC controller. The operation mode will only be Join after part replacement.
STOR13.Resolution: Make sure that the newly inserted storage sled has the same number of PERC controllers as the previous storage sled so that the new sled will have the same operation mode after part replacement.
STOR13.Message: Unable to set the operation mode of the newly inserted storage sled in slot %1 to Split Single or Split Dual Host, because the storage sled has only one PERC controller.

IOID111.Description: The virtual address of the NIC port identified in the message could not be successfully configured because either the network port connection is not enabled or the NIC is not capable of Virtual Addressing.
IOID111.Resolution: Verify that the network port is enabled and that the port has Virtual Addressing capability and then retry the operation.
IOID111.Message: Unable to configure the virtual address of %1 Port %2.

PSU1005.Description: The enclosure detected that a power supply unit was switched on.

RAC0269.Resolution: Enter a valid NIC MTU. Expected range: 576-1500 or 0x240-0x5DC.
RAC0269.Message: The NIC MTU is invalid. Expected range: 576-1500 or 0x240-0x5DC.

PDR64.Description: The rebuild or recovery operation encountered an unrecoverable disk media error.
PDR64.Message: An unrecoverable disk media error occurred on %1.

USR8505.Description: The operation to invalidate the Session identified in the message was successful.

BAT0007.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may have failed because of thermal exceptions.
BAT0007.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation. 2) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.

USR8513.Description: Successful login from IP address identified in the message by username identified in the message.

SRV003.Description: Unable to start another SupportAssist job because an existing SupportAssist job is already running on the server.
SRV003.Resolution: Wait for the current SupportAssist operation to complete and retry the operation.
SRV003.Message: A SupportAssist job is already running on the server.

IOV107.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has detected the removal of a PCIe adapter card while it was powered on.
IOV107.Resolution: Power down the affected server(s) and then power on the server(s). Note: OS reboot only will not correct this issue.
IOV107.Message: PCIe adapter %1 in slot %2 was removed while powered on.

OSD76.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is invalid.
OSD76.Resolution: Check the value provided for input parameter "ResetType" and retry the operation.
OSD76.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is invalid.

PWR8595.Description: The turn-on request for the server identified in the message did not succeed because of insufficient power to the chassis component identified in the message.
PWR8595.Resolution: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) will retry turning on the server and the corresponding components associated to the server after a predefined interval. If the issue persists, refer to the Managing and Monitoring Power section in the CMC User Guide for more information on configuring power management settings.
PWR8595.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server %1 due to insufficient power for the %2.

BAR029.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware and configuration import is in progress.
BAR029.Message: Restoring Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

ENC4.Description: The firmware on the EMM modules is not the same version. It is required that both modules have the same version of the firmware. This alert may be caused when you attempt to insert an EMM module that has a different firmware version than an existing module.
ENC4.Resolution: Download the same version of the firmware to both EMM modules.

PDR104.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message has turned off because the critical temperature threshold of the device was exceeded.
PDR104.Message: The %1 has turned off because the critical temperature threshold is exceeded.

SUP0539.Description: Update Packages are missing from the specified repository.
SUP0539.Resolution: Enter another repository location that contains the desired Update Packages and retry the operation.
SUP0539.Message: Update Packages missing in the repository.

PWR8684.Description: The storage sled controller in the slot identified in the message turned on successfully.
PWR8684.Message: Storage sled controller %1 in slot %2 turned on successfully.

MEM9010.Description: BIOS logged the major and minor code of a QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) Reference Code warning. This information can be reviewed by using a tool which displays raw IPMI SEL log data such as IPMItool with the -vvv option or RACADM with the -E option.
MEM9010.Message: A QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) Reference Code warning message code is logged.

PWR2210.Message: The system was forced into a soft-off state.

FAN0028.Description: The fan identified in the message is inserted.

RDU8510.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.
RDU8510.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8510.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover, CMC firmware versions are different

TMP0126.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0126.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0126.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

PWR8578.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on the iDRAC because power required is less than available power.
PWR8578.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Go to, the Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field, view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis. Remove and reinsert the server when enough power is available.
PWR8578.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on the iDRAC on server-%1 because power required is less than available power.

SUP024.Description: The InstanceID value provided for update operation is invalid.
SUP024.Resolution: Enumerate inventory, copy the InstanceID value and provide that value for the update operation.
SUP024.Message: InstanceID value provided for the update operation is invalid

BIOS034.Description: The record operation cannot be retrieved because the requested record is not available.
BIOS034.Resolution: Make sure that the record data entered is correct and retry the operation.
BIOS034.Message: Unable to retrieve the record information because the requested record is not available.

SWC0141.Message: Certificate successfully downloaded from the RAC

PSU1006.Description: The enclosure detected that a power supply unit was inserted.

FAN0009.Description: The fan may be required for optimal performance.

SYS285.Description: The Repository Update file cannot be read because the Repository Update file path has more than 1024 characters.
SYS285.Resolution: Make sure that the Repository Update file path has less than 1024 characters and retry the operation.
SYS285.Message: Unable to read Repository Update file because the Repository Update file path has more than 1024 characters.

PWR2250.Description: The server did not turn on because the chassis infrastructure is not ready. The chassis infrastructure includes: PCIe subsystem, storage components, and the chassis management controller.
PWR2250.Resolution: Check the status of the chassis infrastructure in the CMC Web or RACADM interface. Wait until the chassis infrastructure components are fully turned on.
PWR2250.Message: Unable to turn on the server because the chassis infrastructure not ready.

NIC021.Description: The old BIOS password used to change the password is incorrect.
NIC021.Resolution: Enter the correct old password for the BIOS and retry the operation.

PCI5007.Description: The 3.3 Volt Regulator power related issue of PCIe carrier present in the slot identified in the message is resolved.
PCI5007.Message: The auxiliary power-related issue of the PCIe adapter in slot %1 is resolved.

SUP0537.Description: Unable to continue the firmware update due to an internal error.
SUP0537.Resolution: Reboot the system and retry. If the problem persists, contact your service provider for the latest Update Package.
SUP0537.Message: Unable to continue the firmware update.

RAC031.Description: The operation cannot be completed because an incorrect username is entered.
RAC031.Resolution: Enter a valid username and retry the operation.
RAC031.Message: Unable to complete the operation because an incorrect username is entered.

UEFI0037.Description: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI). Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as active power management, thermal management.
UEFI0037.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0037.Message: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).

HWC1200.Description: The sled identified in the message is inserted in the slot identified in the message.
HWC1200.Message: The sled %1 is inserted in slot %2.

IOV1005.Description: The FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) entered for the operation does not map to any instance of the DCIM_ChassisPCISlot class.
IOV1005.Resolution: Perform the Enumerate operation on the DCIM_ChassisPCISlot class to determine the correct FQDD value for the required slot. Retry the operation with the correct FQDD value.

SUP0130.Message: TFTP firmware update has been initiated. This update process may take several minutes to complete.

SEC0003.Description: The processor area is open. A drive may be added or removed. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0003.Resolution: Close the processor area. Check system logs.

STOR030.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the specified controller is not found.
STOR030.Resolution: Provide a valid controller FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) and retry the operation.

PSU0800.Description: Lists the complete status of the power supply unit.
PSU0800.Message: Power Supply %1: Status = 0x%2, IOUT = 0x%3, VOUT= 0x%4, TEMP= 0x%5, FAN = 0x%6, INPUT= 0x%7.

LC065.Description: The static IPv4 information for the iDRAC represented by the related iDRACCard Attributes must be configured correctly.
LC065.Resolution: Configure the iDRAC static IP address information by setting the related iDRACCard Attributes. The related attributes that must be configured are the following:: 1) In the IPv4 group: Address, NetMask, Gateway, DNS1 2) In the NIC Static group: DNSDomainName.
LC065.Message: The iDRAC static IP address information is not fully configured. The missing attribute InstanceID is %1.

LNK0005.Description: Error occurred while communicating with the DHCP server because the network settings are not configured correctly or the DHCP server could not be contacted.
LNK0005.Resolution: Verify if the network cable is connected and network configuration settings are correct, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the network interface controller (NIC) firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
LNK0005.Message: Unable to connect to DHCP server.

STOR067.Description: The operation did not succeed since the selected controller does not support creating uneven span RAID10 virtual disks.
STOR067.Resolution: The selected controller is not capable of creating an uneven span RAID10 virtual disk. Specify the proper span length and span depth combination for creating RAID10 virtual disk on the selected controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR067.Message: Controller does not support uneven span RAID10 virtual disks.

PR8.Description: The indicated device has been removed from the system, is no longer functioning, or has been disabled.
PR8.Resolution: If the part is present, make sure it is properly installed. Ensure that the device has not been disabled in the system BIOS or other configuration utility. Contact technical support if the device is still non functional.

SWC0313.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0313.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0313.Message: Invalid syntax. The -h option is not valid with any other options.

CMC8604.Description: The FRU on the storage sled specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8604.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reinsert the specified storage sled or virtual reseat the sled 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes for the CMC to finish restarting. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8604.Message: The FRU on storage sled %1 is not functioning.

HWC1103.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message is removed from the unsupported slot identified in the message.
HWC1103.Message: The %1 installed in an unsupported slot %2 is removed.

RAC0259.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv6 address does not conform to the required format.

SUP0107.Description: The file path provided as a parameter is too long.
SUP0107.Resolution: Shorten the length of the string given as file path by either moving the file or renaming the folders along the path.

PDR77.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR77.Message: %1 state changed from READY to Non-RAID.

UEFI0140.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This situation is caused by missing LC partitions.
UEFI0140.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0140.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

RAC1216.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the certificate data entered does not exist.
RAC1216.Resolution: Make sure that valid certificate data exists and retry the operation. For more information, see the RACADM CLI Reference Guide available on the support site.
RAC1216.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the certificate data entered does not exist.

PWR8582.Description: Unable to turn on the server identified in the message because the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) is enabled. After MPCM is enabled, the chassis will be in power conservation mode and the CMC cannot process any further server power on operation requests.
PWR8582.Resolution: Disable the Max Power Conservation Mode and retry the operation.
PWR8582.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because Max Power Conservation Mode is enabled.

LNK0001.Description: The entered network share name is not valid.
LNK0001.Resolution: Enter a valid network share name and retry the operation. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.

RFM1031.Message: Removable Flash Media has finished booting.

PR7.Description: The specified device was added to the system.

RED023.Description: The Lifecycle Controller is unable to access internal storage currently in use by another operation.
RED023.Resolution: Make sure all other Lifecycle Controller operations are finished and retry the operation. Using the iDRAC Web UI, select Server (on 12th and 13th Generation servers) or Maintenance (on 14th Generation Servers) and then Job Queue, check the job queue for unfinished jobs and wait for the jobs to finish before retrying the operation. Also, check whether there are update packages being executed in the server OS and wait for these operations to finish before retrying the operation. For remote web services API access, make sure that the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status, and then retry the operation. If OS Deploy has been enabled then boot the server into LC UI to clear. Always exit LC UI using "Exit" and not by removing power.
RED023.Message: Lifecycle Controller in use. This job will start when Lifecycle Controller is available.

SRV026.Description: The checksum cannot be computed because OS Collector files are not readable.
SRV026.Resolution: Reinstall the OS Collector in the iDRAC and retry the operation. To install the OS Collector using the iDRAC Web UI, get the latest OC Collector update package and then select the Update and Rollback link from the iDRAC Web UI home page and upload the install package. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SRV026.Message: Unable to compute the checksum because OS Collector files are not readable.

JCP029.Description: Only one Job of the JobType requested can be created or scheduled at any time. A job of the same type already exists in the job queue.
JCP029.Resolution: Wait until the existing job is complete or delete the existing job and then retry the operation.
JCP029.Message: A Job of JobType %1 already exists.

SEC0034.Message: The chassis is closed while the power is off.

PWR1002.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1002.Resolution: Review system configuration and system logs for thermal or environmental failures and warnings.
PWR1002.Message: The system performance degraded because of thermal protection.

GMGR0031.Description: The Secondary Controller iDRAC is unavailable. Group redundancy is degraded. The group automatically selects a Secondary Controller after 10 minutes.
GMGR0031.Message: The iDRAC local group Secondary Controller %1 is unavailable.

SYS264.Description: Unable to transfer a file because the proxy server was incapable of performing the file transfer operations even when the network connection is available to the proxy server.
SYS264.Resolution: Make sure that correct proxy settings and file transfer parameters are set, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, try connecting to a different proxy.
SYS264.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the proxy server was incapable of performing the file transfer operations.

PDR1004.Message: Consistency check is in progress for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

RED033.Description: The request to shut down the operating system did not complete successfully. The iDRAC was unable to complete the system reboot. Any operation that depends on the system reboot will not complete until reboot is complete.
RED033.Resolution: Identify and resolve any operating system issues that prevented the shutdown. After resolving the issues preventing the operating system shutdown, retry the operation or reboot the system using other methods or interfaces.

LIC003.Description: System resources may be unavailable at the time command is issued.
LIC003.Resolution: Re-issue the command. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC003.Message: License Manager was unable to create and/or allocate the required resources.

OSD51.Description: There are pending System Services tasks on the host system that are preventing the execution of this method.
OSD51.Resolution: Reboot the host system. The system will automatically enter System Services and complete the pending tasks.
OSD51.Message: Reboot the system to run pending System Services Tasks.

SWC4006.Description: FlexAddress is not implemented in one of the versions of firmware. Please update the firmware.
SWC4006.Resolution: Check firmware versions of BIOS and CMC. Update to latest version.
SWC4006.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility detected between system BIOS in slot %1 and CMC.

SWC0268.Description: The ASR screen is already cleared.
SWC0268.Message: There is no ASR screen currently available to clear

PDR7.Description: A physical disk has reported an error condition and may be degraded. The physical disk may have reported the error condition in response to a check consistency or other operation.
PDR7.Resolution: Replace the degraded physical disk. Identify the disk that is degraded by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. Perform a rescan after replacing the disk.

RAC087.Description: The file cannot be imported because of insufficient disk space on iDRAC local storage.
RAC087.Resolution: Delete the unused files by invoking the ClearTransferSession method, and then retry the operation.
RAC087.Message: Unable to import or store the file because of insufficient disk space on iDRAC local storage.

RAC0249.Description: The vFlash partition is in-use by another process. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0249.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.
RAC0249.Message: One or more partitions are in-use by another process.

RAC0761.Description: The system inventory cannot be retrieved because the maximum number of inventory collections allowed is reached, or because of an internal issue where the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.
RAC0761.Resolution: The total number of hardware inventory instances might have exceeded the maximum limit. Wait for the operation to complete and retry the operation. If no other system inventory operation is in progress, enable the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature, restart the system, and then retry the operation.
RAC0761.Message: Unable to retrieve the system inventory because the maximum number of inventory collections allowed is reached, or because of an internal issue where the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

IOV112.Description: Chassis infrastructure firmware is not valid and must be reinstalled.
IOV112.Resolution: Update the Chassis Infrastructure firmware. Using Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM, run the command "racadm fwupdate -g -u -a <TFTP server IP Address> -d mainboard.bin -m main_board" to upload the latest firmware version to the Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard.
IOV112.Message: Chassis Infrastructure firmware is not valid.

RAC0762.Description: Unable to perform a firmware update because a valid catalog file is not available on the network share.
RAC0762.Resolution: Make sure that a valid catalog file is available on the network share and retry the operation.
RAC0762.Message: Unable to perform a firmware update because a valid catalog file is not available on the network share.

CTL53.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL53.Message: A controller hot plug has been detected.

SWC0004.Description: The operation to add a work note to the Lifecycle Log encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0004.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0004.Message: Unable to add a work note to the Lifecycle Log.

SYS034.Description: The configuration operation for the specified device is in progress.

FAN0001.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.
FAN0001.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0001.Message: Fan %1 RPM is less than the lower critical threshold.

MEM0007.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.
MEM0007.Resolution: Review product documentation for supported memory configurations.
MEM0007.Message: Unsupported memory configuration; check memory device at location %1.

DH010.Description: The iDRAC must be reset to apply a new certificate. Until the iDRAC has reset, the old certificate will be active.
DH010.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC. The iDRAC can be reset by pressing the Identify button for 15 seconds. Using the RACADM command line utility, run "racadm racreset".
DH010.Message: Reset iDRAC to apply new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset, the old certificate will be active.

PCI3021.Description: The Airflow Linear Flow per Minute (LFM) custom value cannot be set because the LFM Mode is not set to 'Cusom'.
PCI3021.Resolution: Set the Linear Flow per Minute (LFM Mode) to 'Custom' and retry the operation. To set the LFM Mode to Custom using iDRAC GUI, navigate to Configuration -> System Settings -> Hardware Settings -> PCIe Airflow Settings page.
PCI3021.Message: Unable to set the Airflow Linear Flow per Minute (LFM) custom value because the LFM Mode is not set to 'Custom'.

SWC0303.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0303.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0303.Message: The -r option is not valid with any other option.

IPA0003.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.

VF013.Description: The SD card is locked by another operation.
VF013.Resolution: Rerun the command after about 2 minutes.

SYS067.Description: Some or all configuration actions during the import of configuration profile operation did not complete successfully. The configuration action details are logged into the Lifecycle Log.
SYS067.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log and identify the configuration changes that did not successfully complete. Resolve any issues with the configuration profile content and retry the import operation.
SYS067.Message: Unable to complete application of configuration profile values.

HWC0012.Description: The USB drive is write protected.
HWC0012.Resolution: Remove write protection on the USB drive before retrying the operation.
HWC0012.Message: Unable to write to the USB drive.

BIOS044.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the operation is not allowed when the Secure Boot Policy is in Standard mode.
BIOS044.Resolution: Make sure that the BIOS.Setup.1-1:SecureBootPolicy is set to Custom in the DCIM_BIOSEnumeration class by running the WS-Man get command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation.
BIOS044.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the operation is not allowed when the Secure Boot Policy is in Standard mode.

UEFI0094.Description: Unsupported Non-ECC memory module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0094.Resolution: Remove all Non-ECC DIMMs and replace them with ECC DIMMs. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0094.Message: Unsupported Non-ECC memory module is installed on memory slot: %1.

PDR67.Description: The physical disk does not comply with the standards set by service provider and is not supported.
PDR67.Resolution: Replace the physical disk with a supported physical disk.
PDR67.Message: An unsupported physical disk drive has been detected.

PWR2403.Description: The iDRAC controller established communication to the power management firmware. System performance will return to normal.
PWR2403.Message: iDRAC communication with power management firmware has been restored.

RAC039.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.
RAC039.Resolution: Verify the value for the specified parameter. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

UEFI0147.Description: The system hardware or cabling configuration is invalid.
UEFI0147.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure the system cables, risers, and CPU configuration are installed correctly. 2) Reseat each PCIe riser and reconnect the cables. For more information, see the system Owner's Manual.
UEFI0147.Message: The system hardware or cabling configuration is invalid.

SYS060.Description: Some configuration changes for the component identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) in the configuration job results were not successfully applied.
SYS060.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log and identify the configuration changes that did not complete or retrieve the configuration results using the GetConfigResults() method. Retry those changes that did not complete in a separate import operation.

SYS441.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the index entered as identified in the message is not a valid offset in the array.
SYS441.Resolution: Enter a valid index within the limits of the array and retry the operation.
SYS441.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the index %1 entered is not a valid offset in the array.

RAC0728.Description: The Quick Sync communication or the connection to the iDRAC is no longer functioning.
RAC0728.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove and reseat the bezel. 2) Turn the bezel on by pressing the activation button. 3) Try the Quick Sync feature again. If the issue persists, contact your technical support provider.
RAC0728.Message: The Quick Sync communication is no longer functioning.

SWC1929.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout value is set to the value identified in the message.
SWC1929.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout value is set to %1.

SEL1514.Description: The sensor indicating the inlet temperature is not responding either because the sensor is damaged, or because of damaged circuit lines for I2C bus, or a faulty sensor state.
SEL1514.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC: a) By using graphical user interface (GUI), click Overview > Server > Quick Launch Tasks > Reset iDRAC. b) by running RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), enter racadm racreset. 2) Change the corresponding I2C sensor by contacting your service provider.
SEL1514.Message: The sensor indicating the inlet temperature is not responding either because the sensor is damaged, or because of damaged circuit lines for I2C bus, or a faulty sensor state.

UEFI0305.Description: The BIOS firmware could not be updated during the previous reboot operation because of some issues.
UEFI0305.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0305.Message: Unable to update BIOS firmware in the previous boot because of some issues.

RAC1184.Description: The getuscvresion RACADM subcommand will be deprecated in a future release.
RAC1184.Resolution: Instead of getuscversion, run the getversion -f lc subcommand.
RAC1184.Message: The getuscvresion RACADM subcommand will be deprecated in a future release.

RAC917.Description: The syntax of the specified command is incorrect.
RAC917.Resolution: See the command help text. To see the help text, run "racadm help <subcommand>".
RAC917.Message: The syntax of the specified command is not correct.

SYS071.Description: The export of Server Configuration Profile did not complete because the operation took too long.
SYS071.Resolution: Make sure the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) Lifecycle Controller setting is enabled and reboot the system. Retry the operation after CSIOR has completed. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds and retry the operation after iDRAC has fully restarted.
SYS071.Message: Server Configuration Profile export operation timed-out.

RAC1043.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the option identified in the message.
RAC1043.Resolution: Retry with a correct value for the option identified in the message. For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help autoupdatescheduler".
RAC1043.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings. The option %1 is either invalid or not provided.

RAC0289.Description: When creating a user account, the same value must be entered for New Password and Confirm New Password.
RAC0289.Resolution: Enter the same values for both New Password and Confirm New Password.
RAC0289.Message: Values in New Password and Confirm New Password fields do not match.

AMP0316.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0316.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0316.Message: System level current is outside of range.

SUP0541.Description: The maximum disk space (storage capacity) for storing firmware image files is reached. The rollback firmware image file identified in the message was deleted to create free disk space.
SUP0541.Message: The maximum disk space (storage capacity) for storing firmware image files is reached. The rollback firmware image file of %1 was deleted to create free disk space.

RAC1048.Description: The Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings must already exist in order to be cleared.
RAC1048.Message: Unable to clear the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings because there is currently no configuration.

RAC1196.Description: The Enhanced User Logging is disabled by the user identified in the message. It is disabled for all users working on this iDRAC.
RAC1196.Message: The Enhanced User Logging is disabled by %1.
