LIC020.Description: Importing an upgrade license without a base license is not allowed, as it may be a violation of the license EULA agreement. If the base license was deleted, the system allows the user to override the warning by invoking the import override option.
LIC020.Resolution: If the base license was deleted, override the warning by invoking the import override option.
LIC020.Message: Import failed: End User License Agreement (EULA) import upgrade warning.

BAR021.Description: The system profile export could not complete successfully as there is insufficient space on the network share or connectivity was lost.
BAR021.Resolution: Delete files to free up 384 MB of space on the current network share, or specify another destination that has enough space.

SWC9004.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate Import operation cannot be completed because of one or more of the following reasons: corrupted input file (Certificate or UEFI Driver/op-ROM/boot loader file), invalid file, invalid file encoding format, input file (Certificate or UEFI Driver/op-ROM/boot loader file) is not found, the policy that is being updated already exists, insufficient space in certificate store and internal error.
SWC9004.Resolution: Enter valid parameters and retry the operation. If the issue persists, free some space in the certificate store by deleting few certificates, restart iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SWC9004.Message: The requested SecureBoot Certificate Import operation cannot be completed.

SYS233.Description: The file identified in the message cannot be transferred because of an unsupported hostname value.
SYS233.Resolution: Make sure that the correct hostname value is used, and then retry the operation.
SYS233.Message: Unable to transfer the file, %1, because of an unsupported hostname value, %2.

IOID119.Description: The FlexAddress feature is enabled on the system. The iDRAC will assign FlexAddress defined MAC and WWN values to all the ports and/or partitions of bNDCs and mezzanine adapters of the system.
IOID119.Message: FlexAddress is enabled on all NIC and FC HBA devices.

RAC0617.Description: An error occurred while generating new iDRAC SSL Certificate or signing it with new custom signing certificate.
RAC0617.Resolution: Make sure to upload an PKCS#12 file that contains a valid custom signing certificate and private key, then retry the operation.
RAC0617.Message: An error was encountered while generating new SSL Certificate.

NIC100.Description: The network link is down. Either the network cable is not connected or the network device is not working.
NIC100.Resolution: Verify that the network port is enabled and if the port has Activity/Speed LEDs, that they are lit. Check the network cable, network cable connections, and the attached network switch.
NIC100.Message: The %1 Port %2 network link is down.

PCI1316.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1316.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1316.Message: A bus uncorrectable error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

SUP019.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G and above generations : Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
SUP019.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

SWC8615.Description: A profile was successfully generated from a server.

USR8516.Description: The Baseboard Management Controller (BMC) is unable to communicate to the LCD device embedded in the panel because of connection issues in the LCD ribbon cable.
USR8516.Resolution: Make sure that LCD ribbon cable is properly connected to the LCD device in the panel, and then retry the operation. For more information about connection procedure, see the server's Owner's Manual available on the support site.
USR8516.Message: The Baseboard Management Controller (BMC) is unable to communicate to the LCD device embedded in the panel because of connection issues in the LCD ribbon cable.

PWR8577.Description: A virtual reseat operation is initiated on the Sleeve or Sled identified in the message. A virtual reseat is the same as removing and inserting a Sleeve or Sled.
PWR8577.Message: A virtual reseat operation is initiated on Sleeve or Sled %1.

SWC0008.Description: The export As Shipped hardware inventory operation did not complete because the destination: 1) does not have the specified folder, 2) does not have enough free space, or 3) is read-only.
SWC0008.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, verify the following and retry the operation: 1) Destination has the specified folder. 2) Destination has enough free space. 3) Destination is not write-protected.
SWC0008.Message: Unable to write the As Shipped hardware inventory to the specified destination.

SYS167.Description: The TTY Log data export did not complete within the allocated time. Currently the maximum allocated time is 20 minutes.
SYS167.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
SYS167.Message: TTY Log data export did not complete within the allocated time.

SRV044.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server OS is turned off.
SRV044.Resolution: Turn on the server and wait until the OS finishes booting, and then retry the operation.
SRV044.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server is turned off.

SWC0249.Description: The specified parameter needs to be given with its legal value.
SWC0249.Resolution: Enter the proper index preceded by -i.
SWC0249.Message: Invalid syntax. The requested subcommand requires -i %1 to be specified.

UEFI0268.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI target name is invalid.
UEFI0268.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, make sure the iSCSI Target Name in the iSCSI setup page is correct, and retry the operation.
UEFI0268.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI target name is invalid.

SWC0273.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0273.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0273.Message: Invalid syntax. The -g option requires -o to also be specified.

UEFI0000.Description: A CPU type 0x00, divide by zero exception, (type 0x00) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment. The software attempted to do a mathematical divide by zero, an illegal operation.
UEFI0000.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception.Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0000.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x00: Divide by Zero (Software).

LIC502.Description: The attempted features are not available in the system.
LIC502.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

PDR1107.Message: Rebuild is in progress for drive %1.

NIC014.Description: AttributeValue may be invalid because of the following causes: 1) Length of new AttributeValue is not within minLength and maxLength 2) Value of new AttributeValue is not within LowerBound and UpperBound 3) Value of new AttributeValue is not one of the possible values.
NIC014.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on valid attribute values.

RDU8522.Description: The standby CMC identified in the message became the active CMC.

ENC17.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
ENC17.Message: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has been discovered on %1.

RAC0610.Description: Different values were entered for passphrase and confirm passphrase field.
RAC0610.Resolution: Values entered in passphrase and confirm passphrase fields must be the same.
RAC0610.Message: The passphrase and confirm passphrase values entered do not match.

SYS194.Description: The Collection of System Inventory successfully completed by Lifecycle Controller firmware.
SYS194.Message: The Collection of System Inventory successfully completed.

TMP0132.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0132.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0132.Message: The control panel temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

CMC8501.Description: Multi Chassis Management feature on CMC allows for pushing the lead chassis configuration data to it's members. This message appears in the member's log when the configuration data is successfully synchronized with the Chassis group leader's configuration data.
CMC8501.Message: Chassis Group Leader has synchronized this member's configuration.

SYS416.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the username and/or password is not entered, and therefore authentication failed.
SYS416.Resolution: Enter valid user name and password and retry the operation.
SYS416.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the username and/or password is not entered, and therefore authentication failed.

RAC1116.Description: The command could not be successfully run, because an incorrect "restart flag" value was entered in the command.
RAC1116.Resolution: Enter a correct flag value. The recommended values are "true" and "false". Make sure that you have entered the correct value, and then retry the operation.
RAC1116.Message: Unable to run the command, because the restart flag entered is incorrect.

VLT0224.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0224.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0224.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

LC008.Description: The parameter value is not supported.
LC008.Resolution: Confirm that the parameters provided are correct. For a list of parameters for this method refer to the Lifecycle Controller User Guide.

SWC0252.Description: Invalid number of arguments were passed to the command.
SWC0252.Resolution: Refer the help text for the command, and enter the required parameters.
SWC0252.Message: No options were specified. The subcommand requires options to be used.

SWC0108.Description: The Service Tag string is empty.
SWC0108.Message: The service tag is not currently populated.

VDR22.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RED099.Description: The firmware version of the component identified in the message will be updated to the available version identified in the message.
RED099.Message: The firmware version of %1 will be updated. Current version: %2, Available version: %3.

VDR47.Description: A disk media error was detected while the controller was completing a background task. A bad disk block was identified. The disk block was remapped.
VDR47.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle log for information related to members of this virtual disk.
VDR47.Message: A disk media error was corrected on %1.

LIC006.Description: The license end date has been reached.
LIC006.Resolution: Obtain a replacement license and import it.

RED081.Description: The requested operation was not successful because an Automatic Update schedule already exists.
RED081.Resolution: Delete the existing Automatic Update schedule operation before retrying the operation.
RED081.Message: The Automatic Update schedule already exists.

RAC1016.Description: iDRAC does not allow duplicate user names for each of the 16 users.
RAC1016.Resolution: Make sure that each of the 16 user names are unique.
RAC1016.Message: The specified user already exists. Duplicate user names are not allowed.

RED037.Description: The currently installed firmware of the components on the server match with the specified remote repository.
RED037.Message: All components' firmware match with the specified remote repository.

SWC1947.Description: The Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-write mode.
SWC1947.Message: The Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-write mode.

BAR048.Description: The server motherboard does not have a Service Tag assigned, the operation cannot continue.
BAR048.Resolution: Perform a System Profile import from a previous backup file. If no backup file is available, contact your service provider.

RAC0669.Description: Initializing the virtual disk will permanently delete data from the virtual disk.
RAC0669.Message: Initializing the virtual disk will permanently delete data from the virtual disk.

VDR38.Description: A user renamed a virtual disk. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC916.Description: The value given is greater than the maximum threshold value.
RAC916.Resolution: Set values lesser than the maximum threshold value. To view the maximum threshold value, run racadm get System.Power. Cap.MaxThreshold at the command prompt.
RAC916.Message: Value given exceeds the maximum threshold value.

RDU0004.Description: One of more fans have failed or have been removed or a configuration change occurred which requires additional fans.
RDU0004.Resolution: Remove and re-install failed fans or install additional fans.

SWC0259.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0259.Resolution: Refer the list of groups and enter a valid option.

SRV058.Description: The SupportAssist registration operation cannot be completed because registration information field identified in the message is invalid.
SRV058.Resolution: Ensure that valid data is entered for SupportAssist registration and then retry the operation.
SRV058.Message: Unable to proceed with the SupportAssist registration operation because registration information: %1 is invalid.

STOR302.Description: The job could not be created because the Apply Operation Mode selected is not supported for this operation.
STOR302.Resolution: Choose a different Apply Operation mode "Apply at Next Reboot" from the Apply Operation Mode drop-down menu.
STOR302.Message: Unable to create the job because the Apply Operation Mode selected is not supported for this operation.

VF034.Description: The specified partition access type is not a valid type.
VF034.Resolution: Try a partition access type that is supported.

CPU0805.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0805.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0805.Message: The power input for CPU %1 voltage regulator module is outside of range, but it is attached to the system.

RAC0163.Description: The hardware identity certificate is either missing or corrupted. If the hardware identity certificate is missing, certain security features are not enabled.
RAC0163.Resolution: To restore the hardware identify certificate, replace the iDRAC board.
RAC0163.Message: The hardware identity certificate is either missing or corrupted.

SWC8627.Description: Unable to configure storage array. This could happen if CMC could not communicate with storage device.
SWC8627.Resolution: 1. Reset iDRAC by using the graphical user interface (GUI): Click Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components. In the Reset Server section, from the Reset drop-down menu, select iDRAC Reset corresponding to the server iDRAC to be reset, and then click Apply Selection. Or, reset iDRAC by running the following command at the command line interface (CLI): racadm racreset -m server-n.2. Reset Chassis Management Controller (CMC) by using the GUI: Click Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components, and then click Reset/Failover CMC. Or, reset CMC by running the following command at the CLI: racadm racreset.For more information about the syntax and parameters used, see the iDRAC 8/7 v2.30.30.30 RACADM CLI Guide and the Chassis Management Controller Version 5.0 for Dell PowerEdge M1000e RACADM Command Line Reference Guide available on the support site.
SWC8627.Message: Unable to configure the storage array in slot %1, because there is no communication between Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and the storage device.

RAC0616.Description: iDRAC was unable to continue with the operation after the PKCS#12 file was uploaded, because it is not able to extract the custom signing certificate and private key.
RAC0616.Resolution: Make sure to upload the PKCS#12 file that contains a valid custom signing certificate and private key.
RAC0616.Message: Error while extracting custom signing certificate and private key from the PKCS#12 file.

TMP0113.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0113.Message: The %1 temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

UEFI0132.Description: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient base memory. The base memory is memory below 640K.
UEFI0132.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove unused PCIe card(s) to free up option ROM space. 2) Disable unused boot protocol instances (such as PXE, iSCSI, etc.) from applicable PCIe card(s) option ROM configurations. 3) If possible, install and run the Operating System in UEFI boot mode.
UEFI0132.Message: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient base memory.

SUP003.Description: One of the uniform resource input (URI) string, target or reboot flag parameters is missing or exceeds the prescribed length.
SUP003.Resolution: Verify that the URI, target or reboot flag parameter values are correct and retry the action.
SUP003.Message: Invalid URI, target or reboot flag.

FCD8501.Description: The FlexAddress, FlexAddress+ or extended storage feature is deactivated. Turn chassis off and remove the feature card.
FCD8501.Resolution: Turn chassis OFF and remove card. Alternately, to repair the card, perform Repair by navigating to the CMC GUI -> Chassis Controller -> Flash Media page.

STOR319.Description: The storage controller only allows one reconfiguration operation at a time on a Virtual Disk. A new reconfiguration operation cannot be requested until the currently executing reconfiguration operation is complete or is canceled.
STOR319.Resolution: There are two possible actions. 1) Wait for the current reconfiguration operation to complete and then retry the new reconfiguration operation. 2) Cancel the current reconfiguration operation and then start the new reconfiguration operation.
STOR319.Message: Unable to perform the reconfiguration operation because a reconfiguration operation is already in progress for the Virtual Disk.

SSD0001.Description: The Write Endurance of solid state drive identified in the message is less than the threshold value of 'Remaining Write Rated Endurance'.
SSD0001.Resolution: Back up the data on the solid state drive (SSD), and then contact your service provider for more assistance.
SSD0001.Message: The Write Endurance of Solid state drive (SSD) %1 is less than the threshold value of 'Remaining Write Rated Endurance'.

IOV2008.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) could not successfully connect to the PCIe subsystem.
IOV2008.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Perform an AC Power Cycle operation on the Chassis by disconnecting the chassis from AC power, wait for 30 seconds, and then reconnect AC power. 2) Turn on at least one server. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Server Overview->Power->Control and select the Power On Server option. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
IOV2008.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to communicate with the PCIe subsystem.

RAC0698.Description: Unable to modify USB management settings because the USB device is currently in use.
RAC0698.Resolution: Wait for the current USB operations to complete and retry the operation.
RAC0698.Message: Unable to modify USB management settings because the USB device is currently in use.

PCI1319.Description: A high-severity issue was detected in the SSD bay identified in the message.
PCI1319.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the component identified in the message, and then monitor the log for a re-occurrence of the issue. If the issue persists, and occurs during server startup, update the component firmware. If the issue persists and occurs during OS runtime, restart the server and update the OS drivers for the component identified in the message.
PCI1319.Message: A high-severity issue is detected in the SSD bay %1, Slot %2.

SYS170.Description: The SHA256 Hash value and the clear text value for an iDRAC user password cannot be used at the same time for a password configuration operation.
SYS170.Resolution: Make sure that the user password is configured using either the clear text or the SHA256 Hash, but not both.
SYS170.Message: The SHA256 Hash value and the clear text value for an iDRAC user password cannot be entered together.

STOR316.Description: This occurs when a disk group is sliced to create multiple Virtual Disks. Reconfiguration of such sliced Virtual Disks is not supported.
STOR316.Resolution: Make sure that the physical disk group has a single Virtual Disk and retry the reconfiguration operation.
STOR316.Message: Unable to perform the reconfiguration operation because the storage controller does not support reconfiguration of a Virtual Disk that is part of a disk group that has multiple Virtual Disks.

PSU1000.Description: The power supply unit is not receiving input AC power. The power cable may not be connected properly or removed. This can happen if there is an AC failure or problems with the power strip attached to the enclosure power supply.
PSU1000.Resolution: Reconnect the power cable to the power supply unit if it was disconnected. Restore the input AC power supply. Make sure the power supply is restored to the enclosure from the mains.
PSU1000.Message: Power supply cable has been removed from %1.

LIC212.Description: The features are updated because the license was imported or deleted, or the license has expired.

PWR8571.Description: Another power action is in progress. The requested power action cannot be carried out until the power action in progress completes.
PWR8571.Resolution: Wait for the power action in progress to complete and retry the operation. It may take a few minutes for the current power action to complete.
PWR8571.Message: Unable to perform the power action requested for the server %1because another power action is in progress.

PDR62.Description: It is not possible to rebuild data that resides on a defective disk.
PDR62.Resolution: Replace the target disk. If a rebuild does not automatically start after replacing the disk, then initiate the Rebuild task. You may need to assign the new disk as a hot spare to initiate the rebuild.
PDR62.Message: The rebuild failed due to errors on the target %1.

UEFI0265.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 address is invalid.
UEFI0265.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the Initiator IP address field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0265.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 address is invalid.

CPU0004.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is inserted correctly, if the processor is removable.3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

UEFI0295.Description: An issue has occurred in processor Built-In-Self-Test (BIST). The affected tile and socket are identified by the message.
UEFI0295.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0295.Message: An issue has occurred during processor Built-In Self-Test (BIST). Tiles Affected: %1 on Socket %2.

PSU1010.Description: The power supply unit is switched off. Either you have switched off the power supply unit or it is defective.
PSU1010.Resolution: Check to see whether the power switch is turned off or on. If it is turned off, turn it on. If the problem is not corrected, verify that the power cord is attached and functional. If the problem continues or if the power switch is already turned on, then replace the power supply unit.
PSU1010.Message: The DC power supply is switched off.

RAC1007.Description: The job specified in the message cannot be deleted when it is Running, Scheduled, or transitioning from Downloading to Scheduled.
RAC1007.Resolution: Wait until the specified job is completed, or reboot the system to move the job to Completed state. To view the job status, use"racadm jobqueue view -i <Job ID>".

RAC0651.Description: The Enclosure Split Mode configuration process is started. However, the setting will be applied only during the next AC power cycle operation of the Chassis. This may result in loss of configuration and/or access to physical disk drive(s).
RAC0651.Message: The Enclosure Split Mode configuration process is started. However, the setting will be applied only during the next AC power cycle operation of the Chassis. This may result in loss of configuration and/or access to physical disk drive(s).

PST0064.Description: System BIOS is displaying power on splash screen.

BAT1016.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1016.Message: The %1 battery learn mode has changed to Auto.

RAC012.Description: The user credentials supplied do not have sufficient privileges to perform the operation.
RAC012.Resolution: Retry the operation with user credentials authorized for the requested operation.
RAC012.Message: Unable to perform the operation because of insufficient user privileges.

ISM0025.Description: The NVMe device cannot be prepared for removal from (the PCIe slot identified in the message because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) NVMe device is busy, 2) NVMe device is not present or 3) NVMe driver is not present.
ISM0025.Resolution: Make sure of the following: 1)That the NVMe device identified in the message is not in use, 2) the NVMe device is present, and 3) NVMe device drive is installed.
ISM0025.Message: Unable to prepare the NVMe device %1 for removal from the PCIe slot %2 because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) NVMe device is busy, 2) NVMe device is not present or 3) NVMe driver is not installed.

SYS008.Description: The input value for the specified attribute is not a valid boolean value for the attribute.
SYS008.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and provide a valid boolean value for the specified attribute.
SYS008.Message: Invalid boolean in value for attribute: %1.

UEFI0157.Description: The request to reset BIOS to default settings is successfully completed.
UEFI0157.Message: The iDRAC request to reset BIOS to default settings is successfully completed.

CMC8525.Description: The FRU on the sleeve specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8525.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8525.Message: The FRU on the sleeve %1 is not functioning.

CTL115.Description: The Secure Drive related operations cannot be performed because a key mismatch was detected between peer controllers.
CTL115.Resolution: Make sure that the encryption key for the peer controllers matches by using controller security operations such as creating a security key, modifying a security key, deleting a security key, and then retry the operation.
CTL115.Message: Unable to perform Secure Drive related operations because a key mismatch was detected between peer controllers.

FAN0031.Description: The configuration mismatch of fan identified in the message is successfully resolved. For more information about recommended fan configurations, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
FAN0031.Message: The configuration mismatch of fan %1 is successfully resolved.

PST0140.Description: System BIOS failed to initialize the system management interrupt. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code 8C) .
PST0140.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

CTL54.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation.

RAC0682.Description: Enabling iDRAC Direct USB Configuration XML allows any USB key containing a correctly formatted configuration XML file to reconfigure the server when plugged into the USB management port identified by the wrench icon. This may include operations on RAID configurations, user accounts, and alert settings.
RAC0682.Message: Enabling iDRAC Direct USB Configuration XML allows any USB key containing a correctly formatted configuration XML file to reconfigure the server when plugged into the USB management port identified by the wrench icon. This may include operations on RAID configurations, user accounts, and alert settings.

NIC024.Description: The attribute specified in the operation is currently read only and the value cannot be modified.
NIC024.Resolution: For more information on the attribute, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
NIC024.Message: The set operation did not complete successfully as the attribute is read-only.

PR18.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference between the current and previous components. Depending on the Part Firmware Update setting value this may cause a firmware update to the replaced part.
PR18.Message: Firmware version difference detected for device: %1

DIS108.Description: The server could not be successfully configured, because Lifecycle Controller is either not installed or not enabled.
DIS108.Resolution: Verify that the Lifecycle Controller firmware on the server being configured is installed and enabled, then restart the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for 15 seconds. For more information about Lifecycle Controller, see the Lifecycle Controller Users Guide available at dell.com/support/manuals.
DIS108.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig import operation, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

VFL0014.Description: The vFlash SD card is not initialized. Either the card is not properly formatted or it may not be supported.
VFL0014.Resolution: Format the vFlash SD card by running the command "racadm vflashsd initialize". Make sure that the card is supported by contacting your service provider for a list of supported SD card types.
VFL0014.Message: The vFlash SD card is not initialized.

SYS197.Description: The OEM ID module cannot be installed because of some issues.
SYS197.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log report to analyze the issue, resolve the issue, and then retry the installation process.
SYS197.Message: Unable to install the OEM ID module because of some issues. %1

SYS139.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.
SYS139.Resolution: Retry the operation after the server has finished starting and POST has completed.
SYS139.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.

RDU0017.Description: The storage system has redundant power lines. One of power lines is no longer available.
RDU0017.Resolution: Turn system off and remove AC input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. If the issue still persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
RDU0017.Message: The storage power redundancy is no longer available.

SEL1406.Message: The platform generated a SNMP trap.

PWR8675.Description: AC power supply is detected in the NEBS configuration.
PWR8675.Message: AC power supply is detected in the NEBS configuration.

SWC0131.Description: The destination Ip address must be configured for the Trap.
SWC0131.Resolution: Set cfgIpmiPetAlertDestIpAddr in cfgIpmiPet group using config subcommand for the corresponding index.
SWC0131.Message: Trap destination address must be configured.

RAC0302.Description: This error message is displayed when iDRAC does not have a valid Enterprise license.
RAC0302.Resolution: Upgrade to iDRAC Enterprise for supporting this feature.
RAC0302.Message: iDRAC Express does not support this feature.

CMC8512.Description: The Extended Storage feature is not activated if the removable flash media SD card on the secondary CMC does not respond within 90 seconds after activation is initiated.
CMC8512.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration, and verify if the SD card on secondary CMC displays errors. 2) If errors are displayed, execute the following racadm command: "racadm cmcchangeover". 3) Repair the removable flash media SD Card by selecting the Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration > Repair Active Controller Media in the CMC Web interface. Repairing is only allowed on the SD card of the primary CMC. If the problem persists, replace the card.
CMC8512.Message: The Extended Storage feature activation timed out. The feature is not active.

ISM0015.Description: The iDRAC Service Module detected a change in the host name of the server OS.
ISM0015.Message: The iDRAC Service Module detected a change in the host name of the server operating system (OS).

BAR084.Description: System profile backup file validation failed because the host system service tag information does not match the value stored in the file.
BAR084.Resolution: Obtain a valid host system backup image and try the operation again. Reboot the remote access controller and try the operation again. If the error continues, download a new remote access controller firmware image and try the operation again.
BAR084.Message: Host System Service Tag does not match the Backup file Service Tag.

FAN903.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode cannot be enabled because an unsupported fan is present in the Chassis.
FAN903.Resolution: Insert a fan that is supported by the Chassis, and then retry the operation. For a list of fans that are supported by Chassis, see the Chassis Management Controller Users Guide.
FAN903.Message: Cannot enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode because an unsupported fan is inserted in the Chassis.

UEFI0095.Description: A DIMM with unsupported voltage is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0095.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module and replace it with a DIMM with a supported voltage. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0095.Message: A DIMM with unsupported voltage is installed on memory slot %1.

RAC051.Description: The parameter name is not supported.
RAC051.Resolution: Remove the unsupported parameter and retry the operation.

SWC8523.Description: Unable to complete a configuration sync with the member identified in the message.
SWC8523.Resolution: Check the communications between the Chassis Group Leader and the member. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping <DNS or IP address> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, resolve the communications issue. If the communications are functional, remove the member from the group and re-add the member. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8523.Message: Unable to complete Chassis Group Leader update of member %1.

UEFI0274.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI login operation did not complete successfully.
UEFI0274.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, make sure the target name is correct. 2) On the iSCSI target system, make sure the initiator name is added into the target identifiers. 3) Compare the authentication settings in the iSCSI initiator setup page to that of the iSCSI target system and make sure the settings match. 4) Retry the operation.
UEFI0274.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI login operation did not complete successfully.

NIC010.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G and above generations: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
NIC010.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.
NIC010.Message: Lifecycle Controller is not enabled, cannot create Configuration job.

BAR005.Description: The Lifecycle Controller data is being collected and copied into the backup file.

DIS008.Description: iDRAC IP address change in progress with Provisioning Server.
DIS008.Message: Notification of iDRAC IP address changed to %1 from %2 sent to Provisioning Server.

RAC0620.Description: Lifecycle Controller is currently busy performing tasks. The selected jobs cannot be deleted until the following: 1) The Lifecycle Controller tasks are completed. 2) The system completes all the Power-on-Self-test (POST) operations.
RAC0620.Resolution: Wait until Lifecycle Controller completes the current tasks and the system completes Power-on Self-test (POST).
RAC0620.Message: Lifecycle Controller is unable to delete the selected jobs.

SYS288.Description: The catalog file cannot be obtained from the network share for preview because the file does not exist in the specified location.
SYS288.Resolution: Make sure that the specified catalog file is available on the remote share, and then retry the operation.
SYS288.Message: Unable to get the Repository Update catalog file from the network share for preview because the file does not exist in the specified location.

BAT0005.Description: To charge the battery, the system has to remain powered on.
BAT0005.Resolution: Allow the PERC RAID controller battery to charge. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

CTL32.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL32.Message: Abort CC on Error is modified for %1.

RAC1164.Description: A remote diagnostics operation is already under execution and another operation can be started only after the current execution is completed.
RAC1164.Resolution: Initiate another diagnostics operation only after the currently running operation is completed.
RAC1164.Message: A remote diagnostics operation is currently running and not completed.

FC006.Description: A configuration job already exists for the specified target. No further configuration operations are allowed until the existing job is competed or the job is cancelled.
FC006.Resolution: Wait until the existing configuration job for the targeted component is complete or cancel the existing job before retrying the operation.
FC006.Message: Configuration job already created, cannot set attribute on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled.

SEC0611.Message: An Out-of-band password violation was corrected.

RAC0622.Description: The certificate file is invalid for one of the following reasons: 1) CA Certificate is corrupted, expired, or does not have signing privileges. 2) CA private key does not match with CA Certificate being uploaded.
RAC0622.Resolution: Make sure the CA certificate and private key are correct and retry the operation. The certificate can be validated using the OpenSSL tools.
RAC0622.Message: An invalid certificate file is uploaded.

RED029.Description: The scheduled action requires a system reboot and reboot will be performed at the scheduled start time.

CPU0819.Message: The power input for CPU %1 voltage regulator module has been restored.

VFL0004.Description: The requested vFlash media operation could not be performed, because some of the iDRAC services are busy.
VFL0004.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation. If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
VFL0004.Message: Unable to perform the vFlash media operation.

HWC8507.Description: The USB device inserted in to the I/O Panel USB port is causing an issue and cannot be used. The USB device may not be operational.
HWC8507.Resolution: Remove the USB device from the I/O Panel USB port, and then retry the operation with another USB device.
HWC8507.Message: The USB device inserted in to the I/O Panel USB port is causing an issue and cannot be used.

PSU500.Description: Racadm tool cannot obtain the power status possible reason is that the IPMI call failed.
PSU500.Message: Unable to get the current server power status.

RAC0245.Description: The vFlash partition is in-use by another process. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0245.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes or with another partition. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.
RAC0245.Message: The partition is in-use by another process.

LC021.Description: The contents of the PKCS12 parameter was not valid because: 1) not a valid PKCS12 file 2) not a valid pfx file 3) did not contain a valid key.
LC021.Resolution: Validate that the PKCS12 file was Base64 encoded. OpenSSL can be used to create or validate a PKCS12 file.
LC021.Message: PKCS12 decrypt of private key could not complete.

RAC0218.Description: A maximum of 4 iDRAC Web GUI sessions can be open at any time.
RAC0218.Resolution: Close one or more sessions before opening another session.
RAC0218.Message: The maximum number of user sessions is reached.

ISM0020.Description: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the iDRAC emulated USB device with the OS Collector application was not found.
ISM0020.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
ISM0020.Message: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the iDRAC emulated USB device with the OS Collector application was not found.

PST0256.Description: System BIOS detected a functional or configuration issue during system POST. Check the system video screen for more information. The system event log may contain additional details.
PST0256.Resolution: Check system video and review event log for additional information.

SYS122.Description: The operation to collect OS and Application Data is successfully completed.
SYS122.Message: OS Collector: The operation to collect OS and Application Data is successfully completed.

LC014.Resolution: Limit the number of characters in the comment to 255 characters.

LIC902.Description: Unable to allocate the resource because of lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC.
LIC902.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.

SRV096.Description: The SupportAssist Collection file identified in the message is successfully created.
SRV096.Message: The SupportAssist Collection %1 is successfully created.

BAR082.Description: Remote access controller firmware and configuration import in progress.

RAC964.Description: The operation cannot be performed because of an internal error.
RAC964.Resolution: Wait for some time before retrying the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

SRV037.Description: Unable to communicate with the OS IPMI service because the service is not running.
SRV037.Resolution: For more information about checking whether the IPMI service is running, see the iDRAC9 User's Guide.
SRV037.Message: The OS Collector application is unable to communicate with the OS IPMI service.

RAC096.Description: The System LockDown mode is successfully disabled.
RAC096.Message: The System Lockdown mode is successfully disabled.

SWC0217.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0217.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0217.Message: The -c option requires -u to also be specified.

STOR032.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to gain access to internal storage because it is in use by another application or operation.
STOR032.Resolution: Wait for current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Configuration utility 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
STOR032.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

SWC9011.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate Export operation is successfully completed.
SWC9011.Message: The SecureBoot Certificate Export operation is successfully completed.

BOOT005.Description: One or more of the invoked methods required parameters are missing.
BOOT005.Resolution: Check documentation for the method in question and try again.

STOR028.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the specified virtual disk is not found.
STOR028.Resolution: Provide a valid virtual disk FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) and retry the operation.

PDR54.Description: This message is generated after a disk media error is corrected on a physical disk.
PDR54.Message: A disk media error on %1 was corrected during recovery.

SEL1304.Description: PXE is one way to boot a system from the network. (IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 02h).
SEL1304.Resolution: Check network and PXE server configuration.

SWC0281.Description: The value being modified is READ only.
SWC0281.Message: The specified object is READ ONLY and cannot be modified.

PDR47.Description: The controller encountered an unrecoverable medium error when attempting to read a block on the physical disk and marked that block as invalid. If the controller encountered the unrecoverable medium error on a source physical disk during a rebuild or reconfigure operation, it punctures the corresponding block on the target physical disk. The invalid block clears on a write operation.
PDR47.Resolution: Back up the data from the disk. Start disk initialization and wait for it to complete, and then restore the data from a backup copy.
PDR47.Message: A block on %1 was punctured by the controller.

RAC0751.Description: The value for information or warning threshold should not be less than lower critical threshold value.
RAC0751.Resolution: Enter a threshold value that is greater than the lower warning or critical threshold values and retry the operation.
RAC0751.Message: The threshold value entered is less than the lower warning or critical threshold.

SWC0082.Description: An error occurred while joining the Dell Integrated Data Center Network because the Provisioning Server on Integrated Data Center did not respond. Refer to Integrated Data Center setup instructions to setup the Provisioning Server.
SWC0082.Resolution: Refer to Integrated Data Center User Guide for setup instructions.
SWC0082.Message: Unable to join Integrated Data Center network.

PST0008.Description: System BIOS has started System Management Mode (SMM) initialization.

PR21.Description: The specified job did not complete successfully.
PR21.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log for more details associated with this failure then retry the operation.

RAC971.Description: The import or export operation cannot continue if the value specified for the file type is incorrect. The correct value for the file type is "xml" or "ini".
RAC971.Resolution: Make sure to specify either "xml" or "ini" for the file type (-t) option. If no file type is specified, "ini" is used as default.

RAC1166.Description: The Configuration XML file preview operation was successfully initiated after it was invoked by the user name identified in the message.
RAC1166.Message: Successfully initiated Configuration XML file preview operation that was invoked by %1.

PCI1318.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1318.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1318.Message: A fatal error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

UEFI0208.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Command Clock Training - Group All phase.
UEFI0208.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0208.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC0124.Description: All characters in the label must be alphanumeric.
RAC0124.Message: Invalid label: Label must be exclusively alphanumeric characters.

CBL8500.Description: SAS cables are not connected to the expander correctly.
CBL8500.Resolution: Check whether or not the SAS cables are connected to the expander. Reconnect the cables and retry the operation.
CBL8500.Message: SAS cable %1 to expander %2 is not connected.

RAC0105.Description: Communication with the Smart Card reader cannot be established, or is lost.
RAC0105.Resolution: This error may occur because:1. Check connection between reader and system.2. There may be an issue with the Smart Card reader. Try reinstalling the reader driver or use a different reader.
RAC0105.Message: The Smart Card reader cannot be detected. Check whether the reader is installed correctly.

CPU0822.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is configured correctly.

SWC0251.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0251.Resolution: Enter the index value as specified by the message.
SWC0251.Message: Invalid index value. Only index values %1 - %1 are permitted.

UEFI0135.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This issue is caused by LC partition attach issues.
UEFI0135.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0135.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

VDR50.Description: The background initialization task encountered errors that cannot be corrected. The virtual disk contains physical disks that have unusable disk space or disk errors that cannot be corrected.
VDR50.Resolution: Review other messages to identify whether the physical disk that has errors. If the virtual disk is redundant, you can replace the physical disk and continue using the virtual disk. If the virtual disk is non-redundant, you need to recreate the virtual disk after replacing the physical disk. After replacing the physical disk, run a consistency check to verify the data.
VDR50.Message: Background Initialization (BGI) completed with uncorrectable errors on %1.

RED002.Description: Package has been successfully downloaded. The Job Scheduler will schedule it at the time specified.
RED002.Resolution: Schedule the job if it is not already scheduled.

UEFI0048.Description: The Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) operation is not performed during this restart because Lifecycle Controller firmware could not be accessed or run properly.
UEFI0048.Resolution: Repair Lifecycle Controller using the Update Package. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
UEFI0048.Message: The Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) operation is not performed during this restart because Lifecycle Controller is not functioning.

RAC0750.Description: The USB NIC IP address cannot be accessed by using the PING process.
RAC0750.Resolution: Enter another appropriate IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC0750.Message: Unable to access the USB NIC IP address by using PING process.

VDR48.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The virtual disk has inconsistent data. This may be caused when a power loss or system shutdown occurs while data is being written to the virtual disk.

STOR0110.Description: The specified Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDDs) system component name is invalid.
STOR0110.Resolution: Verify that the correct Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) system component name is specified. See the help text (The help text for the raid subcommand can be obtained by running "racadm help raid") or documentation for valid FQDD system component names.

SWC8612.Description: The profile identified in the message does not contain boot device information in a usable format.
SWC8612.Resolution: Recreate the profile identified in the message or use a different profile.
SWC8612.Message: Unable to fully extract boot device information from profile: %1.

PDR100.Description: The controller is not able to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a dedicated hot spare. The disk may have been removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.
PDR100.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and that it has not been removed. Check the cables. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the dedicated hot spare.
PDR100.Message: Dedicated Hot Spare %1 no longer useful for all arrays.

USR0177.Description: Configuring the Front Panel USB Port Mode to Automatic because the iDRAC is unable to retrieve the Front Panel USB Port Mode.
USR0177.Message: Configuring the Front Panel USB Port Mode to Automatic because the iDRAC is unable to retrieve the Front Panel USB Port Mode.

MEM1202.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM1202.Message: Memory RAID redundancy is degraded. Check memory device at location(s) %1.

OSD46.Description: Another process (iDRAC GUI /racadm/iDRAC configuration utility) is currently accessing vFlash.
OSD46.Resolution: Wait until the access to vFlash is relinquished and then retry this command.

CTL79.Description: This controller does not support features required for this chassis. This controller will not be powered on to prevent data loss.
CTL79.Resolution: Replace the controller with a supported controller.
CTL79.Message: Controller in %1 is not supported and will not be powered on.

MEM1011.Message: Memory device at location %1 is on-duty.

SWC0080.Description: iDRAC exited from Integrated Data Center Troubleshooting Mode. Integrated Data Center may revert some of the network settings made by the user while in Troubleshooting Mode.
SWC0080.Message: iDRAC exited from Integrated Data Center Troubleshooting Mode.

SRV135.Description: The filtered Operating System (OS) and Application Data collection is not supported on the OS installed on the server.
SRV135.Message: The filtered Operating System (OS) and Application Data collection is not supported on the OS installed on the server.

PSU8502.Description: The input voltage of the PSU specified in the message does not match the input voltage of the PSUs already present in the chassis.
PSU8502.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the power configuration "Allow 110 VAC Operation" setting and make sure it is enabled. 2) Check if the input voltage of all the PSUs are the same. 3) If the input voltage of the PSU specified in the message is not the same, then remove the unmatched PSU.
PSU8502.Message: The PSU in slot %1 detected 110 VAC input voltage and does not match chassis configuration.

SRV110.Description: Unable to detect the host network connection because the SupportAssist back-end server is either down or is not responding to client requests.
SRV110.Resolution: If the issue persists, retry the operation after some time as SupportAssist back-end server might be under maintenance.
SRV110.Message: Unable to detect the host network connection because the SupportAssist back-end server is either down or is not responding to client requests.

USR8510.Description: Successful login by Username identified in the message.

SWC0011.Description: The front panel security settings were successfully configured.
SWC0011.Message: Successfully applied front panel security settings.

SYS128.Description: Unable to generate a zip archive of the OS and Application Data report.
SYS128.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS128.Message: OS Collector: Unable to generate a zip archive of the OS and Application Data report.

UEFI0032.Description: The TPM chip cannot be initialized because the TPM chip is not functioning.
UEFI0032.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0032.Message: Unable to initialize the TPM chip because the TPM chip is not functioning.

VRM0012.Description: The Virtual Media server is already connected.
VRM0012.Message: The Virtual Media image server is already connected.

SWU8561.Description: The firmware version selected for rollback does not support the current chassis hardware configuration.
SWU8561.Resolution: Make sure that firmware version selected for rollback is supported for the current hardware configuration, such as I/O modules, PSU modules, and servers. For example, a newer generation PSU may not work with an earlier iDRAC or CMC firmware. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual or CMC or iDRAC Release Notes for details.
SWU8561.Message: Unable to downgrade the firmware version because the current hardware configuration does not support rollback to the earlier firmware version.

SWC8548.Description: The Media Access Control (MAC) addresses cannot be deleted from the pool because they are not present in the MAC address pool.
SWC8548.Message: Unable to delete some of the Media Access Control (MAC) addresses because the MAC addresses are not present in the MAC address pool or used by Boot Identity profile.

FAN0014.Description: The cooling device is not performing optimally. The cooling device may be installed improperly.
FAN0014.Resolution: Remove and re-install the cooling device. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0014.Message: %1 RPM is greater than the upper warning threshold.

LC029.Description: An invalid File Path was specified in the export operation.
LC029.Resolution: Correct the specified file path and try again.

UEFI0071.Description: One or more UEFI network interfaces is not available. The corresponding UEFI network devices are disabled.
UEFI0071.Resolution: Connect the missing network interface card to the system and enable the UEFI network interface in System Setup.
UEFI0071.Message: One or more UEFI network interfaces is not available. The corresponding UEFI network devices are disabled.

RAC068.Description: Both SHA256Password and Plain Password cannot be attempted to set together on Configuration import per user.
RAC068.Resolution: One of either SHA256Password or Plain password can be attempted to be imported for an user.
RAC068.Message: SHA256Password and Plain Password cannot be imported together.

PCI2001.Message: The component at bus %1 device %2 function %3 recovered from a fatal IO error.

USR8500.Description: Multiple login attempts were unsuccessful from the identified IP address. After detecting this error condition, this IP address will be blocked from login for the duration specified in the message.
USR8500.Resolution: Make sure the username and password credentials used are correct, wait for the duration specified in the message and then retry the login.
USR8500.Message: Excessive login failures from %1; blocked for %2 seconds.

OSD49.Description: vFlash cannot be accessed because RIPS mode is enabled.
OSD49.Resolution: Disable the RIPS mode from BIOS or from the iDRAC GUI, and then continue executing the method.
OSD49.Message: Disable RIPS mode to access VFlash.

PWR8569.Description: The requested power cycle operation cannot be performed when the server is not turned on. The server should be already turned on for the power cycle operation to be successful.
PWR8569.Resolution: Turn on the server, if necessary, before requesting a power cycle operation.
PWR8569.Message: Unable to power cycle the server %1 because the server is off.

RAC0148.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about the batteries.
RAC0148.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0148.Message: Unable to retrieve the batteries information. The system is powered off.

LC084.Description: The video log cannot be exported because there are no files in the source folder that can be compressed and exported.
LC084.Resolution: For boot capture, make sure that VirtualConsole.1#BootCaptureSequence attribute is enabled in the DCIM_iDracCardInteger class by running the winrm get WS-Man command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation.
LC084.Message: Unable to export the video log because there are no files in the source folder that can be compressed and exported.

PWR8520.Description: The chassis reset operation was initiated.

BAR026.Description: The configuration is being set for each component.

PSU0907.Resolution: Remove input power at the power supply.
PSU0907.Message: An interlock power down error was corrected for power unit %1.

GMGR0005.Description: The iDRAC with the Service Tag identified in the message has successfully joined the local iDRAC group identified in the message.
GMGR0005.Message: iDRAC %1 successfully joined the local iDRAC Group %2.

PDR96.Description: Security on a secure encrypted disk was disabled.

RAC997.Description: The DHCP for Domain Name cannot be enabled if IPv4 and IPv4 DHCP or IPv6 and IPv6 AutoConfig is disabled.
RAC997.Resolution: Make sure that IPv4 and IPv4 DHCP are enabled, or IPv6 and IPv6 AutoConfig are enabled.
RAC997.Message: The object DNSDomainFromDHCP cannot be enabled.

RAC1169.Description: The RACADM "config" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.
RAC1169.Resolution: Run the RACADM "racadm set" command to configure the iDRAC configuration parameters. For more information on the set command, run the RACADM command "racadm help set".
RAC1169.Message: The RACADM "config" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.

SYS142.Description: The OS driver pack is deleted because of a System Erase operation.
SYS142.Message: The OS driver pack is deleted.

SUP0507.Description: The FTP server setting details are incorrect.
SUP0507.Resolution: Enter the correct FTP server settings details, and retry the operation.
SUP0507.Message: Unable to download the Update Packages from the FTP server.

MEM8000.Description: Errors are being corrected but no longer logged.
MEM8000.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>.
MEM8000.Message: Correctable memory error logging disabled for a memory device at location %1.

SUP0531.Description: The repository location is invalid or the repository does not contain the Update Packages.
SUP0531.Resolution: Enter another repository location that contains the desired Update Packages and retry the operation.
SUP0531.Message: Unable to install the Update Packages.

HWC5014.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
HWC5014.Message: %1 is not functional and is powered off.

PWR8524.Description: The redundancy was lost because the power requirement of the chassis exceeds the current redundant policy.
PWR8524.Resolution: No response action is required. Review the power requirements and determine if more PSUs are needed to restore redundancy.
PWR8524.Message: Redundancy was lost, while Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is enabled.

RAC987.Description: After initiating the firmware update job, the time taken to complete it depends on size of the update file.
RAC987.Resolution: This firmware update job may take several minutes to complete depending on the component or firmware being updated. To view the progress of the job, use the "racadm jobqueue view" command.
RAC987.Message: Firmware update job for %1 is initiated.

CTL57.Description: The controller was reset to factory default configuration settings.
CTL57.Message: The factory default settings were restored on %1.

TMP0105.Message: The system board %1 temperature is within range.

OSD9.Description: Resetting the targeted server using the standard IPMI command has failed.
OSD9.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD9.Message: Failed to reboot the system using an IPMI command.

RAC084.Description: The Clear Transfer Session operation is successfully completed and the corresponding files or folders are deleted on the basis of input value entered.
RAC084.Message: The Clear Transfer Session operation is successfully completed.

PDR103.Description: Cryptographic Erase operation is successfully completed on the physical disk drive identified in the message.
PDR103.Message: Cryptographic Erase operation is successfully completed on %1.

RAC059.Description: When the Network Time Protocol (NTP) feature is enabled, the iDRAC will get time from the configured NTP server. Directly configuration of the iDRAC time is disabled when NTP is enabled.
RAC059.Resolution: Disable Network Time Protocol (NTP) and retry the operation.
RAC059.Message: Unable to configure iDRAC time because Network Time Protocol (NTP) is enabled.

IOID115.Description: The target settings properties of the NIC port identified in the message could not be configured, because either iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is not enabled; or, the network controller is not functioning.
IOID115.Resolution: Make sure that the iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is enabled. Check whether or not the network controller is working.
IOID115.Message: Unable to configure the target settings properties of the %1 Port %2.

RAC1161.Description: Unable to initiate the techsupreport collect operation because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running.
RAC1161.Resolution: Run the command 'racadm get iDRAC.ServiceModule to make sure that iDRAC Service Module is installed and running on the server operation system (OS) and also to verify that the collection of the server OS data is enabled.
RAC1161.Message: Unable to initiate the techsupreport collect operation for the Tech Support Report (TSR) because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running.

SWC8538.Description: The Public Key (PK) SSH Authentication key file delete operation did not complete successfully because the Chassis Management Controller is unable to access the configuration database.
SWC8538.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8538.Message: Unable to delete key for slot %1 of service account, due to problem saving key file.

CPU0700.Description: System BIOS was unable to boot the processor.
CPU0700.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PWR8590.Description: The PCIe Mezzanine card in the slot C1 is absent. Without PCIe Mezzanine cards, the chassis PCIe cards will not be available for servers.
PWR8590.Resolution: Insert a PCIe Mezzanine card in slot C1.
PWR8590.Message: The server-%1 does not have PCIe Mezzanine card in slot C1.

RAC079.Description: The Import File operation cannot be started because an import operation is already in progress.
RAC079.Resolution: Wait till the current process is completed and retry the operation.
RAC079.Message: Unable to start the Import File operation because an import operation is already in progress.

SUP0502.Description: iDRAC is unable generate the inventory file or the inventory file received from iDRAC is faulty. For more information about the failure, see Lifecycle Log.
SUP0502.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2.) Wait for five seconds. 3.) Reconnect the power cord and turn on the system. 4) Press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem continues to persist, update iDRAC firmware to the latest version, and retry the operation. Else, contact the service provider.

SWC1923.Description: The server configuration cannot be modified by using Quick Sync because invalid credentials are entered.
SWC1923.Resolution: Make sure that correct user name and password are entered, and then retry the operation.
SWC1923.Message: Unable to modify the server configuration by using Quick Sync because invalid credentials are entered.

DIS016.Description: Provisioning Server responded to iDRAC IP address change.
DIS016.Message: Response received from Provisioning Server to the notification of iDRAC IP address change.

PWR2006.Message: The OS run-time software initiated a warm reset.

LC086.Description: The Export Video Log operation cannot be completed because of internal issues.
LC086.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart iDRAC by invoking the WS-Man iDRACReset method which is defined in the DCIM_iDRACCardService class , and then retry the operation.
LC086.Message: Unable to complete the Export Video Log operation because of internal issues.

RAC0134.Description: The SD card is not a valid vFlash SD card. The use of non-Dell media prevents the use of some extended capabilities and functions.
RAC0134.Resolution: Insert a valid vFlash SD card.
RAC0134.Message: This operation is unavailable for non-vFlash SD cards.

UEFI0187.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Clock Detection phase.
UEFI0187.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0187.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RFM1022.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.

ISM0011.Description: The server OS could not start the iDRAC Service Module, because the iDRAC Service Module disabled on iDRAC.
ISM0011.Resolution: Enable the iDRAC Service Module on the iDRAC before starting this service on the server OS, and then retry the operation. To enable the module by using iDRAC GUI: Click Network, click OS to iDRAC Pass-through, and then click the USB NIC option. In the OS IP Address box , type an IP address, and then click Apply. To enable the module by using RACADM command, run the following command at the command line interface: racadm set idrac.servicemodule. ServiceModuleEnable enabled.
ISM0011.Message: The server operating system (OS) is unable to start the iDRAC Service Module, because it is set to "disabled" in iDRAC.

BAR079.Description: The collection and export of Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration was not successful.
BAR079.Resolution: Apply the integrated remote access controller firmware, manually set the configuration attributes, and try the operation again.
BAR079.Message: Unable to collect the Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration.

RAC1034.Description: This operation will cause the server to shutdown immediately. This may result in the applications losing data.
RAC1034.Resolution: Before continuing, exit all the programs running on this server, and make sure that there is no inbound and outbound traffic associated with this server. Inability to do so may prevent all the servers in the chassis from accessing the shared-storage devices for up to two minutes. To continue the operation, enter a -f at the end of command "racadm serveraction powerdown -f", and then retry.
RAC1034.Message: This action will ungracefully turn off the server.

MEM8001.Message: Persistent correctable memory error logging enabled for a memory device at location %1.

SRV079.Description: The SupportAssist feature is enabled on iDRAC.
SRV079.Message: The SupportAssist feature is enabled on iDRAC.

RAC942.Description: The system configuration profile import operation is initiated. No other operations can be performed on the system while the system configuration server profile is being imported from the system configuration profile.
RAC942.Resolution: Monitor the job status using "racadm jobqueue view -i <Job ID>".
RAC942.Message: Successfully initiated the import operation. This operation may take several minutes to complete and may cause multiple system restarts while device firmware and configuration are applied.

RAC0753.Description: Reset iDRAC to apply the pending new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset old certificate will be active. A manual reset of iDRAC is needed for the new certificate to take into effect.
RAC0753.Resolution: Click the Reset iDRAC link to reset iDRAC.
RAC0753.Message: Reset iDRAC to apply the pending new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset the old certificate will be active.

CTL94.Description: The controller identified in the message has been changed to operate as a single controller and not as part of a fault tolerant pair.
CTL94.Message: %1 has been successfully changed to operate in single controller mode.

SWC0042.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation.
SWC0042.Resolution: Exit the Import Server Profile wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0042.Message: Unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation.

RED041.Description: The license required to perform the operation identified in the message is expired or is not available.
RED041.Resolution: Install an iDRAC license that supports the following features: Automatic Update or Server Profile Export and Import. After the appropriate license has been installed, retry the operation.
RED041.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was not created because the required license is not available.

SWU8502.Description: The specified Lifecycle Controller operation is successfully submitted and the operation will be executed on the basis of scheduling criteria.
SWU8502.Message: A %1 request was submitted to the Lifecycle Controller on server %2.

BAR086.Description: The system profile import of Lifecycle Controller configuration data has failed.
BAR086.Resolution: If collect system inventory on reboot (CSIOR) is not enabled, enter and exit System Services in USC to update the database, reboot the system and try the operation again. If the error continues, use the field service repair software to repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download all Dell Update Packages for USC, Diagnostics Driver Packs, and device firmware for all host system devices, install all packages and retry the operation.
BAR086.Message: Unable to Restore The Lifecycle Controller Configuration database.

BIOS042.Description: The file identified in the message cannot be imported because the file does not exist in the source directory.
BIOS042.Resolution: Make sure that the file exists in the remote share and retry the operation.
BIOS042.Message: Unable to import the file %1 because the file does not exist in the source directory.

STOR012.Description: One or more of the specified physical disks cannot be used for the operation requested. Physical disk protocol and media type, along with other physical disk characteristics like Secure Encryption and T10 protection, need to match the requirements of the requested operation.
STOR012.Resolution: Make sure the specified physical disk has the appropriate protocol and media type for the requested operation. Specify a different physical disk with a state appropriate for the requested operation and retry the operation.
STOR012.Message: Provided Physical disk not valid for this operation.

UEFI0083.Description: One or more PCI System errors (SERR) have occurred.
UEFI0083.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCI device that caused the SERR. Update the identified device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0083.Message: One or more PCI System errors (SERR) have occurred.

SYS058.Description: Running Lifecycle Controller Automated Task Execution application in Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) environment to apply configuration changes.

RED043.Description: The operation identified in the message is currently disabled.
RED043.Resolution: Enable the operation identified in the message and retry the operation. To enable the Automatic Server Profile Backup operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoBackup 1". To enable the Automatic Update operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoUpdate 1".
RED043.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was not created because the operation type is disabled.

HWC4018.Description: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between the components identified in the message.
HWC4018.Message: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between %1%2 and %3%4.

PWR8517.Description: Chassis power state transition did not complete successfully. This may be due to one of the following: 1) Unable to turn off one or more servers, 2) A firmware update may be in progress.
