PWR8517.Resolution: Check the tracelog for more information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8517.Message: Unable to turn off chassis power.

SWC0293.Description: The specified object is not present in the iDRAC.
SWC0293.Message: The specified object is not recognized by iDRAC.

RAC947.Description: The value used for the object set operation is invalid.
RAC947.Resolution: Make sure to specify the value depending on the type of object. For more information, see RACADM help.

SRV080.Description: The SupportAssist feature is disabled on iDRAC.
SRV080.Message: The SupportAssist feature is disabled on iDRAC.

UEFI0042.Description: Unable to enable the TXT feature because Trusted Platform Module (TPM) configuration is invalid.
UEFI0042.Resolution: Go to System Setup > System Security page, select the "On with pre-boot measurement" option for TPM Security, and click the "Activate" option under TPM command. Restart the system, go to System Setup > System Security page, and then enable TXT.
UEFI0042.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because Trusted Platform Module (TPM) configuration is invalid.

RAC0282.Description: This is the number of login failures attempted from an IP address before further login attempts are rejected from that address. The default value is 10.
RAC0282.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Blocking Fail Count. Expected range: 2-16.
RAC0282.Message: IP Blocking Fail Count is invalid. Expected range: 2-16.

RFL2004.Description: The SD card module is installed but improperly configured or failed to initialize.
RFL2004.Resolution: Reinstall the SD module and remove and reinstall SD cards.
RFL2004.Message: Failure detected on Internal Dual SD Module %1.

SUP0131.Message: FTP firmware update has been initiated. This update process may take several minutes to complete.

RAC0723.Description: The Chassis Management Controller firmware version identified in the message is earlier than the version required to support the server.
RAC0723.Resolution: Update the Chassis Management Controller firmware to the required version identified in the message.
RAC0723.Message: The firmware version %1 of the Chassis Management Controller is earlier than the required version %1.

SUP015.Description: One of the parameters specified received a NULL value that prevented the action from completing.
SUP015.Resolution: Correct the parameter value and retry the command.
SUP015.Message: Input parameters values should not be NULL.

OSD48.Description: ISO Images of more than 4GB are not supported and cannot be copied to VFlash.
OSD48.Resolution: Use an ISO that is smaller than 4GB.
OSD48.Message: ISO Images of more than 4GB not supported.

RED013.Description: The DUP specified is not compatible with the target device.
RED013.Resolution: Download and use the DUP that matches the device being targeted.
RED013.Message: The DUP specified is not compatible with the target device.

BIOS024.Description: The operation cannot run as the attribute value cannot be modified.
BIOS024.Resolution: For more information on the attribute, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
BIOS024.Message: The set operation did not complete successfully as the attribute is read-only.

SWC1920.Description: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is enabled.
SWC1920.Message: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is enabled.

UEFI0153.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology 2.0 (DPAT 2.0) Enterprise license. Related DPAT 2.0 BIOS settings will be lost if the license is not found in three consecutive reboots.
UEFI0153.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0153.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license. Related DPAT BIOS settings will be lost if the license is not found in three consecutive reboots.

LIC007.Description: Each License Manager object has a unique identifier by which it may be accessed. If the user supplied identifier is outside the acceptable range or the object no longer exists in the system, then this error is returned. Most common identifiers are the license entitlement identifier, the device Fully Qualified Device Descriptor, or the import transaction identifier assigned to a license when imported.
LIC007.Resolution: Re-issue this command with correct License Manager object identifier.
LIC007.Message: Invalid entry: Object does not exist or cannot be found.

RAC0905.Description: Unable to obtain the USC version details.
RAC0905.Message: Failed to get the USC version details.

PWR2264.Description: The Intel Management Engine has recovered the ability to utilize the PECI over DMI facility.
PWR2264.Resolution: If the PWR2262 "internal system error" was logged within the previous 30 seconds, ignore the message. No response action required.
PWR2264.Message: The Intel Management Engine has reported normal system operation.

RAC1219.Description: The Secure Boot certificate data cannot be exported to remote share because of insufficient storage space.
RAC1219.Resolution: Make sure that the remote share has sufficient storage space and retry the operation.
RAC1219.Message: Unable to export the Secure Boot certificate data to remote share because of insufficient storage space.

OSD56.Description: An ISO is already connected using Remote File Share (RFS). The connection might have been initiated from iDRAC GUI, racadm, or Remote Services API.
OSD56.Resolution: Disconnect the Remote File Share (RFS) using iDRAC GUI, racadm, or Remote Services API and then retry the operation to connect the ISO again.
OSD56.Message: An ISO is already connected using Remote File Share (RFS).

CTL99.Description: The security key assigned to the controller identified in the message is deleted.
CTL99.Message: Security key assigned to %1 is deleted.

PWR8589.Description: The PCIe Mezzanine card in the slot B1 is absent. Without PCIe Mezzanine cards, the chassis PCIe cards will not be available for servers.
PWR8589.Resolution: Insert a PCIe Mezzanine card in slot B1.
PWR8589.Message: The server-%1 does not have PCIe Mezzanine card in slot B1.

PWR223.Description: Cannot perform a 110V AC operation because the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is enabled.
PWR223.Resolution: Disable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature and retry the operation.
PWR223.Message: Cannot perform a 110V AC operation because the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is enabled.

PWR8674.Description: Unable to change the value of the Allow 110 VAC Operation property because it is not supported in NEBS configuration PWR or PSU.
PWR8674.Message: Unable to change the value of Allow 110 VAC Operation property because it is not supported in NEBS configuration PWR or PSU.

SYS403.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because the resource identified in the message does not exist.
SYS403.Resolution: Enter the correct resource and retry the operation. For information about valid resource, see the Redfish Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS403.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the resource %1 entered in not found.

RAC0227.Description: The SD card is not present, or communication with the SD card is lost. This could result in reduced functionality and capabilities.
RAC0227.Resolution: This error may occur because: 1. Make sure the SD card is seated correctly. 2. The SD card is invalid. Insert a valid SD card of size greater than 256MB and try again.
RAC0227.Message: SD card is not detected: Insert an SD Card of size greater than 256MB.

PST0133.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the DMA controller during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 85).

SUP0108.Description: The firmware update is in progress and another update cannot be done.
SUP0108.Resolution: Wait for the update operation to conclude and then re-try.
SUP0108.Message: A firmware update operation is already in progress.

GMGR0062.Description: The job cannot be run because invalid user credentials are entered.
GMGR0062.Resolution: Enter valid credentials and retry the operation.
GMGR0062.Message: Unable to run the job because invalid user credentials are entered.

SRV122.Description: The operation cannot be started because the SupportAssist Host OS Proxy Configured setting is not enabled in iDRAC.
SRV122.Resolution: Enable the SupportAssist Host OS Proxy Configured setting in iDRAC, and then retry the operation. To enable the SupportAssist Host OS Proxy Configured setting by using the RACADM command line interface, enter "racadm set idrac.supportassist.HostOSProxyConfigured Yes".
SRV122.Message: Unable to start the operation because the SupportAssist Host OS Proxy Configured setting is not enabled in iDRAC.

GMGR0030.Description: The passcode for joining iDRAC local group is successfully changed.
GMGR0030.Message: The iDRAC local group passcode is successfully changed.

CTL81.Description: The security key assigned to the controller identified in the message is modified.
CTL81.Message: Security key assigned to %1 is modified.

TMP0119.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0119.Message: The system inlet temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

HWC1104.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message that is inserted in the slot identified in the message is not supported by the chassis or the current CMC firmware version.
HWC1104.Resolution: Make sure that the peripheral sled identified in the message is supported by the chassis and the CMC firmware. For information about the supported sleds and firmware versions, see the System Manual available at the support site.
HWC1104.Message: The %1 installed in slot %2 is not supported by the chassis.

SWC8510.Description: Unable to communicate with the iDRAC of the requested Server.
SWC8510.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required. The Lifecycle log in the server may have additional information about the inability of the iDRAC to apply Profile settings.
SWC8510.Message: Unable to apply %1 Profile to requested Server(s)

SWU8521.Description: The firmware update operation of iDRAC identified in the message was stopped. The selected Image file is not compatible with the server hardware.
SWU8521.Resolution: Make sure that the Image file is compatible with the server hardware, and then retry the operation.
SWU8521.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 was stopped. The selected Image file is not compatible with the server hardware.

PWR2203.Message: The system is sleeping with system hardware and processor context lost.

RAC0268.Description: The NIC is disabled. This may adversely affect the current operation, and might not allow subsequent GUI interactions to this NIC.
RAC0268.Resolution: Enable the NIC before performing the operation.

CTL59.Description: There may be a problem with the enclosure. Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. To verify the health of the enclosure, select the enclosure object in the tree view. The Health sub-tab displays a red X or yellow exclamation point for enclosure components that are failed or degraded. See the enclosure documentation for more information.
CTL59.Resolution: There may be a problem with the enclosure. Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. To verify the health of the enclosure, select the enclosure object in the tree view. The Health sub-tab displays a red X or yellow exclamation mark for enclosure components that are failed or degraded. See the enclosure documentation for more information.

SRV131.Description: The SupportAssist operation cannot be completed because of an unknown error in iDRAC.
SRV131.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm racreset".
SRV131.Message: Unable to complete the SupportAssist operation because of an unknown error in iDRAC.

SYS187.Description: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.
SYS187.Resolution: Retry the operation after the server has finished starting and POST has completed.
SYS187.Message: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.

RAC0151.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about removable flash media.
RAC0151.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0151.Message: Unable to retrieve the removable flash media information. The system is powered off.

SUP0529.Description: The selected USB drive is disconnected.
SUP0529.Resolution: Make sure the USB drive is connected and retry the operation.

RAC0280.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0280.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Range Address. Expected range: 0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255.
RAC0280.Message: The IP Range Address is invalid. Expected range: 0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255.

STOR2.Description: A SCSI device experienced an error, but may have recovered.

RAC1039.Description: The subcommand entered is not supported on the specified server.
RAC1039.Message: The subcommand entered is not supported on the specified server.

JCP015.Description: The job is currently executing and cannot be deleted. The job needs to finish running, whether successful or not, before it can be deleted.
JCP015.Resolution: Wait for the job to have a completed job status. Retry the operation.
JCP015.Message: A running job cannot be deleted.

STOR8.Description: High Availability RAID is not supported by this firmware release. This event may occur during the upgrade process.
STOR8.Message: Detected two RAID controllers in integrated slots. This configuration is not currently supported and the second controller will not be powered on.

PST0208.Description: System BIOS has halted and is unable to continue.
PST0208.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) If new hardware has been added, remove the new hardware and restart the server, 2) Turn server off and back on using the power button, or 3) Remove and reapply server input power. If the problem persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

BAT1029.Description: The controller battery cannot recharge. The battery may have already recharged the maximum number of times or the battery charger may not be working.
BAT1029.Message: The battery on %1 can no longer recharge.

VFL0715.Resolution: Contact the administrator for the required permissions and try again.
VFL0715.Message: Error occurred while initializing the SD Card due to insufficient permission.

PWR8668.Description: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has initiated the process of resetting iKVM.
PWR8668.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has initiated the process of resetting iKVM.

SWU8522.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful.
SWU8522.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the original source, and then retry the operation.
SWU8522.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC on the server in %1 firmware: ErrorCode=0x%2.

RAC985.Description: The object "cfgServerBootOnce" cannot be configured if the object "cfgServerFirstBootDevice" is set to F10, F11, or BIOS value.
RAC985.Resolution: Change the value of the object "cfgServerFirstBootDevice" using the RACADM command "racadm config -g cfgServerInfo -o cfgServerFirstBootDevice<value other than F10, F11, and BIOS>", and retry configuring the object "cfgServerBootOnce".
RAC985.Message: Unable to configure the cfgServerBootOnce object.

RAC0279.Description: An invalid IPMI encryption key was entered.
RAC0279.Resolution: Enter a valid encryption key of up to 40 characters. Odd number of characters and blank spaces are not allowed.
RAC0279.Message: Invalid Encryption Key. Expected format: 0 to 40 characters, even number of characters and no blank spaces are allowed.

SYS136.Description: An issue was encountered while communicating with iDRAC Service Module (iSM) present on the operating system.
SYS136.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Restart the iDRAC Module Service on the OS and retry the operation. 2) Stop iDRAC Service Module Service on the OS and try manually executing the OS Collector application .
SYS136.Message: An issue was encountered while communicating with iDRAC Service Module (iSM) present on the operating system.

RFL2009.Description: The Internal Dual SD Card redundancy feature was enabled. The SD card identified in the message is enabled.
RFL2009.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is enabled.

FAN906.Description: Changes are not made to the current settings.
FAN906.Resolution: Make sure that changes are made to the settings and retry the operation.
FAN906.Message: Changes are not made to the current settings.

RAC003.Description: One or more required parameters for the method are missing.
RAC003.Resolution: Refer to the profile document and provide the required parameters.

BAT0017.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.

PCI3015.Message: The component at slot %1 recovered from a non-fatal PCIe error.

OSD10.Description: Installation for the selected operating system is not supported. Make sure that the correct operating system name was entered.
OSD10.Resolution: Recheck the operating system name with the output of GetDriverPackInfo().
OSD10.Message: Installation not supported for the selected operating system.

BAR102.Description: Unable to import license data from the backup Server Profile.
BAR102.Resolution: Refer to iDRAC User Guide documentation license installation instructions and retry the operation.

NIC507.Description: For the requested operation, enable the NIC to get the NIC details.
NIC507.Resolution: Check if the NIC is disabled. If disabled, enable the NIC.
NIC507.Message: Unable to determine current NIC state.

STOR042.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because the attribute value specified is not supported in the current configuration.
STOR042.Resolution: Specify a value for the attribute identified in the message by using one of the possible values currently available for that attribute.

VF014.Description: Enabling vFlash was not successful because the vFlash feature is not disabled.
VF014.Resolution: The vFlash is enabled and any attempt to enable it will not be successful.

UEFI0231.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Configuration Read phase.
UEFI0231.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0231.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RED004.Description: The job cannot be run because of an unknown issue.
RED004.Resolution: Check the uniform resource identifier (URI), target path and make sure the repository server is available.
RED004.Message: The job cannot be run because of an unknown issue.

SUP0522.Description: Write protection is enabled for the BIOS image and local BIOS update is disabled.
SUP0522.Resolution: To flash the BIOS locally, enable local BIOS update by selecting System Setup.
SUP0522.Message: Unable to update the BIOS firmware because write protection is enabled.

HWC5012.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
HWC5012.Message: On screen display (OSCAR) is not functional for the %1.

PDR2.Description: This message is generated if a physical disk does not have enough space to do a copyback operation.
PDR2.Resolution: Replace the physical disk with a larger physical disk, and then restart the copyback operation.
PDR2.Message: Insufficient space available on %1 to perform a copyback operation.

SWC8521.Description: Unable to modify the timeout for the session.
SWC8521.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have chassis config administration privilege, 2) The session timeout given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8521.Message: Unable to modify timeout for session: %1: %2-%3

SWU8546.Description: The firmware update operation of the Standby CMC was not successful.
SWU8546.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware.

SRV119.Description: The SupportAssist operation cannot be started because the Lifecycle Controller is in recovery mode.
SRV119.Resolution: Clear the Lifecycle Controller Recovery mode and retry the operation. To clear the Recovery mode: 1) Restart the server. When the company logo is displayed, press F2. 2) On the iDRAC Settings Page, select Lifecycle Controller Settings. 3) Update the Lifecycle Controller Setting to Enabled.
SRV119.Message: Unable to start the SupportAssist operation because the Lifecycle Controller is in recovery mode.

LIC205.Description: The License Manager sets a maximum time period that its database may be locked. If that timeout exceeds, it releases the lock conditions and reports the error. The user must assume that the Lifecycle Controller backup or restore operation failed and should repeat the operation.
LIC205.Resolution: Repeat the backup or restore operation.
LIC205.Message: License Manager database lock timeout has been exceeded.

BAR119.Description: The Backup operation is currently validating the ability to access the HTTP destination.
BAR119.Message: The Backup operation is currently validating the ability to access the HTTP destination.

SWC0065.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to copy the OS drivers from the OS driver pack.
SWC0065.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following:1) Update the system with the latest operating system driver packs using the Firmware Update feature and retry the operation. 2) Reboot the system, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.
SWC0065.Message: Unable to retrieve the drivers for the selected operating system.

FCD8531.Description: The CMC is not responding. The chassis has the factory-programmed service tag.
FCD8531.Message: Unable to activate the %1. The chassis service tag is unavailable.

CMC8538.Description: The length of the CMC firmware version to be sent in the message from local CMC to peer CMC is too long. Under these conditions, CMC version in the message is displayed as 1.0.
CMC8538.Message: Firmware version string is too long.

SYS056.Description: Waiting for the system to shut down before applying configuration changes.
SYS056.Message: Waiting for the system to shut down.

OSD35.Description: Lifecycle Controller is disabled on the system, so none of the remote operating system deployment commands will work. Make sure Lifecycle Controller is enabled before running any command.
OSD35.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

FAN902.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode cannot be set because required power is not available.
FAN902.Resolution: Add PSUs with higher power capability or remove Chassis components such as I/O Modules or servers until the power requirements have been lowered enough to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode, and then retry the operation.
FAN902.Message: Cannot enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode because sufficient power is not available.

UEFI0291.Description: The Processor Embedded Memory mode cannot be enabled because no on-package memory was detected.
UEFI0291.Resolution: Replace the processor to make sure that the Processor Embedded Memory mode is supported, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0291.Message: Unable to configure the requested Processor Embedded Memory mode because no on-package memory was detected.

VF026.Description: This partition index has already been used.
VF026.Resolution: This partition index has already been used. Try a different index.

RAC019.Description: The submitted job did not complete successfully.
RAC019.Resolution: Examine source of the errors by inspecting the results from the job execution, and after resolving the issues, retry the operation. Job results can be retrieved from the Lifecycle Log or the WSMan API.

DH005.Resolution: Close other iDRAC sessions and activities. Try again.
DH005.Message: CA Cert is corrupted, expired, or does not have signing privileges.

SUP1907.Resolution: Reacquire the image from the original source and retry the operation.

PDR35.Description: The only physical disk available to be assigned as a hot spare is using SATA technology. The physical disks in the virtual disk are using SAS technology. Because of this difference in technology, the hot spare cannot rebuild data if one of the physical disks in the virtual disk fails.
PDR35.Resolution: Add a SAS disk that is large enough to be used as the hot spare and assign the new disk as a hot spare.
PDR35.Message: The only hot spare available is a SATA disk %1.

UEFI0023.Description: The End of POST message could not be sent to the Management Engine because the Management Engine is not responding.
UEFI0023.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0023.Message: BIOS is unable to send the End of POST message to Management Engine because the Management Engine is not responding.

RAC1024.Description: The pending value is applied during the next reboot of system.
RAC1024.Resolution: Verify the job status using "racadm jobqueue view -i JID_xxxxx" command.

STOR083.Description: The Physical Disk(s) specified are too small to create a Virtual Disk of the requested size.
STOR083.Resolution: Specify Physical Disk FQDD IDs of physical disk drive(s) that have a larger disk space, and retry the operation.
STOR083.Message: The Physical Disk(s) specified are too small to create a Virtual Disk of the requested size.

PDR106.Description: A physical disk identified in the hot-spare that was assigned as a hot spare has been un-assigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically by the storage management software. When one of the disks in a virtual disk fails, data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, The hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. In this situation, assigning a new hot spare to maintain data protection in recommended.
PDR106.Resolution: No response action is required. Assigning a new dedicated hot spare to the virtual disk is recommended.
PDR106.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is unassigned as a dedicated hot-spare.

PST0134.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the interrupt controller during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 86).
PST0134.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PSU8506.Description: When the Server Power Management mode is enabled the Power cap cannot be set.
PSU8506.Resolution: To enable the ability to set the power cap, switch to external Power Management and disable the Server Based Management Mode in the CMC Web interface.
PSU8506.Message: Unable to change power cap because Server Based Power Management Mode is enabled.

SEC0005.Description: A removable component may have been tampered with, or installed incorrectly, or does not meet system requirements.
SEC0005.Resolution: Check removable hardware components for correct installation. Review installation documentation.

ENC22.Description: The enclosure has a bad sensor. The enclosure sensors monitor the fan speeds, temperature probes, and so on.
ENC22.Resolution: Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information.

PWR8666.Description: The iKVM power cycle operation is initiated.
PWR8666.Message: The iKVM power cycle operation is initiated.

CMC8505.Description: IPv4 and IPv6 are disabled on the specified server and the CMC is unable to display the link to launch iDRAC web interface.
CMC8505.Resolution: Enable IPv4 or IPv6 for the specified server using the CMC command line or CMC Web GUI interface, so that the link to launch iDRAC is displayed on the CMC Web interface. To enable the NIC for DHCP using RACADM, enter "racadm setniccfg -m server-<slot number> -d" where <slot number> is the server identified in the message. To enable the NIC using the Web interface, click Server Overview > select the identified server, go to Setup > select the Enable IPv4 check box and/or the Enable IPv6 check box.
CMC8505.Message: Unable to access server: %1 because both IPv4 and IPv6 are disabled. NIC Enabled = %2.

AMP0307.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0307.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is less than the lower critical threshold.

IOV105.Description: An error by the Chassis Infrastructure slot management detected an error which may prevent the physical assignment/unassignment or power off of a slot. The errors may be caused by PCIE training timeouts, false hot plug signals, or installation of an unsupported PCIe adapter card. For a list of supported PCIe adapter cards contact your service provider.
IOV105.Resolution: Make sure that supported adapters are used and installed correctly in the PCIe slot.
IOV105.Message: Unable to manage PCIE adapter %1 located in %2 %3.

SEL0006.Description: This message appears when all event logging has been disabled by the user. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 03h).

SWU8529.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred to the target.
SWU8529.Resolution: Make sure that the iKVM firmware Image file is available at the specified location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8529.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware, because the Image file was not transferred to the iKVM target.

SWC0006.Description: The view As Shipped hardware inventory operation encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0006.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0006.Message: Unable to display the As Shipped hardware inventory.

PWR8655.Description: CMC could not successfully turn on the component identified in the message, because of insufficient power available.
PWR8655.Resolution: Make sure there is sufficient power available, and then retry the operation. To view the available power, on the CMC Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. The available power is displayed in the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field. To increase available power, add more PSUs or remove unused components from the Chassis.
PWR8655.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the component %1-%2 because of insufficient power. The minimum required power is %3 AC Watts, but only %4 AC Watts is available.

CTL4.Description: You have disabled the controller alarm. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

GMGR0049.Description: The Discovered Servers are not detected in the current network configuration.
GMGR0049.Message: The Discovered Servers are not detected in the current network configuration.

CTL114.Description: The encryption key for the controller identified in the message matches with its peer.
CTL114.Message: The encryption key of %1 matches with its peer controller.

OSD43.Description: vFlash is not present on the server.
OSD43.Resolution: Insert a Dell-licensed vFlash and then retry this command.

RED084.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because of an issue in the communication between iDRAC and CMC.
RED084.Resolution: Verify the status of CMC by accessing the CMC and making sure it is functioning and responding and then retry the operation. For more information about troubleshooting a CMC issue, see the CMC User Manual. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RED084.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware because of an issue in the network communication between iDRAC and CMC.

CMC8555.Description: An internal memory error occurred affecting the configuration database and CMC has initiated a failover . If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8555.Message: An internal memory error has occurred and a failover condition is detected.

MEM1004.Message: Memory device at location %1 is powered off.

UEFI0068.Description: The mezzanine card configuration used is not supported on this Chassis. Server modules used in different Chassis may require cards with different configuration properties. For more information, contact your service provider.
UEFI0068.Resolution: Make sure that a supported mezzanine card is used and retry the operation. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual of the Chassis available at the support site.
UEFI0068.Message: The mezzanine card configuration used is not supported on this Chassis.

RAC0618.Description: The data entered caused an error while processing the request.
RAC0618.Resolution: Make sure to enter the correct data and retry the operation.

UEFI0170.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because of an attempt to simultaneously configure incompatible A7 mode and Target Address Decode (TAD) 3-way interleave during memory initialization.
UEFI0170.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0170.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

VRM0010.Description: The virtual media could not be disconnected. Possible reason is that it might be in use.
VRM0010.Message: Unable to disconnect Virtual Media devices.

STOR0101.Description: No RAID controller data to display. The system is powered off, no RAID controller is present in the system, or the RAID controller is not connected to the system.
STOR0101.Resolution: Check if the server has power, RAID controller is available, and that a RAID controller is connected to the system.

CPU0801.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0801.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SWU8547.Description: The firmware update operation of Standby CMC was not successful. The firmware image could not be transferred.
SWU8547.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8547.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware. The Image transfer process was not successful.

RED061.Description: The job is successfully scheduled. The job will automatically start at the specified start time.

UEFI0025.Description: The Management Engine firmware cannot be initialized. The BIOS will reset the system to retry the initialization process.
UEFI0025.Resolution: Wait for the BIOS to reset the system and reinitialize the Management Engine. If the issue persists, turn off the input power to the system and turn on again.
UEFI0025.Message: Unable to initialize Management Engine firmware.

RRDU0002.Description: Either one of the SD card or both the SD cards are not functioning properly.
RRDU0002.Message: Internal Dual SD Module redundancy is lost.

RED046.Description: The operation identified in the message was disabled and the iDRAC was unable to create the next job in the sequence.
RED046.Resolution: Enable the operation identified in the message and retry the operation. To enable the Automatic Server Profile Backup operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoBackup 1". To enable the Automatic Update operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoUpdate 1".
RED046.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was unable to create a job because the task type is now disabled.

SYS298.Description: The import operation cannot be started either because the Server Configuration Profile file is not available on the USB drive, or because the USB drive has more than one compressed file.
SYS298.Resolution: Make sure of the following and retry the operation: 1) The correct Server Configuration Profile file is available on the USB drive. 2) Only one compressed file is stored on the USB drive, if stored in a compressed file.
SYS298.Message: Unable to start the import operation either because the Server Configuration Profile file is not available on the USB drive, or because the USB drive has more than one compressed file.

RAC085.Description: The files are imported in chunks. When the last chunk is transferred, the CRC must be entered. However, if the CRC is incorrect, all the previous chunks imported are deleted and the import operation must be tried again.
RAC085.Resolution: Make sure that the correct CRC checksum is entered by using MD5 algorithm, and then retry the operation.
RAC085.Message: Unable to complete the Import File operation because an invalid Cycle Redundancy Check (CRC) checksum parameter is entered.

OSE1011.Resolution: Check system event logs for additional exception information. Power down the system and attempt to boot again.

OSD73.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'HashValue' is missing.
OSD73.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "HashValue" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD73.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'HashValue' is missing.

RAC991.Description: The "jobqueue" command cannot be run, because the existing update jobs are transitioning to one of these states: "New", "Downloading", or "Running".
RAC991.Resolution: Wait until the existing update jobs are completed before retrying the operation. To monitor the status of the existing jobs, use the "racadm jobqueue view" command.

VLT0226.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0226.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0226.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

RAC0147.Description: Firmware rollback image is missing or is corrupt.

HWC8501.Description: The operation could not successfully completed because of an issue with the I/O panel cable.
HWC8501.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Connect the I/O panel cable properly 2) Replace the I/O panel cable.
HWC8501.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of an issue with the I/O panel cable.

LIC018.Description: The license is already imported on the system and does not need to be reimported.

PDR40.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR40.Message: The blink operation has ceased on %1.

SWC0261.Description: The option requested is not available on the interface being used.
SWC0261.Resolution: Refer to the help to get the list of commands/options valid for the interface.
SWC0261.Message: The specified option is not supported with the interface being used.

SYS030.Description: Collecting the data required for component configuration.

VF018.Description: The specified partition index is not valid for the command.

USR0005.Description: Login failed from UserID: IP Address.
USR0005.Resolution: Contact the iDRAC administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct.

BIOS027.Description: The attribute identified in the message cannot be set, because the password is currently being reset by using plain text. The BIOS password cannot be simultaneously configured by using plain text and a hash.
BIOS027.Resolution: Wait until the current password configuration process is completed, and then retry the operation.
BIOS027.Message: Unable to change the BIOS password because the password is currently being configured using plain text. Unable to set the attribute %1.

BAR100.Description: An error occurred accessing license data. Cannot collect license data to copy to Server Profile backup file.
BAR100.Resolution: Refer to License Management documentation for re-installation of license(s) instructions and retry the operation.

HWC0018.Description: The necessary drivers cannot be loaded because of internal issues between iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller.
HWC0018.Resolution: Issue is because of an internal error. To resolve the issue:1) Turn off the server and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for 10 seconds, reconnect the power cord, turn on the server, and retry starting Lifecycle Controller by pressing F10 when the company logo is displayed. 3) If the issue persists, update iDRAC firmware to the latest version, and then retry the operation. Else, contact your service provider.
HWC0018.Message: Unable to load the necessary drivers because of internal issues between iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller %1.

PCI3030.Description: New PCI card(s) have been detected in the system that may require additional airflow. Fan speeds may have changed to add additional cooling to the cards.
PCI3030.Resolution: If the automatic cooling response is insufficient, additional cooling can be added by one of the following methods. 1) From iDRAC Web GUI, click Cooling -> Configure Fans -> PCIe Airflow Settings, then select Custom option for that PCIe slot and define desired LFM value. 2) For RACADM commands run "racadm help system.PcieSlotLFM". If automatic cooling response is above desired levels, this response can be turned off in most cases and/or a different LFM target can be set using PCIe Airflow Settings options in iDRAC GUI or Racadm. See iDRAC User Guide for more details by searching for "cooling" . Changing default fan response to PCIe cards should be done in alignment with vendor specification for PCIe cooling needs of the cards present in the system.
PCI3030.Message: New PCI card(s) have been detected in the system. Fan speeds may have changed to add additional cooling to the cards.

ISM0029.Description: Unable to complete the iDRAC Hard Reset operation because BIOS on the server does not support this feature.
ISM0029.Resolution: Install the required BIOS version and retry the operation. To know about the recommended BIOS version, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
ISM0029.Message: Unable to complete the iDRAC Hard Reset operation because BIOS on the server does not support this feature.

RAC0612.Description: Cancelling the firmware update operation will cancel all firmware updates selected and delete all uploaded firmware files.
RAC0612.Resolution: Select Yes to cancel the firmware update operation and delete all uploaded firmware files. Select No to dismiss the message and continue the firmware update operation.
RAC0612.Message: Cancelling the firmware update operation will delete all the uploaded firmware files. Do you want to continue?

PST0132.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with CMOS memory during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception Code 84).
PST0132.Resolution: Check system event log for CMOS battery exceptions. Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

STOR0507.Description: The RAID controller does not have sufficient number of initialized physical disks or adequate disk space to create the requested virtual disk.
STOR0507.Resolution: Connect additional physical disks to the RAID controller, initialize the physical disks, and retry the operation. To initialize the physical disks, reboot the system and select Option ROM during system startup.
STOR0507.Message: Insufficient physical disk space on selected RAID controller.

VDR46.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC0755.Description: The selected value is not supported on this server.
RAC0755.Resolution: Retry the operation with another value.
RAC0755.Message: The selected value is not supported on this server.

RAC0303.Description: This error message is displayed when Virtual Console feature is unavailable.
RAC0303.Resolution: Enable Virtual Console and ask the administrator to grant Access Virtual Console privilege.
RAC0303.Message: Virtual Console is disabled or you do not have the Access Virtual Console privilege.

PWR2256.Description: The chassis infrastructure components are being initialized and are not ready to grant power on permission to the servers.
PWR2256.Resolution: Wait until the chassis infrastructure has been initialized and then retry the operation. To check that the infrastructure is initialized, using the RACADM command line utility run the command "racadm getmodinfo" and check that the "pwrstate" field is on for the chassis component.
PWR2256.Message: Unable to allocate power for servers to turn on because the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is initializing chassis infrastructure components.

SWC9010.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate Import operation is successfully scheduled.
SWC9010.Resolution: Restart the host server for the changes to take effect.
SWC9010.Message: The SecureBoot Certificate Import operation is successfully scheduled. Restart the host server for the changes to take effect.

SWC1903.Description: RAC SSL Certificate has been changed.
SWC1903.Message: RAC SSL Certificate has been changed.

RAC1148.Description: The Integrated Service Module (ISM) Installer is successfully made available to the host system.
RAC1148.Resolution: Boot into the host operating system to check for the availability of Integrated Service Module (ISM) Installer.
RAC1148.Message: The Integrated Service Module (ISM) Installer is successfully made available to the host system.

RAC1045.Description: Individual component firmware updates may occur frequently and cause changes to the catalog on ftp.dell.com. Specifying ftp.dell.com as the catalog source for the Automatic Update feature may result in frequent system firmware updates.
RAC1045.Resolution: Creating a custom repository using the Repository Manager tool allows control of the frequency of component firmware updates.
RAC1045.Message: Specifying ftp.dell.comas the catalog source for the Automatic Update feature may result in frequent system firmware updates because the catalog on ftp.dell.comchanges often.

TMP0116.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0116.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0116.Message: The %1 temperature is outside of range.

VF015.Description: Disabling vFlash was not successful because the vFlash feature is not enabled.
VF015.Resolution: The vFlash is disabled and an attempts to disable it will not be successful.

VFL0721.Description: The SD card Initialization did not complete within the maximum process allotted time.
VFL0721.Message: Error occurred while initializing the SD Card due to a timeout.

RAC0113.Description: Data entered is not an integer value in the valid range of numbers.
RAC0113.Resolution: Enter a Remote Syslog Port number. Expected range: [1-65535 or 0x1-0xFFFF].
RAC0113.Message: Remote Syslog Port value is invalid: Valid range is 1-65535 or 0x1-0xFFFF.

SYS404.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because the If-Match request header is missing.
SYS404.Resolution: Make sure that the If-Match request header is entered and retry the operation. For information about the necessary headers, see the Redfish specification and Redfish Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS404.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the If-Match request header is missing.

RAC0301.Description: User will be unable to connect to Remote File Share.
RAC0301.Resolution: Make sure proper connectivity exists between the client and the remote file share before using this feature.
RAC0301.Message: Remote File Share connection is unavailable. Check the settings and try again.

VDR36.Description: Virtual disk initialization is in-progress. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

FAN0013.Description: The cooling device is not performing optimally. The cooling device may be installed improperly.
FAN0013.Resolution: Remove and re-install the cooling device. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0013.Message: %1 RPM is less than the lower critical threshold.

CTL89.Description: The peer controller is no longer active in this fault tolerant pair. This can be a temporary situation.
CTL89.Resolution: Check the chassis log for issues with the peer controller. If the peer controller does not resume normal operations after 5 minutes contact your service provider.
CTL89.Message: %1 is no longer fault tolerant because the peer controller is not available.

GMGR0075.Description: Some Group members are offline. Changing a group passcode when some group members are offline results in the creation of duplicate groups.
GMGR0075.Resolution: Do one or all of the following and retry the operation: 1) Resolve all the connectivity issues in the group, and then change the group passcode. 2) Remove the offline group members, and then change the group password.
GMGR0075.Message: Some Group members are offline. Changing the group passcode when some group members are offline results in the creation of duplicate groups. Do you want to continue?

CTL112.Description: The Loadbalance Mode of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL112.Message: The Loadbalance Mode of %1 is set to %2.

SYS169.Description: The iDRAC Service Module installed on the operating system is not up to date and does not support the Technical Support Report.
SYS169.Resolution: Make sure the operating system (OS) is a supported OS for the Technical Support Report feature and the latest iDRAC Service Module software is installed on the OS.
SYS169.Message: The iDRAC Service Module installed on the operating system is not up to date and does not support the Technical Support Report feature.

SWC0102.Description: The option requested is not available on the interface being used.
SWC0102.Resolution: Refer to the help to get the list of options valid for the interface.
SWC0102.Message: The -m option is not supported by the interface being used.

PWR202.Description: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature forces servers in to a low-power and limited-performance mode, and then disables the ability to turn on additional servers.
PWR202.Message: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature forces servers in to a low-power and limited-performance mode, and then disables the ability to turn on additional servers.

SYS084.Description: Export of ePSA Diagnostics results did not complete successfully because the iDRAC internal storage containing the results could not be accessed.
SYS084.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Delete all jobs, 2) Reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and 3) Retry the operation.
SYS084.Message: Export of ePSA Diagnostics results did not complete successfully because the iDRAC internal storage containing the results could not be accessed.

SRV134.Description: The SupportAssist Collection requested by the server Operating System (OS) user identified in the message is successfully created.
SRV134.Message: The SupportAssist Collection requested by the server Operating System (OS) user %1 is successfully created at %2.

VDR28.Description: A user has caused a mirrored virtual disk to be split. When a virtual disk is mirrored, its data is copied to another virtual disk to maintain redundancy. After being split, both virtual disks retain a copy of the data. Because the mirror is no longer intact, updates to the data are no longer copied to the mirror.
VDR28.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR28.Message: A virtual disk and its mirror have been split.

VDR100.Description: The virtual disk identified in message cannot be used because of missing features on the current controller. The features may be missing because they are not available in the firmware version on the controller or the necessary licenses are not installed.
VDR100.Resolution: Update the controller firmware and license to match the peer controller.
VDR100.Message: %1 is unavailable because of incompatibilities with the current controller.

SWC0321.Description: Could not open the log file for reading.
SWC0321.Message: Unable to open the log for reading.

CPU0005.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.
CPU0005.Resolution: Review product documentation for supported CPU configurations.

RAC995.Description: The hardware inventory cannot be retrieved because another hardware inventory operation may already be in progress or due to an internal error whether or not Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) is enabled or disabled.
RAC995.Resolution: Another hardware inventory operation may already be in progress and must complete before retrying the operation. If no other hardware inventory operation was in progress, make sure to enable Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature, reboot the system, and retry the operation. If CSIOR is already enabled and no other hardware inventory operation was in progress, reboot the iDRAC using "racadm racreset" command and then retry the operation.
RAC995.Message: Unable to retrieve the hardware inventory.

PDR60.Description: The reason for the error can vary depending on the situation. The firmware error code is indicated in the message.
PDR60.Resolution: Verify the health of attached devices. Review the Lifecycle log for significant events. Replace faulty hardware, if required. Make sure the cables are attached securely. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cable connections.

LC068.Description: The import or export system configuration operation cannot be performed because there are pending attribute changes or a configuration job is in progress.
LC068.Resolution: Apply or cancel any pending attribute changes. Changes can be applied by creating a targeted configuration job, or the changes can be cancelled by invoking the DeletePendingConfiguration method. If a configuration job is in progress, wait until it is completed before retrying the import or export system configuration operation.
LC068.Message: Unable to perform the import or export operation because there are pending attribute changes or a configuration job is in progress.

HWC1009.Description: The backplane may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC1009.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

CTL83.Description: The management controller is not communicating with the storage controller identified in the message. This may be because of any one of the following: 1) PCIe subsystem is has stopped functioning 2) An issue in the storage controller 3) An issue in the management controller.
CTL83.Resolution: Restart the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

SYS140.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running in the server OS.
SYS140.Resolution: Enable and start the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) from within the server OS and then retry the operation.
SYS140.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running in the server OS.

RAC0291.Description: The user name value does not accept these characters.
RAC0291.Resolution: Do not enter /, \, @, ., or " (quotation mark) for user name.
RAC0291.Message: The user name cannot contain: /, \, @, ., or " (quotation mark).

LIC002.Description: The error may occur when License Manager: 1) Is unable to allocate system resources.2) Determines one or more files is incompatible with the current firmware version. This occurs when an older firmware version has been uploaded to a system that was previously running a newer firmware version. If this occurs, the current internal License Manager files are deleted and new ones are created, which align with the firmware version. A license reimport may be required. NOTE: All import, delete, export, view license commands are blocked until this issue is resolved.
LIC002.Resolution: If the firmware has been rolled back to a previous version, this error may occur. All previously installed licenses must be re-imported. If this is not the case, contact technical support.
LIC002.Message: License Manager is unable to allocate the required resources at startup.

SUP002.Description: Could not create a new job because of a network error or an unresponsive iDRAC.
SUP002.Resolution: Retry the action. If this fails, reboot the iDRAC.

SYS248.Description: The file cannot be transferred because proxy credentials are not entered, or the proxy credentials entered do not correspond to an authorized user of the proxy server.
SYS248.Resolution: Make sure that the correct proxy credentials are entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS248.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because the proxy credentials are not entered, or the proxy credentials entered do not correspond to an authorized user of the proxy server.

JCP003.Description: The Job did not complete successfully.
JCP003.Resolution: Retry the operation, and if necessary, make sure that valid parameters are provided for the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
JCP003.Message: The Job did not complete successfully.

SWC8605.Description: Information about the server identified in the message is not recognized.
SWC8605.Resolution: Restart the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and retry the operation. The CMC can be restarted by using the Web UI interface and selecting Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components and then select the Reset/Failover CMC button. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8605.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Server %1 generation information is not recognized.

UEFI0010.Description: A CPU stack-segment fault (type 0x0C) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0010.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

RAC0206.Description: Certificate upload failed because this is not a certificate file.
RAC0206.Message: Certificate upload failed: Not a certificate file.

CMC8542.Description: The CMC specified in the message was manually restarted.
CMC8542.Message: The CMC %1 was restarted because of a manual reset.

SWC1910.Description: User ID Name has been changed.
SWC1910.Message: User ID %1 User Name has been changed.

RED044.Description: The license required to perform the operation identified in the message either has expired or was removed and the iDRAC was unable to create the next job in the sequence.
RED044.Resolution: Install an iDRAC license that supports the following features: Automatic Update or Server Profile Export and Import. After the appropriate license has been installed, retry the operation.
RED044.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was unable to create a job because the required license is not available now.

TMP0128.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0128.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0128.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is outside of range.

POW004.Description: Host failed to power up because of unacknowledged use of 110V. This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2254.
POW004.Message: Power on permission error, unacknowledged use of 110V.

OSD18.Description: Unable to find the ISO file specified in the network share. Make sure that the correct ISO file path was entered into the command and that all other user credentials are correct.
OSD18.Resolution: Rerun the command with the correct ISO file path.
OSD18.Message: Unable to locate the ISO image on the network share point.

SWU8518.Description: The server was pulled out from the chassis during the iDRAC firmware update operation.
SWU8518.Resolution: Reinsert the server and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8518.Message: The firmware update operation on the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is stopped.

RDU8518.Description: The active CMC requests the Standby CMC to go active. If the user did not initiate this request, review the chassis log for the reason.
RDU8518.Message: CMC%1: active CMC%1 requests Standby CMC to go active state.

PWR8678.Description: The power property identified in the message is changed as identified in the message.
PWR8678.Message: The value of the property %1 is %2.

LOG006.Description: This message is generated while performing a Test Event action. Performing a Test Event action logs an event in the Lifecycle Log with the user specified message ID. It may also generate events through SNMP, email, or other event notification sources if they are enabled. The test event does not indicate that there is a hardware or software problem. It provides a mechanism for users to test their event processing applications.
LOG006.Message: Test event generated for message ID %1.

RAC0561.Description: iDRAC lost connection with CMC proxy component that enables agent free monitoring of PCIe slots. Agent free monitoring will not be supported for Chassis PCIe slots while this connection is not functioning.
RAC0561.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the Lifecycle Log for the subsequent RAC0562 communications restored message that will indicate the link was re-established automatically. 2) If there is no subsequent RAC0562 message in the Lifecycle Log, restart the iDRAC. The iDRAC can be restarted by using the RACADM command line utility and entering "racadm racreset". 3) After the iDRAC has restarted, if the communications link is still not functioning, restart the CMC and check the Lifecycle Log for this link error after the CMC has restarted. 4) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0561.Message: iDRAC to CMC communication link is not functioning for agent free monitoring of chassis PCIe slots.

PDR66.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR66.Message: %1 that was marked as missing has been replaced.

PWR2267.Description: The power supply unit (PSU) identified in the message is disabled because of a capacity mismatch and therefore the PSU is not supported on the server.
PWR2267.Resolution: Install a supported power supply unit (PSU). For information about PSUs of supported capacities, see the product documentation available on the support site.
PWR2267.Message: The power supply unit (PSU) %1 is disabled because of a capacity mismatch and therefore the PSU is not supported on the server.

SWC8606.Description: The server identified in the message never reported that remote services were ready.
SWC8606.Resolution: Make sure that the iDRAC on the server identified in the message is operating properly and that Lifecycle Controller is enabled, then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform a virtual reseat of the server and retry the operation. The server can be virtually reseated by using the CMC Web UI interface and selecting Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components and then select Virtual Reseat from the drop down operation for the server identified in the message.
SWC8606.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Timeout exceeded while waiting for remote services ready on Server %1.

SWC0311.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0311.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0311.Message: Invalid syntax. The -g option is only valid with -i and -o options.

SRV009.Description: There was an issue retrieving System information from the iDRAC. This may be because Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled and has never executed or the iDRAC Remote Services API status may not be in the Ready state.
SRV009.Resolution: Make sure the Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) is enabled and has run at least once before retrying this operation. For remote web services API access, make sure the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status before trying this operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
SRV009.Message: There was an issue retrieving System information for SupportAssist.

VDR8.Description: The virtual drive on the Controller identified in the message is degraded either because the physical disk drive in the drive group is removed or the physical disk drive added in a redundant virtual drive has failed.
VDR8.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Insert a physical disk drive. After the drive is inserted, the previous data is automatically rebuilt by the system. 2) If not already done, configure a hot-spare for the virtual drive. 3) If a physical disk drive is removed from the disk drive group, either replace the disk or restore the original disk drive.
VDR8.Message: %1 is degraded either because the physical disk drive in the drive group is removed or the physical disk drive added in a redundant virtual drive has failed.

RAC1140.Description: The file name cannot be specified when the Technical Support Report (TSR) is exported to a remote share.
RAC1140.Resolution: Run the command without using the -f option. For more information on exporting Technical Support Report (TSR), run the command 'racadm help techsupreport export'.
RAC1140.Message: File name is not required to export the Technical Support Report (TSR) to a remote share.

UEFI0249.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. A requested resource could not be allocated. Resource was forced to maximum possible value instead.
UEFI0249.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0249.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

SWC0244.Description: The specified Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDDs) system component name is invalid.
SWC0244.Resolution: Verify that the correct Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) system component name is specified. See the help text (The help text for the get subcommand can be obtained by running "racadm help get") or documentation for valid FQDD system component names.

SRV054.Description: The Debug Logs collection operation cannot be fully completed for SupportAssist collection because some of the commands could not be run while collecting debug logs.
SRV054.Resolution: Retry the action. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and then retry the operation.
SRV054.Message: Unable to fully complete the Debug Logs Collection operation.

USR0206.Description: The Quick Sync feature is enabled because the activate/deactivate button on the panel was pressed.
USR0206.Message: The Quick Sync feature is enabled because the activate/deactivate button on the panel was pressed.

PSU502.Description: The server was already down, when the user gave a power off request.

RAC0272.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0272.Resolution: Disable NIC only if remote access is undesired.
RAC0272.Message: Disabling NIC will prevent the user from accessing the iDRAC remotely through Web GUI, Remote Racadm, Ssh, and Telnet. Local Racadm and serial interface will continue to work.

HWC1102.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message is installed in the unsupported slot identified in the message.
HWC1102.Resolution: Install the Storage sled in a supported slot and retry the operation. For information about the supported sleds and slots, see the User's Guide available at the support site.
HWC1102.Message: The %1 is installed in an unsupported slot %2.

PDR34.Description: The hot spare is no longer required because the virtual disk it was assigned to has been deleted.
PDR34.Message: A dedicated hot spare has been automatically unassigned.%1

SYS186.Description: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server OS is turned off.
SYS186.Resolution: Turn on the server and wait until the OS finishes booting, and then retry the operation.
SYS186.Message: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server is turned off.

ENC3.Description: The physical disk enclosure is either hotter or cooler than the maximum or minimum allowable temperature range.
ENC3.Resolution: Check for factors that may cause overheating or excessive cooling. For example, verify that the enclosure fan is working. You should also check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source. Make sure the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot or too cold. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information.

TMP0137.Description: The system cooling is working normally.
TMP0137.Message: The system cooling is working normally.

SRV076.Description: The SupportAssist operation to present iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer to Host operating system (OS) is waiting on a user action to install iSM service in Host OS.
SRV076.Resolution: Install the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service from the iSM installer that is presented to the Host operating system (OS).
SRV076.Message: The SupportAssist operation to present iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer to Host operating system (OS) is waiting on a user action to install iSM service in Host OS.

RAC1201.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the server is in the lockdown mode. Modifications are not allowed when the server is in the lockdown mode.
RAC1201.Resolution: Disable the lockdown mode by running the following RACADM at the command line interface (CLI): racadm set iDRAC.Lockdown.SystemLockdownMode 0.
RAC1201.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the server is in the lockdown mode.

PCI3022.Description: The Airflow Linear Flow per Minute (LFM) settings of the PCIe slot cannot be adjusted because the LFM settings can be adjusted only for installed cards that are identified as third party cards.
PCI3022.Resolution: Make sure that the cards installed in the PCIe slots are third party cards.
PCI3022.Message: Unable to adjust the Airflow Linear Flow per Minute (LFM) settings of the PCIe slot because the LFM settings can be adjusted only for installed cards that are identified as third party cards.

SWC1948.Description: The Quick Sync inactivity timeout value is set to the value identified in the message.
SWC1948.Message: The Quick Sync inactivity timeout value is set to %1.

SWC8515.Description: Successfully modified privileges of User identified in the message.

SYS148.Description: The BIOS is configured to reset to defaults on the next system restart because of a System Erase operation.
SYS148.Message: BIOS is configured to reset to defaults on next system restart.

SWC0227.Description: Invalid values passed to the function.
SWC0227.Resolution: Enter a shorter path to the firmware image file.
SWC0227.Message: Partition label exceeds maximum limit of 6 alphanumeric characters.

VF010.Description: Formatting the specified partition did not complete successfully.
VF010.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
VF010.Message: Partition formatting did not complete successfully.

ENC25.Description: The enclosure or an enclosure component is in a Failed or Degraded state.
ENC25.Resolution: Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. See the storage hardware documentation for more information. Contact technical support.

GMGR0034.Description: The group job identified in the message is successfully deleted.
GMGR0034.Message: The group job %1 is successfully deleted.

RED055.Description: A reboot job for applying one or more update packages has been created. The server will reboot at the specified start time.

SYS434.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the uploaded firmware image file extension is not supported.
SYS434.Resolution: Make sure to use a valid firmware image and retry the operation. For information about the supported file extension types, see the Redfish Users Guide available on the support site.
SYS434.Message: Unable to upload the firmware image because the file extension is not supported.

RED011.Description: Current USC version does not support this component. Check InstanceID.
RED011.Resolution: Use the latest version of USC available if possible.

RAC1151.Description: The export operation did not complete successfully.
RAC1151.Resolution: Run the RACADM techsupreport collect command again and then retry the export operation.

BAR118.Description: The Restore operation cannot be completed because the backup image file name is invalid.
BAR118.Resolution: Make sure the backup image file name has valid characters and is not too long, and then retry the operation. For information about valid image file names, see the iDRAC's User's Guide available on the support site.
BAR118.Message: Unable to continue with Restore operation because the backup image file name is invalid.

PCI3004.Description: Either the BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, or mezzanine card firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3004.Resolution: Update BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, and mezzanine card firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3004.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card %1 failed to support Link Tuning or FlexAddress.

VDR24.Description: The re-configuration operation on the virtual disk completed.

OSD8.Description: The BIOS boot order set to PXE using a standard IPMI command has failed.
OSD8.Resolution: 1) Check BIOS PXE settings. 2) Rerun the command. 3) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD8.Message: Setting Boot to PXE through IPMI failed.

PDR1025.Message: Drive mismatch corrected for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

OSD50.Description: Lifecycle Controller is in field service mode and needs to be updated before proceeding further.
OSD50.Resolution: Install the Lifecycle Controller field services package using the iDRAC GUI.
OSD50.Message: Lifecycle Controller is in field service mode.

SWC0290.Description: Failed to configure the object specified in the error message.
SWC0290.Message: Failed to configure object. Group: %1, Object : %2

HWC7010.Description: Server <number> health changed to a critical state from a non-recoverable state.
HWC7010.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7010.Message: Server %1 health changed to a critical state from a non-recoverable state.

IOV1006.Description: The PCI slot or Server slot FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) values entered for the operation are not valid.
IOV1006.Resolution: Perform the Enumerate operation on the DCIM_ChassisPCISlot class and DCIM_BladeServerView class to get the correct FQDD values for the PCIe slot and Server slot. Retry the operation with the correct FQDD values.
IOV1006.Message: Invalid PCI slot or Server slot.

SWU8504.Description: The specified Lifecycle Controller operation is successfully submitted and the operation will be executed on the basis of scheduling criteria.
SWU8504.Message: Successfully scheduled the %1 operation on the server %2.

RAC0710.Resolution: Ensure that the IO Module (IOM) and Mezzanine (Mezz) cards are appropriately matched. Check the M1000e Hardware Manual for correct component compatibility.

PWR8663.Description: The server identified in the message could not be successfully turned on because of incompatibility between the I/O module and mezzanine card.
PWR8663.Resolution: Make sure that the I/O module and mezzanine card are compatible. For information about compatibility of hardware components, see the Modular System Chassis Hardware Manual.
PWR8663.Message: Unable to turn on the server %1 because of an inconsistency between the I/O module and mezzanine card.

PWR8514.Description: The user account credentials provided for this chassis power action do not have the correct privilege. Chassis control privilege is required to perform chassis power actions.
PWR8514.Resolution: Retry to action with a different user account that has chassis power control privilege.
PWR8514.Message: Unable to perform chassis power action due to insufficient privileges.

SYS247.Description: The file cannot be transferred because credentials are not entered, or the credentials entered do not correspond to an authorized user of the remote host.
SYS247.Resolution: Make sure that the correct credentials are entered, and then retry the operation.
SYS247.Message: Unable to transfer a file, %1, because credentials are not entered, or the credentials entered do not correspond to an authorized user of the remote host.

PST0080.Description: System is at the F1/F2 prompt because the system BIOS detected an issue other than "No bootable devices".
PST0080.Resolution: Check post display screen for details. Press F1 to continue boot, or press F2 to go to setup.
PST0080.Message: An issue was detected. System at boot F1/F2 prompt. Requires entry to continue.

SWC0015.Description: The operating system driver pack is missing or not accessible.
SWC0015.Resolution: Update the system with the latest Lifecycle Controller OS Driver Pack. Obtain the OS Driver Pack from the service provider.
SWC0015.Message: Unable to retrieve the list of supported operating systems.

SYS051.Description: Sometimes, the operating system on the server may not allow a graceful shutdown or may not complete within the specified graceful shutdown timeout. This error indicates that the system could not be shutdown within the time specified. The default timeout value is 5 minutes and the maximum value allowed is 1 hour.
SYS051.Resolution: Retry the operation with a longer specified graceful shutdown timeout or with the system shutdown option.
