SYS051.Message: The system could not be shut down within the specified time.

SWU8501.Description: This message is displayed when:1. A reboot job is unable to provide a valid reboot ID.2. The WSMAN command to set up a job queue on Lifecycle Controller was not successful.
SWU8501.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the error persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8501.Message: The reinstall/rollback request to Lifecycle Controller on server %1 was not successful.

VLT0304.Description: Voltages outside the allowable range may damage electrical components or may cause the system to shutdown.
VLT0304.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0304.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is outside of range.

SWC8604.Description: The target server identified in the message does not support server configuration using profiles.
SWC8604.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Server %1 does not support configuration using profiles.

PST0129.Description: System BIOS detected memory, but was unable to configure the memory for system operation. Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce the system to minimum memory configuration if acceptable. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.(BIOS POST Exception Code 81).
PST0129.Resolution: Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations.
PST0129.Message: Memory is detected, but is not configurable.

STOR019.Description: The passphrase specified does not follow the passphrase character criteria of the controller character.
STOR019.Resolution: Enter a passphrase that meets the passphrase character criteria of the controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR019.Message: The specified passphrase is not valid.

STOR031.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G and above generations: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
STOR031.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G and above generations: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

SYS165.Description: One or more Tech Support Report data collection options selected did not complete successfully.
SYS165.Resolution: Look at the Lifecycle Log for exception messages and resolve the issues described.
SYS165.Message: One or more Tech Support Report data collection options selected did not complete successfully.

RAC0222.Description: The specified email address does not match an email address format. Ex: "janedoe@email.com".
RAC0222.Message: The Destination E-mail Address is invalid.

USR0153.Description: The VNC client is logged off from the IP address identified in the message.
USR0153.Resolution: To re-establish the remote VNC session, log in again using the VNC client.
USR0153.Message: Logging off the remote VNC session from the IP address %1, because the session timed out.

RAC0757.Description: The requested operation using the USB Management Port cannot be completed because the port is disabled in BIOS configuration.
RAC0757.Resolution: Enable the USB Management Port in BIOS configuration to use this feature.
RAC0757.Message: USB Management Port is currently disabled in BIOS configuration.

LC003.Description: An error occurred while trying to set the firmware update mode.
LC003.Resolution: Verify that the firmware version supports this mode. Also confirm that the command and parameters are correct. The parameter choices are: 1) Disable (default) 2) Allow version upgrade only 3) Match firmware of replaced part.
LC003.Message: Failed to change the firmware update mode.

RAC0634.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid username is entered.
RAC0634.Resolution: Enter a valid network file share username, and then retry the operation.
RAC0634.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid network file share username is entered.

SWU8552.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC was not successful.
SWU8552.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8552.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Active CMC.

BAR057.Description: The configuration import was completed, but some of the imported values were not set correctly.
BAR057.Resolution: The system event log captures the values that were not set, and they must be reset manually.
BAR057.Message: Some of the configuration values not applied to Device: %1

BIOS029.Description: The BIOS password cannot be configured because an Export Server Profile operation is already running.
BIOS029.Resolution: Wait until the current export operation is completed, and then retry the operation.
BIOS029.Message: Unable to change the BIOS password because an Export Server Profile operation is already running.

SYS092.Description: The iDRAC is collecting information about the server for a Tech Support Report.
SYS092.Message: The iDRAC is collecting information about the server for a Tech Support Report.

PDR75.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC8534.Description: All keys saved in the Chassis Management Controller for PK SSH Authentication are deleted.
SWC8534.Message: All keys deleted for all slots of service account.

CTL29.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL29.Message: The Patrol Read rate has changed for %1.

LC018.Description: The certificate modification operation was successful. Communication to iDRAC will be lost as iDRAC restarts to use the new server certificate.
LC018.Message: Server certificate successfully modified. iDRAC will now restart and be unavailable during restart.

CTL73.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL73.Message: Foreign configuration is imported only partially. Some configurations failed to import on %1.

STOR004.Description: Provided parameter value is not valid.
STOR004.Resolution: Refer to the RAID profile to determine the valid parameters values.

SWC0275.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0275.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0275.Message: Invalid syntax. The -c option is only valid with -f or -g.

SWC0117.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.
SWC0117.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertdownload subcommand.
SWC0117.Message: Invalid syntax. Both -f and -t must be specified.

PWR2209.Message: The system is in an undermined sleep state.

CPU0803.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0803.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0803.Message: The power input for CPU %1 voltage regulator module is lost.

RAC041.Description: The event filters set operation did not complete successfully due to invalid input parameters.
RAC041.Resolution: Verify the specified input parameters and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC041.Message: The set operation on the event filters failed.

RAC1057.Description: Rollback operation did not complete successfully. The component identifier (FQDD) specified in the operation is not valid or does not have a Rollback firmware image available.
RAC1057.Resolution: Run the RACADM command "racadm swinventory" to see the list of Rollback firmware images available and the corresponding component identifier (FQDD).
RAC1057.Message: Rollback operation did not complete successfully. The component identifier specified is not valid or does not have a rollback firmware image available.

UEFI0045.Description: Unable to enable the TXT feature because a TPM chip is not present.
UEFI0045.Resolution: Install a TPM chip module by following the installation procedure. Refer to the platform Owner's Manual for more information or contact your service provider.
UEFI0045.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because a TPM chip is not present.

UEFI0203.Description: A failing memory buffer has been identified on the memory riser identified in the message.
UEFI0203.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0203.Message: A failing memory buffer has been detected during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RAC0283.Description: This is the time span (in seconds) within which IP Blocking Fail Count failures must occur to trigger the IP Blocking Penalty Time. The default value is 3600 seconds (1 hour).
RAC0283.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Blocking Fail Window. Expected range: 10-65535.
RAC0283.Message: IP Blocking Fail Window is invalid. Expected range: 10-65535.

ENC14.Description: There are too many enclosures attached to the controller port. When the enclosure limit is exceeded, the controller loses contact with all enclosures attached to the port. This is an unsupported configuration.
ENC14.Resolution: Remove the extra enclosures. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for maximum number of enclosures that can be connected.
ENC14.Message: The number of enclosures connected on %1 has exceeded the maximum limit supported by the controller.

GMGR0044.Description: The group job identified in the message cannot be completed because a group job is already in progress.
GMGR0044.Resolution: Wait for the group configuration job to get completed and retry the operation.
GMGR0044.Message: Unable to start a system configuration job of type %1 because a group configuration job is already in progress. The job status is %2.

SWC8619.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to process inventory data from the server in the slot identified in the message. This can happen if: 1) There is a communications issue between the CMC and the iDRAC on the server identified in the message. 2) Incorrect firmware is installed on network cards. 3) Incorrect firmware is installed on the server iDRAC. 4) There is no free temporary storage in the CMC.
SWC8619.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Make sure the latest firmware is installed on the network cards and iDRAC on the server identified in the message. 2) Reset the Chassis Management Controller. 3) Reset the server iDRAC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8619.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to process data from the server in slot %1.

RAC1068.Description: The minimum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum non critical threshold value.
RAC1068.Resolution: Check the maximum non critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the maximum non critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1068.Message: Unable to set minimum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum non critical threshold value.

VFL0020.Description: The vFlash SD card is currently in use by another operation.
VFL0020.Resolution: Wait for the current vFlash SD card operation to finish, and they retry.
VFL0020.Message: vFlash SD card is not ready.

UEFI0280.Description: The Hardware P State (HWP) mode cannot be enabled because the processor does not support the HWP mode. The CPU Power Management setting has changed to System DBPM (DAPC).
UEFI0280.Resolution: Install an HWP-capable processor and retry the operation.
UEFI0280.Message: Cannot enable the Hardware P State (HWP) mode because the processor does not support the HWP mode.

LOG503.Description: The command cannot be run because the value of the parameter identified in the message is not valid.
LOG503.Resolution: Enter all the parameters required in the command as per the enumeration, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the Chassis Record Log Profile.
LOG503.Message: Unable to run the method because the parameter %1 is not valid.

SYS433.Description: The server configuration profile data cannot be uploaded because the file type used for the data file is not in the JSON or XML format.
SYS433.Resolution: Make sure that the file format used is of JSON or XML format, and then retry the operation.
SYS433.Message: Unable to upload the server configuration profile data because the file type used for the data file is not in the JSON or XML format.

BOOT011.Description: The provided vFlash partition could not be set for one time boot.
BOOT011.Resolution: Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
BOOT011.Message: Failed to set vFlash partition for one time boot

SYS192.Description: The provided Server Configuration Profile is being previewed on the system. No configuration changes will be applied.
SYS192.Resolution: No response action is required. Use the GetConfigResults() method to get the preview job results or export the Lifecycle Log to review the preview job results.

PDR217.Description: The cryptographic erase operation cannot be completed on the physical disk drive identified in the message.
PDR217.Message: Unable to complete the Cryptographic erase operation on the physical disk drive %1.

OSD34.Description: Unable to continue with BootToPXE command because the system has an ISO image attached. Detach the ISO image before continuing with BootToPXE.
OSD34.Resolution: Run the DetachISOImage command and then run BootToPXE.
OSD34.Message: Unable to continue with BootToPXE - ISO image is attached to the system.

HWC8508.Description: A device causing an issue in the I/O panel USB port is removed.
HWC8508.Message: A device causing an issue in the I/O panel USB port is removed.

PST0085.Description: System is performing CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart).

RAC984.Description: iDRAC is unable to extract the custom signing certificate and the private key from the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file.
RAC984.Resolution: Check if the specified file and passphrase are valid, and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC984.Message: Unable to upload the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file.

SEC0044.Description: TXT initialization cannot be completed because system configuration may have changed.
SEC0044.Resolution: Check system hardware inventory for TPM presence, clear and reconfigure TPM and TXT in BIOS setup menu.
SEC0044.Message: SINIT Authenticated Code Module detected an Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) problem at boot.

VFL0015.Description: The request could not be successfully completed, because the vFlash SD Card partition is in read-only mode. Write operations cannot be performed on the card partition.
VFL0015.Resolution: Change the partition access type to read-write by running the command 'racadm set idrac.vFlashPartition.<index>.accesstype 1'.
VFL0015.Message: vFlash media partition is of read-only type.

RAC0140.Description: The firmware update process returned an 'Update Failed' status.
RAC0140.Resolution: Try the firmware update again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, try uploading the firmware through another interface such as Web GUI, RACADM, or DUPs.

OSD38.Description: There was an error while copying the ISO from the network share.
OSD38.Resolution: 1) Make sure the network connection is functional. 2) Make sure the Dell vFlash does not have hardware issues by accessing it through the iDRAC GUI.
OSD38.Message: Copying the ISO image from the network failed.

SWC0033.Description: Exporting the Server Configuration Profile image file to the network share was successful.
SWC0033.Message: Successfully exported the Server Configuration Profile image file to network share.

CTL102.Description: The controller identified in the message is enabled by a user action.

SRV056.Description: Unable to collect Debug Logs because none of the iDRAC debug commands could be executed for this operation.
SRV056.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and then retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm racreset".
SRV056.Message: Unable to collect any of the SupportAssist Debug Log files because none of the debug commands could be run while collecting iDRAC debug logs.

UEFI0001.Description: A CPU software breakpoint exception (type 0x03) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment. The software used it for debugging purposes.
UEFI0001.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

SWC8517.Description: Successfully modified the password for the User identified in the message.

RAC1185.Description: The static IPv6 address is not configured because an invalid IPv6 address or IPv6 Gateway is entered.
RAC1185.Resolution: Enter a valid IPv6 address and IPv6 Gateway, and retry the operation.
RAC1185.Message: Unable to configure static IPv6 address because an invalid IPv6 address or IPv6 Gateway is entered.

CMC8506.Description: A command to shut down the CMC was initiated.
CMC8506.Message: A command to shut down the CMC was initiated.

OSD28.Description: Hash verification on the ISO image has failed. The hash value specified in the command is either incorrect or the ISO image has been changed.
OSD28.Resolution: 1) Verify that the hash value specified in the command is correct. 2) Make sure that the ISO has not been changed 3) Replace the ISO image on the share and rerun the command.
OSD28.Message: Hash verification on the ISO image failed.

SRV045.Description: Unable to start the operation because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.
SRV045.Resolution: Retry the operation after the server has finished starting and POST has completed.
SRV045.Message: Unable to start the operation because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.

RAC1026.Description: A custom signing certificate must be present in the system to delete or download the certificate.
RAC1026.Message: A custom signing certificate does not exist.

RAC0141.Description: Firmware update verification process failed; the firmware update status is unknown.
RAC0141.Resolution: Verify if the firmware has been updated by checking the new firmware version number. If it has not been updated try the firmware update again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, try uploading the firmware through another interface such as Web GUI, RACADM, or DUPs.
RAC0141.Message: Firmware update verification failed: The update status is unknown.

PR36.Description: The system has detected a different firmware version than previously recorded for the indicated device. This may be due to a firmware update, rollback, or part replacement.
PR36.Message: Version change detected for %1 firmware. Previous version:%2, Current version:%3

LC061.Description: Jobs, invoke methods, enumerates can now be performed on Lifecycle controller. Lifecycle controller is ready to take provisioning requests.
LC061.Message: Lifecycle controller is ready to take provisioning requests

RAC0605.Description: There are no jobs to be displayed.
RAC0605.Message: There are no jobs to be displayed.

CTL52.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation.

SWC8522.Description: Successfully completed a configuration sync with the member identified in the message.
SWC8522.Message: Chassis Group Leader update of member %1 configuration successful.

BAT1025.Description: The controller was unable to recover data from the cache. This may indicate data loss has occurred.
BAT1025.Resolution: Verify that the battery is charged and in good health. See the hardware documentation for more information. When the battery charge is unacceptably low, the battery cannot maintain cached data. Data loss may also have occurred, restoring data from backups may be needed. Verify whether the battery has met its recharge limit. The battery may need to be recharged. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
BAT1025.Message: %1 is unable to recover cached data from the Battery Backup Unit (BBU).

ENC31.Description: The system was unable to download firmware to the enclosure. The controller may have lost communication with the enclosure. There may have been problems with the data transfer or the download media may be corrupt.
ENC31.Resolution: Attempt to download the enclosure firmware again. If problems continue, verify that the controller can communicate with the enclosure. Make sure that the enclosure is powered ON. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on checking the cables.

BAR015.Description: The Backup file information was not properly processed and the operation cannot continue. This can be due to resource constraints within the processing environment. If the network share is read only, this error will be thrown also.
BAR015.Resolution: If this is backup to network share, check to make sure network share is read/write accessible. Restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) and retry the operation.

SRV097.Description: The SupportAssist Collection is successfully exported to the local path.
SRV097.Message: The SupportAssist Collection is successfully exported to the local path.

SWC0284.Description: Local Configuration using RACADM may be disabled.
SWC0284.Resolution: Check if the Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled and enable it through GUI.
SWC0284.Message: Failed to set the object value. Possible reason may be that Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled.

SYS042.Description: The requested component configuration successfully completed.

RAC0285.Description: The user name cannot be empty when creating a user account.

BAT1005.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1005.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has been postponed.

PDR93.Description: The physical disk firmware update operation has completed.

SRV020.Description: The memory cannot be allocated because of insufficient storage space in iDRAC.
SRV020.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and then retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC using the RACADM command line utility, enter "racadm racreset".
SRV020.Message: Unable to allocate memory because of insufficient storage space in iDRAC.

LC092.Description: The Client Trust Certificate cannot be deleted because of issues in the Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).
LC092.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation.
LC092.Message: Unable to delete the Client Trust Certificate because of issues in the Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).

STOR103.Description: The physical disk drive cannot be converted to Ready status because either the input value is not supported or the controller's current RAID mode does not allow the input value. The RAIDMode may not match the RAIDType or the SoftwareRAIDMode requested.
STOR103.Resolution: Make sure that the input value is correct and retry the operation. If RAIDMode has a value then the requested RAIDType or SoftwareRAIDMode value must match.
STOR103.Message: Unable to convert the physical disk drive to Ready status because either the input value is not supported or the controller's current RAID mode does not allow the input value.

RAC009.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the length of the input string exceeds maximum length allowed.
RAC009.Resolution: Verify the string length and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC009.Message: Input string length exceeds maximum length.

OSE1001.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. Verify the media in a: is bootable. See system video for additional information.

SRV078.Description: The SupportAssist operation to present iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer to Host operating system (OS) completed but iSM was not installed on the Host OS.
SRV078.Resolution: Retry the operation and install the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service manually once installer is presented to the Host operating system (OS).
SRV078.Message: The SupportAssist operation to present iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installer to Host operating system (OS) completed but iSM was not installed on the Host OS.

ISM0021.Description: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the OS Collector executable was not found.
ISM0021.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the OS Collector on the iDRAC to the most recent version available, and then retry the operation.
ISM0021.Message: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the OS Collector executable was not found.

CMC8570.Description: The server slot specified in the message is disabled for DVD drive mapping. The DVD drive cannot be mapped to this server slot.
CMC8570.Message: The server slot %1 is enabled for DVD drive mapping.

RAC941.Description: A system configuration profile export operation may take several minutes to complete depending on the system configuration.
RAC941.Resolution: Monitor the job status using "racadm jobqueue view -i <Job ID>".
RAC941.Message: Successfully initiated the export operation. This operation may take several minutes to complete.

SRV064.Description: The SupportAssist Enclosure Controller logs collection operation is started.
SRV064.Message: The SupportAssist Enclosure Controller logs collection operation is started.

STOR003.Resolution: Refer to the RAID profile to determine required parameters.

RAC0903.Description: The syntax of the specified command is invalid. In this case, the usage of the -d option is invalid.
RAC0903.Resolution: See the help text/documentation for valid syntax of the subcommand.
RAC0903.Message: The -d option cannot be used with any other options.

CMC8520.Description: FRU on the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8520.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8520.Message: The FRU on server %1 is not functioning.

VF0060.Description: The SD card was not detected. Therefore, the requested operation cannot be completed.
VF0060.Resolution: Verify whether the SD card is inserted and enabled, then re-try.
VF0060.Message: Unable to perform the requested operation. Make sure the SD card is inserted and enabled.

UEFI0061.Description: The request to change one or more attribute(s) is being processed.
UEFI0061.Message: The request to change attributes is being processed.

BIOS021.Description: The old BIOS password specified in the change BIOS password operation was incorrect.
BIOS021.Resolution: Retry the operation with correct old BIOS password.

RAC0668.Description: This setting will be applied during the next server restart. If the setting is not compatible with the RAID Controller, then LED status indicators on all the associated hard disk drives (HDDs) stop functioning.
RAC0668.Message: This setting will be applied during the next server restart. If the setting is not compatible with the RAID Controller, then LED status indicators on all the associated hard disk drives (HDDs) stop functioning.

SWC1944.Description: The Quick Sync access feature is set to the Disabled mode.
SWC1944.Message: The Quick Sync access feature is set to the Disabled mode.

SWC0113.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0113.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0113.Message: The -6 option can only be used in combination with the -d or -s option.

PWR8532.Description: Server Based Power Management Mode is disabled.
PWR8532.Message: Server Based Power Management Mode is disabled.

USR0170.Description: The device identified in the message is connected to the Front Panel USB port and attached to the iDRAC.
USR0170.Message: The Front Panel USB port is attached to iDRAC Disk.USBFront.%1. Device details: Device class %2, Vendor ID %3, Manufacturer Name %4, Product ID %5, Product Name %6, Serial Number %7.

OSD13.Description: iDRAC was unable to mount the drivers as a USB device for the OS installation to proceed.
OSD13.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD13.Message: Cannot mount the USB device needed to copy drivers for the selected operating system.

CTL124.Description: The firmware version of the RAID controller identified in the message cannot be updated because of an issue detected in the firmware image file during the verification process.
CTL124.Resolution: Download the correct firmware image file and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CTL124.Message: Unable to update the RAID controller %1 firmware version because of an issue detected in the firmware image file during the verification process.

SWC0062.Description: The destination folder is not present, the destination is full or write-protected.
SWC0062.Resolution: Verify the following and retry the operation:1) Destination folder is present.2) Destination has enough free space.3) Destination is not write-protected.If the problem persists, perform an AC power cycle and retry.

RAC1191.Description: The file import operation has failed because of large file size.
RAC1191.Resolution: The file import operation has timed out, because the file is invalid or is exceeding the permissible size. Retry the operation with a valid file.
RAC1191.Message: Unable to import the specified file to iDRAC.

BAR099.Description: License data is being collected and copied into the backup Server Profile.

RAC035.Description: There are no pending values for the any of the iDRAC attributes.
RAC035.Resolution: Make sure there are pending values for the attributes that are targeted for configuration.

RAC0265.Description: If VLAN is enabled, specify the VLAN ID and VLAN Priority.
RAC0265.Resolution: Enter a VLAN ID and VLAN Priority.
RAC0265.Message: Specify the VLAN ID and VLAN Priority.

UEFI0167.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because the number of allowable Rank Interleave Register (RIR) rules exceeded during memory initialization.
UEFI0167.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0167.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

VF051.Description: The copying partition operation did not complete successfully.
VF051.Message: Export partition operation did not complete successfully.

SWC9009.Description: The SecureBoot Certificate ResetAll operation is successfully scheduled.
SWC9009.Resolution: Restart the host server for the changes to take effect.
SWC9009.Message: The SecureBoot Certificate ResetAll operation is successfully scheduled. Restart the host server for the changes to take effect.

CTL8.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL8.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL8.Message: Bad block extended sense error on %1.

SYS300.Description: The import operation cannot be started because the Control file has incorrect schema.
SYS300.Resolution: Make sure that the input file is compliant with the Control file schema described in the Lifecycle Controller Profile Schema Guide available on the delltechcenter.com/lc.
SYS300.Message: Unable to start the import operation because the Control file has incorrect schema.

SYS289.Description: The catalog file cannot be obtained from the network share for importing because it does not exist in the specified location.
SYS289.Resolution: Make sure that the specified catalog file is available on the remote share, and then retry the operation.
SYS289.Message: Unable to get the Repository Update catalog file from the network share for import because the file does not exist in the specified location.

VDR99.Description: The virtual disk identified in the message cannot be used because of an ID conflict with another virtual disk.
VDR99.Resolution: Power cycle the system chassis to restore the virtual disk. If this does not correct the problem then contact your service provider.
VDR99.Message: %1 is unavailable because of an ID conflict in the fault-tolerant pair.

VF006.Description: Creating a partition without image failed.
VF006.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.

OSD74.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is invalid.
OSD74.Resolution: Check the value provided for input parameter "ShareType" and retry the operation.
OSD74.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is invalid.

SWC0050.Description: Unable to initiate Import operation since iDRAC is not responding.
SWC0050.Resolution: Retry the Import operation using a valid backup image file and the correct passphrase. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.

PCI3016.Description: Either the BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, or mezzanine card firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3016.Resolution: Update BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, and mezzanine card firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3016.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card failed to support Link Tuning or FlexAddress.

PDR84.Description: The Security key on a secure encrypted disk was activated.

LIC017.Description: This error can occur when the license file: 1) Signature is not valid. 2) Data is not in the correct format. 3) Missing needed data. 4) Contains unknown data.5) Has not been unzipped.
LIC017.Resolution: Download the license file, unzip and import the license.
LIC017.Message: The license file is corrupted, has not been unzipped, or is not a valid license file.

RAC0155.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about system temperature.
RAC0155.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0155.Message: Unable to retrieve the temperature information. The system is powered off.

SRV133.Description: The SupportAssist Collection operation is started by the server Operating System (OS) user identified in the message.
SRV133.Message: The SupportAssist Collection operation is started by the server Operating System (OS) user %1.

STOR0512.Description: Unable to apply the encryption key due to an internal error.
STOR0512.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
STOR0512.Message: Unable to apply the encryption key.

RAC0118.Description: The SD card is not a valid vFlash SD card. The use of non-Dell media prevents the use of some extended capabilities and functions.
RAC0118.Resolution: Insert a supported vFlash SD card.

VFL1006.Description: At boot, the Card Identification (CID) signature of the card is different from the Non-volatile (NV) storage value or the card is the destination of a copy operation that is in-progress.
VFL1006.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.

RAC0128.Description: A non-specific error has been detected while accessing the vFlash.
RAC0128.Resolution: Try the operation again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC before trying the operation again.
RAC0128.Message: An error has occurred in vFlash.

PST0086.Description: System BIOS has launched the Lifecycle Controller user interface.

UEFI0006.Description: A CPU double fault exception (type 0x08) occurred.
UEFI0006.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

BAR103.Description: System branding data is being collected and copied to the backup Server Profile.

RAC018.Description: All the tasks in the Job were attempted, but some did not complete successfully.
RAC018.Resolution: Examine source of the errors by inspecting the results from the Job execution, and after resolving the issues, retry the operation. Job results can be retrieved from the Lifecycle Log or the WSMan API.
RAC018.Message: The Job is completed but with errors.

CTL14.Description: The storage controller memory identified in the message is not operating correctly.
CTL14.Message: Single-bit ECC error limit exceeded on the %1 DIMM.

SYS080.Description: Preview of Server Configuration Profile import operation indicates that no changes will be applied successfully. This is likely due to a mismatch between the actual target system components and component FQDDs specified in the configuration profile.
SYS080.Resolution: Make sure that the input file is compliant with the system configuration schema published on www.delltechcenter.com/lcand contains valid FQDDs that represent actual components in the target system.
SYS080.Message: Preview of Server Configuration Profile import operation indicated that no configuration changes will be successful.

CMC8508.Description: The Extended Storage feature is not activated if the removable flash media SD Card on the secondary CMC is not functioning properly.
CMC8508.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration, and verify if the SD card on secondary CMC displays errors. 2) If errors are displayed, execute the following racadm command: "racadm cmcchangeover". 3) Repair the removable flash media SD Card by selecting the Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration > Repair Active Controller Media in the CMC Web interface. Repairing is only allowed on the SD card of the primary CMC. If the problem persists, replace the card.
CMC8508.Message: Unable to synchronize the primary and secondary CMC removable flash media and the Extended Storage feature is not available.

RED036.Description: Firmware updates are available for component identified in the message in the specified remote repository and it is recommended to update to the firmware available in the repository.
RED036.Resolution: Update the component firmware to the version available in the specified remote repository.

PWR218.Description: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) the feature because the Fresh Air (FA) mode is enabled.
PWR218.Message: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature because the Fresh Air (FA) mode is enabled.

VF047.Description: This is not a Dell-licensed VFlash.
VF047.Resolution: This feature requires a Dell SD card.

SYS422.Description: The ETag in the response headers cannot be displayed because of unknown internal issues.
SYS422.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC, and then retry the operation. Reset the iDRAC by using the "Manager Reset Actions" Redfish API.
SYS422.Message: Unable to display the ETag in the response headers because of unknown internal issues.

AMP0321.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0321.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0321.Message: Chassis power level current is greater than the upper critical threshold.

BIOS040.Description: The SecureBoot certificate data cannot be imported because of insufficient disk space to store the certificate data.
BIOS040.Resolution: Delete the current SecureBoot certificate and retry the operation. If the issue, persists, contact service provider.
BIOS040.Message: Unable to import the SecureBoot certificate data because of insufficient disk space to store the certificate data.

RAC945.Description: The dedicated NIC or shared NIC scan time value is not between 5 and 255 seconds.
RAC945.Resolution: Make sure to set the scan time value between 5 and 255 seconds, and retry the operation. For more information, see RACADM help.

SYS070.Description: The configuration changes that require system reboot into the UEFI environment on the system did not complete for all components.
SYS070.Message: Configuration changes that require system reboot were not applied.

SWC1925.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the Disabled mode.
SWC1925.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the Disabled mode.

VDR26.Description: You paused the Check Consistency operation on a virtual disk.
VDR26.Resolution: To resume the Check Consistency operation, right-click the virtual disk in the Storage Management tree view and select Resume Check Consistency.
VDR26.Message: The check consistency on a %1 has been paused (suspended).

SWU8544.Description: The firmware update operation of the Standby CMC was not successful. The Standby CMC could not be prepared for firmware update.
SWU8544.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware because the Standby CMC could not be prepared for firmware update.

RAC0625.Description: The requested job cannot be scheduled, because job schedule types such as Automatic Backup or Automatic Update is not enabled.
RAC0625.Resolution: Enable the correct job schedule type, and then retry the operation. For example, to enable the Automatic Backup feature, select the Enable Automatic Backup option.
RAC0625.Message: Unable to schedule, because the requested job schedule type is not enabled.

SWC0073.Description: The Repurpose or Retire system operation cannot be successfully started because the current version of iDRAC firmware does not support the operation.
SWC0073.Resolution: Update iDRAC firmware to the latest version and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC0073.Message: Unable to start operation with the current iDRAC version.

UEFI0004.Description: A CPU invalid opcode exception (type 0x06) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment. The software attempted to execute invalid code.
UEFI0004.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

LC011.Description: There was a general failure in the certificate import process.
LC011.Resolution: Try one of the following: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and run the command.

TMP6.Description: You have changed the value for the minimum temperature probe warning threshold. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
TMP6.Message: The temperature probe minimum warning value was changed on %1.

RFM1023.Description: The media is being prepared or is under maintenance. If the problem persists, reinstall the card.
RFM1023.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
RFM1023.Message: Removable Flash Media is not ready.

TMP8502.Description: The system has recovered from being unable to read planar board or control panel temperature sensors.
TMP8502.Message: Able to read planar board temperature sensors. Cooling set for normal chassis operation.

PWR213.Description: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) is enabled.
PWR213.Resolution: Disable the Max Power Conservation Mode and retry the operation.
PWR213.Message: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) is enabled.

PWR210.Description: The redundancy policy cannot be changed to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.
PWR210.Message: The redundancy policy cannot be changed to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.

PSU8516.Description: Unable to set redundancy policy because PSU enumeration is in progress. The policy can be set after PSU enumeration is complete.
PSU8516.Resolution: Retry the operation after the PSU enumeration is complete.
PSU8516.Message: Unable to set redundancy policy because PSU enumeration is in progress.

OSD59.Description: Disconnecting ISO using Remote File Share (RFS) operation did not complete successfully.
OSD59.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
OSD59.Message: Unable to disconnect from ISO using Remote File Share (RFS).

RAC0293.Description: This error is displayed when LDAP or Active Directory cannot find an associated Certificate Authority (CA) certificate.
RAC0293.Resolution: Upload a valid root Certificate Authority (CA) certificate.
RAC0293.Message: When certificate validation is enabled, a valid root Certificate Authority (CA) certificate must be uploaded. The CA certificate is used to verify the directory server SSL certificate.

GMGR0060.Description: The group member cannot be removed because the group needs at least one active member. A member in a group that has only one member or whole group members all together cannot be removed, but the group itself must be deleted by running the command.
GMGR0060.Resolution: Delete the group by using the graphical user interface (GUI): On the Group Manager Summary page, click the Edit Group tab. Or, run the RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI): - racadm groupmanager delete -g <groupname>.
GMGR0060.Message: Unable to remove the group member because the group needs at least one member.

RAC0667.Description: This setting will be applied after the server has been turned off and turned on again. This may result in loss of configuration and/or access physical disk drive(s) or virtual disk(s) being marked offline. This may also result in some disk(s) being identified as foreign disks. Foreign physical disk drive(s) or virtual disk(s) can be imported or cleared.
RAC0667.Message: This setting will be applied after the server has been turned off and turned on again. This may result in loss of configuration and/or access to physical disk drive(s).

RAC0294.Description: The amount of time iDRAC waits before sending a partial Serial Over LAN (SOL) data packet. This parameter is specified in milliseconds. It is recommended to use 10 milliseconds for optimal performance.
RAC0294.Resolution: Enter a valid Character Accumulate Interval value. Expected range: 1-255.
RAC0294.Message: The Character Accumulate Interval value is invalid. Expected range: 1-255.

RAC0169.Description: Certificate upload failed because the certificate is not valid.
RAC0169.Resolution: Certificate may be corrupt. Try creating a new Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and then upload the certificate.
RAC0169.Message: Certificate upload failed: Certificate is not valid.

RAC1187.Description: The remote diagnostics operation could not be initiated because the Start Time entered is invalid. It is earlier than the current iDRAC time.
RAC1187.Resolution: Enter a Start Time that is later than the current iDRAC time and retry the operation. Run the "racadm getractime" command to obtain the current iDRAC time.
RAC1187.Message: Invalid Start Time Entered. Unable to start the Remote Diagnostics operation because the Start Time entered is earlier than the current iDRAC time.

PST0004.Description: System BIOS has started memory configuration.

BIOS028.Description: The BIOS password cannot be simultaneously configured by using plain text and a hash.
BIOS028.Resolution: Wait until the current password configuration process is completed and retry the operation.
BIOS028.Message: Unable to change the BIOS password using plain text because the password is currently being configured using a hash.

ENC13.Description: An unsupported configuration was detected. The SCSI rate of the Enclosure Management Modules (EMMs) are not the same.
ENC13.Resolution: Replace one of the EMMs with the matching SCSI rate EMM.

VDR58.Description: Virtual disk bad blocks are due to presence of unrecoverable bad blocks on one or more member physical disks.
VDR58.Resolution: Recovering a physical disk bad block depends on the RAID level and state of the virtual disk. If a virtual disk is redundant, the controller can recover a bad block on a physical disk. If a virtual disk is not redundant, then the physical disk bad block results in a virtual disk bad block.
VDR58.Message: Bad block medium error is detected at block %1 on %2.

CTL35.Description: The operation to import foreign configuration (virtual disks, host spares, and so on) completed successfully.
CTL35.Resolution: Verify the foreign configuration was successfully imported by viewing the virtual disks and hot spares. See the hardware documentation for more information.
CTL35.Message: A foreign configuration was imported on %1.

RAC944.Description: A configuration job cannot be created if Lifecycle Controller is disabled.
RAC944.Resolution: Run "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1" to enable Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.
RAC944.Message: Unable to create the configuration job.

SWU8524.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful. This may be due to a problem encountered by the firmware, or because a server was removed during the firmware update operation.
SWU8524.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source folder, and then retry the operation.
SWU8524.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 firmware: ErrorCode=0x%2.

RAC021.Description: The static values for IPAddress Net mask or Gateway cannot be set because DHCP is enabled.
RAC021.Resolution: Disable DHCP to set static values for IPAddress Net mask or Gateway.
RAC021.Message: Unable to set static values for IPAddress Net mask or Gateway because DHCP is Enabled.

CTL60.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL60.Message: A user has discarded data from the %1 cache.

BAT1034.Description: One or more battery properties were modified.
BAT1034.Message: The battery properties for %1 have changed.

RAC0693.Description: Pending operations are created for the selected operations on the selected physical disk drives.
RAC0693.Resolution: To view the pending operations, click the Pending Operations button.
RAC0693.Message: Pending operations are created for the selected operations on the selected physical disk drives.

PWR8565.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate with the iDRAC service processor for the Server identified in the message and the Server could not be turned off. This situation may occur when iDRAC is rebooting.
PWR8565.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Wait for a few minutes for the iDRAC service processor to complete startup. 2) Retry the operation. 3) If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and wait a few minutes for the iDRAC startup to complete before retrying the operation.
PWR8565.Message: Unable to turn off the Server %1 due to iDRAC communication issue.

FAN907.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already enabled.
FAN907.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already enabled.

HWC9005.Description: The BOSS device identified in the message has a fan installed in it.
HWC9005.Message: The BOSS-S1 device has a fan installed in it.

OSE1005.Resolution: Review system boot configuration, local PXE configuration, and PXE server configuration.

RAC0132.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while formatting the vFlash partition.
RAC0132.Message: An error has occurred while formatting a partition.

SWC8563.Description: The Boot Identity profile identified in the message is cleared from the server identified in the message.
SWC8563.Message: Boot Identity profile %1 is cleared from server in slot %2.

DKM1001.Message: The key management service is operating correctly.

RAC058.Description: The value provided for the specified attribute is not unique. For example, the user name for a user account must be unique.
RAC058.Resolution: Provide a unique value for the specified attribute. For more information about the component being managed, see the DCIM Profile documentation.
RAC058.Message: AttributeValue is not unique for AttributeName %1.

OSD33.Description: The system has an older version of BIOS that does not support this method. Install the latest version of BIOS to use this method.
OSD33.Resolution: Update the BIOS to version 1.2 or later and then rerun the command.
OSD33.Message: Installed BIOS version does not support this method.

VDR98.Description: The virtual disk identified in the message has changed active paths. This can be because of an attempt to optimize the throughput of the system or it could be because of a controller failover.
VDR98.Message: %1 has switched active controllers. Its active path is now through %2.

PWR8508.Description: If the power budget exceeds the effective capacity for the current redundancy policy, it is possible for power allocations to grow beyond the effective capacity, which would reduce redundancy capabilities.
PWR8508.Resolution: No response action is required. Make sure there are enough PSUs to support redundancy at the specified power budget.
PWR8508.Message: New power budget (%1W AC) may permit future degradation of redundancy.

SWC0294.Description: The group name specified is incorrect.
SWC0294.Resolution: Refer to the list of groups available and choose the correct one.

ENC7.Description: You have enabled the enclosure alarm. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PWR8531.Description: Server Based Power Management Mode is enabled.
PWR8531.Message: Server Based Power Management Mode is enabled.

SEL0008.Description: When the event log is full, additional events are not written to the log; or older events will be overwritten and lost. This message may also appear if the user disabled event logging. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 04h).

LIC211.Description: License import/delete/expiration resulted in a feature set change.
LIC211.Message: The iDRAC feature set has changed.

SWC0209.Message: Connect or disconnect image server connections

SWC0702.Description: Power capping is disabled and sets recommended limits for the system.

CTL72.Description: There is too much foreign configuration data to be imported in one attempt.
CTL72.Resolution: Import these foreign configurations in multiple attempts.
CTL72.Message: The foreign configuration overflow has occurred on %1.

CTL61.Description: The controller has detected a change in the storage configuration between since its last shut down. This can generally happen if some configured physical disks are removed from the system when the system was shutdown.
CTL61.Resolution: Shut down the system. Re-insert the removed physical disks and re-start the system.
CTL61.Message: Physical disks found missing from configuration during boot time on %1.

JCP032.Description: The configuration job cannot be created because the -r and --realtime options cannot be used at the same time.
JCP032.Resolution: Make sure that only one of either -r or --realtime option is entered. For example, to run a job immediately, enter the --realtime option. To schedule a job that will be run after restarting a server, use the -r option. For more information about options, see the RACADM Command Line Reference Guide available at the support site. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
JCP032.Message: Unable to create a job because conflicting options are entered.

STOR0108.Description: No temperature data to display. The system is powered off, no enclosure temperature probes are present in the system, or the temperature probes are not connected to the enclosures.
STOR0108.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosure temperature probe is available, and temperature probe is connected to the enclosure.
STOR0108.Message: Temperature probes are not connected to enclosures or data about temperature is unavailable.

CMC8605.Description: The chassis health state is no longer OK and is currently the state identified in the message. Actions should be taken to resolve any outstanding issues so that the chassis health state will return to OK.
CMC8605.Resolution: Review the Chassis log or the Chassis Management Controller(CMC) SEL log for any outstanding issue(s) and resolve any issues found by performing the recommended response action for each issue found. If the issue persists, export the chassis log and CMC SEL log and contact your support provider.
CMC8605.Message: The chassis health state is no longer OK and is currently %1.

PST0089.Description: A problem was detected during Power-On Self-Test (POST). The next logged message contains more specific details for the detected issue.
PST0089.Resolution: Review the next logged message for the recommended response action to resolve the problem.
PST0089.Message: A problem was detected during Power-On Self-Test (POST).

FAN0010.Description: The fan may be required for optimal performance.

VF045.Description: File transfer was not successful. This could be because of network problems or an operational problem with the file server.
VF045.Resolution: Try the download again. If the issue persists, validate that the network share is operational.
VF045.Message: FTP download operation was not successful.

RAC0295.Description: This is the number of characters per Serial Over LAN (SOL) data packet. When the number of characters accepted by iDRAC is equal to or greater than the Character Send Threshold value, iDRAC starts transmitting SOL data packets that contain the numbers of characters equal to or less than the Character Send Threshold value. If a packet contains fewer characters than this value, it is defined to be a partial SOL data packet. It is recommended to use 255 characters for optimal performance.
RAC0295.Resolution: Enter a valid Character Send Threshold value. Expected range: 1-255.
RAC0295.Message: The Character Send Threshold value is invalid. Expected range: 1-255.

RAC072.Description: The iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation cannot be completed because a firmware upgrade operation is in progress.
RAC072.Resolution: Wait for the current update process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC072.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation because the firmware upgrade is in progress.

FC011.Description: Configuration job already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job is completed.
FC011.Resolution: Cancel the configuration job or wait for the job to complete. Refer to documentation on job cancellation.
FC011.Message: Configuration job already created, pending data cannot be deleted.

RAC0659.Description: The storage configuration operation(s) cannot be performed on the adapter identified in the message because a job is currently pending or is running on the adapter.
RAC0659.Resolution: Wait for the job to completely run, or delete the job, and then retry the operation. To view the status of the scheduled jobs, go to the Job Queue page of iDRAC.
RAC0659.Message: Unable to perform the storage configuration operation(s) on %1 because a job is currently pending or is running on the adapter.

PWR2257.Description: The target power allocation override has been enabled or disabled as identified in the message.
PWR2257.Message: The target power allocation override is %1. The target power allocation (AC) is %2 Watts.

SWC1943.Description: The Quick Sync Wifi feature has been set to Disabled.
SWC1943.Message: The Quick Sync Wifi feature is disabled.

STOR020.Description: The controller key cannot be set because a key is already present.
STOR020.Resolution: Delete the current key and retry the operation.
STOR020.Message: A controller key is already present.

STOR065.Description: Unable to create the requested virtual disk because one or more specified physical disk(s) is not T10 Protection Information capable.
STOR065.Resolution: Verify that the physical disks selected for creating a virtual disk are T10 Protection Information capable, and then retry the operation.
STOR065.Message: One or more physical disks specified for creating a virtual disk are not T10 Protection Information capable.

HWC2008.Description: The fabric type for the IOM and mezzanine cards must match. Once an IOM or mezzanine card is inserted into the chassis, the fabric type is then set for the CMC and the CMC will ensure that all subsequent IOM's and mezzanine cards match.
HWC2008.Resolution: Check chassis fabric type in CMC GUI and compare to the type of IOM or mezzanine card.
HWC2008.Message: A fabric mismatch detected for mezzanine card %1.

PSU0076.Description: Power supplies should be of the same input type and power rating.
PSU0076.Resolution: Install matched power supplies and review product documentation for proper configuration.
PSU0076.Message: A power supply wattage mismatch is detected; power supply %1 is rated for %2 watts.

CTL1.Description: This event is retrieved from the controller when iDRAC storage monitoring was not running. Such events which are generated in the past are logged as informational severity.

STOR026.Description: A configuration job was not created because there are no pending configuration changes.
STOR026.Message: A configuration job was not created because there are no pending configuration changes.

CTL121.Description: The firmware version of the RAID controller identified in the message cannot be updated because of an issue during the update process (programming error).
CTL121.Resolution: Do not reset, restart, or turn off the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). However, retry the operation by using a correct firmware image file. If the issue persists, contact the service provider.
CTL121.Message: Unable to update the RAID controller %1 firmware version because of an issue during the update process (programming error).

MEM0600.Message: Memory device was added at location %1.

CTL58.Description: The text for this alert is generated by the firmware and can vary depending on the situation. The reference to SMP in this text refers to SAS Management Protocol.
CTL58.Resolution: There may be a SAS topology error. See the hardware documentation for information on correct SAS topology configurations. There may be problems with the cables such as a loose connection or an invalid cabling configuration. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. See the hardware documentation for information on correct cabling configurations. Verify that the firmware version is supported.

USR0204.Description: The BMC cannot communicate with the Quick Sync device embedded in the panel, due to a problem with the interface to the device.
USR0204.Resolution: Make sure ribbon cable is connected properly to the communications device embedded in the panel, and retry operation.
USR0204.Message: Quick Sync feature is not available due to hardware failure.

RAC0214.Description: Login page is missing a password.

RAC0713.Description: Server failed to power up due to fabric mismatch.
RAC0713.Resolution: Ensure that the hardware compatibility between the IO Module (IOM) and the Mezzanine (Mezz) card is correct. Check the M1000e Hardware Manual for correct component compatibility.
RAC0713.Message: Server failed to power up due to fabric mismatch.

JCP031.Description: The job ID specified as input to the operation has configuration data that is currently being processed by the iDRAC. The job can be deleted after the processing is done.
JCP031.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for 15 seconds, wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting, and then retry the operation.
JCP031.Message: Unable to delete the job because the configuration is still being committed.

PDR38.Description: A user has initiated a clear operation on a physical disk.

PDR69.Description: Physical disk inserted is of the incorrect protocol. SAS or SATA mixing is not supported in the same virtual disk.
PDR69.Resolution: Remove drive, insert correct protocol type, and force a rebuild as imposed for controller and system.

RAC055.Description: The user name for the user account cannot be cleared because the user account is enabled in the configuration XML file.
RAC055.Resolution: Retry the operation after disabling the user account in the configuration XML file.
RAC055.Message: User name cannot be cleared because the user account is enabled in the input configuration XML file.

USR104.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in iDRAC.
USR104.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
USR104.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

SRV129.Description: The SupportAssist Collection operation is either fully or partially completed, and then exported to the local path.
SRV129.Message: The SupportAssist Collection operation is either fully or partially completed, and then exported to the local path.

SWC0238.Description: The key specified by the public key is too long.
SWC0238.Resolution: Request for a valid public key from the system and re-try the command.

CTL2.Description: You have changed the controller rebuild rate. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

VRM0013.Description: Simultaneously connecting Virtual Media and USB interface is not possible.
VRM0013.Resolution: Detach the USB interface and re-try.
VRM0013.Message: Virtual Media services is currently attached to the USB interface. It must be detached before the image server can be connected.

SYS093.Description: The iDRAC is exporting the Tech Support Report to the specified destination.
SYS093.Message: The iDRAC is exporting the Tech Support Report.

RAC036.Description: The value of the specified attribute is dependent on the value of another attribute. The current value dependency is invalid. The other attribute value must be changed before the specified attribute value can be set.
RAC036.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation for the specified attribute dependency on another attribute value and retry the operation.

STOR050.Description: The controller is in Local Key Management mode.
STOR050.Message: Controller is in Dell Key Management mode.

RFM1021.Description: The removable flash media is installed but improperly configured or failed to initialize.
RFM1021.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
RFM1021.Message: Removable Flash Media is not IPMI-function ready.

SWC0319.Description: The syntax for the getraclog command is invalid.
SWC0319.Resolution: Refer the help text for getraclog command.
SWC0319.Message: The -i option is not valid with any other options.

VF037.Description: The attaching partition operation did not complete successfully.
VF037.Message: Attach partition operation did not complete successfully.

SWU8548.Description: The firmware update operation of Standby CMC was not successful. The firmware image could not be accessed.
SWU8548.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8548.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware. The Image was not accessible.

SWC0143.Message: SSL key successfully uploaded to the RAC.

UEFI0098.Description: The memory Built-In Self-test (BIST) has detected one or more errors on the DIMM installed on memory slot: <slot number>. As a result, the corresponding DIMM has been disabled.
UEFI0098.Resolution: Replace the DIMM module identified in the message. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0098.Message: The memory Built-In Self-test (BIST) has detected one or more errors on the DIMM installed on memory slot: %1. As a result, the corresponding DIMM has been disabled.

RAC0686.Description: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.
RAC0686.Resolution: View successful pending operations by clicking the Pending Operations button.
RAC0686.Message: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.

ASR0106.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. No action was taken. (IPMI sensor type code 23h - offset 00h event 3:0 - 4h).
ASR0106.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.

RED027.Description: The temporary storage is full. The uploaded files must be installed to clear space for additional uploads.
RED027.Resolution: Select and install the currently uploaded files before uploading additional files.
RED027.Message: Insufficient space to upload the requested file.

MEM9020.Description: The NVDIMM device in the slot, identified in the message, is about to reach the end of supported life duration.
MEM9020.Resolution: During the next scheduled maintenance, replace the Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device. For more information about the usage of NVDIMMs, see the system Owner's Manual on the support site.
MEM9020.Message: The Non-Volatile Dual In-line Memory Module (NVDIMM) device in the slot %1 is about to reach the end of supported life duration.

RED089.Description: A Chassis firmware update operation is in progress. Any attempt to update Chassis firmware during this period will be unsuccessful.
RED089.Message: A Chassis firmware update operation is in progress.

SWC4004.Description: FlexAddress is not implemented in one of the versions of firmware. Please update the firmware.
SWC4004.Resolution: Check firmware versions of iDRAC and CMC. Update to latest version.
SWC4004.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility detected between iDRAC in slot %1 and CMC.

RAC0715.Description: Image file does not exist in the given remote share path.
RAC0715.Resolution: Ensure that the image file is available on the share path provided. Retry the operation.
RAC0715.Message: Image file does not exist in the given remote share path.

PDR112.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message is approaching the warranted wear-out limit.
PDR112.Message: The %1 has reached %2 of warranted device wear-out limit.

SWC1922.Description: The user identified in the message has successfully modified the server configuration by using Quick Sync.
SWC1922.Message: User %1 has successfully modified the server configuration by using Quick Sync.

USR0176.Description: The Front Panel USB Port Over Current condition is cleared for the port identified in the message.
USR0176.Message: The Front Panel USB Port Over Current condition is cleared for the attached device Disk.USBFront.%1.

PWR2251.Description: The server did not turn on because the chassis cover is open.
PWR2251.Resolution: Close the chassis cover and retry the operation.
PWR2251.Message: Unable to turn on the server because the chassis cover is open.

LOG007.Description: This message is generated after a series of sequential duplicate events. Log entry count is the number of times the previous message was repeated.
LOG007.Message: The previous log entry was repeated %1 times.

UEFI0181.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Write DQ/DQS error was detected.
UEFI0181.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0181.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

RAC1027.Description: A test event was generated and the alert was successfully sent to the destination.
RAC1027.Resolution: Verify if the alerts were received by the configured destination. Otherwise, reconfigure the destination and retry the operation.
RAC1027.Message: Successfully sent the alert for the specified event to the configured destination.

RAC0712.Description: Server failed to power up due to zero power allocated.
RAC0712.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller web interface to check available power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, allocate power necessary and retry the operation.
RAC0712.Message: Server failed to power up due to zero power allocated.

UEFI0217.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Basic Write DQ/DQS Training phase.
UEFI0217.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0217.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

PWR8676.Description: The chassis power property identified in the message cannot be set.
PWR8676.Message: Unable to set the chassis power property %1.

PCI1322.Description: System performance may be degraded. The bus is not operating at maximum speed or width.
PCI1322.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1322.Message: Bus performance degraded for a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

RAC0602.Description: The value for alert recurrence must be within the range 0-365.

CTL62.Description: Physical disk(s) have been removed from a virtual disk. The virtual disk will be in Failed state during the next system reboot. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL62.Message: %1 on %2 has missing drives and will go offline at boot.

HWC4002.Description: A hardware incompatibility was detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and other hardware. An iDRAC or BMC firmware update is needed.
HWC4002.Resolution: Update the BMC/iDRAC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC4002.Message: A hardware incompatibility detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and other hardware.

CPU0011.Resolution: Review System Event Log and Operating System Logs. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0011.Message: Uncorrectable Machine Check Exception detected on CPU %1.

SYS185.Description: The Tech Support Report job that was running has been cancelled by user request.
SYS185.Resolution: To start another Tech Support Report job, wait until the current job that is being cancelled completes and then retry the operation.
SYS185.Message: The Tech Support Report job has been cancelled.

RAC0238.Description: vFlash is unable to service the request at this time. Try again later.
RAC0238.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes.
RAC0238.Message: vFlash is currently in-use by another process. Try again later.

GMGR0025.Description: The group job identified in the message could not be completed.
GMGR0025.Resolution: See the job details in the iDRAC Group Manager job view, and then retry the operation if required.
GMGR0025.Message: Unable to complete the group job %1 of type %2 on the iDRAC %3.

UEFI0262.Description: An issue is observed initializing DDR (double data rate) on the memory riser identified in the message. A possible cause is the DIMM modules are incorrectly seated in the slots.
UEFI0262.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM modules and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory modules identified in the message.
UEFI0262.Message: Unable to initialize DIMM modules on memory riser %1 because of a DDR training error.

HWC7004.Description: Server health changed to a critical state from either a normal or warning state.
HWC7004.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7004.Message: Server %1 health changed to a critical state from either a normal or warning state.

LC002.Description: A general failure occurred while executing the command.
LC002.Resolution: Verify network connectivity. If failure persists, reset the iDRAC to resolve the issue.

LIC009.Description: An upgrade license carries specific information about the license it is replacing. If that information does not match, then the license import is aborted.
LIC009.Resolution: Obtain a new license file with the correct upgrade information.

BOOT010.Description: The provided vFlash partition index could not be found on the system.
BOOT010.Resolution: Verify that a vFlash partition with the desired index exists on the System.
BOOT010.Message: Could not locate vFlash partition index

USR0017.Description: There are no active sessions on the iDRAC for the specified user.
USR0017.Message: No active sessions currently exist for the specified user.

PSU0801.Description: The Power Supply had a CRC error detected.
PSU0801.Resolution: Acquire the power supply firmware image and update the power supply indicated in the message.

RAC1204.Description: The Secure Boot Certificate Delete operation is successfully scheduled. For the changes to become effective, restart the host server.
RAC1204.Message: The Secure Boot Certificate Delete operation is successfully scheduled.

UEFI0155.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.
UEFI0155.Resolution: If the absence of license is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0155.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.

BIOS022.Description: The BIOS password is disabled in the hardware using a jumper and can not be set. See the system owners manual for jumper location.
BIOS022.Resolution: Change the jumper setting on the system board to enable changing the BIOS password.
